1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 d5?! { This leads to an endgame that is very uncomfortable for Black. } 4. Nxe5 (4. Bb5 exd4 (4... dxe4) (4... Bd7) (4... Bg4?! 5. h3 Bxf3 (5... Bd7?! $146 6. exd5 (6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nxe5 dxe4 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $16 { White is just better here: better pawn structure, the king is safe, and the undeveloped pieces can get out easily. } { [%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e4,Gb1d2,Gd2e4,Gb1c3] }) 6... Nxd4 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qxd4 $16 { White is a pawn up, and Black has no compensation. }) 6. Qxf3 { [%cal Ge4d5] } 6... Ne7 (6... dxe4? $146 7. Qxe4 { [%cal Ge4c6,Gb5c6] } 7... Ne7 8. dxe5 $16 a6 $16))) 4... dxe4 (4... Nxe5 { is what most people play online. } 5. dxe5 { And now the best move for Black is Ne7, protecting d5 and developing a piece. Very few players find that. Most will overextend with d4 or go into a bad endgame with dxe4. } 5... Ne7 (5... d4 6. f4 Ne7 (6... Bc5)) (5... dxe4?! { Looks so natural, and yet, it's quite bad: } 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7] } 7... Ke7 (7... Be6?! 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. O-O Bc5 10. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 10... e3 { The pawn will fall anyway. } 11. fxe3 $16) 8. Bd5 f6 9. Bf4 fxe5 10. Bxe5 Nf6 { [%cal Rf6d5] } 11. Bb3)) *


