{ Get a queen that White can't take! }
48... Kh1 { Yes! This is the only winning move. } (48... Kg3 { This allows White to draw with Ke1, and then you can't get a queen. } 49. Ke1) (48... f2 49. Ke2 { [%cal Ge2e3] } 49... Kg1 50. Bh3 f1=Q+ 51. Bxf1) (48... Kg1 { This allows White to draw with Ke1, and then you can't get a queen. }) (48... e2+ { It's a check, but now White can trade the bishop for both pawns. } { [%cal Rf1e2,Rd1e2] } 49. Bxe2 fxe2+ 50. Kxe2) 49. Ke1 { And now force White to make a bad move. } 49... Kg1 { Very good. Now White is in zugzwang (forced to make a move that makes their position worse). } (49... Kh2 { No. Now White can get a draw by moving their bishop along the f1-a6 diagonal. } { [%cal Gf1a6] }) (49... e2 { Now White can get both pawns via Bxe2. }) (49... f2+ { Now White's King can go to e2 and their bishop to h3 … and then you can't get a queen. }) 50. Bd3 f2+ { Yes! Now White's king has to go to e2, where it is blocking their own bishop or to d1. } (50... e2 { Bxe2, and White can get both pawns. }) (50... Kg2 { No. Be4 will pin the f-pawn, and if your king goes away, Bd3 will hold everything for White. } { [%cal Rd3e4,Be4f3,Be4g2] }) (50... Kh2 { No, Kf1 will push you away. } { [%cal Ge1f1] }) (50... Kh1 { No, Kf1 will push you away. }) 51. Kd1 f1=Q+ { Yes! Sacrifice one pawn/queen for the bishop. } (51... f1=N { Congratulations! You just outsmarted yourself. }) 52. Bxf1 { … and now? } 52... Kxf1 { Of course. } { [%csl Ge1,Ge2,Gd2][%cal Ge3d2,Gf1e1,Gf1e2] } 53. Kc2 e2 54. Kd2 e1=Q+ { Well done! Congratulations! } *


