{ White to move and draw. }
1. Ng1 Ne3+ 2. Kh3 (2. Kh2?? { That's a mate in 16, because Black can promote to a knights and restrict White's knight } 2... e1=N! 3. Kh3 N1g2 4. Nf3+ Kd3 5. Ng1 Ke4 6. Ne2 Kf3 7. Nd4+ Kf2 8. Ne6 Nf6 9. Nd4 Nc4 10. Nc6 Ne1 11. Nd4 Nd2 12. Nf5 Ng2 13. Nd4 Nde4 14. Nc2 Ng5+ 15. Kh2 Nf3+ 16. Kh1 Ne4 17. Ne1 Ng3#) 2... Nf4+ (2... e1=N?? 3. Nf3+! { anyway } 3... Nxf3 { Stalemate! }) 3. Kh2 (3. Kg3 { That's a mate in 6, because Black can promote to a queen with check. } 3... e1=Q+ 4. Kxf4 Qxg1 5. Ke5 Qg6 6. Kd4 Qh5 7. Ke4 Qf5+ 8. Kd4 Qd5#) (3. Kh4 { That's a mate in 6, because Black can promote to a queen with check. } 3... e1=Q+ 4. Kg5 Qxg1+ 5. Kf6 Qg6+ 6. Ke7 Ned5+ 7. Kd7 Qe6+ 8. Kd8 Qd6+ 9. Ke8 Qe7#) 3... Ng4+ 4. Kh1 (4. Kg3?? { Now Black can promote to a queen with check, and then it's a mate in 8. } 4... e1=Q+ 5. Kxg4 Qxg1+ 6. Kxf4 Qc5 7. Ke4 Qd6 8. Kf5 Ke3 9. Kg5 Qe6 10. Kh4 Kf4 11. Kh5 Qb6! { [%cal Gb6h6,Gf4f5,Gf4g5,Gf4g4] } 12. Kh4 Qh6#) 4... Nf2+ 5. Kh2 e1=N 6. Nf3+ (6. Kg3 { This loses the knight for White, because Black can drive White's king away. } 6... Ke3 7. Nf3 (7. Kh4 Ned3 8. Kg5 Nc5 9. Kf5 Nce6 10. Ke5 Nd4 11. Kd6 N2d3 12. Kc7 Kf2 { And White's knight is lost. }) 7... Ne4+ 8. Kg4 Nxf3) (6. Ne2 { Well, say good-bye to your knight. } 6... Kxe2) (6. Nh3 { Loses the knight. } 6... N2xh3) 6... Nxf3+ 7. Kg3 { Master fork! Black needs all three knights to win, but they will either lose one or play: } 7... Ke3 { And that's a stalemate. Congratulations! } *


