1. e4 e5 2. d4 { C21 Center Game. The German name is Mittelgambit, meaning Center Gambit. What White is gambiting here is not a pawn but a tempo. } 2... exd4 { C21 Center Game/Accepted } (2... d6 { B0 7 King's Pawn Game/Maróczy Defense } 3. dxe5 (3. Nf3 { C41 Philidor Defense } 3... exd4 { C41 Philidor Defense/Exchange Variation } 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2) 3... Bd7 { B07 King Pawn Game/Philidor Gambit } (3... dxe5 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 5. Bc4 f6 6. Be3)) (2... d5 { C21 King Pawn Game/Beyer Gambit }) (2... Nc6?! { Transposition: B00 Nimzowitsch Defense/Kennedy Variation. } 3. d5 { B00 Nimzowitsch Defense/Kennedy Variation/Linksspringer Variation } (3. dxe5 Nxe5 4. Nf3) 3... Nce7 4. Nc3) (2... Nf6 3. dxe5 Nxe4 4. Qe2 Nc5) (2... Qh4?! { Queen Attack } 3. Bd3 exd4 (3... Nc6 4. Nf3 { Ghane Gardeh, Shojaat - Tikhiy, Sergey, 1-0, Azov Don Cup, 2010, https://lichess.org/XAerwb8T }) (3... d6 4. Nf3 Qh5 (4... Qg4) (4... Qe7))) 3. Qxd4 (3. f4 { C21 Center Game/Halasz-McDonnell Gambit } 3... Bc5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 { C21 Center Game/Halasz-McDonnell Gambit/Crocodile Variation }) (3. Nf3 { C21 Center Game/Kieseritzky Variation } { [%cal Gd1d4,Gf3d4] } 3... Bc5 4. c3 { C21 Center Game/Lanc-Arnold Gambit } (4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3) 4... dxc3 5. Bc4 { C21 Center Game/Lanc-Arnold Gambit/Schippler Gambit }) (3. Bd3 { C21 Center Game/Ross Gambit }) (3. Bc4 { C21 Center Game/Von der Lasa Gambit }) (3. c3 { C21 Danish Gambit/General } 3... dxc3 (3... Ne7 { C21 Danish Gambit/Accepted/Svenonius Defense }) (3... d5 { C21 Danish Gambit/Declined/Sorensen Defense }) 4. Bc4 cxb2 5. Bxb2 { C21 Danish Gambit/Accepted } 5... Qe7 { C21 Danish Gambit/Accepted/Chigorin Defense } (5... Nf6 { C21 Danish Gambit/Accepted/Classical Defense }) (5... Bb4+ { C21 Danish Gambit/Accepted/Copenhagen Defense }) (5... d5 { C21 Danish Gambit/Accepted/Schlechter Defense })) 3... Nc6 { C22 Center Game/Normal Variation. White succeeds in eliminating Black's e-pawn and opening the d-file, but at the cost of moving the queen early and allowing Black to develop a tempo with 3...Nc6. } 4. Qe3 { C22 Center Game/Paulsen Attack Variation. The position of the white queen hinders Black's ability to play ...d5. The back rank is cleared of pieces quickly which facilitates queenside castling and may allow White to quickly develop an attack. From e3, the white queen may later move to g3 where she will pressure Black's g7-square. } (4. Qc4 { Hall Variation. Rarely played. }) 4... Nf6 { C22 Center Game/Berger Variation } 5. Bd2 { Prevent shenanigans with Black's knight or bishop on b4. } { [%csl Bb4][%cal Gd2b4] } (5. Bb5) (5. Nc3 { Statistical main move. }) 5... Be7 6. Nc3 { Now Black could castle or open the center with d5 immediately, pointing out White's lack of development. } 6... d5 (6... O-O 7. O-O-O d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 { [%cal Rd5e3] }) 7. Nxd5 Nxd5 8. exd5 Qxd5 9. Ne2 Bf5 (9... O-O 10. Nf4 Qc5 11. O-O-O) 10. Nf4 Qd7 11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. Bd3 g5 (12... Bf6 13. Rhe1 (13. Bxf5 Qxf5)) *


