1. e4 e5 2. d4 Qh4? { Queen Attack. A mistake that you might see in blitz games sometimes. } { [%cal Rh4e4] } 3. Bd3 exd4 (3... d6 { The main problem with this move is that the queen is running out of retreat squares. As you can see in all of the following lines, Black's queen stays under constant attack. } 4. Nf3 { The queen has to move already. There is no counter attack. } 4... Qh5 (4... Qg4 5. Nc3 { This knight wants to go to c7. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gc3d5,Gd5c7] } (5. dxe5) 5... Ne7 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Re7d5] } 6. O-O Ng6 $16) (4... Qe7 5. c3) (4... Bg4? 5. Nxh4 Bxd1 6. Kxd1 { And White is a piece up. }) 5. c3 { White should try to keep two center pawns. } (5. Be2 Bg4 6. O-O { Prepare h3. } 6... Nf6 { [%cal Rf6e4] } 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Bxf3 { [%cal Gf3h5] } 8... Qg6) (5. d5 { Questionable as that pawn can be challenged with c6 later. }) 5... Nc6 (5... Be7 6. h3 Qg6 7. g4 Nd7) (5... Nf6) 6. O-O Bd7 (6... Nf6 7. Re1 Qg6 8. Nbd2 h6 9. Nf1 (9. Nc4 Bg4 10. Ne3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qh5 12. Qxh5 Nxh5 $16) (9. Nh4 Qg5 10. Ndf3 Qh5 $16) 9... Be7 10. Ng3 Bd8 $16) (6... Be7 7. Re1 Qg6 8. Qb3 h6 $16) 7. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7] } (7. Re1 Nf6 8. Qb3 O-O-O 9. d5 Ne7 10. Nbd2 g5 $16) 7... O-O-O 8. Re1 f5 $16) (3... Nc6 4. d5 (4. Nf3) 4... Nb4 5. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gf3h4] } 5... Nxd3+ 6. cxd3 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qe7 $16) 4. Nf3 { The question for Black is now: Should I try to hold d4? } { [%cal Gf3h4,Gf3d4] } 4... Qh5 (4... Qd8 { Engine's second best suggestion. Very sad. } 5. Nxd4) (4... Qe7 5. Nxd4) (4... Qf6 { White can now go for faster development with a gambit (c3), for safety with O-O, or for an immediate attack with e5. I think the gambit line is in the spirit of this opening, e5 is for the tactical player, and O-O for someone is isn't very experienced. } { [%cal Rf6d4] } 5. c3 { Gambit line. } (5. O-O { King safety first. }) (5. e5 { Attack! }) 5... Nc6 { Just protect the pawn, decline the gambit. } (5... d5 { Counter gambit! }) (5... dxc3 { Accept. }) 6. O-O (6. Bg5 Qd6 { [%cal Rd6d4,Rc6d4] } 7. O-O Be7 8. Bc1) (6. e5 { Attack anyway. } 6... Qd8 { Engine's best move. Not sure why. } (6... Qe7 7. O-O { exd4 isn't possible, because then the rook would pin the queen. } 7... d6) (6... Qe6 7. cxd4) (6... Nxe5? 7. Qe2 $18 { Now Black is in deep, deep trouble. Everything is hanging, and there is no way out. } { Ghane Gardeh, Shojaat - Tikhiy, Sergey, 1-0, Azov Don Cup, 2010, https://lichess.org/XAerwb8T } { [%cal Gc3d4,Ge2e5,Gf3e5,Gc1g5] }) 7. cxd4) 6... Ne5 7. Nxe5 Qxe5 8. cxd4 Qxd4 9. e5 { [%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e7] }) 5. c3 { A gambit. Why not? :) } (5. O-O Bc5 6. Be2 Qg6 { [%cal Rg6e4,Gf3d4,Gd1d4] } 7. Ng5 { The queen is running out of squares very soon. } { [%cal Gg5e4,Ge2h5,Gh5g6] } 7... Qb6 8. c3) (5. Be2) 5... dxc3 (5... d5) 6. Nxc3 Bb4 7. O-O (7. Bd2) 7... Ne7 (7... Bxc3) 8. Qb3 Bc5 (8... Bxc3) (8... Nbc6) 9. Ne2 { [%cal Ge2g3] } 9... Bd6 *


