[Event "The Caro-Kann/Panov Attack in depth: Introduction"]
[Date "2019.05.13"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B14"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Panov Attack, Main Line"]
[StudyName "The Caro-Kann/Panov Attack in depth"]
[ChapterName "Introduction"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/JWmJD6hp/euYV2mhS"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.13"]
[UTCTime "10:53:21"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 (2. c4 { This is a different move order. But if you really want to play the Panov as White, you should take the main line here via Exchange variation. The reason is that Black can now play e5 instead of d5, and then you get a completely different game. } 2... d5 (2... e5! { See ➡ Accelerated Panov/Open https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/GjjvWvMM }) 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4) 2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 { c4 marks the beginning of the Panov Attack, sometimes also called the Panov-Botvinnik Attack. White goes for an IQP position hoping for a very sharp and aggressive game. The resulting middle game positions can arise from a number of different openings: Nimzo-Indian, English, and others. } { [%csl Bd4] } 4... Nf6 (4... g6?! { ➡ Accelerated Fianchetto Defense }) (4... e6 { Different move order leading to the same position as in the main line given here. } 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Nf3) (4... Nc6 { ➡ 4…Nc6 } 5. Nc3) (4... dxc4 5. Bxc4 { transposes to a line from the Queen's Gambit Accepted. } 5... Qc7 6. Bb3 Bg4 { [%cal Gc7c1] } 7. f3 Bd7) 5. Nc3 (5. c5 { ➡ Gunderam Attack } { [%cal Rf1b5,Rd1a4] }) (5. Nf3 { A very rare move. Will most likely transpose back into one of the main lines. } 5... g6 6. Nc3 (6. c5 Bg7) 6... Bg7) 5... e6 (5... g6 { Fianchetto Defense.
The idea here is NOT to play e6. This keeps the light-squared bishop active, and it makes it more difficult for White to play Nf3, because Black can then pin that knight.
The dark-squared bishop on g7 will keep the king safe and put pressure on d4. } { [%csl Be7,Bd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg7d4] } 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } (6. cxd5 Bg7 { ➡ Fianchetto gambit } (6... Nxd5 { is of course possible and playable. } 7. Bc4 { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 8 } (7. Qb3 Nb6! { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 5 } { [%cal Gc8e6,Gf8g7] } (7... e6 { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 6 }) (7... Nxc3?! { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 7 })))) (6. Nf3?! Bg7) (6. Bg5 Bg7 7. Bxf6 (7. Nf3) (7. cxd5)) 6... Bg7 { Now it's a gambit anyway, even if it isn't called one. d5 will fall, and the question is if Black will get it back or enough compensation. The difference to the Fianchetto gambit is that White hasn't taken d5 yet and played Qb3 instead. } (6... e6?! { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 9 }) 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Be2 { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 1 } { [%cal Re2f3,Rf3d5] } (8. Nge2 { The second most common move. White's idea is to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 8... Na6 { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 2 } (8... e6?! { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 3 }) (8... Nbd7 { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 4 }))) (5... Nc6 { Panov Attack/Modern Defense. } 6. Nf3 { ➡ Modern Defense 1 } (6. Bg5 e6 { ➡ Carlsbad Line } (6... Qa5 { ➡ Czerniak Line }) (6... Qb6 { ➡ Reifir-Spielmann Line }) (6... Be6 { ➡ Modern Defense 3 }) (6... dxc4 { ➡ Modern Defense 4 } 7. d5 Na5 { Panov-Botvinnik/Herzog Defense })) (6. cxd5 { ➡ Modern Defense 2 })) (5... Bg4? { Serious mistake } 6. Qb3! { [%cal Rc4d5,Rb3b7] } 6... Qb6 7. cxd5) (5... Bf5 { Same problem as in the Bg4 line. } 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. cxd5 Qxb3 8. axb3) 6. Nf3 (6. cxd5) (6. c5) 6... Bb4 { This is now a transposition to the Nimzo-Indian defense. The idea behind this move is preventing the later Re1! White will now bring the dark-squared bishop to d2 in order to remove this pin. But that move breaks the connection between the queen and the d-pawn. } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Rh1e1,Rd1d4,Bc1d2] } (6... Be7 { The old main line. } 7. cxd5 (7. a3 O-O) 7... Nxd5 (7... exd5 8. Bb5+ (8. Bd3 O-O)) 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1) 7. cxd5 (7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. O-O b6 (9... a6) 10. Bg5 (10. Qe2 Bb7 (10... Nc6) 11. Rd1 (11. Bg5))) 7... Nxd5 (7... exd5 8. Bd3 (8. Bb5+ Bd7 (8... Nc6))) 8. Bd2 { Now the queen doesn't watch d4 anymore. } { [%cal Rd1d4] } (8. Qc2 Nc6 9. Bc4 Qc7 10. Bd3 Bd6 11. Nxd5 exd5 $10) (8. Qb3 Nc6) 8... Nc6 9. Bd3 (9. Rc1) (9. a3) 9... Be7 (9... O-O { The move order isn't so important here. } 10. O-O Be7) 10. O-O (10. Nxd5 exd5 (10... Qxd5)) 10... O-O { White has now to deal with the threat of Ndb4. Or play Re1 anyway, which leads to interesting complications. } { [%cal Gd5b4,Bd8d4,Bc6d4] } 11. Qc2 (11. Nxd5 exd5 (11... Qxd5)) (11. a3 { This is the main move; it watches b4. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ra3b4] } 11... Bf6 { Black attacks d4 once more. } 12. Qc2 { [%cal Rd3h7] } 12... g6 { Allows Bh6 which is a bit uncomfortable for Black. } (12... h6 { Now the h-pawn is safe, and d4 is attacked twice and defended just once, so } { [%cal Gf6d4,Gc6d4,Rf3d4] } 13. Be3 { adds the missing protection. } 13... Nce7 14. Ne4 { [%csl Rc5][%cal Re4f6,Re4c5] } 14... b6 { is a prophylactic move: it prevents Nc5, and it allows Black later to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 16. Ne5 (16. Rac1 Bb7 17. Ne5 { Pommrich, Rainer - Larsen, Søren M, 1/2-1/2, CT17/pr27, 2009, https://lichess.org/UvTtYpWs }) 16... Bb7 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. Qa4 { [%cal Ra4a7] } 18... Rxc1 (18... Qd5 { A very simple threat. } { [%cal Gd5g2] } 19. f3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6a7] } 20. Nxc6 (20. Bc4) 20... Bxc6 { [%cal Gc6a4] } 21. Qb4 (21. Qxa7? { is not that useful } 21... Qb3! { forks pawn and bishop. } { [%cal Gb3b2,Gb3d3] } 22. Qa6 { has to protect the bishop } { [%cal Ga6d3] } 22... Nd5 { protects b6 and attacks the bishop on e3. } { [%cal Gd5b6,Gd5e3] } 23. Bf2 Qxb2 $17 { Black is better here. Bb7 is a nice idea, Nf4 and Ra8 are also good moves. White is in a very difficult position now. } { [%cal Gc6b7,Gd5f4,Bf4d3,Gc8a8,Ba8a3,Rc1b1,Bb2d2] }) 21... Qd7 22. Ba6 Rcd8 $10 { This is at least equal if not better for Black. The pawn structure is better and easier to hold, Nd5 will be very annoying for White. } { [%cal Gf6d5] }) 19. Rxc1 a5 20. Qb5 { [%csl Bd7][%cal Rb5d7,Re5d7,Gf6d7] } 20... Nc8 $10 { [%cal Gc8d6,Gd6b5] }) 13. Bh6 { Black can now either Bg7, exchanging the dark-squared bishops, or Re8, weakening f7. } 13... Re8 14. Rad1 { [%cal Rc3e4,Be4f6] } 14... Nxc3 { Make sure this knight can't go to e4 anymore. } 15. bxc3 { The question for Black is now how to develop the light-squared bishop: to d7 or b7? d7 is faster, but it does block the queen's view at d5. } { [%cal Gc8d7,Gc8b7,Gd8d5] } 15... b6 (15... Bd7) 16. Bb5 Bb7 17. Ne5 { [%cal Re5c6,Rb5c6] } (17. c4 { Prevents Qd5. } 17... a6 18. Ba4 { Zhang, Zhong - Jobava, Baadur, 1/2-1/2, Taiyuan schev, 2006, https://lichess.org/1895EADz }) 17... Rc8) (11. Re1 { White can also ignore this threat and give d4 with good compensation: } { [%csl Bd4] } 11... Ndb4 12. Bf4 { If Black goes for the Bf6 line, they will win a pawn temporarily. But White will get it back, as we can see. So it might be easier to take the bishop and let White sit on their IQP with less material. } 12... Nxd3 (12... Bf6 13. Be4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Nb5 { [%cal Rb5d4,Rd1d4] } 15... e5 16. Nxd4 exf4 17. Qd2 $10 { Still equal. And now Nc6 is the best continuation. Note that the knight on d4 is pinned. } { [%cal Gd8d2] } 17... Nc6 (17... Nd5 18. b3 $146 { Prophylactic move, anticipating Qb6. Novelty. } (18. Rad1 Nf6 19. Qxf4 Qb6 20. b3 { Frolyanov, Dmitry - Drozdovskij, Yuri, 1/2-1/2, RUS-chT2 17th, 2010, https://lichess.org/Z5TQr32t }) 18... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 19. Qxf4 Nxe4 20. Qxe4 h6 { Make some luft. And both sides are fine. }) 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Qxf4 Qb6 20. b3 c5 21. Nf5 (21. Nf3?! h6 22. Rac1 Be6 $10) 21... Bxf5 22. Qxf5 g6 23. Qe5 Rfd8 { Equal, but not drawish. White's idea is probably h4 and h5 or pressure on Black's weak c-pawn. Black should try to get one or even two rooks to the 2nd rank and attack f2. } { Danin, Alexandre - Sumets, Andrey, 1/2-1/2, Bergamo op 11th, 2012, https://lichess.org/Ga48lq7p } { [%csl Bf2,Bc5][%cal Rh2h4,Ra1c1,Rc1c5,Re5c5,Gd8d2,Gd2f2,Gb6f2] }) 13. Qxd3 Nb4 14. Qe4 Re8 { and not the adventurous f5! } (14... f5?! { Weakens e6 } { [%csl Be6] } 15. Qe2 { There are only three games in the database with this position, and they all continue with the rather cocky g5. Stockfish wants the solid Nd5. } 15... g5 16. Bc1 Bf6 17. Rd1 { White really wants to play h4 here and open up Black's king even more! The only way to prevent that is by pressing even harder. This is dangerous. } { [%cal Rh2h4] } 17... Nd5 { White will gladly take and give Black an IQP too! } (17... g4?! 18. Ne5! { Bh6 is White's next idea. } { [%cal Rc1h6] } 18... b6! { [%cal Gc8a6] } 19. Bh6 (19. Qc4 a5 { Baghdasaryan, Vahe - Harutjunyan, Gevorg, 1-0, Yerevan Margaryan Memorial, 2012, https://lichess.org/euGosvwg }) 19... Ba6 { [%cal Ga6e2] } 20. Qd2 Bxe5 21. Bxf8 Bxh2+ 22. Kxh2 Qh4+ 23. Kg1 Rxf8 24. Qe3 f4 $16 { White is just better here. }) 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. h4 { Yilmaz, Mustafa Enes - Kovchan, Alexander, 1/2-1/2, Kharkov Rector Cup, 2011, https://lichess.org/kCgprj2h }) 15. Rac1 Bd7 16. Ne5 { Black has choice here: give b7 and trade off material into a drawish position (Bf6 line) or give the light-squared bishop on c6? Nc6 isn't that good. } 16... Bc6 { I recommend this line. } (16... Bf6 $146 { Novelty! } 17. Qxb7 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Nd3 19. Red1 { [%cal Rd1d7,Rb7d7] } 19... Rb8 20. Qxa7 Nxf4 21. Qxd7 Qxd7 22. Rxd7 Rxb2 23. Ra1) (16... Nc6?! { is dubious. } { [%cal Gc6e5] } 17. Red1! $146 { Novelty! } (17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. d5 exd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Nxd5 Bf8 { Kopinits, Anna Christina - Makka, Ioulia, 1/2-1/2, Baska (Women), 2009, https://lichess.org/H9fTa8Qu }) 17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 { And White has no IQP anymore. } 18... Qc8 $14 { Step out of the pin. White is a bit better here: more space, control over the open files, and a centralized queen. }) 17. Nxc6 Nxc6 18. Rcd1 Bf6 $146 { Novelty! } 19. Nb5 Re7 $10 { The position is still equal, but not drawish! } { [%cal Ge7d7,Gd8b6,Rb5d6,Rf4e5] }) (11. Qe2 Ndb4 (11... Nf6) (11... Bf6?!)) 11... Nf6 (11... Ndb4 12. Bxh7+ Kh8 13. Qb1 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4) 12. Ne4 h6 (12... Nd5) 13. Rad1 Bd7 14. a3 (14. Nxf6+ Bxf6) 14... Rc8 *


