1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 { [%csl Be7][%cal Bc8g4] } 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } 6... Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Be2 { [%cal Re2f3,Rf3d5] } 8... Nbd7 { Starting position for this chapter. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5] } (8... Na6 { See See ➡ Fianchetto Defense 1b } { [%cal Ga6c7,Bc7d5] }) 9. Bf3 { [%cal Rf3d5] } 9... Nb6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gb6d5,Gd8d5,Rf3d5,Rc3d5,Rb3d5] } 10. Nge2 { [%cal Re2f4,Rf4d5] } 10... Bg4 { Remove the first defender. } 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 { But now also Black is "down" one attacker on d5. Temporarily. The knight should go back to f6 on the next move. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Re2d4] } 12. a4 { is the main move. } { [%cal Ga4a5] } (12. O-O { Maybe the most pragmatic option for White. } 12... Nf6 { Attack d5. This doesn't allow White to play Bf4. } { [%cal Gf6d5,Gd8d5,Gb6d5] } (12... Qd7 { is equally good. It mobilizes the knight on b6 by protecting b7. } { [%csl Bb6][%cal Gd7b7] } 13. Bf4 { main move here. } 13... Nf6 14. d6 exd6 15. Rfe1 { Step on the open file, protect the knight. A good prophylactic move. } (15. Nb5?! { Main move. But it forces Black to improve their position. } { [%cal Rb5d6,Rf4d6] } 15... d5! $15 { Black is already more than fine. } { [%cal Gf8e8] }) 15... Rfe8 16. a4 d5! $146 (16... Qe6 { is also good. } 17. Qxe6 Rxe6 18. Be3 { Free f4 for the knight } { [%cal Re2f4] } (18. Nb5?! { De la Riva Aguado, Oscar - Gonzalez Custodio, Rafael, 1/2-1/2, ESP-ch, 1996, https://lichess.org/AOKWQeiD }) 18... Nbd5 { Covers f4. } { [%cal Gd5f4] } 19. Nf4 { anyway } 19... Nxf4 20. Bxf4 d5 $10 { Equal. }) 17. Qb5 { Black should not take the queen and let White's knight enter their side with pressure on a7. } { [%cal Rc3b5,Bb5a7] } 17... Rad8 $10 { Completely equal. }) 13. Nf4 { Defend d5. } 13... Qd7 14. Re1 (14. Be3 { It's not very pressing, but it does allow the a1 rook to come into the game. } { [%csl Ba1] } 14... Rfd8 15. Rac1 { And now Black should take the pawn back: } 15... Nfxd5 { After all the exchanges, the position is dead equal and it will probably end in a draw. } 16. Ncxd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Rxd5 19. Rc7 Bxd4 $146 20. Rxe7 (20. Bxd4 Rxd4 21. Rxb7 Rd2 $10) 20... b6 $10) (14. d6?! Qxd6 $15 { The queen takes with a tempo on d4, so this is bad for White. } { [%cal Gd6d4] }) 14... Rfd8 15. h3 (15. d6 e6 { stop the second pawn! })) (12. Bf4 Nf6 13. d6 exd6 14. O-O { The main move here is Nh5, but Qd7 and Re8 are superior in my opinion. } 14... Qd7 { This is the only move that keeps complete equality. } (14... Re8 15. a4 { The most active move. } { [%cal Ra4a5] } 15... Qd7 { protect b7. } 16. a5 Nc8 { keeps the tension for a while. But that's a rather sad square for the knight. } (16... Nbd5 { Get some pieces off the board. } 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 (17... Rxe2 $146 18. Nc3 { [%cal Rc3e2] } 18... Ree8 19. Ra4 { [%cal Ra4b4,Rb4b7] } 19... h6 { Prepare Re7 by preventing a pin on the knight. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Bf4g5] } 20. Rb4 { [%cal Rb4b7] } 20... Re7 $14 { White has the initiative here, and Black's pieces don't have many options. } { [%cal Gg6g5] }) 18. Qxd5 Rxe2 19. b4 Re6 $14 { Almost equal. White's pawns are more advanced which can become dangerous. }) 17. Ng3 { steps out of the view of the rook on e8. Now the other knight can move. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Ge8e2] } 17... Ne7 $146 { Get the knight back into play. } 18. d5! h5 $10 { Equal, but probably easier to play for White for due to the space advantage. }) (14... Nh5?! { h5 is just not a good square for the knight. } 15. Be3 d5 16. Rad1 Qd7 { The only move that has been played in this position. 3 games. } (16... Rc8 $146 { Occupy the open file. } 17. Rfe1 Re8 $10) 17. Rfe1 $146 (17. Nf4?! { was the follow-up in all three games. Dubious, this is helping Black to do something useful with the misplaced knight. } 17... Nxf4 18. Bxf4 Rfe8 19. h3 { Make some luft, and create a retreat square for the bishop. } { [%cal Bf4h2] } 19... Nc4 { Prepare queenside pawn pushes. } { [%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] } (19... Re6?! { Langer, Mikhail - Pruess, David, 1-0, USA-ch, 2007, https://lichess.org/Kz820ztK }) 20. Qc2 Rac8 $10 { Very equal, maybe a bit better for Black because their rooks are on better squares. } { [%cal Ge8e2,Gc8c2] }) 17... Rfe8 18. Qb5 Qd6 $10) 15. Rfe1 Rfe8 16. h3 { Retreat square for the bishop. } { [%cal Rf4h2] } (16. Rad1 { Solleveld, Maarten - Dyce, Andrew, 1-0, ECI op U18 25th, 1998, https://lichess.org/7TYZbe7w }) 16... Rac8 $146 (16... Re6?! { Wall, Tim - Arkell, Keith C, 1/2-1/2, Oxford GM-B, 1998, https://lichess.org/mTmuo9Nj }) 17. Nb5 { [%cal Rb5a7,Rb5d6] } 17... Nbd5! { And now White can't take anything. } 18. Bh2 (18. Nxa7? Rxe2! 19. Rxe2 Nxf4 20. Re3 Rb8 $17) (18. Bxd6? a6 19. Na7 Ra8 20. Be5 Rxa7 $17) 18... Rc6! 19. Nec3 (19. Nxa7? Rb6 20. Qd3 Ra8 $19 { And the knight is trapped. } { [%cal Gb6b2] }) 19... Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Rb6 { [%cal Ga7a6] } 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Qxd5 Rxb5 23. Qxd6 Qxd6 24. Bxd6 Bxd4 $10 { Completely equal and very likely a draw. }) 12... Nf6 13. Nf4 (13. a5?! { Judith Polgar played this first in 1988 against Keith Arkell. And she won.
White can win a pawn here, but that gives Black a good initiative. } 13... Nbxd5 14. Qxb7 e6! { has been played only once. The engine likes it, and it does make sense: with the light-squared off, Black doesn't need this diagonal open anymore, and pawns are best protected by pawns – the e-pawn is safer on e6. } (14... Qd6 { Main move in this position. } { [%cal Gf8b8] } 15. Qb3 Rab8 16. Qd1 Rfc8 { Take the second open file. } { [%cal Gd5c3,Gf6d5,Gc8c3] } (16... Qa6 $146 { Engine suggestion. The idea is to get the queen off the d-file to play Rfd8 and e5! } 17. O-O Rfd8 { [%cal Gd8d1] } 18. Re1 e5 19. Nxd5 Rxd5 20. Nc3 Rxd4 21. Qf3 Rbd8 22. Be3 e4! { Push the queen away. } 23. Qe2 Rd3 $13 { This is technically equal, but very sharp. } { [%cal Re3a7,Re2a6,Ga6c6,Bc6e4,Gf6d5] }) 17. O-O { White would like to play Qd3 next to get the rook to d1 and protect the pawn from behind. } 17... Qa6 { prevents that. } 18. Qd2 { The downside for White is that the queen is blocking the dark-squared bishop now. } { [%csl Bc1] }) 15. O-O Qd6 $146 { This is a novelty in this position, but a motif we can see in other lines too. Black played the rather dubious Qc7 in Sofyia Krasnokutskaya - Dominika Tomcikova, World Youth U16 Olympiad 2016.
White should now retreat the queen before it gets trapped with Rb8. } { [%cal Gf8b8] } 16. Qb3 { Black could now put rooks on the open files … or make a one-move threat to misplace White's knight! } 16... Ng4! { White has only g3 or Ng3 here, and opening the pawns in front of the king is probably not a good idea, so } { [%cal Gg4h2,Gd6h2] } 17. Ng3 { is the best move. } { [%cal Gg7d4] } 17... Rab8 { time to claim some space. } 18. Qd1 { [%cal Rd1g4] } 18... Ngf6 $15 { This is a very nice position for Black: the pieces are active, the semi-open c-file can be taken next, and it is difficult for White to activate their pieces. } { [%cal Gf8c8,Gc8c3,Gd5b4,Gd5c3,Rd1d3,Rh2h3,Bb8b2,Bc1b2] }) 13... a5 14. O-O Qd6 15. Nb5 Qd7 16. d6 { White can't keep the d-pawn anyway, so pushing it makes it slightly mor uncomfortable for Black to take it. } 16... exd6 17. Be3 Rfc8 $14 { Material is equal here, but White has a bit more space. One plan for Black: play d5, and use that as an anchor for the knights. IQP versus IQP. } { [%cal Gd6d5,Gb6c4,Gf6e4,Bd5c4,Bd5e4] } *


