[UTCTime "10:32:15"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 { [%csl Be7][%cal Bc8g4] } 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } 6... Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Be2 { Starting position for this chapter. } { [%cal Re2f3,Rf3d5] } 8... Na6?! { with the idea of Nc7. White has a rather obvious counter.
I marked this move as dubious, because Black's gets an uncomfortable position by force. Doubled b-pawns, a light-squared bishop that can't move, and most important: None of the "usual" motifs of the Fianchetto Defense work here, you have to learn the whole line from scratch. } { [%cal Ga6c7,Bc7d5] } (8... Nbd7 { See ➡ Fianchetto Defense 1a } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5] }) 9. Bf3 { threatening to push the d-pawn with a tempo on b7. } { [%cal Rf3b7,Rb3b7] } 9... Qb6 { can prevent that, but that leads to an uncomfortable position. Black's dark-squared can't move for a while. } 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Nge2 Nb4 { [%cal Gb4d5,Gf6d5,Gb4c2] } 12. O-O Rd8 13. d6 Rxd6 14. Bf4 { The problem here is: Rd8 invites Bc7, and then b7 is lost. Rd7 blocks the dark-squared bishop. } 14... Rd7 (14... Rd8 15. Bc7 Rd7 16. Bxb6 Nfd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Rxd5 $14 { This is playable, but it's hard for Black to win another pawn. } { Afromeev, Vladimir - Biriukov, Ilja, 1-0, Tula Stek Cup, 2004, https://lichess.org/tiLQQcZQ }) 15. Rfd1 (15. Be5) 15... Nfd5 16. Bg3 { Main move. } (16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Be5 Ra5 $146 { Novelty. The idea is to play Nb4 after Bxe5 dxe5, and attack both pawns on e5 and a2 simultaneously. This is why White should play } { [%csl Ba2,Be5][%cal Gd5b4,Bb4a2,Ba5e5] } (17... Bxe5 18. dxe5 Nb4 19. Rxd7 Bxd7 20. Bxb7 Rxa2 21. Rxa2 Nxa2 $10 { Afromeev, Vladimir - Kulikov, Oleg, 1/2-1/2, RUS-ch sf, 2003, https://lichess.org/yHXiwl35 } { As equal as it gets. }) 18. a3 { Stops Nb4 and keeps the a-pawn safe. White's next ideas are Rc8, attacking the sad light-squared bishop on c8, and Nf4 to put pressure on the pinned knight on d5. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Ra1c1,Re2f4,Bf3b7] } 18... Rd8 { [%cal Gd8c8] } 19. Bxd5 (19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Rac1 Be6 $10 { Equal, but there is still some tension. }) 19... Raxd5 20. Nc3 R5d7 { White has to exchange the other bishop now, otherwise Black plays f6 and wins the second d-pawn. } 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. d5 { Black's most pragmatic option here is probably e6. This forces a sequence of exchanges. } 22... e6 23. dxe6 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 25. Nxd1 Bxe6 $10 { Equal. White might have a slight edge due to Black's doubled b-pawns, but it shouldn't be enough for a win. }) 16... Nxc3 17. bxc3 Nc6 18. Nf4 { [%cal Rf4d5] } 18... Ra5 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ga5d5] } 19. Nd3 Ra3 { [%cal Ga3c3] } 20. Rac1 { [%cal Rc1c2] } (20. Rdc1 b5! $146 { Black's chance to resolve the doubled b-pawns. } (20... Na5 { is also playable. } { [%cal Ga5c4] } 21. Rc2 $146 (21. Rab1 Nc4 22. Rb4 Nd2 23. Rxb6 Nxf3+ 24. gxf3 Rxa2 $10 { Gelfand, Boris - Morozevich, Alexander, 0-1, Amber-blindfold 11th, 2002, https://lichess.org/HYUIZWje }) 21... Nc4 22. Re1 { threatening Bg4, and after Rd8 the e-pawn is lost. } { [%cal Rf3g4,Re1e7,Bg4d7] } 22... h5 { [%cal Gh5g4] } (22... Bf6 { is also possible. }) 23. Nb4 { [%cal Rb4d5] } 23... Ra5 $10 { This is equal, maybe a bit easier to play for White. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ga5d5,Gd7d5] }) 21. Nc5 { [%cal Rc5d7] } 21... Rd8 { [%cal Gb5b4] } 22. Rab1 b4 { anyway. } (22... Rxa2? 23. Rxb5 { [%cal Rc5b7,Rb5b7] } 23... Ra7 24. Bc7 Re8 { Now Black's pieces are frozen defending the b-pawn. }) 23. Bc7 Rf8 24. Bxc6 bxc6 25. Rxb4 Rxa2 26. Bf4 Bf5 $10) 20... Rxa2 21. Ra1 Ra5 22. Rdb1 { And here Black has the cute move } 22... Nxd4! $146 { This piece is worth three pawns. } (22... Rxa1 23. Rxa1 Na5 24. Rb1 Nc4 25. Bf4 { Isaev, Jamshed - Burmakin, Vladimir, 0-1, Dubai op 15th, 2013, https://lichess.org/rVAQ0crl } 25... Rd8 $10 { Equal, but probably easier to play for White. The doubled b-pawns are a liability. } { [%csl Bb6,Bb7] }) 23. cxd4 Rxd4 24. Ne5 (24. Rxa5?! bxa5 25. Nf4 h5 { Make some luft. } 26. h4 a4 27. Rb5 { Trying to get behind the a-pawn. } 27... e5 28. Nh3 (28. Ne2 Rd1+ 29. Kh2 a3 30. Ra5 f5 { [%cal Ge5e4] } 31. Ra8 a2! 32. Rxa2 Rd8 33. Ra8 e4 34. Bxh5 gxh5 $10 { Equal, but still very sharp. }) 28... e4 29. Be2 a3 30. Ra5 Rd2 31. Bc4 b5! 32. Bb3 Bxh3 { Avoid all pins on the h-rank. } 33. Ra8+ Bf8 { leads to a forced draw: } (33... Kh7 34. gxh3 Bd4 { [%cal Gd4f2,Gd2f2] } 35. Bxf7 { [%cal Rf7g8,Rg3f4,Rf4h6] } 35... Kg7 36. Be6 b4 37. Ra4 Rb2 $10 { This is technically equal. Black's pawns can't promote as long as White's light-squared bishop stays on the a2-g8 diagonal. }) 34. gxh3 Rd3 35. Bc2 Rd2 { Black's rook can't leave the d-file because Bd6 is a serious threat. } { [%cal Rg3d6] } 36. Bb3 $10 { Move repetition. Draw. }) 24... f5 25. Rxa5 bxa5 26. Rd1 (26. Bxb7?? { Not possible! } 26... Bxb7 27. Rxb7 Rd1#) 26... Rxd1+ 27. Bxd1 Be6 (27... b5? 28. Nc6! { [%cal Rc6a5,Rc6e7] }) 28. Ba4 g5 { [%cal Gf5f4] } 29. f4 Bf6 (29... h6 30. h4 Bf6 31. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3h4,Rf3g5] } 31... gxf4 32. Bxf4 Bc4 $10 { Stockfish thinks White is a bit better here. But White has only two pawns left, and unless Black blunders a piece, both pawns can't promote. This should be a draw. }) 30. Be1 { [%cal Re1a5,Rg2g3] } 30... gxf4 31. Nf3 Bc4 32. Bxa5 e6 $14 { Black's only task here is not to let White promote one of the remaining two pawns. This should be possible. } *


