1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } 6... Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Nge2 { The second most common move. The idea here is to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 8... Na6 { Starting position for this chapter. Na6 is one of the main moves here. The idea is Nc7 or Nb4 from where Black can go for White's first d-pawn. } { [%cal Ga6c7,Bc7d5] } 9. g3 b5! { My recommendation. } (9... Qb6 { Trading off the queens isn't a bad idea against the IQP. } 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Bg2 Nb4 { [%cal Gb4d5,Gf6d5] } 12. O-O Rd8 { And now it's clear that White cannot hold d5. Pushing it forces Black to take with the rook, so they cannot centralize a knight. } { [%cal Gf6d5,Gd8d5,Gb4d5,Rc3d5,Rg2d5] } 13. d6 Rxd6 14. Bf4 Rd7 { Black has a very sad light-squared bishop now. } { [%csl Bc8] } 15. Be5 (15. Rfd1 Nfd5 { [%cal Gd5f4,Gd5c3,Gg7d4] } 16. Be5 { There is a lot of pressure in the position now. Time to resolve some. } { [%cal Re5g7,Rc3d5,Rg2d5,Bd5b7,Gd5c3] } (16. Bd2 Rd8 17. a3 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Nc6 19. Bf4 Bg4 20. f3 Be6 $10 { Kobalia, Mihail - Kamsky, Gata, 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Blitz 2013, https://lichess.org/rsBvWc94 }) 16... Nxc3 $146 (16... f6?! { too early } 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bf4 { Genova, Ly - Zimina, O., 1/2-1/2, 43rd TCh-GRE 2015, https://lichess.org/moola1Ne }) 17. Nxc3 Nc2! { [%cal Gc2d4,Gc2a1,Gg7d4] } 18. Rab1 f6 { Now this is a move. } 19. Bf4 Nxd4 20. Bd5+ { Breaks the rook's protection of the knight. } { [%cal Rc3d5] } 20... e6 21. Rxd4 exd5 22. Nxd5 { [%cal Rd5b6] } 22... Ra5 { [%cal Gd7d4] } 23. Rc4 { [%cal Rc4c8] } 23... Raxd5 24. Rxc8+ Kf7 $10 { This is equal. It's probably a tiny bit harder to play for Black due to the doubled b-pawns and the currently blocked bishop. }) 15... Nbd5 { Hamdouchi, Hicham - Kasparov, Sergey, 1/2-1/2, Sort op 3rd, 2007, https://lichess.org/fMGaAQKZ } { Bauer, Christian - Arkell, Keith C, 1/2-1/2, Wrexham, 2002, https://lichess.org/dZNmdfZN } { White has bit more space here and a better pawn structure. Besides that, the position equal. }) 10. Bg2 (10. Nxb5?! { hands the initiative over to Black. } 10... Nxd5 11. Bg2 Be6 12. Qd1 Nab4 $146 { Bring the knight to a better position. } (12... Qa5+?! 13. Nbc3 Nxc3?! 14. bxc3 { Adams, Michael - Granda Zuniga, Julio E, 1-0, Madrid Magistral 7th, 1998, https://lichess.org/CtuVttjB }) 13. O-O Qd7 { Connect the rooks and add protection for a7. Also push the knight away. } { [%cal Gd7a7,Gd7b5] } 14. Nbc3 Rac8 $10 { Equal and maybe a bit easier to play for Black due to the more active pieces. White should try to develop their queenside now, Black should play against the isolated d-pawn. } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Gf8d8,Gd8d4,Rc1g5] }) 10... b4 { Not so easy to find a good square for this knight. } 11. Nd1 { is the main move. Black's best option here is to offer the b-pawn and take d5 with tempo: } (11. Na4 Bb7 12. Nf4 { Not so easy to decide what is the best move now. The engine recommends Qa5 or g5; Qd6 has been tried in the past. } { [%cal Rf4d5,Rb3d5,Rg2d5,Gf6d5,Gd8d5,Gb7d5] } 12... Qa5! $146 { With the idea to clear d8 for a rook to add more pressure on d5. } { [%cal Gf8d8] } (12... g5 { Pushes the knight away, but this g-pawn will fall. } 13. Ne2 Bxd5 14. Bxd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxg5 Rfc8 { [%cal Gc8c4] } 17. Rc1 $146 { [%cal Rg5c1] } (17. Kd2?! { Geller, Jakov - Kravtsov, Sergey, 1-0, RUS-chT2 17th, 2010, https://lichess.org/DSjfxoNE }) 17... Rxc1+ 18. Bxc1 Rd8 $14 { White has an extra pawn and is slightly better here. }) (12... Qd6?! { This does prevent d6, a common motif for White when the first d-pawn is lost anyway. } { [%cal Ga6c7,Bc7d5,Gf8d8,Rd5d6] } 13. O-O Nc7?! $146 (13... Rfd8?! $146 14. Be3 Nxd5 15. Nc5! { [%cal Rc5b7] } 15... Nxc5 16. dxc5 Qe5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxb4 $14 { White is just a pawn up here, and Black has no compensation. }) 14. Nc5 { Interrupt the connection between queen and b4. } { [%cal Rb3b4,Rc5b7] } 14... Bxd5 15. Nxd5 Nfxd5 { [%cal Gg7d4] } 16. Be3 e6 { Black's light-squared bishop is gone, so e6 can be played finally. } 17. Rac1 { [%cal Rg2a8] } 17... Rab8 $10 { This is equal, with an edge for White. The following play will probably focus on the open c-file and White's d-pawn. } { [%csl Rb7,Bd5][%cal Rc5b7,Gb8b4,Yc8c1,Yc1c8,Gf8c8] }) 13. O-O Rfd8 14. Re1 { [%cal Re1e7] } 14... Nxd5 { [%cal Gg7d4] } 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Qxd5 Rxd5 18. Rxe7 Bxd4 19. Bh6 Nc5 { [%cal Gc5a4] } 20. Nxc5 Bxc5 $10 { Equal. } { [%cal Gc5f8,Gc5b6] }) (11. Ne4 $146 { has never been played, mostly because it allows the immediate } 11... Nxd5 { but that pawn was to fall anyway. } 12. O-O { White can now pin and attack the knight on d5. Black can either counter-attack or protect d5. } { [%cal Rg2a8] } 12... Bg4 { [%cal Gg4e2] } 13. Re1 Nac7 14. Nc5 { [%cal Rb3d5,Rg2d5,Rc5b7,Rc1d2,Bd2b4] } 14... Rc8 { Unpins the knight. } 15. Nd3 Be6 $13 { Technically equal, but the position is very sharp. } { [%cal Gb3a4] }) 11... Nc7 { [%cal Gf6d5,Bd5b4,Rb3b4] } 12. Ne3 { [%cal Re3d5,Rb3d5,Rg2d5,Gf6d5,Gc7d5,Gd8d5] } (12. Qxb4?! $146 { Black can make many moves with tempo now. } 12... Nfxd5 { [%cal Gd5b4,Gg7d4] } 13. Qd2 Bb7 14. O-O Qc8 { Free the d8 square for the rook and protect the light-squared bishop. } { [%cal Gf8d8,Gc8b7] } 15. Ndc3 { And White does the same on their side. } 15... Rd8 { The question for White is now: Being a pawn up, should they trade material (Nxd5) and hope for a better endgame? Or develop pieces first (Rd1)? } 16. Nxd5 (16. Rd1 Nb4 { A trade of light-squared bishops would be in Black's favor, because White would have weak light squares on the kingside then. } { [%cal Gb7g2,Gb4c2,Gc8c2] } 17. Ne4 { prevents that trade for now. } 17... Rb8 { develops the last piece and adds further protection for the bishop. Now the queen can move away if needed. } 18. b3 { b2 is probably the best way to develop White's dark-squared bishop. } { [%cal Rc1b2,Rb2d4] } 18... Qf5! { [%cal Gf5e4,Gb7e4] } 19. Qxb4 Bxe4 { [%cal Gb8b4,Ge4g2] } 20. Qc4 (20. Bxe4 Qxe4 21. Qc4 Rbc8 { [%cal Gc8c4,Ge4e2] } 22. Be3 { Protect the knight by blockading Black's queen. } { [%cal Ge4e2] } 22... Nd5 23. Qd3 Qxd3 24. Rxd3 Rc2 $10 { Technically equal, but Black is pressing here. }) 20... Bxg2 21. Kxg2 { [%cal Rc4c7] } 21... Ne6 { [%cal Ge6d4,Gg7d4,Gd8d4,Re2d4,Rd1d4,Rc4d4] } 22. Be3 Qe4+ 23. Kg1 Rbc8 24. Qd3 Qb7 $10 { Equal. Black has the option Nc5 now, because White's d-pawn is pinned to the queen. } { [%cal Ge6c5,Gd8d3,Bc5e4,Bb7e4] } (24... Qxd3?! 25. Rxd3 Rc2 $14 { Not as good as in the 20.Bxe4 line, because Black's knight is in a slightly worse position. } { [%csl Rf4,Rc5,Rg5] })) 16... Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. b3 Rd7 19. Bb2 Qb7 $10 { Equal, maybe a bit better for Black due to the light square weakness on White's kingside. } { [%csl Bh3,Bf3][%cal Ga8d8] }) 12... Ba6! $146 { Tricky move. White can't castle now, and if they take the knight away, the bishop does still prevent castling! } { [%cal Ga6e2,Be2f1] } (12... a5?! 13. O-O { Kislinsky, Alexey - Tukhaev, Adam, 1/2-1/2, UKR-ch, 2010, https://lichess.org/iRiZgUba }) 13. Nf4 Rb8 { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gb8b4] } 14. Nd3 { Interrupts the light-squared bishop's view. } { [%cal Ga6f1] } 14... Bb7 { White can play Nf4 again and offer a draw indirectly by move repetition here. Let's not do that. } { [%cal Bd3f4,Bb7a6] } 15. O-O Nfxd5 { This is now rather comfortable for Black. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd5b4] } 16. Rd1 e6 $15 { Black has a very harmonious position and is not in a hurry to resolve the tension. White still needs to complete development somehow. } *


