1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } 6... Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Nge2 { The second most common move. The idea here is to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 8... e6?! { is a dubious little gambit that has been tried a few times. } 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Qxb7 Nbd7 { The point is that this opens the e-file, before White can fianchetto and castle. } { [%cal Ge8e1] } 11. Nf4 { [%cal Rf4e6] } 11... Bf5 { But White hasn't committed to g3, so } { [%cal Gf8e8] } (11... Ng4 $146 { could be a try here. Novelty. } { [%cal Gg7d4] } 12. Be2 Bxd4 { Black regains at least one pawn. } { [%cal Gg4f2,Gd4f2] } 13. O-O Qh4 { [%cal Gg4h2,Gh4h2] } 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 $14 { This looks dangerous, but Black doesn't really have anything here. White is better. Not a whole pawn value better, but still … better. } { [%csl Bg2][%cal Bb7g2] }) 12. Be2 { is still possible, and } 12... Re8 { comes too late. } 13. O-O $14 { White is just a pawn up here. } *


