1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } 6... Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Nge2 Nbd7 { Starting position for this chapter. This is one of the main moves, and Black wants to watch d5 via Nb6, a common motif in all fianchetto lines. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Bb6d5] } 9. g3 (9. Nf4?! { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 4b }) 9... Nb6 10. Bg2 Bf5! { This is why Black doesn't play e6! The threat is Bd3. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gf5d3,Bd3c4,Bc4b3,Bd3e2] } 11. O-O (11. Nf4?! { prevents that. But I don't think this is a good line for White. } 11... Rc8 (11... Qd7 { Main move. The queen protects b7, so the knight can move, and the rooks are connected – development completed. White is still a bit behind in that regard. This is Black's compensation for the pawn.
Black's plan is now to push the knight away from f4 per g5 and h6. And that's why White often plays h4 here. h3 is also possible. Even a4, because a5 would remove one of Black's attackers. } { [%cal Gd7b7,Rb3b7,Gh7h6,Gg6g5,Ra2a4,Rh2h3,Rh3h4,Rg3g4] } 12. h4 { Five different moves have been played here. But Stockfish's recommendation is a novelty: } (12. h3 $146 Rac8 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gb6c4] } 13. g4 { And now we go into some exchanges: } 13... g5 14. gxf5 gxf4 15. Bxf4 Qxf5 16. Bg3 Nc4 { [%csl Gd2][%cal Rb3b7,Gc4d2] } 17. Rd1 (17. O-O?! Nd2 { [%cal Gd2b3,Gd2f1] } 18. Qxb7 Nxf1 19. Rxf1 Nh5 $10) (17. Qxb7?! Nh5 { [%cal Gh5g3,Gg7d4] } 18. O-O Bxd4 19. Ne2 Bxb2 $10) 17... Nh5 { [%cal Gh5g3] } 18. Be4 Qf6 19. Bh2 Kh8 $10 { [%cal Rh1g1,Rg1g8] }) (12. a4 { Threatening the knight. } { [%cal Ra4a5] } 12... Rac8 { creates an escape square. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc8c4] } 13. a5 Nc4 14. O-O { and here comes the g5-h6 maneuver. } 14... g5 15. Nfe2 h6 { The engine says, White should go for a queen trade. Let's see. } 16. Qb5 $146 (16. Re1 { is the only move that has been played here so far. Both games continued with the very slow Rfd8. But Black should probaly play Nd6 first to prevent the queen exchange on b5. } 16... Nd6 $146 { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gd6b5] } (16... Rfd8 { Shadrina, Tatiana - Turov, Maxim, 1-0, RUS-Cup, 2000, https://lichess.org/Jpda6ltF } { Midoux, Sebastien - Petrosian, Suren, 0-1, Lyon Rhone op, 2003, https://lichess.org/F5vktqhd }) 17. Qa4 { White can still try. Now Rfd8 makes sense. } 17... Rfd8 18. Qxd7 Rxd7 $10 { This is of course equal. }) 16... Qxb5 17. Nxb5 a6 18. Nbc3 $13 { The engine says it's equal, it's unclear for me. White is still a pawn up, although these doubled d-pawns will probably not stay forever. White might try to open the kingside with h4. Black should attack in the center and defend the kingside. }) (12. O-O?! g5 13. Nfe2 h6 { White could just stop fighting for the first d-pawn here and give it with usual d6. Or keep the tension for a while with a4. } 14. d6 { This is probably the most practical decision. } (14. a4 Rfd8) 14... Qxd6 $146 { Again, the most obvious move is a novelty. } (14... exd6?! { Why would Black damage their own pawn structure? } { Tuomala, Timo - Salo, Tapio, 1/2-1/2, FIN-chT2 0506, 2005, https://lichess.org/cD4hnjKe }) 15. Rd1 Rfd8 { transposes back into a known position. } 16. d5 $146 (16. Bxb7?! { This is too greedy. } 16... Rab8 { gives Black two nice tempi. } 17. Bg2 Nbd5 { [%cal Gb8b3] } 18. Qa4 { [%cal Ra4a7] } 18... Qe6! $146 { This is a very aggressive line suggested by Stockfish. I'm not sure if Black can afford to give another pawn for that. I give the complete line just for entertainment. This will probably never happen. } { [%csl Bf3][%cal Gf5g4,Gg4d1,Bf2f3] } (18... Qc7 $146 { is the safe line and probably easier to play than the weird pawn storm on the kingside. } { [%cal Gc7a7] } 19. h3 $15 { Black is a tiny bit better here due to the better development. e6 can follow now, fixing the structure in the center, or Bd7, attacking the queen, and even the rather aggressive Nb4.
White should find a way to develop the queenside, maybe even at the cost of b2. } { [%cal Ge7e6,Gf5d7,Gd5b4] }) (18... Nb4?! { a simple on-move threat. } { [%cal Gf5c2] } 19. Qa5 Bc2?! 20. Rd2 Bg6 { Potkin, Vladimir - Turov, Maxim, 1-0, RUS Cup Qualifier 5, 2004, https://lichess.org/Pt8rmfiu }) 19. Qxa7 Bg4 20. Rd2 h5 21. Qc5 h4 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Qc2 h3 24. Bh1 Rd6 25. a4 f5 26. Qc4 f4 { [%cal Gf4f3] } 27. gxf4 Nxf4 28. d5 Bxe2 { [%cal Ge2c4] } 29. Qxf4 gxf4 30. dxe6 Rxd2 31. Bxd2 f3 { White has no good move here. } { [%cal Gb8b4,Gb4g4,Gb8b2,Gg7b2] } 32. Bxf3 (32. Rb1 Kh7 { [%cal Gb8g8,Gg8g2] } 33. Bf4 Rb4 34. Bg3 Bxb2 35. a5 Ra4 { [%cal Ga4a1] } 36. Bc7 Rg4+ 37. Bg3 Ra4 38. Bc7 Kg6 $19 { [%cal Gg6e6] }) (32. Bg5 Bxb2 33. Rb1 Rb4 $19 { [%cal Gb4g4,Gb4a4,Ga4a1] }) 32... Bxf3 $17) 16... Rdc8 17. Nd4 Bg4 18. Re1 Qd7 $10 { Equal with a tiny advantage for Black due to White's underdeveloped queenside. } { [%csl Bc1,Ba1] }) 12... Rfc8 $146 { Preparing the typical Nc4 move. } { [%cal Gb6c4] } (12... Rac8 { Main move and playable. } 13. O-O Nc4 14. Rd1 $146 { [%csl Bd4][%cal Rd1d4] } (14. a4 a5?! { Some dubious moves in } { Chekhov, Sergey - Rodin, Dmitrij, 0-1, Voronezh op-A, 2008, https://lichess.org/nSgOZ02U }) 14... Ng4 $14) 13. O-O Ne8 $10 { is possible now because Black played Rfc8, not Rac8. This is a very equal position. } { [%csl Bc8][%cal Ge8d6,Gg7d4] }) 12. h3 Qd7 13. g4 g5 14. gxf5 gxf4 15. Bxf4 Qxf5 16. Bg3 Nh5 17. Be4 Qg5 18. Bh2 { [%cal Rh1g1,Rg1g8] } 18... Kh8 $10 { White is a pawn up, but the pawn islands are hard to defend, and Black has multiple threats. This is technically equal, but surely easier to play for Black } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gb6c4,Bc4d2,Bg5d2] }) 11... Bd3 { It is important to get this in before White can play Rd8. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gd3c4] } (11... Qd7?! { Main move. I think is not accurate. Black should take the opportunity to play Bd3 instead. } 12. Rd1 { Protects d4, stops Bd3.
What Black wants to take d5, preferably per Nfxd5, or at least per Nbxd5. But both moves aren't possible, and there is no time to create that opportunity.
If White plays d6, Black wants to capture that pawn with a knight and without dropping b7. Again, this is very difficult, because White will not just sit and wait. a5, Nf4, and maybe Bg5 are incoming.
This isn't really a pressing move, so Black has time for } { [%csl Bd6,Rd3][%cal Rd1d4,Gg7d4,Rg2b7,Rb3b7,Gf6e8,Ge8d6] } (12. a4?! Rad8 $146 { Now a5 can be answered with Nxd5. White can now either give the pawn with e6 or hold on for a few moves with Nf4. Re1 is also possible to put some pressure on the e-pawn. } (12... Bd3 { [%cal Gd3c4,Bc4b3] } 13. a5 (13. d6 { The idea is to either misplace the queen, so it doesn't protect b7 anymore, or to damage Black's pawn structure with exd6. } { [%csl Bb7][%cal Rb3b7,Ra4a5,Ge7d6] } 13... Qxd6 $146 { is the better option for Black. } (13... exd6?! { is at least an inaccuracy if not a mistake. Played once in Liberzon - Gurgenidze, 1968. Gurgenidze lost the game. } 14. a5! { The knight has no good square. Nc4 and Qd1 is just terrible. } { [%cal Yb6c4,Yb3d1,Bd1d3] } 14... Bc4 15. Qb4 Bxe2 16. Nxe2 Nbd5 17. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Rg2d5] } 17... Rfe8 { [%cal Ge8e2] } 18. Nc3 { Now Black is forced to repair White's pawn structure. } 18... Nxc3 19. bxc3 $14) 14. Nb5 (14. a5?! { is less effective here, because Black's queen covers b4. } 14... Bc4 { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gd6b4] } 15. Qa3 Qxa3 16. Rxa3 Nbd5 $10 { [%cal Gc4e2,Gd5c3] }) 14... Bxb5 15. Qxb5 Nbd5 $10 { The difference to the exd6 line is that the queen protects the knight on d5. }) 13... Bc4! $146 { Zwischenzug. The point is that the queen, once moved away, doesn't protect d5 anymore. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Rb3d5] } (13... Bxe2?! { Too early. } 14. Nxe2 Nbxd5 { The difference to the Bc4 line is that White has an extra tempo here, because the queen is still on b3 and Nbxd5 didn't come with a tempo. } 15. Nf4 e6) 14. Qb4 Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Nbxd5 { with a tempo on the queen. } { [%cal Gd5b4] } 16. Qb3 { The light-squared bishop is gone, we can play e6 now. } 16... e6 $10 { Completely equal. White has the bishop pair, Black a better pawn structure and piece development. }) 13. Re1 (13. Nf4 { provoking the usual } 13... g5 { and a counterattack with } 14. a5 Nc8 15. Nfe2 h6 $10 { This is very equal. It's hard to recommend a move for White here. d6 doesn't work, because Black has Nxd6. But White has most of the other moves we can see in the 13.Re1 line, plus maybe f4.
Black should get the knight off the 8th rank to d6. Bh3 is also an idea, and b6 could help simplifying the situation on the queenside. } { [%cal Gf5h3,Gc8d6,Gb7b6] }) (13. d6 Qxd6 { Black has to take immediately; Be6 is not good. And now comes the maneuver we have seen in the line after 13.Re1 Rfe8 14.d6 Qxd6: } (13... Be6 { The zwischenzug is less attractive here, because there is no rook on e8: } 14. d5 Nfxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd6 16. Bf4 Bxd5 17. Bxd6 Bxb3 18. Bxe7 { Compare this to the situation after 13.Re1 Rfe8 14.d6 Be6. White could not go into the trades there, because their dark-squared would just be taken at the end. } { [%csl Be8] }) 14. Nb5 Qd7 15. Nxa7 Nbd5 16. Nb5) 13... Rfe8 14. d6 (14. a5 Nbxd5 15. Nf4 { This is a bit uncomfortable for Black: Either the knight has to move (Nxc3 or Nxf4, otherwise White gets a lot of space) and help White's development, or e6 has to be played. The latter is anti-positional, because the light-squared bishop is still on the board. } { [%cal Gd5c3,Gd5f4] } 15... Nxc3 { The lesser evil. } (15... e6?! { The problem with this move is that Black will get an isolated d-pawn now. } 16. Ncxd5 exd5 17. Rxe8+ Nxe8 18. Be3 Be4 $14 { White is a bit better here, because they have more space and more threats. } { [%cal Rf4d3,Bd3e5,Bd3c5,Rb3a4,Ba4d7,Ra1e1] }) (15... Nxf4?! { This is what White wanted all the time: an opportunity to develop the dark-squared bishop. } 16. Bxf4 { [%cal Rg2b7,Rb3b7] } 16... b6 17. axb6 axb6 18. d5! Nh5 $14 { Slightly better for White. Black's b-pawn has no future, while White's d-pawn is safe for now. } { [%cal Gg7c3,Gh5f4] }) 16. bxc3 e5! { Destroy White's new little pawn chain immediately. } 17. dxe5 g5! { White's e-pawn is pinned. } { [%cal Ge8e1] } 18. Ne2 Rxe5 { Pressure on the e0file is Black's plan now. } { [%cal Gd7e8,Ge8e2] } 19. Be3 $13 { Technically equal, but very sharp now. Black should put the queen to d8 now and tray a bishop exchange via Be4. White should try to control the d-file and maybe get Black's pawns on the a- and b-files. } { [%csl Bb7,Ba7][%cal Gd7e8,Gf5e4,Ra1d1,Rd1d8,Rb3d1] }) (14. Nf4 g5 15. a5! { The only move that saves d5 for now. } 15... Nc8 16. Nfe2 h6 $10 { Equal. White should try to exchange queens to get some tension off the center. Black has to get the knight off the 8th rank, probably to d6. Bh3 is also an idea: trading of the light-squared bishops is always good for Black here. } { [%cal Rb3a4,Rb3b5,Gc8d6,Gf5h3] }) 14... Be6 { Zwischenzug. Makes a5 less attractive for White, because the knight has now the escape square c4. Note that White cannot play d5 here, in contrast to the immediate 13.d6 without the Re1 Rfe8 intermezzo. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Ge6b3,Gb6c4] } (14... Qxd6?! { Taking immediately gives White the a-pawn. } 15. Nb5 (15. Bxb7?! { Probably too greedy. Black can now force to trade this bishop off. } 15... Nbd5 { [%cal Gd5b4,Gb4c2] } 16. a5 Qb4 17. Qxb4 Nxb4 { [%cal Gb4c2,Gf5c2] } 18. Rf1 Nfd5 19. Bd2 Nc7 { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd8d4,Gb4c2] }) 15... Qd7 16. Nxa7 { And with that White gets the pawn back. } { [%cal Rb3b6] } 16... Nbd5 17. Nb5 $10 { Equal, maybe a bit easier to play for White. Ideas for Black here are Bh3, Be6 and maybe even e5. And White still has to develop the queenside. }) 15. Qb5 { Black should not take on b5, of course. } { [%csl Ra7][%cal Ra1a7,Rg2b7] } 15... Bc4 16. Qxd7 Rxd7 { [%cal Gd7b7,Rg2b7] } 17. a5 Nc8 18. b3 { Poisoned pawn! } { [%cal Ra1b1,Rb1b7,Rg2b7] } 18... Bxe2 19. Nxe2 Nxd6 $10) 12... Rfc8 $146 { secures c4 for the knight. White can play d6 already, but it isn't very effective here. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Gc8c4] } (12... Rfd8 { Simply doesn't work: Black is never in time to capture on d5. } 13. Nf4 h6 (13... g5 14. Nd3 { [%cal Rd3e5] } 14... Bxd3 15. Rxd3 h6 16. h4 gxh4 17. d6 { [%cal Rg2b7] } 17... exd6 18. gxh4) 14. a4 g5 15. a5 gxf4 16. axb6 fxg3 17. hxg3 axb6 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. Qxb6 Bc2 20. Rf1) 13. a4 { Black has no way to stop that pawn. } (13. d6?! exd6 14. a4 Rab8 { This is why Black played Rfc8, not Rac8. Having a protection for b7 is crucial. } 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6) 13... Nc4 { The goal is now to blockade White's d5-pawn, to prevent d6. } { [%cal Gc4d6,Rg2b7,Rb3b7] } 14. a5 { White wants to develop the rook finally. } { [%cal Ra1a4,Ra4b4] } 14... Nd6 { This move also opens the opportunity to occupy e4 when needed. } { [%csl Be4][%cal Gf6e4,Gf5e4,Gd6e4] } 15. Nf4 { White's idea is Nd3, moving the knight to c5 later and protecting the bishop that goes to f4. } { [%cal Rf4d3,Rd3c5,Rc1f4] } 15... Nfe8 { The only move that prevents Nd3 for the moment. } { [%cal Gg7d4] } 16. Bf1 { Covers c4 and allows Nd3 after Be3 is played. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Rf1c4] } 16... Qd8 $14 { The idea is playing b6 to resolve the problems on the queenside.
White is a bit better here. Black has no good threats and is merely defending. } { [%cal Gb7b6] }) 12. d6 { And now White can give the first d-pawn for Black's b-pawn. } { [%cal Rg2b7] } 12... Qxd6 (12... exd6 { is the main move, but I don't recommend it. This IQP is now a liability for Black. } { [%csl Bd6] } 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bg2 Re8 { Black has to keep pressing here. } { [%cal Ge8e2,Gd3e2] } 15. Qd1 { [%cal Rd1d3] } 15... Ba6 16. Re1 { [%cal Gb6c4,Bc4b2,Bb8b2] } 16... Qc8 $146 { with the idea to bring the queen to f5. } { [%cal Gc8f5] } (16... Nc4?! { not yet } 17. b3) 17. b3 Qf5 $14 { This is still easier for White, despite the many retreated pieces. Black has to take care of the own IQP now. }) 13. Bxb7 (13. Nb5?! Bxb5 14. Qxb5 { Boschma, Bouwe - Ellis, Les, 1/2-1/2, WC36/pr07, 2012, https://lichess.org/7bhxoCQv } 14... Nfd5 $10) 13... Bc4! $146 14. Qc2 Rad8 15. Bg2 { It's probably better for White to keep this bishop in the game. Frome here on, every decent move keeps equality. } (15. b3 Bd5 { [%cal Gd5b7] } 16. Bxd5 Nbxd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Rd1 Rd7 19. Bg5 Qe6 20. Rac1 Qg4 21. Qd2 e6 $10 { Equal position, but not as bad for White as the Nf4 line, so that's my recommendation for White. }) (15. Bf4 Qd7 16. Bg2 Nfd5 { Finally Black's dark-squared bishop comes into the game. } 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 { And now Black has pressure on d4. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd7d4] } 18. Rfd1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Nd5 $10) *


