1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } 6... Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Nge2 Nbd7 { Starting position for this chapter. This is one of the main moves, and Black wants to watch d5 via Nb6, a common motif in all fianchetto lines. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Bb6d5] } 9. Nf4?! (9. g3 { ➡ Fianchetto Defense 4a }) 9... Qb6 { Probably Black's best option. The other lines don't lead to good positions. } { [%cal Gb6d4,Gb6b3] } (9... Ne8 { attacks d4 } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7d4] } 10. Be3 { protects it. } 10... Nd6 { The idea is Nf5 with a fork. } { [%cal Gd6f5,Bf5e3,Bf5d4] } 11. Bd3 { prevents the fork and develops the next piece. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Rd3f5,Gd6f5] } (11. Be2 { Yakovich, Yuri - Miroshnichenko, Evgenij, 1/2-1/2, Noyabrsk Fakel Jamala, 2003, https://lichess.org/l3Tl2I3J }) 11... Nb6 { opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and blockades the queen's view on b7. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8f5,Rb3b7] } 12. O-O Bf5 { White did allow that, because the bishop on f5 doesn't threaten d4. } 13. Be2 Rc8 $10 { Zvjaginsev, Vadim - Deviatkin, Andrei, 1/2-1/2, Moscow-ch blitz, 2004, https://lichess.org/lIovtmms } { This is equal. }) (9... Nb6 10. Be2 { Bf5 and Bg4 are the main moves here, but the engine suggests the surprising moves g5 and a5! Let's take a look at all of them. } 10... Bf5 (10... Bg4 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 { And now d4 is hanging. So White's best try is to push the knight back to f6. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7d4] } 12. h3 Nf6 (12... Nh6?! { is begging for an attack. } { [%cal Rc1h6] } 13. g4! Bxd4 14. Nh5! { [%cal Rc1h6] } 14... Nf5 15. gxf5 gxh5 16. Bh6 $14 Qd6 (16... Re8?!) 17. Bxf8 $16 { Anikaev, Yuri N - Seoev, Robert, 1-0, URS-ch otbor, 1979, https://lichess.org/zxU5V1rE } 17... Kxf8) 13. a4 a5 14. O-O $14 { Still a bit better for White, but playable for both sides. }) (10... a5 { White has to stop the a-pawn now. } { [%csl Ba4][%cal Ga5a4,Bb6a4,Ba8a4] } 11. a4 Bf5 { Finally develop the light-squared bishop. } 12. O-O Qd6 { Just connect the rooks. } 13. Nb5 Qd8 (13... Qd7 14. d6! { White has to give back the pawn now, but on d6 Black gets an IQP too. } 14... exd6 15. Be3 (15. Nc3?! { [%cal Rb3b6] } 15... Qd8 { [%cal Gd8b6] } 16. Bf3 { Krush, Irina - Foisor, Sabina Francesca, 1-0, USA-ch (Women), 2012, https://lichess.org/uvpbjbdH } { [%cal Rf3b7] }) 15... d5 $14 { Overall, this is still slightly better for White. The knight and the pawn on the b-file are a bit weak. }) 14. Nc3 { This is an invitation to go for a draw by repetition. } { [%cal Gd8d6,Rc3b5] } (14. Bf3 $146 { Might be a way to avoid the draw. But the line given by the engine is rather confusing. } 14... Rc8 { step off the diagonal. } { [%cal Rf3a8] } (14... Rb8 { The engine doesn't like this move. Hard to tell why. }) 15. d6 { [%cal Rb5d6] } 15... exd6 16. Bxb7 Bc2 17. Qa3 Bxa4 18. Nxd6 Rc7 19. Ba6 Bc6 $13)) (10... g5 $146 { Novelty. This does remove a defender from d5. Nh5 is the only way to keep d5 } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Rf4d5] } 11. Nh5 { [%cal Rh5g7] } 11... Nxh5 12. Bxh5 { [%cal Rc1g5] } 12... e6?! { defends d5 too. I just don't like the possible contuniations in this line. } { [%cal Gd8g5] } (12... h6 13. O-O Bf5 14. Re1 Qd7 $10 { This is … okay. Black will get the pawn eventually per Rad8. e6 might be a move soon. } { [%cal Ga8d8,Ge7e6,Bf5e6,Be6b3] }) 13. O-O { And now Black can decide either to fix the center with exd5 or to go into lots of trades with Nxd5. But none of these moves lead to a good position. } (13. dxe6? { is not really an option for White } 13... Bxe6 { gives Black the initiative. } { [%cal Ge6b3] } 14. Qd1 $15 { This is almost equal with a slight edge for Black who has the initiative and interesting threats. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd8d4,Ge6c4] }) 13... exd5?! { d4 is hanging, so } { [%cal Gg7d4] } (13... Nxd5?! { Also not a so nice: } 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Bxg5 Bxd4 $14 { Material is equal, but Black's damaged pawn structure is hard to defend. } { [%cal Gd4b2,Rh5f3,Bf3d5] }) 14. Ne2 { And here Black can grab some space with f5, develop the light-squared bishop to f5, or just relieve the queen with h6. } 14... f5 { the only option that doesn't give White f4. } { [%csl Gg4,Rf4][%cal Rf2f4,Gg5g4] } (14... Bf5 { with the idea to trade bishops on g6. But White can now grab the initiative with } { [%cal Gf5g6] } 15. Qg3! { Now Black has to defend g5. } { [%cal Rc1g5,Rg3g5] } 15... h6 16. f4! { This is really uncomfortable. } 16... g4 { The only thing Black can hope for here is to give the pawn on their conditions. } (16... f6?! { opens the diagonal for White's light-squared bishop, and the dark-squared will follow soon: } { [%cal Rh5e8] } 17. b3! { [%cal Rc1a3,Ra3f8] } 17... Nc8 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc8e7] } 18. Ba3 { now the rook can't go anywhere, and the knight gets the sad job of defending it. } 18... Ne7 $16 { White is much better here. }) 17. Bxg4 Qd7 18. Bxf5 Qxf5 $14 { Not a nice position for Black: one pawn down, a miserable structure and merely defending everything with the queen. }) (14... h6 { is probably too passive, because it gives White } 15. f4! { and Black has nothing better than } 15... f5 $14 { This is slightly better for White: Black's king is less safe, and the IQP is easier for White, because Black's is "pinned" and can't be used as an anchor for other pieces. } { [%cal Rb3g8] }) 15. a4 { [%cal Ra4a5] } 15... f4 16. h4 h6 17. hxg5 hxg5 18. Re1 Bf5 19. a5 Nc4 20. Qxb7 Be4 $14 { This is equal … says the engine. I'm not convinced. This is very sharp, Black is one pawn down (temporarily at least), and their king is an open target. In practical play White is probably better, because the position is easier to play. } { [%cal Re2c3,Gc4a5,Gd8a5] }) 11. O-O g5 12. Nd3 { Moving the knight to c5 is a good plan, and there's nothing Black can do to prevent that. } { [%cal Rd3c5] } (12. Nh5 Nxh5 13. Bxh5 h6 14. Re1 Qd7 { Prepares Rad8 and covers b7. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Ga8d8,Gd7b7] } 15. h3 { Prepares Bf3 which could be attacked per g4 otherwise. } { [%cal Rh5f3] } 15... Rad8 16. Bf3 { and now finally } 16... e6 { The break in the center. White can obviously not take. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf5e6,Be6b3,Gg7d4,Gd7d4] } 17. Qb4 Nxd5 { [%cal Gd5b4] } 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Re7! Qc8 20. Rxb7 Bxd4 21. Be3 Bxe3 22. fxe3 a5 $10 { This position is fairly equal, maybe with a slight edge for White } { [%cal Gc8b7,Rb4b7,Gf8e8,Ge8e3] }) 12... h6 13. Nc5 { [%cal Rc5b7] } 13... Nbxd5! $146 { Novelty! And an active move. } (13... Rb8?! { Too passive. } 14. h4 { Khismatullin, Denis - Mustakaev, Artur, 1-0, Kazan Region-ch 6th, 2008, https://lichess.org/oCFen5UP }) 14. Nxb7 { [%cal Rb7d8] } 14... Nxc3! { just trade off the "problem knight" that Black has to defend with the queen otherwise. } (14... Qd7 { Black's queen has to protect the knight on d5. } { [%cal Rc3d5,Rb3d5,Gf6d5,Bd7d5] } 15. Nc5 { Again with tempo on the queen. } { [%cal Rc5d7] } 15... Qd6 16. Bf3 { [%cal Rf3a8] } 16... e6 { White is a pawn up here and happy to trade some pieces off. } 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5 exd5 $14 { The question is: Is the bishop pair enough compensation for the pawn? Probably not. I think White has a good edge here. }) 15. bxc3 { forced move. } (15. Nxd8? { very bad! } 15... Nxe2+ 16. Kh1 Nxd4 17. Qb7 Rfxd8 $17 { Black got three minor pieces for the queen, and they are well coordinated. } { [%cal Gf5e4,Be4b7,Be4g2] }) (15. Qxc3?! { is not good: } 15... Qd5! { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd5b7,Gd5d4] } 16. Nc5 Ne4 { [%cal Ge4c3,Ge4c5,Gg7d4] } 17. Qf3 Bxd4 $15 { This is a nice, active position for Black. }) 15... Qc7 { [%cal Gc7b7,Gc7c3] } 16. Nc5 e5! { That pawn is bound to the knight. } { [%cal Bd4c5,Gc7c5] } (16... Ne4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Ba3 { [%cal Ra3e7] } 18... Rab8 19. Qc4 Qxc4 20. Bxc4 Rfc8 21. Bc5 e6 $14 { White is better for the passed pawn that isn't so easy to remove. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Rc5a7,Ra1e1] }) 17. Be3 Rac8 { aiming at c3 } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc7c3] } 18. Rac1 $14 { I think this is easier to play for White. }) 10. Be3 Qxb3 11. axb3 Nb6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gb6d5,Rc3d5,Rf4d5,Gf8d8] } 12. Bd3! $146 { Novelty. Makes Bf5 very unattractive for Black. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Gc8f5,Rd3f5] } 12... Rd8 13. Ra5 g5 { Remove one defender for d5. } { [%cal Rf4d5] } 14. Nfe2 Nbxd5 { and now Black is getting the pawn back … temporarily. } 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxg5 b6 $10 { This is very equal. White is still a pawn up, but that's a doubled pawn on the b-file and not worth that much. } { [%csl Bb3,Bb2] } *


