1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Qb3 Nb6! { Main move and my recommendation if you follow the 8…Nc6 line.. The idea is to play Be6 next if possible, or just Bg7 and castle. } { [%cal Gc8e6,Gf8g7] } 8. Bb5+ { prevents both. Most people play Bd7 here, in some games a knight was put on d7. But Nc6 is not as bad as it looks. Yes, it runs into d5, but there is counterplay. } 8... Nc6! $146 { Novelty. And my recommendation, because the follow-up is just beautiful. } (8... Bd7?! { Main move, with the idea to trade the light-squared bishops off. } 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Ne5 { And this move kind of refutes the line: White keeps their light-squared bishop, Black loses theirs. } 10... O-O 11. Nxd7 N8xd7 12. O-O Nf6 13. Rd1 { The main move for Black here is Nfd5, blockading the d-pawn and opening the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. But that allows White to develop their dark-squared bishop to g5 where it pins the e-pawn against the queen. That's why I recommend the cute little move e6 here. } { [%cal Gf6d5] } 13... e6! $146 { A novelty, but it transposes to a known position (4 games in the database). } 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bh4 $10 { Yu, Jennifer - Foisor, S., 1-0, ch-USA w 2018, https://lichess.org/XcF15lbO } { Equal position, but a little bit easier to play for White, because their pieces are more mobile. }) 9. d5 a6! 10. Ba4 (10. dxc6?! { enters a line of forced moves: } 10... axb5 11. cxb7 Bxb7 { [%cal Gb7g2] } 12. Qxb5+ Qd7 13. Qxd7+ Nxd7 14. Nf3 Bg7 15. O-O O-O $13 { The engine says this is completely equal. Yes, White has two connected passed pawns, but Black has the bishop pair, and the field is open, so they are very strong. }) (10. Bxc6+?! bxc6 { White does get rid of the IQP, although the c-pawn isn't really connected, but Black gets the initiative now. } 11. dxc6 Be6 12. Qb4 Bg7 13. Nf3 Rc8 { and there is no way that White can keep this pawn. } 14. O-O Rxc6 $10 { This is good for Black: bishop pair, open field to operate on, and equal material. }) 10... Nxa4 11. Qxa4 b5! 12. Nxb5 axb5! 13. Qxa8 Nd4 { Threatening to fork king and rook on c2. } { [%cal Gd4c2] } 14. Kf1 Bg7 15. Be3 O-O 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 { [%cal Gd4b2] } 17. Nf3 (17. Rb1? { White cannot hold this pawn. } 17... Qc7 { Qc2 would be mate in 7! } { [%cal Gc7c2] } 18. Qc6 Qa7 $17 { Black is much better here. }) 17... Bxb2 18. Rd1 b4 { Opens up the diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop and gives the dark-squared bishop an achor.. } { [%cal Ba6f1,Gf8a8,Gc8a6,Gd8b6] } 19. Kg1 Bc3 $15 { Black is better here. The compensation for the exchange sacrifice is a strong initiative, and White's pieces are all misplaced and poorly coordinated. } *


