1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Qb3 e6?! { Starting position for this chapter.
e6 is playable, but I don't recommend it. You shouldn't play e6 in the Fianchetto Defense as long as your light-squared bishop is still on c8. } 8. Nf3 { White's threats are: Bc4 (which would win a pawn), Bb5 and even Nxd5. } { [%csl Rc4,Rb5][%cal Rf1c4,Rc4b5,Rc3d5] } (8. Nxd5?! { White with the IQP should not trade material. } 8... Qxd5 9. Nf3 Qxb3 10. axb3 $15 { This is great for Black. }) (8. Bb5+?! { This leads to too many trades and directly into a very drawish position. } 8... Bd7 { gives Black a good opportunity to trade off the "bad" bishop. And more. } 9. Nge2 $146 (9. Nf3 Bxb5 10. Qxb5+ Qd7 11. Nxd5 { [%cal Rd5c7,Bc7b5,Bc7e8] } 11... exd5 $10) 9... Bxb5 10. Qxb5+ Qd7 11. Nxd5 (11. Qxd7+ Kxd7 (11... Nxd7 12. Nxd5 exd5 $10) 12. Nxd5 exd5) 11... exd5 12. Nc3 Qxb5 13. Nxb5 Kd7) 8... Bg7 (8... Nc6?! { The problem with this move is that Bb5 and Bxc6 damages Black's pawn structure. } 9. Bb5 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxc6 { Makes Black pawn structure a bit worse, but also gives up the bishop pair. } 11... bxc6 12. Na4 { It's not easy to recommend a move for Black now. The main moves are Qd6 and Ba6, the engine also likes Qa5 (a novelty!), Qc7 (6 games) and Nb6 (played only twice). } { [%cal Ra4c5] } 12... Qd6 { is the main move. The idea is to play Rb8. This a rather soft threat; White ignores that usually and just develops a rook. } { [%csl Bb8][%cal Bd6b8,Ga8b8,Gb8b3] } (12... Ba6?! { is one of the main moves, but I don't recommend it. Follow this line to see why. } { [%cal Ga6f1] } 13. Re1 Nb6 { supports the square c4 which would be a nice place for Black's light-squared bishop. White can either ignore that and just play Nc5 or activate their dark-squared bishop a tempo on Black's queen with Bg5. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Ga6c4,Bb6c4] } 14. Bg5 { my recommendation for White. } (14. Nc5?! { The main move. But it allows Black a cute little maneuver: } 14... Bc4 15. Qc3 Bd5 { And this is a good blockader for the IQP now. } 16. Ne5 { White would like to play Bf4 next or Qh3 and Bh6. } { [%csl Rf4,Rh6][%cal Rc3h3,Rc1h6] } 16... Qh4 $10 { prevents that. And it pins the knight on e5 against the d-pawn. Black still wants to play Nc4 eventually. Two moves have been tried here: b3 and f3.
In both cases the position is fairly equal, but not drawish. There is still a lot to play for. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gh4d4,Gb6c4] } 17. f3 { with the idea to reroute the dark-squared bishop to f2. } { [%cal Rc1e3,Re3f2] } (17. b3 { to prevent Nc4 } 17... Rfe8?! { Aronian, Levon - Caruana, Fabiano, 1/2-1/2, Grand Slam Final 5th, 2012, https://lichess.org/UEJ8ewHG }) 17... Nc4 { Wang Yue - Xu, Minghui, 1-0, TCh-CHN 2016, https://lichess.org/TnALjLEd }) 14... Qd5 { is the best move for Black here. It looks like a queen trade should favor Black here, but intuition fails us sometimes. You have to see the follow-up to understand why White should take the queen: } 15. Qxd5 $146 { has never been played. But I recommend it! The follow-up is a series of forced moves that leads to an excellent position for White. The basic idea is that after Nc5 White can push the a- and b-pawns and force Black's light-squared bishop into a passive, uncomfortable position where it disconnects the rooks. } { [%cal Rb2b5,Ra2a5] } (15. Qd1 { might be an option to avoid the trade, but then } 15... Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Bb5 { is excellent for Black. }) (15. Nc3?! { is just bad. } 15... Qxb3 (15... Qd7?! { Christiansen, Johan-Sebastian - Vocaturo, D., 0-1, Qatar Masters Open 2015, https://lichess.org/5Jv0npG5 } { even worse. }) 16. axb3 Bb5 { and Black is fine. White's b-pawns are easy targets, and if White trades their knight for Black's light-squared bishop, Black has an excellent pawn structure. } { [%csl Bb3,Bb2][%cal Gf8b8,Gb8b3,Ga7a3] }) 15... cxd5 (15... Nxd5 16. Nc5 Bc8?! { is even worse }) 16. Nc5 { Attacks the bishop on a6. } { [%cal Rc5a6] } 16... Bb5 { The only free square that doesn't disconnect the rooks. } 17. a4! { Attacks the bishop again. } 17... Bc6 { again the only square. Bd7 would allow White to trade off the bishop. } 18. b4 { Threatening b5 after which the bishop has to go to e8 and lock the rook in. So } { [%csl Bf8][%cal Rb4b5,Bc6e8] } 18... Rfc8 { should be played immediately. } 19. b5 Be8 $14 { and now we see why the queen trade wasn't so bad for White: Black lost a lot of space, and White owns a few squares deep in Black's camp.
In other words: 12…Ba6 is based on the hope that White avoids the queen trade, and that's just a bad reason to play it. } { [%csl Rb7,Rd7,Re7][%cal Rg5e7,Rc5d7,Rc5b7] }) (12... Qc7 { Prevents Bf4 and frees the knight from this job, a motif that we see in many Caro-Kann lines, especially in the Exchange variation. Keep that in mind. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gc7f4,Gd5f4] } 13. Bd2 { Enables Rc8 } { [%cal Ra1c1,Rc1c6] } 13... Rb8 { Activate the rook with tempo. } { [%cal Gb8b3] } (13... Ne7 $146 { is a suggestion by Stockfish and a novelty too! } 14. Nc5 { is not a concrete threat, but it does improve the knight. } 14... Nf5 { Puts pressure on the d-pawn. White's queen has to help out now somehow. } { [%cal Gf5d4,Gg7d4] } 15. Qa4 { Threatens Ba5. } { [%cal Rd2a5] } 15... Qb6 { and this is an opportunity to reconnect the pawns on the queen side: } 16. Ba5 Qb5! { White has to take now. } { [%cal Gb5a5,Gb5a4] } 17. Qxb5 cxb5 $10 { Good for Black. The better pawn structure and the bishop pair are good advantages. White has to bring one rook behind the d-pawn in order to protect it. Black should try to activate the light-squared bishop finally. }) 14. Qa3 { White a few threats here that Black needs to address somehow. An active move that comes with a counter-threat is probably the best here. } { [%cal Rf1e1,Ra1c1,Ra4c5,Rf3e5] } (14. Qc2 { allows } 14... Nb4 { and here moving the Queen back to b3 is the best move. } 15. Qb3 $146 { It's understandable that White doesn't want to go into this. No one has ever played this move. } { [%cal Gb8b3] } (15. Bxb4 { is very fine for Black. } 15... Rxb4 16. a3 Rb8 $10 { Khairullin, I. - Xiu Deshun, 1/2-1/2, Moscow Open A 2015, https://lichess.org/xlmGrOaZ } { This is a good position for Black. White's d-pawn will come under heavy attack, meaning that Black gets the initiative. } { [%cal Gb8b3,Gf8d8,Gd8d5] })) 14... Nb6! $146 { Novelty, and my recommendation. The simple threat is Nc4, forking White's queen and bishop. White's best option are Ba5 and b3, and both are moves that White actually doesn't want to play. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Gb6c4,Bc4a3,Bc4d2] } (14... f6 { is technically also fine and has been played before, but it's an ugly move to make. } 15. Rac1 g5 16. Ne1 { Nepomniachtchi, I. - Areshchenko, A., 1-0, 20th European Teams, 2015, https://lichess.org/mC7lMgTj }) 15. Ba5 { b6 is covered twice, so Black's queen can and should move away to a better square. } { [%cal Bb8b6,Ba7b6] } (15. b3 { covers c5, but it is also very uncomfortable to open the diagonal for Black's bishop. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gg7a1,Rb3c4] } 15... Nxa4 { Here Black should just take that annoying knight. } 16. Qxa4 { And now a Grünfeld move: } 16... c5! { This doesn't win a pawn, but it activates the light-squared bishop. } 17. Rac1 { is required. } 17... Bd7 { [%cal Gd7a4] } 18. Qa3 { and now the somewhat surprising move } { [%cal Ra3c5,Ra3a7] } 18... Qb7 { Yes, this loses the c-pawn. It's a positional sacrifice. } 19. Qxc5 { an attempt to prevent Bc6, but } { [%cal Gd7c6,Gc6f3] } 19... Rfc8 { renews the threat. } { [%cal Gd7c6] } 20. Qe7 { [%cal Re7b7] } 20... Re8 21. Qd6 { Black cannot play Bc6 but enforce a few useful exchanges now. } 21... Rbc8 $13 { It's hard to judge this position. Black has the bishop pair but not yet the space to use it. Rook trades are probably better for Black, so White should avoid them. } { [%cal Bc8c1,Bc1c8] }) 15... Qf4 { White's bishop on a5 is pointless now. It should find a better square too. } { [%csl Ba5] } 16. Bb4 { [%cal Rb4f8] } 16... Rd8 { [%cal Gd8d4,Gf4d4,Gg7d4] } 17. Be7 Rd7 18. Nxb6 (18. Bc5?! Nxa4 19. Qxa4 Rxb2) 18... axb6 19. Bh4 { [%cal Gh4g3] } 19... Rbb7 { [%cal Gb7a7,Ga7a3] } 20. Bg3 Qf5 $13 { Unclear position. Both sides have options here. } { [%cal Rg3b8,Ra3a8,Gd7d8,Gd8c8,Rf3e5] }) (12... Nb6 { I don't recommend this move, because the follow-up is so much easier to play for White, and once they have their bishop on d6, Black's play is very difficult. } 13. Nc5 Nd7 { Black should try to get rid of this annoying knight. } 14. Bf4! { is my recommendation for White. It restricts Black's play in their own field even further. } { [%cal Rf4d6,Rf3e5] } 14... Nxc5 { Of course. } 15. dxc5 Qd5 { Offer a queen trade now. Black has the bishop pair and doesn't have to fear the endgame. } { [%cal Gd5b3] } 16. Bd6! { A very annoying move. Black should use the opportunity to trade queens. } 16... Qxb3 17. axb3 { But keep the rooks! Do not take on b2 now. } { [%cal Yg7b2] } 17... Rd8 18. Rfd1 { [%cal Rd1d8,Bd6e5] } 18... Bb7 { Connect the rooks and don't allow discovery attacks by White. } 19. Be5 { Black should not accept the bishop trade, that would give up the only advantage they have in this position. } 19... f6 { doesn't only push the bishop away, it also restricts White's knight a little bit. However, it also blocks the bishop's view on b2. } { [%csl Bg5,Be5][%cal Bf3g5] } 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 { [%cal Ra1a7] } 21. Bd6 Bf8! $146 { Novelty. Although we are so deep in the game now that novelties don't anymore. } (21... a6 22. Nd2 Kf7?! { Gordievsky, D. - Bocharov, D., 1-0, 20th Voronezh Master Open, 2016, https://lichess.org/3aS4j1PP } { was played in }) 22. Bxf8 Kxf8 23. Kf1 a6 $10 { This is an equal position. White's knight is clearly better than Black's bishop, but Black has a slightly better pawn structure, and once the bishop is activated, more mobility in the field. }) (12... Qa5 $146 { Novelty. The idea is Qb5 and maybe a queen trade that repairs Black's queenside pawn structure. } { [%cal Ga5b5,Gc6b5] } 13. Bd2 { White has to use this opportunity to active their dark-squared bishop. } 13... Qb5 { White should of course not trade! } 14. Qa3 { [%cal Rb2b3,Ra4c5,Rf1e1] } 14... a5 $13 { Unclear position. }) 13. Re1 Rb8 { White's queen has now three options, and they are almost equally good: d3, d1 and c2. The squares on the d-file have the additional benefit that the queen can protect d4. } 14. Qd3 { is my recommendation for White for the simple reason that it doesn't sit between the rooks like Qd1 would. } 14... Nb4! $146 { Novelty. My recommendation } (14... Rb5!? { is recommended by Stockfish. I'm not sure how playable this is. This rook is a target for White on the 5th rank. The idea is Nb4 or Ne7, followed by Re5 and an exchange with White's only active rook. } { [%cal Gd5b4,Gb5e5,Be5e1] } 15. Bd2 { stops the Nb4 idea. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rd2b4] } (15. Nc5)) (14... c5 { was a try by Nepomniatchi, a positional sacrifice to activate the light-squared bishop. } 15. Nxc5 Nb4 16. Qc3 Bb7 { [%cal Gb7f3] } 17. a3 (17. Nxb7 Rxb7 18. Be3! $146 { Novelty. My recommendation for White. } (18. Bd2?! { Yilmaz, M. - Cheparinov, I., 1/2-1/2, TCh-TUR Super League 2015, https://lichess.org/WvIG46pD }) 18... Rc7 19. Qa3 Rfc8 $13) (17. Ne5?! Qd5 18. Nxb7 Rxb7 19. b3 Rbb8 20. Bb2 Rfc8 $15 { Matlakov, M. - Wei Yi, 1/2-1/2, 11th World Teams 2017, https://lichess.org/fsXWcvQE } { This is good for Black. The knight on b4 is strong, the open c-file is controlled, and the pawn structure is slightly better. Clear compensation for the pawn sacrifice. }) 17... Nd5 18. Qd3 Ba8 19. b4 Rbc8 20. Ne5 Ne7 21. Bb2 Nf5 22. Rad1 Rfd8 $10 { Radjabov, T. - Nepomniachtchi, I., 1-0, 21st European Teams, 2017, https://lichess.org/6jLKs4uM } { The engine says this is equal, but in practical play, White's knights are very strong. }) 15. Qd1 { Transposes to a known position that has been reached per English Opening/Symmetrical/Four Knights or Zukertort/Sicilian. } 15... c5! { A positional sacrifice played by Svidler against Erdos, similar to the game Radjabov - Nepomniatchi } 16. Nxc5 Bb7 { That light-squared bishop hasn't found a good square anyway. Exchanging it for the pesky knight is certainly good for Black. } 17. Nxb7 Rxb7 { [%cal Gg7b2,Gb7b2] } 18. b3 $10 { Erdos, V. - Svidler, P., 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Cup 2017, https://lichess.org/EVVEGRlG } { This is a very equal position, and Black will eventually get the d-pawn. Svidler continued with Nc6 here, and the game ended in a draw. } { [%cal Gf8d8,Gb7d7,Gb4c6,Bc6d4] }) 9. Nxd5 { is what White should play. And Black should take back with the Queen. } (9. Bb5+ Nc6 (9... Bd7 $146 { Now White can take. } 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. O-O O-O 12. Bg5 Qb6 13. Bxd7 Qxb3 14. axb3 Nxd7 $10 { This is actually equal. But due to the lack of pieces it's also a bit drawish. }) 10. O-O (10. Bg5 Qb6 { The point is that Black can answer Bxc6 with Qxc6. } { [%csl Bc6] } 11. Qa3 { The notorious downside of the early e6: Black can't castle. } (11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qa3 { doesn't let Black castle. And it has a funny one-move threat. } { [%csl Be7][%cal Ra3f8,Rg5e7] } 13... f6 14. O-O! Kf7 { [%cal Gg7f8,Gh8e8] } (14... fxg5?? { Not possible! } 15. Rfe1+ Kf7 16. Nxg5+ Kf6 17. Qe7+ Kf5 18. Re5+ Bxe5 19. Qxe5+ Kg4 20. h3+ Kh5 21. Ne6+ g5 22. Qxg5#) 15. Bf4 (15. Rae1 Bf8 16. Qe3 fxg5 17. Qe8+ Kg7 18. Re7+ Bxe7 19. Qxe7+ Kg8 20. Nxg5 Qb7 21. Qe8+ Kg7 22. Qe5+ Kg8 23. Qe8+ $10 { Draw by repetition. }) (15. Rfe1 Bf8 16. Qe3 fxg5 (16... Bd6 17. Bf4 Bb4 18. Ne5+ (18. Bg5 Qc7 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc7e7] } 19. Bf4 Qe7 20. Qxe7+ Bxe7 21. Rac1 Bd7 $15 { This is slightly better for Black due to the bishop pair. }) 18... fxe5 19. Bxe5 Bxe1 (19... Qd8 20. Bxh8 Qxh8 21. Qf4+ Qf6 22. Qc7+ Kf8 23. Re3 Bd6 24. Qxh7 Bf5 25. Rae1 Qxd4 26. Rf3 Qg7 27. Rxf5+ gxf5 28. Qxf5+ Qf7 29. Qh3 $10 { Again, White has to keep giving checks, but with accurate play by Black this is just a draw. }) 20. Rxe1 Rf8 21. Qh6 Qb4 22. Qxh7+ Ke8 23. Qxg6+ Kd7 $10 { White has keep giving checks now, but it's never enough for a mate. }) 17. Qe8+ Kg7 18. Re7+ Bxe7 19. Qxe7+ Kg8 20. Qe8+ Kg7 $10 { Draw by move repetition } { Potkin, Vladimir - Nepomniachtchi, Ian, 1/2-1/2, Capablanca Memorial Elite 47th, 2012, https://lichess.org/0wgnM2UE } { Belous, V. - Jones, G., 1/2-1/2, 22nd Abu Dhabi Masters, 2015, https://lichess.org/AuIwjm3N }) (15. Ne5+?! $146 { A very sharp line that has never been tried. It require accurate play by Black to survive this, but White is worse at the end. } 15... Kg8 (15... fxe5 { Leads just to a different move order. } 16. Qe7+ Kg8 17. Qe8+ Bf8 18. Bf6) 16. Qe7 { [%cal Re7f7] } 16... fxe5 17. Qe8+ Bf8 18. Bf6 { [%cal Rf6h8] } 18... Qb7 19. Bxh8 Bd7 20. Qxe5 Re8 21. Qf6 Re7 { [%cal Ge7f7] } 22. Qf3 Rf7 23. Qb3 Qxb3 24. axb3 Kxh8 25. Rxa7 Kg7 $15 { Black is better here. The bishop pair is compensation enough for the two pawns. }) 15... Re8 16. Bd6 a5 17. Qc3) (11. O-O { Not the most challenging line, because it allows Black to castle. } 11... O-O 12. Nxd5 (12. Bxc6 Qxc6 $146 13. Rfc1 f6 { A move the engine is insisting one. It looks a little bit anti-positional to me. Opening up the diagonal between the queen on b3 and the king? It does send the bishop away and it restricts the knight on f3. } { [%csl Ge5,Gg5][%cal Rb3g8,Bf3g5,Bf3e5] } (13... b6 14. Ne5 Qb7 15. Nxd5 exd5 { threatening f6 now. } { [%cal Gf7f6] } 16. Be3 Be6 $10 { Completely equal. White has a bit more space, Black is better developed. } { [%csl Ba1] }) 14. Bd2 Bd7 $10) 12... exd5 13. Bxc6 bxc6 $10 { Now Qxc6 isn't as useful. Black wants a pawn protecting d5. }) 11... f6 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. O-O $10 { This transposes into the 11.Nxd5 line given below. }) (10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. O-O O-O $10 { A very equal position that is usually a result of the Zukertort/Sicilian Invitation (1.Nf3 c5) }) 10... O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 { Black would like to play Qb6 next. A queen exchange on b6 or even b3 would favor Black. } { [%cal Gd8b6] } 12. Na4 { prevents that. } 12... Qd6 { An attempt to claim the semi-open b-file per Rb8. White can't stop that. } { [%cal Ga8b8] } 13. Re1 Rb8 { And from here on Black is fighting for the d4-pawn with good chances. } { [%cal Gb8b3] } 14. Qd3 (14. Qc2 Nb4 { [%cal Gb4c2,Gd6d4,Gg7d4] } (14... c5 15. Nxc5 Nb4 16. Qc3 { transposes to the Qd3 line given above. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd6d4] }) 15. Qd1 c5 16. Nxc5 Bb7 17. Nxb7 Rxb7 18. b3 Nc6 19. Bb2 Rd8 $10 { Erdos, V. - Svidler, P., 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Cup 2017, https://lichess.org/EVVEGRlG } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd6d4,Gd8d4] }) (14. Qd1 Ne7 { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd6d4] } 15. Bd2 { [%cal Rd2c3] } 15... Nf5 (15... c5 { This sacrifice might still work. }) 16. Bc3 Rd8 17. Ba5 $146 (17. Nc5 Nxd4 18. Ne4 { Save the knight first. } { [%cal Re4d6] } (18. Bxd4?! { trades don't help White here. } 18... Bxd4 { [%cal Gd4b2,Gd4c5] } 19. Ne4 Qb4 $15) 18... Qd5 { And now White can trade. } 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. Qa4 { [%csl Rf6][%cal Ra4a7,Ra4c6,Re4f6,Bf6d5,Bf6g8] } 20... Qb5 21. Qxd4! { A queen sacrifice with good compensation. } 21... Rxd4 22. Bxd4 { [%cal Rd4a7,Re4f6,Bf6h7,Gg8f8] } 22... c5 $146 (22... f5 { Creates a light-squared escape route for the king. } 23. Nf6+ Kf7 24. Nxh7 c5 25. Bc3 { [%cal Ra1d1,Rd1d8,Rh7g5,Bg5e6,Be1e6] } 25... Rb7 26. Re3 Re7 { in Grischuk, A. - Safarli, E., 1-0, World Rapid 2017, https://lichess.org/QdeucHiu
The engine says Qa4 is the only move to keep equality for Black. } (26... Qa4 $146)) 23. Be5 { The bishop has to keep an eye on b2. } { [%cal Re5b2] } 23... Ra8 24. Rad1 { [%cal Rd1d8] } 24... Bb7 25. Nf6+ Kf8 26. Nxh7+ Ke8 27. Nf6+ Kf8 $10 { White has at least a perpetual check here. }) (17. Re4?! Rb5 { Threatening e5. Note that White's d-pawn is pinned to the queen. } { [%cal Ge6e5,Bd6d1] } 18. Qe1 { is forced. } 18... Rd5 19. Ba5 Rd7 20. Bb4! Qb8 { [%cal Gb8b4] } 21. Nc5 Rd8 22. Nb3 Ba6 23. Bc3 $146 (23. Ne5? Nxd4? { A weird continuation in } { Aronian, L. - So, W., 1/2-1/2, GCT Blitz Paris 2016, https://lichess.org/Wr3kPZHa }) 23... Bd3! { trapping the rook. } { [%csl Ge2,Ge3,Ge5][%cal Gd3e2,Gd3e4,Gg7e5,Gf5e3] } 24. Re5 Bxe5 25. Nxe5 $15 { This is very fine for Black. }) 17... Rf8 18. Bc3 Rd8 { And here White can force a draw with move repetition or go into the Nc5 line. }) 14... c5! 15. Nxc5 Nb4 16. Qc3 { White has to stay in contact with the d-pawn. } 16... Bb7 { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd6d4,Gb7f3] } 17. a3 (17. Nxb7 Rxb7 $10 { Yilmaz, M. - Cheparinov, I., 1/2-1/2, TCh-TUR Super League 2015, https://lichess.org/WvIG46pD }) 17... Nd5 18. Qd3 Ba8 { [%cal Gb8b2] } 19. b4 Rbc8 20. Ne5?! (20. Bg5 { is probably stronger than Ne5. } 20... h6 21. Bh4 g5 22. Bg3 Nf4 { [%cal Gf4d3,Gd6d4,Gg7d4,Ga8f3] } 23. Qe3 Bxf3 24. Qxf3 Qxd4 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gc3f3] } 25. Rad1 Qf6 { [%cal Gf4h3] } 26. Qe3 (26. Nd7?! { Allows Black to trade queens off and damage White's pawn structure. } 26... Nh3+! { [%cal Gf6f3] } 27. Kf1 Qxf3 28. gxf3 Rfd8 $10) 26... Rfd8 $10 { Equal, but still sharp. }) 20... Ne7 21. Bb2 { Radjabov, T. - Nepomniachtchi, I., 1-0, 21st European Teams, 2017, https://lichess.org/6jLKs4uM }) 9... Qxd5 (9... exd5?! { is technically playable, but not a good pawn structure for Black. } 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. O-O O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Bf4 $10) 10. Bc4 $146 { My recommendation for White. } (10. Qxd5 exd5 $10 { has been played in Roepke - Zaerban, 1995, which ended in a draw. I think Black's position is fine here. }) 10... Qf5 11. Qa3 { is annoying here, because it doesn't let Black castle. } 11... Nc6 12. O-O Qa5 13. b3 Bd7 $13 { This is an unclear position. Black has to fight a little bit for a castling opportunity, but the pawn structure is better than in the 8…Nc6 line, and the position is new to both sides. } *


