1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Qb3 Nxc3?! { This gives White a strong initiative. } 8. Bc4! { Zwischenzug! Black cannot allow Bxf7 } 8... Nd5 { The knight is gone anyway, so we don't should allow White to resolve the IQP. } (8... e6?! { isn't much better, because now the bishop will look at the small pawn chain once it landed on g7. } { [%cal Gg7c3] } 9. bxc3 Bg7 { [%csl Bd4,Bc3] } 10. Ba3 { Prevents castling for now. } { [%cal Ra3f8] } 10... Nc6 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc6e7] } 11. Nf3 { [%cal Gg7f8] } 11... Ne7 12. O-O O-O $14 { White is a bit better here: no real weaknesses, more space, and their pieces are placed better. Black's dark-squared bishop looks at the pawn chain, the light-squared bishop is bound to defend b7, and so it keeps the rook on a8 locked in. } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gg7d4,Gc8b7] }) 9. Bxd5 e6 10. Bxb7 Bxb7 11. Qxb7 Nd7 $14 { Black is just a pawn down here. No compensation. } *


