1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 { Main move. This looks aggressive, but is actually not that challenging. Black should not play e6 here! } 7... Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4] } 8. Bb3 (8. d5 $146 { is an interesting novelty. It leads to a sequence of sharp tactics. } 8... Nxc4 (8... Bg7 9. Bb3 O-O { transposes to the main line. }) 9. Qd4! { and here White is getting the piece back } { [%cal Rd4c4,Rd4h8] } 9... e5! { the only good response. } 10. Qxc4 Bg7 11. Bg5! { Black should not trade bishops, because in that line, White wins b7. } { [%cal Rc4c8] } 11... Qd7 { [%cal Gd7c8,Gd7b7] } 12. Nge2 b6 13. O-O O-O $10) 8... Bg7 9. Nf3 O-O { and now Black wants to play Bg4, so h3 should probably be played by White prior to castling. } { [%cal Gc8g4] } 10. O-O (10. h3 Nc6 { pressures d4, so White has to push it. } { [%cal Gc6d4,Gg7d4,Gd8d4,Rd1d4,Rf3d4] } 11. d5 (11. Be3?! { Too passive. } 11... Na5! 12. Bc2 Nac4 { pushes the bishop back to c1. } { [%cal Gc4e3,Gc4b2] } 13. Bc1 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6] } (13... Be6 { is also playable. } 14. O-O Rc8 $10) 14. O-O Rc8 15. Re1 Bc6 $15 { This is a good position for Black. The isolani can't be pushed forward, and Black has so much pressure on it that White's pieces are bound to defend it. } (15... Re8 { Medak, Bojan - Dobos, Jozsef, 1/2-1/2, Pecs Suto op 4th, 1996, https://lichess.org/uP9YMfsc })) (11. O-O?! { is excellent for Black: } 11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4) 11... Na5 { [%cal Ga5b3] } 12. O-O Re8 { Preparing White's inevitable Re1. } (12... Nxb3 { is also possible, although not needed. } 13. axb3 Qd6 (13... Bxc3 { wins a pawn, but giving up that beautiful bishop doesn't seem right. } 14. bxc3 Qxd5) 14. Re1 { [%cal Re1e7] } 14... Bf5 15. Bg5 $146 { Novelty } 15... Rfe8 $13 { is forced. }) 13. Re1 { And now it's time to develop the queenside: } 13... Bf5 { Black really wants to play Nbc4 here, so White could try } { [%cal Gb6c4] } (13... Nxb3?! { Main move. Looks like Black can win a pawn here, but I'm not convinced. } 14. axb3 Bxc3 { Giving up that great dark-squared bishop? } 15. bxc3 Qxd5 $14 { Potkin, V. - Christiansen, Johan-Sebastian, 1-0, World Blitz 2017, https://lichess.org/csHZT5vy } { White has good compensation for the pawn: control over two semi-open files, and better development. Note that Black's queenside is still not developed. } { [%cal Re1e6,Ra1a6] } 16. Be3 Qxd1 17. Rexd1 Be6 18. c4 { Fressinet, L. - Safarli, E., 1/2-1/2, World Rapid 2017, https://lichess.org/ni5S7rnp }) 14. Ne5 $146 { Novelty. } 14... Qd6 { Attack this knight immediately. } { [%cal Gg7e5,Gd6e5] }) 10... Nc6 11. d5 Na5 { [%cal Ga5b3] } 12. Re1 { This is already completely equal, and Black has to decide now which plan to follow. } 12... Bg4 { Main move. } (12... Nxb3 13. axb3 (13. Qxb3 { Black can get the d-pawn here. But that gives away the strong dark-squared bishop. } 13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qxd5 { [%cal Re1e7] } 15. Re5 $146 (15. Qxd5 $146 Nxd5 16. c4 Nb6 17. Rxe7 Nxc4 $10 { Black is a pawn up, but it's difficult to get the light-squared out without losing a pawn. Equal. }) (15. Rxe7 $146 Be6 $10) 15... Qxb3 16. axb3 Re8 $10) 13... Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Re8 16. Be3 { Most people play Bxc3 here to avoid d6. But Qd6 does the same without giving the good bishop. } { [%cal Rf3b7] } 16... Qd6 (16... Bxc3?! 17. Bxb6! Qxb6 18. bxc3 Qxb3 19. Rab1 Qa3 20. Rxb7 Rac8 21. Rd7 Qxc3 $146 (21... Rxc3 22. Qf4 Qc5 $10 { Ribli, Zoltan - Kovacevic, Aleksandar, 1/2-1/2, SLO-chT, 2012, https://lichess.org/DmQlp0Pw }) 22. Qxc3 Rxc3 23. d6! e6 $10 { Equal, but White's d-pawn is dangerous. } { [%cal Rd7a7,Gc3d3,Bd3d6] }) 17. Bf4 $146 Qd7 18. Rad1 { keeps the d-pawn for a long time. } 18... Nc8 $10 { Equal, but there is still a lot to play for. } { [%cal Gc8d6,Rf4e5] }) (12... Re8 { A good prophylactic move. } 13. Bg5 { The engine suggests Bxc3 here, which looks very anti-positional. } (13. h3 { Prevents Bg4. See 10.h3 for ideas. }) 13... Bg4 14. h3 (14. d6! { goes into a tactically sharp line: } { [%cal Rg5d8] } 14... Qxd6 15. Bxf7+! Kxf7 16. Rxe7+ Qxe7 17. Bxe7 Kxe7 (17... Rxe7?? 18. Ng5+! Kg8 19. Qxg4) 18. Nd5+ $146 (18. Nb5 { [%cal Rd1e1,Be1a5,Be1e7] } 18... Kf8 { Escape the incoming fork. } 19. Qd6+ Kg8 20. Nc7 { [%cal Rc7e8,Rc7a8] } 20... Red8 21. Qb4 Rac8 22. Qxg4 Rxc7 { Tregubov, Pavel V - Kurnosov, Igor, 0-1, Moscow op-A 04th, 2008, https://lichess.org/lV33yfmS }) 18... Kf8 19. Qd2 { White has many threats now. } { [%cal Rd2a5,Rd2f4,Bf4f8,Bf4g4,Rd5c7] } 19... Bxf3 20. Nc7 Bc6 21. Qxa5 $13 { The engine it's very equal, but … Black has to find some very precise moves now. }) 14... Nxb3 15. axb3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 19. c4 f6 20. cxd5 fxg5 $10 { Very equal and drawish. }) 13. h3 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Re8 $10 *


