1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Qb3 e6?! { This is a bit anti-positional. One of Black's main ideas in the Fianchetto Defense is the open h3-c8 diagonal. Closing it with e6 doesn't really fit in here. It also makes Bg5 very strong for White. And, as we will see, the diagonal a3-f8 is a problem for Black after Bg7, because White can prevent castling with Qa3.
However, technically it is playable, and Black has chances to equalize. } { [%cal Yc8h3,Rb3a3,Ra3f8,Gf8g7] } 7. Nf3 (7. cxd5 { Played only once so far, by Vugar Gashimov against Veselin Topalov 2010. } 7... exd5 (7... Nxd5 { Transposes to ➡ Fianchetto Defense 6 }) 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Qa3 { transposes to the main line. } 9... Qe7+ 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7) (7. Bg5 Nc6 8. cxd5 $146 exd5 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O $10) 7... Nc6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb5 Bg7 10. Qa3 { [%cal Ra3f8] } (10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qa3) 10... Qe7+ 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. O-O Be6 $10 { Equal, but Black's king a bit exposed. } *


