1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Bg7 { Fianchetto gambit. Instead of taking the pawn back with Nxd5, as we have seen in the previous chapters, Black fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop immediately.
Note how Black has developed two pieces already and is only one step away from castling. } 7. Qb3 (7. Nf3?!) 7... O-O 8. Nf3 (8. Nge2 Na6 { transposes to Fianchetto Defense 2 }) (8. g3) (8. Be2 { Main move. The idea is the same as in the regular Fianchetto Defense: Bring the bishop to f3, the knight via e2 to f4 and try to hold the d5-pawn. } { [%cal Re2f3,Bg1e2,Be2f4,Rf3d5,Bf4d5] } 8... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6b3,Gb6d4] } (8... Na6 { transposes to Fianchetto Defense 1b }) (8... Nbd7 { transposes to Fianchetto Defense 1a }) 9. Qxb6 (9. Bc4 Qxd4!?) (9. Nf3) 9... axb6 10. Bf3 (10. Nf3) (10. Bf4) 10... Na6 (10... Bg4) 11. Nge2 Nb4 12. O-O Rd8 13. d6 Rxd6 14. Bf4 Rd7 (14... Rd8 15. Bc7 Rd7) 15. Rfd1 Nbd5 (15... Nfd5) 16. Be5 Rd8 17. Nxd5 (17. Bxd5) (17. a3) (17. Nf4) 17... Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Rxd5 19. Nc3 (19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nc3) 19... Rd8 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. d5 e6 22. a3 Bd7 23. Rd4 (23. f3 exd5 24. Rxd5 Bc6 25. Rxd8 { Sveshnikov, Evgeny - Adorjan, Andras, 1/2-1/2, GMA op, 1989, https://lichess.org/J5xI3hyH } 25... Rxd8) 23... Bc6 (23... exd5 24. Rad1 (24. Rxd5 Bc6 $10) 24... Bc6 25. Nxd5 Ra5 26. Nxb6 Rxd4 27. Rxd4 $10)) *


