1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Bg7 { Fianchetto gambit. Instead of taking the pawn back with Nxd5, as we have seen in the previous chapters, Black fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop immediately.
Note how Black has developed two pieces already and is only one step away from castling. } 7. Bb5+ { White tries to counter Black's development advantage by developing the bishop with a tempo. But now Black develops another piece to block the check. } 7... Nbd7 (7... Bd7?! { is very dubious: where does the knight on b8 go now after Bc4? } 8. Bc4 { [%cal Yb8c6,Yb8a6] } 8... O-O 9. Qb3 Bf5 10. Nge2 (10. Qxb7?! { White is giving up their advantage with that. } 10... Nbd7 11. Bf4 Nb6 (11... Ne8?! 12. Nf3 { Nunn, John DM - Hickl, Joerg, 1-0, Dortmund-A, 1987, https://lichess.org/B5aBZaOR }) 12. Bb3 Nh5 13. Bc7 Qd7 14. Qc6 Rfc8 15. Qxd7 Nxd7 16. d6 exd6 17. Bd5 { [%cal Rd5a8] } 17... Re8+ 18. Nge2 Rac8 $10) 10... Nbd7 11. Ng3 Nb6 12. Nxf5 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 gxf5 14. O-O Rc8 15. Qb3 Qd6 $14) 8. d6 { White cannot defend this pawn anyway. Exchanging it in a way that damages Black's pawn structure is the best White can do here. } (8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Nb6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gb6d5,Gd8d5] } 10. Re1 a6 11. Be2 (11. Bf1 { is the database move. Also fine. } 11... Nbxd5 12. Qb3 $10) 11... Nbxd5 $10) 8... O-O! { This is better than getting an IQP for Black. } (8... exd6 { is the main move here. It keeps material equality, but now Black has an IQP too. } 9. Qe2+ Qe7 10. Bf4 Qxe2+ 11. Ngxe2 { and now Black has to play the ugly move } (11. Bxe2 { The idea here is to bring the knight from g1 to f3 from where it controls more squares in Black's side. } { [%cal Gg1f3,Bf3g5,Bf3e5] } 11... O-O! { Giving up the d-pawn in favor of better development. } (11... Ke7 { is the main move, similar to the 11.Ngxe2 line. }) 12. Bxd6?! Re8 { Pins the bishop. } { [%cal Ge8e1] } 13. Nf3 Ne4 { Attack White's dark-squared bishop on d6. } { [%cal Ge4d6] } 14. Bf4 { The engine suggests the counter-intuitive move Nxc3 here. Nb6 is also playable. Both moves are novelties. Cherenkov played the passive Nf8 and lost his game.
The side with the IQP is responsible for the attack. As long as the opponent doesn't allow that they are fine. Black has to play aggressively. } { [%csl Bd4] } (14. Nxe4?! Rxe4 { White would love to castle here. But that's not possible. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Ge4d4] } 15. Kf1 { White's bishop wants to go to c4 now. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Re2c4] } 15... Nb6 $10 { prevents that. Maybe it's better to let White keep the extra pawn and have bit more tension in the position. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Gb6c4] } (15... Bxd4 { is of course playable. The downside is that White now has the bishop pair in an otherwise completely equal position. } 16. Nxd4 Rxd4 $10 { [%cal Gd4d6] })) 14... Nb6! $146 (14... Nxc3 $146 15. bxc3 Nb6 { [%cal Gc8f5,Ga8c8] } 16. Kd2 { This is the main difference to the 14…Nb6 line: The king can step out of the pin and protect the c-pawn. } 16... Nd5 { [%cal Gd5f4,Gd5c3] } 17. Bb5 { [%cal Rb5e8] } 17... Re7 18. Bg5 Rc7 $10 { This is equal. Black can now push the a- and b-pawn with tempo, keep pressure on White's c-pawn, and develop the light-squared bishop to f5. } { [%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gc8f5] }) (14... Nf8?! { Frolyanov, D. - Cherenkov, And, 1-0, RUS Rapid GP Serpukhov, 2018, https://lichess.org/E08qRnNg }) 15. Be3 { protects the d-pawn and resolves he pressure of the rook on e8. It's a bit passive, though. } { [%csl Be8][%cal Ge8e1] } 15... Nxc3 { is still a good move. } 16. bxc3 Nd5 { pushing the bishop even futher back. } { [%cal Gd5c3] } 17. Bd2 Bf5 { Now White's king has to step out of the pin and lose castling rights. } { [%cal Gf5d3,Bd3e2] } 18. Kf1 Rac8 $10 { This is equal despite White's extra pawn. Black's pieces are well coordinated, and attacking, while White is just defending, and the rook on h1 out of play. } { [%cal Gd5c3,Gc8c3] }) 11... Ke7 12. O-O Nb6 13. Rfe1 Be6 14. Bd3 (14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6+ (15. Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 Rhd8 $10 { This is technically equal, but certainly easier to play for White. }) 15... Bxf6 16. Bd3 (16. d5?! { overly ambitious } 16... Bd7 17. Ng3+?! Kd8 { Zarychta, Krzysztof - Kaszowski, Dariusz, 0-1, POL-ch sf, 2002, https://lichess.org/qJzL58se }) 16... Rhe8 $10 { Completely equal, Black has probably even a slight edge here due to the bishop pair. The king should move to f8 and maybe to g7 later where it is safe. The second rook should control the open c-file.
White should try Nf4, Ne4, and a4 to gain some space. } { [%cal Ge7f8,Gf8g7,Ga8c8,Re2f4,Ra2a4,Gg6g5,Rc3e4] }) 14... Rhd8 { Relieve the king from protecting d6. } 15. Bg3 Kf8 $10 { Equal position. It will be important for both sides to protect their IQPs and the square in front of them. This is currently easier for Black, because their pawn isn't so advanced.
The control over the open c-file is another question, because that might allow to bring a rook into the opponent's pawn rank. } { [%csl Gd6,Rd4,Bd5][%cal Ga8c8] }) 9. dxe7 Qxe7+ 10. Nge2 (10. Be2?! b5! { Gambiting another pawn! The compensation is not so easy to see and only visible after a couple of moves. White has only two good moves here: Nxb5 and a3. The follow-ups given here have never been played, and you will probably not get them over the board. But they do illustrate why b5 is so good. } 11. Nxb5 { White should take the pawn. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gf6d5] } (11. a3 { A line suggested by Stockfish, depth 44. Note how Black comes out with an extra pawn! } 11... Bb7 { Just let b5 hang. } { [%csl Gg2][%cal Gb7g2] } 12. Nf3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Rad8! $146 (13... a6 { Kun, Gabor - Chernyshov, Konstantin, 0-1, Budapest FS05 GM, 2005, https://lichess.org/d97KGFfd } { Also good, but not as strong as Rad8. }) 14. O-O (14. Nxb5? Nh5 { [%cal Gg7d4] } 15. Be3 Nc5 16. d5 Rfe8 { [%cal Gh5f4,Ge7h4] }) 14... a6 15. Re1 Rfe8 16. Bg5 Nf8 17. d5 h6 18. Bh4 g5 19. Bg3 Qd7 20. Bf1 Nxd5 { Get the pawn back. } 21. Rxe8 Qxe8 22. Nxd5 Qe6 23. a4 Rxd5 24. Qc2 Qf6 25. axb5 axb5 26. Ra5 Qxf3 { Extra pawn! } 27. Be2 Qf6 28. Rxb5 Rxb5 29. Bxb5 Qxb2 30. Qxb2 Bxb2 $10 { Black is one pawn up, but this should be a draw. }) 11... Nb6! $146 { Novelty. A line suggested by Stockfish, depth 44 } (11... Nd5 $146 { Novelty. The following line is a suggestion by Houdini: } 12. Nf3 Re8 13. Bg5 Qb4+ 14. Kf1 Qxb2 15. Bd3 N7b6 16. Rb1 Qxa2 17. Ra1 Qb2 18. Rb1 $10 { Draw by repetition. }) (11... Bb7 { Is the only move you'll find in the database. Playable, but the knight move lines are better. }) 12. Nf3 Re8 { Prevents castling. } { [%cal Ge7e2] } 13. Nc3 { Add protection to the bishop. } { [%cal Rc3e2] } 13... Nbd5 { Attack the defender immediately. } 14. Ne5 { Blocks the queen's view. } { [%cal Ge7e2] } 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd5 { And here comes the idea to life: d5 is used as a pivot point for the attacking pieces. White should give up c3 and just castle. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Gd5c3] } 16. O-O (16. Bf3? Ba6! 17. Bxd5 Bxe5 18. Be3 Bf4 19. c4 Bxe3 20. O-O $17) 16... Nxc3 { Black gets one pawn back. } { [%cal Gc3e2,Gc3d1] } 17. Qd2 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 Qe6 { Prepare Ba6. } { [%csl Ga6][%cal Ge6a6] } 19. Rd1 Ba6 20. Qf3 Bc4 { [%cal Gc4a2,Ge6c4] } 21. Bf4 Bd5 22. Qg4 Qxg4 23. Nxg4 Re2 { [%cal Ge2a2,Gd5a2] } 24. Ne3 Bxa2 { And here is the second pawn. } 25. Kf1 Rb2 26. d5 Bb3 27. Rd3 a5 28. d6 Be6 29. d7 Rd8 30. Rxa5 Rb1+ 31. Rd1 Rxd1+ 32. Nxd1 f6 33. f3 Rxd7 $10 { Completely equal. }) 10... a6 { Gain some space and kick the bishop back into White's camp. } 11. Bd3 { The bishop should stay on the diagonal that protects the knight on e2. } (11. Bc4?! { is dangerous, because } 11... b5 { is coming anyway. } 12. Nd5 { A "justification" for the bishop on c4. } 12... Qe4 { Note that White's bishop is still hanging. And the knight on d5 is attacked twice. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gf6d5,Ge4d5] } (12... Qd8 { has been played once. It unpins the knight on e2, but that pin wasn't so strong anyway. } 13. Bb3 Bb7 { The knight has to move now. } { [%cal Gf6d5,Gb7d5,Rb3d5] } 14. Nxf6+ (14. Ne3 $10 $146 { if White wants to keep the material on the board. Black's position is so good that there are a few good options to choose from:
Nb6 to control the center better
a5 with the threat of a4
Re to claim the open e-file })) 13. f3 Qe6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Ge6d5] } 14. Nxf6+ { the only move here. } 14... Qxf6 15. Bd5 Ra7 16. O-O { and now White can finally castle. } 16... Nb6 { That poor bishop has to move again. } { [%cal Gb6d5] } 17. Be4 Bb7 { Black will happily trade off the light-squared bishop: all pawns are on light squares. } 18. Be3 Nc4 $10 { [%cal Gc4b2,Gc4e3] }) 11... b5 12. O-O Bb7 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gh7h6,Ra2a3,Rf8e8,Bc1f4,Bd7b6] } 13. Bg5 { is a little bit annoying. Re1 is incoming, and then the queen has to go away. } { [%cal Rf1e1] } 13... b4 { Black, being a pawn down, should try to keep the initiative. } (13... Rfe8 { Less forcing, but playable. }) 14. Na4 Qd6 { Step out of the pin, and create a very simple threat. Actually two: Ng4 and Qd5 are mate threats. } { [%cal Gd6d5,Bd5g2,Gf6g4,Bg4h2,Bd6h2,Bd5g5] } 15. Bf4 (15. f3 { is an ugly move to make. Black will now try to get control over both open files, and to damage White's queenside with the weak knight. There are different move orders with subtle differences, but the basic idea is that simple. } { [%csl Ba4][%cal Re8e2,Be8e1,Bc8c1,Gb7c6,Gc6a4,Ga8c8,Gf8e8] } 15... Bc6 $146 { The knight has no square to go, and White probably wants to keep it. } { [%cal Gc6a4] } (15... Nd5 { [%cal Gf8e8,Gh7h6,Gg7d4] } 16. Re1 $146 (16. Qd2 Bc6 { The idea is to get the knight from d7 to c4. } { [%cal Bd7b6,Bb6c4] } 17. b3 $146 (17. Bc2 Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e2,Rd2e2,Bg7d4] } 18. Rfe1 $146 (18. Rfd1?! Rae8! $146 (18... h6?! 19. Bh4 Rfe8 { Russek Libni, Guil - Martin del Campo, Jorge, 1-0, Fide Mercenarios 7th, 1995, https://lichess.org/c8G6Zwnw }) 19. Re1 $146 (19. Ng3 Qc6! { [%cal Gb5a4] } 20. Nc5 Nxc5 21. dxc5 Qxc5+ 22. Kh1 { [%cal Gc5c2] } 22... Ne3 23. Bxe3 Qxe3 24. Qxb4 Be5 { [%cal Ge3h6,Be5g3] } 25. Nf1 Qh6 { [%cal Gb5f1,Bh6h2,Be5h2] } 26. Bd3 Bxd3 27. Rxd3 Rb8 $15 { Black has good compensation for the pawn and a strong initiative. }) 19... a5 20. Kh1 Qc6 21. Rac1 Bxa4 22. Bd1! Qb5 23. b3 Bxb3 24. axb3 Nc3! $14 { Material is equal, but Black is clearly the pressing side here. }) 18... Rfe8 19. Bb3 N5b6 20. Nxb6 Nxb6 21. Rac1 Rac8 $10 { Equal, White is just defending here. }) 17... Rfe8 18. Kh1 Bxa4 19. bxa4 N7b6 20. a5 Na4 $13 { Technically equal, but very sharp. White will not manage to keep both a-pawns. } { [%csl Ba5][%cal Gd5c3,Ga4c3] }) 16... Rfe8 17. Kh1 Ne3 { [%cal Ge3d1] } 18. Qd2 (18. Bxe3?! Rxe3 19. Ng3 Qxd4 $17) 18... Nxg2! { Piece sacrifice! } 19. Kxg2 Qc6 { threatening mate in 2. } { [%cal Gc6f3] } 20. Qf4 Qxa4 $10 { gets the piece back. We have equal material now. } 21. Bc4 { [%cal Rc4f7,Rf4f7] } 21... Kh8) (15... Rfe8 $146 { Just claim the e-file. } 16. Kh1 { Important prophylactic move. } 16... Nd5 { Keep the knight on the board, and blockade the isolani. Knights are perfect for that job. One idea is Ne3, therefore White should play } { [%cal Gd5e3] } 17. Qd2 { [%csl Be3][%cal Rg5e3,Rd2e3,Gd5e3,Ge8e3] } 17... Bc6 { That knight has no good square to go, so } { [%cal Gc6a4] } 18. b3 $10 { is probably the lesser evil.
This is completely equal. Black is one pawn down, but the pieces are active and well coordinated } { [%cal Gc6a4,Gd7f8,Bf8e6,Rf1e1,Ra4b2,Bc6b5,Ye6g5,Ye6d4] }) 16. b3 { This protects the knight, and it creates a useful free square. Black can take it anyway and damage White's pawn structure. Or just keep the tension and play Nd5, that's auseful move anyway. } { [%cal Ra4b2] } 16... Nd5 { The target is e3! } { [%csl Be3][%cal Gd5e3,Rg5e3] } (16... Bxa4 17. bxa4 Nd5 { Threat: Nc3! } { [%cal Gd5c3] } 18. Qd2 Nc3 { Attack the d-pawn immediately. But Black is not in a hurry to take it. It's better to improve the other pieces first. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd6d4] } (18... N7b6 { The idea is Na4 and then Nac3! } { [%cal Gb6a4] } 19. a5 Na4 { This is getting very uncomfortable for White. The d-pawn will very likely fall soon, and that comes with a check at the current situation. That's why White should play Kh1 here. } { [%cal Gd5c3,Ga4c3,Gg7d4] } 20. Kh1 Nac3 { Note how well coordinated Black's pieces are. White's dark-squared bishop stares into the nothingness, knight and Queen can't move, the pawns are awkward. } { [%csl Bf3,Ba5,Ba2,Bd4,Bg5][%cal Gd6a6,Gd5b4,Gc3d5,Gg7d4,Yg5d8,Gf8f7,Gc3a2] } 21. Bc4 { Protects a2, so the rook can finally move. } { [%csl Ba1][%cal Rc4a2] } (21. Nxc3? { Not really possible. This gives Black a passed pawn that is already on the third rank. } 21... bxc3) 21... Rac8 $10 { This is equal. Says the engine. In practical play Black is probably better. } { [%cal Gc3e2,Gd5c3,Gh7h6,Gf8e8,Rc4b3] }) 19. Kh1 (19. Bc4? { doesn't help: } { [%cal Re2d4,Rd2d4] } 19... Nxe2+ 20. Bxe2 Qxd4+ 21. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 22. Kh1 Bxa1! $17) 19... Nb6 { The d-pawn and the knight should not be on the same file when Black takes on d4. } { [%cal Gb6a4] } (19... Nxe2?! { This is too early: } 20. Bxe2 Qxd4 21. Qxd4 Bxd4 22. Rad1 { This is why 19…Nb6 is so important. Black cannot avoid losing material here: } { [%cal Rd1d7] } 22... Bf6 23. Bxf6 Nxf6 24. Rd6! Ne8 25. Rxa6 $14 { This is better White. }) 20. a5 Nbd5 21. Bc4 Rac8 { The idea is to overprotect the knight on c3. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Gc8c4,Gc8c3] } 22. Bb3 h6 { Push the bishop away from the c1-h6 diagonal. } 23. Bh4 Rfe8 { Attack the knight which is protecting d4. } { [%cal Ge8e2,Gc3e2,Re2d4] } 24. Rfe1 Qc7 { Step off the d-file to avoid any threats on that file after d4 has been taken. Also Look at the weak a5-pawn. } { [%cal Gc7a5] } 25. Rac1 { And now Black can finally start a series of exchanges: } 25... Qxa5 26. Nxc3 bxc3 27. Rxe8+ Rxe8 28. Qd3 { [%csl Bd5][%cal Rd3c4,Bc4d5] } 28... Rb8 $10 { Very equal, still some tension. }) 17. Kh1 { [%csl Be3][%cal Gd5e3,Rg5e3] } 17... h6 { [%csl Be3][%cal Gd5e3,Rg5e3] } 18. Bd2 { [%csl Be3][%cal Rd2e3,Gd5e3] } 18... Bb5! { [%cal Gb5d3] } 19. Nb2 (19. Bxb5? axb5 20. Nb2 Nb8! { [%cal Gb8c6] } 21. Nd3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4,Gg7d4,Re2d4] } 22. Nf2 Rfd8 { [%cal Gg7a1] } 23. Rc1 { Required! The bishop on d4 after the exchange would drive the rook away anyway. } 23... Rxa2 { Now Black can't take d4 immediately, because that would lose h6. } { [%cal Gc6d4,Re2d4,Bd2h6,Bg7d4] } 24. Ne4 { [%cal Re4d6] } 24... Qc7 $15) 19... Bxd3 { Time to trade off the light-squared bishops. } 20. Nxd3 Rfe8 { Black still wants to play Ne3 eventually. And even that doesn't happen: The open files on both sides of the isolani are usually what White wants to own. } { [%csl Be3][%cal Gd5e3,Ge8e2,Gc8c2] } 21. Rc1 a5 $10 { Equal, with an edge for Black who has more space. }) 15... Qd5 $146 { [%csl Gg2][%cal Gd5g2] } (15... Qc6 { is basically the same idea. But it allows White to play Rc1 with a tempo. } 16. f3 Nd5 17. Rc1 Qf6 { The bishop has to move. } { [%cal Gf6f4,Gd5f4] } 18. Bd2 { [%cal Rd2b4,Gd5b4] } 18... a5 $10 $146 { Equal, but White has a bit more space than in the Qd5 line. }) 16. f3 { is still forced. } 16... Rfe8 { Black's idea here is Nh5! Then the bishop had to move. } { [%cal Gf6h5] } 17. Bg3 { Now White's bishop is safe, and it can help protecting the d-pawn from f2. The downside is that Black can now take over the c1-h6 diagonal: } { [%cal Rg3f2] } 17... Bh6! $10 { Black is still down one pawn, but they have the initiative and more space. All in all: equal but not drawish. } { [%cal Gh6e3,Be3d4,Bd5d4,Rg1h1,Rb2b3,Ra4b2] } *


