1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Bg7 { Fianchetto gambit. Instead of taking the pawn back with Nxd5, as we have seen in the previous chapters, Black fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop immediately.
Note how Black has developed two pieces already and is only one step away from castling. } 7. Bc4 { White decides to keep the first d-pawn for a while. Spoiler: It doesn't work. } 7... O-O 8. Nge2 { Main move. The main response for Black here is Nbd7, a move that I consider a bit anti-positional: White's idea is Nf4, an additional defender for d5. So Black needs an additional attacker. The knight should go to c7, the light-squared bishop to b7. } { [%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c7,Bc8b7,Re2f4,Rf4d5,Yf6d5,Yd8d5,Yc7d5,Yb7d5,Rc3d5,Rc4d5] } (8. Nf3 Nbd7 { This knight goes to b6, a motif we can see in many fianchetto lines here. } { [%cal Gd7b6] } 9. O-O Nb6 { Harassing the bishop is a nice side effect. Bb3 is the main move here and the best one. Qe2 is the second best, but no one has ever found it. Some people play Qb3. Let's see. } { [%cal Gb6c4,Gb6d5] } 10. Bb3 (10. Qb3?! { Black can either just take the bishop, or go for d5. } 10... Nxc4 (10... Bf5 { The idea here is to drive the light-squared bishop per Rc8 away and to get the d5-pawn. } { [%cal Ga8c8] } 11. Re1 Rc8 12. Bf1 Nfxd5 { Now the material is even. Temporarily. White should really avoid any further pieces trades, because an endgame with the isolani will be difficult. And yet, most people play Nxd5 here, because that wins a pawn. Bd2 is better. } 13. Bd2 $146 (13. Nxd5 Qxd5 (13... Nxd5 14. Qxb7 { [%cal Rb7a7] } 14... a5 15. a3 Rb8 16. Qa6 Qc7 $10) 14. Rxe7 Be6 { Tucking the rook in. The threat is Qd6! } { [%cal Gd5d6] } 15. Qxd5 Bxd5 { Bf6 is now coming, so White should just retreat with the rook. } { [%cal Gg7f6] } 16. Re2 $146 Rfd8 $10 { Black will win d4. White's second rook is still not in game, so it can't help out. This is equal. } { [%cal Gd5f3,Bd8d4] }) 13... Be6 { [%cal Ge6b3] } 14. Rxe6! { This looks a bit odd, but it creates an interesting positional imbalance and very weak pawns on Black's side. And White has the bishop pair - enough compensation for the exchange sacrifice. } (14. Ng5 { [%cal Rg5e6,Re1e6] } 14... Nc7 { [%cal Ge6b3] } 15. Nxe6 Nxe6 { Attacking the d-pawn. } { [%cal Ge6d4,Gg7d4,Gd8d4] } 16. Be3 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. Nb5 { White will get the pawn back. } { [%cal Rb5d4,Rb5a7] } 18... Bc5 { Protect e7. } { [%cal Gc5e7] } 19. Nxa7 Ra8 $10 { This is equal. White doesn't have to worry about the isolani anymore. }) (14. Qa3 { [%cal Ra3a7] } 14... a6 15. Rac1 Nxc3 { [%cal Gg7d4] } 16. bxc3 Nc4 { [%cal Gc4d2,Gc4a3] } 17. Bxc4 Rxc4 $10) 14... fxe6 15. Re1 { Develops the rook with a tempo. } { [%cal Re1e6] } 15... Nc7 { Black has to defend now for a while. } { [%cal Gc7e6,Gg7d4,Gd8d4] } 16. Bg5 { [%cal Rg5e7] } 16... Nbd5 $10 { This is equal, but Black's side is clearly harder to play. }) 11. Qxc4 b6 { If White doesn't respond to the threat Bb7 immediately, Black wins d5. } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 12. Bg5 { is that response. } 12... Bb7 13. Bxf6 exf6 $15 { is better than Bxf6 for a very simple reason: Now Black doesn't have to protect this pawn anymore, and there is access to the e-file.
Black has now the only bishops on the board in a game with a semi-open center. This is already very good. And a good reason for White not to play 10.Qb3. }) (10. Qe2 $146 { The difference to Qb3 is that Bf5 is not a good option here for Black. } 10... Nxc4 (10... Bf5?! { Playable, but White comes a bit better out of this. } 11. Re1 { [%cal Re2e7] } 11... Rc8 12. Bb3 Nbxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qb5 { [%cal Rb3d5,Rb5d5,Gd8d5] } 14... Nb6) 11. Qxc4 { Transposes to the Qb3 line. }) 10... Nfxd5 (10... Nbxd5 { Main move. Nfxd5 is a bit better. } 11. Re1 b6 { Prepare the fianchetto. } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 12. Bg5 { Main move. } 12... Bb7 13. Ne5 Rc8 { White has to protect c3 now. Nxd5 would exchange too much material. } { [%cal Gd5c3,Gc8c3] } 14. Rc1 { There are 4 games in the database, and in all games Black played the dubious Rc7 here. My recommendation is } (14. Qd3 { Paul Keres played this 1969 in a Sicilian/Hyperaccelerated Pterodactyl, and the game was over 7 moves later: } 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd5?! { Pawns can move forwards! } 16. c4 Nb4 17. Qd2 Bxe5 18. Rxe5 { [%cal Re5e7,Rg5e7] } 18... f6 19. Re2 fxg5?! 20. Qxb4 { [%csl Gd4] } 20... Qxd4?? { Pawns can still move forwards! } 21. c5+! { Paul Keres - Alfred Beni, 1969, 1-0. https://lichess.org/0LNybzdu
This game illustrates how difficult the whole position is after 10.Bb3. Black has to be very careful with their captures. } { [%cal Rb4d4,Rb3g8] }) 14... Nxc3 $146 { just to get some tension out of the position. } 15. bxc3) 11. a4 { Now Black should get the light-squared bishop out before it's squares are blocked by a retreating knight. } { [%cal Ra4a5] } (11. h3 { Now where to put Black's light-squared bishop? Bf5 is the main move, but … the bishop doesn't do much there, and it's asking to be attacked. Be6 is more sensible, although it looks a bit odd. The engine favors the latter, but wants a zwischenzug: a5. } 11... a5 { This position has been played only two times so far, and in both cases White played Re1. } { [%cal Ga5a4] } (11... Be6 12. Re1 (12. Ng5?! { has been tried twice, but … } 12... Nxc3 { [%cal Gc3d1] } 13. bxc3 Bd5 14. Bxd5 Qxd5 $15 { and Black is better. }) 12... Rc8 $146 13. Ne4 { Moving the knight to c5, a very typical maneuver in this line. } { [%cal Re4c5] } 13... Nc7 { [%cal Ge6b3] } 14. Bg5 { Preventing e6 later. } { [%cal Rg5e7,Re1e7] } 14... Bxb3 15. Qxb3 $10 { Equal, a lot of tension left. }) (11... Bf5 12. Re1 { [%cal Re1e7] } 12... Rc8 { develop the rook with a tempo on c3. } { [%cal Gc8c3,Gd5c3,Rb2c3] } 13. Bd2 (13. Bg5?! h6 { Berchtenbreiter, M. - Wojtaszek, R., 0-1, European Blitz 2017, https://lichess.org/5D3e6UTp }) 13... Nxc3 $146 { This looks a bit anti-positional, but it keeps the initiative on Black's side, and it preempts Rc1. } (13... Re8?! $14 { The only move that has been played in this position so far. It's too passive. White has now a comfortable choice between Ne5, Rc1 and Nxd5. }) 14. bxc3 Nc4! { Now White can't keep the bishop pair. } { [%cal Gc4d2] } 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 16. Qb3 $14 { This is still a bit better for White: Qc7 provokes Rxe7, Rc7 Bf4, and Rc6 Qxb7. This is why I don't recommend the 11…Bf5 line. } { [%cal Re1e7,Rb3c4,Rb3b7] }) 12. a4 $146 { Stops the threat a5-a4. } (12. Re1 { It's not a bad move, but it's also not very active. } 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 a4 14. Bc2 Be6 { [%cal Ge6d5] } (14... Qc7 $10 { Sedina, Elena - Harika, Dronavalli, 1/2-1/2, Dresden ol (Women) 38th, 2008, https://lichess.org/F532PUPC }) 15. Rxe6! { A motif that we have seen in other lines. } 15... fxe6 $10 { This is still equal, but Black's pawn structure is a liability and enough compensation for the exchange sacrifice. }) 12... h6 { Just prevent Bg5 and all the difficult tactics coming with that move. } 13. Ne5 { Frees the f3 square for White's queen. Black can't prevent Qf3, and the dark-squared bishop is bound to h6. That's why e6 has to be played now to keep the knight on d5 safe. } { [%cal Rd1f3,Bf3d5,Bc3d5,Bb3d5,Gg7h6,Rc1h6,Bd5b7,Bd5f7,Re5f7,Bf3f7] } 13... e6 { A necessary prophylactic move to lower the pressure on f7 and d5. Forcing Black to make this move before the light-squared bishop is developed is already a tiny victory for White. } { [%csl Bc8,Bd5,Bf7] } 14. Re1 { And now Re1 is good. } 14... Ne7 { Regrouping the knights so they are closer to the king in the coming attack. } { [%cal Ge7g6,Ge7f5,Gb6d5] } 15. Bf4 { Get the rook into the game. } { [%cal Ra1c1] } 15... Bd7 $10 { Same idea: Activate the a-rook, and prevent Nb5.
This is equal, but White is pressing at the moment. Kh7 will be necessary soon, Bc6 and Rc8 are other ideas for Black. White should try to attack the king directly. } { [%cal Rc3b5,Rd1d2,Rf4h6,Gg8h7,Gd7c6] }) (11. Re1 { Main move. } 11... Bg4 { Black should use this opportunity to develop the light-squared bishop. } 12. Bg5 (12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 e6 { As we have seen many times before: Once the light-squared bishop is developed, e6 can be played safely. But not earlier. This might be the moment for White to simplify with Nxd5. Or keep the tension with Ne4. } 14. Ne4 { [%cal Rc1g5,Re4f6,Re4d6] } (14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 16. Qxd5 exd5 17. Be3 $10 { This is dead equal. Ian Rogers - Viswanathan Anand, London 1987, ½-½ https://lichess.org/EtDBbLHD. A Closed Catalan! }) 14... h6 { The Bxd4 lines are all very dangerous for Black. My recommendation is therefore not to take d4 yet and to prevent Bg5 instead. } (14... Bxd4 { The problem with this move is that White profits from the open d-file. } { [%cal Re4f6,Re4d6,Gd4b2] } 15. Bg5 { [%cal Re4f6,Re4d6] } 15... Qd7?! { That's a dangerous file. } { [%cal Ra1d1,Rd1d7] } (15... Qb8 $146 16. Rad1 Bg7 (16... Bxb2?! { Too greedy! } 17. Bh6 Qc7 { Looking at the alternatives, giving the exchange is the best Black can do here. } (17... Bg7?? { Disaster! } 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Bxd5 Nxd5 20. Rxd5 exd5 21. Qc3+ f6 22. Nxf6 Kf7 23. Ng4 { [%cal Rc3f6] } 23... Qf4 24. g3 Qg5 25. Qc7+ Kg8 26. Re7 $18) (17... Rc8 18. a4! a5 19. Ng5 { A very simple mate threat. } { [%cal Rf3f7] } 19... Qf4 20. Qxf4 Nxf4 { And now a simple tactic: } 21. Nxf7! Kxf7 22. Bxf4 { [%cal Rb3e6] } 22... Nd5 $14 { White is a pawn down and yet a bit better. Black's pieces are poorly coordinated and vulnerable to tactics. }) 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 $14 { White has the initiative here, Black too many weaknesses. } { [%cal Rf3f6,Rb3d5,Rd1d5,Rd1b1] }) 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5! exd5 19. Nf6+! Kh8 (19... Bxf6?? 20. Qxf6 { This is lost already. } { [%cal Rg5h6,Rf6g7] } 20... Qd8 21. Re7! Qxe7 22. Qxe7 Rfe8 23. Qxb7 $18) 20. Nd7 Re8 21. Nxb8 Rxe1+ 22. Kh2 Rxb8 23. Qxf7 Rf8 24. Qxd5 Rxf2 $10 { Equal, but not drawish at all! The material imbalance here forces both sides to play very accurately. }) (15... Qc7 16. Rac1 Qb8 { has to be played anyway. }) 16. Rad1! { [%cal Rd1d5] } 16... Bxb2?! 17. Bf6 { [%cal Rf6b2] } (17. Bxd5? { Bokros, Albert - Kraft, Volker, 1/2-1/2, Internet Section 08A g/8'+2, 2004, https://lichess.org/ls5p7VsX } { The best continuation wasn't found in: }) 17... Bxf6 18. Bxd5! Bg7 19. Bxb7! { [%cal Rd1d7,Re4f6] } 19... Qc7 20. Bxa8 $16) 15. a4 $146 Rc8 { Create a square for the knight. } { [%csl Ba8,Bc4] } 16. Nc5 { This blocks the rook's view to c4, so Black can either make a new square on d5 or take d4. } 16... Bxd4 (16... Ne7 17. Nxb7 { [%cal Rb7d8] } 17... Qxd4 18. Rd1 Qe5 19. Nd6 { [%cal Rd6c8] } 19... Rcd8 $10 { Equal and fine for Black. }) 17. Nxb7 { [%cal Rb7d8] } 17... Qd7 18. Bxh6 Bxb2 19. Bxf8 Bxa1 20. Nc5! { [%cal Rc5d7,Bf8c5] } 20... Qd8 21. Rxa1 Qxf8 $10 { This is equal, but maybe a bit uncomfortable to play for Black. } { [%cal Ra4a5] }) 12... Qd7 { Black has to step out of the pin in order to play e6. } 13. Nxd5 $146 (13. h3 Bxf3 (13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 e6 16. Rac1 $146 (16. h4 Qc6 { Glek, Igor V - Deviatkin, Andrei, 0-1, Moscow-ch, 2002, https://lichess.org/SnlcKp30 }) 16... h6) 14. Qxf3 e6 { The engine says, White should go into many exchanges on d5 now, give Black an isolani and reach an equal endgame. Igor Glek played Rad1 first and made few exchanges later, but couldn't get more than a draw.
I think Ne4 is the most ambitious try here. } 15. Ne4 $146 { This is dangerous for Black. d4 is hanging, but I don't recommend to take it. } { [%cal Re4f6,Rg5f6,Rf3f6,Gg7d4,Re4c5,Bc5d7] } (15. Bxd5 $146 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 17. Qxd5 exd5 $10) (15. Rad1 Rac8 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Re7 Qb5 { Glek, Igor V - Dausch, Rene, 1/2-1/2, Baden-Baden op, 2001, https://lichess.org/6nChOoHq }) 15... Rac8 (15... h6 { Push the very annoying bishop away. } 16. Bd2 Qe7 { Watch f6 } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge7f6,Re4f6,Rf3f6] } 17. Nc3 { Pin the e-pawn. } { [%cal Re1e7] } 17... Qd7 { and step out of the pin again. White can now go for a move repetition with Ne4, or play } 18. Rac1 Rac8 $10) 16. Nc5 { Very uncomfortable for Black. } { [%cal Rc5d7,Rc5b7,Rg5e7] } 16... Qb5 (16... Qc6 { is slightly better for White } 17. Rac1 { [%cal Rc5e6,Bc1c6] } 17... Qe8 $14 { [%cal Gg7d4] }) 17. Nxb7 Qc6 18. Na5 Qb5 { Now a move repetition per Nb7 Qc6 is possible. Or … } 19. Qe2 { [%cal Rg5d2] } 19... Nc3! { [%cal Gc3e2] } 20. bxc3 Qxg5 $10 { Still equal, but a lot of tension. }) 13... Nxd5 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 e6 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 { [%cal Gd5g5,Gd5f3] } 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. Re7 Bxd4 19. Rxb7 $10 { Now it's Black who has to hold an isolani! Still equal, but probably a bit easier to play for White. }) 11... Be6 (11... a5 { is also fine. } 12. h3 $146 { Prevent the pin. } { [%cal Yc8g4] } (12. Bg5?! { Colding, Ernest - Rogers, Norman, 1/2-1/2, Wilbert Paige Memorial, 2001, https://lichess.org/JxwTs9DS }) 12... Bf5 (12... h6 { Prophylactic move with a similar idea. } { [%cal Rc1g5] } 13. Ne5 { With the threat of Qf3. And that requires the sad move } { [%cal Rd1f3,Bf3d5,Bc3d5,Bb3d5] } 13... e6) 13. Re1 Rc8 14. Ne5 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd5 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 $10 { Equal. White's weakness is now the c-pawn. It should probably be pushed forwards, followed by d4-d5. Black's queen can be harassed a bit now per Ba3, and it's not clear where the best square is. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Rc3c4,Rc1a3,Ra1c1,Gd5d6,Gd6c7] }) 12. Re1 Nxc3 { The whole point of Be6! Trade off some pieces and find better squares for the rest. } 13. bxc3 Bxb3 14. Qxb3 { [%csl Bb7][%cal Rb3b7] } 14... Qd5 15. Qxd5 Nxd5 $10 { White has hanging pawns now. That's a bit easier to play then the IQP, especially with less pieces on the board. These pawns should be pushed forwards. Black's pawn structure is a tiny bit better, and once White's center pawns move, the dark-squared bishop comes to life. }) 8... Na6 { The next moves until move 13 can happen in any order. } { [%cal Re2f4,Re1g1,Ra2a4,Rd1b3,Ga6c7,Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gd8d6] } (8... Nbd7?!) 9. Nf4 (9. O-O { Main move. } 9... Nc7 10. Nf4 { The next step is the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop. } 10... b6 11. a4 (11. Qb3 Bb7 12. Re1 (12. a4 Qd6 { Prevents d5-d6 by White. } { [%csl Bd5] } (12... Rb8 13. Nb5! $146 { A nice idea that hasn't been played so far. Now White can trade d5 for one of Black's pawns. } { [%cal Rb5a7,Rb5c7,Rd5d6] } 13... a5 (13... Nfxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Nxa7 { Black cannot take d4 yet, because Rd8 would be crushing. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Rf1d1] } 15... e6 { changes that. } { [%cal Gg7d4] } 16. Rd1 Ra8 17. Nb5 Bc6 $10 { Equal, but White is still a pawn up. } { [%cal Gc6b5] }) 14. d6 Nxb5 (14... exd6 15. Nxc7 Qxc7 16. Be3 { [%cal Re3b6,Rb3b6] } 16... Be4 17. Rfe1 Qb7 18. d5! g5 { Now it's getting sharp. } 19. Ne2 Bxd5 20. Bxg5 Bxc4 21. Qxc4 Qe4 { [%cal Ge4c4] } 22. Qd4 { [%cal Re2d4] } 22... Qg6 $14 { White is a tiny bit better here, mostly due to the pawn structure. } { [%cal Gg6g5] }) 15. dxe7 Qxe7 16. Bxb5 Rbc8 17. Be3 Rfd8 $10 { Black is still one pawn down here, but the structure is much easier to play than in the 14…exd6 line. }) 13. Re1 { Takes the semi-open e-file and puts a bit pressure on e7. } { [%cal Re1e7] } 13... Rfd8 $10 { More pressure on d5. Now White can (and probably should) give up d5, or play Re5 and "shoulder" the pawn. } { [%cal Gf6d5,Gc7d5,Gb7d5,Rf4d5,Rc3d5,Rc4d5,Rb3d5,Gd6d5,Gd8d5] } 14. Nd3 $146 { Giving up d5 immediately seems to be the most pragmatic option. } { [%cal Rd3e5] } (14. Re5 $146 { Black doesn't have to go into some serious action here. Just improve the rest. Or play Ng4 for a draw. } 14... a6 $10 { White's problem is: As long as there is a knight on f4, the dark-squared bishop can't be developed properly. And that means, Black can wait! It's up to White to resolve the position in the center.
That's why I think this is at least equal and vertainly easier to play for Black. } { [%csl Bf4] } (14... Ng4 15. Rg5 Nf6 16. Re5 Ng4 $10 { Draw by repetition. })) (14. a5 Rab8 15. axb6 axb6 16. Nb5 $146 { White is trading everything off in this line. } (16. Be3 $146 Ba8 { Keep b6 protected. Note that Black is attacking d5 5 times, while White is defending it only 4 times. This means, White has to give up that pawn now. } (16... Nfxd5 17. Nfxd5 Bxd5 18. Nxd5 (18. Bxd5 Nxd5 19. Ra7 { [%cal Re1e7,Ra7e7] } 19... Bf6 20. h3 { Make some luft. } 20... Rbc8 $10)) (16... Bxd5 17. Nfxd5 Nfxd5 18. Ra7 { [%cal Ra7e7,Re1e7] } 18... e6 { The light-squared bishop is gone, we can play e6. } 19. Bxd5 Nxd5 $10 { Equal material, Black has a slightly better pawn structure. }) 17. Nd3 { Open the diagonal for the bishop and reroute the knight to a more annoying square. } { [%cal Rd3e5] } 17... Nfxd5 18. Ne4 Qd7 19. Ne5 { [%cal Re5d7] } 19... Qe8 $10 { White has bit more space at the moment, Black the better pawn structure. Black's next idea is b5 and maybe Nxe3 to get the bishop pair and move the light-squared bishop to d5. } { [%cal Gb6b5,Gd5e3,Ba8d5] }) (16. Qa3?! Qxa3 17. Rxa3 b5! $146 { Engine suggestion. The idea is to distract a defender for d5. } { [%cal Bc4d5,Bc3d5,Rc4b5,Rc3b5] } (17... Ncxd5 $146 { [%cal Gd5e7] } 18. h3 { Make some luft. } 18... Rbc8 { [%cal Gc8c4] } 19. Bb3 Rd7 $10) 18. Rxe7 { [%cal Re7c7,Gb5c4] } (18. Nxb5 Nxb5 { Tempo on the rook. } { [%cal Gb5a3] } 19. Bxb5 Nxd5 { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd5e7] } 20. Rb3 (20. Bc4 Bxd4 $10) 20... Nxf4! 21. Bxf4 Bd5 { [%cal Gd5b3,Rf4b8] } 22. Bxb8 Bxb3 { [%cal Gd8b8] } 23. Re3 Bxd4 24. Rxb3 Rxb8 $10 { Material is equal, Black's pawns are easier to defend, because they are all connected, but White has a passed pawn which is the center of attention now. } { [%cal Gd4b2] }) 18... Nfe8! { The only good move here! } 19. Nxb5 (19. d6 Rxd6 20. Bxb5 Nxb5 21. Nxb5 { [%cal Rb5d6] } 21... Rb6 { [%cal Gb6b5] } 22. Rae3! { [%csl Re8][%cal Re7e8] } 22... Nf6 23. Nc3 Bf8 { [%cal Gf8e7] } 24. R7e5 Bd6 { And now the rook can't hide anymore, because the knight on f4 is unprotected. } { [%cal Gd6f4] } 25. h3 Ra6 { Just add threats! } { [%cal Ga6a1] } 26. Re1 Bxe5 27. dxe5 Nd7 $15 { Black is down two pawns but up one exchange. White's pawns on the e- and b-file are hard to defend, and Ra1 will be very annoying. } { [%cal Ga6a1] }) 19... Nxb5 20. Bxb5 Bf8! { [%cal Gf8a3] } 21. Re1 (21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. Bxe8 Bxa3 23. bxa3 Rxe8 24. Bd2 Rd8 $15 { Three pawns down, an exchange up, but this is good for Black. White cannot hold the isolated pawns with two pieces that don't coordinate so well. }) 21... Bxa3 22. bxa3 { [%cal Rb5e8,Re1e8] } 22... Nc7 { [%cal Gc7b5,Gc7d5,Gb7d5,Gd8d5] } 23. Bd3 Nxd5 $15 { This is great for Black. Exchanging White's last rook is the next goal, and after that an attack on the isolated pawns. }) 16... Nxb5 17. Qxb5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 Rxd5 21. Rxe7 Bxd4 $10 { White should make some luft for the king now with g3. } { [%cal Rg2g3] }) 14... Nfxd5 15. Ne4 { [%cal Re4d6] } 15... Qc6 16. Ne5 { Hitting the queen again. } { [%cal Re5c6] } 16... Bxe5 { is the best response, says Stockfish. Not sure how good that is in practical play. the dark-squared bishop is needed later. } (16... Qe8 17. Qh3! { [%cal Rh3h7,Re4g5,Bg5h7] } 17... f6 { Not a nice move to make, but necessary here. Note that the knight on d5 is now pinned. } { [%cal Rc4g8] } 18. Nd3 Rac8 { [%cal Ge8d7] } (18... Qd7 { Maybe too early? } 19. Qh4 g5 20. Qh5 Qe8 21. Qg4 Rac8 22. h4 Qd7 23. Qxd7 Rxd7 24. hxg5 Ne6 25. gxf6 exf6 $14 { White is just better here. Black's position is very uncomfortable. }) 19. Bd2 { Connect the rooks, maybe bring the bishop to c3. } { [%cal Rd2c3] } 19... Kh8 { [%cal Gc8c4] } 20. Bb3 { Step out of any discovery attacks. } { [%cal Gc8c4] } 20... Qd7 { The difference to 18…Qd7 is that White's light-squared bishop isn't on c4 anymore, so now after Qh4 Black has Ba6! } 21. Qxd7 (21. Qh4 Ne6 { Attacking the unprotected d4. } { [%cal Ge6d4] } (21... Ba6 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Ga6d3] } 22. Nf4 Nxf4 23. Bxf4 Nd5 { [%cal Gd5f4] } 24. Bd2 Bd3) 22. Nc3 { [%cal Rh4d4] } 22... Nxd4! { And take it anyway! } 23. Qxd4 e5! 24. Nxe5 (24. Qh4?! Ne7 { One of these pieces will fall. } { [%csl Bd3,Bd2][%cal Gd7d3] } 25. Bc2 { This is just a temporary protection. } 25... Nf5! { [%cal Gf5h4,Bf5h6] } 26. Qg4 Nd4 { [%cal Gd4c2,Gd4b3,Gd7g4] } 27. Bd1 { [%cal Rd1g4] } (27. Qxd7 Rxd7 28. Bd1 { White has to cover b3 to prevent a knight fork there. } { [%csl Bb3][%cal Gd4b3,Bb3a1,Bb3d2] } 28... Nf5 { [%cal Gd7d3] } 29. Be2 e4 { And here White has to give the piece back. } { [%csl Bd2,Bd3][%cal Gd7d2,Ge4d3] } 30. Nxe4 Bxe4 31. Bc3 Rxd3! (31... Bxd3?! 32. Rad1 { [%cal Re2d3,Rd1d3] } 32... Rcd8 33. Bxd3 { [%cal Rd3c2,Bc2d1,Re1e8] } 33... Rxd3 34. Rxd3 Rxd3 35. Re8+ Bf8 36. Rxf8+ Kg7 { [%cal Gd3d1] } 37. Re8 Kf7 38. Re1 $10 { Very equal. }) 32. Bxd3 Bxd3 33. Rad1 Bc2 { [%cal Gc2a4] } 34. Rd7 { [%cal Rd7a7] } 34... a5 35. Rb7 Kg8 $15 { Prophylactic move, avoiding any backrank mate threats.
Black is slightly better here, having one piece more. }) 27... Qxg4 28. Bxg4 { [%cal Rg4c8] } 28... Nf5 { [%cal Gd8d3] } 29. Nxe5 { Just give back the piece immediately. It can't be avoided anyway. Black has a choice now. The knight is stronger than the bishop here, But taking the bishop gives Black the only bishop pair. Both decisions are fine. } (29. Be2 e4! { [%csl Bd2][%cal Gd8d2] } 30. Bg4 Rxd3 31. Be3 { [%cal Ra4a5] } 31... Rb8 { Make a5 less attractive. } 32. Bxf5 { Damage Black's pawn structure. } 32... gxf5 $15 { Black is one pawn up. That and the bishop pair makes their position a tiny bit better. White should try a5 next with the idea to break through on the queenside and maybe win a pawn back. }) 29... fxe5 (29... Rxd2 30. Nf7+ Kg8 31. Bxf5 gxf5 { The knight is trapped here. } { [%csl Bd6][%cal Gg8f7,Bd2d6,Rf7d6] } 32. Rad1 Rxb2 33. Re7 { [%cal Re7b7] } 33... Rc2 34. Rxb7 R2xc3 $10 { Pretty much equal. White has to play g3 next to avoid backrank mate. Then the pawn on a7 might fall. } { [%cal Gc3c1,Gc8c7] }) 30. Red1 Bf6 { [%cal Gf6d8] } 31. a5 h5 $10) 24... fxe5 25. Qd3 e4! (25... Nb4 26. Qxd7 Rxd7 { [%cal Gd7d2] } 27. Red1 { [%cal Rb3e6,Be6c8] } 27... Rcd8 28. Bg5 Rxd1+ 29. Bxd1 $10) 26. Nxe4 Nf6 27. Qxd7 Rxd7 28. Be6 Nxe4 29. Bxd7 Rd8 $10) 21... Rxd7 22. Rac1 { [%cal Rc1c8] } 22... e6 $10 { Completely equal. })) 12... Qd6 { Prevent d5-d6. } 13. a4 { transposes into the 12.a4 line. }) 11... Bb7 12. Qb3 Qd6 13. Re1 { transposes into the 11.Qb3 line. }) 9... Nc7 10. O-O b6 11. a4 Bb7 12. Qb3 Qd6 13. Re1 Rfd8 *


