1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 g6?! { This is probably too early. Let's call it the Accelerated Fianchetto Defense. This will either transpose to one of the main lines in the Fianchetto Defense, or to a very unique and open game after 5.cxd5 Qxd5. I do not recommend this line for Black. } 5. cxd5 (5. Nc3 Nf6 { Transposes to the normal Fianchetto defense }) 5... Qxd5?! { This is the unique setup I was talking about. And as in the Scandinavian, White can now develop the knight with a tempo on the queen. } (5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg7 { transposes to the ➡ Fianchetto Gambit }) 6. Nc3 Qd8 7. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7] } (7. Nf3?! { not aggressive enough. } 7... Bg7) 7... Bg7 8. Qb3 { [%cal Rc4f7] } 8... e6 9. d5 { What a convinient way to get rid of the IQP. Black shouldn't make this so easy for White. } 9... exd5 $14 { White is already better here: 3 active pieces and a serious threat. } 10. Nxd5 (10. Bxd5 { Two threats, one move to deal with them: } { [%cal Rd5f7,Rb3d5,Rd5b7,Rb3b7] } 10... Qe7+ 11. Be3 (11. Nge2 Nf6 12. O-O O-O 13. Bg5 $14 { Rohl Montes, Juan Armando - Gabarro Sole, Ramon, 1-0, Barcelona op rap, 1996, https://lichess.org/bioBb6fN }) 11... Nf6 12. Nf3 O-O 13. O-O Nc6 $146 (13... Na6?! 14. Rad1 Nc7 15. Bg5 { Petschar, Kurt - Kraschl, Joerg, 1-0, AUT-ch, 1994, https://lichess.org/nhDvraaV }) 14. Rfe1 { [%cal Re1e7] } 14... Qb4 15. Qxb4 Nxb4 16. Bb3 b6 $14 { White has an edge here, not much, but Black's pieces are not so well coordinated. } { [%cal Gc8b7,Ra2a3,Rh2h3,Gc8g4,Gb4c6] }) 10... Nf6 (10... Nc6? 11. Bf4 Nd4 12. Qg3! { [%cal Rd5c7,Rc7e8,Rc7a8] } (12. Qe3+? Be6 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. Ne2 { Yemelin, Vasily - Rumiantsev, Anton, 1-0, Chigorin Memorial 13th, 2005, https://lichess.org/kuXnIc5p } { Godena, Michele - Nemet, Ivan, 1/2-1/2, Reggio Memorial Chicco 33rd, 1991, https://lichess.org/znSSQEwv })) 11. Qe3+ Be6 12. Nf4 Bh6 $14 *


