1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 { Panov Attack/Modern Defense. } 6. Bg5 Qa5 { Czerniak Line } 7. Bxf6 (7. Bd2) (7. Be2) (7. Nf3) (7. Qd2) 7... exf6 8. cxd5 { And now White's IQP is a passed pawn. But Black can enforce some material trades now. } 8... Bb4! { [%cal Ga5d5] } 9. Qd2 (9. Qe2+?! Ne7 10. Qb5+ Bd7 11. Qxa5 Bxa5) 9... Ne7 (9... Bxc3?! { This gives White a protection for d4. } 10. bxc3 Qxd5 11. Ne2 (11. Nf3?! O-O (11... Bh3?! { A dubious attempt to be clever. Yes, it keeps White's light-squared bishop in place, but } 12. gxh3 Qxf3 13. Qe3+ Qxe3+ 14. fxe3 $14 { look at White center! The doubled h-pawns don't matter when you have such a gret center. } { [%cal Rd4d8] }) 12. Be2 Bg4 13. O-O Na5 14. Rfe1 (14. Qf4?! { Now the knight really pinned. } 14... Bh5 (14... Rfe8 { [%cal Ge8e4] } 15. Bd3 { [%csl Be4][%cal Rd3e4] } 15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 (16. gxf3 { Doesn't really change the situation. White cannot avoid the queen trade. } 16... Qg5+ 17. Qxg5 fxg5 $15) 16... Qxf3 17. gxf3 Rac8 $15 { Janosevic, Dragoljub - Nikolac, Juraj, 0-1, YUG-chT 31st, 1979, https://lichess.org/r87TbRwK } { This is good for Black, because White's pawns structure leads to a very defensive play. } { [%cal Gc8c3] }) 15. Rfb1 { [%cal Rb1b7] } 15... a6 16. Rb6 { [%cal Rb6d6] } 16... Rfd8 17. g4 Bg6 18. Nd2 Rac8 $10 { Van der Sterren, Paul - Nikolac, Juraj, 1/2-1/2, Eerbeek Henspapier, 1978, https://lichess.org/b0aW72st }))) 10. Bb5+ (10. Bc4) 10... Qxb5 11. Nxb5 Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Nxd5 *


