1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nc6 { This is a very rare, but playable sideline. Here it is Black who gets an IQP! } 5. Nc3 (5. cxd5 Qxd5 { This is a common position in the Sicilian Defense/Alapin Variation } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 6. Nf3 Bg4 (6... e5 7. Nc3 { [%cal Rc3d5] } 7... Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 e4 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ne7 $10) 7. Nc3 Bxf3 8. gxf3 Qxd4 9. Qxd4 Nxd4 10. Nb5 $10) 5... e5! { This is a nice surprise move. It's better than it looks (which is easy). White's best option is to keep the tension and play Nf3. } (5... Nf6 { is the main move, and this is a transposition to the Panov/Modern Defense }) 6. Nf3 { Is the best move … says the engine. } (6. dxe5 { This is the move most people play. The response is the move that we know from the Albin Countergambit: } 6... d4! 7. Nd5 { the only move that has been played in this position. It's also the best. } 7... Nge7 { [%cal Ge7d5,Gd8d5] } 8. Bg5 { pinning the knight. } { [%cal Rg5d8] } 8... Be6 { pressure the knight again } { [%cal Ge6d5] } (8... h6 $146 9. Bxe7 Bxe7 10. f4 Be6 11. Nf3 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Bd3 $14) 9. Nf3 $146 h6 10. Bxe7 Bxe7 11. Bd3 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Qa5+! { Force White's king to move and lose castling rights. White's knight has to hold e5, and the queen is vulnerable to Bb4. } { [%cal Gc6e5,Ge7b4,Rf3e5] } 13. Ke2 Qxd5 { Now e5 is under attack, and White can either prevent that (for the moment) per Qb3, or counterattack d4 per Qa4. } { [%cal Gd5e5,Gc6e5] } 14. Qb3 (14. Qa4?! O-O { This also unpins the knight and renews the threat Nxe5. } { [%csl Bc6][%cal Gc6e5] } 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 $10 { This is completely equal. } { [%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8,Gd8d4,Ge8e5,Ge7c5,Rd3b5,Rd3e4,Ra1c1,Rc1c6,Rh1d1,Rd1d4] }) 14... O-O-O { [%cal Gd8d5] } 15. Qxd5 Rxd5 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gd5e5] } 16. Rac1 { Pin the knight. } { [%cal Rc1c8] } 16... Bg5 17. Rc4 Kb8 { [%cal Gc6e5] } 18. Be4 d3+ 19. Kd1 Ra5 { [%cal Ga5a2] } 20. h4 Be7 21. Bxc6 bxc6 $14 { This is better for White. Black's pawns on c6 and d3 will very likely fall. } { [%csl Bc6,Bd3] }) (6. cxd5 Nxd4) 6... exd4 $146 { Black takes. Of course! Oddly enough, this is a novelty. } (6... Bb4?! { was played in Mark Hebden - Andrew Martin, 1984. Hebden won that game. }) 7. Nxd4 Nf6 { And this transposes to a known position that is usually a result of an English Opening/King's English/Two Knights. 13 games in the database.
White should start exchanging some material. } { [%cal Gf6d5] } 8. Nxc6 (8. cxd5 Nxd5 { It's rare to see a completely symmetrical position on move 8. And as it is in symmetrical opening or middle game positions: the side with the move has a slight edge. } 9. Nxc6 bxc6 { Disconnect Black's queenside pawns. } 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Qxd5 cxd5 $10 { Playing an IQP with so little material left is not easy for Black. But … this is a passed pawn now. It's up to Black to prove that this is an asset and not a liability. }) (8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. cxd5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 O-O $10) 8... bxc6 9. Bd3 $146 (9. cxd5 Nxd5) 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 (10. Qe2+ { Avoids the queen trade. } 10... Be7 11. Bxc4 O-O) 10... Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Bg4+ 12. f3 O-O-O+ 13. Ke2 Re8+ 14. Kf1 Be6 15. Ba6+ Kc7 $10 { Equal position, but still enough material to fight for three results. } { [%cal Rc1e3,Gf6d5] } *


