1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. c5 { Gunderam Attack. White tries to use its pawn majority on the queen side for an immediate attack. Nc6 is the most played move, but b6 and e5 are better for Black.
The basic problem for White here is that Black's pawn on d5 is now very strong for quite some time. } { [%cal Rf1b5,Rd1a4] } 5... b6 (5... e5?! { Is a dubious counter attack. } 6. dxe5?! { Nd7 attacks both pawns. Ne4 is an annoying outpost that can only be attacked with Nc3 (White gets doubled pawns) or f3 (weakens the king side to which White needs to castle), Ng4 can be kicked away with h3, again weakening the king side. } { [%cal Gf6g4,Bg4e5,Gf6d7,Bd7e5,Bd7c5,Gf6e4] } (6. Nc3 exd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 { Black has now the initiative. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 8. Bb5 { Develop instead of running away with the queen. } 8... Be7 { c5 is a liability for White, it has to do something about it soon. } { [%csl Rc5] } 9. Be3 (9. Nf3?! O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. O-O Nd7 12. b4 a5 13. Ba3 $17 { The bishop is just a pawn now. }) 9... O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qa4 { [%cal Ra4c6] } 11... Rb8 { [%cal Gb8b2] } 12. b4 $17 Ng4!) (6. Be3 Ng4 7. Nc3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4,Ge5d4] } 8. Bb5 Be7 9. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5,Rd4e5] } 9... e4 10. Ng1!? $10) 6... Ne4 { [%cal Ge4c5,Gf8c5] } 7. Nc3 (7. Bd3 { A crazy line that has never been played like here. I have added it just for fun. You'll see in a moment why. } 7... Bxc5 8. Bxe4 Qh4 { [%cal Gh4e4,Gh4f2,Gc5f2] } 9. Qxd5 Qxf2+ 10. Kd1 Bg4+ 11. Nf3 Qxg2 12. Re1 Nc6 13. Re2 Bf2 14. Qxf7+! Kxf7 15. Ng5+! Ke7 16. Bxg2 Rad8+ 17. Bd2 Nd4 { [%cal Gg4e2,Gd4e2] } 18. Bf3 Nxf3 19. Rxf2 Nxd2+ 20. Kc2 Nxb1 21. Rxb1 Rhf8 { [%cal Gg4f5,Bf5c2,Bf5h7] } 22. Rxf8 Rxf8 23. Rg1 $17) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nc6 { Keep the tension, attack another pawn. } { [%cal Gc6e5,Gf8c5] } 9. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] } 9... Bxc5 10. Be2 { [%cal Re1g1] } 10... O-O 11. O-O $10) (5... Nc6 { is the most played move. But there are less than 300 games with 5.c5, so every statistic is useless. } 6. Bb5 (6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Be2 Qc7 { Prevents Bf4 } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gc7f4] } (7... e6 { looks natural, but } 8. Bf4 { is a very annoying move. } { [%cal Rf4b8] } 8... Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O Ne4 { [%cal Ge7f6] })) 6... e5 { is more aggressive, but again: Black will end up with an IQP. } (6... Bd7 { is very passive } 7. Nf3 { White has a good game here. } 7... g6 { might be a plan: attack d4 from the flank. } 8. O-O Bg7 9. Nc3 O-O { This is equal, White might even have a slight edge. }) 7. dxe5 { [%csl Bd5] } 7... Ne4 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc5 { [%cal Gd8b6] } 10. Nf3 Qb6 11. Nd4 O-O { [%cal Gc5d4,Gb6b5] } 12. Bxc6 bxc6 $15 { Black is slightly better here. }) (5... g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Be2 { This will just peter out. } (8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] } 9... Ne4 (9... Nc6) 10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 b6)) 6. b4 (6. Bb5+ { is an interesting troll move. } 6... Bd7 { is forced, otherwise White plays c6! } (6... Nbd7?? 7. c6 e6 8. cxd7+ Bxd7 $18) 7. Bxd7+ (7. cxb6 { is a very cheap trap. } 7... Qxb6 (7... Bxb5?? 8. b7! { and White wins the rook. } 8... Nc6 9. bxa8=Q Qxa8 $16) 8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 9. Nf3 e6 $17 { Black is better here. White has an IQP and not the material to play it properly. Black is also ahead in development. }) 7... Nbxd7 8. b4 bxc5 9. bxc5 e5 10. c6! Nb8 11. dxe5 { Black has an IQP now, and to be honest: I wouldn't want to play this as Black. It's technically okay, but not so easy in practice. } 11... Ne4 12. Nf3 Nxc6 13. O-O Be7 14. Ba3 $10 Rc8 (14... O-O 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 { [%cal Ga8c8] } 16. Nbd2 Ng6 17. Re1 Nc3 $10) 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Nbd2 Nc3 17. Qb3 O-O $10) 6... bxc5 7. bxc5 e5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. dxe5 Ne4 11. Ba3 Bxc5 12. Bxc5 Nxc5 13. Ne2 $10 { [%csl Gc6,Rf4][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6e5,Re2f4,Bd1d5,Bf4d5] } 13... O-O 14. O-O Nc6 { Black is more than fine here. The plan is to push the IQP down the board, and to occupy the the files on both sides of the pawn with rooks. There is probably not enough material left for the typical attack on White's f-pawn. } { [%cal Gd5d1,Gf8e8,Ga8c8] } *


