1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Qb3?! { B10 Accelerated Panov/Van Weersel Attack.
White sacrifices a pawn for activity and pressure on f7 and b7. This is similar to the French Defense/Orthoschnapp Gambit (1.e4 e6 2.c4 d5 3.cxd5 exd5 4.Qb3). The difference is that Black can still play e6 in the Caro-Kann and protect f7 in a simple way. } 4... dxe4 5. Bc4 { You will find not many games in an OTB database. The first one is Arlette Van Weersel - Julia Laurens, Faber Cup 2001. Hence the name of the line.
https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arlette_van_Weersel } { [%cal Rc4f7] } 5... e6 { Now the light-squared bishop cannot move for a while, but Black is a pawn up, and that pawn hinders White's development. } { [%csl Bf3][%cal Rg1f3,Ge4f3] } 6. Nc3 { Main move, but not the best. White should not try to get back the pawn. } (6. d3 { Distract the pawn in order to the knight on the kingside developed. } 6... exd3 7. Nf3 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 9. Rd1 O-O 10. Bxd3 { Careful now! } { [%cal Rd3h7,Rd1d8] } 10... Bd7 11. Bf4 (11. Qxb7 Bc6 12. Qb3 (12. Bxh7+?? Nxh7 13. Rxd8 Bxb7 14. Rxf8+ Kxf8 $19) 12... Nbd7)) *


