{ In this chapter I'd like to recommend you the lines that you should learn first. }
1. e4 c6 { It's up to White here how to proceed. } 2. d4 { Just play d5 here. } { [%cal Gd7d5] } (2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 { is the Two Knights Attack, and my recommendation is Nf6. } (3. d4 { transposes to the Main Line } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4) 3... Nf6 { See the chapter ➡Two Knights Attack: Nf6 }) (2. c4 { The Accelerated Panov. This is what I play with White against the Caro-Kann, hoping for d5. My recommendation for Black is therefore } 2... e5! { See ➡Accelerated Panov/Open Variation }) (2. Nf3 { Is a rare move otb, but you get it sometimes online. See ➡ King's Knight Opening } 2... g6 { Go for the fianchetto. It's easy to play and to learn. }) 2... d5 { and see what happens next. } 3. e5 { is the Advance Variation, and now you have to pick one of two options: Bf5 or c5. My recommendation is c5, the ➡ Botvinnik-Carls Defense. } (3. Nc3 { In this case I recommend to take a look at g6, the ➡Gurgendidze System } 3... g6 { The reason is: The fianchetto systems work in many cases, and they feature similar ideas, so they are quite easy to learn and to reuse. } (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { is the Main Line, and here you can play the ➡Karpov Variation : } 4... Nd7 (4... Bf5 { or the main, main line ➡ Spassky Variation } 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3))) (3. exd5 { is the Exchange Variation, and here you have to look at the Panov Attack and the Bd3 line. } 3... cxd5 4. c4 { ➡Panov Attack } (4. Bd3 { ➡Exchange Variation/4.Bd3 })) (3. Nd2 { This is the "new" main line. You should not try the Gurgenidze System against that. Take the d-pawn instead. } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { And here I recommend the ➡ Karpov Variation or the ➡ Spassky Variaton. } 4... Nd7) 3... c5 { Over the board, you will most likely see dxc5 here. But online many players will not take the pawn and play something else. You have to prepare for both. } (3... Bf5 { is also fine, but then you have to learn the ➡Van der Wiel/Shirov Attack and how to respond properly. Not so easy. }) *


