{ "The opening is named after the English player Horatio Caro and the Austrian player Marcus Kann who analysed it in 1886." —Wikipedia. 1.e4 c6 has been played much earlier. For a historical overview see http://www.chesshistory.com/winter/extra/carokann.html }
1. e4 (1. Nc3 { A00 Van Geet Opening. Can transpose into a CK with the moves: } 1... d5 2. e4 c6 { Van Geet Opening, Caro-Kann Variation }) 1... c6 { This is already "B10 Caro-Kann Defense". The basic idea here is to support the following d5. This is slower but more solid than the immediate d5 in the Scandinavian defense. Black will often try to develop the light-square bishop first to f5 or g4, White tries to get a hold on the center. } 2. d4 (2. Ne2 Qa5 { Hauge, Lars Oskar - Fedoseev, Vl3, 0-1, 11th World Teams 2017, https://lichess.org/0Ypyd9ld } { A very odd move that you can see online sometimes. Pins the d-pawn for a while. } { [%cal Ga5d2] } (2... d5 3. e5 c5 4. d4 Nc6)) (2. f4 { NN, but not a rare move. I call it the ➡ Bird Variation }) (2. d3 { ➡ Breyer Variation }) (2. c4 { Accelerated Panov Attack } 2... d5 (2... e5 { ➡Accelerated Panov/Open Variation }) (2... g6 { Third-common move, no name. } 3. d4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6) 3. exd5 (3. e5 { ➡ Toikkanen Gambit }) 3... cxd5 4. d4 Nf6) (2. b3 { ➡ Euwe Attack }) (2. Bc4 { ➡ Hillbilly Attack }) (2. b4 { ➡Labahn Attack } 2... e5 (2... d5 3. b5? { Labahn Attack/Double Gambit } 3... dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6) 3. Bb2 { Labahn Attack/Polish Variation } { [%csl Re5,Gb4] } 3... Bxb4) (2. g4?! { Spike Variation } 2... d5 3. Bg2 { Transposes to the Grob Opening }) (2. c3 { Alapin's Variation? } 2... d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. d4 e6 { Just transposing to the Advanced variation. }) (2. g3 { Unnamed, rarely played. Too slow. } 2... d5 3. Bg2 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bg2 { [%cal Ge7e5,Gf8c5] }) (2. Qf3?! e5 3. Bc4 { [%cal Rc4f7,Rf3f7] } 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 Bc5 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 a5 7. a4 b4 8. Nd1 d6 $15) (2. e5 { TODO } 2... d6 3. f4 (3. Nf3 dxe5 4. Nxe5 Nd7 5. Nxd7 (5. f4 { [%cal Rd1h5,Rh5f7,Re5f7] } 5... e6 (5... Nxe5 6. fxe5))) (3. exd6 exd6 (3... e5) 4. d4 d5 5. Nf3 (5. Bd3) 5... Bd6 6. h3 (6. Bd3 Ne7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 $10) (6. c4 Nf6 7. Bd3 dxc4 (7... O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bg4 { Chigaev, M. - Girya, O., 1-0, European Rapid 2014, https://lichess.org/etUEnHS3 }) 8. Qe2+ Be7 9. Bxc4 O-O $10) 6... Bf5 $10) 3... dxe5 4. fxe5 Bf5 $10 5. Nf3 e6) (2. Nc3 g6 (2... d6 3. d4 Nf6 { Transposition to the Czech Defense } 4. f4 Qa5 5. Bd3 e5 6. Nf3 exd4 7. Nxd4) (2... e5 3. d4 d6 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8) (2... b5 { ➡ Gurgenidze Counterattack }) (2... d5 3. Nf3 { ➡ Two Knights Attack } (3. d4 dxe4 4. Nxe4 { ➡ Main Line } 4... Bf5 { Classical Variation }) (3. Qf3 { ➡ Goldmann Variation }) (3. Qe2 d4 4. Nd1 e5 5. g3 Bd6 6. d3) (3. f4 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6) (3. d3 dxe4 (3... d4 4. Nce2 e5) 4. Bg5 { Scorpion-Horus Gambit TODO } 4... exd3 5. Bxd3 h6 6. Bh4 $15 { [%cal Gg8f6,Gd8b6] }) (3. exd5 { Very rare. } 3... cxd5) (3. f3?! { TODO } 3... d4 4. Nce2 e5) (3. g3 { Unnamed sideline. Playable but not very challenging. }) 3... dxe4 4. Ng5 { Hector Gambit }) 3. d4 d5 { ➡ Gurgenidze System }) (2. Nf3 { ➡ King's Knight Variation } 2... d5 3. d4 (3. Nc3 { Transposition to Two Knights Attack }) 3... dxe4 4. Ng5 { Ulysses Gambit. TODO }) 2... d5 (2... g6 { Unnamed sideline. Keep the question of d5 open, fianchetto the dark-squared bishop to enter the Gurgenidze System early. } 3. Nc3 (3. Nf3 d5 (3... d6 4. Bd3 Bg7)) (3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 { The problem here is that d5 allows White to close the center. } 4... d6 (4... d5 5. e5 Nh6)) 3... d5 { ➡ Gurgenidze System }) (2... Na6 { De Bruycker Defense. The idea is to bring that weird knight to c7. Slow, rarely played. TODO }) (2... Nf6 { Masi Variation. TODO } 3. e5 Nd5 { Like an Advance with a knight on d5. Very vulnerable. } 4. c4 Nc7 $16) (2... f5? { Massachussets Defense. TODO } 3. exf5 Qa5+ (3... Nf6 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nf3) 4. Nc3 Qxf5) (2... e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Nf6) (2... b5?! 3. Nf3 e6 4. Bd3) 3. e5 { ➡ Advance Variation } (3. Nd2 { "Modern Variation". This is an attempt to avoid the Gurgenidze System. Otherwise it's like the ➡ Main Line } 3... Qb6 $14 { Edinburgh Vatiation. TODO } { [%cal Gb6d4] }) (3. exd5 { ➡ Exchange Variation } 3... cxd5 4. c4 { ➡ Panov Attack } (4. Bd3 { ➡ Exchange/4.Bd3 }) (4. Nf3 { ➡ Exchange/4.Nf3 }) (4. c3 Nc6 5. Bf4)) (3. f3 { ➡ Maroczy Variation } 3... e6 (3... dxe4 4. fxe4 (4. Nc3) 4... e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Bc4 { Maroczy Variation/Maroczy Gambit } 6... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 7. O-O { Black can't play Nxe4, because then Re1 will pin that knight. } 7... Nbd7 8. c3 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4] } 9. Bb3 dxc3 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nxc3 $10) 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bf4) (3. Bd3 Nf6 { This a very bad response to Bd3. } (3... dxe4 { The only move. } 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nxe4 6. Nxe4 Qd5) 4. e5 Nfd7 5. e6 { Mieses Attack/Landau Gambit. fxe6 would ruin Black's pawn structure. } 5... Nf6 6. exf7+ Kxf7 $16) (3. Be3 { Mieses Gambit. TODO } 3... dxe4 { No idea what the point here is. Black is just better. }) (3. Nc3 dxe4 (3... g6 { ➡ Gurgenidze System }) (3... b5 { ➡ Gurgenidze Counterattack }) (3... a6?! 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. h3) (3... h6?! 4. Nf3 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bf5) (3... e6?! 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 Be7) 4. Nxe4 { ➡ Main Line (Advance is played more often) } (4. f3?! { ➡ Rasa-Studier Gambit }) (4. Bc4?! { ➡ Von Hennig Gambit }) 4... Bf5 (4... h6?! { Finnish Variation }) (4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ (5. Bd3 { ➡ Alekhine Gambit }) 5... exf6 { ➡ Tartakower Variation }) 5. Ng3 Bg6) *


