1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 { This move makes g6, the Gurgenidze System less attractive, because now White can play c3 immediately, and then Black's fianchettoed bishop wouldn't be very useful. } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { Same result. }) 3... dxe4 { And here we see why this line is attractive for White: In contrast to other lines Black doesn't get two center pawns. } (3... b5 { ➡ Gurgenidze Counterattack }) 4. Nxe4 { Nxe4 is the "B15 Caro-Kann Defense: Main Line". It's not the most played line – that award goes to the Advanced variation. From here on, paths split up. } (4. Bc4 { ➡ von Hennig Gambit }) (4. f3 { ➡ Rasa-Studier Gambit }) 4... Bf5 { B18 Classical Variation. Still the most common move, but is has some drawbacks for Black. } (4... Nd7 { B17 ➡ Karpov Variation } 5. Ng5 { Karpov Variation/Modern Main Line } (5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Ng3 { Karpov Variation/Modern Variation/Kasparov Attack }) (5. Bc4 Ngf6 6. Ng5 (6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 { Karpov Variation/Tiviakov-Fischer Attack } 7. c3 Qc7 8. Qb3) 6... e6 7. Qe2 Nb6 { Karpov Variation/Smyslov Variation } 8. Bb3 { Karpov Variation/Smyslov Variation/Main Line }) (5. Qe2 Ndf6 6. c3 (6. Nf3 Bf5 (6... Nxe4) 7. Ng3 (7. Nxf6+ Nxf6 8. c3 Qd5 { [%cal Gf5e4,Gf6e4,Gd5e4] }) 7... Bg6 8. c3 e6 9. a4 h6 $10) 6... Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Nf6 8. Qe5 Qd5 9. Nf3 (9. Qxd5) 9... Bf5 10. Nh4 $10 { [%cal Gf5c2,Gf5e6,Ge6d7] }) 5... Ngf6 (5... Ndf6 { Karpov Variation/Modern Variation/Ivanchuk Defense } 6. N1f3 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Nxf3 e6) 6. Bd3 (6. Bc4 e6 7. Qe2 Nb6 { Karpov Variation, Smyslov Variation, Main Line. See [Fitzsimons - Arkell] }) 6... e6 7. N1f3 Bd6 8. Qe2) (4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ (5. Bd3 { ➡ Alekhine Gambit } { [%csl Rd4] }) (5. Ng3 { a very rare and passive move that isn't played anymore. }) 5... exf6 { Tartakower Variation } (5... gxf6 { ➡ Bronstein-Larsen Variation. I do not recommend this line. }) 6. Bc4 { Forgacs Variation }) (4... h6 { Finnish Variation }) 5. Ng3 { [%cal Rg3f5] } (5. Nc5 { [%cal Rc5b7] } 5... b6 6. Nb3 { c6 is now slightly weakened, so Black has to take care of that. Nd7, Rc8 and Qc7 } { [%csl Gc6,Rf3,Re5][%cal Rg1f3,Rf3e5,Re5c6,Bf1g2,Bg2g3,Bg2c6,Gb8d7,Ga8c8] } 6... e6 (6... Nf6 { [%csl Gc6] }) 7. Nf3 { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf3e5] } 7... Bd6 8. g3 Ne7 9. Bg2 h6 10. O-O Nd7 11. Qe2 O-O) (5. Qf3 e6 6. Ne2 (6. c3)) 5... Bg6 { The only sensible move. But the bishop is not safe yet. } 6. h4 { Classical Variation/Main Line. The bishop needs a retreat square urgently. So … } { [%cal Rh4h5] } (6. f4 { Classical Variation/Maróczy Attack } { [%cal Rf4f5] } 6... e6 7. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] }) (6. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] } 6... e6 { Black can omit Nd7 completely, wait for c6-c5, and then play Nc6. } (6... Nd7 7. h4 (7. Nh4?! { This is a little bit annoying, because now White will keep the light-squared bishop and trade off Black's for a knight. But it's not so bad for Black: We will get the semi-open h-file, and we can still castle long.
The two main options here are e6 and e5. The latter opens up the position which is slightly better for White in my opinion, because that helps the bishop pair. e6 is the main move. } { [%cal Gh4g6] } 7... e6 (7... e5 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. dxe5 Qa5+! { Important zwischenzug. } { [%cal Ga5e5,Gd7e5] } 10. Bd2 Qxe5+ 11. Qe2 O-O-O 12. O-O-O Ngf6 { This is completely equal. Black is a tiny bit better developed, but the open h2-b8 diagonal might be a problem in the future. } { [%cal Bh2b8] }) 8. Nxg6 hxg6 { Here is the downside of this line: White has too many options in contrast to the e5-line, so it's harder to prepare for it. } 9. c3 { Blocks the Qa5 check and solidifies the center. } 9... Qc7 { Prepares castling long and pins the knight on g3 against the pawn on a2. Now it's in White's interest to trade off the queens! Black's plan is again castling long, get the pieces out and then decide on which to attack. } { [%csl Gh2][%cal Gh8h2,Gc7h2,Be8c8,Bf8d6,Bg8f6] }) 7... h6 8. h5 { Classical/Spassky Variation } 8... Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2 (11. Bf4 Qa5+! 12. Bd2 Bb4 13. c3 Be7 14. c4 Qc7 15. O-O-O Ngf6 16. Kb1 O-O) 11... Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 15. Qe2 (15. Qd3 O-O 16. Ne5 c5 17. dxc5 Qc7! { [%cal Ge7c5,Gc7c5,Gc7e5] } 18. Qe2 (18. f4 Qxc5 19. g4 Rfd8 20. Qe2 Rac8 { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gc5c2,Bc8c2] } 21. c3 Qd5 { [%cal Gd5a2] } 22. Kb1 Qe4+! { Forcing the queen trade will slow down White's attack on the kingside. } 23. Qxe4 Nxe4 { It also gets the knight out of the danger zone, and it creates a new threat. } { [%cal Ge4d2] } 24. Be3 { [%cal Re3a7] } 24... a6 $10 { And now we trade off at least one pair of rooks, and it's a draw. }) 18... Qxc5) 15... Qd5! { [%cal Gd5a2] } 16. c4 (16. Kb1 Rd8 $10) 16... Qe4 17. Qxe4 Nxe4 { [%cal Ge4d2,Ge4f2] } 18. Be3 (18. Be1 Bf6 19. Ne5 Rd8) 18... f5) (6... Nf6 7. h4 h6 8. Ne5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2 Nbd7 12. f4 Be7 13. O-O-O O-O 14. Qf3 Qc7 15. Rhe1 { Black should centralize the rooks here first, and only then try to open the center with c5. } { [%csl Gd8,Ge8][%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8,Gc6c5] }) 7. Ne5 { immediately without the h4 intermezzo means that White will trade the knight for the light-squared bishop, like in the line 6…Nd7 7.Nh4. The plan for Black is the same: Claim the semi-open h-file, castle long, and put the queen on c7, as we do in so many Caro-Kann positions. } { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gh7g6,Gd8c7,Gb8d7,Ge8c8,Bh8h2,Bc7h2] } (7. h4 h6 8. Ne5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nd7 11. f4 Bb4+ { Create a weakness. } 12. c3 Be7 13. Bd2 (13. Nh5 Bxh4+ 14. Kd1 Bf6 15. Kc2 g6 16. Nxf6+ Ngxf6) 13... Ngf6 14. O-O-O O-O 15. Qf3 Qc7) 7... Nd7 8. Nxg6 hxg6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 9. c3 Qc7 { Immobilize White's knight. } { [%cal Gh8h2,Gc7h2,Gg8f6,Ge8c8] }) (6. Nh3 { Flohr Variation } 6... e6 7. Nf4 Bd6 8. Ngh5 { [%cal Rh5g7] }) (6. N1e2 e6 (6... e5 7. Be3 (7. dxe5?! Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nd7 9. f4 (9. e6 Nc5 10. exf7+ Bxf7)) (7. h4)) 7. Nf4) 6... h6 (6... h5?! { Gives White the g5 square. } { [%csl Gg5] } 7. Nf3 (7. Nh3 { [%cal Rh3f4] } 7... Nd7 8. Nf4 Bh7 { [%csl Rh5] } 9. Nfxh5) 7... Nd7 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3) 7. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5,Re5g6] } (7. h5 Bh7 8. Nf3 { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf3e5] } 8... Nd7 { Transposes back into the main line, except for Bc4: } { [%csl Be5][%cal Gd7e5,Rf3e5] } 9. Bc4 e6 10. Qe2 { [%csl Re6][%cal Rc4e6,Re2e6] } 10... Ngf6 11. Ne5 { The idea is to sac on f7, then Qx6 and checkmate on f7. } { [%csl Gf7,Be6][%cal Ge5f7] } 11... Nd5 { takes the air out of the attack } (11... Nxe5 { is also fine } 12. dxe5 Nd5 $10) (11... Be7?? { just to illustrate what happens } 12. Nxf7 Qa5+ (12... Kxf7?? 13. Qxe6+ Kf8 14. Qf7#) 13. Bd2 Bb4 14. Nxh8 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2) 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Nxd3 $10) 7... Nd7 { [%cal Rf3e5,Rd7e5] } (7... e6 8. h5 (8. Ne5 Bh7 9. Bd3 { Main move. Note that White's d4 is *not* hanging. } { [%csl Bd4] } (9. Qh5?! { [%cal Re5f7,Rh5f7] } 9... Qc7 { Defends f7 } { [%cal Gc7f7] } 10. Bc4 { Threatens Bxe6, but Black has now time to push the queen away: } { [%csl Gf7] } 10... Nf6 11. Qe2 Bd6 { This is nice and solid for Black. } 12. Bf4 O-O $15) 9... Bxd3 (9... Qxd4?? 10. Nxf7! { [%cal Gf7h8] } 10... Bxd3 (10... Kxf7?? 11. Bg6+ Bxg6 12. Qxd4 $18 { And Black is completely lost here. }) 11. Nxh8 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Qxb2 13. Rb1 Qe5+ 14. Ne2 $16) 10. Qxd3 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5] } 11. f4 Bb4+ { Provoke a weakness. } 12. c3 Bd6 { [%cal Gd6e5,Gd7e5,Bd8d3] } 13. Qe2 { Get the queen off the d-file and unpin the d-pawn with that. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Ge2g4] } (13. Bd2 Ngf6 14. O-O-O O-O) 13... Ngf6 { Covers h5. } { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gf6h5] } (13... Qc7?! { allows White } 14. Nh5! { [%cal Rh5g7] } 14... g6 15. Ng7+! Kf8 16. Nxe6+! fxe6 17. Nxg6+ Kg7 18. Nxh8 Kxh8 $13 { This is technically still okay for Black, but certainly not what you want to play in an actual game. }) 14. Nf5! { [%cal Gf5g7] } 14... Bf8 (14... exf5?? 15. Nxc6+! { [%cal Gc6d8] }) 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. Ne3 (16. Ng3 Bd6 17. O-O-O O-O { [%cal Gc6c5] }) 16... Ne4 { [%cal Ge4g3] } 17. Rh3?! { Briet, A. - Navara, D., 0-1, 27th Czech Rapid G1 2016, https://lichess.org/6sBpYGxZ } (17. Nf1)) 8... Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nf6 { White has two options here: Bf4 and Bd2 } 11. Bf4 (11. Bd2 { Avoids the problems in the Bf4 line. } 11... Be7 12. O-O-O { White wants to set up a pawn storm on the kingside. Black should counter that with an attack in the center. } { [%cal Rd2g5,Rh1h5,Rd3g6,Rg2g4,Rf2f4] } 12... O-O 13. Kb1 c5! 14. Ne4 { [%cal Re4c5] } 14... Nc6! { Gambiting the c-pawn. This will give White an isolated d-pawn that cannot be defended. } 15. Nxf6+ (15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. dxc5 Qxd3 17. cxd3 Rfd8 18. Be3) (15. dxc5?! { The difference to Nxc5 is that Black keeps the dark-squared bishop, which is even better. } 15... Qxd3 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. cxd3 Rfd8) 15... Bxf6 16. dxc5 Qxd3 17. cxd3 Rfd8 18. Be3 Rd5 { [%cal Gd5c5,Gd5h5,Gd5d3] } 19. d4 (19. a3 Rad8 20. Kc2 a5) 19... Rad8 20. Rd2 a5 { [%cal Rb2b4,Gf6d4,Gc6d4,Gd8d4,Bd5d4,Gd5h5] }) 11... Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Bb4 { The idea is to exchange some pieces, so White doesn't have enough material for a kingside attack. Also the side with more space usually doesn't want to trade material. } 13. c3 { And this creates a weakness for White. } 13... Be7 14. c4 Bb4! 15. a3 Bxd2+ 16. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 $15 { White has more space, but Black's pawn structure is more solid. }) 8. h5 { B19 Classical, Spassky Variation. Hunting the bishop and gaining space. } 8... Bh7 9. Bd3 { Now White can force the exchange. } 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 { And here is Black's problem with this line: the bishop had to move FOUR times and is gone now. White has three developed pieces already, Black has one. Also called the Seirawan Variation. } 10... e6 (10... Ngf6 11. Bf4 (11. Bd2 e6 (11... Qc7 12. O-O-O e6 13. Ne4 O-O-O 14. g3 Nxe4 (14... Nc5 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. c4 Rhe8 17. Bc3 Bb6 18. Qc2) 15. Qxe4 Bd6 16. c4 c5 17. d5 Nf6 18. Qc2 exd5 19. cxd5) 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 (13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 15. Qe2 (15. Qd3)) (13. Qe2 O-O) 13... O-O (13... Qb6)) 11... Qa5+ (11... e6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 O-O 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 16. Qe2) 12. Bd2 Qc7 13. O-O-O e6 (13... O-O-O)) 11. Bd2 (11. Bf4 Qa5+ (11... Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 (13. Ne4 Nxe4) (13. Ne5 O-O 14. Kb1 (14. Ne4 Nxe4 { is the main move here, and also the move the engine recommends. } (14... Nd5 $146 { Novelty! A simple deviation from theory. This forces White's bishop off of one of the strong diagonals. } { [%cal Gd5f4,Rf4h6,Rf4b8] } 15. Bd2 (15. Bg3 { No g-pawn push in the near future. } { [%csl Bg2] }))))) 12. Bd2 Bb4 13. c3 Be7 14. c4 Qc7 15. O-O-O Ngf6 16. Kb1 O-O) 11... Ngf6 (11... Qc7 12. O-O-O Ngf6 13. Ne4 O-O-O 14. g3) 12. O-O-O Be7 { Classical Variation/Lobron System } 13. Kb1 { Main move } (13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 15. Qe2 Qd5 16. c4 Qe4 17. Qxe4 (17. Rde1 Qxe2 18. Rxe2 O-O $10) 17... Nxe4 { [%cal Ge4f2] } 18. Be3 (18. Be1 { Rather modern move, played by Mamedyarov and Rozum for example. } 18... Bf6 19. Ne5 Nd6 { [%cal Gd6c4] } (19... c5 20. f3 cxd4 21. Rxd4 (21. Ng4 Bg5+ 22. Kc2) 21... Nd6 22. Rxd6 (22. f4 Nf5 23. Re4 $10 { Opportunity for move repetition. } { [%cal Gf5d6,Re4d4] }) 22... Bxe5 23. Rd3 Rc8) 20. b3 (20. c5 Nb5))) (13. Qe2) (13. Bf4 { Rare move. }) 13... O-O { Main move } (13... Qc7) (13... Qb6) 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 16. Qe2 Qd5 17. Ne5 (17. Be3 Qb5 (17... Ng4 18. Bc1 (18. Bf4 Qf5 19. g3 Nf6 20. Ne5 { Muzychuk, M. - Khotenashvili, B., 1-0, SportAccord Rapid w 2014, https://lichess.org/DevRvb5q }) 18... Nf6 19. Ne5 Qe4 20. Qf1 c5 21. f3 Qh7?! (21... Qd5 22. c4 Qd6 23. Bf4 { Palac, Mladen - Michalik, Peter, 0-1, Kozloduy Danube Countries, 2012, https://lichess.org/Bxsqt7gl } 23... cxd4 24. Ng6 Qc5 25. Nxe7+ Qxe7 26. Be5) 22. dxc5 Bxc5 23. Nd7 Nxd7 24. Rxd7 Rac8 25. g4 { Karjakin, Sergey - Gustafsson, Jan, 1-0, Dortmund SuperGM 40th, 2012, https://lichess.org/ygj2vEkr }) 18. c4 Qf5+ 19. Ka1) 17... Qe4 18. Qxe4 Nxe4 { [%cal Ge4d2] } 19. Be1 (19. Be3) 19... Rfd8 (19... Nf6) 20. f3 Nf6 (20... Nd6) 21. Bf2 (21. Bh4) (21. g4) 21... Nd7 (21... a5) (21... Rac8) 22. Nd3 (22. c3) (22. g4) 22... a5 (22... b5) (22... Nb6) 23. c3 b5 (23... a4) *


