[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "– Karpov/Steinitz Variation: 4…Nd7"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/b1Kfhqsg"]
[UTCDate "2017.09.02"]
[UTCTime "07:25:54"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 { Main Line } 4... Nd7 { B17 Karpov Variation, sometimes also called Steinitz Variation. The normal continuation here is Bf5 (see chapter Main Line). But then the bishop has to move four times until it is taken off the board. In the Karpov Variation f6 is used as a pivot point for the knights and a faster attack on the center. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gg8f6,Gd7f6] } 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 Ngf6 6. Ng5 { Be very careful here! } { [%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] } (6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 { Tiviakov-Fischer Attack } 7. c3 Qc7 (7... e5! 8. Qb3 { [%cal Rc4f7] } (8. dxe5? Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Ng4 10. Nh3 Nxe5 11. Re1 f6 12. f4 Bxh3 13. fxe5 O-O-O+ 14. Kc2 Bf5+ 15. Kb3 fxe5 16. Rxe5 Bg6 $10) 8... Qe7 9. dxe5 Qxe5+ 10. Ne2 Nd5) 8. Qb3) 6... e6 7. Qe2 Nb6 { Smyslov Variation } { [%cal Gb6c4,Gc8e6] } (7... h6?? 8. Nxf7 Qe7 (8... Kxf7?? 9. Qxe6+ Kg6 10. Bd3+ Kh5 11. Qh3#) 9. Nxh8 $18) 8. Bb3 { Smyslov Variation/Main Line } (8. Bd3 h6 9. N5f3 c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Ne5 O-O) 8... h6 (8... a5 { [%cal Ga5a4] } 9. c3 h6 10. Ne4 { f3 is needed by the other knight. } 10... Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Nd5) 9. N5f3 (9. Nxf7? { Now it doesn't work } 9... Kxf7 { [%cal Gc8e6] }) 9... c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Ne5 O-O 12. Ngf3 Nbd7 13. O-O Nxe5 14. Nxe5 b6) (5. Qe2 Ndf6 { Covers the d6-square, so there is no mate. } { [%csl Bd6][%cal Gd8d6] } (5... Ngf6?? { TRAP! } 6. Nd6#) 6. c3 (6. Nf3 Bf5 (6... Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Nf6 8. Qd3 g6 9. g3) 7. Ng3 (7. Nxf6+ Nxf6 8. c3 Qd5) 7... Bg6 8. c3 e6 9. a4 h6 $10) 6... Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Nf6 8. Qe5 (8. Qc2 Bg4 9. Bd3 e6 (9... Bh5 10. Ne2 Bg6 { Fernandez, Daniel Howard - Seirawan, Yasser, 1/2-1/2, Vlissingen HZ op 15th, 2011, https://lichess.org/UhhHHBjb }) 10. Ne2 Bd6 11. h3 Bh5 12. Nf4 { Chan, Yi Ren Daniel - Paciencia, Enrique Rivas, 1/2-1/2, Singapore Masters 5th, 2008, https://lichess.org/K1Dvy5Cq }) 8... Qd5 9. Nf3 (9. Qxd5 Nxd5) 9... Bf5 10. Nh4 $10) (5. c3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bc4 Qc7 8. Qb3 e6 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O O-O $10) (5. Ng5 { Karpov Variation/Modern Main Line. Threats are an attack on f7 via Bc4 or Qf3. } { [%cal Rf1c4,Bc4f7,Bg5f7,Rd1f3,Bf3f7] } 5... Ngf6 { This rules out Qf3 threat, Bc4 can be answered with e6. } { [%csl Bg4,Bh5] } (5... Ndf6 { Modern Variation/Ivanchuk Defense } 6. N1f3 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Nxf3 e6) (5... h6 { This forces Black to bring the queen out early. Not recommended. } 6. Ne6! { The point is that fxe6 is deadly. } 6... Qa5+ (6... fxe6?? 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qxg6#) 7. Bd2 Qb6) 6. Bd3 { Occupy some space and prepare short castling. } (6. Bc4 e6 7. Qe2 Nb6 { Karpov Variation, Smyslov Variation, Main Line. See [Fitzsimons - Arkell] }) 6... e6 { The ls-bishop has no good square now anyway, so Black delays its development and develop the bs-bishop instead. This also prevents any Bc4 ideas. } 7. N1f3 { Prepares castling again, and refreshed the threat on f7. } { [%csl Bf7][%cal Rf3e5,Be5f7,Bg5f7] } 7... Bd6 { Get the bishop out and prevent Ne5. } 8. Qe2 { More pressure on e5. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Re2e5,Rf3e5,Rd4e5] } 8... h6 { Kick that annoying knight away. } 9. Ne4 Nxe4 { And now we see the "Karpov knights" in action. The next moves are the core idea of 4…Nd7. } 10. Qxe4 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } (10... Qc7 { This move is an alternative to Nf6. The idea is to play c5. } 11. Qg4 { [%cal Rg4g7] } (11. O-O b6 12. Qg4 { [%cal Rg4g7] } 12... Kf8 13. b3 Bb7 14. Bb2 Nf6 15. Qh4 Nd5 $10) 11... Kf8 { Castling would just lose the h-pawn per Bxh6. } 12. O-O c5 (12... b6 13. b3 Bb7 14. Bb2 Nf6 15. Qh4 Nd5 $10) 13. Qh4 { The queen on g4 was a bit vulnerable to attacks per Nf6 or e4 } { [%cal Gd7f6,Bf6g4,Ge6e5,Bc8g4] } (13. c3 b6 14. Qh4 Bb7 15. Be4 Be7 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. Nxg5 hxg5 (17... Kg8 18. Bxb7 hxg5 19. Qxh8+ Kxh8 20. Bxa8 cxd4 21. cxd4 Nf6 $10) 18. Qxh8+ Ke7 19. Qxa8 Bxa8 20. Bxa8 $10) 13... b6 14. Be4 (14. Re1) 14... Rb8 (14... Bb7?! 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. dxc5 { The problem here is that Black has no good piece to take the pawn back: bxc5 creates an isolated pawn, Nxc5 or Bxc5 will be attacked per Be3, and an exchange there would open the f-file for White's rook. } 16... Be7 17. Qf4 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Rf4d6,Rc5d6] } 17... bxc5) 15. Rd1 { From here Black has many interesting options. } { [%cal Rd1d6] } 15... c4 { Most often played move, but not the best one. } (15... Be7 { This will result in an interesting material imbalance. } { [%cal Ge7h4] } 16. Bf4 { [%cal Rf4c7,Bc7b8] } 16... e5 17. Nxe5!? (17. Qxe7+ Kxe7 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Bxe5 Qd7 20. dxc5 Qb5 21. Bxb8 bxc5 $13) 17... Bxh4 18. Ng6+ fxg6 19. Bxc7 Rb7 20. Bxb7 Bxb7 21. Bd6+ Kf7 22. dxc5 Bf6 $10) (15... f5 16. Bd3 (16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Bd3 Ne5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. c3 $10) 16... c4 17. Bf1 Bb7 $10) (15... Ba6 16. d5 (16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Bd2 Be2 18. Re1 $10) 16... Re8 17. dxe6 Rxe6 $10) 16. Bc6! { Black can't take the bishop, Qd8+ is mate! } { [%cal Rh4d8] } 16... Nf6 (16... Qxc6?? 17. Qd8#) (16... Ba6 { [%cal Gb8d8,Ga6c4] } 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. Bf4 { Again, the fight for e5. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf4e5,Rf3e5,Rd4e5] } 18... Re8 19. Ne5 { [%cal Re5d7,Re5c4] } 19... Bxe5 20. dxe5 { [%cal Rd1d7] } 20... Qc7 $14) 17. Ne5 Nd5 18. Qh5 { [%cal Rh5e5] } 18... Bxe5 19. Qxe5 Bb7 20. Bxd5 Qxe5 21. dxe5 Bxd5 $10) 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. Bd2 b6 13. O-O-O Bb7) 5... Ngf6 6. Ng3 { Modern Variation/Kasparov Attack } (6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Ne5 (7. Bc4 Bf5 (7... Bg4? { This loses at least one pawn: } 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. Ne5+ Kg8 10. Nxg4 $16) 8. O-O e6 9. Re1) 7... Be6 8. Be2 g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. c4 O-O 11. Be3 Ne4) 6... e6 7. Bd3 c5 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Rd1 Qc7 11. c4 Re8 (11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 a6 { Don't allow the white knight on b4. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Rd4b5] } 13. b3 (13. Bd2) 13... Re8 $10) 12. dxc5 Nxc5 (12... Bxc5) 13. Bc2 Ncd7 14. Ba4 (14. Ng5 { [%cal Rg5h7,Rc2h7] } 14... h6 (14... Nf8 15. Rb1 (15. N3e4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 f5 17. Qf3 (17. Qe2) 17... Qxc4)) 15. N5e4 b6 $10) (14. Ne4) 14... Rd8 { [Ivanchuk - Karpov, 1997] ½-½ https://lichess.org/nkPhwGaY } (14... a6) *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: – Tartakower Variation: 4...Nf6 5.Nxf6+ exf6"]
[Date "2018.11.15"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Tartakower Variation"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "– Tartakower Variation: 4...Nf6 5.Nxf6+ exf6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/YRKD3XyH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2018.11.15"]
[UTCTime "19:34:13"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 { Nd2, avoiding the ➡Gurgenidze System, leads to the same position. } (3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 { Tartakower Variation. This is a very solid structure with good king safety for Black. Also note that both bishops are free to move already.
White's plan is an early attack on h7 by lining up Queen and bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal and pushing the h-pawn. Which means White will probably castle long. } { [%cal Gf8b4,Gc8g4,Rf1d3,Rc2c3,Rd1c2,Rc2d3,Bd3h7,Rh2h6] } 6. c3 { [%cal Rd1c2,Rf1d3] } (6. Bc4 { Forgacs Variation } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rc4f7] } 6... Qe7+ (6... Bf5?! 7. Qe2+) (6... Bd6 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 (8... Bxe7 9. Ne2) 9. Ne2) 7. Qe2 Be6 8. Bxe6 (8. Bb3 a5 (8... Bxb3) (8... Na6)) 8... Qxe6 9. Bf4 Na6 10. O-O-O O-O-O 11. Qxe6+ fxe6) (6. Nf3 Bd6 7. Bd3 (7. Be2 { Slightly inaccurate. This bishop really belongs to d3. } 7... O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Re1 (9. c4 Nd7 10. Bd3 { A bit too late. } 10... Nf8 11. h3 Ng6 12. Qc2 { Nepomniachtchi, I. - Carlsen, M., 0-1, World Rapid 2016, https://lichess.org/klUMP3Pe }) 9... Bf5 10. Be3 Nd7 { Karpov, Anatoly - Hort, Vlastimil, 1-0, Tilburg, 1979, https://lichess.org/XPvbbG39 }) 7... O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. c4 { This is a line that a cheater played against me: https://lichess.org/TNlJUi7F Very instructive. } { [%cal Rc4c5] } 9... Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Be3 { [%cal Re3a7] } 11... Nd7 12. Re1 c5 13. Bf5 cxd4 14. Qxd4 { [%cal Gd4d6] } 14... Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Qxd8 Rexd8 { Inaccuracy by me, should have played Raxd8. } (16... Raxd8 17. Bxa7 Bg6 18. Bxg6 fxg6 19. Re2 { Prevent Rd2 and Bxb2 by Black. } 19... g5 (19... Rd3)) 17. Be4 { [%cal Re4b7,Re3a7] } 17... Bxb2 { Mistake. Rac8 was better. } (17... Rac8 { [%cal Gc8c4] } 18. c5 Rc7) 18. Rab1 { Here my position was already very difficult, and Stockfish converted easily. }) 6... Bd6 { The idea here is that Black can Qc7 if White doesn't prevent that. Rarely possible, but keep an eye on that opportunity. } { [%cal Gd8c7,Bd6h2] } 7. Bd3 O-O (7... Qc7 { It is an option right now. I'm just not sure how good it is. Rarely played. } 8. h3 { Engine suggestion. Only 4 games by <2200 players in the database. } (8. Ne2 { Main move here. } 8... O-O 9. Qc2 { [%cal Rd3h7] } 9... h6 10. h3 { Black should now play Nd7 and Re8, the order doesn't matter that much. } 10... Nd7 11. O-O Re8 12. Be3 Nf8 $14 { [%csl Gh7,Gg6][%cal Gf8g6,Gf8h7] }) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 $146 { Novelty. } 9... Re8+ 10. Ne2 { h6, f5, and g6 are options now. } 10... h6 { Transposes back to a more common line, so we can again find some games in the database. }) 8. Qc2 { White is already lining up against h2, forcing Black to move one pawn in this formation (h or g) pawn soon. } { [%cal Rd3h7] } (8. Ne2 Re8 9. Qc2 (9. O-O { If White doesn't line up queen and bishop early, Black has time to bring the knight to f8. And that's a very solid setup. } 9... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f8] } 10. Bf4 Nf8 { [%cal Gf8h7] } 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Ng3) 9... h5 { Andriasian, Z. - Vidit, S., 0-1, PRO League Group Stage, 2018, https://lichess.org/tomn44Da } { A very instructive game by Vidit. The h-pawn is later used to support a bishop on g3. } (9... g6 10. h4 Nd7 { Jobava is playing this line, develops the knight earlier than the light-squared bishop. })) 8... Re8+ { Important zwischenzug. } 9. Ne2 (9. Be3) 9... g6 (9... h6 10. O-O Qc7 11. Ng3 (11. h3 Nd7) 11... Nd7) (9... h5!? { A rather new "main" line. } 10. Be3 Nd7 11. O-O-O) 10. h4 { This does two things: It threatens to open the h-file for White, and it opens the diagonal for White's ds bishop in case f5 is played. } { [%cal Rc1h6,Rh4h5,Rh5g6] } 10... Be6 (10... f5 11. h5 (11. Bg5 Be7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. O-O-O Be6) 11... Be6 12. hxg6 fxg6 13. Bh6) 11. h5 f5 12. hxg6 fxg6 13. Bh6 Bf7 14. O-O-O Qa5 15. a3 Nd7 *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: – Bronstein-Larsen Variation: 4…Nf6 5.Nxf6 gxf6"]
[Date "2019.04.25"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B16"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Bronstein-Larsen Variation"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "– Bronstein-Larsen Variation: 4…Nf6 5.Nxf6 gxf6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/elirGeaM"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.25"]
[UTCTime "17:59:14"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ (5. Ng3 { is very rare. }) 5... gxf6 { Bronstein-Larsen Variation. The idea is to get the open g-file for an attack. But the damaged pawn structure is a long-term liability. I don't recommend this line.
White should discourage Black from playing e5 now. c3 and Nf3 are two ways to do that. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } (5... exf6 { ➡ Tartakower Variation } 6. Bc4 { Forgacs Variation }) 6. c3 (6. Nf3 Bg4 { points out why Nf3 isn't played so often. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 7. Bf4 { takes control over e5 again. And after an exchange, White's queen will be replaced with the rook now, preserving the control over the d-file. This also makes castling harder for Black. } { [%cal Ra1d1,Gf4b8] } 7... Nd7 { keeps the idea of e5 alive. } 8. h3 { This is an interesting moment: Black can go into a quiet game with Bh5 or Bxf3 now, or play Qa5+. } 8... Qa5+ { [%csl Ge5,Gh5][%cal Ga5e5,Ge5h5] } 9. Bd2?! (9. c3 { is now almost forced. Bd2 gives Black a nice initiative. } 9... Bh5 { White will very likely not play g4 here. The simple reason is that White's king had no safe place afterwards. } 10. Be2 { And now Black can finally play e5. The engine even recommends it. But … castling first is probably easier to play. } 10... O-O-O { This looks a bit uncomfortable for White. } { [%cal Gd8d1] } (10... e5 { Stockfish's recommendation } 11. Bg3 O-O-O { transposes to the theory }) 11. Bg3 e5 12. O-O Rg8 { Black's rooks are now perfectly placed. And while the engine still says that White is better, it's hard to recommend a move. Re1, Qc2, even a4 are okay. } { [%cal Gg8g1,Gd8d1] } 13. b4 { might be a good multi-purpose move: it drives the queen away from the 5th rank (Qd5 is just asking for further attacks) and starts the typical pawn storm in positions with opposite castling. } (13. Nh4 { was played in Potrata - Schmitzer. It's not the best move, but it does lead to a more quiet game that is easier to play for White. } 13... Bxe2 14. Qxe2 exd4 15. cxd4 Qd5 16. Rac1 Nb6 17. Nf5 h5 18. h4 Rg4 { Potrata, Janko - Schmitzer, Klaus, 1-0, WC35/pr09, 2011, https://lichess.org/siwhYUl0 } (18... Qxf5?! { doesn't really work: } 19. Rxc6+! bxc6 20. Qa6+ { [%csl Rc7,Rb8][%cal Rg3b8,Ra6c8] } 20... Kd7 21. Qxa7+ Ke8 22. Re1+ { [%csl Re7][%cal Re1e7,Ra7e7] } 22... Qe6 23. Rxe6+ { and with that, Black loses the queen } 23... fxe6 24. Qxb6 $18 { White is completely winning here. The a-pawn is almost unstoppable. } { [%cal Ra2a8] })) 13... Qa3 { is a good, aggressive reply. White is better here — says Stockfish — but I'd say it's a very sharp position in which both sides can play for a win. } { [%cal Ga3c3] }) 9... Qh5! { Pinning the h-pawn. } { [%cal Gh5h1] } 10. Be2 (10. Rg1) 10... Rg8 { [%csl Bg2][%cal Gg8g2] } 11. Rg1 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Qh4 { [%cal Gh4d4] }) (6. Bc4 { Threat: Qh5 } { [%cal Rd1h5,Bh5f7] } 6... Bf5 { Now Qh5 can be answered with Bg6. } { [%cal Gf5g6] } 7. Ne2 e6) 6... e5 { right away. This is almost never played, but clearly worth a try. I'll recommend this for now. } (6... Bf5 { Bf5 is the main move here. } 7. Nf3 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Rf3h4,Rh4f5] } 7... Nd7 8. Nh4 Bg6 { Hoping for an exchange to fix the pawn structure. :) } 9. Be2 e6) (6... h5?! 7. Bc4 { Pressing on the weakest square. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rc4f7] } 7... Nd7 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gd7b6,Bb6c4] } 8. Qb3 { Forcing e6. Rh7 is playable, but it disconnects the rooks forever. } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Rc4f7,Rb3c4,Gh8h7,Bh7f7] } 8... e6 (8... Rh7?! 9. Nf3 { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rc4d3,Bd3h7] } 9... Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4] } 10. Be2 Rg7 { [%csl Gg2][%cal Gg7g2] } 11. g3 $14 { The engine thinks just castling short is okay here, but … with the open g-file for Black, this is a difficult decision to make when you can't play like Stockfish. }) 9. Nf3 Nb6 10. Be2 Qc7 11. O-O $16 { White has enough defenders on the kingside to block any attack. After c4, the queen can also switch to the kingside.
Black has to castle long and then try to attack White's king per Rg8 and Bd6. But all of this slow, and White is already better developed. } { [%cal Rc3c4,Bb3h3,Gh8g8,Bg8g2,Gf8d6,Bd6h2,Gc8d7,Ge8c8] }) (6... Qd5 7. Be3 Bf5 { Main move. } (7... Rg8 { is maybe a bit too early. } 8. Nf3 Nd7 9. Qb3 Nb6 10. c4 Qh5 11. O-O-O Bh6 12. Re1 Be6 13. Qb4 O-O-O 14. b3?! Rd7 15. Nd2 Rgd8 16. f4 Bg4 17. g3? e5 { Kagan, Shimon - Basman, Michael J, 0-1, Birmingham, 1977, https://lichess.org/yDngmztZ }) (7... h5 8. Qb3 Bh6 9. Nf3 Bxe3 10. fxe3 Qe4 11. Kd2 Nd7 12. Bc4?! e6?! { Godena, Michele - Short, Nigel D, 0-1, Reggio Emilia 53rd, 2011, https://lichess.org/y7MM2G9l }) 8. Ne2 e5 { Can and should now be played safely. } 9. Ng3 (9. dxe5 { is okay for Black: } 9... fxe5 10. Ng3 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Be6 12. Bd3 Bxa2) 9... Be6 { [%cal Ge6a2] } 10. Qd2 (10. Qh5?! Nd7 { Eggleston, D. - Pakleza, Z., 0-1, 6th Rethymno Open 2014, https://lichess.org/azJGc5iU }) 10... Nd7) 7. Nf3 (7. Bc4?! Nd7?! { Alonso, Salvador - Moreda, Lucas, 1-0, Mar del Plata op 40th, 2009, https://lichess.org/4jDxbmnz }) (7. dxe5?! Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 fxe5) 7... Qe7 8. Qc2 exd4+ 9. Be2 dxc3 10. O-O Rg8 { White is *still* better. } { [%cal Gc8h3] } (10... cxb2 { is probably too greedy. } 11. Bxb2 Be6 12. Rad1 Nd7 13. Nd4 Qc5 { ask for a queen trade that White should decline. } 14. Qd3 Bxa2) *


