1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 { Same position as in 3.Nc3. }) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Bd3 { Alekhine Gambit. This is rarely played nowadays, and I don't recommend it. Sacrifices d4 with the idea to develop the white pieces with tempo: attacks on the queen. Black should accept nevertheless. } { [%csl Rd4] } 5... Qxd4 { A basic rule for Black here is: Piece trades are good for Black. This is now a Scandinavian in which Black is a pawn up. } 6. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3d4] } 6... Qd5 { Prevents Nge5. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gd5g5,Re4g5] } (6... Qd8 { is also possible. But it might give White too much freedom in the center. } 7. Neg5 { is the critical idea for White } { [%cal Rg5f7,Rd1d8,Bd3c4,Bc4f7] } (7. Qe2 Nxe4 8. Bxe4 (8. Qxe4 Na6 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ga6c5,Bc5d3,Bc5e4] } 9. Be3 { [%csl Rc5][%cal Re3c5] } (9. Bxa6?! { doesn't work: } 9... Qa5+! 10. Bd2 Qxa6 $15) 9... Be6 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Bd5e4] } 10. O-O Bd5 11. Qa4 { [%cal Rd3a6,Ra4a6] } 11... Nc7) 8... g6 9. O-O Bg7 { [%cal Gg7b2] } 10. c3 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5,Gd7f6,Gc5e4,Gf6e4] } 11. Bc2 e5 { Block squares for the knight and the bishop. } { [%csl Gf4,Gd4][%cal Rf3d4,Rc1f4] }) 7... Qc7 { is the best response. The queen has to step out of the unprotected square d8. } { [%cal Rd1d8] } (7... h6 { for example would lose the game immediately: } 8. Nxf7 { [%cal Gf7h8,Gf7d8] } 8... Kxf7 9. Bg6+! Kxg6 10. Qxd8)) 7. Qe2 (7. c4 Qd7) 7... Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Qh5 9. Be3 Bf5 10. Bxf5 Qxf5 11. O-O-O Nd7 { Black is fine here. White has very little compensation for the pawn. } *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: Advance Variation Overview: 2.d4 d5 3.e5"]
[Date "2017.05.15"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B12"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Advance Variation, Short Variation"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "Advance Variation Overview: 2.d4 d5 3.e5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/5Uo7uFSH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.05.15"]
[UTCTime "16:51:11"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { The Advance Variation begins here. e5 is the most common move, takes more space, but leaves f5 to black. On the other hand, Black's knight has no access to f6 anymore. } { [%csl Gf5,Rf6] } 3... Bf5 { In contrast to the French defense, black can get the light square bishop out early before e3 is played. Again similar to the Scandinavian where this bishop's best place is also f5. } (3... c5 { ➡ Botvinnik-Carls Defense or Arkell/Khenkin Variation. }) (3... Qb6 { This move has been played a few times, but I think the queen is misplaced here. The little pressure on b2 isn't really worth a tempo. After c4, c5 the queen has to retreat anyway. } 4. Nc3 (4. c4 Bf5 5. Nc3 (5. c5 Qc7 6. Nc3 e6 7. Nf3 Ne7 $14) (5. Nf3 e6 6. Be2 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Ne7 $14) 5... e6 6. c5 Qc7 $14 { Przedmojski, Rafal - Dmitriev, Igor, 1-0, Polanica Zdroj op, 2017, https://lichess.org/J9pX5s1i }) 4... Bf5 { Van der Wiel Attack, Dreyev Defense } 5. Nf3 e6) (3... g6 { This leads to a mix of ideas from the Panov and the Gurgenidze system that is overall not very harmonious. The only 2600+ GM who has played this was Boris Spassky – he lost against Nigel Short in 2001. } 4. c4 { White uses the opportunity to grab some space. } { [%cal Rf1c4] } 4... Bg7 5. Nc3 Nh6 { And here almost every move is good for White. } 6. Bf4 (6. cxd5 cxd5 7. h3 O-O) (6. h4 { A move by Mihail Tal. Of course. } 6... Be6 7. Nge2 dxc4 8. Nf4 Bd5 9. b3! cxb3 10. axb3 e6 11. Bd3 Nf5 12. Bxf5 exf5 13. Ba3 Bf8 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 15. Qd2 Be6 16. Rd1 Qe7 17. Rh3 Na6 18. d5 cxd5 19. Nfxd5 Bxd5 20. Nxd5 Qxe5+ 21. Re3 Qd6 22. Qc3 f6 23. Nc7 { Tal, Mihail - Zilberstein, Valery I, 1-0, URS-ch40, 1972, https://lichess.org/hVnlZN1K })) 4. Nf3 { Often used by Nigel Short and therefore called the Short Variation. } (4. Nc3 { ▶ Van der Wiel Attack }) (4. h4 { "Tal Variation" } 4... h5 5. c4 e6 6. Nc3 Ne7) (4. Nd2 e6 5. Nb3 Nd7 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. Be2) (4. Be3 e6 5. Nd2 Nd7 6. Ngf3 Ne7 7. Be2) (4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 Ne7 6. a3 { [%cal Gb8d7,Gd5c4] }) (4. c3 e6 5. Be3 Nd7) (4. Ne2 { "Bronstein Variation" (often played by Naiditsch) } 4... e6 5. Ng3 Bg6) (4. Be2 { NN } 4... e6 5. Nf3 Nd7) (4. g4 { ▶ Bayonet Attack }) (4. Bd3 { NN } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6) (4. f4 { NN (Morozevich, Van den Doel) } 4... e6 5. Nf3 Nd7) (4. b4 { Prins Attack }) 4... e6 5. Be2 { White is now ahead in development with good positions for its king-side pieces. } 5... Nd7 { Support c5. } (5... c5 { Undermine White's pawn chain, and give the knight on b8 the square c6. } 6. c3 { Not really good. Better is Be3. } (6. Be3 { Encourage Black to take d4. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4) (6. O-O Nc6 7. c3) 6... Nc6 7. O-O cxd4 8. cxd4 Nge7 { There is no pawn hanging on c5 anymore, so the black square bishop isn't needed to protect it. } 9. Nc3 Nc8 10. Be3 Be7 11. Rc1 O-O { [%cal Gc8b6,Ga8c8,Gd8d7] }) 6. O-O Ne7 7. Nbd2 h6 8. Nb3 g5 9. Ne1 Qc7 10. Nd3 b6 11. Be3 Bg7 12. f4 c5 13. dxc5 gxf4 14. cxb6 axb6 15. Bxf4 Ng6 16. Bg3 O-O 17. Nd4 Be4 18. c3 Ngxe5 19. Nf2 Bg6 20. a4 { None of the most common moves in the database match the first three engine recommendations from now on. } 20... Qd8 21. Bb5 Qe7 22. Qe2 Rfc8 23. Rae1 Ra7 24. Kh1 Raa8 25. Qd1 Kh7 *


