{ Many notes are taken from Michael Goeller's "The Caveman Caro-Kann" http://www.kenilworthchessclub.org/games/java/2013/complete-caveman.htm }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 { Tal Variation } 4... h5 5. Bg5?! (5. c4 { is the main move in this position. It allows Black to develop a compact but safe position: } 5... e6 6. Nc3 Ne7 7. Nge2 Nd7 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. Bg5 Qb6 10. Qd2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O-O $10) (5. Bd3 { Second main move. } 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Qb6 8. Nd2 c5 9. c4 Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qxd4 { [%cal Gb1b7] }) 5... Qb6 { The point is not so much to attack b2. But Black has to play e6 in order to develop the dark-squared bishop, and that pawn has to get unpinned. } { [%csl Bf8][%cal Gb6b2,Ge7e6,Rg5d8] } 6. Bd3?! { [%cal Gd3f5] } 6... Qxd4! { is what Black should play here. The point is that White can't play Bxf5. } (6... Bxd3? { Mistake. Qxd4 is the only decent move in this position. } 7. Qxd3 e6 (7... Qxb2? 8. e6! Qxa1 (8... fxe6? 9. Nf3) 9. Qb3 Qxd4 10. Qxb7 fxe6 11. Be3 Qa4 12. Qxa8 Qa5+ 13. Nd2 Qd8 14. Ngf3 Nf6 15. O-O g6 16. Rb1 Nbd7 17. Qxc6 Bg7 18. Ng5 { Perunovic, Milos - Lalith, Babu MR, 1-0, Dubai op 11th, 2009, https://lichess.org/fBFbHQps }) 8. Nd2 c5 9. c4 Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qxd4) 7. Nf3 { Protecting e5 and attacking the queen. } { [%cal Rf3e5,Rf3d4] } (7. Bxf5?? Qxe5+! 8. Ne2 Qxf5 { And this is just winning. }) 7... Qg4 (7... Qxb2 { And now take b2. }) 8. Bxf5 (8. Be2) (8. O-O) (8. Nc3?! f6 { And now White has to find the only move Rh3. } 9. Rh3! $146 { Novelty. } (9. exf6) (9. Be3) 9... fxg5 (9... e6) (9... Bxd3) 10. Rg3 Bxd3 11. Rxg4 hxg4 12. Nxg5 Bf5 13. Nxd5 $7 { [%cal Gd5c7,Bc7e8,Bc7a8] } 13... Na6 $7 (13... cxd5?? 14. Qxd5 $18 { [%cal Gd5f7,Gg5f7,Gd5b7] })) 8... Qxf5 9. c4 Qe4+ 10. Be3 e6 $15 { Just to stop White from playing e6 } (10... Qxc4) *


