[UTCDate "2017.07.04"]
[UTCTime "11:52:24"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 { g4 starts the Bayonet Attack. White's plan is to attack Black on the king side immediately and block Black's light square bishop. This leads to a very sharp game. Unlike in the ▶ van der Wiel Attack, White doesn't protect e4 with Nc3 first. } (4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 { Van der Wiel Attack }) 4... Be4 { Provoke f3, so White has a pawn where it wants to have a knight. } (4... Bd7 { Very passive, but also very solid. } { Ponkratov, Pavel - Kamsky, Gata, 0-1, Wch Rapid, 2013, https://lichess.org/7dJGISUC } 5. c4 e6 { See [Shirov - Anand] and [Ponkratov - Kamsky] } 6. Nc3) (4... Bg6 { Retreat without the e4 intermezzo. } 5. e6 { This is basically a little gambit. White hopes to ruin Black's pawn structure and to lock in the black squared bishop for a long time. } (5. Nh3 e6 { See [Morozevich - Topalov] } { Morozevich, Alexander - Topalov, Veselin, 0-1, Amber-rapid 12th, 2003, https://lichess.org/GyktelD4 } 6. Nf4 { This is completely equal according to SF8, but much easier to play for Black. f3 is now a weakness, the white king slightly exposed. But developing Black's black squared bishop is still difficult, as always in the Advanced variation. } { [%csl Ge4,Bh4][%cal Rf4g6,Gg6e4,Ge4h1,Bf2f3,Bd8h4,Bh4e1,Bf8e7,Bg8e7] }) 5... fxe6 { Accept the gambit. } (5... Nh6 { Novelty? Decline the gambit temporarily. } { [%cal Gh6f7,Rh2h4,Rf2f4] } 6. f4 { [%cal Rf4f5] } 6... fxe6 { … and accept it now, because the bishop would be trapped otherwise. } (6... Be4 7. Nf3) 7. Bh3 { Prepare a double attack on the knight and the e6-pawn. Hmm, can be answered with Nf5 … } { [%cal Rh3e6,Rg4g5,Rg5h6,Gh6f5] }) 6. h4 { Novelty? } (6. Nf3 { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf3e5,Re5g6] } 6... Qd6 7. Qe2 { Novelty? } 7... Nd7 8. Bh3?! h6 { [%cal Gg6h7,Gg7g5] }) 6... Nf6 7. h5 Bf7 8. g5 { [%cal Gf6e4,Gf6d7] } 8... Nfd7) 5. f3 { Black opens White's king side before the bishop retreats to g6. See [Najer - Belozerov] } (5. Nf3 { Maybe too passive for White, Black's bishop can stay on e4 for now and later be traded off for the knight on f3. } 5... e6 { Prepare c5 like in the "usual" Advance variations. } 6. Nbd2 { [%cal Rd2e4] } 6... Bg6 7. Nb3 { Bramburg, Boris Vulfovich - Vasin, Mikhail Mikhailovic, 1-0, RUS/C11/qf3 (RUS), 2011, https://lichess.org/Kz6Sr5oj } (7. c3 { Motwani, Paul - Sadkowsky, Daniel, 1-0, BEL-chT 0001, 2000, https://lichess.org/1MQzUTvG })) 5... Bg6 { White should keep the pressure on Black's bishop, otherwise the attack is just good for Black. This can be done either by playing h4 immediately or by preparing that move with Ne2. e6 is also an interesting option, see [Najer - Belozerov]. } { [%csl Rf4,Re2][%cal Rg1e2,Re2f4,Rf4g6] } 6. Ne2 { The downside (for White) of this preparing move is that Black has time to develop the black squared bishop and start a counter-attack with c5. } (6. h4 h5 7. e6 Qd6 (7... fxe6?! 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qd6)) (6. e6 { Najer, E. - Belozerov, A., 1-0, 70th ch-RUS HL 2017, https://lichess.org/SILO5FxY }) 6... e6 7. h4 h5 { Almost an "only move". h6 would allow White to play h5 himself. } (7... h6?! 8. Be3 (8. h5 Bh7) 8... Qb6) 8. Nf4 { Black has to make an important decision now: Bh7 drops the pawn on h5, Ne7 blocks the black squared bishop. } { [%cal Rf4h5,Rg4h5,Rf4g6] } 8... Ne7 (8... Bh7 9. Nxh5) 9. Nc3 { Continue development. Both sides will castle long now if at all. This move also makes c6-c5 more difficult for Black, because White eyes on b5 now. Black can either play the defensive a6 or the more aggressive Nd7. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Rf1b5,Rc3b5] } 9... Nd7 (9... a6 10. b4!? (10. Nxg6 Nxg6 11. Bg5 Ne7 12. Qe2 { [%cal Re1c1] } 12... Qc7 13. O-O-O c5 { Finally! } 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. f4) 10... hxg4 (10... Nd7) 11. fxg4 Bh7 12. h5 b6 { Again, try get c5 done. } 13. Na4 { [%cal Rd4c5,Rb4c5,Ra4c5,Gb6c5] } 13... Be4 { [%cal Gg7g5] } 14. Bg2 a5) 10. Be3 hxg4 11. fxg4 Qb6 12. Qd2 { White doesn't have to worry about the pawn on b2. It will get a pawn back. } 12... Qxb2 13. Rb1 Qxc2 { This pawn however is gone for good. } { [%cal Gg6c2] } 14. Rxb7 Qxd2+ 15. Bxd2 a6 16. Nxg6 Nxg6 17. h5 { hxg6 is not a threat yet, the white rook is hanging. } 17... Be7 { [%cal Gg6h4,Ge7h4] } 18. Na4 c5 19. Rh3 { [%cal Gf1h3] } 19... Ngf8 20. dxc5 Bxc5 { [%cal Gd7c5,Gd7e5] } 21. Nxc5 Nxc5 { [%cal Gc5b7] } 22. Rc7 Nfd7 23. Bb4 Ne4 $10 *


