{ The street name for this variation is Shirov Attack, because Shirov played it quite often during the 90s. The basic idea is a very early attack on Black's ls-bishop and the whole king side with tempo. If you are not comfortable playing this with Black, go for the Botvinnik-Carls defense, 3…c5 instead of Bf5. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 { This is the basic position for White's attack. Nc3 was played to cover e4, so that Black's bishop cannot go forward when it is attacked with g4. In other words: Black can see it coming. } { [%csl Re4,Rg4][%cal Rc3e4,Rg2g4] } (4. Nd2 { Maybe better than Nc3? Doesn't block the c-pawn, but the bs-bishop … and enables Nb3 later. } 4... e6 5. g4 Bg6 6. Ne2 c5 7. h4 h5 (7... h6 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 { [Morozevich - Tomashevsky], 2013, 0-1, https://lichess.org/zvw55ldZ }) 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Nxh5 cxd4 10. Nb3 { [Vallejo Pons - Karpov], 2009, 1-0, https://lichess.org/IE8CVU11 }) 4... e6 { Main line. } (4... h5 { This prevents g4, but it weakens the king side. } 5. Bd3 { Common motif: White tries to exchange Blacks light square bishop with Bd3. We see that in many variations. } (5. Nf3 e6 (5... Nh6 6. Bg5 { Ask Black to play f6 and weaken the king side further. } 6... f6 7. Be3) 6. Bd3 { LSB exchange } 6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Nh6 8. Ne2 Nf5 9. c3 $10) 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Nf3 Nh6 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gh6f5,Bf5d4] } 8. Ne2 Nf5 9. c3 $10) (4... Qb6 { Dreyev Defense. Keep the retreat path open for the ls-bishop. } { [%cal Gb6b2] } 5. Nf3 (5. g4?! Bg6 $146 { Hasn't been played (often?). But it's the engine's first choice. } (5... Bd7 { The most common move here. } 6. Na4 Qc7 7. Be3) 6. Nge2 e6 7. a4 Na6) 5... e6 6. Be2 Ne7 7. O-O Nd7) (4... a6 { Allows c5 without a weakness on b5. } 5. Be3 (5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2) 5... e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. Nge2 c5 8. dxc5 Nd7 { [%cal Gf8c5,Gd7c5] } 9. f4 Qh4+! 10. Bf2 Qxg4 11. b4 Ne7 12. Qd2 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6b4] } 13. a3 Rd8 $10) 5. g4 Bg6 6. Nge2 { Prepare Nf4. } { [%cal Re2f4,Bf4g6] } 6... c5 $132 (6... f6 { Try to open the center and to create a retreat square for the bishop. } 7. h4 { Continue the attack anyway. } (7. Nf4) (7. exf6) 7... Nd7 (7... fxe5) 8. f4 (8. h5) 8... fxe5 (8... Bf7) 9. fxe5 Ne7 (9... Be7)) (6... Ne7 7. Nf4 { [%cal Rf4g6] } 7... Nd7 8. h4 h6) 7. h4 h5 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Nxh5 Nc6 (9... cxd4 10. Nb5 Nc6 11. Nxd4 Nge7 12. c3 Nxe5 13. Bg5 N5c6 (13... Qc7 14. Bb5+ N7c6) (13... Qd6 14. Bf4) 14. Bd3 (14. Bg2 Bg8) (14. Nxc6 bxc6) 14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3) 10. dxc5 Bxc5 { [%csl Gg7] } 11. Bb5 (11. Nxg7+?! Kf8 12. Nh5 d4 13. Nb5 a6 14. Na3 (14. Nd6 Nxe5 15. f4 (15. Nxb7? Bb4+ 16. Bd2 Bxd2+ 17. Qxd2 Nf3+ 18. Ke2 Qd5 19. Qf4 Qxb7 20. Qxf3 d3+ { [%cal Gb7f3] } 21. Ke3 Qb6+ $17) 15... Bxc2!? 16. Qxc2 Bb4+ 17. Kd1 Nxg4 { [%cal Gh8h5] } 18. Qg2 Rxh5) 14... Nxe5) 11... Qb6 { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gc5f2] } 12. Qe2 a6 13. Bxc6+ Qxc6 { [%cal Gc6h1,Gd5d4,Gd4c3] } 14. f3 { [%cal Gh5g7] } 14... Kf8 15. Bg5 Rc8 { [%cal Gh7c2,Gc6c2,Bc8c2] } 16. Nd1 { [%csl Rc2][%cal Rd1e3,Re3c2] } *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: – Botvinnik-Carls Defense: 3…c5"]
