[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Advance Variation, Botvinnik-Carls Defense"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "– Botvinnik-Carls Defense: 3…c5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/y1hMSldV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.07.07"]
[UTCTime "14:59:27"]

{ This is my favorite line in the CK. The fight for the initiative begins on move three, and it's often successful in binding White's pieces to the defense of the d4-pawn. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 { The very early c5 is the beginning of the Botvinnik-Carls Defense. Instead of Bf5, Black tries to undermine White's center pawns immediately. White now has to make an important decision: to take or not to take. Looks like a gambit, but Black will very likely get this pawn back. } 4. dxc5 { The most common move move on the board. But online, most players smell a rat and don't take. They'll play c3 instead. Black's problem after dxc5: Getting the pawn back as fast as possible, either requires e6 now – which locks the light squared bishop in, or play Nc6 which can be pinned. The best outcome is getting White's e-pawn for Black's c-pawn. } (4. Ne2 { Rarely played. The knight is not a good defender for the center pawns. And the ls-bishop is blocked for a while. } 4... Nc6 { Most played move. } (4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6) (4... e6) 5. c3 { Almost the only move. Black has a wide range of options now. Most players follow with Bf5 or cxd4, but Bd7, Bg4, and e6 are also possible. } 5... Bf5 { Most common move. Same is true for the following moves here. I don't recommend it. } (5... cxd4 { Open up the position, so Black can get some luft. This is probably the easiest line to play for Black. } 6. cxd4 Bf5 7. Nbc3 e6 8. Ng3 { [%cal Rg3f5] } 8... Bg6 9. Be3 f6 { Van Kampen, Robin - Iotov, Valentin, 0-1, Enschede Twente YM, 2010, https://lichess.org/A3PasNvw }) (5... Bd7 6. g3 Bg4 7. Bg2 e6 $10) (5... Bg4 6. h3 (6. Be3 e6 7. h3) 6... Bf5 { Vukovic, Zdravko - Iordachescu, Viorel, 0-1, Ciocaltea Memorial, 2000, https://lichess.org/uZpXQUnh } (6... Bxe2 7. Bxe2 e6 8. O-O cxd4 (8... Nge7 { Baklan, V. - Fier, A., 1/2-1/2, TCh-FRA Top 12 2014, https://lichess.org/LqZ5GBrH }) 9. cxd4 { Emodi, Gyula - Szabolcsi, Janos, 1-0, HUN-chT 9798, 2017, https://lichess.org/oYHUtGQr })) (5... e6) 6. dxc5 e6 7. b4 Nxe5 8. Nd4 { [%cal Rd4f5] } 8... Bg6 { Mamedov, Rauf - Gunina, Valentina, 1-0, TUR-chT, 2012, https://lichess.org/xISZEvrX } 9. Bb5+ Nd7 10. O-O Be7 $10 { Very typical CK position, but Black isn't very mobile. } { Mamedov, Rauf - Gunina, Valentina, 1-0, TUR-chT, 2012, https://lichess.org/xISZEvrX }) (4. Nf3 cxd4 (4... e6) (4... Nc6 5. dxc5 (5. c4) 5... Bg4 6. c3 (6. a3) 6... Bxf3 (6... e6 7. Be3 a6 (7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qc7 $14) (7... Nge7 8. Nbd2 Nf5 9. Bd4 Be7 $14) 8. Nbd2 Nxe5 9. h3 (9. Be2) 9... Nxf3+ 10. Nxf3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nf6 $10) (6... a6) 7. Qxf3 e6 { [%cal Gf8c5,Gc6e5] } 8. Be3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Nc6 $14) 5. Nxd4 (5. Nbd2) (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qf4 (6. Qe3 g6 7. Bb5 Bh6 8. Qc3 Bxc1 9. O-O { [%cal Rc3c6,Rb5c6] } 9... Bxb2!? 10. Qxb2 Bg4 $10) (6. Bb5 e6 7. O-O Ne7 8. Rd1 Bd7 9. Bxc6 { [%cal Ge7c6,Gd7c6,Gb7c6] } 9... Bxc6 $10) 6... e6 7. Nc3 Nge7 { [%cal Ge7g6] } 8. Bd3 Ng6 9. Qg3 $10)) (4. c3 { The engine thinks cxd4 is good here, and maybe that's true. In practical play however, this would give White the c3 square for the knight. My recommendation is not to do that and develop our knight instead. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Rb1c3] } 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 (5. Bb5?! Qa5! { And here it's handy that White can't protect this bishop with Nc3. Note that this position never happens in top level chess. The following lines don't have to be learned; it's enough if you have seen them once. } { [%csl Bc3] } 6. Bxc6+ { The main move online. } (6. a4 cxd4 7. b4 Qb6 8. Nf3 { dxc3 is not good because of Qxd5. } { [%cal Rd1d5] } 8... e6 (8... dxc3?! 9. Qxd5 { Mildly annoying, but not that bad. } 9... e6 10. Qb3) 9. Nxd4 Bd7 $10) (6. Qa4 { And we take this trade offer. } 6... Qxa4 7. Bxa4 e6 $10 { Black is fine here. }) 6... bxc6 { [%cal Gc5d4] } 7. Ne2 cxd4 8. Nxd4 { The c-pawn is still pinned. e5 is now a very weak pawn. } { [%csl Be5] } 8... e6 9. O-O (9. Nxc6?! Qc7 { [%cal Gc7e5,Gc7c6] } 10. Nd4 Qxe5+ $15 { This is fine for Black. The engine says already -1.1. }) 9... Bd7 $10 { Equal, maybe a slight edge for Black. Next we develop our knight to g6 to avoid kingside attacks and put pressure on the e5-pawn.. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6] }) 5... Bg4 (5... cxd4 { Black can use this chance to open the c-file. The rook on c8 will be very strong later. } 6. cxd4 Bg4 7. Nbd2 e6 8. h3 Bxf3 (8... Bf5) (8... Bh5) 9. Nxf3 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Bb4 11. Bd3 Nge7) 6. dxc5 e6 7. Be3 (7. b4 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Nc6) 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Nc6) (4. a3?! cxd4 5. Qxd4 (5. Ne2) 5... Nc6) 4... e6 (4... Nc6 { Develop first, try to recapture later. } 5. Nf3 { As long as c5 isn't attacked, White can also just develop. It's a race. } (5. Bb5 { Most common move, but not the best. } 5... e6 (5... Qa5+?! { Looks tempting, but it doesn't go anywhere. It's not a real threat for White, but it can be attacked while it doesn't control enough fields in order to fight for Black's initiative. The queen on a5 is just misplaced. } 6. Nc3 e6 (6... a6 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 { [%cal Ga5c5] } 8. Qd4 e6 9. b4 Qd8 $14) 7. Be3 Bd7 { Unpin the knight. } { [%cal Gc6e5] } (7... Ne7 8. Nf3 Nf5 { [%cal Gf5e3] } 9. Bd2 (9. a3 Nxe3 10. fxe3 Be7 11. b4 Qc7 12. e4 { Hulmes, David I - Arkell, Keith C, 0-1, BCF-chTc 1112 (4NCL), 2012, https://lichess.org/UeW6FYpC }) 9... Bxc5 10. Nxd5! { Isn't that queen just awkward? } { [%cal Rd2a5] } 10... Qd8 11. Nc3 $14 { Now Black is one pawn down, and there is no initiative. }) 8. Bxc6 { Most common move. Not the best. An Attack on Black's queen is better. } 8... Bxc6 9. Nf3 Bxc5 10. Bxc5 Qxc5 11. O-O (11. Qd4 b6 { If White wants to go for an early end game, Black should try to keep as many pawns in the center as possible. } 12. Qg4 { [%cal Rg4g7] } 12... Ne7!? 13. Qxg7 Rg8 14. Qxh7 Rxg2 { There is no way to defend the f2-pawn without losing material elsewhere. So long castling is White's best option. } { [%csl Bf2][%cal Gg2f2,Gc5f2] } 15. O-O-O (15. Rf1?! d4 { [%cal Gc6a4,Gc6e4,Gc5c2] } 16. Ne4 Qa5+ 17. Nfd2 (17. c3?! Nf5 { [%cal Gc6e4] } 18. Qh8+ Kd7 19. Qf6 { [%cal Gf6f7] } 19... Rf8 20. Nxd4 Bxe4 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Qxf8 Qd5 23. Qf7+ Kd8 { White can only continue giving checks, because if Black can play Bf3 it's mate in 11. } 24. Qf8+ Kd7 25. Qf7+ Kc8 26. Qf8+ Kb7 27. Qf7+ Ka6 { [%csl Ge7] } 28. Qe8 Rg7 29. Qc8+ Rb7 30. f3 Ne7 $17) 17... Qxe5 $17 { And Black gets the pawn back. A center pawn for one from the h-file. Good trade. }) (15. Nd1) 15... Rxf2 $10) 11... Ne7 $10) 6. Be3 Ne7 7. c3 Bd7 { [%cal Gc6e5] } 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Nf3 Nf5 10. Bd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Qc7 12. b4 b6 13. cxb6 axb6 14. O-O Be7 15. Qe3 Bd7) 5... Bg4 { The bishop is now developed like in the Ruy Lopez. The usual place for this bishop is f5 in many Advance variations. White should now prepare the b4 protection with either a3 or c3. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ra2a3,Rc2c3,Rb2b4] } 6. c3 { [%csl Rd4,Rb4] } 6... e6 { And now the logical and normal e6 to attack c4 and to develop the black-square bishop. b4 and Be3 are now options for White. The former develops a piece, it is therefore the preferred move for many players. } { [%cal Gf8c5] } 7. Be3 { Note that e5 is hanging. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6e5] } (7. b4 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Nc6 10. O-O Be7 (10... g6 11. Re1 Bg7 12. a4 Rc8) (10... Nf6) 11. Rd1 (11. Ba4) (11. Nd2) (11. Bf4)) 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 { Get the pawn back with a tempo. Here we see why this defense is so attractive for Black: Black has *two* center pawns, White has none. This happens in many variations of this defense. } { [%cal Ge5f3] } 9. Bb5+ { White's queen is attacked, but that's no reason to stop piece development. If Black doesn't want to play Ke7, it must retreat with the knight. } 9... Nc6 { Note that Black has only *one* developed piece, and even that is pinned. The black-squared bishop has only e7, the second knight f6. White will play c4 soon in order to attack Black's strong center. } { [%cal Gf8e7,Gg8f6,Rc3c4,Rc4d5,Ga7a6,Ga6b5] } 10. O-O Nf6 (10... Ne7) 11. c4 a6 12. Ba4 Rc8 13. Rd1 Qa5 14. Nc3 dxc4) 5. Nf3 { Give the c-pawn back immediately, protect the center pawn on e5 instead. } (5. Be3 { One way to cling to that pawn. The same as in the 4…Nc6 line above. } 5... Nh6 { This is an indirect attack on the bishop – and an invitation for a trade. } { [%cal Gh6f5,Gf5e3] } (5... Nd7 { Attack c4 again. But } { [%cal Gf8c5,Gd7c5] } 6. Bb5 { prevents that for now. a6 doesn't help, because after Ba4 Black cannot play b5. } 6... Ne7 { Develop instead. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge7f5,Gf5e3] } 7. c3 (7. Nf3 Nf5 8. b4 Nxe3 9. fxe3 a5 10. c3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Qc7 13. Bxd7 Bxd7 14. Qd4) 7... a6 8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 9. Nf3 Nf5 { [%cal Gf5e3,Gf8c5] } 10. Qd2 (10. Bd4 Nxd4 11. cxd4 b6! { Now it is a gambit. } 12. cxb6 Qxb6 { [%cal Gb6b2] } 13. Qb3)) (5... Ne7 { Again, the same motif: Try to attack White's bishop on e3 with the knight. This is slow tough. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge7f5,Gf5e3] } 6. c3 { Now White can dream about an exchange of that bishop on d4. This would restore its center pawns. } { [%cal Re3d4] } 6... Nd7 { Well, the other pawn is tasty too. } { [%cal Gd7e5] } 7. Nf3 { Black is really missing the light-square bishop here. This is the reason why the 4…Nc6 is so attractive for Black. } { [%cal Rf3e5] } 7... Nf5 { A nice move that creates attacks all over the place. } { [%cal Gf5e3,Gf8c5,Gd7c5] }) 6. Bxh6 gxh6 { White could now try to protect c5 again with pawns, but that would cost a few tempi and give Black a lead in development. } 7. Nf3 { Develop instead. } (7. Nc3 Bxc5) 7... Bxc5 (7... Nc6 8. Bb5 Bd7) 8. Bb5+ Bd7) (5. a3 Bxc5 6. b4 Bb6 (6... Be7 7. Qg4 { [%cal Gg4g7] } 7... g6 8. Nf3 a5 9. b5 Nd7) 7. Qg4 Ne7 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 Bd4 10. Ra2 Bxe5 11. Nf3 Bf6 12. c4 Nbc6 13. h4 Qc7 14. Bg5 Rh8 15. Qd3 Bxg5 16. Nxg5 $13) 5... Bxc5 6. Bd3 Ne7 7. Qe2 { The best move according to Stockfish 8, depth 40. Rarely played. But e5 will be under fire soon. } { [%cal Re2e5,Rf3e5,Re2b5] } 7... Nbc6 { [%cal Gc6e5,Ge7g6,Bg6e5,Gd8c7,Bc7e5] } 8. O-O Bd7 { Prepare for pins from b5. This might be a novelty already. Then engine likes it more than Ng6 or 0-0. } 9. Be3 { Black can either lose a tempo with Bb6 or b6, or they can accept the invitation to the exchange. White's bs-bishop could help protecting e5 better than Black's bs-bishop can attack it. } 9... Bxe3 10. Qxe3 *


