1. e4 { The nice thing here is that you can reach the Two Knights position with different move orders. } (1. Nf3 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4) (1. Nc3 c6 2. e4 d5 3. Nf3) 1... c6 2. Nc3 (2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3) 2... d5 3. Nf3 { The order of White's knight development doesn't matter much. White wants to develop its pieces quickly and keep the d-pawn question open. } 3... e6 { Very rare. Mostly because it's not good. } (3... Bg4 { ➡ "Mindeno Variation" }) (3... Nf6 { ➡ Two Knights 3…Nf6. This is the line I recommend. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gd5e4,Rc3e4] }) (3... a6 $14 { Very passive, perhaps too slow. SF8: +0.7. See [Polgar - Nisipeanu] } 4. d4 Bg4 $14 { [%csl Bd3,Re2,Re3,Ge6][%cal Rf1e2,Be2d3,Rc1e3,Ge7e6] }) (3... d4?! { This is tempting, but it's a very bad move strategically. } 4. Ne2 $14 { [%cal Re2d4,Rf3d4] } 4... c5 $14 (4... Nf6 $14 $146 { SF8 recommendation. This is going to be *very* sharp. And better for White. } 5. e5 d3 6. exf6 dxe2 7. Qxe2 gxf6 8. d4 Bg7 $16) 5. c3 (5. b4!? { Interesting move, rarely played. Downside for White is that it will fall behind in development. } 5... Nc6 { [%csl Ge5,Gc5][%cal Ge7e5,Gf8c5] } 6. b5 Na5 7. Ng3 { [%cal Gd8c7,Gb7b6] } 7... g6!? $10 { After the Fianchetto, this is very similar to a Modern Defense structure. b6 should be played eventually to get a retreat square for the knight on a5. Once e5 is played, Black has a strong center, more space, good bishops, and a safe king after the short castling. White should play e5 before Black can do that. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf8g7,Rd2d3,Ge7e5,Gg8h6,Gb7b6,Ba5b7] }) 5... dxc3 6. Nxc3 $146 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Rc3b5,Rf1b5,Rb5e8] } 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 e6 { White will not exchange its good bishop against the poor knight. Better to protect c5 than going Bd7 now. } 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 $16 { Black will get an isolated c-pawn. Not nice. }) (3... dxe4 { See ➡ 3…dxe4 } 4. Ng5 { ➡ Hector Gambit } { [%cal Rg5e4,Rc3e4] }) (3... g6 { NN. I call it "The Fianchetto Line". See [Svidler - Krasenkow] } 4. d4 Bg7 { We can reach the same position from the Modern Defense. } 5. h3 Nf6 6. e5 Ne4) 4. d4 Bb4 (4... Nf6 5. Bd3 Be7 6. O-O O-O $14 { Black should play b6 soon to free the "French Bishop". }) 5. Bd3 (5. e5 { Now we have a structure like in the "Advance Variation". But with a bad bishop on c8 like in the French. Not sure about this line, mostly unclear SF8 moves. } 5... Ne7 6. Bd2 $146 b6 7. Bd3 Bxc3?! 8. Bxc3 Ba6 9. b4 Nf5 $10) (5. exd5 exd5 { Now the bishop on c8 can move. } 6. a3 $146 Bd6 $10 { Bxc3 instead is also good. }) 5... dxe4 6. Bxe4 Nf6 7. Bd3 c5 $14 *


