1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 { This is nowadays the main line and my recommendation for Black. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gd5e4,Rc3e4] } 4. e5 { The main move here. And probably the best one. } (4. exd5?! cxd5 { Now Black has two central pawns, White has one. } { [%cal Gd5d4] } 5. d4 (5. h3 Bf5) 5... Nc6 $10 { Completely equal position, White's bishops are more mobile. } { [%csl Gg4,Ge6,Rb5,Rg5,Rh3,Rd2][%cal Rh2h3,Rf1b5,Rc1g5,Ge7e6,Gc8g4] }) (4. d3?! { This allows Black to claim the center: } 4... e5! { White cannot take this pawn. } { [%cal Gf8b4,Gd8a5,Ga5e5] } 5. Be2 (5. Nxe5? { loses a knight: } 5... d4 6. Nxf7 { Getting a second pawn and removing Black's castling rights is the best White can do now. } (6. Ne2? { Fails to } 6... Qa5+! { A simple fork. } { [%cal Ga5e5,Ga5e1] } 7. c3 dxc3 { Threatening to win the rook. } { [%cal Gc3b2] } 8. Nxc3 Qxe5 $19 { And now Black is just winning. }) 6... Kxf7 7. Ne2 { [%cal Re2d4] } 7... Bc5 $17) 5... d4 { [%csl Ga4,Gb5][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5a4,Gc6d5] } 6. Nb1 Bd6 $15 { In this rarely played line Black changed the pawn colors, so the light-squared bishop should not be traded off. }) 4... Ne4 { [%cal Ge4c3] } 5. Ne2 (5. Nb1!? { Very passive, but still playable for White. It keeps the f1-a6 diagonal open for White. } { [%cal Rf1a6] } 5... Qb6 { A very simple one-move threat. } { [%cal Ge4f2,Gb6f2] } 6. d4 (6. Qe2?! { Blocks White's development of the bishop on f1, and it raises the question why Nb1 has been played then. } { [%csl Bf1] } 6... h6 $146 { is a nice prophylactic move, suggested by Stockfish. Has never been played on the board. } (6... Bg4 7. h3 $146 { The only sensible move. And yet, it has never been played. } (7. d3?! Ng5 (7... Nc5 8. Nbd2 e6 9. h3 { Chudinovskih, Alexander - Lenic, Luka, 0-1, EU-ch 11th, 2010, https://lichess.org/uU1uwNJT }) 8. Nbd2 { Karthikeyan, M2. - Swapnil, SD., 0-1, 53rd ch-IND Challengers, 2015, https://lichess.org/WKiOtCrm }) 7... Bxf3 8. gxf3 Ng5 9. c3 Ne6 { The point here is that Black should prevent White from playing e6, an idea that is always in the air. } { [%cal Re5e6] }) 7. c3 { Prepare d4. } (7. d4?! { Creates too many weaknesses } { [%cal Bb4e1,Gc8f5,Gf5c2] }) 7... Bg4 8. h3 Bh5) 6... c5 7. c3 (7. dxc5 Qxc5 8. Be3 Qb4+ { [%csl Gc3][%cal Ge4c3,Gb4e1] } 9. Nbd2 { [%cal Gb4b2] } 9... Nc6!? $10 { Don't take the b-pawn yet, prevent the check per Bb5 first. }) 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Bf5 $10) (5. Nxe4?! dxe4 6. Ng5 Qd5! 7. Qe2 { [%cal Re2e4,Rg5e4] } (7. d4 exd3 8. Qxd3 Qxe5+ 9. Be2 Qf5 { [%cal Gf5d3] } 10. Ne4 Na6 (10... Qd5)) 7... Bf5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bg2 { And now the pawn can no longer be held. } { [%cal Gg2e4,Ge2e4,Gg5e4] } 9... Qxe5 { [%cal Ge5g5] } 10. Nxe4 h5 11. g5 h4 (11... Bxe4 { This bishop is now pinned. And g6 is annoying. } { [%cal Re2e5,Rg5g6] }) 12. h3 Bxe4 $10 { [%cal Ge5g5,Rd2d4,Re2e4,Rg2e4] } (12... Nd7 { Maybe easier to play than Bxe4. } 13. d3 f5) 13. d3 { [%cal Re2e5] } 13... Bxg2!? 14. Qxe5 Bxh1 15. f3 Bg2 (15... Bxf3? { Mistake! } 16. Qf5! { [%cal Rf5c8,Rf5f3] } 16... Bd5?? (16... e6 17. Qxf3) 17. Qc8#) 16. Qf5 { [%cal Rf5c8] } 16... e6 17. Qg4 { [%cal Rg4g2] } 17... Bxh3 18. Qxh3 $14 { Material is equal here, but White is slightly better. } { [%csl Gh4] }) (5. d4 { is not bad as it looks. If Black takes on c3 immediately, White's dark-squared bishop can come to a3 after bxc3. And that's a very annoying bishop! } 5... Nxc3 (5... Qa5 6. Bd3 (6. Bd2 Nxd2 7. Qxd2 (7. Nxd2 Qb6 8. Nb3 $10) 7... Bf5) 6... c5 (6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bg4 (7... Qxc3+? 8. Bd2 Qa3 9. Ng5 { White gets a strong kingside attack now, and Black can't help with the queen. } { [%cal Rd3h7,Rg5h7,Rd1g4] }))) 6. bxc3 { It is crucial to play e6 here to prevent Ba3. } { [%cal Rc1a3] } 6... e6 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gf8a3] } (6... Bg4? { A wasted tempo. White has now at least three annoying moves: } 7. Ba3 { And now it is difficult to castle. } (7. c4 e6 8. Rb1 Qc7) (7. Rb1 { Qc7 looks natural and tempting here, but b5 is better. } 7... b5 (7... Qc7 8. Ba3 { And here is the Ba3 idea again. It's not deadly, just annoying. It does slow down Black's development. } { Kosteniuk, A. - Mikadze, M., 0-1, European ACP w Rapid 2018, https://lichess.org/s59QVmjq }) 8. a4 a6) 7... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f8] } 8. Be2 e6 9. Bxf8 Nxf8 $10)) 5... Qb6 6. d4 e6 (6... c5?! 7. dxc5 (7. Ng3?! { Carlsen, M. - Grischuk, A., 1-0, ICC Open Final 2016, https://lichess.org/6zf8xzXS }) 7... Qxc5 { Note that the queen can't be harassed by any of White's knights. } 8. Ned4 Nc6 9. Bb5 Bd7 $14) 7. Ng3 (7. Nfg1 f6 8. f3 Ng5 9. exf6 gxf6 10. f4 Ne4 (10... Nf7) 11. Ng3) (7. c3) 7... c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. Bd3 cxd4 (9... Nxg3) 10. Nxe4 (10. cxd4) 10... dxe4 11. Bxe4 dxc3 12. bxc3 Qa5 { [%cal Ga5c3,Ga5e5] } (12... Qa6) (12... Qc7 { [%cal Gc7e5,Gc6e5] } 13. Qe2 { [%cal Re2e5,Re4c6,Rc6e8] } 13... b6) 13. O-O Nxe5 14. Rb1 { [%cal Re4b7,Rb1b7] } 14... Nd7 15. Bxb7 Bxb7 16. Rxb7 Rd8 $14 *


