1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 { "Mindeno Variation". Main line. } 4. h3 { Everyone plays either Bxf3 or Bh5 here. Perhaps something else is possible. I could not find anything convincing. See my experiments below. } (4. d4 dxe4 (4... Nf6 5. Bd3) 5. Nxe4 e6 6. c3 Nd7 $146 7. Bg5 { Provoke Black to play f6 which would weaken the king side pawns. } 7... Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6) (4. Be2?! e6 5. O-O Nf6 6. h3 (6. Ne5?! Bxe2 7. Qxe2) 6... Bh5 7. Ne5) 4... Bxf3 { "Mindeno Variation, Exchange Line" } (4... Bh5 { "Mindeno Variation, Retreat Line" } 5. d4 (5. exd5 { Main line. } 5... cxd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. g4 (7. d4 e6 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 Rc8 $10) 7... Bg6 8. Ne5 Rc8 9. d4 e6 $10 { See 7.d4 for a different move order. } 10. Bxc6+ $146 bxc6 11. h4 { Immediate attack on the king side. } { [%cal Rh4h6,Rg4g5,Rc1h6,Rh1h4,Re5g6] } 11... f6 { See [Kasimdzhanov - Seirawan] } 12. Nxg6 hxg6 $10 { Black's king will not castle, but it has a safe place on f7. } 13. Qd3 Kf7 14. Bd2) (5. g4 Bg6 6. exd5 cxd5 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne5 Rc8 9. d4 e6 10. h4 f6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qd3 Kf7 13. Bxc6 Rxc6 14. Bd2 Bb4) 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nf6 7. Bd3 $146 Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Qc7?! 9. O-O e6 $14) (4... dxe4 $16 $146 5. hxg4 exf3 6. Qxf3 e6 7. b3 Nf6 $16 (7... Nd7)) (4... d4 $16 $146 { A gambit without enough compensation. } 5. hxg4 dxc3 6. bxc3 Nf6 $16) (4... Be6 $16 $146 5. d4 dxe4 { Prevent e5 by White. } 6. Nxe4 Nf6 $14 { [%cal Re4c5,Re4g3,Re4f6] }) 5. Qxf3 (5. gxf3 e6 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd5d4] } (5... d4 { Rarely played but best move acc. to SF8. } 6. Ne2 c5 7. d3 $146 { Looks like a reversed Advanced Caro-Kann now. } 7... Nc6 $10) (5... Nf6 6. d4 e6 (6... Nbd7 $146 7. Rg1 g6 8. Bg5 Qa5 { Just a different move order. }) 7. Rg1 g6 8. Qd3 Nbd7 $146 9. Bg5 Qa5 $10) 6. d4 { d3 and Rg1 have been played also, but d4 is by far the best: It prevents the very annoying d4 by Black. Normal responses here are: Nf6, Nd7, and g6. } 6... Bb4 $146 { SF8 suggestion, not in the database. Threatening to create a second pair of doubled pawns. } { [%cal Gb4c3] } (6... Nf6 { One of the main moves. } 7. Rg1 g6 8. Qd3 Nbd7 $146 9. Bg5 Qa5 $10) (6... Nd7 { One of the main moves. Best option according to SF8. } 7. Qd3 g6 8. h4 Ngf6 9. Bg5 Qc7 $10) (6... g6 { One of the main moves. Second best option after Nd7 according to SF8. } 7. Be3 Nf6 $10) 7. Rg1 { [%cal Gg1g7] } 7... Ne7 { If Rxe7 now, the knight can trap that rook. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Ge7g6,Rg1g7] } 8. h4 { [%csl Rh5,Gg6][%cal Ge7g6] } (8. Rxg7? Ng6 9. Bh6 Qf6 { [%cal Gf6d4,Bd4c3,Bb4c3,Yc3a1,Yc3e1,Gf6f3] } 10. Qe2 Nh4 { White in hell now. } { [%cal Gh4f3,Gf6f3,Gf6h6] } 11. Qe3 { [%cal Re3h6,Re3c3,Re3e4,Re3f3] } 11... Bf8 { Just add more threats. Niiice! } 12. e5 Nxf3+ { No castling for White. } 13. Kd1 Qf5 14. Rg4 Nxd4! 15. Qxd4 (15. Rxd4?! Qh5+ 16. Be2 Qxh6 { [%cal Gh6h3,Gf8c5] } 17. Qxh6 Bxh6 $17) 15... Bxh6 16. f4 Qh5 17. Be2 Qxh3 18. Kd2 { [%csl Rg1][%cal Ra1g1,Rg1g8] } 18... Bf8 19. Qd3 Qxd3+ $17) 8... Rg8 (8... g6 { Too passive, and it weakens the pawn structure. } 9. Qd3 { Freeing the 1st line for the king. } { [%cal Rc1d2,Re1c1,Ra1d1] } 9... c5!? { [%cal Gc5c4,Gc5d4,Gc4d3] } 10. Bg5 { [%cal Gd8a5,Gb8c6,Gc5d4,Gc5c4] } 10... Qa5 $10) 9. Bd2 Nd7 { Black needs to castle queen side now. Same for White. } 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. O-O-O Ba5!? 12. Kb1 Nf6 $14 { [%cal Gf6d5,Ge7d5] }) 5... e6 (5... Nf6 6. Qf4 $146 (6. e5 Nfd7 7. d4 e6 8. Bf4) 6... e6 7. Be2 Be7 8. O-O O-O $10) (5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nd7 7. c3 $146 (7. d4 Ngf6 8. Bd3 e6 9. c3 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 $14) 7... Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $14 { [%cal Rf1c4,Rd2d4,Rf3g3,Ge7e6] } 9. Bc4 { Pins the knight. } { [%cal Rc4f7,Rf3f7] } 9... e6 $14) 6. d4 (6. d3 { One of the main moves, but probably too passive. In the following lines the engine will always put d4 as one of the top moves for White. Which is very unlikely to happen for plain psychological reasons. You don't want to move the pawn twice in the opening. } 6... Nd7 7. Bd2 { Main move. The most common responses here are g6, Ngf6, and Bc5. My recommendation is to play for the initiative right away and go for some forcing moves like Qb6 or d4 (both moves are often played in combination, see the line with 7.Qg3 Ne7 …10…Qb6). } (7. Qg3 { This is quite annoying for the black side, because it locks the bishop on f8 to its current place. } { [%cal Rg3g7] } 7... g6 { Fianchetto is a sensible way to handle this. Most of the pawns are on light squares anyway, and the a1-h8 diagonal is available. It is very important now for Black to keep the dark-squared bishop as long as possible. } { [%csl Bc2,Bd3,Be4,Bg2,Bh3,Bh7,Bg6,Bf7,Be6,Bd5,Bc6,Bb7][%cal Bg7c3] } (7... Ne7 { If Black doesn't want to go for the fianchetto, putting this knight to g6 will aslo protect g7. } { [%cal Be7g6] } 8. Be2 Ng6 { It is however an invitation for White to play } 9. h4 { and this requires the answer } 9... h5 { and after } 10. Bg5 { Black will find it very difficult to castle. } 10... Qb6 (10... Qb8?! { Asking for a queen trade that White shouldn't accept. } 11. Qe3 (11. Qxb8+?! Rxb8 12. O-O-O?! { Salakhutdinov, Ildar - Konings, Leon, 1-0, Lost Boys op, 2002, https://lichess.org/0TCQNDWH })) (10... Be7 11. d4! dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nf6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. O-O-O $13 { Certainly easier to play for White. } { Bortnik, A. - Zenzera, A., 1-0, Somov Memorial 2014, https://lichess.org/5vbJVPLC }) 11. O-O-O d4! 12. Nb1 { is absolutely playable. } 12... e5! $10 { cuts the board in half and suddenly White's queen is quite misplaced: it has nothing to do on g3. Also White's light-squared bishop is now worth much less than any of Black's knights. } { [%cal Gf8e7] }) 8. Be2 Bg7 9. O-O Ne7 $10 { Black has already equalized here } { Jones, Gawain C - Ivanchuk, Vassily, 0-1, EU-ch blitz 29th, 2010, https://lichess.org/NX0USJO1 } { Polgar, Judit - Seirawan, Yasser, 0-1, Amber-blindfold 03rd, 1994, https://lichess.org/J4QU03zt }) 7... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6b2,Gb6f2] } (7... d4 8. Ne2 { [%cal Ge2d4] } 8... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6b2] } (8... e5 { Rendle, T. - Molyneux, J., 1-0, 4NCL Rapid Team 2014, https://lichess.org/tQLxgurB } { I am not so sure about this change of pawn colors. Black has no light-squared bishop anymore. }) 9. O-O-O) 8. O-O-O { [%cal Gb6b2,Gb6f2] } 8... Bd6 { The idea is to discourage White from putting the queen onto the g-file. This works in practical play – no one goes for for Qg4 now – but technically, it fails! } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gd6g3,Gb6f2] } 9. Qg4! { If Black accepts the pawn trade } 9... Qxf2 { then White has an interesting zwischenzug before Qxg7: } { [%cal Rg4g7] } 10. exd5 cxd5 { weakens the pawn structure on the queen-side where Black should try a pawn storm in normal cases. } (10... exd5 { is also possible, but asking for Re1. } 11. Qxg7 Be5 { [%cal Ge5h8] } 12. Qg4 O-O-O $10 { This is still okay for both sides, but the lack of a light-squared bishop is now a strategic problem for Black. }) 11. Qxg7 Be5 12. Qg4 Ne7 $10 { This is equal. Black's king is and will be for some time a little bit exposed }) *


