1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 { This is strategically dubious: Black's trumps are the two center pawns, trading one off without a compensation in development or a new weakness on White's side makes just no sense to me. } 4. Nxe4 (4. Ng5 { ➡ Hector Gambit } { [%cal Rg5e4,Rc3e4] } 4... e5 { [%cal Gd8g5] } (4... e6 5. Ngxe4 f5 (5... c5?! 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. d3 Bxb5 8. Nxb5 Nc6?! { Hector, Jonny - Hansen, Lars Bo, 1/2-1/2, Tastrup, 1992, https://lichess.org/kQvnZn05 }) 6. Ng3 Bc5 7. Be2) 5. Ngxe4 f5 6. Ng3 Be6 { [%cal Gg8f6] } 7. d4 Qxd4 8. Qxd4 exd4 9. Nce2 c5 10. Nf4 { [%cal Rf4e6] } 10... Bf7 11. Nxf5 g6 12. Ng3 Nd7 $15 { Black is just ahead in development. }) 4... Nf6 { Most played move here. Not so nice for Black's pawn structure, but the exchange will open the field for the black-squared bishop. After the exchange Nxf6 exf6 we have a position very similar to the ➡ Tartakower variation. } (4... Nd7 { Prepares Ngf6, like in the ➡ Karpov variation. } { [%cal Gg8f6] } 5. Bc4 { [%csl Rg5,Gf7][%cal Rc4f7,Rf3g5,Rg5f7] } (5. Qe2 { Careful here, this is a trap! Now Black can't play Ngf6; they have to play Ndf6 instead.
Most people play e6 or Ndf6 here, but Qc7 is also playable. } 5... Ndf6 (5... Ngf6?? 6. Nd6#!) (5... Qc7 { The idea is to delay the piece trades and keep the diagonal for the light-squared bishop open. It also doesn't allow White to play Bf4 once the d-pawn is advanced. } { [%csl Bf4][%cal Rc1f4,Gc7f4,Gc8g4] } 6. g3 { Just logical, because the queen blocks the bishop's other diagonal. } { [%csl Be2,Bf1] } 6... Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ (7. Bg2 Nxe4 { And now the trade is fine. } 8. Qxe4 Nf6 { Now the queen has to move a third time, and it's not so clear where it can go without being attacked again. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } 9. Qc4) 7... Nxf6 8. Bg2 Bg4) 6. d3 { [%cal Rc1f4,Rf4g5] } (6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. g3) 6... Nxe4 7. dxe4) 5... b5 $146 (5... Ngf6 6. Neg5 e6 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. d4 Be7 (8... h6 { Different move order. } 9. Ne4 Be7 10. O-O O-O) 9. O-O h6 10. Ne4 O-O $10) 6. Bb3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ exf6!? { Weird SF8 gives +0.1 for this move, +0.4 for Nxf6. It does prevent Ng5 and Ne5. } (7... Nxf6) 8. c3 Qe7+ { Removes White's right to castle. Queen exchange on e2 would do that too, but White's king would be on an uncomfortable place. So … } 9. Kf1 $10) (4... Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 Nd7 7. d4 Ngf6 $14) (4... Bf5 { This is better for White. } 5. Ng3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Nf6 $14) 5. Nxf6+ (5. Qe2 { This is surprisingly White's best move here. } 5... Nxe4 6. Qxe4 { Black has a range of choices here. Qd5 is the most common move. } 6... Qd5 { offers a queen trade that White declines here, because this would only strengthen Black's pawn center. } { [%cal Gc6d5] } (6... Nd7 7. Bc4 { [%cal Rf3g5,Rg5f7,Rc4f7] } 7... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 8. Ne5! { Trap! Black can't take White's queen here. f7 has to be protected first. } 8... e6 (8... Nxe4?? 9. Bxf7#) 9. Qe2 Be7 (9... b5 { This gives White a threat. } { [%cal Re5c6] } 10. Bb3 { [%cal Re5c6] } 10... Qc7 { [%cal Re5c6,Gc7c6] } (10... Qb6?! 11. O-O Bd6 12. c3 c5 $14 { Muzychuk, A. - Gunina, V., 1-0, European ACP w Rapid 2018, https://lichess.org/Ht3jRD5V }) 11. O-O (11. d4 Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 Bb7 14. c3 a5 15. a4 b4 $10 (15... c5? $16 { Stukopin, A. - Kumar, Nikhil, 1-0, 11th Philadelphia Int, 2017, https://lichess.org/4vNrGWvu })) 11... Bd6 12. Re1 O-O 13. a4 b4 $10 { Mitkov, N1. - Kumar, Nikhil, 1/2-1/2, 26th North American Open, 2016, https://lichess.org/oPAy9MDH }) 10. O-O O-O 11. c3 Nd5 { Sosulin, Eduard - Arakeljan, Armen M, 0-1, Bogoroditsk 03, 2011, https://lichess.org/WS2RBJPu }) (6... Be6 { The idea here is Bd5, a very unusual place for the light-squared bishop in the Caro-Kann. } { [%cal Ge6d5] } 7. Be2 (7. b3 Bd5 (7... Nd7 8. Bb2) 8. Qe3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 (9. gxf3?! e6 10. Bb2 Nd7 11. f4 $10 { L'Ami, E. - Girya, O., 1/2-1/2, 80th Tata Steel GpB, 2018, https://lichess.org/VKRqYotn }) 9... Qd4 { [%cal Gd4a1] } 10. c3 Qd5 $14) 7... Bd5 8. Qe3 e6 9. O-O Bd6) (6... Qa5) 7. Qh4 (7. Qf4) 7... Qe6+ 8. Be2 Qg4 { and now White can't avoid the trade anymore, but they will get the open h-file for this. } 9. Qg3 Qxg3 10. hxg3 { This situation is slightly better for White, because Black is behind in development. But it's still playable for both sides. } 10... Bg4 (10... Bf5 { is the main move here, and I don't really see why. Black can't take on c2 anyway. } { [%cal Gf5c2] } 11. d3 { [%cal Gc1f4] } (11. b3 Bxc2?? (11... Nd7 12. Bb2 e6 13. O-O-O h6 14. Rde1 (14. Nh4 Bh7 15. g4 Rg8 16. Nf3 Bg6 17. Nh4 Bh7 { Howell, D. - Svane, R., 1-0, PRO League Group Stage, 2017, https://lichess.org/nhRRClOF }) 14... Rg8 15. Nh4 Bh7 16. Bh5 Ke7 { Liang, Awonder - Brattain, Mika A, 1-0, ch-USA Junior 2017, https://lichess.org/H1Y3Vssa }) 12. d3! { And now the bishop is trapped. }) 11... h6 12. Be3 Nd7) (10... g6 11. d4 Bg7 12. Bh6 Bf6 13. Ne5 { Bacrot, E. - Topalov, V., 1/2-1/2, GCT Rapid Paris 2017, https://lichess.org/aAMypkLw }) 11. b3 Nd7 12. Bb2) 5... exf6 6. d4 (6. Bc4 Bd6 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1+ Kf8 11. Rxe8+ Kxe8 12. d4 Bf5 $10) 6... Bd6 7. Be2 $10 O-O 8. O-O Re8 $10 { [%cal Rc1e3,Rf1e1,Rc2c4,Gc8f5,Gc6c5] } *


