1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 { B13 Caro-Kann Defense: Exchange Variation. exd5 simplifies the position, White doesn't keep the tension in the center. The "average rating" of this move is a bit lower than for most of the alternatives (e5, Nc3). } 3... cxd5 (3... Qxd5?! { Rarely seen at the higher level. This just helps White's development. } 4. c4 Qa5+?! (4... Qd8 { Actually the best option here. What a sad move. }) 5. Bd2 Qb6 { [%cal Gb6b2] } 6. Bc3 $14) (3... Qa5+?! { Also rare. For the same good reason. } 4. Bd2 Qxd5 5. Nf3 $14) (3... Nf6?! { A little gambit with no name. Ivanchuk played this once – successfully, because his opponent declined it. https://lichess.org/Dda3adKV. White should just accept. This position is more likely to occur in the Scandinavian: 1.e4 d5 2.exd5 Nf6 3.d4 c6. After 4.dxc6 e5 it is called the Kadas Gambit. } 4. dxc6 Nxc6 (4... e5 $16 { B01 Scandinavian Defense: Kadas Gambit }) 5. Nf3 (5. c3 e5 6. Nf3 exd4 7. cxd4 (7. Bb5 Qe7+ 8. Be2 dxc3 9. Nxc3 Qc7 10. O-O a6 $14) 7... Bb4+ (7... Bg4 8. Nc3 Bb4 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nxd4 12. Bxb7 Rb8) 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be2 Bg4 $14) 5... Bg4 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4,Gd8d4] } (5... e5 6. Bb5) 6. Bb5 (6. Be2 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Nxd4 8. Bxb7 Rb8 9. Be3 Nxc2+ 10. Qxc2 Rxb7 11. O-O e6) 6... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6d4,Gc6d4,Bb6b5] } 7. Nc3 $14 O-O-O 8. Bxc6 Qxc6) 4. c3 { A very common variation, usually just a different move order than the main line with Bd3 immediately. See ➡ 4.Bd3 } (4. Bd3 { See ➡ 4.Bd3. Main move nowadays. }) (4. g4?! { Bulla Attack. This reminds us of the ➡ Advance/Bayonet Attack, except for the fact that White has nothing here.
Peter Bulla had this position 1993 as a result of a Grob opening: 1.g4 d5 2. e3 c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.exd4 – he won.
The following moves are engine suggestions. Black seems to be just better. } 4... Nc6 5. Nc3 Bd7 (5... e5) 6. h4 e6 7. a3 Bd6 8. Be3 Rc8 9. Qd2 Qb6 10. h5 Na5 { [%cal Gb6b2] } 11. b3 h6 $15) (4. Nc3 { This is not very aggressive, and it's blockading White's c-pawn. Which means there is no Qa4 in the near future, and we can safely develop our bishop to g4, if we want.
However, my recommendation here is Nc6 and wait what White does with their kingside knight. } 4... Nc6) (4. c4 { See ➡ Panov Attack }) (4. Nf3 { See ➡ 4.Nf3 }) 4... Nc6 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. Bd3 { And now we are in the Rubinstein Variation, see ➡ Bd3. } *


