1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 { The idea here is to take all good places for Black's light-squared bishop away. So the usual early development of this piece is not possible anymore.
In the Exchange Variation, Black's light-squared bishop works often better on f5 than on g4. The reasons are:
1. White plays c3 or c4 quite often, escaping the knight-pin on g4 with a check. And then Nf3-e5 is very annoying for Black, because that move forks c6 and g4.
2. Black's queenside knight goes to c6 usually. Together with a bishop on f5 it can put a lot of pressure on c2.
And that's why Bd3 is such a good move for White. It prevents all that and leaves the question of their c-pawn open. } { [%csl Rh3,Rg4,Rf5][%cal Rd1a4,Rg1f3,Bf3e5,Gb8c6,Gc8f5,Bc6b4,Bb4c2,Bf5c2] } 4... Nc6 { The downside of Bd3 is that White can't play c4 so easily. After Nc6 White has to play c3 in order to protect d4. Nf3 does that too, but that's a knight that wants to be as mobile as possible. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } (4... Nf6 { Regains the g4 square for the bishop. } { [%csl Gg4] } 5. c3 { Now Bf4 isn't such a good idea, because: } 5... Bg4 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3b7] } 6... Qc7 { Prevents Bf4. } 7. h3 Bd7 { And now the bishop has to go back. Not very efficient. } (7... Bh5?! { Loses a pawn, if White is ready to play an IQP game. } 8. g4 (8. Ne2 { [%cal Gc1f4] } 8... Nc6 9. Bf4 Qd7 10. Nd2 e6 { Black is fine here. }) 8... Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. g5 Nfd7 11. Qxd5 { Gone is the center pawn. } 11... e5 { Fast counter-attack. } 12. Ne2 Nc6 13. Be3 exd4 14. cxd4 { Now White has an IQP. } { [%cal Rd4e5,Rd4c5] } (14. Nxd4?! O-O-O! 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Qg2 Ne5 { White is slightly better, but not a full pawn better. Black's knight is very annoying, b2 is hanging, and castling either side is risky or even impossible. } { [%cal Gd8d1,Gc7b7,Gf8c5,Ge5d3] } 17. Nd2 Nd3+ { Ruin castling for good. } 18. Ke2 { Black should not take on b2 and give White the open b-file! } { [%csl Gb2] } 18... Bc5 $10) 14... Bb4+ 15. Nbc3 Ne7 16. Qb3) 8. Nf3 { Loss of tempo for Black. }) (4... a6!?) 5. c3 (5. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3d4] } 5... Bg4 { Renewing the threat on d4. This is one of these situations in which we put the bishop on g4 and not on f5. } 6. c3 Qc7 { Prevent Bf4. See the 4…Nf6 line. } 7. h3 { Everyone and their dog plays Bh5 here. But Bxf3 is also very interesting. } 7... Bh5 (7... Bxf3 { Very rare. I could find only 7 games with it. } 8. Qxf3 Nxd4! { White can't play cxd4, because the bishop on c1 is hanging. } { [%cal Gc7c1] } 9. Qxd5 Rd8 10. Qe4 (10. Bb5+ Nxb5 11. Qxb5+ Rd7 { No need to trade queens so early. } 12. Qa4 { [%cal Ra4a7,Rc1f4] } 12... a6 13. Bf4 e5 { Black will now develop the bishop to d6, the knight to f6, and castle. b5 is always an option.
White will castle short, develop the knight to d2 and the rook from f1 to e1. } { [%cal Gf8d6,Rf4g3,Gg8f6,Ge8g8,Gb1d2,Ge1g1,Ga1e1,Gb7b5] }) 10... Nf6 11. Qe3 { Now White's bishop doesn't hang anymore. } 11... Nc6 12. Nd2 { h6, a6 and e6 are good candidate moves for Black now. White will probably castle short and move the queen to e2 to let the dark-squared bishop out.
The position is equal. White has the bishop pair, but Black has still a center pawn in contrast to White. } { [%cal Gh7h6,Ga7a6,Ge7e6,Re1g1,Re3e2,Rc1g5] }) 8. Be3 e6 9. Nbd2 { [%cal Rc3c4,Rd2f3,Rd1b3] } 9... Bd6 10. O-O Nge7 $10) 5... Nf6 { If you can't develop the light-squared bishop, develop the second knight. } (5... Qc7 { An attempt to prepare e5. } 6. Ne2 (6. h3 { [%csl Gg4] } 6... Nf6 (6... e5 7. dxe5 Qxe5+ (7... Nxe5) 8. Ne2) (6... g6 7. Ne2) 7. Nf3 g6) 6... Bg4 7. f3 (7. O-O e6 (7... Nf6 8. Qe1 e6 9. Ng3) 8. Qe1 Bd6 9. f3 Bh5 10. Qh4 Bg6 11. Bxg6 fxg6) 7... Bd7 8. Bf4 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. O-O Bd6) (5... e5 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Nf3 Nxd3+ 8. Qxd3) 6. Bf4 $10 { Rubinstein Variation } (6. Nf3 Bg4 7. O-O e6) 6... Bg4 { Now it's a move. Still with a similar follow-up: } 7. Qb3 { There are many alternatives to the most played move Qc8. Let's take a look. } { [%cal Rb3b7] } 7... e5 { The start of a nice little maneuver. } (7... Qc8 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O) (7... Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 g6 10. Nf3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O) 8. dxe5 Nh5 9. Be3 (9. Bg3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 Nxe5 11. Bb5+ Nc6 { Chigaev, M. - Navara, D., 0-1, European Blitz 2017, https://lichess.org/VVx0TfLF }) (9. Qxb7 Nxf4 10. Qxc6+ Bd7) 9... Nxe5 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. h3 Be6 { Threat: d4 } { [%cal Bd5d4] } 12. Qd1 Nf6 13. Nf3 Bd6 { Black's pieces are placed perfectly. The IQP can be a strength or a liability. } { [%csl Bd5] } 14. O-O O-O 15. Nbd2 a6 (15... Qd7 16. Re1 a6 17. Bf1 Rac8 18. Nb3 Ne4 { Wei Yi - Navara, D., 0-1, Wei Yi - Navara Match TB, 2018, https://lichess.org/t4MPkBzy }) 16. Bd3 Re8 17. Nb3 Ne4 { Zhang Xiaowen - Lei Tingjie, 1/2-1/2, TCh-CHN 2017, https://lichess.org/ziLPkUoO } *


