1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 { This is my recommendation. } (4... Nf6 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. c3 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Bf4) 5. c3 (5. c4 { Pseudo-Panov structure, often played by Sveshnikov. } 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 g6 { This is my recommendation. As in the ➡ Grugenidze System, White cannot protect d4 with the c-pawn. } (6... Bg4 { And we transpose to the Panov Attack/Modern Defense Mieses Line. See ▶ Panov Attack }) 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 e6 $10 { White has excellent development options for their bishops, but also an IQP. Black will put his bishop on g7 and castle short. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] } (8... Nxc3 9. Bc4 { [%cal Rc4f7] } 9... Nd5 10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O Qd5) 9. Bb5 Bg7 $10) (5. Nc3?! { Rare sideline. White is blocking their c-pawn, which leaves d4 a bit weak. A long-term plan for Black is to put pressure on c2 per Rc8 and Qc7. That immobilizes the knight and b2 which is protecting it. } { [%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Gd8c7,Ga8c8,Bc7c2] } 5... Bg4 { Threatening Bxf3 gxf3 with a damaged pawn structure for White, or Bxf3 Qxf3 and maybe Nxd4, although White will get d5 in this case. } 6. Be2 (6. Bb5 e6 7. O-O Bd6 8. h3 Bh5 { Keep the pressure! g4 would weaken White's kingside. } 9. Re1 { Note that e6 is pinned, so the threat here is Nxd5! } { [%cal Rc3d5] } 9... Nf6 { Defends d5 and prepares castling. } { [%cal Gf6d5] } (9... Ne7 { Black is fine here. After O-O, Qc7 and maybe Bg6, there are no weaknesses on Black's side. } { [%cal Ge8g8,Gd8c7,Gh5g6,Bg6c2] }) 10. Qd3 { Unpins the knight on f3. } { [%csl Bf3][%cal Gh5f3] } 10... Bg6 { This an important motif you should keep in mind: Whenever white's queen goes to d3, play Bg6. Especially in this line it's putting pressure on c2 already as mentioned earlier. } { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gg6d3] } 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Bg5 Rc8 $15 { [%cal Gg6c2,Gc8c2] }) 6... e6 7. O-O Bd6 { Black should always try to place the dark-squared bishop on d6 in this line. Together with Qc7 it adds a lot of pressure on White's kingside. } 8. Nb5 Bb8 9. c3 a6 10. Na3 { This knight is out of play for a while. } 10... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6g4] } 11. Ne5 { [%cal Re5g4,Re2g4] } 11... Bxe5 12. Bxg4 Bd6 $15 { [%cal Gf6g4] }) 5... Nf6 6. Bf4 { Black has tried a number of moves here, g6 or Bg4 for example. My recommendation if Bf5. See the chapter ➡ 4.Bd3 for my musings about the light-squared bishop in the Exchange variation. } 6... Bf5 7. Qb3 { The natural square c7 is covered by White's light-squared bishop, so we have to protect b7 with } { [%cal Rb3b7] } 7... Qc8 (7... Na5?! { is possible, but the knight is misplaced here and practically out of play. }) 8. Nbd2 e6 9. Nh4 { [%cal Gh4f5] } 9... Be4 10. Nxe4 { dxe4 is possible, but this pawn becomes an easy target for White. } 10... Nxe4 { Threatens g5! So White has to move one of the pieces now, or attack the knight with Bd3, which is probably the best move: it develops the bishop to its natural square and isn't just defensive. } { [%cal Gg7g5] } (10... dxe4?! 11. g3 Be7 { [%cal Ge7h4] } 12. Ng2 Nd5 { [%cal Gd5f4] } 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Be2) 11. Nf3 (11. Be3 { is very passive for White. } 11... Be7 { Looking at the knight on h4. g3 doesn't really prevent the exchange, so White should play Nf3. Another passive move. } { [%cal Ge7h4] } 12. Nf3 O-O { This is fine for Black: the development is completed, f5 is possible now, and White still hasn't even castled. } { [%cal Gf7f5] } 13. Bd3 f5 14. O-O Bd6 { It is important not to let White's knight to e5. } { [%csl Be5][%cal Gc8c7,Gd6h2] }) (11. Bd3 { Probably White's best move here. Everyone is playing Bd6 now, but maybe g5 is an option? } 11... g5 (11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 (12. Bxe4?! { A very dubious move played by Kamsky 2016. } 12... Bxf4 13. Bd3 { Black can now push the g-pawn with tempo: } 13... g5! 14. Nf3 g4! 15. Ng1 { The only good move! } 15... h5 16. Ne2 Bh6 { Kamsky, G. - Onischuk, Al, 1/2-1/2, ch-USA 2016, https://lichess.org/mU8W8hLO } { This is just great for Black. } { [%cal Gf7f5] }) (12. Be3 { Too passive. } 12... Nf6 { Black should keep this knight. } 13. O-O O-O 14. Nf3 Qc7 { And we have a very typical Caro-Kann situation. Fine for both sides. }) 12... Nxd6 13. Nf3 O-O { This is now very similar to the 11.Be3 line and quite good for Black. }) 12. Bxe4 gxf4 13. Bd3 Qc7 { Black can only castle long now. } 14. Nf3 O-O-O { and White should do the same. Castling short when Black has the open g-file seems to be very risky. The engine says that's fine, but … you have to play the rest like an engine if you want to win this. } 15. O-O-O $10) 11... Bd6! 12. Bxd6 Nxd6 13. Bd3 Qc7 { Carlsen, M. - Wojtaszek, R., 1-0, 20th European Teams, 2015, https://lichess.org/4Y0qan8k } { This is a good setup for both sides. White's queen is a bit off, but there are no serious problems. } *


