1. e4 c6 2. d4 (2. c4 { This is a different move order. But if you really want to play the Panov as White, you should take the main line here via Exchange variation. The reason is that Black can now play e5 instead of d5, and then you get a completely different game. } 2... d5 (2... e5! { See ➡ Accelerated Panov/Open }) 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4) 2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 { c4 marks the beginning of the Panov Attack, sometimes also called the Panov–Botvinnik Attack. } 4... Nf6 (4... g6?! { This is probably too early. Let's call it the Accelerated Fianchetto Defense. This will either transpose to one of the main lines in the Fianchetto Defense, or to a very unique and open game after 5.cxd5 Qxd5. I do not recommend this line for Black. } 5. Nc3 (5. cxd5 Qxd5?! { This is the unique setup I was talking about. And as in the Scandinavian, White can now develop the knight with a tempo on the queen. } (5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg7 { transposes to the Fianchetto Gambit }) 6. Nc3 Qd8 7. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7] } 7... Bg7 8. Qb3 { [%cal Rc4f7] } 8... e6 9. d5 { What a convinient way to get rid of the IQP. Black shouldn't make this so easy for White. } 9... exd5 $14 { White is already better here: 3 active pieces and a serious threat. } 10. Nxd5 (10. Bxd5 { █████ CONTINUE }) 10... Nf6 (10... Nc6? 11. Bf4 Nd4 12. Qg3! { [%cal Rd5c7,Rc7e8,Rc7a8] } (12. Qe3+? Be6 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. Ne2 { Godena, Michele - Nemet, Ivan, 1/2-1/2, Reggio Memorial Chicco 33rd, 1991, https://lichess.org/znSSQEwv } { Yemelin, Vasily - Rumiantsev, Anton, 1-0, Chigorin Memorial 13th, 2005, https://lichess.org/kuXnIc5p })) 11. Qe3+ Be6 12. Nf4) 5... Nf6 { Transposes to the normal Fianchetto defense }) 5. Nc3 (5. c5 { ➡ Gunderam Attack } { [%cal Rf1b5,Rd1a4] }) 5... e6 (5... g6 { Panov Attack/Fianchetto Defense. If White doesn't take d5 immediately, this will usually continue as a gambit. } 6. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Bc4d5,Yc3d5] } (6. cxd5 Nxd5 { is of course possible and playable. } (6... Bg7 { Fianchetto gambit } 7. Bb5+ Nbd7 (7... Bd7?! { is very dubious: where does the knight on b8 go now after Bc4? } 8. Bc4 { [%cal Yb8c6,Yb8a6] } 8... O-O 9. Qb3 Bf5 10. Nge2 (10. Qxb7?! { White is giving up their advantage with that. } 10... Nbd7 11. Bf4 Nb6 (11... Ne8?! 12. Nf3 { Nunn, John DM - Hickl, Joerg, 1-0, Dortmund-A, 1987, https://lichess.org/B5aBZaOR }) 12. Bb3 Nh5 13. Bc7 Qd7 14. Qc6 Rfc8 15. Qxd7 Nxd7 16. d6 exd6 17. Bd5 { [%cal Rd5a8] } 17... Re8+ 18. Nge2 Rac8 $10) 10... Nbd7 11. Ng3 Nb6 12. Nxf5 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 gxf5 14. O-O Rc8 15. Qb3 Qd6 $14) 8. d6 { White cannot defend this pawn anyway. Exchanging it in a way that damages Black's pawn structure is the best White can do here. } (8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Nb6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gb6d5,Gd8d5] } 10. Re1 a6 11. Be2 (11. Bf1 { is the database move. Also fine. } 11... Nbxd5 12. Qb3 $10) 11... Nbxd5 $10) 8... exd6 { is the main move here. It keeps material equality, but now Black has an IQP too. } (8... O-O!? { This is better than getting an IQP for Black. } 9. dxe7 Qxe7+ 10. Nge2 (10. Be2 b5! { Gambiting another pawn! The compensation is not so easy to see and only visible after a couple of moves. White has only two good moves here: Nxb5 and a3. The follow-ups given here have never been played, and you will probably not get them over the board. But they do illustrate why b5 is so good. } 11. Nxb5 { White should take the pawn. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gf6d5] } (11. a3 { A line suggested by Stockfish, depth 44. Note how Black comes out with an extra pawn! } 11... Bb7 { Just let b5 hang. } { [%csl Gg2][%cal Gb7g2] } 12. Nf3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Rad8! $146 (13... a6 { Also good, but not as strong as Rad8. } { Kun, Gabor - Chernyshov, Konstantin, 0-1, Budapest FS05 GM, 2005, https://lichess.org/d97KGFfd }) 14. O-O (14. Nxb5? Nh5 { [%cal Gg7d4] } 15. Be3 Nc5 16. d5 Rfe8 { [%cal Gh5f4,Ge7h4] }) 14... a6 15. Re1 Rfe8 16. Bg5 Nf8 17. d5 h6 18. Bh4 g5 19. Bg3 Qd7 20. Bf1 Nxd5 { Get the pawn back. } 21. Rxe8 Qxe8 22. Nxd5 Qe6 23. a4 Rxd5 24. Qc2 Qf6 25. axb5 axb5 26. Ra5 Qxf3 { Extra pawn! } 27. Be2 Qf6 28. Rxb5 Rxb5 29. Bxb5 Qxb2 30. Qxb2 Bxb2 $10 { Black is one pawn up, but this should be a draw. }) 11... Nb6! $146 { Novelty. A line suggested by Stockfish, depth 44 } (11... Nd5 $146 { Novelty. The following line is a suggestion by Houdini: } 12. Nf3 Re8 13. Bg5 Qb4+ 14. Kf1 Qxb2 15. Bd3 N7b6 16. Rb1 Qxa2 17. Ra1 Qb2 18. Rb1 $10 { Draw by repetition. }) (11... Bb7 { Is the only move you'll find in the database. Playable, but the knight move lines are better. }) 12. Nf3 Re8 { Prevents castling. } { [%cal Ge7e2] } 13. Nc3 { Add protection to the bishop. } { [%cal Rc3e2] } 13... Nbd5 { Attack the defender immediately. } 14. Ne5 { Blocks the queen's view. } { [%cal Ge7e2] } 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd5 { And here comes the idea to life: d5 is used as a pivot point for attacking pieces. White should give up c3 and just castle. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Gd5c3] } 16. O-O (16. Bf3? Ba6! 17. Bxd5 Bxe5 18. Be3 Bf4 19. c4 Bxe3 20. O-O $17) 16... Nxc3 { Black gets one pawn back. } { [%cal Gc3e2,Gc3d1] } 17. Qd2 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 Qe6 { Prepare Ba6. } { [%csl Ga6][%cal Ge6a6] } 19. Rd1 Ba6 20. Qf3 Bc4 { [%cal Gc4a2,Ge6c4] } 21. Bf4 Bd5 22. Qg4 Qxg4 23. Nxg4 Re2 { [%cal Ge2a2,Gd5a2] } 24. Ne3 Bxa2 { And here is the second pawn. } 25. Kf1 Rb2 26. d5 Bb3 27. Rd3 a5 28. d6 Be6 29. d7 Rd8 30. Rxa5 Rb1+ 31. Rd1 Rxd1+ 32. Nxd1 f6 33. f3 Rxd7 $10 { Completely equal. }) 10... a6 11. Bd3 b5 12. O-O Bb7 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gh7h6,Ra2a3,Rf8e8,Bc1f4,Bd7b6] } 13. Bg5 { is annoying. █ █ █ █ █ }) 9. Qe2+ Qe7 10. Bf4 Qxe2+ 11. Ngxe2 { and now Black has to play the ugly move } (11. Bxe2 { The idea here is to bring the knight from g1 to f3 from where it controls more squares in Black's side. } { [%cal Gg1f3,Bf3g5,Bf3e5] } 11... O-O! { Giving up the d-pawn in favor of better development. } (11... Ke7 { is the main move, similar to the 11.Ngxe2 line. }) 12. Bxd6?! Re8 { Pins the bishop. } { [%cal Ge8e1] } 13. Nf3 Ne4 { Attack White's dark-squared bishop on d6. } { [%cal Ge4d6] } 14. Bf4 { The engine suggests the counter-intuitive move Nxc3 here. Nb6 is also playable. Both moves are novelties. Cherenkov played the passive Nf8 and lost his game.
The side with the IQP is responsible for the attack. As long as the opponent doesn't allow that they are fine. Black has to play aggressively. } { [%csl Bd4] } (14. Nxe4?! Rxe4 { White would love to castle here. But that's not possible. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Ge4d4] } 15. Kf1 { White's bishop wants to go to c4 now. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Re2c4] } 15... Nb6 $10 { prevents that. Maybe it's better to let White keep the extra pawn and have bit more tension in the position. } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Gb6c4] } (15... Bxd4 { is of course playable. The downside is that White now has the bishop pair in an otherwise completely equal position. } 16. Nxd4 Rxd4 $10 { [%cal Gd4d6] })) 14... Nb6! $146 (14... Nxc3 $146 15. bxc3 Nb6 { [%cal Gc8f5,Ga8c8] } 16. Kd2 { This is the main difference to the 14…Nb6 line: The king can step out of the pin and protect the c-pawn. } 16... Nd5 { [%cal Gd5f4,Gd5c3] } 17. Bb5 { [%cal Rb5e8] } 17... Re7 18. Bg5 Rc7 $10 { This is equal. Black can now push the a- and b-pawn with tempo, keep pressure on White's c-pawn, and develop the light-squared bishop to f5. } { [%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gc8f5] }) (14... Nf8?! { Frolyanov, D. - Cherenkov, And, 1-0, RUS Rapid GP Serpukhov, 2018, https://lichess.org/E08qRnNg }) 15. Be3 { protects the d-pawn and resolves he pressure of the rook on e8. It's a bit passive, though. } { [%csl Be8][%cal Ge8e1] } 15... Nxc3 { is still a good move. } 16. bxc3 Nd5 { pushing the bishop even futher back. } { [%cal Gd5c3] } 17. Bd2 Bf5 { Now White's king has to step out of the pin and lose castling rights. } { [%cal Gf5d3,Bd3e2] } 18. Kf1 Rac8 $10 { This is equal despite White's extra pawn. Black's pieces are well coordinated, and attacking, while White is just defending, and the rook on h1 out of play. } { [%cal Gd5c3,Gc8c3] }) 11... Ke7 12. O-O Nb6 13. Rfe1 Be6 14. Bd3 (14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6+ (15. Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 Rhd8 $10 { This is technically equal, but certainly easier to play for White. }) 15... Bxf6 16. Bd3 (16. d5?! { overly ambitious } 16... Bd7 17. Ng3+?! Kd8 { Zarychta, Krzysztof - Kaszowski, Dariusz, 0-1, POL-ch sf, 2002, https://lichess.org/qJzL58se }) 16... Rhe8 $10 { Completely equal, Black has probably even a slight edge here due to the bishop pair. The king should move to f8 and maybe to g7 later where it is safe. The second rook should control the open c-file.
White should try Nf4, Ne4, and a4 to gain some space. } { [%cal Ge7f8,Gf8g7,Ga8c8,Re2f4,Ra2a4,Gg6g5,Rc3e4] }) 14... Rhd8 { Relieve the king from protecting d6. } 15. Bg3 Kf8 $10 { Equal position. It will be important for both sides to protect their IQPs and the square in front of them. This is currently easier for Black, because their pawn isn't so advanced.
