 Novelty, and my recommendation for White. } (10. Qxd5 exd5 $10 { has been played in Roepke - Zaerban, 1995, which ended in a draw. I think Black's position is fine here. }) 10... Qf5 11. Qa3 { is annoying here, because it doesn't let Black castle. } 11... Nc6 12. O-O Qa5 13. b3 Bd7 $13 { This is an unclear position. Black has to fight a little bit for a castling opportunity, but the pawn structure is better than in the 8…Nc6 line, and the position is new to both sides. }) (7... Nxc3?! { This gives White a strong initiative. } 8. Bc4! { Zwischenzug! Black cannot allow Bxf7 } 8... Nd5 { The knight is gone anyway, so we don't should allow White to resolve the IQP. } (8... e6?! { isn't much better, because now the bishop will look at the small pawn chain once it landed on g7. } { [%cal Gg7c3] } 9. bxc3 Bg7 { [%csl Bd4,Bc3] } 10. Ba3 { Prevents castling for now. } { [%cal Ra3f8] } 10... Nc6 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc6e7] } 11. Nf3 { [%cal Gg7f8] } 11... Ne7 12. O-O O-O $14 { White is a bit better here: no real weaknesses, more space, and their pieces are placed better. Black's dark-squared bishop looks at the pawn chain, the light-squared bishop is bound to defend b7, and so it keeps the rook on a8 locked in. } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gg7d4,Gc8b7] }) 9. Bxd5 e6 10. Bxb7 Bxb7 11. Qxb7 Nd7 $14 { Black is just a pawn down here. No compensation. }) 8. Bb5+ { prevents both. Most people play Bd7 here, in some games a knight was put on d7. But Nc6 is not as bad as it looks. Yes, it runs into d5, but there is counterplay. } 8... Nc6! $146 { Novelty. And my recommendation, because the follow-up is just beautiful. } (8... Bd7?! { Main move, with the idea to trade the light-squared bishops off. } 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Ne5 { And this move kind of refutes the line: White keeps their light-squared bishop, Black loses theirs. } 10... O-O 11. Nxd7 N8xd7 12. O-O Nf6 13. Rd1 { The main move for Black here is Nfd5, blockading the d-pawn and opening the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. But that allows White to develop their dark-squared bishop to g5 where it pins the e-pawn against the queen. That's why I recommend the cute little move e6 here. } { [%cal Gf6d5] } 13... e6! $146 { A novelty, but it transposes to a known position (4 games in the database). } 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bh4 $10 { Yu, Jennifer - Foisor, S., 1-0, ch-USA w 2018, https://lichess.org/XcF15lbO } { Equal position, but a little bit easier to play for White, because their pieces are more mobile. }) 9. d5 a6! 10. Ba4 (10. dxc6?! { enters a line of forced moves: } 10... axb5 11. cxb7 Bxb7 { [%cal Gb7g2] } 12. Qxb5+ Qd7 13. Qxd7+ Nxd7 14. Nf3 Bg7 15. O-O O-O $13 { The engine says this is completely equal. Yes, White has two connected passed pawns, but Black has the bishop pair, and the field is open, so they are very strong. }) (10. Bxc6+?! bxc6 { White does get rid of the IQP, although the c-pawn isn't really connected, but Black gets the initiative now. } 11. dxc6 Be6 12. Qb4 Bg7 13. Nf3 Rc8 { and there is no way that White can keep this pawn. } 14. O-O Rxc6 $10 { This is good for Black: bishop pair, open field to operate on, and equal material. }) 10... Nxa4 11. Qxa4 b5! 12. Nxb5 axb5! 13. Qxa8 Nd4 { Threatening to fork king and rook on c2. } { [%cal Gd4c2] } 14. Kf1 Bg7 15. Be3 O-O 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 { [%cal Gd4b2] } 17. Nf3 (17. Rb1? { White cannot hold this pawn. } 17... Qc7 { Qc2 would be mate in 7! } { [%cal Gc7c2] } 18. Qc6 Qa7 $17 { Black is much better here. }) 17... Bxb2 18. Rd1 b4 { Opens up the diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop and gives the dark-squared bishop an achor.. } { [%cal Ba6f1,Gf8a8,Gc8a6,Gd8b6] } 19. Kg1 Bc3 $15 { Black is better here. The compensation for the exchange sacrifice is a strong initiative, and White's pieces are all misplaced and poorly coordinated. }) 6... Bg7 { Now it's a gambit anyway, even if it isn't called one. d5 will fall, and the question is if Black will get it back or enough compensation. The difference to the Fianchetto gambit is that White hasn't taken d5 yet and played Qb3 instead. } (6... e6 { █ █ █ █ █ }) 7. cxd5 O-O 8. Be2 { [%cal Re2f3,Rf3d5] } (8. Nge2 { The second most common move. The idea here is to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 8... Na6 (8... e6?! { is a dubious little gambit that has been tried a few times: } 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Qxb7 Nbd7 { The point is that this opens the e-file, before White can fianchetto and castle. } { [%cal Ge8e1] } 11. Nf4 { [%cal Rf4e6] } 11... Bf5 { But White hasn't committed to g3, so } { [%cal Gf8e8] } (11... Ng4 $146 { could be a try here. Novelty. } { [%cal Gg7d4] } 12. Be2 Bxd4 { Black regains at least one pawn. } { [%cal Gg4f2,Gd4f2] } 13. O-O Qh4 { [%cal Gg4h2,Gh4h2] } 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 $14 { This looks dangerous, but Black doesn't really have anything here. White is better. Not a whole pawn value better, but still … better. } { [%csl Bg2][%cal Bb7g2] }) 12. Be2 { is still possible, and } 12... Re8 { comes too late. } 13. O-O $14 { White is just a pawn up here. }) (8... Nbd7 9. Nf4 (9. g3 Nb6 10. Bg2 Bf5! { The threat is Bd3. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gf5d3,Bd3c4,Bc4b3,Bd3e2] } 11. O-O (11. Nf4 { prevents that. } 11... Rc8 12. h3 Qd7 13. g4 g5 14. gxf5 gxf4 15. Bxf4 Qxf5 16. Bg3 Nh5 17. Be4 Qg5 18. Bh2 { [%cal Rh1g1,Rg1g8] } 18... Kh8 $10 { White is a pawn up, but the pawn islands are hard to defend, and Black has multiple threats. This technically equal, but surely easier to play for Black } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gb6c4,Bc4d2,Bg5d2] }) 11... Bd3 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gd3c4] } 12. d6 { [%cal Rg2b7] } 12... Qxd6 13. Bxb7 Bc4 14. Qc2 Rad8 15. b3 Bd5 { [%cal Gd5b7] } 16. Bxd5 Nbxd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Rd1 Rd7 19. Bg5 Qe6 20. Rac1 Qg4 21. Qd2 e6 $10 { Equal position, but not as bad for White as the Nf4 line, so that's my recommendation for White. }) 9... Qb6 { Probably Black's best option. The other lines don't lead to good positions. } { [%cal Gb6d4,Gb6b3] } (9... Ne8 { attacks d4 } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7d4] } 10. Be3 { protects it. } 10... Nd6 { The idea is Nf5 with a fork. } { [%cal Gd6f5,Bf5e3,Bf5d4] } 11. Bd3 { prevents the fork and develops the next piece. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Rd3f5,Gd6f5] } (11. Be2 { Yakovich, Yuri - Miroshnichenko, Evgenij, 1/2-1/2, Noyabrsk Fakel Jamala, 2003, https://lichess.org/l3Tl2I3J }) 11... Nb6 { opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and blockades the queen's view on b7. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8f5,Rb3b7] } 12. O-O Bf5 { White did allow that, because the bishop on f5 doesn't threaten d4. } 13. Be2 Rc8 $10 { This is equal. } { Zvjaginsev, Vadim - Deviatkin, Andrei, 1/2-1/2, Moscow-ch blitz, 2004, https://lichess.org/lIovtmms }) (9... Nb6 10. Be2 { Bf5 and Bg4 are the main moves here, but the engine suggests the surprising moves g5 and a5! Let's take a look at all of them. } 10... Bf5 (10... Bg4 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 { And now d4 is hanging. So White's best try is to push the knight back to f6. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7d4] } 12. h3 Nf6 (12... Nh6?! { is begging for an attack. } { [%cal Rc1h6] } 13. g4! Bxd4 14. Nh5! { [%cal Rc1h6] } 14... Nf5 15. gxf5 gxh5 16. Bh6 $14 Qd6 (16... Re8?!) 17. Bxf8 $16 { Anikaev, Yuri N - Seoev, Robert, 1-0, URS-ch otbor, 1979, https://lichess.org/zxU5V1rE } 17... Kxf8) 13. a4 a5 14. O-O $14 { Still a bit better for White, but playable for both sides. }) (10... a5 { White has to stop the a-pawn now. } { [%csl Ba4][%cal Ga5a4,Bb6a4,Ba8a4] } 11. a4 Bf5 { Finally develop the light-squared bishop. } 12. O-O Qd6 { Just connect the rooks. } 13. Nb5 Qd8 (13... Qd7 14. d6! { White has to give back the pawn now, but on d6 Black gets an IQP too. } 14... exd6 15. Be3 (15. Nc3?! { [%cal Rb3b6] } 15... Qd8 { [%cal Gd8b6] } 16. Bf3 { Krush, Irina - Foisor, Sabina Francesca, 1-0, USA-ch (Women), 2012, https://lichess.org/uvpbjbdH } { [%cal Rf3b7] }) 15... d5 $14 { Overall, this is still slightly better for White. The knight and the pawn on the b-file are a bit weak. }) 14. Nc3 { This is an invitation to go for a draw by repetition. } { [%cal Gd8d6,Rc3b5] } (14. Bf3 { Might be a way to avoid the draw. █████ CONTINUE })) (10... g5 $146 { Novelty. This does remove a defender from d5. Nh5 is the only way to keep d5 } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Rf4d5] } 11. Nh5 { [%cal Rh5g7] } 11... Nxh5 12. Bxh5 { [%cal Rc1g5] } 12... e6?! { defends d5 too. I just don't like the possible contuniations in this line. } { [%cal Gd8g5] } (12... h6 13. O-O Bf5 14. Re1 Qd7 $10 { This is … okay. Black will get the pawn eventually per Rad8. e6 might be a move soon. } { [%cal Ga8d8,Ge7e6,Bf5e6,Be6b3] }) 13. O-O { And now Black can decide either to fix the center with exd5 or to go into lots of trades with Nxd5. But none of these moves lead to a good position. } (13. dxe6? { is not really an option for White }) 13... exd5?! { d4 is hanging, so } { [%cal Gg7d4] } (13... Nxd5?! { Also not a so nice: } 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Bxg5 Bxd4 $14 { Material is equal, but Black's damaged pawn structure is hard to defend. } { [%cal Gd4b2,Rh5f3,Bf3d5] }) 14. Ne2 { And here Black can grab some space with f5, develop the light-squared bishop to f5, or just relieve the queen with h6. } 14... f5 { the only option that doesn't give White f4. } { [%csl Gg4,Rf4][%cal Rf2f4,Gg5g4] } (14... Bf5 { with the idea to trade bishops on g6. But White can now grab the initiative with } { [%cal Gf5g6] } 15. Qg3! { Now Black has to defend g5. } { [%cal Rc1g5,Rg3g5] } 15... h6 16. f4! { This is really uncomfortable. } 16... g4 { The only thing Black can hope for here is to give the pawn on their conditions. } (16... f6?! { opens the diagonal for White's light-squared bishop, and the dark-squared will follow soon: } { [%cal Rh5e8] } 17. b3! { [%cal Rc1a3,Ra3f8] } 17... Nc8 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc8e7] } 18. Ba3 { now the rook can't go anywhere, and the knight gets the sad job of defending it. } 18... Ne7 $16 { White is much better here. }) 17. Bxg4 Qd7 18. Bxf5 Qxf5 $14 { Not a nice position for Black: one pawn down, a miserable structure and merely defending everything with the queen. }) (14... h6 { is probably too passive, because it gives White } 15. f4! { and Black has nothing better than } 15... f5 $14 { This is slightly better for White: Black's king is less safe, and the IQP is easier for White, because Black's is "pinned" and can't be used as an anchor for other pieces. } { [%cal Rb3g8] }) 15. a4 { [%cal Ra4a5] } 15... f4 16. h4 h6 17. hxg5 hxg5 18. Re1 Bf5 (18... a5) 19. a5 Nc4 20. Qxb7 Be4 $14 { This is equal … says the engine. I'm not convinced. This is very sharp, Black is one pawn down (temporarily at least), and their king is an open target. In practical play White is probably better, because the position is easier to play. } { [%cal Re2c3,Gc4a5,Gd8a5] }) 11. O-O g5 12. Nd3 { Moving the knight to c5 is a good plan, and there's nothing Black can do to prevent that. } { [%cal Rd3c5] } (12. Nh5 Nxh5 13. Bxh5 h6 14. Re1 Qd7 { Prepares Rad8 and covers b7. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Ga8d8,Gd7b7] } 15. h3 { Prepares Bf3 which could be attacked per g4 otherwise. } { [%cal Rh5f3] } 15... Rad8 16. Bf3 { and now finally } 16... e6 { The break in the center. White can obviously not take. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf5e6,Be6b3,Gg7d4,Gd7d4] } 17. Qb4 Nxd5 { [%cal Gd5b4] } 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Re7! Qc8 20. Rxb7 Bxd4 21. Be3 Bxe3 22. fxe3 a5 $10 { This position is fairly equal, maybe with a slight edge for White } { [%cal Gc8b7,Rb4b7,Gf8e8,Ge8e3] }) 12... h6 13. Nc5 { [%cal Rc5b7] } 13... Nbxd5! $146 { Novelty! And an active move. } (13... Rb8?! { Too passive. } 14. h4 { Khismatullin, Denis - Mustakaev, Artur, 1-0, Kazan Region-ch 6th, 2008, https://lichess.org/oCFen5UP }) 14. Nxb7 { [%cal Rb7d8] } 14... Nxc3! { just trade off the "problem knight" that Black has to defend with the queen otherwise. } (14... Qd7 { Black's queen has to protect the knight on d5. } { [%cal Rc3d5,Rb3d5,Gf6d5,Bd7d5] } 15. Nc5 { Again with tempo on the queen. } { [%cal Rc5d7] } 15... Qd6 16. Bf3 { [%cal Rf3a8] } 16... e6 { White is a pawn up here and happy to trade some pieces off. } 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5 exd5 $14 { The question is: Is the bishop pair enough compensation for the pawn? Probably not. I think White has a good edge here. }) 15. bxc3 { forced move. } (15. Nxd8? { very bad! } 15... Nxe2+ 16. Kh1 Nxd4 17. Qb7 Rfxd8 $17 { Black got three minor pieces for the queen, and they are well coordinated. } { [%cal Gf5e4,Be4b7,Be4g2] }) (15. Qxc3?! { is not good: } 15... Qd5! { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd5b7,Gd5d4] } 16. Nc5 Ne4 { [%cal Ge4c3,Ge4c5,Gg7d4] } 17. Qf3 Bxd4 $15 { This is a nice, active position for Black. }) 15... Qc7 { [%cal Gc7b7,Gc7c3] } 16. Nc5 e5! { That pawn is bound to the knight. } { [%cal Bd4c5,Gc7c5] } (16... Ne4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Ba3 { [%cal Ra3e7] } 18... Rab8 19. Qc4 Qxc4 20. Bxc4 Rfc8 21. Bc5 e6 $14 { White is better for the passed pawn that isn't so easy to remove. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Rc5a7,Ra1e1] }) 17. Be3 Rac8 { aiming at c3 } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc7c3] } 18. Rac1 $14 { I think this is easier to play for White. }) 10. Be3 Qxb3 11. axb3 Nb6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gb6d5,Rc3d5,Rf4d5,Gf8d8] } 12. Bd3! $146 { Novelty. Makes Bf5 very unattractive for Black. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Gc8f5,Rd3f5] } 12... Rd8 13. Ra5 g5 { Remove one defender for d5. } { [%cal Rf4d5] } 14. Nfe2 Nbxd5 { and now Black is getting the pawn back … temporarily. } 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxg5 b6 $10 { This is very equal. White is still a pawn up, but that's a doubled pawn on the b-file and not worth that much. } { [%csl Bb3,Bb2] }) 9. g3 Qb6 { █████ CONTINUE } (9... b5 { █████ CONTINUE } 10. Bg2 (10. Nxb5) 10... b4)) 8... Nbd7 { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5] } 9. Bf3 { [%cal Rf3d5] } 9... Nb6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gb6d5,Gd8d5,Rf3d5,Rc3d5,Rb3d5] } 10. Nge2 { [%cal Re2f4,Rf4d5] } 10... Bg4 { Remove the first defender. } 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 { But now also Black is "down" one defender for d5. Temporarily. On the other hand, it attacks White's second IQP now. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Re2d4] }) (5... Nc6 { Panov Attack/Modern Defense. } 6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 e6 { Carlsbad Line } (6... Qa5 { Czerniak Line }) (6... Qb6 { Reifir-Spielmann Line }) (6... Be6) (6... dxc4)) 6... Bg4 { Mieses Line } 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6 10. Qxb7 Nxd4 11. Bb5+ Nxb5 12. Qc6+ { is as good as the immediate Qxb5. } (12. Qxb5+ Qd7 13. Qxd7+ (13. Nxd5 { Sneaky trap, if Black dares to take White's queen first. } 13... exd5 (13... Qxb5?? 14. Nc7+ Kd7 15. Nxb5 $18) 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7) 13... Kxd7 14. Nxd5 exd5 { █ █ █ █ █ }) 12... Ke7 13. Qxb5 Qd7 14. Nxd5+ Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5) (5... Bg4? { Serious mistake } 6. Qb3! { [%cal Rc4d5,Rb3b7] } 6... Qb6 7. cxd5) (5... Bf5 { Same problem as in the Bg4 line. } 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. cxd5 Qxb3 8. axb3) 6. Nf3 (6. cxd5) (6. c5) 6... Bb4 { This is now a transposition to the Nimzo-Indian defense. The idea behind this move is preventing the later Re1! White will now bring the dark-squared bishop to d2 in order to remove this pin. But that move breaks the connection between the queen and the d-pawn. } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Rh1e1,Rd1d4,Bc1d2] } (6... Be7 { The old main line. } 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1) 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bd2 { Now the queen doesn't watch d4 anymore. } { [%cal Rd1d4] } (8. Qc2 Nc6 9. Bc4 Qc7 10. Bd3 Bd6 11. Nxd5 exd5 $10) 8... Nc6 9. Bd3 Be7 (9... O-O { The move order isn't so important here. } 10. O-O Be7) 10. O-O O-O { White has now to deal with the threat of Ndb4. Or play Re1 anyway, which leads to interesting complications. } { [%cal Gd5b4,Bd8d4,Bc6d4] } 11. Qc2 (11. Nxd5) (11. a3 { This is the main move; it watches b4. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ra3b4] } 11... Bf6 { Black attacks d4 once more. } 12. Qc2 { [%cal Rd3h7] } 12... g6 { Allows Bh6 which is a bit uncomfortable for Black. } (12... h6 { Now the h-pawn is safe, and d4 is attacked twice and defended just once, so } { [%cal Gf6d4,Gc6d4,Rf3d4] } 13. Be3 { adds the missing protection. } 13... Nce7 14. Ne4 { [%csl Rc5][%cal Re4f6,Re4c5] } 14... b6 { is a prophylactic move: it prevents Nc5, and it allows Black later to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 16. Ne5 (16. Rac1 Bb7 17. Ne5 { Pommrich, Rainer - Larsen, Søren M, 1/2-1/2, CT17/pr27, 2009, https://lichess.org/UvTtYpWs }) 16... Bb7 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. Qa4 { [%cal Ra4a7] } 18... Rxc1 (18... Qd5 { A very simple threat. } { [%cal Gd5g2] } 19. f3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6a7] } 20. Nxc6 (20. Bc4) 20... Bxc6 { [%cal Gc6a4] } 21. Qb4 (21. Qxa7? { is not that useful } 21... Qb3! { forks pawn and bishop. } { [%cal Gb3b2,Gb3d3] } 22. Qa6 { has to protect the bishop } { [%cal Ga6d3] } 22... Nd5 { protects b6 and attacks the bishop on e3. } { [%cal Gd5b6,Gd5e3] } 23. Bf2 Qxb2 $17 { Black is better here. Bb7 is a nice idea, Nf4 and Ra8 are also good moves. White is in a very difficult position now. } { [%cal Gc6b7,Gd5f4,Bf4d3,Gc8a8,Ba8a3,Rc1b1,Bb2d2] }) 21... Qd7 22. Ba6 Rcd8 $10 { This is at least equal if not better for Black. The pawn structure is better and easier to hold, Nd5 will be very annoying for White. } { [%cal Gf6d5] }) 19. Rxc1 a5 20. Qb5 { [%csl Bd7][%cal Rb5d7,Re5d7,Gf6d7] } 20... Nc8 $10 { [%cal Gc8d6,Gd6b5] }) 13. Bh6 { Black can now either Bg7, exchanging the dark-squared bishops, or Re8, weakening f7. } 13... Re8 14. Rad1 { [%cal Rc3e4,Be4f6] } 14... Nxc3 { Make sure this knight can't go to e4 anymore. } 15. bxc3 { The question for Black is now how to develop the light-squared bishop: to d7 or b7? d7 is faster, but it does block the queen's view at d5. } { [%cal Gc8d7,Gc8b7,Gd8d5] } 15... b6 (15... Bd7) 16. Bb5 Bb7 17. Ne5 { [%cal Re5c6,Rb5c6] } (17. c4 { Prevents Qd5. } 17... a6 18. Ba4 { Zhang, Zhong - Jobava, Baadur, 1/2-1/2, Taiyuan schev, 2006, https://lichess.org/1895EADz }) 17... Rc8) (11. Re1 { White can also ignore this threat and give d4 with good compensation: } { [%csl Bd4] } 11... Ndb4 12. Bf4 { If Black goes for the Bf6 line, they will win a pawn temporarily. But White will get it back, as we can see. So it might be easier to take the bishop and let White sit on their IQP with less material. } 12... Nxd3 (12... Bf6 13. Be4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Nb5 { [%cal Rb5d4,Rd1d4] } 15... e5 16. Nxd4 exf4 17. Qd2 $10 { Still equal. And now Nc6 is the best continuation. Note that the knight on d4 is pinned. } { [%cal Gd8d2] } 17... Nc6 (17... Nd5 18. b3 $146 { Prophylactic move, anticipating Qb6. Novelty. } (18. Rad1 Nf6 19. Qxf4 Qb6 20. b3 { Frolyanov, Dmitry - Drozdovskij, Yuri, 1/2-1/2, RUS-chT2 17th, 2010, https://lichess.org/Z5TQr32t }) 18... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 19. Qxf4 Nxe4 20. Qxe4 h6 { Make some luft. And both sides are fine. }) 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Qxf4 Qb6 20. b3 c5 21. Nf5 (21. Nf3?! h6 22. Rac1 Be6 $10) 21... Bxf5 22. Qxf5 g6 23. Qe5 Rfd8 { Danin, Alexandre - Sumets, Andrey, 1/2-1/2, Bergamo op 11th, 2012, https://lichess.org/Ga48lq7p } { Equal, but not drawish. White's idea is probably h4 and h5 or pressure on Black's weak c-pawn. Black should try to get one or even two rooks to the 2nd rank and attack f2. } { [%csl Bf2,Bc5][%cal Rh2h4,Ra1c1,Rc1c5,Re5c5,Gd8d2,Gd2f2,Gb6f2] }) 13. Qxd3 Nb4 14. Qe4 Re8 { and not the adventurous f5! } (14... f5?! { Weakens e6 } { [%csl Be6] } 15. Qe2 { There are only three games in the database with this position, and they all continue with the rather cocky g5. Stockfish wants the solid Nd5. } 15... g5 16. Bc1 Bf6 17. Rd1 { White really wants to play h4 here and open up Black's king even more! The only way to prevent that is by pressing even harder. This is dangerous. } { [%cal Rh2h4] } 17... Nd5 { White will gladly take and give Black an IQP too! } (17... g4?! 18. Ne5! { Bh6 is White's next idea. } { [%cal Rc1h6] } 18... b6! { [%cal Gc8a6] } 19. Bh6 (19. Qc4 a5 { Baghdasaryan, Vahe - Harutjunyan, Gevorg, 1-0, Yerevan Margaryan Memorial, 2012, https://lichess.org/euGosvwg }) 19... Ba6 { [%cal Ga6e2] } 20. Qd2 Bxe5 21. Bxf8 Bxh2+ 22. Kxh2 Qh4+ 23. Kg1 Rxf8 24. Qe3 f4 $16 { White is just better here. }) 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. h4 { Yilmaz, Mustafa Enes - Kovchan, Alexander, 1/2-1/2, Kharkov Rector Cup, 2011, https://lichess.org/kCgprj2h }) 15. Rac1 Bd7 16. Ne5 { Black has choice here: give b7 and trade off material into a drawish position (Bf6 line) or give the light-squared bishop on c6? Nc6 isn't that good. } 16... Bc6 { I recommend this line. } (16... Bf6 $146 { Novelty! } 17. Qxb7 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Nd3 19. Red1 { [%cal Rd1d7,Rb7d7] } 19... Rb8 20. Qxa7 Nxf4 21. Qxd7 Qxd7 22. Rxd7 Rxb2 23. Ra1) (16... Nc6?! { is dubious. } { [%cal Gc6e5] } 17. Red1! $146 { Novelty! } (17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. d5 exd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Nxd5 Bf8 { Kopinits, Anna Christina - Makka, Ioulia, 1/2-1/2, Baska (Women), 2009, https://lichess.org/H9fTa8Qu }) 17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 { And White has no IQP anymore. } 18... Qc8 $14 { Step out of the pin. White is a bit better here: more space, control over the open files, and a centralized queen. }) 17. Nxc6 Nxc6 18. Rcd1 Bf6 $146 { Novelty! } 19. Nb5 Re7 $10 { The position is still equal, but not drawish! } { [%cal Ge7d7,Gd8b6,Rb5d6,Rf4e5] }) 11... Nf6 (11... Ndb4 12. Bxh7+ Kh8 13. Qb1 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4) 12. Ne4 h6 13. Rad1 Bd7 *


