[UTCTime "17:50:01"]

{ This variation made its debut with the game [Tarrasch - Teichmann]. }
1. e4 c6 2. c4 { The basic position for the Accelerated Panov Attack. Can also arise from the English Opening with 1.c4 c6 2. e4.
The name is a bit misleading. Both sides have other options than in the ➡ Exchange/Panov Attack. } 2... d5 { Main line. This is a double purpose move: 1. It opens the line for the ls-bishop. 2. It prevents a Maróczy bind on White's side. } (2... e5 { Open Variation. This is my recommendation for Black. See ➡ Accelerated Panov/Open Variation. }) (2... e6 { NN. Played by Shabalov, Petrosian and others. Not recommended. } 3. d4 d5 4. Nc3 { Transposes to the Semi-Slav/Marshall Gambit } (4. exd5 cxd5 5. Nc3 { Transposes to the ➡ Exchange/Panov Attack }) (4. e5 c5 { Transposes to the ➡ Advance Variation/Botvinnik-Carls Defense })) (2... g6?! { I'm really not sure about this move. The justification might be that White can't protect d4 with the c-pawn anymore. But … if you want to play a Modern Defense, do it right away with 2.g6. } { [%cal Gg7d4] } 3. d4 { White has a lot of space here. } 3... Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 { Prevents e5 by White. } (4... d5 5. e5 { And now Black has to play f6 eventually in order to break this up. }) 5. Be3 Nf6) 3. exd5 (3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Qb3 { Van Weersel Attack. Played only *once* by Arlette van Weersel in 2009, and that game was a draw. http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1173339 } 4... dxe4 { The idea is to get the light-squared bishop out and attack f7. But Black can defend that easily. } 5. Bc4 e6) (3. e5 { ➡ Toikkanen Gambit }) 3... cxd5 4. cxd5 (4. d4 { transposes to the ➡ Panov Attack }) 4... Nf6 { Modern Variation } (4... Qxd5 { Pseudo-Scandinavian? Not the best option. White can now develop with tempo. } 5. Nc3 { This is similar to the regular Scandinavian, except that White's d-pawn is harder to protect. } { [%cal Rc3d5] } 5... Qd6 (5... Qd8 6. d4 e6 7. Nf3 Nf6 8. Bd3 Be7 9. O-O O-O) 6. d4 Nf6 7. Nf3 e6 8. Bd3 Be7 9. O-O O-O) 5. Bb5+ { The main move here is Nbd7, but my recommendation is Bd7 } (5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bb5 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. d4 O-O 10. Re1 Bd7 11. Bd3 Rc8 $10) 5... Bd7 (5... Nbd7 6. Nc3 a6 7. Qa4 Rb8 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qxd7+ Bxd7 10. Nge2 Rd8 11. d4 Bf5 { [%cal Gd8d5,Gf6d5] } 12. Nf4 (12. f3 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Rxd5 14. Be3 e6 15. Rc1 Rd7 16. h4 Be7 $10) (12. Be3 b5 $10) 12... g5 13. Nfe2 Rg8 14. Be3 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Rxd5 16. Rc1 Ra5 17. a3 Rg6 $10) 6. Bc4 b5! 7. Bb3 a5 { Is rare, but I think it's better than the more common Bg4 here. } (7... Bg4 8. Nf3 a5 $14) 8. a3 Na6 9. d4 Nc7 { White cannot hold the d5-pawn anyway and should develop instead. } 10. Nf3 $146 { This is the best move, and yet, it's a novelty! } (10. Qf3 { Short tried to protect the pawn, and now Bg4 was very strong: } 10... Bg4 11. Qg3 Ncxd5 12. Nf3 e6 13. O-O { Short, Nigel D - Karpov, Anatoly, 1-0, SWIFT-Chess World Championship, 1987, https://lichess.org/6Y9xasT7 } { Karrpov blundered the game away later, but in this position here he had equalized already. }) 10... Ncxd5 { Black is fine here. e6 followed by Bd6 are the next moves if White doesn't do anything unusual. White has an IQP, and Black should not change that. Trading material (except on c3 of course) is therefore in favor of Black, because the IQP is a liability in the endgame. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6,Ge8g8] } *


[Event "Toikkanen Gambit"]
[Date "2019.04.27"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B10"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Toikkanen Gambit"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "– Toikkanen Gambit"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/yjUA0LpN"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.27"]
[UTCTime "20:08:55"]

{ The Toikkanen Gambit is a rare line in the Caro-Kann/Accelerated Panov Attack. It is not really a gambit. But it's very beautiful. You'll get a perfect harmony between tactical and positional challenges for both sides in almost all variations. }
1. e4 (1. c4 { Different move order, same result. } 1... c6 2. e4 d5 3. e5) 1... c6 2. c4 d5 3. e5 { This is already the Toikkanen Gambit. There are different responses that lead to very different games. dxc4 is the best. } 3... dxc4 { This is the best response … and one of the rarest. } (3... d4?! { Pawns are usually on light squares in the Caro-Kann. d4 changes that a bit, and we get a very unique structure. } 4. f4 { The best response. It grabs some space and saves the e-pawn for a while.
Ivanisevic, I. - Van Foreest, Jorden, ½-½, Sunway Sitges Open 2016, https://lichess.org/ffrUt8fC } (4. Bd3 { Belous, Vladimir - Dubov, Daniil, 0-1, World Youth Stars 7th, 2009, https://lichess.org/zabIfcM0 }) (4. Nf3 Bg4)) (3... e6 { Third best move. Stops the e-pawn from advancing to e6 where it can do much damage. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. d4 c5) (3... Be6 { Short, N. - Sundararajan, K., ½-½, 19th Kolkata GM Open 2014, https://lichess.org/QWhv2MMh }) (3... Bf5 { Most common response, albeit not the best one. But you develop your light-squared bishop in the Caro-Kann, right? } 4. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7,Gb3d5] } (4. d4 { Transposition to Advance variation. }) 4... dxc4 (4... Qb6 5. Qxb6 axb6 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. d4 e6 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Nc3 f6 10. exf6 Nxf6) 5. Bxc4 e6 6. Qxb7 Nd7 7. d4 (7. Qxc6? Rc8 8. Qa4 { [%cal Ga4d7,Rd7e5] } 8... Qh4 { [%cal Rc8c4,Rh4c4] } 9. b3 Bc5 { [%cal Gc5f2,Gh4f2] }) 7... Be4 { [%cal Ge4g2] }) 4. Bxc4 { And this move is the reason why I don't call it a gambit. It's also the best move, according to Stockfish 8/depth 47. } (4. Nf3 { The Gambit line. } 4... Bg4 5. Bxc4 e6 6. O-O Ne7) 4... Qd4 { Attack both squares, and there is only one good move for White: } { [%cal Rd4c4,Rd4e5] } 5. Qe2 { [%cal Re2c4,Re2e5] } 5... Bg4 { Must be played immediately! } (5... b5?! { This is a serious mistake. Now White has one move to bring the light-squared bishop to a safe square. } 6. Bb3 Bg4 7. e6! { White is asking Black to take the queen. Which would be another mistake. fxe6 is the only good move here. } 7... fxe6 (7... Bxe2? { Mistake! } 8. exf7+ Kd7 9. fxg8=Q (9. Nxe2 Qg4 10. fxg8=Q Rxg8 11. Bxg8 Na6 (11... Qxg2?! 12. Be6+ { Black can't take the bishop, because of the knight fork. } { [%cal Ge2f4] } 12... Kc7 13. Rg1 Qe4 14. Bg4 e5 15. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 15... Qc4 16. b3 Qf7 $16) 12. Nbc3 b4 13. Na4 e6 { [%cal Ra8g8] } 14. Bxh7 g6 15. Ng3 Nc5 16. Nxc5+ Bxc5 17. d4!? Bxd4 18. O-O Kc7 $14) 9... Bg4! { The only move } (9... Rxg8? 10. Nxe2 Qe4 11. Bxg8 Qxg2 12. Be6+ { Black can't take. } { [%csl Bf4][%cal Re2f4,Bf4g2,Bf4e6] } 12... Kc7 13. Rg1 Qe4 $16 { White is up in material here! And Black's pieces are poorly coordinated. }) 10. Qxh8 Qe4+ 11. Kf1 Qd3+ 12. Ke1 Qe4+ { Black has to take the perpetual check here. Everything else loses the game. }) 8. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3d4] } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qe5+) 6. f3 Bf5 (6... Bh5?! { I think the bishop is slightly misplaced here.
Van Foreest, Jorden - Lei Tingjie, 0-1, 79th Tata Steel GpB, 2017, https://lichess.org/rRsYiYmE }) 7. e6! { And here things are getting ver interesting. } (7. g4 { Playable, but then there is no safe place for white's king anymore. } { [%csl Be1] } 7... Bg6 8. e6 fxe6 9. Qxe6) 7... Bxe6 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Qxe6 { [%cal Ge6c8] } (9. f4 { Is the best, according to Stockfish. } 9... Nf6 (9... Qxf4 10. Nf3 e5) 10. Nc3) 9... Na6 10. Ne2 Qh4+ 11. g3 Qf6 12. Qe3 Nh6 13. g4 Nf7 14. Nbc3 Nb4 15. Kd1 e5 16. Rf1 Be7 17. b3 O-O 18. Ba3 Na6 19. Ne4 Qe6 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 { Short, N. - Howell, D., 1/2-1/2, 5th Classic GpD 2013, https://lichess.org/XgBH8khq } *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: – Open: 2.c4 e5"]
[Date "2017.07.28"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B10"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Accelerated Panov Attack, Open Variation"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "– Open: 2.c4 e5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/GjjvWvMM"]
[UTCDate "2017.07.28"]
[UTCTime "07:18:33"]

1. e4 c6 2. c4 e5 { Open Variation. That name is somewhat ironic, because we will see that the center can get crammed up pretty soon in this line. The main line is much more "open". } 3. Nf3 { White prepares a Maróczy bind } { [%cal Rf3e5,Rd2d4] } (3. d4 Nf6 { "Best move" line. } (3... d6 { "Common move" line } 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. dxe5 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 dxe5 8. Qg3 Bf6 $14 { Illustrates how easily things can go wrong. White has established a Maróczy Bind and has the bishop pair. }) 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nxe5 (5. Bd3 Bb4+ 6. Nbd2 Nxd2 7. Bxd2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 exd4 9. Nxd4 d6 10. O-O O-O $10 { Black is a pawn up, White ahead in development. Both queens have to compensate the missing bs bishops and should stay on dark squares. Black should try to use their extra pawn for an attack in the center. }) 5... Bb4+ (5... d6 6. Nf3 d5 7. Nbd2 Bd6 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Ng5 Bb4+ (9... Bf5 10. g4?! Bb4+ 11. Bd2 { g5 is hanging now. } 11... Na6 12. Bxb4 Nxb4 13. gxf5 Qxg5 $10) (9... O-O { I think this gives White a dangerous tempo: an opportunity to solidify the center. } 10. c5 Bc7 11. Bc4 h6 12. Nxe4 Re8 13. f3 Qh4+ 14. Kf1 Bf5 $10) 10. Bd2 Na6 11. Bxb4 Nxb4 12. Nxe4 Bf5 13. a3 Bxe4 $10) 6. Nd2 Bxd2+ (6... O-O 7. Be2 Bxd2+ (7... d6) 8. Bxd2 Qb6 9. Bc1 Qb4+ 10. Kf1 d6 11. Nf3 d5 $10) 7. Bxd2 O-O 8. Be2 Qb6 9. Bc1 Qb4+ 10. Kf1 d6 11. Nf3 d5 $10) (3. Nc3 Bc5 { Makes d4 less attractive. } (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 d6 (4... Bb4 5. Nxe5 O-O 6. Nd3 Bxc3 7. dxc3 Nxe4 8. Be2 d6 $14 { [%csl Ge5,Gc5] }) 5. d4 Nbd7 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 (8. Re1 a6 $14) 8... Re8 $14) (3... d6 4. d4 Nf6 (4... exd4 5. Qxd4 Nf6 6. Be2 Be7 $14) 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 Re8 $14) 4. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] } (4. g3?! { Normunds Miezis' favorite move. }) 4... d6 5. Be2 (5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O $10 { This is fine for Black. White's Maróczy Bind can be a bit annoying, but at least is doesn't get sharp so fast. }) 5... Nf6 $10) 3... Nf6 { This is my recommendation. Counter play immediately: a great way to fight for the initiative very early. The position resembles the Petrov's Defense a bit. Now White cannot play d4, e4 needs protection first. Or take the pawn on e5. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } (3... d6 { The main move here, but … it's questionable. Now White can play d4 without having to worry about the other two advanced pawns. } 4. d4 Nd7 { Main move again, and again dubious at best. } (4... Nf6 { Suggested by SF 8. } 5. Nc3 (5. dxe5 Nxe4 6. Bd3 (6. exd6 Bxd6 { This is perfect for Black. } { [%cal Gc8g4,Gb8a6,Ge8g8] })) 5... Bg4 (5... exd4 6. Nxd4) 6. Be3 Nbd7 7. Be2 { This position can also arise from the Old Indian defense, it's not even rare there. See [Korobov - Jobava, 2013] https://lichess.org/1VjYLC0I/black#17 } 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 g6 $14 { White has established a Maróczy bind and is ahead in development. }) (4... exd4 5. Qxd4 c5) 5. Nc3 Ngf6 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O $14 { This is the line of the most common moves, and I don't like it at all. White has a strong hold in the center, and Black's bishops are just clumsy pieces. }) 4. Nc3 { Main move. Black has now a few options: d6, the main move, is rather passive and "solid". Qa5 or Bb4 are more active. } (4. Nxe5 d6 { The main move here, but Nxe4 is stronger in my opinion. } (4... Nxe4 5. Qe2 { Black cannot move the knight away, because then there is a discovered attack with White's knight in the air. } { [%cal Re2e4,Re5g6,Re2e8,Be5e8] } (5. d3? Qa5+! { [%cal Ga5e5,Ga5e1] } 6. Ke2 Qxe5 7. dxe4 Qxe4+ 8. Kd2 $17) 5... Qe7 6. Qxe4 d6 { Note that the knight is pinned, because White's queen is hanging. } 7. f4 (7. d4) 7... dxe5 8. fxe5 g6 { Black will attack the e5-pawn from the flank with the bishop. And castle after that. This is already uncomfortable for White. } 9. d4 Bf5 10. Qf3 Na6 { Make room for the rook (or even castling long) and threaten to bring the knight to c2. } { [%cal Ga8d8,Ra6b4,Bb4c2] } 11. Be2 (11. g4 Qh4+ 12. Qf2 Qxg4 { Getting the pawn back. } 13. Be2 Qh3 14. Bf1 Qh5 $10) (11. a3 { Preventing Nb4. } 11... f6 12. Qg3 fxe5 13. d5!? Qg7 14. b4 Be7 $10) 11... O-O-O { [%cal Gd8d4] } 12. Qf2 Nb4 { [%cal Gb4c2] } 13. Na3 f6 $15 { Black is slightly better here: ahead in development and attacking. }) 5. Nf3 Nxe4 { And there goes the Maróczy bind. } 6. Nc3 Nxc3 (6... d5 7. a3 (7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Qa4+ Nc6 10. Qxe4+ Be7 $10) 7... Bf5 $10) 7. dxc3 Nd7 { Get the knight out before the bishops are developed. } (7... Be7 8. Bf4 O-O 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nd7 $10) 9... Nd7 10. h3 Bf6 11. O-O Ne5 $10) 8. Bd3 Qe7+!? 9. Be2 g6 10. Bf4 Ne5 11. O-O Bg7 $14 { Engine says White is slightly better (+0.5), but this looks very playable for both sides. }) 4... Bb4 (4... Qa5 { Protects e5. } { [%cal Ga5e5] } 5. Be2 Bb4 6. O-O (6. Qc2 O-O 7. O-O { The move order doesn't really matter here. }) 6... O-O 7. Qc2 Re8 { [%cal Ge8e5] } 8. a3) 5. a3 (5. Nxe5 O-O 6. Nf3 Re8 $10 7. Be2 Bxc3 8. dxc3 Nxe4 { Black can finally recapture the pawn, and the position is equal with a slight edge for White. }) 5... Bxc3 6. dxc3 d6 $10 *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: Breyer: 2.d3"]
[Date "2017.07.08"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B10"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Breyer Variation"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "Breyer: 2.d3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/tigB84KX"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.07.08"]
[UTCTime "18:22:45"]

{ This variation was first played by the Hungarian player Gyula Breyer, a leading pioneer of hypermodern chess. There are also variations named after him in the Ruy Lopez and the Vienna Gambit, and there is the Breyer Gambit (1.e4 e5 2.f4 exf4 3.Qf3). }
1. e4 c6 2. d3 { The basic position for this variation. In many cases it turns out to be a King's Indian Attack versus Caro-Kann. A rather dull line: Both players develop their pieces without much interaction. If you are an experienced KIA player and don't like overly sharp games, this line is for you. But with 5.d4 White can create a very sharp game. Interesting fact: This line has a drawing chance of only 33.9%. } 2... d5 { Normal continuation, but not a necessary part of this line. } 3. Nd2 { This gives Black the rare opportunity to play e5 immediately. } (3. Nc3?! { This is one of these very rare cases in which Black changes the pawn color to dark squares. Be aware that now the light-squared bishop is the "good" bishop. } { [%csl Bc8] } 3... d4 4. Nce2 e5 5. f4 exf4 6. Bxf4 c5 { This is fine for Black. }) 3... e5 (3... g6 { Invites White to play the Stein Attack, a moderate attempt by Black to get a slightly sharper game } 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 e5 6. Ngf3 Ne7 7. O-O O-O 8. b4 { Official marker for the Stein Attack. b4 instead of the usual b3 in the main line. Everyone is mildly impressed now. Please!? } 8... a5) 4. Ngf3 { Oh, we are attacking something! } { [%cal Rf3e5] } 4... Bd6 5. g3 (5. d4 { This is one way to spice the game up. Using two moves to get to d4 looks a bit odd, but it can work as a surprise weapon. See [Jobava - Vidit] for a very sharp example. } { [%cal Rf3e5,Rd4e5] } 5... exd4 { The only reasonable move. } { [%cal Re4d5,Rf1d3,Rf3d4] } 6. Nxd4 (6. Bd3 { d4 doesn't run away, and it's pretty hard for Black to protect it. This avoids the weak c2 from the 6.Nxd4 line. } 6... Ne7 7. O-O O-O 8. exd5 Nxd5 { Black really doesn't want an IQP, so no cxd4. } 9. Nxd4 { And now that Black has lured the knight away from f3, it can unfold its evil plan … } 9... Bxh2+! 10. Kxh2 Qh4+ 11. Kg1 Qxd4 { Get the piece back, and have an extra pawn. }) (6. exd5 { Asks Black an important question: Do you want an IQP and an extra pawn? } 6... cxd5 7. Nxd4 { Black's d-pawn will be the center of attention in the following game. } { [%csl Gd5] } 7... Nc6 { White should not take that knight, because then Black could add a defender to its IQP. } 8. N2f3 { [%cal Rf3h2,Rf3d4] } 8... Nf6) 6... Nf6 7. exd5 O-O! { Black sacrifices a pawn for a faster development. } 8. dxc6 Nxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8+ 10. Be2 Qxc6 { Note how well developed Black is now. } { [%cal Gc6g2,Gc6c2,Gd6h2] } 11. O-O { Candidate moves for Black are Rd8 12. Bd3 (White's queen can't move away), Bf5 12. Bd3 (attack the weak c2), Re8 12. Nb3 } { [%cal Gf8d8,Rc8f5,Re2d3,Bf8e8,Bd2b3] }) 5... Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. Re1 Nbd7 { Absolutely nothing happened so far. White will usually try to push the a/b/c pawns now(b3 and c3 are the normal moves), Black will send its own pawns against that. } *


