1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. g3 { White's idea is to neutralize Black's little queenside pawn chain. Black can – and probably should – still switch the color complex. } 3... d4 (3... dxe4?! { Playable. } 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. Nf3 Bd6 { Kokarev, Dm - Howell, D., 0-1, World Blitz 2017, https://lichess.org/3nPS6DTS }) 4. Nce2 e5 { And the fianchettoed bishop on g2 will stare at its own pawn for a while.
The engine say f4 is the best move here for White. No one has ever played that. } 5. f4 $146 exf4 6. Nxf4 (6. gxf4?! Qh4+! 7. Ng3 { Only move. } 7... Qxf4 $15) 6... Nf6 *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: King's Knight/Apocalypse Attack: 2.Nf3"]
[Date "2019.04.28"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B06"]
[Opening "Modern Defense: Two Knights Variation, Suttles Variation"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "King's Knight/Apocalypse Attack: 2.Nf3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/0635rYoN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.28"]
[UTCTime "09:33:22"]

1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 { This is rather rare over the board, but a very popular move online. I call it the King's Knight Opening. We have a choice here: continue with the classical plan and play d5 immediately, or go for a kingside fianchetto. The latter avoids the "Apokalypse Attack". } 2... g6 { This is the easiest to play in my experience. It looks like an Accelerated Dragon, but the actual play is a bit different. } (2... d5 3. exd5 (3. e5 { is very rare. Just play } 3... c5 { and after } 4. d4 { it transposes to the ➡ Botvinnik-Carls Defense with 4.Nf3. } (4. b4 { Some poor version of the Wing Gambit. We take the first pawn … } 4... cxb4 5. a3 { … but not the second. Just pin that pawn. } 5... Qa5 6. c3 (6. Bb2 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6b4,Gc8g4] } 7. Be2 Bg4 8. O-O e6 $10 { This is just firn for black. } { [%cal Gg8h6] }) 6... bxc3 7. Nxc3 Nc6 { [%cal Ga5d5] } 8. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3d5,Rc3d5,Ga5d5] } 8... d4 9. Ne4 (9. Bc4 e6 10. Ne2 a6 11. Bb2 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Bxd4 Qd6 $15) 9... e6)) (3. d4 dxe4 4. Ng5) 3... cxd5 4. Ne5 { This is sometimes called the Apocalypse Attack. See http://www.kenilworthchessclub.org/articles/opening/apocalypse/apocalypse.htm
It's aggressive, but it also violates the opening principle that you shouldn't move a piece twice. There are two ideas for White here: Bb5+ and Qh5. } { [%csl Yd7,Yc6,Yf7][%cal Rf1b5,Bb5e8,Ye5c6,Ye5d7,Rd1h5,Bh5f7,Ye5f7] } (4. d4 { Transposes to the ➡ Exchange Variation/4.Nf3 }) (4. Bb5+ { Black should accept the offer to trade off the light-squared bishops so early. Nc6 is strategically worse. } 4... Bd7 (4... Nc6?! { Not recommended. } 5. Ne5 Bd7 (5... Qc7 6. d4 e6 { Now black has a French setup – not what we want. } { [%cal Gf8d6] } 7. Bf4 Bd6 8. Qg4 { [%cal Gg4g7] } 8... Kf8 $13 { The engine thinks this is equal. In practical play it's rather uncomfortable for black, because the kingside development has been slowed down a lot. }) 6. Nxd7 Qxd7 { Now White has the bishop pair. That's the whole idea behind Bb5+. }) 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 { Preserve the option to play Nc6. } { [%cal Gd7b7,Gd7d5,Gb8c6] } 6. d4 Nc6 7. O-O e6 8. Bf4 Nge7 9. Re1 (9. c3 Ng6 { [%cal Gg6f4] } 10. Ne5 Ngxe5 11. Bxe5 f6 12. Bg3 h5 13. h3 { Yousry, S. - Shimanov, A., 0-1, 17th Dubai Chess Open, 2015, https://lichess.org/Xboml255 }) 9... Ng6 { [%cal Gg6f4] } 10. Bg3 $10 { This is just a fine position. The engine wants to see black playing Bd6. I'm not so sure, maybe it's better to keep the dark-squared bishop. White might play c4 eventually if black stops asking questions, that explains Bd6. } { [%cal Yf8d6,Rc2c4] }) 4... Nc6 { challenges the knight on e5 directly. } (4... Nf6 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Nxd7 Nbxd7) (4... a6 { Prevents Bb5+. But it's not really a developments move, and we have hole on b6 now. } { [%csl Bb6] } 5. d4 Nc6 6. c4 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Be6!? 8. cxd5 (8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qb3 Bc6 10. cxd5 (10. Nc3? d4! 11. Ne2 (11. Nd5 e6 12. Nb6 Rb8 $15)) 10... Qxd5) 8... Qxd5 9. Qxd5 Bxd5 $10) 5. Bb5 { And here we are in the problematic line shown in 4.Bb5+ Nc6. } (5. d4 Nf6 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. c3 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Nd2 O-O { Black is fine here. The tempo that White lost with the extra knight move means that Black could complete the development while White still has to get the dark-squared bishop out. And the light-squared bishop on b5 is rather pointless. } { [%csl Bc1,Gc7][%cal Gd6h2,Gd7c7,Gc7d6] }) 5... Bd7 { This gives White the bishop pair, but Black does have compensation in form of a faster develeopment. } (5... Qc7?! { Avoids the trade knight vs. bishop, but } 6. d4 { threatens Bf4, and now the queen isn't so comfortable anymore. } 6... e6 7. Bf4 Bd6 8. Qg4! { [%cal Rg4g7] } 8... Kf8 $10 { is now mandatory, and that's not a move you want to play. It's still technically equal, but certainly easier to play for White. } (8... f6? { fails to a tactic: } { [%cal Gc7g7] } 9. Nxc6! { and Black can't take back. } 9... Kf8 { Christiansen, Johan-Sebastian - Risting, Eivind Olav, 1-0, Kragero Resort Chess 2018, https://lichess.org/8qq6NWYC } (9... bxc6?? 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Qxg7 cxb5 12. Qxh8 $18 { This is lost for Black. }))) 6. Nxd7 Qxd7 { If we ae just counting the developed pieces and pawns, Black wins 3:1.
This is of course just a dynamic advantage, meaning it will vanish over time. } { [%csl Bb5,Gd7,Gc6,Gd5] } 7. d4 e6 (7... a6 { is a move here. But White can't attack c6 with another piece, so the bishop isn't a real threat. Just develop instead with e6. } 8. Be2 e6 9. Bf4 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. c3 Nf6 12. Nd2 O-O 13. O-O Rfe8 $146 { This is good for Black. The plan is now to play for e5. This move is a novelty. } { [%cal Ge6e3] }) 8. c3 Bd6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Nd2 O-O { Same resulting position as in the 5.d4 line. Black is very fine: Development is complete, and there are no weaknesses in the position. This can also arise from an Exchange variation, see Kramnik - Caruana 2018 } { Kramnik, V. - Caruana, F., 1-0, 80th Tata Steel GpA, 2018, https://lichess.org/yUgIepOl }) 3. d4 (3. c4 d5 4. exd5 cxd5 5. cxd5 Nf6 { This is now an Accelerated Panov/Fianchetto Defense. }) 3... Bg7 { [%cal Gg7d4] } 4. Nc3 d6 { The idea is guarding the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop with pawns. } { [%csl Bf6,Be5,Bd4][%cal Gc6c5,Bg7c3] } 5. Bc4 { The downside is that White has good access to light squares. } { [%cal Gc4f7] } 5... b5 6. Nxb5! d5 (6... cxb5? 7. Bd5! { Wins the rook. }) 7. exd5 cxb5 8. Bxb5+ Bd7 *


