1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 { B12 Maroczy Variation. There is no good square for Black's light-squared bishop now. On the other hand, White has opened the g1-a7 diagonal which weakens their king side if they want to castle that way. } { [%cal Bg1b6] } 3... e6 { Try to develop the bs bishop first instead, prepare c4. } (3... dxe4 { An attempt to create a free square for ls bishop. } 4. fxe4 e5 { dxe5 is … impossible. } 5. Nf3 (5. dxe5? Qh4+ { [%cal Gh4e4,Be4h1] } 6. Kd2 Qf4+ 7. Ke1 Qxe4+ { [%csl Gc5,Gb4][%cal Gf8c5] } 8. Qe2 Bf5 $17) 5... exd4 (5... Be6) (5... Bg4) 6. Bc4 { B12 Maroczy Variation/Maroczy Gambit } (6. Qxd4?! Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Nb3 Bd6 $10) (6. Nxd4? Qh4+ 7. g3 Qxe4+ { [%cal Ge4h1,Ge4e1] } 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Bh3 $15) 6... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 7. O-O Nbd7 { [%cal Gd7b6,Gc6c5] } 8. c3 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4] } 9. Bb3 dxc3 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { Go to the endgame. Castling isn't really necessary for Black now. } 11. Nxc3 Be6 $10) (3... Nf6?!) (3... Qb6 4. Nc3 dxe4 5. Bc4 Nf6 (5... exf3?! { Black should not accept this gambit. The kingside is too underdeveloped. } 6. Nxf3) 6. fxe4 e5 7. dxe5 Ng4 { [%cal Gb6f2] } 8. Qe2 Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1] } 9. e6! { [%cal Ge2g4] }) 4. Nc3 Bb4 (4... Nf6) 5. Bf4 Ne7 (5... Nf6 6. Qd3 (6. e5?! Nfd7 7. Qd3 { Collins, Sam E - Hole, Oystein, 0-1, Gausdal Classic IM-A, 2004, https://lichess.org/AlebzOQ9 }) 6... O-O (6... b6 { is the main move } 7. Ne2 Ba6 8. Qe3 O-O 9. O-O-O { Now we have a sharp game with opposite castling and the following race of pawn storms towards the opponent's king. These pawns are best supported from behind, so Black should retreat the dark-squared bishop now, which doesn't do anything anymore on b4. } { [%cal Rh2h6,Rg2g6,Gb6b3,Gc6c3,Ga7a3] } 9... Be7 10. g4) 7. O-O-O) 6. Qd3 Nd7 7. O-O-O O-O 8. Nge2 b5 *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: Gurgenidze System: 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 g6"]
[Date "2017.10.25"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Gurgenidze System"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "Gurgenidze System: 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 g6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/3Zjm99OY"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.10.25"]
[UTCTime "20:40:30"]

{ This is NOT the classical Gurgenidze System in which White plays f4, e5, and d4, and Black places a knight on f5. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 { The Modern Variation is played for exactly this one reason: to avoid the Gurgenidze system. Now White has still the option to play c3, and then a bishop on g7 wouldn't be very effective. } 3... g6 4. Ngf3 Bg7 5. c3 c5 { c5 is recommended by the engine. Not a move most humans would play. } { Kochyev, Alexander - Titov, German, 1-0, URS-ch sf, 1985, https://lichess.org/yJvHK5EF }) 3... g6 { Black prepares to fianchetto the bishop on g7, in order to attack White's d4 pawn. There's also the usual pin Nf3 Bg4 incoming, so White can play h3 now to prevent it or one move later after Bg7.
The c6-c5 break is not supported by the dark-squared bishop, so the knight has to do this job by going to d7. } { [%cal Gf8g7,Bg7d4,Gc6c5,Gc8g4,Gb8d7] } (3... b5 { The "Gurgenidze Counterattack". Not related to the system we are looking at here. It's more like the ➡ Main Line/Tartakower Variation } 4. a3 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ exf6 $14) 4. Nf3 (4. h3 { Prevent the pin immediately. } 4... Bg7 5. Nf3) (4. e5 Bg7 5. f4 (5. Bf4) 5... Nh6 6. Nf3 f6 7. Be3 O-O 8. h3) 4... Bg7 { Now we have basically a ➡Two Knights Attack. Instead of Nf6 or Bg4, Black has fianchettoed the bishop. The Problem is that such an operation takes two moves, not just one. So White had an extra move for d4.
White's plan is to play c3 eventually, in order to support d4. So the knight on c3 has to move, and that gives Black the tempo back. In other words: This is a rather slow, positional fight for d4.
Black will castle king-side and then launch an attack on the queen side. } { [%csl Rd4,Yg7,Yg6,Bc3][%cal Gc6c5,Gb8d7,Bd7c5] } 5. h3 { Most played move here. It prevents Bg4 for the moment. But it also weakens the king-side pawns, and if White castles queen-side later, c3 isn't so attractive anymore. Also, it doesn't develop a piece. } (5. Be2 { An alternative to prevent the pin. Also develops the bishop, and enables king-side castling.
Note that White has already developed three pieces, and they can castle. Black has only one piece developed. } 5... Bg4 { anyway. There is no other good square for Black's light-squared bishop. } (5... dxe4 { is not recommended, because it improves White's knight. } 6. Nxe4 { [%cal Re4f6,Re4c5,Re4g5] }) 6. Be3 (6. O-O { is probably the most accurate here. Now it's time to get Black's knight to f6 to enable castling. However, e5 by White would be very uncomfortable, so Black has to take e4 now. } { [%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8] } 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nf6 (7... Bxf3?! { Black can win a pawn here temporarily, at the cost of development. Don't try that! } 8. Bxf3 Qxd4 9. Qxd4 Bxd4 { But White has counterplay. } 10. Re1! { with the threat of Nd6. It's not so easy to deal with that. } { [%cal Re4d6,Rd6b7,Re1e7] } 10... Na6 11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. Nxb7 { And White regains the pawn. } 12... Rb8 13. Rd1 { And this rook will enter the 7th rank now. Also, c6 is hanging. } { [%cal Rd1d7,Rf3c6] }) 8. Nxf6+ exf6 9. c3 O-O 10. h3 Bf5 $146 { is my recommendation. Black wants to exchange this bishop for White's good light-squared bishop, not for a knight. It's a novelty. }) 6... dxe4 (6... Nf6) (6... e6) 7. Nxe4 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5,Bf5e3,Bf5d4] } (7... Nf6 8. h3 (8. Nxf6+)) (7... Nd7) 8. c3 Nf5 { [%cal Rf5e3] } 9. Bf4 Nd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 { Brown, Martin - Arkell, Keith C, 0-1, GBR-ch 99th, 2012, https://lichess.org/ixYqQxU3 }) (5. e5 Bg4 6. Be2 e6 { [%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Bd7c5,Gg4f3,Gg8e7] }) 5... Nf6 (5... dxe4 { The exchange here leads to a very open game with lots of material trades and a high chance for a draw. } 6. Nxe4 Nf6 7. Nxf6+ exf6 8. Bc4 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 10. Re1 Nb6 11. Bb3 a5 12. a4 (12. a3 a4 13. Ba2 Re8) 12... Nd5 (12... f5?! { Too early, it gives White a chance to push the rook to the 7th rank. } 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. Re7) (12... Re8 { Black should try to exchange te rooks, so White can't invade on the 7th rank when Black plays f5. } { [%cal Gf6f5,Rc1g5,Re1e7] } 13. Bd2) 13. c4 Nb4) 6. e5 Ne4 { Similar to the Two Knights attack, but here White can take that knight. } 7. Nxe4 (7. Bd3 Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5) 7... dxe4 8. Ng5 { [%cal Rg5e4] } 8... c5 9. Bc4 O-O 10. c3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 { Note that this knight cannot be pinned, in contrast to many other CK variations. } (11... b5 12. Bb3 Bb7) 12. Be3 Qa5+ 13. Kf1 h6 14. Nxe4 Rd8 { Pin the pawn for an attack on e4. } { [%cal Gc6e5,Gg7e5] } 15. f4 b5 16. Bb3 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qb4 { [%cal Gb4d4,Gd8d4] } 18. Qf3 { [%cal Rf3a8] } 18... Rxd4 { [%csl Bf4][%cal Gd4f4] } 19. a3 Qa5 20. Nf6+ Bxf6 (20... exf6 21. Qxa8 Qc7 22. Kg1 Bf8 { Ibragimov, Ildar - Stangl, Markus, 1-0, Dortmund op-A, 1992, https://lichess.org/V7s6Ma0f }) 21. Qxa8 (21. exf6 Qb6 22. f5 Bb7 { Xiong, Jeffery - Shabalov, A., 0-1, ch-USA 2017, https://lichess.org/FvCIv1T6 }) 21... Rxf4+ 22. Ke2 Qc7 23. exf6 Qe5+ 24. Kd1 Kh7 (24... Qxb2) 25. Qxc8 Qxb2 26. Qc2 Qxa1+ 27. Qc1 Qxf6 { [%cal Gf4f1] } 28. Kc2 Qf5+ $15 *


