1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 b5 { Gurgenidze Counterattack. Invented by Bukhuti Gurgenidze in 1968. He played this against Zaitsev (draw) and Tal (lost). It's a funny line, but I don't recommend it. It's better to develop pieces instead and preserve the option for a c6-c5 break.
The idea is to play b4, push the knight away and maybe give a check with Qa5+.
White has quite a number of ways to handle this. } { [%cal Gb5b4,Gd8a5] } 4. a3 { Stop the b-pawn. } (4. e5 { Allow b4. } 4... b4 5. Na4 e6 6. Nf3 Nd7 { Werner, Clemens - Salvermoser, Bernd, 1/2-1/2, BL2-Sued 0304, 2003, https://lichess.org/tc1PydoM }) (4. exd5 { Create a free square on e4 for the knight. } { [%csl Be4] } 4... b4 5. Ne4 cxd5 6. Nc5 e6 7. a3! bxa3 { Black has to take, the pawn can't be defended. } 8. b4! { That knight is a monster now, a real pain in the position. } { [%csl Bc5] }) (4. Bd3 b4 5. Na4 { Novelty! } (5. Nce2 dxe4 (5... e6 6. Nf3 dxe4 { should probably be played here to prevent e5 by White. } 7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Bg5 Be7 { Jovanovic, Alexandar - Radlovacki, Jovan, 1/2-1/2, Belgrade Spring op, 2013, https://lichess.org/GvY7Cq8X }) 6. Bxe4 { [%cal Re4c6] } 6... Nf6 7. Bd3) 5... dxe4 6. Bxe4 { transposes into the game } { Karasev, Vladimir I - Bataev, Evgeny, 0-1, Chigorin Memorial 07th, 1999, https://lichess.org/jOds9Pz6 } 6... Nf6 7. Bf3 e6) 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 (5... Bf5 6. Ng3 Bg6 7. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] } 7... Nd7 { [%csl Be5][%cal Rf3e5,Gd7e5] } 8. Nh4 e6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 $14 { And here Black faces the simple question: What about castling? Both sides are open. }) (5... Nd7 6. Bd3 Ngf6) 6. Nxf6+ exf6 { Now we have some kind of ➡ Tartakower Variation. } 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 { Overall, this line – including the variations listed above – is playable, but not that good. } *


