1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Bc4 { Von Hennig Gambit. White goes for a fast development and an early attack on f7. } { [%cal Rc4f7] } 4... Nf6 { We protect that extra pawn. This also comes with the threat of Bg4 } { [%csl Bg4][%cal Gc8g4,Bg4d1] } 5. f3 (5. Nge2 { This is a slow line in which White will get the pawn back, and we end in a "normal" position. } 5... Bf5 6. Ng3 { [%cal Rg3f5,Rg3e4,Rc3e4] } 6... Bg6 7. O-O e6 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Re1 Nbd7 10. Ncxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe7 Nxf2! { We want a queen trade here } 12. Bxe6 Nxd1 13. Bxd8 Kxd8 14. Bxd7 Kxd7 15. Raxd1 Bxc2 $17 { Black is just better here: one pawn up, better pawn structure, active king, and a bishop against a knight. }) (5. Bg5 b5 (5... Bg4 6. Nge2 Nbd7) 6. Bb3 (6. Bxf6?! exf6 { [%cal Gf6f5] } 7. Bb3 f5 { That's a very safe pawn now. }) 6... b4 7. Nb1) 5... exf3 6. Nxf3 { The best response here is to stick with the normal development in the Classical variation and develop the light-squared bishop first, then play e6. White is still not fast enough to counter that. } { [%cal Rf3e5,Re5f7] } 6... Bf5 7. Ne5 { [%cal Re5f7,Rc4f7] } 7... e6 { This shuts down the attack on f7. } { [%csl Gc4] } 8. g4 (8. O-O Bg6 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 { [%cal Gd8c7,Gc7h2,Gh8h2] } 12. Rae1 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4,Gf6d5,Gb6d5] }) 8... Bg6 9. h4 { [%cal Rh4h5] } 9... Bb4! { This pins the knight and creates a free square on e4 for the bishop in case of h4. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gg6e4,Rh4h5,Gb4c3,Gb4e1] } 10. O-O { is White's best try. } (10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nbd7 { Attack that annoying knight and prepare O-O-O. } { [%cal Gd7e5] } 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Qf3 Nd5) 10... Bxc2! { [%cal Gd8d4,Bd4g1,Bd4e5] } 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 (11... Bxd1) 12. Qe2 { [%cal Re2e6,Rc4e6] } 12... Re8 (12... Qxd4+) 13. Kg2 Kg8 *


