1. e4 c6 2. Bc4?! { Basic position for the Hillbilly Attack which is really a gambit. The idea is to get a very fast attack on Black's king side.
Peter Svidler called this line an insult. And he is right. } 2... d5 { Usually, White doesn't even take the time to exchange the pawns. The reason is that exd5 gives Black time to protect h5. } 3. Bb3 (3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb3 { The "downside" is that Black now can develop before the white queen comes out: } (4. Bb5+ Bd7 { We use this opportunity to trade off the light-squared bishop immediately. } 5. Bxd7+ Nxd7 6. d4 e6 $15 { This is just fine for Black. } { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c2,Gf8d6,Gg8f6] }) 4... Nf6 { [%csl Gh5] }) 3... a5! { The "declined" line. Threatening to trap the bishop, enforcing the exchange. I could not find a game for that in the databases, so this might be a novelty. Please contact me, if you find an existing game! } { [%cal Ga5a4] } (3... dxe4?! { The "accepted" line. My recommendation is not to go that way. Decline it with a5 instead, and take all the fun away for White.
If you take, White will get that pawn back later. } 4. Qh5 { Everyone and their dog plays g6 here. If you follow the main line, you see how uncomfortable that is for Black — albeit not really dangerous with accurate play. And yet, White keeps the initiative for a long time, dictates what Black has to do. } { [%cal Rb3f7,Rh5f7] } 4... g6 (4... e6 { Second best move after g6, according to SF8. Downside is the French bishop for Black. See [Carlsen - Tomashevsky] } 5. Nc3 { The engine recommends for Black not to fight for the e4-pawn: the preferred moves are a5, Nd7 and c5 in that order. } { [%cal Rc3e4] } 5... a5 6. Nxe4 a4 7. Bc4! Ra5 { [%cal Ga5h5] } 8. Qe2 (8. Qf3) 8... b5 { [%cal Gf8a3] } 9. Bd3 Ne7 $15 { This is fine for Black. Intact pawns on the king side } { [%cal Ge7d5,Bd5f4,Ge7g6,Bg6f4] }) 5. Qh4 { [%cal Rh4e4] } 5... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } (5... Bg7 6. Qxe4 a5 { [%cal Ga5a4] } 7. Nc3 Nf6) 6. f3 exf3 7. Nxf3 Bg7 8. O-O Bf5 9. d4 (9. d3 { [%cal Gd8b6,Gb6g1] } 9... O-O 10. Nc3 Nbd7 { [%cal Gd7e5,Gd7c5] } 11. Bh6 b5 (11... Nc5 { [%cal Gc5b3] } 12. Ng5 a5) 12. Ng5 a5 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Bxf7 Qb6+ (14... Rxf7 15. Rxf5 gxf5 16. Ne6+) 15. Kh1 Rxf7 16. g4 Bxg4 17. Nxf7 Qe3 18. Ng5 (18. Kg2 Rf8 19. Ng5 h6 20. Nge4)) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 Nbd7 { Start removing Black's defenders } 11. Bh6 b5 12. h3 { [%cal Rg2g4] } 12... a5 13. g4 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 a4 15. gxf5 axb3 16. fxg6 fxg6 17. Ng5 Qc7 { [%cal Gc7g3] } 18. Nce4 { [%csl Rg3][%cal Re4g3,Re4f6] } 18... Qa7 $16 { [%cal Ga7d4,Ga7h7] }) (3... e6 { Another way to decline, but now Black has a "French bishop" on c8. } 4. d4 dxe4 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Ne2 f5 $10 { Equal position, but I think it's easier to play for White. Black is also behind in development. }) 4. exd5 (4. a4 dxe4 5. Qh5 { Maybe the most logical line for White. } 5... g6 6. Qh4 Nf6 7. f3 Na6! 8. fxe4 Nc5 { [%cal Gf6e4,Gc5e4,Gc5b3] } 9. Bc4 Ncxe4 { [%cal Gg6g5] } 10. Nf3 Nd6 { [%cal Gd6c4] } (10... g5) 11. Na3 Bg7 12. O-O O-O { [%cal Gd8b6,Gb6g1] } 13. c3!? (13. d3) 13... Nxc4) (4. Nc3 { An attempt to prevent a4. } { [%cal Rc3a4,Rb3a4,Rc3e4] } 4... d4 5. Nce2 a4 6. Bc4 { The only move. } { [%cal Gb7b5,Ge7e5,Bb8d7,Bd7e5] } 6... e5 (6... b5 { Also playable. } 7. Bd3 Na6 { [%cal Ga6c5] } 8. Nf3 { [%cal Re2d4,Rf3d4] } 8... Nb4 9. Nexd4 e5 { [%cal Gd8d4,Ge5d4] } 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. Bxb5 Qb6 12. c4 Bg4 13. O-O (13. Bxa4 Bxf3 14. Bxc6+ Qxc6 15. Qxf3 Qxc4 $17 { Black is one piece up and three pawns down. })) 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. a3 { [%cal Rf3g5,Rg5f7,Rc4f7] } 8... b5 $10 { h6 was also a move, but a bit passive. This position is also just fine for Black. }) 4... a4 { cxd5 and b5 are slightly better for White. } 5. Bc4 cxd5 6. Bb5+ (6. Be2 e5 7. d4 { [%csl Rc1] } 7... exd4 { Now Black has an IQP. } { [%cal Rd1d4,Gb8c6,Gc6d4] } (7... e4 8. a3 Nf6 { [%cal Gb1c3,Gf8e7,Re2b5,Rc8d7,Bc1e3,Be7d6] }) 8. c3!? Nf6!? 9. Nf3) 6... Bd7 7. Qe2 { Black has now no need to rush. Just develop. } 7... Nf6 8. Nf3 Qa5 { [%cal Gd7b5,Ga5b5] } 9. Nc3 (9. Bxd7+?! { takes away some tension, but } 9... Nbxd7 { … now Black is better developed. } { [%csl Bf6,Bd7,Ba5,Rf3,Re2] }) 9... e6 10. O-O Be7 (10... Bd6 { This is not a safe square for the bishop. } { [%cal Rc3b5,Rb5d6] } 11. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 12. Nb5 { Black is still more than fine, but now the bishop has to move again. A wasted tempo. } { [%cal Rb5d6] }) 11. d4 { There are many good moves here for Black. a3 is the most interesting. } 11... a3!? { White can't take the pawn, because then the knight falls. That was the idea behind Qa5. } { [%cal Ga5c3] } (11... O-O 12. Bd3) (11... Bxb5 { I'm not so sure about this. Looks a bit dangerous. } 12. Nxb5 Nc6 13. Bf4 { [%csl Rc7,Rd6][%cal Rf4c7,Rb5d6,Rb5c7] } 13... O-O) 12. Bd3 { [%cal Ge7a3] } 12... axb2 13. Bxb2 O-O $15 { This is just fine for Black. } *


[Event "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory: Euwe Attack: 2.b3"]
[Date "2018.09.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B10"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Euwe Attack"]
[StudyName "Caro-Kann Defense. The Theory"]
[ChapterName "Euwe Attack: 2.b3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/UVdBvtb7"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2018.09.02"]
[UTCTime "18:47:08"]

1. e4 c6 2. b3 { Euwe Attack, named after Max Euwe who played this line against Richard Réti.
This is a "hypermodern" idea: attack the center with pieces, not with pawns. Very similar to the Réti Attack against the French or the Snyder against the Sicilian. } 2... e5 { A very rare move! I found only two games with that in the database. But it is certainly a playable line. It activates the dark-squared bishop and delays d5. } { [%cal Rf8b4] } (2... d5 { And here White has to make an important decision already: Play Bb2 first, and gambit the e-pawn in favor of a faster development, or exchange the pawns first. The latter avoids Black's d4 push which can be a bit annoying. e5 is also a move, although rarely played. White wants to use the a1-h8 diagonale for the bishop after all. } 3. Bb2 dxe4 (3... d4 { Rarely played. The idea is to secure that pawn with e5 and create a strong center. It doesn't work.
White can now attack the center by developing pieces, and Black is forced into a sequence of rather passive moves. } { [%cal Re7e5] } 4. Nf3 { Prevents e5. } { [%cal Gb2d4,Gf3d4,Gf3e5] } 4... Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 e5 { And here we see that Black has "mixed pawn colors, which means that both bishops are needed for an effective defense. The trade is positionally wrong. } { [%csl Bd4,Be5,Bc6,Bb7] } 7. c3 dxc3 (7... Bc5?! 8. Qg3! { Immediate counter-attack. } { [%cal Gg3g7,Gg3e5] } 8... Qf6 { The only move that protects both attacked pawns. But it removes a defender for the d-pawn. } { [%csl Bd4] } 9. b4 { Grab some space with a tempo. } 9... Bb6 10. cxd4 exd4 { Now the e-pawn can be pushed eventually. } { [%cal Ge4e5] } 11. Bd3 { Prepare castling, blockade Black's d-pawn, and target the king side once more. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Gd3h7,Ge1g1] } 11... Ne7 { Black should also develop. } 12. e5! Qh6 { [%cal Rh6d2] } 13. O-O O-O $14 { White is slightly better: better developed and the bishop pair. f4 or a queen side attack are possible plans. } { [%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4,Gf2f4] }) 8. Nxc3 { [%cal Ge1c1,Gf1c4,Gc4f7] }) 4. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 4... Nf6 { [%cal Rf6e4] } (4... f5?! { This weakens Black's king side too much. } 5. d3 { Challenge this pawn immediately. } 5... Nf6 (5... e5 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 Nf6 8. Nf3 (8. exf5?! { Good for Black! } 8... Bxf5 { [%cal Rf5c2] } 9. Bd3 e4! 10. Bc4 b5 11. Bf1) 8... fxe4 9. Nxe5) (5... e3 6. fxe3 Nf6 7. Nf3 e6 { [%cal Rf8c5,Rc5e3,Rc5b4,Rb4c3] }) (5... exd3 6. Bxd3) 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 fxe4 8. Nge2 { [%cal Ge2g3,Re7e5] }) 5. Nge2 { [%cal Ge2g3,Gg3e4] } 5... Bf5 6. Ng3 Bg6 7. Qe2 { We know this move from the Réti Gambit. And now Black can't add another defender. } { [%cal Gc3e4,Ge2e4,Gg3e4] } 7... e6 { Black should just continue the development and let White recapture the pawn. } 8. Ngxe4 Nbd7 { White has a few options now: g3 and fianchetto the other bishop, like Euwe did against Réti; h4 and attack on the king side immediately; castle long and protect c2 with that. } { [%csl Bc2][%cal Ge1c1,Gg2g3,Gh2h4] } 9. O-O-O { I like this move. It also aligns the rook with Black's queen } (9. g3 Be7 (9... Qa5 10. Bg2 Ba3 11. Bxa3 Qxa3 { This is an indirect attack on c2. } { [%csl Bc2][%cal Ra3b2,Rb2c2,Rg6c2] } 12. O-O O-O { [%csl Bc2][%cal Ra3b2,Rb2c2,Rg6c2] } 13. d3 { d3 solves all those problems. } { [%cal Ge2c2] } (13. h4?! { Prasenjit, Datta - Swapnil, S Dhopade, 0-1, IND-chB 51st, 2013, https://lichess.org/vAO3w4dC })) 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O $10) (9. h4 { A bit premature. } 9... Be7 10. O-O-O { Semenova, Lidia K - Nogin, Nikolai, 1-0, Kiev Independence Cup-A 8th, 2008, https://lichess.org/y81jhUPT })) 3. Bb2 { In the games in the database, Black tried f6 and d6; both are too passive for this setup. } { [%cal Gb2e5] } 3... Nf6! $146 { Novelty. Black doesn't defend, they start a counter-attack! } 4. Bxe5 Nxe4 5. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2e8] } 5... Qe7 { This situation reminds me of the Damiano line in the Petroff's Defense. See https://lichess.org/study/yVVpkkLT/Jm7zJK0T#8
Now White can either retreat the bishop to b2 or develop the knight to f3. Even Qxe4 is a move, but it leads to too much material exchange in my opinion. } 6. Nf3 (6. Bb2 d5 7. Nc3 Nf6 { Note that whoever starts the queen trade, helps the other side's development. } { [%cal Gf8e7,Gf1e2,Be2e7,Be7e2] } 8. Nf3) (6. Qxe4 d6 { Note that the bishop is pinned. } { [%cal Re7e4] } 7. f4 Nd7 { [%cal Rd7e5] } 8. Nf3 f6 9. Bd3 { Now the queen is defended. As soon as that happens Black has to take on e5. Or … play Nc5! } 9... dxe5 (9... Nc5 10. Bxf6! { Almost any trade is okay now. } 10... Qxe4+ 11. Bxe4 gxf6 12. Nc3 d5 13. Bd3 Bg4 $10) 10. fxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Qxe5+ fxe5 $10 { Black has an IQP and the bishop pair as compensation. White on the other hand can claim the open f-file faster by castling, and their pawn structure is better. A slight imbalance that leaves a lot to play. }) 6... d5 7. d3 Nc5 { is in my opinion the best option. } (7... Nf6 { is not ideal: if White decides to give up the dark-squared bishop, they can ruin Black's pawn structure a little bit: } 8. Bxf6 gxf6 { This isn't so bad; the engine even thinks Black has a small edge. But I'd rather not play this position. } 9. Qxe7+ Bxe7 $10) 8. Bb2 { Now Black should exchange queens, because otherwise White does it, and then Black has to take back with the king. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Rb2a3,Re2e7,Rb2g7] } 8... Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 { And now the question is: Can Black develop the rest of the pieces? White's dark-squared bishop keeps his counterpart in place. } { [%cal Gb2g7] } 9... Ne6 { Overprotect g7. Passive, but probably the best solution. } { [%cal Ge6g7,Rb2g7] } 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. O-O O-O $10 *


