1. e4 c6 2. f4 { This has no name, but it is played sometimes. I call it the Bird Variation. It weakens White's king side very much. } 2... d5 { This is the usual way to play. It gives White some space advantage after e5. } (2... e5 { Now we are in a rarely played King's Gambit position, that can arise after 1.e4 e5 2.f4 c6.
There are a few nice traps here. } 3. Nf3 (3. fxe5? Qh4+! 4. g3 Qxe4+ 5. Qe2 Qxh1 6. Nf3 $17) (3. f5?? Qh4+! 4. g3 Qxe4+ 5. Qe2 Qxh1 6. Nf3 (6. Qxe5+ Ne7 7. f6 gxf6 8. Qxf6 Qxh2 9. Ne2 (9. Qxh8? Qxg3+! 10. Kd1 Qxg1 $19 { [%cal Gg1f1] })) 6... d6) 3... exf4 4. d4 d5 5. Nc3 (5. Bxf4 dxe4 6. Ng5 Bf5 7. Bc4 { [%cal Rc4f7,Rg5f7] } 7... Bg6 $10)) 3. e5 (3. exd5 cxd5 4. Nf3 (4. d4 Nc6 5. Bb5 Qb6) 4... Nf6 5. d4 Nc6 6. Ne5 g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Bb5 Qc7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3) 3... c5! { This now all bout the control over the d4 square. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4] } (3... Bf5 { The most played move here. c5 is stronger. } 4. Nf3 e6 5. d4 h5 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh5g4] } (5... c5 6. Be3)) 4. Nf3 { [%csl Bd4][%cal Rf3d4,Gc5d4] } 4... Nc6 { [%csl Bd4][%cal Rf3d4,Gc6d4,Gc5d4] } 5. c3 { Block b4 and d4 for Black's knight, maybe prepare d4. } { [%csl Rb4,Bd4][%cal Rc3d4,Rc3b4,Rf3d4,Gc5d4,Gc6d4] } 5... Bg4 { [%csl Bd4][%cal Rc3d4,Gc6d4,Gc5d4] } 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 8. Be2 (8. Na3 { [%cal Ra3b5,Rb5d6] } 8... Nge7 9. Be2 (9. d4?! cxd4 10. Nb5 Nf5 11. g4 Nh4 12. Qg3 dxc3 13. bxc3 { Alcazar Jimenez, Victor Manuel - San Segundo Carrillo, Pablo, 0-1, Loyola Festival 1st, 2002, https://lichess.org/jMqDJK92 })) 8... Nge7 { Black is fine here. Nf5 is the next step, followed by castling and an attack on White's exposed king. } { [%cal Ge7f5] } *


