1. c4 c6 { The idea is the same as in 1.e4 c6: Support d5. But this line will often transpose into a Slav or Semi-Slav, so you should be prepared for both. } { [%cal Gd7d5] } 2. Nf3 (2. e4 { Transposition: B10 Caro-Kann Defense: Accelerated Panov Attack }) (2. g3 { One of the possible move orders in the English Opening. } 2... d5 { Bg2 is the most played next move here (see [Carls - Tarrasch]), Nf3 the best according to SF8. d4 and cxd5 are also possible. } { [%cal Rf1g2,Rg1f3,Rc4d5,Rd2d4] } (2... Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Qc2 Nb6 7. a4 a5 8. Na3 Qd5 9. Ne1 Bf5) 3. Bg2 { Offers c4 as a sacrifice. Most players don't take it immediately. } (3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Qc2 Nb6) 3... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gc6d5] } (3... dxc4 4. Na3 { [%cal Ga3c4] } 4... g6 (4... b5? { Doesn't work: } 5. Nxb5! { [%cal Rg2b7] }) (4... Be6 { Blocks the own center. } 5. Qc2 Nf6 6. Nxc4 { g6, Nbd7 and Bxc4 are good continuations for Black here. But White is already slightly better. }) 5. Nxc4 Bg7 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 (8. b3) 8... Nbd7) (3... e5 { Maybe Black's best option. } 4. cxd5 (4. d4) 4... cxd5 5. d4 e4 (5... Bb4+) 6. Nc3 (6. Nh3) (6. f3) 6... Nf6 (6... Bb4) (6... Nc6 { Most played move. } 7. Nh3 h6 8. O-O Nf6 9. f3 exf3 { [%cal Gc8h3] } 10. exf3 Be7 $10 { [%cal Rh3f4,Rf1e1,Rc1e3,Ge8g8,Gc8f5] }) 7. Bg5 (7. f3)) 4. Nf3 { [%cal Re1g1] } 4... dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Qc2 (6. Na3 { Different move order } 6... Nb6 7. Qc2) 6... Nb6?! { Most played move, according to the db, but not a very good one. } 7. Na3 (7. a4 { [%cal Ra4a5] } 7... a5 8. Na3 Qd5 9. Ne1 { [%cal Rg2d5] } 9... Bf5 { Now the games is getting sharp. } { [%cal Gf5c2,Rg2d5] } 10. Bxd5 Bxc2 11. Bxc6+ { Best move. } (11. Bxf7+ Kxf7 { This helps black getting the rook out without castling. The king is rather safe on a light square, and it can get active easily. } 12. Naxc2 (12. Nexc2 { Romanov, Evgeny - Kuipers, Stefan, 1-0, GER-ch U20 int, 2009, https://lichess.org/1ve2iIVj }) 12... e5 $15) (11. Nxc4 { [%cal Re1c2,Rc4b6,Gf6d5,Gb6d5] } 11... Nfxd5 12. Nxb6 Nxb6 13. Nxc2 e5 $10 (13... g6)) (11. Bxc4?! { Drops the a-pawn. } 11... Bxa4 12. Nf3 Nxc4 13. Nxc4 { [%cal Ra1a4] } 13... Bb5 $17) (11. Naxc2? cxd5 $17 { Now black is a pawn up, and it has a very strong center. }) 11... bxc6 12. Nexc2 e6 $10)) 2... d5 3. e3 (3. cxd5 cxd5 4. d4 (4. Nc3 Nc6 5. d4 Nf6 { Also a Slav position. }) 4... Nf6 { Transposition to Slav Defense/Exchange Variation } 5. Nc3 Nc6) (3. d4 { Transposition to Slav/Modern Line }) (3. b3 { Transposition: A12 Reti Opening: Anglo-Slav Variation, Bogoljubov Variation, III }) (3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7) 3... Nf6 (3... e6 4. b3 Nf6 5. Bb2 Nbd7 6. Be2 Bd6 7. d4 O-O $10) 4. Nc3 (4. d4 { Transposition: Slav Defense/Quiet Variation } 4... Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. Bd2 Nbd7 9. Rc1 Bd6 10. g3 Qe7 11. Qb3 Rb8 12. Bg2 O-O 13. O-O dxc4 14. Qxc4 e5) 4... e6 (4... Nbd7 5. d4 e6 { Transposition: Semi-Slav Defense/Normal Variation }) 5. b3 (5. d4 { Transposition: D45 Semi-Slav Defense: Main Line }) 5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 (6. Qc2 Bd6) 6... Bd6 7. Qc2 O-O 8. Be2 Re8 9. O-O e5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Ne4 Bc7 *


