[ChapterName "St. Patrick's Attack: 2.h3 d5 3.Nc3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/mniAPhXM"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2022.01.02"]
[UTCTime "14:04:27"]

1. e4 c6 2. h3 d5 3. Nc3 { St. Patrick's Attack. I'm not sure about the origin of the name, but it has been played on St. Patrick's Day, March 17, in 1991 between Matthias Hermann (2217) and Peter Wirthgen (unrated) in the German Oberliga Nord.
There are no GM games with this opening.
Black has a choice here. } 3... d4 { Bg4 and Bf5 are not available in the near future, so keeping the light-squared bishop and making it the "good" bishop is an option. This does change the color structure the Caro-Kann player is used to - many familiar maneuvers are not available anymore.
On the other hand: Black has now a space advantage, and after e5 both bishops can develop quickly. } (3... dxe4 { I wonder if White has a decent gambit here. } 4. Nxe4 (4. d4 f5 { This is quite ambitious. } (4... exd3 5. Bxd3 { The engine doesn't like it, but White is very active here. Black has only one pawn developed, if we can even say that. } { [%cal Rc1h6,Rd3g6,Bc3d5,Bc3e4,Bc3b5] } 5... Nf6 6. Nf3 { The practical problem is the light-squared bishop: It has no squares, and if we play e6 here, it will be useless for a long time. So how do we develop the dark-squared bishop then? g6 might be an idea. } 6... g6 (6... Nbd7 7. O-O Nc5 { [%cal Gc5d3] } 8. Bc4 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bf5 { And now it's developed! } 10. Be3 e6 { White has a very cute move here: } 11. Nb5! cxb5 12. Bxb5+ Ncd7 13. Ne5 a6 14. Bxd7+ Nxd7 15. Nxd7 $10) 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Qe2 { [%cal Re2e7] } 9... Re8 10. Bf4 Be6 11. Rad1 Nbd7 12. a3 Qb6 $15 { I think Black is fine here: weaknesses on White's side to attack, and a decent development. } { [%cal Ga8d8,Gb6b2] }) 5. g4 e6 6. Nge2 Nf6 7. Rg1!? (7. g5 Nd5 { [%cal Gf8b4] } 8. Nxd5 exd5 9. Nf4 Qd6 (9... Qxg5?! { Dangerous. } 10. Nxd5! Qd8 (10... cxd5?? 11. Bxg5)) 10. c3 Nd7 $15)) 4... Bf5 { This is very similar to the Classical variation, but White hasn't the fast h2-h4 anymore to harass the bishop once it's retreated to g6. } 5. Nc3 (5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nf3 e6 7. d4 $10 { This is fine and well-known. See the Classical variation/Main Line. })) (3... Nf6?! 4. e5 Nfd7 5. d4 { I can see no reason to play this. It's technically equal, but how do you develop your pieces now? White will be much faster. }) (3... e6?! { The engine thinks this is decent, but now we have just a French with a very bad light-squared bishop. }) 4. Nce2 e5 { [%cal Gf8b4,Gc8e6] } 5. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] } 5... Bd6 (5... Nf6 { Counter-attack instead of defense. But if you want an open game, you could also just play 3...dxe4. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Rf3e5] } 6. Ng3 (6. Nxe5 { Not so good for White, because now Black dominates the center. } 6... Nxe4 7. Nf3 c5) 6... Bd6 { Just a different move order. }) 6. Ng3 (6. c3 c5 7. cxd4 cxd4 8. Ng3 Nf6) 6... Nf6 7. Bc4 { [%cal Rc4f7,Rf3g5,Bg5f7] } 7... h6 8. d3 O-O 9. O-O b5 10. Bb3 a5 11. a4 Nbd7 $10 { [%cal Gd7c5] } *


