1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 (5... a6 { Najdorf Variation }) 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6 { The so-called Dragadorf, a reference to the Najdorf where a6 is played on move 5. } 8. Qd2 Nbd7 (8... h5 { An attempt to stop white's ideas on the kingside early. } 9. O-O-O (9. Be2 Nbd7 (9... b5 10. a4 b4 11. Na2 a5 12. c3 bxc3 13. Nxc3 (13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Nxc3 O-O 15. O-O Na6 16. Nc6 $14 { Carlsen, M. - Aronian, L., 1-0, 11th London Classic 2019, https://lichess.org/cQrlMATG }) 13... O-O 14. O-O Bb7 15. Rfd1 Na6 $14 { Shankland, S. - Gareev, T., 1/2-1/2, ch-USA 2014, https://lichess.org/oy4kEKEn }) 10. O-O O-O 11. f4 { Engine recommendation. Covers e5, and maybe even f5 can be played eventually. } { [%cal Gf4e5] } (11. a4 { stops b5. } { [%cal Gb7b5] } 11... Ne5 { 11.f4 would have prevented that. } 12. Nd5 { Shields, Glen D - Krabbe, Wolf-Dieter, 1/2-1/2, Rochade-25/TT, 2014, https://lichess.org/9U0VVgKd }) (11. Rfd1?! { Leaves the king alone. I don't recommend this. Rad1 is better. } 11... Qc7 { Popilski, G. - Shumilov, I., 1-0, Grand Europe Cup 2014, https://lichess.org/xVnXVSiT }) (11. Rad1 Nc5 { Makes f4 impossible for the moment. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gc5e4] } (11... b5) 12. b4 Ncd7)) 9... b5 10. Nd5 Bb7 11. Nxf6+ (11. Nb6!? { Going for serious complications. } 11... Qxb6 12. Nf5 { [%cal Ge3b6,Gf5g7] } (12. Ne6?! { [%cal Ge6g7] } 12... Bh6! { [%cal Gh6d2,Ge3b6] } 13. Ng7+ Kd7 (13... Kf8 14. Bxh6 Kg8 15. Nf5 Qc7 $13 { Arslanov, Shamil - Losev, Dmitry, 0-1, Moscow-ch, 2012, https://lichess.org/fDqVJ5Sh }) 14. Bxh6 (14. Bxb6? Bxd2+ 15. Rxd2 $17) 14... Nc6 15. Bg5 $15) 12... Qc7 13. Nxg7+ Kf8 14. Bh6 Kg8 (14... Rxh6? 15. Qxh6 $16 { Sean, W. - Priasmoro, Novendra, 1-0, Japfa IGM 2018, https://lichess.org/owYzl0ii }) 15. Nf5 { gxf5 would be suicide. } { [%cal Gd2g5] } 15... Nc6 $13) 11... Bxf6) 9. g4 (9. O-O-O h5 (9... b5 { White can start a serious attack here: } 10. g4 Bb7 (10... b4?! 11. Na4 { [%cal Ge3b6,Ga4b6] } 11... Qa5 12. b3 { [%cal Gd4c6] } 12... Ne5 $14 { [%cal Re5c6,Gd4c6] }) 11. h4 h5 12. g5 Nh7 13. f4) 10. Bc4 { Add a defender to the king. } { [%cal Gc4b3] } 10... b5 11. Bb3 { [%cal Gd4c6] } (11. Nc6? { doesn't work yet: } 11... Qc7 12. Bd5 e6!) 11... Bb7 { [%cal Rd7e5,Ra8c8] } 12. Kb1 { King safety! We don't want to see the king lined up with the rook that's coming to c8 now. } 12... Rc8 { Rxc3 is a common motif to weaken the king's defense. Keep that in mind. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rc8c3] } 13. Rhe1 { Move the attack to the center. That way our pieces are close enough to the king to defend it. } { [%csl Bb1][%cal Ge4e5] } 13... Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4] } 14. Bg5 (14. h3!? Nc4) 14... Nc4 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 16. Nb3 { Now black has to watch a5, otherwise White gets a nice fork. } { [%cal Gb3a5,Ba5b7,Ba5c4,Rd8a5] } 16... Qc7 { [%cal Rc7b7,Rc7c4,Rb5b4] } (16... Nh7) 17. a3 { The passive solution } (17. Nd5 { more aggressive, forcing a trade. } { [%cal Gd5c7] } 17... Bxd5 18. exd5 O-O 19. Na5 Ra4 20. Nc6! e6 { [%cal Rf6d5,Re6d5] } 21. Bxf6 { Remove the knight, so d5 is not attacked twice anymore. } 21... Bxf6 22. b3 Rh4 (22... exd5))) 9... b5 (9... Ne5) 10. h4 (10. O-O-O) (10. g5?! Nh5) 10... b4 (10... h5?! 11. g5 Nh7 (11... b4 12. Nce2 Nh7)) *


