[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/iELlTRpu/jb4pSova"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.12.13"]
[UTCTime "04:05:56"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 (2. c4 { Staunton-Cochrane Variation. Another way to get the Maróczy Bind. And here Black can't prevent it. } 2... Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 { White wants to keep the option to play f4, so Nf3 is usually not played. The main moves are g3, d3, f4, and Nge2. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } 4. Nge2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 (5... Nf6 6. g3)) 2... Nc6 (2... d6 3. c4 { Also some kind of Maróczy Bind. But here Black keeps a strong center for themself. } 3... e5 4. Nc3 Nc6) 3. d4 (3. Bb5 { B30 Nyezhmetdinov-Rossolimo Attack. } 3... g6 { B31 Sicilian Defense: Nyezhmetdinov-Rossolimo Attack, Fianchetto Variation }) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 { Accelerated Dragon } (4... Nf6 { leading to the normal Dragon, prevents the Maróczy Bind: White has to protect e4 first and hence no time to play c4 here. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } 5. Nc3 { Blocks the c-pawn. } { [%csl Gc2] } (5. f3?! { Keeping the option for c4 open. } 5... e6 { In this case it's probably better for Black to develop the dark-squared bishop to the g1-a7 diagonal. } { [%cal Gf8c5,Gc5g1] } 6. c4 Bc5 7. Nxc6 (7. Nb3 Bb6 $10 { It's now very difficult for White to find a safe square for the king. }) 7... bxc6 8. e5 { And this is the end of the Maróczy Bind. } 8... Nh5 $10) 5... d6 (5... e5 { Lasker-Pelikan Variation } 6. Ndb5) 6. Bg5) 5. c4 { Accelerated Dragon/Maroczy Bind } 5... Bg7 (5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 (9. Bg5 O-O 10. Qd2 Be6 11. Rc1 Qa5 12. f3 Rfc8 13. b3 a6 14. Na4 { [%cal Gd2a5] } 14... Qxd2+ (14... Qd8 15. O-O Bd7 (15... Rab8 16. c5 Rc6 17. Rfd1 $14)) 15. Kxd2 Nd7 16. g4 f6?! { Main move } (16... Re8 17. Be3 Rac8 $14) 17. Be3 f5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. h3 Rf8 20. f4 Rad8) 9... O-O 10. Qd2 Be6 (10... a5) (10... Qa5) (10... Ng4 11. Bxg4 (11. Bg5) (11. Bf4 f5))) 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O (7... Ng4 { This is only possible now, before White has played Be2. } { [%cal Gg4e3] } 8. Qxg4 { White has to take. The dark-squared bishop is too important. } 8... Nxd4 9. Qd1 Ne6 10. Rc1 O-O (10... Qa5 { Main move. } 11. Bd3 b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. f4 Rc8 $14 (13... O-O 14. Bb1 { [%cal Gb1a2] } 14... d6 (14... Qh5!? { Stockfish recommendation. } 15. Nd5 { [%cal Gd5e7,Gg7b2,Gh5d1] } 15... Qxd1 16. Nxe7+ Kh8 17. Rcxd1 Bxb2 18. Rxd7 Ba6 $14)))) 8. Be2 { Stopping Ng4 for good. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Ge2g4] } 8... d6 { [%cal Ge4e5,Gc8h3] } 9. O-O Bd7 10. Qd2 { Creating the battery that goes for Black's dark-squared bishop. } { [%csl Bh6][%cal Gd2h6] } 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 { The pressure on White's e-pawn forces them to play f3 – and not f4 as they'd like to. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gc6e4,Rc3e4] } 12. f3 a5 { And Black can start to go for White's queen side. This encourages White to play b3. } 13. b3 { And now almost all of White's pawns are on light squares. This means that they are not interested in a trade of dark-squared bishops anymore. } { [%csl Ba2,Bb3,Bc4,Be4,Bf3,Bg2] } 13... Nd7 { … which is why Black can offer that trade now. White should not accept that offer, at least for now. } 14. Be3 (14. Bxg7?! Kxg7 15. Rab1 (15. Qd4+ f6) 15... Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Nc5 { Bologan, V. - Iturrizaga, E., 0-1, World Blitz 2015, https://lichess.org/oCCU8QMc }) 14... Nc5 15. Rab1 { Unpin the knight. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Gg7b2] } 15... Qb6 { With the idea Qb4. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gb6b4,Bb4c3,Bg7c3] } 16. Rfc1 (16. Nb5 Rfc8 17. Rbc1 (17. Rfd1) (17. Rfc1 Qd8)) (16. Nd5) 16... Rfc8 17. Rc2 Qd8 18. Bf1 h5 19. a3 Kh7 20. b4 axb4 21. axb4 Ne6 (21... Na4) 22. Nd5 Ra3 *


