1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 { This is all normal, and here comes the blunder: } 8... Na5? 9. e5! Nxb3 (9... Nh5 10. g4! d6 11. gxh5 $16 dxe5 12. h6 Bf6 { Black can't afford to trade more. } 13. Nf3 $16 { One piece up, and a very annoying pawn deep in Black's camp. } { [%csl Bh6] }) (9... Ne8?? 10. Bxf7+! Rxf7 (10... Kxf7 11. Ne6 { [%cal Ge6d8,Ge3b6,Ge6c7,Gd1d8] } 11... dxe6 { The best move. } (11... Kxe6?? 12. Qd5+ Kf5 13. g4+ Kxg4 14. Rg1+ Kh4 (14... Kh5 { Palac, Mladen - Ostojic, Predrag, 1-0, Belgrade GMA op, 1988, https://lichess.org/SHvZiVBc } 15. Qg2 g5 16. Qxg5#) (14... Kh3 15. Qg2+ Kh4 16. Qg4#) 15. Bg5+ Kh5 16. Qd1+ Rf3 17. Qxf3#) 12. Qxd8 $18 { If you look into the database, this has actually happened a few times! } 12... Nc6) 11. Ne6 { The queen has no escape square. } 11... dxe6 12. Qxd8 $18) 10. exf6 Nxa1 11. fxg7 Nxc2+ (11... Kxg7 12. O-O (12. Qxa1 e5)) 12. Qxc2 Kxg7 $16 13. O-O { White is just better here: All pieces are developed and the rook is fully compensated with the two minor pieces. } *


[Event "Hyperaccelerated Dragon"]
[Date "2019.12.23"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "fuxia"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B27"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Hyperaccelerated Fianchetto"]
[StudyName "Bg7 in the Sicilian"]
[ChapterName "2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 - Hyperaccelerated Dragon Part 1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/iELlTRpu/kJERkMWG"]

1. e4 { The lines in this chapter are based on GM Robin van Kampen's ebook "My White repertoire vs. the Sicilian: Part 2"
https://chess24.com/en/learn/advanced/ebook/my-white-repertoire-vs-the-sicilian-part-2-ebook/9 (access restricted to paid membership)
I have changed evaluation indicators and added some lines based on newer games and engine suggestions. } 1... c5 2. Nf3 g6 { B27 Sicilian Defense: Hyperaccelerated Dragon or Hungarian Variation. } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 (5. e5?! Nc6 6. Qa4 Nd5 7. Qe4 Nb6 $10 { Saric, Iv - Hou Yifan, 1/2-1/2, 77th Tata Steel GpA, 2015, https://lichess.org/qhXVTZSE }) 5... Nc6 6. Qa4 d6 { By far the best move. It opens the field for the light-squared bishop and gives Black more control over the important square e5. Not enough to prevent e4-e5, but at least the knight can stay on f6. } (6... Bg7?! 7. e5! { The punishment for not playing d6! Nh5 runs into g4, so Ng8 is the only move here. } 7... Ng8 8. Bf4 { Now Black has to develop the kindside somehow, and the sad move f6 is the only safe way to do that. } 8... f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Bb5 (11. Bc4+ { Looks much stronger than van Kampens suggestion Bb5. } 11... Kh8 12. Bb3 Qb6 13. Be3 Qa5 14. Qc4 e6 15. Kb1 d5 16. Qh4 Bd7 { This is just fine for White: Very mobile pieces, kingside pressure, and better control over the center. }) 11... a6 (11... Na5 12. Bc4+ Nxc4 13. Qxc4+ d5 14. Qb3 (14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Rxd5 Be6 16. Rxd8 Bxc4 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Rd1) 14... e6 15. Rhe1 a6) 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Rhe1 a5 14. Qc4+ Kh8 15. Bg3 Ba6 (15... Ra6 16. Ng5 d5 17. Qc5 Nd7 18. Qe3 Bh6 19. Nf7+ Rxf7 20. Qxh6 $14 { Jemec, Viktor - Krecak, Dr. Zvonko, 1-0, EU/TC8/final, 2012, https://lichess.org/7Hg3T457 }) 16. Qh4 d6 (16... Qe8 17. Bd6) 17. Ng5) (6... Qc7 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. Nd5) 7. e5 dxe5 (7... Ng4 { Not the best move, according to Stockfish, but it comes with a few nice traps and it forces White to play some only moves. } 8. Bf4 (8. exd6 Qxd6 9. Bb5 (9. Bf4 e5?! 10. Bg3 Qb4? { Wells, Peter K - Paschall, William M, 1-0, Koszeg, 1998, https://lichess.org/m0FoGi0R }) 9... Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bf4 Qc5 $14) 8... Bg7 9. exd6 O-O 10. Bb5 (10. h3 { Here we enter a rather wild line. } 10... Qb6! { [%cal Gb6b2] } 11. Ne4 { White cannot take the knight. } (11. hxg4?! { Too greedy! } 11... Qxb2 { [%cal Gb2c3,Gg7c3,Bb2a1] } 12. Rd1 Bxc3+ 13. Bd2 $15 { This is very nice for Black. }) 11... Nf6 12. dxe7 Nxe7 (12... Re8 13. Be3 Qxb2 14. Bd4 Nxe4! 15. Bxb2 Bxb2 16. Qxe4 Bxa1 17. Qh4 Rxe7+ $14 { And Black has sufficient compensation. White is just slightly better. } { Sivic, Jernej - Eilmes, Donald P, 1/2-1/2, WC31/pr06, 2007, https://lichess.org/cX0svDgL }) 13. Be3 Qc7 $14) (10. dxe7?! { Too greedy! } 10... Qxe7+ 11. Be2 Bd7 $15 { The pawn sacrifice is working out for Black: the extra open file can be used by their rook, Bxc3 will damage White's pawn structure, and White's king is still not safe. }) 10... e5 11. Bg5 Qxd6 12. h3 Nh6 { [%cal Gh6f5] }) 8. Nxe5 Bd7 (8... Qd4 9. Nxc6 Qxa4 10. Nxa4 bxc6 11. b3 Bf5 (11... Bg7 12. Bb2 Bf5 (12... O-O 13. Bd3 { Bonn, Thomas - Stephan, Victor, 1/2-1/2, FRA-chT1 1011, 2010, https://lichess.org/ADZ2qcK0 }) 13. O-O-O O-O 14. Bd3 (14. Bd4 Rfd8 15. Be2 e5 16. Bc5) (14. f3?! Rfd8 15. Be2) 14... Bh6+ (14... Bxd3 15. Rxd3 e6 16. Rhd1) 15. Kb1 Bxd3 16. Rxd3 Ne4 17. Rd7 Nxf2 18. Re1 e5 (18... e6 19. Bd4 Ng4 20. h3 Rad8 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. c3 e5 23. Bc5 Nh2 24. Nb2 Rd2 25. Rxe5) 19. Rxe5) 12. Ba6! Bg7 (12... Rd8 13. Bb7 Rd6 14. O-O! e5 (14... Bxc2? 15. Bf4 Re6 16. Nc5) 15. Bb2 Nd7 16. Rad1 Bxc2 17. Rc1 Be4 18. Rfe1 (18. f4?! { Kiewra, Keaton F - Gurevich, Daniel, 1-0, Saint Louis SPICE Cup op 7th, 2013, https://lichess.org/0IoxPJQi }) 18... Bh6 (18... Bd5?! 19. Nc3 Bh6 20. Ba3 Bxc1 21. Rxc1 Re6 22. Nxd5) 19. Rc4 Bd5 20. Rc2 Be4 (20... f6 21. Ba3 Re6 22. Nc3) 21. Rce2 Bf5 22. Ba3 Rf6 (22... Re6?! 23. Bc8!) 23. Bc8 Kd8 24. Bxd7 Kxd7 25. Nc5+ Kc7 26. Bb2) 13. Bb7 Rd8 14. Bxc6+ Kf8 15. Be3 Ng4 16. Rd1 Rxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Nxe3+ 18. fxe3 Be5 (18... Bh6 19. Ke2 Bxc2 20. g4! g5 21. e4!) 19. c4 Kg7 20. e4) (8... Bg7 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Rb8 12. O-O Qc7 13. Re1 Rb6 (13... Bb7 14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. Bf4 Qc5 (15... Qd7 16. Qxd7 Nxd7 17. Rxe7 Rxb2 18. Rb1!) 16. Re5 (16. Rab1 Rc8 17. Qa6 Qc6 18. Qxc6 Rxc6 19. Be5) 16... Qb4 17. Qxb4 Rxb4 18. Bc1 e6 19. Ra5 Rd8 20. Kf1 Rd7 21. Ke2 Ne4 (21... Nd5 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. c3 Re4+ 24. Be3 f5 25. Kf3 { Naiditsch, Arkadij - Hausrath, Daniel, 1-0, Bundesliga 1011, 2011, https://lichess.org/eRSV1Dvu }) 22. Nd1 (22. Nxe4 Rxe4+ 23. Be3 Bxb2 24. Rb1 Bf6) 22... Rc4 23. c3) 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bb7 (15... Bxb2 16. Bxb2 Rxb2 17. Bb3 { Trofimov, Vladimir Markovich - Tleptsok, Ruslan Aslanovich, 1/2-1/2, RUS/C14/sf2 (RUS), 2014, https://lichess.org/59p0oJmo }) 16. Bxb7 Rxb7 17. c3 Rd8 18. Qc2) 9. Nxd7 { And now White has the bishop pair. } 9... Qxd7 (9... Nxd7?! 10. Bb5 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rd1 (12. Bxc6 Nb6 13. Qe4 bxc6 14. Rd1 Qc7 $10 { Vachier Lagrave, M. - Giri, A., 1/2-1/2, SportAccord Blitz Men 2013, https://lichess.org/3mCUcKJg }) 12... Qc8 $14 (12... Bxc3?! 13. bxc3 Qc7 14. Bf4 e5 $14 { Vachier Lagrave, Maxime - Edouard, Romain, 1-0, FRA-chT U20, 2005, https://lichess.org/etgtRFQw })) 10. Be3 Bg7 11. Rd1 Qg4 (11... Qc7 12. g3! O-O 13. Bg2 $14 { Zaragatski, Ilja - Guseinov, Gadir, 0-1, EU-Cup 29th, 2013, https://lichess.org/7JOHVqdR }) (11... Qc8 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O a6 14. Rfe1 b5 15. Qh4 Qc7 (15... Qf5 16. g4! (16. Bf3?! Rac8 { Adhiban, Baskaran - Guseinov, G., 0-1, World Rapid 2015, https://lichess.org/GqSzEg9s }) 16... Qc8 17. g5 Nd7 18. Bf3 Nde5 19. Bg2) 16. a4 b4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Bxb2 (18... Rfd8 19. Red1 Rxd5 20. Rxd5 e6 21. Rc5 Bf8 22. Rc4 Qd7 23. Qe4 Rc8 24. b3) 19. Rc5 Qd6 20. Rd1 Qe6 21. Bc4) 12. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7] } 12... O-O 13. h3 (13. Qxb7?! { Makes no sense. } 13... Nb4! 14. Rd2 Rab8 15. Qf3 Qe6 { Despite being a pawn down, Black has equalized completely. }) 13... Qb4 { The best move according to StockFish 10. Van Kampen gives Qc8 instead, which is the second best move. } (13... Qc8 14. Be2 a6 15. O-O e6 (15... b5 16. a4) 16. Na4 Rb8 17. Nb6 Qc7 18. c3 { White has a tiny edge here due to the bishop pair and a bit more space. }) 14. Be2 Rad8 { Stronger than van Kampen's Qxb3, because Black challenges White's control over the d-file and keeps the tension on the queenside. } (14... Qxb3 15. axb3 Nb4 16. Rd2 Rad8 17. Bf3 b6 18. Ke2 Rxd2+ 19. Kxd2 Rd8+ 20. Kc1) (14... Rfc8 15. O-O Qxb3 16. axb3 Nb4 17. Bf3 Nc6 $16 { Ruperez Benito, A. - Carneiro, C., 1-0, Portugal Open 2018, https://lichess.org/ZYsEhrbp }) 15. O-O b6 $14 { Now the black queen can move without giving up the b-pawn. } *


