1. e4 c5 2. c4 { Staunton-Cochrane Variation. The direct way to the Maróczy Bind. The basic problem is the hole on d4, and that's what Black is going to play against. } { [%csl Bd4] } 2... Nc6 { Stops an immediate d4 or e5. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6e5,Rd2d4,Re4e5] } 3. Nc3 (3. Ne2) (3. Nf3 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. d3 g6 6. Be2 (6. Bg5 { is a nice idea for White, because it is forcing f6. } { [%cal Gg5f6] } 6... f6 (6... Nf6 { Playable, but that pin is a bit annoying. } 7. Be2 Bg7 8. Qc1 { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gc1h6] } 8... h6 9. Bd2 { Now Black can't castle, but Kf8 is safe enough. } { [%csl Gh6] } 9... Kf8 $10) 7. Bd2 (7. Be3 Bg7 8. Be2 Nge7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O f5 $10 { Cabrido, Victor - Mednis, Edmar John, 0-1, Manila op, 1991, https://lichess.org/mU67Kwod }) 7... Bg7 8. a3 Nge7 $10 { Heidenfeld, Mark - Berkvens, Joost, 1/2-1/2, EU-Cup 17th, 2001, https://lichess.org/EMFYsSGk }) 6... Bg7) (3. g3 { English setup. } 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Ne2 (5. Nc3 { Transposition: A36 English Opening: Symmetrical Variation, Botvinnik System } 5... d6 6. Nge2 e6 7. O-O Nge7 { [%cal Ge7c6,Rg2c6] } 8. d3 O-O 9. Rb1 b6 $10) 5... d6 6. Nbc3 e6 7. O-O Nge7 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3 Nd4) 3... g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 { Transposition: A36 English Opening: Symmetrical Variation, Botvinnik System } 5... d6 6. Nge2 e6 7. O-O Nge7 8. d3 O-O 9. Rb1 b6 10. Be3 Nd4 $10 *


