1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4 Nxb4 (3... cxb4 4. d4 d5 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. c4 bxc3 7. Nxc3 Qa5 8. d5 e6! 9. Bd2 (9. dxc6 Bb4 10. Bd2 Bxc3 11. Rc1 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 (12. Nxd2 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7c6] } 13. Bd3 (13. cxb7?! Bxb7 { [%cal Gb7g2,Ga5a2] }) 13... bxc6 $15) 12... Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 bxc6 14. Rxc6 Nf6 $15)) 4. c3 Nc6 5. d4 g6 { The downside here is that White has a very simple plan against this setup: Push the h-pawn. } (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Qa4 { [%cal Gf1b5,Gb1c3] }) 6. d5 Na5 7. h4 Bg7 8. h5 d6 9. h6 Bf6 { This is equal, but given that Black is a pawn up, it should be more. } *


