1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 { One very common motif in the Ponziani is the pinned knight on c6, similar to the Ruy Lopez. There are actually a few transpositions. } { [%cal Gf1b5] } 3. c3 { C44 Ponziani Opening.
This looks dubious: It blocks the c3 square for the knight, doesn't develop a piece and gives Black time for their own development. We can often read that this opening gives Black too many opportunities to equalize early.
White on the other hand can now push d4, and the d1-a4 diagonal is open for the queen. Black's knight has no good squares, and almost all other squares are already covered by White. The hole on c5 is a trap: Some people try to place their bishop there, but d2-d4 will punish them properly for that mistake.
Note that e4 is not yet protected. } { [%csl Re4,Bb4,Bd4,Ba4,Bb5,Bd5,Bf5,Bh4,Bg5,Be5,Bc4,Yc5][%cal Gd2d4,Gf1b5,Gd1a4,Bc3b4,Bc3d4,Be4d5,Be4f5,Bf3g5,Bf3h4,Bf3e5] } 3... Nf6 { Jänisch Counterattack. The most common response to the Ponziani. } { [%cal Rf6e4] } (3... f5 { → Ponziani Countergambit } 4. d4 (4. exf5 Qf6) 4... d6 5. d5 { Ponziani Countergambit/Schmidt Attack } 5... fxe4 6. Ng5 Nb8 7. Nxe4 Nf6 8. Bd3 Be7 { Ponziani Countergambit/Cordel Variation }) (3... Be7?! $14 { → Romanishin Variation }) (3... d6 { → Neumann Variation*. See [Rosenthal - Neumann] } 4. Bb5) (3... Nge7?! $14 { → Reti Variation, aka Kmoch Variation }) (3... g6 { Horwitz Variation* } 4. d4 Bg7 5. dxe5) (3... Bc5?! { This is quite common when you meet unexperienced players. It gives White the tempo back that was lost on c3. } 4. d4 exd4 5. cxd4 Bb4+ (5... Bb6 6. Nc3 { We play Nc3 anyway; it's a good square for the knight. } 6... d6 7. Bb5 { The bishop can't be driven away with a6 + b5, because White's bishop is blocking their b-pawn. } { [%csl Bb7] } 7... a6 8. Ba4) 6. Nc3 $14 { Now White has a very strong center, and e4 is not a problem anymore, because it can be pushed. } { [%cal Gf3g5,Gf3h4,Gf3e5,Gf3d4,Gc1g5,Gf1b5,Gd4c5,Gd4e5,Ge4d5,Ge4f5,Gd1d4] }) (3... Qe7?! { This does block d4 for now, but at the cost of Black's development. } 4. Bb5 Nf6) (3... a6 4. d4 exd4 5. cxd4 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 d5) (3... d5 { The most challenging response for Black. } 4. Bb5 { → Spanish Variation } (4. Qa4 f6 { → Steinitz Variation } (4... Nf6 { → Leonhardt Variation } 5. Nxe5) (4... Bd7 { → Caro Gambit }) (4... Qd6 { → Meitner Variation*. I call it so after Philipp Meitner who played it first in Vienna 1882 against Mikhail Chigorin. And he won! } 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. d3) (4... dxe4?! 5. Nxe5 { Ljubojevic, Ljubomir - Karpov, Anatoly, 1/2-1/2, Portoroz/Ljubljana, 1975, https://lichess.org/G6GNDjqx } 5... Qd6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Qxe4+ Be7 $14 { Now White is a pawn up, and they have a better pawn structure. })) (4. exd5 { → d5 Exchange } 4... Qxd5 { Note that the queen is safe for now, because it can't be harassed by a knight on c3. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Rb1c3] } 5. d4 { Finally we can play d4. }) 4... dxe4 5. Nxe5 Qd5 6. Qa4 { Spanish Variation/Harrwitz Attack/Nikitin Gambit }) 4. d4! { Here is something you have to keep in mind in almost all variations: Push the center pawns. Don't worry about the hanging e4 here. } { [%csl Be4] } (4. Bc4?! $15 { Neumann Gambit, also known as C55 Italian Game/Two Knights Defense/de Riviere Gambit } 4... Nxe4 5. Bd5 Nf6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Bd6 8. d4 O-O $15 { Equal material, but Black is better developed. And White's bishop can't compensate the pawns structure: both are on dark squares. } { [%csl Bc1,Bb2,Bc3,Bd4][%cal Ge1g1,Gb1d2,Gd2f3,Ge5d3,Rc6c5,Rc8g4,Rf8e8] }) (4. d3 { Anti-Fraser System. See ➡ Fraser/Vukovic. The most passive move. Solid, but not in the spirit of the Ponziani. } 4... d5 5. Nbd2 a5 6. exd5 Qxd5 $15 { Equal material, but Black's pieces are much more active, most notably the bishops. } { [%cal Rf8c5,Rc8f5] }) 4... Nxe4 { Kieseritzky Variation*. See [Horwitz - Kieseritzky] } (4... exd4 { Minckwitz Variation*. See [Schmidt - Minckwitz] } 5. e5 Nd5 (5... Ne4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Nxd2 9. Qxd2) (5... Qe7 { Happened once in a game. } 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bb5 dxe5 8. dxe5 Bg4) (5... Nxe5? 6. Nxe5 Qe7 7. Qe2 { Important. Don't waste time with the d-pawn. } 7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 $16) (5... dxc3? { This is a weird ad hoc gambit that you see sometimes online. } 6. exf6 cxb2 7. Bxb2 gxf6 { The material is technically equal now: Black got three pawns for the piece. But White can get the king castled very soon, which is much harder for Black, and the extra piece will help getting the pawns back. } { [%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4,Ge4f6,Gf1d3,Gd1e2] }) 6. cxd4 (6. Qb3 Nb6 7. cxd4 d6 8. Bb5 Be7 $10) (6. Bc4 { This looks a bit slow to me. The bishop has to move twice now, giving away a tempo. } 6... Nb6 7. Bb3 d6 (7... d5 8. cxd4 Bg4 { Hou, Yifan - Carlsen, Magnus, 0-1, Tata Steel-A 75th, 2013, https://lichess.org/ILd2SKbB })) 6... Bb4+ (6... d6) 7. Bd2 (7. Nbd2) 7... d6 $10 (7... Bxd2+)) (4... d6 { Pseudo-Philidor* }) (4... d5 { Brien Variation*. See [Janssens - Brien] }) 5. d5 { Push the pawn! } (5. Bd3 d5 (5... f5) 6. Nxe5 (6. dxe5 Bg4 (6... Be7 7. O-O Bg4 (7... O-O { Petrisor, Adrian Marian - Stegariu, Vlad Ionut, 1/2-1/2, ROM-ch, 2013, https://lichess.org/R7RAbzbS }) 8. Bf4 (8. Re1 { Vajda, Levente - Mastrovasilis, Athanasios, 1/2-1/2, EU-ch 13th, 2012, https://lichess.org/ghCnC7F7 }) 8... Bh5 { Sidorenko, Ilya - Steinberg, Nitzan, 1/2-1/2, ISR-chT 13, 2013, https://lichess.org/1tITYvt3 } (8... O-O { Miladinovic, Igor - Skembris, Spyridon, 1/2-1/2, Karditsa, 2017, https://lichess.org/0CHRJrFC })) 7. O-O Qd7 $10 { [%cal Gd3b5,Gb1d2] } 8. Bb5 (8. Nbd2)) 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Bc5 8. O-O (8. Bxe4 Qh4 { [%cal Rc5f2,Rh4f2] } 9. O-O dxe4 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qc4 Bb6 12. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2e4,Gc4e4] }) 8... Bf5 (8... Qh4 { Bademian Orchanian, Jose - Almada, Enrique, 1/2-1/2, URU-ch, 2017, https://lichess.org/jd5fBopJ }) 9. Qf3 Qc8 10. Qe2 O-O $13) 5... Ne7 (5... Na5? { That knight is lost already. } 6. b4 c6 { The best response now. We can't take c6, because that would save Black's knight. } { [%cal Rc6d5,Rd8a5] } 7. Be2 { No need to take knight now, it won't run away. } 7... d6 8. bxa5 $16) (5... Bc5 { → Vukovic Gambit, aka Fraser Defense. Almost all moves are forced from here on. } { [%cal Rc5f2,Re4f2] }) (5... Nb8 { Not a bad move. But a sad one. } 6. Bd3 { Don't take the e-pwen yet. The knight can get pinned by Qe7, which is a bit annoying. } { [%csl Be5] } (6. Nxe5 Bc5) 6... Nc5 7. Nxe5 { Now we can take. }) 6. Nxe5 Ng6 (6... Nf6 { Rehorek, Martin - Vorisek, Jaroslav, 0-1, CZE-chT2a 9596, 2017, https://lichess.org/plSQ9el6 }) (6... c6) (6... d6? { The most common move online! :) It is a huge mistake. } 7. Bb5+ c6 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 { [%cal Gc6d8] } 9... Qb6 10. Nd4+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 12. O-O $16 { Black is one pawn down, the d-pawn is isolated, and the king exposed. White's plan is to occupy the open e-file with a rook, then develop the knight and the bishop (in that order) and play against Black's weak d-pawn. Winning chances for white here: 91%! } { [%cal Gf1e1,Gb1d2,Gd2f3,Gc1e3] }) 7. Nxg6 (7. Qd4 Nf6 8. Nxg6) 7... hxg6 8. Bd3 Nc5 9. O-O (9. Bc2 d6) *


[Event "Tata Steel A 75th"]
[Date "2013.01.22"]
[White "Hou, Yifan"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "0-1"]
