1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 { Jänisch Counterattack. The most common reply } { [%cal Rf6e4] } 4. d4 exd4 { Minckwitz Variation*. See [Schmidt - Minckwitz]
This is online the most common move. In otb games Nxe4 is the most played (and better) move. } 5. e5 { We push the pawn. } (5. cxd4?! { That would lose the e-pawn. } { [%cal Rf6e4] } 5... Nxe4) 5... Nd5 { cxd4 and Qb3 are both good moves. } (5... Ne4 { Also okay for Black. The target square for Black is now d2. } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Re4d2] } 6. Qe2 (6. cxd4 d5 (6... Bb4+ { [%cal Rb4d2,Re4d2] } 7. Nbd2 O-O (7... d6 { Zelcic, Robert - Lazovic, Gordan, 1-0, Pula op 10th, 1996, https://lichess.org/M4AwVvjy }) (7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Nxd2 9. Qxd2 O-O 10. Bb5 $10 { Equal position. White has two center pawns, Black just one. White's d-pawn will be the first target for Black. Not easy to defend. } { [%csl Yd7,Ye5,Bd4][%cal Ge1g1,Ra7a6,Rc7c5] }) 8. Bb5 a6 (8... Nxd2) 9. Ba4 d5 10. a3 Nxd2 11. Bxd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Bg4 13. Qe3 f6 $10) 7. Nc3 Bb4 { The pinned knight needs further protection. } { [%cal Rb4c3,Re4c3] } 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Be3 Ba5 $14 { Almost equal, with a slight edge for White. Black's knight on e4 is very annoying. It should be pushed away or traded off as soon as possible. } { [%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Rc8g4] }) 6... f5 7. exf6 { [%cal Ge2e8] } 7... d5 8. Nbd2 Qxf6 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Qxe4+ Qe6 11. Bd3 dxc3 12. O-O Qxe4 13. Bxe4 Bb4 14. a3 Bc5 (14... Ba5 15. Bxc6+ bxc6 16. Re1+ Kf7 17. Ne5+ Kf6 18. Nxc6 { [%cal Gc6a5] } 18... Bb6 19. bxc3 Bb7 $14) 15. Bxc6+ bxc6 16. Re1+ Kf7 17. bxc3 Rf8 18. Ne5+ { [%cal Ge5f7,Ge5c6] } 18... Kg8 19. Be3 Bd6 20. Nxc6 $10 { Equal position. White is one pawn up, but Black has the bishop pair as compensation. }) (5... Nxe5? 6. Nxe5 Qe7 7. Qe2 dxc3 8. Nxc3 $16) 6. cxd4 (6. Qb3 Nb6 7. cxd4 d6 8. Bb5 { Pin the knight. As usual. } (8. Ng5?! { This doesn't work. } { [%cal Gb3f7,Gg5f7] } 8... Qe7) 8... Be7 $10) (6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 d5 8. cxd4 Bg4 9. Be3 Bb4+ (9... f6?! { Hou, Yifan - Carlsen, Magnus, 0-1, Tata Steel-A 75th, 2013, https://lichess.org/ILd2SKbB }) 10. Nc3 f6 11. h3 Bh5 12. O-O O-O 13. g4 Bf7 14. Re1 Nc4 $10) 6... Bb4+ (6... d6 7. Bb5 (7. Bc4) 7... dxe5) 7. Bd2 (7. Nbd2 d6 8. a3 Bxd2+ (8... Ba5) 9. Qxd2 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 9... O-O $10 (9... dxe5) 10. Be2 Re8 (10... Nde7 11. O-O dxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd2 13. Bxd2 Be6 14. Be3) (10... dxe5 11. dxe5 Re8 12. b4 { [%cal Gc1b2,Gb2e5] } 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. Bb2) 11. O-O h6 12. b4 { [%cal Gc1b2,Gb2c3] } 12... Nce7) 7... d6 8. Bb5 { Pin the knight, as we have seen a few times already. } 8... O-O { And unpin it. } 9. Bxb4 Ncxb4 10. a3 $10 { [%cal Ge1g1,Gb1c3] } 0-1


[Event "The Ponziani Guide: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3: 3…Nf6 4.d4 Nxe4 - Jänisch/Kieseritzky"]
[Date "2018.03.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C44"]
[Opening "Ponziani Opening: Jaenisch Counterattack"]
[StudyName "The Ponziani Guide: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3"]
[ChapterName "3…Nf6 4.d4 Nxe4 - Jänisch/Kieseritzky"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LLGCk9Bp/gKCv8Xle"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2018.03.26"]
[UTCTime "06:22:47"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 { Jänisch Counterattack. The most common reply } { [%cal Rf6e4] } 4. d4 Nxe4 { Kieseritzky Variation*. See [Horwitz - Kieseritzky].
This is the most common move here otb. And it's probably the most reasonable. } 5. d5 { Push the pawn. As usual. } (5. Bd3 d5 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 (6... Bd6) 7. dxe5 Bc5 8. O-O (8. Bxe4 Qh4 { [%cal Rh4f2,Rc5f2,Rh4e4] } 9. O-O)) 5... Nb8 (5... Bc5 { → Fraser/Vukovic }) (5... Ne7 6. Nxe5 { If Black plays d6 now, a "natural looking move", White is already winning. } 6... d6?? { Yes, this happens sometimes. See https://lichess.org/TBIEtMSv for an example. It's the second most common move on lichess for this position! } (6... g6?! 7. Nc4 Bg7 8. Bd3 Nc5 9. d6! Nc6) (6... Ng6 { Black has to open e7 for the bishop. This is also an invitation to trade the knights on g6. Black would get the open h-file for that, so White should not accept it. } { [%cal Rf8c5] } 7. Nxg6 (7. Qd4 Qf6 8. Qxe4 Qxe5 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Bf4 d6 11. Na3 Be7 12. Nc4 (12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. O-O O-O-O 14. Rfe1 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 a6 16. Nd4 Bf6 { Maier, Alexander - Smejkal, Jan, 0-1, Munich op 9293, 1993, https://lichess.org/htA5aa3g }) 12... Nxc4 13. Bxc4 Bd7 (13... O-O 14. Kd2 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 14... Bd7 15. a4 (15. Rhe1 Rfe8 16. a4 a6 17. a5 Bf6 18. Bd3 h6 { Velimirovic, Dragoljub - Malaniuk, Vladimir P, 1/2-1/2, YUG-Cup 36th, 1993, https://lichess.org/GHWhxPyD }) 15... a5 16. Rhe1 Rfe8 17. Bb5 Bxb5 18. axb5 Kf8 19. Ra4 b6 { De la Riva Aguado, O. - Wiedenkeller, M., 1/2-1/2, European Small Nations, 2016, https://lichess.org/8PN7zhUp }) 14. Kd2 $10 { Velimirovic, Dragoljub - Malaniuk, Vladimir P, 1/2-1/2, YUG-Cup 36th, 1993, https://lichess.org/GHWhxPyD }) (7. Qf3 Nf6 (7... Nxe5 8. Qxe4 Qe7 9. Be2) 8. Nxg6 hxg6) 7... hxg6 8. Bd3 Nc5 9. O-O Nxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 11. Re1 { Black has to unpin the bishop now, or play d6. Otherwise White will push the d-pawn and win the bishop. } { [%cal Gd5d6] } 11... Kf8 { Keep the rook on the open file.
The engine thinks White has a slight edge here. But Black has the bishop pair and a very dangerous half-open h-file. But the pawn on h2 can be guarded by White's knight and bishop. } { [%cal Rh8h2,Gc1e3,Bb1d2,Gc3c4,Rc8f5,Rd7d6,Bd2f3,Bd2e4] }) 7. Bb5+ c6 8. dxc6 bxc6 (8... dxe5?? 9. cxb7+ Nc6 10. Bxc6+ Ke7 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. bxa8=Q $18) 9. Nxc6 Qb6 10. Nd4+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 12. O-O $18 { White is up a pawn, and the king is safe. } { [%cal Gd1g4,Bg4d7,Gf1e1,Be1e4] }) 6. Nxe5 Bc5 (6... d6? { Happened to me in a game. https://lichess.org/oCE4brxM/white#12 } 7. Qa4+ c6 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 { [%cal Gc6d8,Ga4e4] } 9... Nc5 10. Nxd8+ Nxa4 11. Nc6 Nxb2 12. Nd4) 7. Nd3 (7. Qe2) *


[Event "The Ponziani Guide: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3: 3…Nf6 4.d4 Nxe4 5.d5 Bc5 - Fraser/Vukovic"]
[Date "2017.12.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C44"]
[Opening "Ponziani Opening: Vukovic Gambit"]
[StudyName "The Ponziani Guide: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3"]
[ChapterName "3…Nf6 4.d4 Nxe4 5.d5 Bc5 - Fraser/Vukovic"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LLGCk9Bp/5A3fWl1J"]
[UTCDate "2017.12.03"]
[UTCTime "15:55:30"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 { C44 Ponziani Opening } 3... Nf6 4. d4 Nxe4 5. d5 (5. Bd3 { Bd3 prevents the Fraser defense, but at the cost of a tempo. Black can and should now play d5. } 5... d5 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Bc5 8. O-O (8. Bxe4 Qh4 { [%cal Rh4f2,Rc5f2] } 9. O-O dxe4 $10)) 5... Bc5 { Vukovic Gambit, aka Fraser Defense. Black sacrifices the knight on c6 for an attack. Now they have to prove that this is a sound sacrifice. Not so easy.
Many moves are forced from here on. I've marked them with a □. } { [%csl Bc6][%cal Rc5f2,Re4f2] } 6. dxc6 $7 Bxf2+ $7 7. Ke2 $7 Bb6 $7 (7... bxc6 { has been played too, but it's better for white. } 8. Qa4 $7 { [%cal Ga4e4] } 8... f5 $7 9. Nbd2 $7 O-O $7 10. Nxe4 $7 fxe4 $7 11. Qxe4 (11. Kxf2 d5!? { Engine recommendation. Why not exf3? } (11... exf3 12. gxf3 Qf6 13. Be2 (13. Bg2 { Baranyai, Szabolcs Jr - Mathe, Gaspar, 1-0, Hajduboszormeny op, 2017, https://lichess.org/3khYmTVe }) 13... d5 14. Rg1 c5 $16)) 11... d5 (11... Bb6?! { White now needs to avoid the pin by Re8 if they want to take the e-pawn. } 12. Kd2 d6 13. Bd3 Bf5 14. Qxc6 Qf6 $16 { The entire line is just a bit better for White. } 15. Rf1 (15. Bxf5 { Hector, Jonny - Sandstrom, Ludvig, 1-0, Copenhagen op, 2017, https://lichess.org/tw9g6zD8 })) 12. Qxe5 $7 Rf5 { Now the queen has no square! } (12... Re8 { Queen is pinned and has to be traded off. } { [%cal Ge8e2] } 13. Qxe8+ Qxe8+ 14. Kxf2 $14 { Material imbalance. The difference to the Rf5 line is that Black's bishop is still not developed. } { Hector, Jonny - Nielsen, Peter Heine, 1-0, Tastrup, 2016, https://lichess.org/zyHlRlk7 } { [%cal Rc6c5,Rc8f5,Rf5g4] }) 13. Qxf5 $7 Bxf5 $7 14. Kxf2 $7 $13 { Beautiful material imbalance. White's plan is now to coordinate their pieces better, Black will try to push their pawns. White is a tiny bit better according to the engine, but that's not really clear. } { Tscharotschkin, Michael - Vasilev, Milen, 0-1, Staufer op 18th, 2006, https://lichess.org/PSve8CiU }) (7... O-O?! 8. Qd5 { [%cal Gd5e5,Gd5e4] } 8... Nf6 $7 9. cxb7 $7 Nxd5 10. bxa8=Q Ba6+ 11. Kxf2 Qxa8 12. Bxa6 { And again, we have a material imbalance. } 12... e4 $14 { Nepomniachtchi, I. - Sargissian, G., 1-0, FIDE World Rapid 2014, https://lichess.org/EjRzCyKC }) 8. Qd5 $7 { [%cal Rd5c6,Rd5e4] } 8... Nf2 $7 9. Rg1 $7 { And now we have finally a position in which one side has a real choice. dxc6 or bxc6. O-O is dubious. } 9... O-O (9... dxc6 10. Qxd8+ $7 Kxd8 $7 11. Be3 Ng4 12. Bxb6 $7 axb6 $13) (9... bxc6 10. Qxe5+ Kf8 11. Nd4 Ng4 12. Qf4) 10. cxb7 $7 (10. Be3?? bxc6 11. Qc4 Bxe3 12. Kxe3 d5 13. Qh4 Ng4+) 10... Bxb7 $7 11. Qxb7 $7 Qf6 12. Na3 e4 13. Nc4 $7 (13. Nd4? { Loses a rook. } 13... Ng4 { [%cal Rb6g1] } 14. Qa6 Qf2+ 15. Kd1 Qxg1 16. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2g4] } 16... Nxh2 { [%cal Rh2f1,Rg1f1] } 17. Ke1 Nxf1 18. Qxf1 Bxd4 19. cxd4 Qxd4 $19) 13... Rab8 $7 14. Qd5 $7 exf3+ $7 15. gxf3 Rbe8+ (15... Rfe8+ { Anderskewitz, Ralf - Ghosh, Atiyo, 1/2-1/2, WC40/pr08, 2016, https://lichess.org/kCAiAVFS }) 16. Kd2 $7 Ne4+ $7 17. fxe4 $7 Bxg1 18. Bd3 $10 { Surprisingly, the Engine says this position is completely equal. That doesn't mean it's a draw, but both sites have equal chances. } { [%cal Gd3e4] } *


