1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 4. d4 d6 { I call this Pseudo-Philidor, because Black's pawn structure is the same as in a real Philidor. d6 is the third-most common move, and not a good one. It is very passive and it gives White too many options. } 5. Bb5 { This is one of the rare cases where we do not push a center pawn. But we are threatening d5. } { [%cal Gd4d5] } (5. d5 { Not strong enough for now. } 5... Ne7 6. Bd3 Ng6 7. Be3 Be7 $14 { Almost equal, with a slight edge for White. } { [%cal Gc3c4,Ge1g1,Gb1d2] }) 5... Bd7 (5... Be7 { The engine wants this move, because it makes castling possible. It is rarely played however. } 6. d5 a6 7. Bd3 (7. Qa4 Rb8)) 6. O-O (6. Bd3 { The safe option. Maybe a bit too passive. }) 6... Be7 (6... Nxe4 { Black can take the pawn here. We will get it back. } 7. Re1 Nf6 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Bd5 12. c4) 7. Re1 O-O 8. Ba4 exd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 { Push it, baby! } 10... Ne4 $14 *


