1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 4. d4 d5 { Brien Variation. I call it so because it has been played first by Robert Brien in 1854.
Not a good move, but White can easily get a worse position by taking the wrong pawn, which is exd5.
Just remember to exchange twice on e5, with the knight first, then develop the other knight to d2. } { [%cal Gf3e5,Gd4e5,Gb1d2] } 5. Nxe5 (5. exd5? { Gives the advantage away. } 5... Qxd5! { [%cal Rd5e5,Rc6e5] } 6. Be3 exd4 (6... Bg4? { Lednicky, Martin - Svana, Peter, 1-0, SVK-chT2C 0708, 2008, https://lichess.org/Xb3pXqwh }) 7. cxd4 { Now White has an IQP but not the position to back it up and play that structure properly: The knight can't go to e5, the light-squared bishop isn't developed at all. } { [%cal Yf3e5] } 7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Qa5 9. Qb3 O-O $10) (5. Bb5 { Most common move here. Also playable. } 5... exd4 6. e5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 { [%cal Gb5c6,Gd4c6,Bc6e8] } 7... Bd7 8. O-O Be7 $14) 5... Nxe5 { If Black doesn't play Nxe5, White pins the knight as usual. } (5... Nxe4 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. O-O f5 $14) (5... dxe4 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3f7,Ge5f7] } 7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Nd5 9. Qxd5 c6 10. Qxe4 cxb5 11. Qxb7 $14) 6. dxe5 Nxe4 7. Nd2 (7. Be3?! Bc5 { This helps Black's development. } 8. Bxc5 Nxc5 { Jahn, Constanze - Schoetzig, Andreas, 1-0, Oberliga Ost-A 0607, 2007, https://lichess.org/dDz2eoEj }) 7... Qe7 { [%cal Re7e5] } 8. Nf3 c6 9. Bd3 Bg4 10. O-O $14 *


