1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 { This a rather rare move, but it's quite playable. It avoids the complications of the Qa4 lines. The downsides are: 1. Black doesn't really have to think. There are no traps, and almost every move is fine. 2. After a series of material exchanges, the resulting positions are very drawish.
Stockfish 9 on depth 50 says that this is the best move, slightly better than Qa4. } 4... Qxd5 5. d4 Bf5 { The following main line is a suggestion by Stockfish. It has never been played. } (5... exd4 { The main move here. Transposes to the Scotch Game/Göring Gambit } 6. cxd4 { Now we have an IQP position. Black's plan here is trade material off, so the isolani becomes an end game problem for White.
White's plan is to attack and to use the open c- and e-files for that. } { [%csl Bd4] } 6... Bg4 7. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3d5] } (7. Be2 Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Bb4+ 9. Nc3 Qc4 10. Qb3 Qxb3 11. axb3 Nge7 12. O-O O-O-O 13. Be3 $13) 7... Bb4 8. Be2 $13) (5... Bg4 6. Be2 O-O-O 7. c4 Qe4 (7... Qa5+) 8. Nbd2 Bb4 9. d5 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Kf1 (11. f3? Bxf3 12. gxf3 Qh4+ 13. Kf1 Qh3+ $17 (13... d3 14. Ne4 dxe2+ 15. Qxe2 f5 16. Ng5 Nf6 { Szegi, Tomas - Janos, Martin, 0-1, SVK-chT1W 0506, 2005, https://lichess.org/BsJpW0lW })) 11... Qxe2+ 12. Qxe2 Bxe2+ 13. Kxe2 $15) (5... Nf6 6. Nxe5 (6. Be3 exd4 (6... Bg4 7. Be2 O-O-O { Lednicky, Martin - Svana, Peter, 1-0, SVK-chT2C 0708, 2008, https://lichess.org/Xb3pXqwh } (7... Bd6 { Markovic, Vladimir - Vlatkovic, Sinisa, 1-0, Belgrade-chT Quality, 2011, https://lichess.org/dIkHHwsq })) 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Qa5 9. Qb3 O-O 10. Bc4 Bd6 11. Rd1 Qh5 12. Be2 Bg4 13. h3 Ne7 14. hxg4 Qxh1+ 15. Kd2 Qxg2 16. Rg1 Qh3 17. Ng5 Qh2 18. Nf3 Qh3 { Might be a draw per repetition. }) 6... Nxe5 7. Qe2 Ng4 8. h3 Qe6 9. Kd2 Nc4+ 10. Qxc4 Nxf2 11. Qxe6+ fxe6 12. Rg1 Bd6 13. Bc4 Bd7 $10) 6. dxe5 (6. Be3 exd4 7. cxd4 Bxb1 8. Qxb1 Bb4+ 9. Kd1 O-O-O 10. Qc2 Bc5 { Vlahovic, Svetozar - Vujosevic, Vladimir, 0-1, YUG-Cup 34th, 1991, https://lichess.org/BKHiWALf }) 6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 8. Nbd2 Nge7 9. Ke1 Ng6 10. Nc4 Ncxe5 11. Nfxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Re8 13. Bf4 Bd6 14. Kd2 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. Rd1 b5 17. Kc1 c6 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Rxd3 Rhe8 20. b3 Re2 21. Rd2 Kc7 22. Rhd1 R8e7 23. Rxe2 Rxe2 24. Rd2 Re1+ 25. Rd1 Rxd1+ 26. Kxd1 Kd6 27. Kd2 g5 28. Ke3 Kd5 29. g3 f6 30. g4 Ke5 31. a3 a5 32. c4 bxc4 33. bxc4 a4 34. f3 c5 35. h3 $10 { Just a draw. Black has more space, but no way to break through. } *


[Event "The Ponziani Guide: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3: 3…d5 4.Qa4 f6 - Steinitz"]
