1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Be7 { Romanishin Variation. This is way too passive. } 4. d4 exd4 (4... d6?! { White has now a wide range of options: } 5. Bd3 { [%cal Ge1g1] } (5. d5 Nb8) (5. Bb5) 5... Nf6 (5... Bg4 6. d5 Nb8) 6. d5 { This position can also arise from a Pirc defense: 1.d4 d6 2.e4 Nf6 3.Bd3 e5 4.c3 Nc6 5.Nf3 Be7 6.d5 } { Shirov, Alexei - Speelman, Jonathan S, 1-0, Lloyds Bank op 15th, 1991, https://lichess.org/vtm2aXzG } 6... Nb8 { What a sad move. } (6... Na5? 7. b4 c6 8. bxa5 cxd5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. exd5 $16) 7. c4 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 { Kacheishvili, Giorgi - Gelashvili, Tamaz, 0-1, GEO-ch 66th, 2007, https://lichess.org/lkzIiQhv } (8... Bxf3 { Vojinovic, Goran - Savicevic, Vlatko, 1-0, YUG-ch sf, 1996, https://lichess.org/Q0DuV6Rw })) (4... d5) 5. cxd4 { White can free the c3 square and develop easily. } 5... d5 6. exd5 { Now we have an IQP game. White either has to wait for Black's castling before they start an attack, or attack in the center immediately.
Generally speaking, the IQP holder is responsible for the attack and should not trade too many pieces, because the endgame would be worse.
See my IQP study for more on that: https://lichess.org/study/XKZQHZM8 } (6. e5) 6... Nb4 { [%cal Rb4d5,Rd8d5] } (6... Qxd5?!) 7. Bb5+ (7. Nc3) 7... Bd7 8. Bc4 { Strategically, White should avoid the material trade as mentioned earlier. } (8. Bxd7+?! { Still a good position, but against the spirit of the IQP play. } 8... Qxd7 9. Ne5 { The natural place for the knight in an IQP game. } (9. O-O { Sax, Gyula - Romanishin, Oleg M, 1/2-1/2, Tilburg, 1979, https://lichess.org/aV7NJdIV }) (9. Nc3 { Velimirovic, Dragoljub - Djuric, Stefan, 1/2-1/2, Banja Luka, 1985, https://lichess.org/EdaFLr9f }) 9... Qxd5 10. O-O Rd8 { White can now trade the IQP off: } 11. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3d5] } 11... Qxd4 { [%cal Rd4e5] } 12. Qxd4 { White can now trade the IQP off. } (12. Qe2 { [%cal Gf1d1] } 12... Qc5 13. a3 Nc2 { [%cal Rc2a1] } 14. Qxc2 Qxe5 15. Qa4+ { [%cal Ga4a7,Ga4e8] } 15... c6 16. Be3 $14 { [%cal Ge3a7,Ga1d1] } (16. Qxa7)) 12... Rxd4 13. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5c7,Gb5d4,Ge5d7,Ge5c4] } 13... Rd8 14. Nxc7+ Kf8 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Re7d6,Rd6e5,Rd6c7] } 15. Nf3 $10) *


