1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:58] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:27:15] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:30:03] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:27:40] } 3. c3 { [%clk 1:29:52] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:27:58] } 4. d3 { This is a rare move, and it's way too passive in my opinion. But there is a reason: If you play d4, you might get a Fraser Defense/Vukovic Gambit, and that's something where you have to know many only moves. See ➡ Fraser/Vukovic } { [%clk 1:30:21] } (4. d4 Nxe4 5. d5 Bc5! 6. dxc6 Bxf2+ 7. Ke2 Bb6 8. Qd5 Nf2 9. Rg1 O-O 10. cxb7 Bxb7 11. Qxb7 Qf6) 4... d5 { Just logical: If White doesn't occupy the center, then Black should do it. It's a similar situation as in the French Defense, just with reversed colors.
One idea here is that after dxe4 dxe4, Black can trade queens and then it's a completely equal and probably even drawish game. White can avoid that by either Nbd2 as played here or Qc2. exd5 is not good, because then Black can develop the queen, and White can't attack it, because c3 isn't free for the knight. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Rd8d1] [%clk 1:24:45] } 5. Nbd2 { [%clk 1:30:48] } (5. exd5?! Qxd5 6. Nbd2 Bf5 { [%cal Rf5d3,Rd5d3] }) 5... Be7 { [%clk 1:24:31] } (5... a5 { is the main move here, restricting White's play on the queen side. } 6. Be2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8. b3) 6. Be2 { [%clk 1:31:12] } (6. b4 { Since Black has not played a5, b4 is an interesting option. But, as indicated by 4.d3 already, Kadric seemed to go for a rather quiet game. For now. } { [%cal Gb4b5] } 6... O-O 7. b5 { Forcing the knight away from the center. } 7... Na5 (7... Nb8 8. Nxe5 a6) (7... dxe4 8. dxe4 Na5 9. Qc2) 8. Nxe5 dxe4 9. dxe4) 6... O-O { [%clk 1:24:06] } 7. O-O { [%clk 1:31:38] } (7. b4 { Last chance. Missed it. } 7... a6 8. O-O) 7... a5! { And now Black went finally for a5. } { [%clk 1:20:08] } 8. Re1 { [%clk 1:31:17] } 8... dxe4?! { Black decided to resolve the tension in the center. Probably too early. } { [%clk 1:19:34] } (8... Re8) 9. dxe4 { [%clk 1:31:28] } 9... Bc5 { Maybe withe idea of Ng4? } { [%cal Rf6g4,Rg4f2] [%clk 1:19:03] } 10. h3 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4] [%clk 1:29:26] } 10... h6 { [%clk 1:17:15] } 11. Qc2 { Get out of the queen trade threat. } { [%cal Rd8d1] [%clk 1:28:30] } 11... Be6 { [%clk 1:14:25] } 12. Nc4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc4e5,Gf3e5,Rc6e5] [%clk 1:19:10] } 12... Qe7 { Nice indirect protection of the pawn on e5. Now White can't take this pawn. } { [%clk 1:02:14] } 13. Ne3 { [%cal Ge3f5,Ge3d5] [%clk 1:18:24] } (13. Ncxe5? Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxf2+! 15. Kxf2 Qc5+! 16. Be3 Qxe5) 13... Rfd8 { [%clk 0:59:57] } 14. b3 { [%cal Gc1b2] [%clk 1:15:32] } 14... Nh5 { [%cal Rh5f4] [%clk 0:36:55] } 15. Bf1 { [%clk 0:55:34] } (15. Bb5) 15... Nf4 { [%clk 0:36:46] } 16. Nf5 { [%clk 0:53:21] } 16... Qf6 { [%clk 0:35:57] } 17. g3 { [%cal Gf1h3] [%clk 0:48:52] } 17... Ng6 { [%clk 0:33:14] } 18. Nh2 { [%clk 0:45:21] } 18... Bxf5 { [%clk 0:23:54] } 19. exf5 { [%clk 0:45:50] } 19... Nge7 { [%clk 0:24:21] } 20. Bd3 { [%clk 0:46:06] } 20... Rxd3! { [%clk 0:20:22] } 21. Qxd3 { [%clk 0:46:33] } 21... Rd8 { Mistake. Nxf5 was much stronger. The whole point of Rxd3 was to remove a defender from f5. } { [%clk 0:18:36] } (21... Nxf5 22. Qd5 Qd6 23. Qc4) 22. Qc4 { [%cal Gc4c5] [%clk 0:43:42] } 22... Bb6 { [%clk 0:18:51] } (22... Rd5) 23. Ng4 { [%clk 0:40:28] } 23... Qxf5 { [%clk 0:19:10] } 24. Bxh6! { Free pawn, because Black can't take back. } { [%clk 0:40:35] } 24... Bxf2+ { [%clk 0:13:32] } (24... gxh6?? 25. Nxh6+ { [%cal Gh6f5,Gh6g8] } 25... Kf8 26. Nxf5) (24... Rd3 25. Be3 Nd5 { [%cal Rd5e3,Rb6e3,Bd5b6] } 26. Bxb6 Nxb6) 25. Nxf2 { [%clk 0:41:02] } 25... gxh6 { [%clk 0:13:58] } 26. Rad1 { If you have two rooks, and your opponent has only one: Trade one pair off, because then you are the only one with a rook. } { [%clk 0:36:57] } 26... Rxd1 { [%csl Gh3][%cal Gf2h3] [%clk 0:13:01] } 27. Rxd1 { And here Black was already much worse. The only hope was to create some safety, for example by stepping off the open g-file … } { [%cal Gc4g4,Gg4g8] [%clk 0:37:24] } 27... Ng6? { Mistake. } { [%clk 0:12:35] } (27... Kf8 28. Kg2 { Freeing the knight. } { [%cal Gf2h3] } 28... Qg6) 28. Rf1 { [%clk 0:35:43] } 28... Qf3 { Mistake. This looks very desperate. } { [%cal Rf3g3] [%clk 0:09:17] } (28... Qe6 29. Qxe6 fxe6 30. Ng4 { [%cal Gg4h6] } 30... Kg7) 29. Ne4! { Hard to count all the threats that are coming with this move. } { [%cal Gc4f7,Gf1f7,Ge4f6,Ge4d2] [%clk 0:31:05] } 29... Qe3+ { [%clk 0:09:41] } 30. Kh2 { And now there are no checks anymore } { [%csl Gd3,Ge2,Bd2,Rf2][%cal Gc4e2,Be4d2,Rf1f2] [%clk 0:31:29] } 30... Nd8 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rd8f7] [%clk 0:09:34] } 31. Qxc7 { [%cal Gc7d8,Gc7f7] [%clk 0:27:46] } 31... Qd3? { Mistake. } { [%cal Rd3d8,Rd3f1] [%clk 0:09:31] } (31... Qxe4 32. Qxd8+ Nf8 33. Qf6) 32. Rf2 { [%clk 0:27:21] } (32. Nf6+) 32... Nf8 { [%clk 0:08:11] } 33. Nf6+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:27:22] } 1-0


