1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 { This is already the Vienna opening. The passive looking Nc3 prepares in fact a very sharp game. The idea behind the early protection of e4 is an improved King’s Gambit via f4: If the black queen ever lands on h4, it doesn’t threaten e4.
And aside from the many gambit lines we will see in this study, the Vienna Opening aims for a very strong center. } { [%cal Rd8h4,Bh4e4,Gc3e4] } 2... Nf6 3. f4 { This is what we are playing for. Exchange the f-pawn for Black's e-pawn, get a strong center, and an open the f-file for our rook. } { [%cal Gf1f7,Rf1c4,Rc4f7] } (3. g3 { Is a rather calm way to play this. I think it's not in the spirit of this great opening. }) 3... d5 { Black on the other hand should always try to open the center as soon as possible, so White doesn’t get this advantage. } 4. fxe5 Nxe4 *


