[UTCTime "01:21:53"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 { C26 Vienna Gambit } 3... exf4?! { This is one of the gambits you shouldn't accept. } 4. e5! { The core idea: Get a strong center while slowing down Black's development. } 4... Ng8 { The only reasonable move. } (4... Qe7 { Doesn't work: } 5. Qe2 Ng8 { Black has an additional problem now: The dark-squared bishop is boxed in. } { [%csl Bf8] } 6. Nf3 { Prevent checks. } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gf3h4,Re7h4] } (6. d4 { An interesting sideline and maybe even more in the spirit of this opening } 6... Qh4+ 7. Kd1 (7. Qf2?! { We don't want to trade! } 7... Qxf2+ 8. Kxf2 d6)) 6... Qe6 { Best move, according to Stockfish 10. The idea is 7…d5. } { [%cal Rd7d5] } (6... d6?? { Second most common move in this position on lichess. } 7. Nd5! { [%cal Gd5e7,Gd5c7] } 7... Qd7 8. Nxc7+ (8. exd6+ Kd8 (8... Qe6 9. Nxc7+ Kd7 10. Nxe6 $18) 9. dxc7+ Qxc7 10. Nxc7 $18) 8... Kd8 (8... Qxc7 9. exd6+ Qe7 10. dxe7) 9. Nxa8 $18) 7. d4 (7. Ng5?! Qf5 { Double attack. } { [%cal Rf5c2,Rf5g5] }) 7... d5 { We should not take with exd6, because that would just help Black's development. Which means, we are getting a semi-closed position for a while, and for that we need our knights. And that means we should protect our knight on c3 from getting pinned. Therefore … } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Rf8b4] } 8. a3 (8. exd6? Bxd6 { Not only does Black protect the pawn on f4 now, they also have a piece developed. }) 8... Ne7 9. Bxf4 $16 { White is a bit better here: More developed, castling long is the next step, and they have more space and control in the center. } { [%cal Ge1c1,Gd4c5,Ge5d6,Ge5f6,Gf3g5,Gc3b5] }) 5. Nf3 { Prevent any trouble on h4. This is always more important than taking back on f4! } { [%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] } 5... d6 (5... g5 { Black is trying to hold that pawn. } 6. d4 { We play d4 whenever we can. The whole idea of this opening is a strong center. } 6... d6 (6... g4 7. Bb5! { White gives the piece. } 7... gxf3 8. Qxf3 Qh4+ { The only decent move for Black. } 9. g3 fxg3 10. hxg3! { [%cal Gf3h1] } 10... Qxd4 11. Be3 Qxe5 12. O-O-O { Black is now up two pawns a piece. And yet, White is much better, because all pieces are in the game, and the king is very vulnerable. } 12... Nc6 13. Bf4 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gf4c7] } 13... Qg7 14. Rhe1+ { [%cal Gc3d5,Bd5e7] } 14... Be7 (14... Nce7? 15. Nd5 c6 16. Nc7+ Kd8 { The knight is protected. } { [%cal Gf4c7] } 17. Bxc6! { And White gives another piece. } 17... bxc6 18. Qxc6 { [%cal Ge1e8,Gc7e8,Gc6a8] } 18... Qg4 (18... Nxc6?? 19. Re8#) 19. Qc4 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gc7a8] }) 15. Nd5 { [%cal Gd5e7,Ge1e7,Gd5c7,Bc7e8,Bc7a8] } 15... Kf8 { Sidestepping the fork on c7. } 16. Nxc7 Rb8 $18) 7. h4 { Counter-attack. } { [%cal Gh4g5] } 7... g4 8. Ng5 h6 9. Nxf7! { White sacrifices the knight like in the 6…g4 line. } 9... Kxf7 10. Bxf4 Nc6 11. e6+! Ke8 (11... Bxe6 12. d5!)) (5... Nc6) (5... d5) (5... Bb4) (5... Be7) 6. d4 (6. Qe2 Be7 (6... dxe5 7. Qxe5+ Be6 8. Ng5 Nc6)) 6... dxe5 7. Qe2 { One of the signature moves in many lines of the Vienna: Pins the pawn, avoids a queen trade and prepares castling long. } { [%csl Be5,Rd1][%cal Ge2e8,Rd8d1,Ge1c1] } (7. dxe5? Qxd1+ 8. Nxd1 { This is not what White wants! }) (7. Nxe5? Qh4+! 8. Kd2 Qf2+ 9. Qe2 Qxd4+ 10. Ke1 Be6 $15 { Black is just better here. }) 7... Be7 (7... Nc6 8. Bxf4 Bb4 9. O-O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qd5 11. Nxe5 Nge7 12. Qh5 { [%cal Gh5f7,Ge5f7] } 12... Nxe5 13. Qxe5 { [%cal Ge5c7] } 13... Qxa2 14. Bd3 $14 (14. Qxg7? { Don't! g2 is weak. } 14... Bf5 15. Bb5+ c6 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. cxd3 Qa3+ 18. Kd2 Rg8 $17 { [%cal Gg8g2] })) 8. Qxe5 Nc6 9. Bb5 a6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Bxf4 Nf6 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Qxc7 Qxc7 14. Bxc7 $14 { This is good for White: One pawn up, and a better structure, and Black doesn't have enough pawns for a pawn storm against the white king. Black's compensation is the bishop pair. White should try to trade at least one bishop off prior to advancing their own pawns. } { [%csl Ba6,Bc6,Yc8,Ye7] } *


