1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 f5? { First played in Falkbeer - Anderssen, Berlin 1851, so I call it the Anderssen Gambit.
It's not good. } 3. exf5 { Gives White immediately a strong threat of Qh5+ } { [%cal Gd1h5,Gf5g6] } 3... Nf6 { And here White should try to keep the pawn. } { [%csl Bh5][%cal Rf6h5] } 4. g4 Bc5 (4... d5 { Most common move, an attempt to establish a strong center. } 5. g5! { The only move that keeps the advantage. The knight cannot move away, because Qh5+ is still a threat. } 5... c6 (5... Bxf5 6. gxf6 gxf6 7. Qf3 { And now we hunt that light-squared bishop. } { [%cal Gf3f5,Gf3d5,Bf3b7] } 7... Be6 (7... Bxc2?! 8. Nxd5 { [%cal Gf3f6,Gd5f6] } 8... Bg7 9. Nb4 { [%cal Gb4c2] } 9... Bg6 10. Qxb7 $18) 8. Bh3 Bf7) (5... Ne4? 6. Qh5+ Kd7 (6... Ke7 7. f6+ gxf6 8. d4 { A rather odd-looking move, heavily preferred by the engine. It prevents Nxg5 by Black. } { [%cal Gc1g5] } 8... Nxc3 (8... Nxg5 9. dxe5 h6 10. exf6+ Ke6 11. h4 Nf7 12. Bh3+ Kxf6 13. Bxc8 Qxc8 14. Nxd5+ Kg7 15. Ne2 { [%cal Gh1g1] } 15... Bd6 16. Rg1+ Kf8 17. Ndf4 $18 { [%cal Gf4g6] }) 9. gxf6+ { [%cal Gc1g5] } 9... Kd6 10. dxe5+ Kc6 11. bxc3 $18) (6... g6 7. fxg6 Qxg5 8. g7+ Qxh5 9. gxh8=Q $18) 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. d3 exd3 9. Bxd3 $18) 6. gxf6 Qxf6) 5. g5 O-O 6. gxf6 Qxf6 7. Qf3 Bb6 8. d3 c6 9. Ne4 Qe7 10. Bd2 d5 11. f6 Qc7 12. O-O-O dxe4 13. dxe4 Rxf6 14. Bc4+ Kh8 15. Qh5 Nd7 16. f4 Rf8 17. Nf3 Nf6 18. Qh4 Bg4 19. Nxe5 Bh5 20. Bc3 Be3+ 21. Kb1 Bxf4 22. Qxf4 Nd5 23. Rxd5 Rxf4 24. Rd7 Qc8 25. Ng6+ hxg6 26. Rxg7 Rf3 27. Be5 Qf8 28. Rf7+ Kg8 29. Rxf3+ Kh7 30. Rxf8 { 1-0 } 1-0


