[ChapterName "Kramnik - Ivanchuk, 2017 [Exchange/Rubinstein] 0-1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/V3830V46/X8UGaW42"]

{ This game in round 3.2 of the Tbilisi FIDE World Cup was very important for Kramnik: It was his best chance to qualify for the Candidates Tournament. See https://chess24.com/en/read/news/tbilisi-wc-3-2-carlsen-kramnik-naka-all-out. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 { The idea here is to block the development of Black's light-square bishop. That piece has no place outside of Black's setup now. Be6 would be awkward. There is however a price to pay which we will see in the next moves. } { [%csl Rf5,Rg4,Rh3][%cal Rd3f5,Rd1g4,Rg2h3] } (4. c4 { c4 is the most common move here, transposing to the Panov Attack. Bd3 comes next. }) 4... Nc6 { d4 under pressure now. Nf3 would go against the idea of White's placement of the light-square bishop: It would give Black g4 for the bishop. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 5. c3 (5. Nf3 Bg4 6. c3 { And now c3 has to be played anyway. }) 5... Nf6 { The idea is to support Black's bishop on g4 } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gf6g4,Gc8g4] } (5... e5 { Black can now play e5, a move that Black is often aiming for in the Caro-Kann. } 6. dxe5 Nxe5 { [%cal Ge5d3] } 7. Nf3?! { Rare move, trading the bishop for a knight. } (7. Qe2 { [%cal Re2d3,Re2e5] } 7... Qe7 8. Bb5+ Bd7 (8... Nc6 9. Be3) 9. Na3 { [%cal Ra3b5,Rb5c7] } (9. Bxd7+ Nxd7) 9... Nc6 $10) 7... Nxd3+ (7... Nc6 8. O-O { Bernard, Ryszard - Jeske, Eckhard, 0-1, Rostock-A 08th, 2017, https://lichess.org/jHIEKWo1 }) 8. Qxd3) 6. Bf4 { B13 Caro-Kann Defense: Exchange Variation, Rubinstein Variation } { Main move in this position. Prevents e5 and Qc7, the natural place for Black's queen, and Rb8 here. } { [%csl Rb8,Rc7][%cal Rf4b8] } (6. h3 { Protect g4. The price is a slightly exposed pawn which can be a target for sacrifices later if White castles short. } { [%csl Bg4] } 6... e5 { See 5...e5. Same idea. } 7. dxe5 Nxe5) (6. Nf3 Bg4 7. O-O Qc7 $10) 6... Bg4 { Trying to provoke f3, which would be a mistake, because it would weaken White's king side. } 7. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3b7] } 7... Qc8 { This is already a bit uncomfortable for Black: The rook on a8 is immobilized, d5 needs better protection. } 8. Nd2 { Prepare to develop the knight from g1 without doubled pawns in case of a trade. Looks like White wants to castle long, but that is not the idea here. } { [%csl Rf3][%cal Rg1f3,Rd2f3] } (8. h3 Bh5 { This gives White the f5 square } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Rd3f5] } 9. Nd2) 8... e6 { Prepare castling. } 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O Bh5 { Prepare Bg6. } (10... O-O 11. Rfe1 Nh5 12. Be3) 11. Rae1 (11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 O-O 13. Rfe1 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 $10) (11. Rfe1 O-O 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 $10) 11... Bg6 { As we have seen in the previous sidelines, this is a very typical move in this position. The ideas is to prevent any attacks on h7 later, for example after trading the knight on f6 off and moving the queen to c2. } 12. Bxg6 { Almost the only move. If White goes away, Black owns a very nice diagonal, and they can push the queen side pawns with a tempo. } (12. Bb5?! a6 13. Be2 O-O) 12... hxg6 { [%csl Re2][%cal Rb3b5,Rb5e2] } 13. h4 { A very rare and ambitious move. Maybe too ambitious? } (13. Qb5 a6 14. Qe2) (13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 (14. dxe5 { Horvath, Alexander - Atakisi, Fatih, 1/2-1/2, WC30/sf02, 2006, https://lichess.org/jWWwr7YK }) 14... Qc6 { Clear c8 for the rook. } 15. a4 { Teichmeister, Dr. Sven - Zhak, Boris Mikhailovich, 1/2-1/2, MT-Simagin (RUS), 2008, https://lichess.org/2pMupgl0 } (15. Qd1 { Kayser, Felix - Schlapp, Thomas, 1/2-1/2, Frankfurt-ch, 2008, https://lichess.org/OjPGHGMU })) 13... a6 { Do not allow White's queen to reroute to e2 via b5. } { [%csl Gb5] } 14. c4 { The idea is to find a new way to get the queen to the king side. Still, it gives up control over b4 which now has to be protected by a3, an additional move that takes a tempo. White is slowing down its own play here. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Rb3d3,Ge7b4,Gc6b4] } (14. Qb6 { Suggestion by the engine. Looks interesting, but I don't see how the queen will help an attack on the king side from here. }) (14. g3 { Support the h4-pawn. }) 14... a5 { Keep control over b4 even if c5 is played. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gc6b4,Ga5b4] } (14... dxc4 { Not a good idea. Playable, but a bit annoying for Black. } 15. Nxc4 { [%csl Rb6][%cal Rc4b6,Rb6c8,Rb6a8] } 15... Nd5 { [%csl Bb6][%cal Gd5b6,Rc4b6,Rb3b6,Rc4d6] } 16. Bg5 { An attempt to remove the defender for d6! } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Rc4d6,Rd6e8,Rd6c8] } 16... Qd7 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 $10) 15. a3 (15. c5) 15... a4 { Doesn't only push the queen away – that piece would have moved anyway – but also prevents the knight from going to b3 where it could protect d4. } { [%cal Rd2b3] } 16. Qd3 O-O 17. c5?! { It looks like it's blocking Black's bishop, but that pawn can be attacked too easily. And that's what happens next. } (17. Rc1 Qd8 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd8d4,Gc6d4,Gf6e4] } 18. Bg5 Qb6 { Not really a threat to take b2. After Rb1, the pawn on b7 would fall, and Black's queen would be stuck on an awkward position. } { [%cal Gb6b2] } 19. c5 Qc7 $10) 17... b6 18. cxb6 Qb7 19. Bc7?! { That a very futile attempt to cling to that pawn. } (19. Rc1 { This was the only line that would have kept the game equal. } 19... Qxb6 20. Rc2 { [%cal Rf1c1,Rc2c6] } 20... Nh5 { [%cal Gh5f4] } 21. Be5 Rfc8 22. Rfc1 Nf6 $10) 19... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb7b6] } 20. Rc1 (20. g3 Nxb6 21. Bf4) 20... Rfc8 21. b4?! (21. g3 Nxb6 22. Bf4) 21... axb3 22. Qxb3 { [%cal Rb3b6] } 22... Bxa3 { Now take a moment and compare the pawn structures. Black's pawns are connected, not attacked and built towards the center. White's pawns … are loose. } 23. Rc3 (23. Ra1 { Better than Rc3. } 23... Be7 24. Rxa8 Rxa8 25. Rb1 { [%cal Rb3b6,Rb1b6] } 25... Nb4! 26. Ne5 Nxb6) 23... Be7 (23... Bf8 { Get out of the way of the Ra1 threat and protect the only slightly weak pawn. }) 24. Rfc1?! { (-0.22 → -0.85) Inaccuracy. Best move was Rb1. } (24. Rb1 Ra3 25. Qb2 Rxc3 26. Qxc3 Nb4 27. Rxb4 Nxb6 28. Rxb6 Qxb6 29. Bxb6 Rxc3 30. Ba5 Ra3) 24... Nb4 { [%csl Ga2][%cal Gb4a2,Ga2c1,Ga2c3] } 25. Ne5 (25. Bg3 Rxc3 26. Rxc3 Qxb6) 25... Nxe5 (25... Nxb6?! 26. Bxb6 Rxc3 27. Qxc3 Qxb6 28. Ndf3) 26. Bxe5 Rxc3 27. Qxc3 Qxb6 { [%cal Gb6d4,Gb4a2] } 28. Nf3 { -1 now. } 28... Qd8 (28... f6 29. Bh2 Qa6) (28... Na2? 29. Qc7 { [%cal Gc7b6] } 29... Qb5 30. Ra1 $15) 29. Qb3 (29. Qc7 Nd3 { [%cal Gd3c1,Gd3e5] } 30. Rc3 Nxe5 31. Nxe5 f6 32. Qxd8+ Bxd8 33. Nxg6 Bb6) 29... Rc8 30. Ra1 Rc4 { [%cal Ge7h4] } 31. g3 Qc8 { [%cal Gc4c1,Gc1g1] } 32. Kg2 Nc6 { Threat is f6 to push the bishop away, followed by Nxd4. } { [%cal Gf7f6] } 33. Qb5 Bf8 (33... f6 { I don't know why Ivanchuk didn't play this. It looks like he prepared exactly the following line. } 34. Bf4 Nxd4 35. Nxd4 Rxd4 { Now Black is two pawns up, one is a passer. Maybe the rest wasn't clear for him? These next moves are probably hard to find. } 36. Ra7 { [%cal Ra7e7] } 36... Rb4 37. Qa5 Qc5 38. Qa6 { [%cal Ra6e6] } 38... Rb6 39. Qd3 { [%cal Rd3g6] } 39... Rb2 { [%cal Gc5f2,Gb2f2,Gc5a7] } 40. Be3 Qc6) 34. Ra4 (34. Qa6 Qxa6 35. Rxa6 f6 36. Bf4 Kf7 37. Nd2 { [%cal Rd2c4] } 37... Rc1 { [%cal Rc1d1,Rd1d4] } 38. Be3 Rc2) 34... Rxa4 35. Qxa4 Nb4 (35... Qd7 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gd7a4] } 36. Qb3 f6 37. Bf4 Bb4 38. Qd3 { [%cal Rd3g6] } 38... Kf7) 36. Qb5?! { (-0.84 → -1.35) Inaccuracy. Best move was Bf4. } (36. Bf4 f6 37. Bd2 Nc6 38. Qc2 Qe8 39. Qb1 Bd6 40. Qb7 Ne7 41. Bb4 Qc8 42. Qxc8+ Nxc8) 36... Qc2 37. Qf1 Qe4 38. Qe1 f6 39. Bc7 Nc2 40. Qxe4 dxe4 41. Nd2 f5 42. Nb3 Ne1+ 43. Kf1 Nf3 44. Ke2 Kf7 45. Bb6 Bb4 46. Ke3 Ke8 47. Bc5 Bc3 48. Ba3 Kf7 49. Bd6 Kf6 50. Bc7 Ke7 51. Bb8 Bb2 52. Bf4 Kd8 53. Bd6 Kd7 54. Bf8 Kc6 55. Bxg7 Kd5 56. Bf6 Bc3 57. Ke2? { (-1.47 → -2.72) Mistake. Best move was Bg7. } (57. Bg7 Kc4 58. Nc5 Nxd4 59. Bf8 Kd5 60. Nd7 e5 61. Nb6+ Ke6 62. Nc4 Nb3 63. Ke2 Nc1+) 57... Kc4 58. Nc5? { (-1.96 → -3.68) Mistake. Best move was Nc1. } (58. Nc1 Bb2 59. Kd1 Nh2 60. Bg5 Ng4 61. Ke2 Bxd4 62. f3 exf3+ 63. Kxf3 e5 64. Ke2 Nf2) 58... e5! { What a move! White can't take. The best move here is actually a knight sacrifice on e4. } 59. Nd7? { (-3.32 → -5.21) Mistake. Best move was Nxe4. } (59. Nxe4 fxe4 60. dxe5 Bxe5 61. Bd8) (59. dxe5? Kxc5) (59. Bxe5? Bxd4) 59... exd4 60. Bd8?? { (-4.79 → -11.26) Blunder. Best move was Kd1. } (60. Kd1 Be1) 60... d3+ 61. Kd1 Bd4 62. Bb6? { (-8.33 → -10.68) Mistake. Best move was Nb6+. } (62. Nb6+ Kb3) 62... Bxb6? { (-10.68 → -8.96) Mistake. Best move was Ne5. } (62... Ne5) 63. Nxb6+ Kd4 64. Nc8 Ne5 65. Ne7? { (-7.04 → -10.29) Mistake. Best move was Nd6. } (65. Nd6 Ng4) 65... Ng4 66. Ke1 Kc3 67. Nd5+ Kb3 68. Kd2 Nxf2 69. h5?! { (-9.20 → -11.78) Inaccuracy. Best move was Ne3. } (69. Ne3 Ng4) 69... gxh5 70. Ne3 h4 71. Nxf5 h3 { White resigns. } { Mate in 24 moves. } 0-1


