1. e4 { [%clk 1:39:58] } 1... c6 { [%clk 1:39:53] } 2. d4 { [%clk 1:39:56] } 2... d5 { [%clk 1:39:46] } 3. e5 { [%clk 1:39:54] } 3... c5 { A bit early. Main move is Bf5 here, followed by e6, but c5 is also common. The idea is to play Bxc5 later to give the black square bishop a field and to castle king side. } { [%clk 1:39:38] } 4. Ne2!? { If Black's bishop were on f5 already, White would have responded to that with Ne2 or Nf3, and now it would play Be3 here, almost forcing Black to play cxd5, and then take with the knight, harassing the f5 bishop. } { [%clk 1:38:05] } 4... Nc6 { [%clk 1:37:34] } 5. c3 { [%clk 1:37:52] } 5... Bg4 { A very unusual position for the light square bishop in an Advanced Caro-Kann. But … d4 is now almost hanging. If White does nothing, Black can play cxd4 cxd4 and White has nothing better than e6. } { [%clk 1:33:31] } 6. h3?! { Be3 would have been stronger, protecting d4 and developing a piece. } { [%clk 1:14:28] } 6... Bxe2 { Better was retreating the bishop to d7. This move just helps White developing his pieces. } { [%clk 1:31:08] } (6... Bd7 7. Nd2 Rc8) 7. Bxe2 { [%clk 1:13:29] } 7... e6 { [%clk 1:31:02] } 8. O-O { [%clk 1:12:34] } 8... Qb6?! { Forces White's next move, because Be3 isn't possible anymore. Exchanging the pawns first in order to develop Black's knight first was another option. } { [%clk 1:18:01] } (8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Nge7) 9. dxc5 { [%clk 1:10:50] } 9... Bxc5 { [%clk 1:17:09] } 10. b4 { Quite commital. Weakens White's queen side a bit, but now the black square bishop can move.. } { [%clk 1:10:27] } 10... Be7 { [%clk 1:14:26] } 11. Be3 { [%clk 1:10:01] } 11... Qc7 { [%clk 1:12:57] } 12. f4 { [%clk 1:09:53] } 12... Nh6 { The only way for Black to castle soon. } { [%clk 1:11:29] } 13. Na3 { [%clk 1:04:56] } 13... a6 { Prevent Nb5. } { [%clk 1:09:54] } 14. Bd3 { [%clk 1:01:35] } (14. Nc2 O-O) 14... O-O { [%clk 1:07:16] } 15. Nc2 { [%clk 1:01:01] } 15... f6 { [%clk 1:05:05] } 16. Nd4 { [%clk 1:00:09] } 16... Nxd4 { [%clk 1:03:24] } 17. Bxd4 { [%clk 0:54:48] } 17... fxe5 { [%clk 1:01:56] } 18. Bxe5 { [%clk 0:53:19] } 18... Bd6 { [%clk 1:01:18] } 19. Bxd6 { [%clk 0:53:14] } 19... Qxd6 { [%clk 1:01:11] } 20. Qd2 { [%clk 0:53:08] } 20... Nf5 { [%clk 0:52:28] } 21. Rae1 { [%clk 0:52:27] } (21. Rf3 a5 22. Rb1) 21... Rac8 { [%clk 0:50:03] } (21... Ng3!? { Does nothing: } 22. Rf3 Nh5 23. g3) 22. Re5 { [%clk 0:48:57] } 22... Rf6?! { Not sure about this move. Disconnects the rooks, and e6 could also be protected by the knight. } { [%clk 0:39:44] } (22... g6 23. g4 Ng7) 23. Rfe1 { [%clk 0:44:45] } 23... g6 { [%clk 0:28:54] } 24. Bxf5 { [%clk 0:31:25] } 24... gxf5 { [%clk 0:27:53] } 25. Qe3 { [%clk 0:31:05] } 25... Rc6 { Now everything is focused on e6. } { [%clk 0:27:14] } 26. a4 { [%clk 0:24:04] } 26... Qc7! { Nice! move the focus to White's c-pawn. } { [%clk 0:23:46] } 27. c4 { [%clk 0:19:47] } (27. Qf2 { Engine suggestion. }) 27... Rxc4 { [%clk 0:19:57] } 28. Rxe6 { [%clk 0:19:10] } 28... Re4 { [%clk 0:19:38] } 29. Qg3+ { [%clk 0:15:22] } 29... Qg7 { [%clk 0:18:49] } 30. Re8+ { [%clk 0:15:07] } 30... Rf8 { [%clk 0:18:42] } 31. Qxg7+ { [%clk 0:14:41] } 31... Kxg7 { [%clk 0:18:37] } 32. R1xe4 { [%clk 0:10:09] } 32... fxe4 { [%clk 0:18:30] } 33. Rxf8 { [%clk 0:09:51] } 33... Kxf8 { [%clk 0:18:24] } 34. Kf2 { [%clk 0:09:45] } 34... d4 { [%clk 0:18:16] } 35. g4 { [%clk 0:09:36] } 35... Kf7 { [%clk 0:18:04] } 36. h4 { [%clk 0:09:22] } 36... h5 { [%clk 0:16:57] } 37. gxh5 { [%clk 0:08:53] } 37... Kf6 { [%clk 0:16:50] } 38. h6 { [%clk 0:08:33] } 38... Kg6 { [%clk 0:16:46] } 39. f5+ { [%clk 0:08:28] } 39... Kxh6 { [%clk 0:16:39] } 40. a5 { [%clk 0:58:23] } 40... Kh5 { [%clk 1:06:34] } 41. Ke2 { [%clk 0:58:19] } 41... Kh6 { [%clk 1:06:28] } 42. Kf2 { [%clk 0:58:17] } 42... Kh5 { [%clk 1:06:22] } 43. Ke2 { [%clk 0:58:14] } 43... Kh6 { [%clk 1:06:13] } 44. Kf2 { ½-½ The game is a draw. } { [%clk 0:58:10] } 1/2-1/2


