1. e4 c6 { B10 Caro-Kann Defense } 2. Ne2 Qa5 { A "novelty". Prevents d4 temporarily, but doesn't help Black otherwise. There is a Qa5+ *late* in the Gurgenidze System, and another one when the CK transposes to the Czech defense. But here … no idea. } (2... d5 { normal continuation } 3. e5 c5 4. d4) 3. c4 (3. Nbc3 { Probably the best response. Develops a piece and ends the queen's pin of the d-pawn. } 3... d5 4. d4 dxe4 5. Ng3 f5 { Protects the pawn, but still no piece development. And it's passive. } (5... Nf6 6. Bc4 Bf5 { Get the bishop out, so e6 can be played. } 7. O-O e6) 6. f3 exf3 7. Qxf3 g6) 3... Nf6 4. Nbc3 e5 5. f4 { Attempt to weaken Black's center. } 5... exf4 { d6 was another option, but then Black's black-squared bishop would have been very passive. } 6. Nxf4 Bb4 { This has two purposes: 1. an exchange on c3 would create a doubled pawn for White now (and weaken e4), and 2. d6 can be played now without locking the bishop in. On the other hand … it looks a little bit like an improvised justification for the oddly placed queen. } 7. Bd3 { Seems logical, but the engine prefers Nd3 here. e4 is poisoned! No need to protect it with the bishop. Also, White's d-pawn cannot move now and with that the black-squared bishop is locked for a long time. Bd3 is a common motif in the CK, but you have to advance the d-pawn first. } (7. Nd3 Bxc3 8. dxc3 { Nxe4 doesn't look so good … } 8... O-O (8... Nxe4?? { Now White has a very nice attack. } 9. Qg4 Kd8!? 10. Qxg7!? Re8 11. Be2 Qf5) 9. e5 Ne4 10. Be2 d6 11. exd6 Nxd6) 7... d6 { Obvious move. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Kh1 { Goes out of the way of the check from c5. But … that would be just one check, no serious threat. Too passive. } (9. Qe1 { Make White's pieces slightly more mobile and protect the e-pawn once more, because after Black's castling it isn't poisoned anymore. } 9... Re8 10. Bc2 { Make room for the d-pawn. But c4 is hanging now. } 10... Nbd7 11. d3) 9... Bg4?! { Aggressive, but it helps White. The queen had to go to e1 anyway, see the comment on the previous move. } (9... Bxc3 { That would have been the logical next step. } 10. bxc3 Re8) 10. Qe1 Nbd7 { Connect the rooks and the knights. Nc5 might also be annoying in the future. } 11. Bc2 { Finally make room for the d-pawn. } 11... Rae8 { The threat is now Bf4. Not really dangerous, because White has d3. } (11... Bxc3 { We are all waiting for this move. But … no. }) 12. Qg3?! { Running away is not the way to go. Yes, it prevents the knight on f6 from taking e4, but almost every piece in White's position is now immobilized. } { (0.08 → -0.52) Inaccuracy. Best move was d3. } (12. d3 d5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Bd2 dxe4 15. dxe4 Bf5 16. a3 Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Qb5 18. Bd3 Qb3) 12... Bxc3?! { Finally. But maybe too late. Nc5 (see comment on move 10) would have been more dangerous now. } { (-0.52 → -0.01) Inaccuracy. Best move was Nc5. } (12... Nc5 13. Nh3) 13. dxc3 { And now White has an IQP that will be a liability for the rest of the game. } (13. bxc3 Nc5 14. Nh3) 13... Be6 { This gives the knight on f6 its mobility back. } 14. b3 Qe5 15. Ne2 { The pawn on e4 is poisoned again. } 15... Bg4 (15... Nxe4? 16. Qxe5 dxe5 17. Bxe4) 16. Bf4?! { Exchanging queens would have better here for White, but it's a hard decision: Black has a better pawn structure and its pieces are more active. Not easy to risk an endgame here. } { (0.04 → -0.46) Inaccuracy. Best move was Qxe5. } (16. Qxe5 Rxe5 17. Nd4 Nxe4 18. Bf4 Nxc3 19. h3 c5 20. Bxe5 Nxe5 21. Nb5 Nxb5 22. cxb5 Be2) 16... Qh5 17. Nd4 Nc5 { Finally! } 18. h3 Be2 19. Nf5?! { Not a convincing threat, but it's easy to see why this idea was so attractive. } { (-0.11 → -0.61) Inaccuracy. Best move was Nxe2. } (19. Nxe2 Qxe2 20. Rac1 Nh5 21. Qh4 Nxf4 22. Qxf4 Re6 23. Rfe1 Qh5 24. Rcd1 Rf6 25. Qg3 Rg6) 19... g6 20. Nxd6 Bxf1 21. Nxe8 Bxg2+ 22. Qxg2 Rxe8 { White has now the bishop pair, but its king looks very naked. } 23. Re1 { Too passive again! } (23. e5! { That would have been an active move. } 23... Nfd7 24. Re1 Ne6) 23... Qh4 24. Bg3 Qh6 25. Bh2 Rd8 26. Re2?! { Way too passive. } { (-0.60 → -1.13) Inaccuracy. Best move was e5. } (26. e5 Nh5 (26... Rd2?? { Doesn't work. } 27. exf6 Rxg2 28. Re8+ Qf8 29. Rxf8+ Kxf8 30. Bd6+ Ke8 31. Kxg2 { Resignable. }) 27. Bg1 Nf4 28. Qg3 Rd2 29. Bxc5 Rxc2) 26... Ne6 27. Rf2 Qe3 28. Rf3 { Too passive. } (28. Rxf6 Rd2 29. Qf3 Qe1+ 30. Qf1 Qxf1+ 31. Rxf1 Rxc2 32. Rd1 { Still better for Black, but not yet a catastrophe for White. }) 28... Qe1+ 29. Qg1?! { (-1.45 → -1.97) Inaccuracy. Best move was Qf1. } (29. Qf1 Qxf1+ 30. Rxf1 Rd2 31. Bb1 Rb2 32. Bd6 Ng5 33. Ba3 Re2 34. Rxf6 Re1+ 35. Kg2 Rxb1) 29... Qh4?! { (-1.97 → -1.10) Inaccuracy. Best move was Qd2. } (29... Qd2 30. Bb1 Nh5 31. h4 Qe2 32. Re3 Qd1 33. e5 Qxg1+ 34. Bxg1 Rd1 35. Be4 Rd2 36. a4) 30. Qf2 Qg5 31. Qg2?! { (-1.04 → -1.57) Inaccuracy. Best move was Re3. } (31. Re3 Nh5 32. b4 b6 33. Ba4 c5 34. Bc2 Nhf4 35. h4 Qg4 36. a3 Nh5 37. Be5 Nef4) 31... Nh5 32. Qxg5 Nxg5 33. Rd3?! { (-1.64 → -2.44) Inaccuracy. Best move was Rf1. } (33. Rf1 Nxh3 34. Rf3 Rd2 35. Rxh3 Rxc2 36. Rd3 Rxa2 37. Rd8+ Kg7 38. Rd7 b6 39. Be5+ Kf8) 33... Rxd3 34. Bxd3 Nxh3 35. Bc2 Nf6?! { (-2.23 → -1.59) Inaccuracy. Best move was N5f4. } (35... N5f4 36. Bg3 Kg7 37. Be1 Kf6 38. Bd2 Ne6 39. Be3 Nhf4 40. Bxa7 Ne2 41. Kg2 Nxc3 42. a4) 36. Bb8?! { (-1.59 → -2.37) Inaccuracy. Best move was Kg2. } (36. Kg2 Ng5 37. e5 Nd7 38. b4 Kg7 39. a4 Ne6 40. a5 a6 41. Kh3 h5 42. c5 Kh7) 36... a6 37. Kg2 Ng5 38. e5 Nfe4 39. a4 Nxc3 40. b4 Ne6 41. Kf2? { (-1.88 → -3.60) Mistake. Best move was Ba7. } (41. Ba7) 41... Nd4 42. Bd3 Nd1+ { White resigns. } 0-1


