{ This is not a finished study. I will work continuously on it, add new theory lines, comments and instructive games. So come back from time to time and see what's new! } { The study has now reached a first complete version. Improvements and additions will be made on a continuous basis. }
1. d4 (1. c4 b5 { Halibut Gambit. Follows similar ideas and can even transpose into a Benko. }) 1... Nf6 2. c4 c5 { Black should have backup plans for cases when White doesn't play d5. } 3. d5 { Now White has a strong center, but rather weak dark squares. That's the reason why Black usually fianchettoes their dark-squared bishop: it's control over the a1-h8 diagonal will be very strong. } { [%csl Bd4,Be5][%cal Gg7a1] } (3. Nf3 { English Opening/Symmetrical Variation/Anti-Benoni Variation. This is quite okay for Black. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d5! 6. cxd5 Bc5 { the Vaganian gambit } 7. N5c3 O-O) (3. e3 g6 4. Nc3 (4. Nf3 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 { transposes. }) (4. dxc5 Na6 5. a3 Nxc5 6. b4 Ne6 7. Bb2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O) 4... Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 8. O-O Nc6 { a reversed Tarrasch defence }) (3. dxc5 e6 4. Nf3 Bxc5 5. e3 O-O 6. a3 b6 7. Be2 Bb7 8. O-O d5) 3... b5 { A57 Benko Gambit, also known as Volga Gambit. Challenges White's center immediately. } (3... e6 { A60 Modern Benoni. }) 4. cxb5 { d5 is now a weak pawn and a target for Black later in the game. } { [%csl Bd5] } (4. Nf3 { Declined/Main Line } 4... g6 (4... Bb7)) (4. Nd2 { Declined/Quiet Line }) (4. a4 { Declined/Sosonko Variation }) (4. Bg5 { Declined/Bishop Attack }) (4. f3 { Declined/Pseudo-Saemisch }) (4. e4 { Declined/Hjoerring Countergambit }) (4. g4 { Mutkin Countergambit } 4... Nxg4 5. e4 d6 6. cxb5 g6 7. h3 Nf6) (4. Qc2 bxc4 5. e4 d6 6. Bxc4) (4. Nc3 b4) (4. g3 d6 5. Bg2) (4. e3 bxc4 (4... g6 5. cxb5 a6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. a4 O-O) (4... Bb7) 5. Bxc4 g6 6. Nc3 d6 { Van Foreest, Jorden - Fedorov, Alex, 1-0, 21st European Teams, 2017, https://lichess.org/jL5JNuBi }) (4. b3?! { Very rare. Played in https://lichess.org/q4kDUgCO/black#7 against me. } 4... g6 (4... e6) 5. Bb2 Bg7 6. e4 O-O { Just wait. } (6... d6 7. cxb5 a6 8. Nd2 O-O { Ponomarenko, Vi - Moiseev, Vik, 0-1, Tula GM 2018, https://lichess.org/y11KMpjq }) 7. e5 (7. Bd3 bxc4 8. bxc4 d6 { Black has a harmonious piece setup here and is probably already equal. Plans are e6 to break up the center and Nbd7 to b6 to add pressure on c4. } { [%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6,Gb6c4,Ge7e6] }) 7... Ne8 $10) 4... a6 { Accepted } 5. bxa6 { Fully Accepted Variation. The compensation for Black's pawn is control over the a- and b-files, a very solid pawn structure after d6 and g6, and after the dark-squared bishop is on g7 a lot of pressure on the queenside. That, and the lead in development is enough for a good game. } { [%csl Bh7,Bg6,Bf7,Be7,Bd6,Bc5][%cal Ga8a3,Gg7c3,Gd7d6,Gg7g6,Gb7b3,Gb8d7] } (5. e3 { Modern Variation }) (5. Nc3 { Zaitsev System } 5... axb5 6. e4 (6. Nxb5) 6... b4 7. Nb5 { Zaitsev Variation/Nescafe Frappe Attack }) (5. b6 { Pawn Return Variation }) (5. f3 { Dlugy Variation. Prepare to play e4 as soon as possible. } { [%cal Re2e4] } 5... axb5 6. e4 Qa5+ 7. Bd2 b4 8. Na3! d6 9. Nc4 Qd8) 5... g6 { There is no need to capture on a6 immediately. Sometimes it is better to bring the light-squared bishop to f5, and then Black takes the pawn on a6 with the rook or in some rare cases with the knight.
The point is that White wants to bring the rook to b2 to step out of the pin by Black's dark-squared bishop. And then Black's light-squared bishop can attack that rook from f5. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Bc8f5,Bf5b1,Ra1b1,Gg7b2] } (5... Bxa6?! 6. Nc3 (6. g3! { the best way to punish Black's imprecise move order } 6... d6 7. Bg2 g6 8. b3 Bg7 9. Bb2 $14 { the double fianchetto variation, easy to play as White }) 6... d6 (6... g6 7. Nf3 d6 8. g3 Bg7 9. Bg2 { Fianchetto Variation }) 7. e4 { Yugoslav without 7...Bxf1 } (7. Nf3 g6 8. g3 { Different move order for the Fianchetto Variation }) 7... Bxf1 8. Kxf1 g6 9. g3 (9. Nge2 { Yugoslav with 7...Bxf1, Nge2 }) 9... Bg7 10. Kg2 O-O 11. Nf3 { King Walk Variation }) 6. Nc3 { The idea is e4. And now Black often takes on a6 to prevent that. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rc3e4,Re2e4] } (6. a7 Rxa7) 6... Bxa6 { [%cal Ga6f1] } (6... Bg7? 7. e4 $16 O-O 8. Nf3 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bxa6 10. Be2 (10. Bxa6 Qxa6 { [%cal Ga6f1] }) 10... d6) 7. e4 { is the main move, but there are some problems, as we will see soon. } (7. f4 { Central Storming Variation }) (7. g3) (7. Nf3 { Waiting with the decision for e4 or g3. } 7... d6 (7... Bg7 8. g3 d6 { Just a slightly different move order. }) 8. g3 { Fianchetto Variation } (8. e4 Bxf1 9. Kxf1 { transposes to the text, the King Walk variation. }) 8... Bg7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. Rb1 (10. O-O Nb6) 10... O-O 11. O-O) 7... Bxf1! 8. Kxf1 { And now White can't castle anymore. White's plan is now to play g3 or h3 and hide the king there, but that is rather slow. } { [%csl Rg2][%cal Rg2g3,Rf1g2] } 8... d6 9. Nf3 (9. g3 Bg7 10. Kg2 O-O 11. Nf3 { Accepted/King Walk Variation }) 9... Bg7 (9... Nbd7) 10. g3 (10. h3 Nbd7 11. Kg1 O-O 12. Kh2 { King Walk variation, Kh2 line (it should really be called the Nenashev line). }) 10... O-O 11. Kg2 { King Walk variation, Kg2 line, also called the Classical Main Line. } 11... Nbd7 12. Re1 (12. h3 Ra6) (12. a4) 12... Ng4 (12... Ra6) (12... Qa5) 13. Qe2 (13. Nd2) (13. Re2) 13... Nge5 (13... Qa5) 14. Nxe5 (14. Nd2 Nb6 15. f4 (15. a4) 15... Ned7 16. a4 (16. Nf3 Na4 (16... Ra7)) 16... Ra7 (16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nxa4 (17... Rxa4 18. Rxa4 Nxa4 19. c4) 18. c4 (18. Qd3 Nab6 19. Bb2 Qc7 { Strunski, Andreas - Vasilev, Milen, 1/2-1/2, Neuhausen op, 2008, https://lichess.org/t3PjZZEB })) 17. a5 Qa8 18. Qb5 (18. a6 { [%cal Gc3b5] } 18... Bxc3 19. bxc3 Nb8 20. c4 Rxa6 21. Rxa6 Qxa6 22. e5 Qa2 { Romanova, Inna - Rohonyan, Katerina, 0-1, UKR tt (Women), 2003, https://lichess.org/4ZXy5QkO }) 18... Rb8 19. axb6 Rxa1 20. Qxd7 Rxb6 (20... Bxc3 21. bxc3 Qa2 22. Qc7 Rxb6 23. Qxb6 Rxc1 { Bekker Jensen, Simon - Petrosian, Suren, 1/2-1/2, Norderstedt, 2003, https://lichess.org/iKwhBfxU }) 21. Qxe7 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Rb2 { Lugovoi, Aleksei - Sivokho, Sergey, 1/2-1/2, Chigorin Memorial 06th, 1998, https://lichess.org/a0u1BLfe }) 14... Nxe5 15. f4 (15. Bf4 Qa5 16. Rac1 Qa6 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Rc2 Qxe2 19. Rexe2 { Naumann, Alexander - Fogarasi, Tibor, 1-0, Elekes Memorial GM, 1998, https://lichess.org/tqtY6Tah }) 15... Nd7 16. Bd2 Qb6 (16... Nb6) *


[Event "Lichess study"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My"]
[Date "2019.04.07"]
[White "Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Variation index"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/A-Cielbleu"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A59"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Accepted: King Walk Variation"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "PART 1 : B.G. Accepted"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/W3s9CiTy"]

{ All chapters (3 to 10) are in cruise mode. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 { Deviations on the second move include the Blackmar-Diemer, the Trompovsky, the London system, the Colle-Zukertort and the Richter-Veresov. Several solutions are possible in each case, depending mostly on taste. } 2... c5 3. d5 { Deviations on move 3 are treated in the chapters on the Benko Gambit Declined. } 3... b5 { Why should Black play this opening ? He must be wary of his move order, offers a wide choice of replies to White and ends up a pawn down in a semi-closed game. In return, for a limited amount of study, Black gets long-term pressure and postpones White's real problems to a later stage where there is little or no theory. This strategy gives decent winning chances even against computer-assisted preparation. } 4. cxb5 { d5 is now a weak pawn and a target for Black later in the game. Deviations on move 4 are treated under "Benko Gambit Declined". } { [%csl Bd5] } 4... a6 5. bxa6 { "Fully Accepted" Variation. Black's short-term lead in development enables him to accumulate several positional advantages : control over the a- and b-files, a very solid pawn structure after d6 and g6, and a lasting pressure on the queenside with the Bg7. } { [%csl Bh7,Bg6,Bf7,Be7,Bd6,Bc5][%cal Ga8a3,Gg7c3,Gd7d6,Gg7g6,Gb7b3,Gb8d7] } (5. e3 { "Modern" or "Quiet" Variation } 5... axb5 { is our recommended answer. It faces some major challenges and is quite complicated but also rewarding. } (5... e6 { is a simpler backup solution. })) (5. Nc3 { Zaitsev System } 5... axb5 6. e4 (6. Nxb5 { transposes to one of the main lines }) 6... b4 7. Nb5 { Zaitsev variation } 7... d6 8. Bc4 { Nescafe Frappe Attack } (8. Nf3 g6) (8. Bf4 g5) 8... Nbd7) (5. b6 { Pawn Return or Shirov Variation } 5... d6 { is the simplest answer. }) (5. f3 { Dlugy Variation. e4 comes next. } { [%cal Re2e4] } 5... axb5 { is our recommendation. } (5... e6 { is very complicated and not objectively better (as it was once thought to be). })) 5... g6 { There is no need to capture on a6 immediately. Sometimes it is better to bring the light-squared bishop to f5, and then Black takes the pawn on a6 with the rook or, in the double fianchetto variation, with the knight. If White brings the rook to b1 to step out of the diagonal of Black's Bg7, then Black's light-squared bishop can attack that rook from f5. } { [%csl Bf5][%cal Bc8f5,Ra1b1,Gg7b2] } (5... Bxa6 6. g3 { the best way to punish Black's imprecise move order. Other moves return to one of the main lines. } 6... d6 7. Bg2 g6 8. b3 Bg7 9. Bb2 $14 { the double fianchetto variation, easy to play as White }) 6. Nc3 { The idea is e4. Black must take on a6 to prevent that. If White plays g3 or Nf3 here, Black should reply d6 and delay Bxa6 until e4 is threatened. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rc3e4,Re2e4] } 6... Bxa6 { [%cal Ga6f1] } (6... Bg7? 7. e4 $16 O-O 8. Nf3 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bxa6 10. Be2 (10. Bxa6?! Qxa6 { [%cal Ga6f1] }) 10... d6 11. O-O $16) 7. e4 { White can choose this line, called the King Walk variation, or delays the e4 push after a kingside fianchetto and castling. These are the two main lines of the Benko Gambit, and the most challenging theoretical debates for Black as well. As such, they must be studied first. } (7. f4 { Central Storming Variation }) (7. g3 { Fianchetto variation } 7... d6 { It's better to block the d6 push early. Good or bad, it would throw Black off balance. }) (7. Nf3 { Waiting with the decision for e4 or g3. } 7... d6 8. g3 { The Fianchetto Variation used to be harmless (10.0-0 Nb6) but the new line 10.Rb1 has become the most critical battleground of the whole opening and a reason why it was absent for a few years from the top level. } (8. e4 Bxf1 9. Kxf1 { transposes to the text, the King Walk variation. }) 8... Bg7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. Rb1 { the contemporary approach, a very dangerous system } (10. O-O Nb6 { the harmless old line }) 10... O-O 11. O-O { Black must seek unconventional solutions here, as we do in chapter 3. }) 7... Bxf1 8. Kxf1 { White can't castle anymore. White's plan is now to play g3 or h3 and hide the king there, but that is rather slow. } { [%csl Rg2][%cal Rg2g3] } 8... d6 9. Nf3 (9. g3 Bg7 10. Kg2 O-O 11. Nf3 { another move order }) 9... Bg7 (9... Nbd7 { equivalent }) 10. g3 (10. h3 Nbd7 11. Kg1 O-O 12. Kh2 { King Walk variation, Kh2 line (it should really be called the Nenashev line). It is treated in chapter 4. }) 10... O-O 11. Kg2 { King Walk variation, Kg2 line, also called the Classical Main Line. It is the main topic of chapter 4. } 11... Nbd7 12. Re1 { the critical test in the King Walk variation } (12. h3 Ra6 { is easier for Black. He gets his usual play on the queenside and in the center. }) (12. a4 { the contemporary variation. No commonly accepted solution exists. In chapter 5, we make some proposals based on Dubov's ideas and on computer analyses. }) 12... Ng4 { Alternatives are deemed worse for Black. } (12... Ra6) (12... Qa5) 13. Qe2 { White prepares for the e5 push. Other moves are not so hard to meet. } (13. Nd2) (13. Re2) 13... Nge5 { the traditional approach, challenged in two ways } (13... Qa5 { An attempt based on the unlikely-looking move Bxc3. It might be Black's best chance in the Classical Main Line. See chapter 4. }) 14. Nd2 (14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. f4 (15. Bf4 { not so critical }) 15... Nd7 16. Bd2 Nb6! (16... Qb6 { White is better here. }) 17. b3 c4 { our proposed solution to 14.Nxe5 in chapter 4. }) 14... Nb6 15. f4 (15. a4 { will transpose sooner or later. }) 15... Ned7 16. a4! { a big theoretical challenge } (16. Nf3 Na4 { this thematic move solves all Black's problems. }) 16... Ra7 (16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nxa4 (17... Rxa4 18. Rxa4 Nxa4 19. c4) 18. c4 { It is very dangerous for Black to get his pawn back in this way. }) 17. a5 Qa8 { our proposed solution to 14.Nd2 in chapter 4. } *


[Event "Lichess study"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/qaFge6My"]
[Date "2019.03.28"]
[White "Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Fianchetto line"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A58"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Accepted: Fianchetto Variation"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "Fianchetto Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/58x2li36"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 { My contributions to this chapter are based on three sources :
1) Jon Edwards (1993) "The Benko Gambit !", R&D Publishing, pp. 12 & 17.
2) Steffen Pedersen (1999) "The Gambit Guide to the Benko Gambit", Gambit, pp. 42 & 50.
3) Valery Aveskulov (2012) "Attack with Black", Gambit, p.182.
Quotations made for research purposes. The authors's analyses are not reproduced at length. } 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 { This is definitely better than Bxa6 here, because it keeps the option open to bring the light-squared bishop to f5. The position after both sides have castled on move 11 can be reached with different move orders. } { In the Benko, Black's move order must be very precise and tailored to White's choices. } { [%cal Gc8f5,Gf5b1] } (5... Bxa6?! 6. g3! { White omits Nc3 and Nf3 to gain time for the fianchettoes. } (6. Nc3 { Here this move would refrain from taking advantage of Black's inaccuracy. } 6... g6 7. Nf3 d6 8. g3 Bg7 9. Bg2 { would transpose to the text. }) 6... g6 7. Bg2 d6 8. b3 Bg7 9. Bb2 $14 { In the double fianchetto line, White consolidates easily his queenside. Black plays for two results (a draw or a loss), and the Benko is arguably not the best defence for this ultra-solid strategy. } 9... O-O 10. Nh3 { In this line, White protects d5 with minor pieces (Bg2, Nc3, maybe Nf4). } 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Ra7 { One possible defence that turned out well in a high-profile example. } 12. Re1 (12. Nf4 Nxd5! { Pedersen } 13. Bxg7 Nxf4 14. Bxf8 Nxe2+ 15. Kh1 Qxf8 16. Re1 Nd4 17. Nc3 Ne5 { "with excellent compensation" (Pedersen) }) 12... Qa8 13. e4 Rb8 $14 { Gheorghiu, Florin - Beliavsky, Alexander G, 0-1, Moscow Interzonal, 1982, https://lichess.org/0LR5k1A4 }) 6. Nc3 { forces Black's reply. } (6. Nf3 d6 { forced because Nc3 would introduce the dual threat of e4 and d6. } (6... Bg7? 7. Nc3 Bxa6 (7... d6 8. e4 $16) 8. d6 $16) 7. g3 (7. Nc3 Bxa6 { again a forced transposition to the main line }) 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 Nbd7 { Black has no time for 0-0 yet. } 9. O-O Nb6 10. Nc3 { Here Bxa6 is not necessary because White's bishop has left the f1-a6 diagonal. So Black may castle and keep the option of Bf5. } 10... O-O $10 { and the unpleasant Rb1 doesn't work in this move order (when White has castled first) because Black would play Bf5, controling e4 and b1. Black has equalized. }) (6. b3 { What if White tries the double fianchetto nonetheless ? } 6... Bg7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. g3 Nxa6 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. Nh3 (10. e4 e6 $15) 10... e6 $15 { Most engines agree on Nb4, but e6 is simpler and roughly equivalent. Edwards attribute this move to Fedorowicz. } 11. Nf4 { Csom, Istvan - Alburt, Lev O, 0-1, New York op, 1987, https://lichess.org/5RkMl9hl } 11... g5!? $15 { Edwards }) 6... Bxa6 { When White threatens to push e4, Black must be ready to take Bxf1. } (6... Bg7? 7. e4! { and Black cannot prevent White from castling comfortably. } (7. Nf3 { Even here White is better. } 7... O-O 8. g3 d6 9. Bg2 Bxa6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Qc2 (11. Rb1) 11... Nb6 { Is now not so strong, because } 12. Rd1 $16 { protects d5, and White's queen is more mobile. } { [%cal Rd1d5] }) 7... d6 $16) 7. g3 (7. Nf3 d6 { Remember that d6 follows Nf3 when Nc3 has been played. } 8. g3 Bg7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. Rb1 O-O 11. O-O { transposes to the text. }) (7. e4 Bxf1 8. Kxf1 d6) 7... d6 { Here Bg7 would be equivalent. } 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. Nf3 { A58 Benko Gambit/Fianchetto Variation. White's idea here is to delay the pushing of the e-pawn until the light-squared bishop is out of the way and to castle first. } { The fianchetto variation is not the engines's prefered line against the Benko, but it sets a long-term trend that is favorable for White. The new line 10.Rb1 is very atypical and unpleasant for Benko devotees. Black cannot trust the customary recipe as in the harmless old line (10.0-0 Nb6) and he must follow a narrow path with complications to escape. } { [%csl Be2] } 9... Nbd7 { It is important to pressure d5 as soon as possible. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5] } (9... O-O?! 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Qc2 Qa5 12. Rd1 Rfb8 13. b3 Rb7 14. Rb1 $16 { followed by Bd2 and White has fully consolidated. "This strategy works especially well against the most aggressive black efforts to develop with ...Qa5 because Bd2 carries with a number of unpleasant threats when the Nc3 moves" (Edwards). } 14... Ne8 15. Bd2 $16 { Smejkal, Jan - Polgar, Zsuzsa, 1-0, Baden-Baden, 1985, https://lichess.org/TKiDbUKD }) 10. Rb1 { Get off the diagonal, so White can play b3 now whenever it is needed, and the knight on c3 can also move. The best setup for White here is the dark-squared bishop on b2 to counter Black's dark-squared bishop. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Gg7b2,Rc1b2] } (10. O-O { is slightly inaccurate. } 10... Nb6 { The threat is Bc4, forking the pawns on d5 and a2. } { "This move is the reason why White mostly prefers 10.Rb1 instead of 10.0-0" (Aveskulov). Still, none of the three quoted sources covers 10.Rb1 0-0 11.0-0 Qa5 (Aveskulov chooses 10...Nb6). } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gb6d5,Ga6c4,Gc4a2] } (10... O-O?! { returns the favor. } 11. Qc2 $14 { and White will play Rd1 and e4, freeing his pieces easily. }) 11. Re1 { Is the main move. It does two things: it gets the rook out ofBlack'slight-squared bishop's view, and it adds support for the e-pawn that can be pushed now to support d5. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Ga6e2,Ge2f1,Re2e4,Re4d5] } 11... O-O (11... Bc4?! { is rare for a good reason: It doesn't work here, because } 12. Nd2 { was played by Loek van Wely once. It allows } (12. e4 $16 { The computer's first choice }) 12... Bxd5 { but } (12... Ba6 { Georgiev just retreated in the sight of all these lines. Two tempi wasted for nothing. Van Wely, Loek - Georgiev, Kiril, 1-0, Dordrecht FPO, 1998, https://lichess.org/VkHdsVa9 }) 13. e4 Be6 14. e5 $18 { … is not nice for Black: } { [%cal Rg2a8,Re5f6] } 14... dxe5 (14... Nfd5 15. exd6 { [%cal Re1e8] } 15... Nxc3 (15... Qxd6 16. Nce4 { [%cal Re4d6,Be4g5,Bg5e6] } 16... Qc6 17. Nb3 { [%cal Rb3c5,Re4c5] } 17... O-O 18. Nexc5 $16 { This is very uncomfortable for Black. Just don't play Bc4 after Re1! } { [%cal Rc5e6,Re1e6] }) 16. bxc3 exd6 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 $16 { loses the exchange too. }) 15. Bxa8 $16 { gives the exchange. }) 12. Bf4 (12. Nd2 { White defends c4. } 12... Nfd7 13. Qc2 Bb7 $44 { followed by Qc7, Rfb8 and a second attempt at occupying c4 via Ne5. }) (12. e4 Nfd7 13. Qc2 Nc4 $44 { Shirov, A. - Dubov, Danii, 1/2-1/2, Battle of the Generations Blitz 2013, https://lichess.org/240tn4NK } 14. b3? { the knight cannot be expelled for tactical reasons. } 14... Qa5 $17 15. Bb2? Nxb2 $19) 12... Nh5 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bc1 Nc4 $44 { ...and life goes on :) . Black occupies the b-file, the dark squares on the long diagonal, the light squares on the f1a6 diagonal vacated by White's bishop and therefore claims full compensation. }) 10... O-O (10... Nb6 11. b3 $14 { is again easy for White. }) 11. O-O { This is the real starting position of this line. Black now has to decide how to proceed. Qa5, followed by Rb8 is the main plan, but Nb6 and Ne8 are also moves. Even Ng4 followed by Nge5 is good, especially when White has played very quickly until now. } (11. Qc2?! { too late } 11... Bc4 $10 { Black regains his pawn, with a likely liquidation on d5. }) 11... Qa5 { White scores well against all moves in practice, but the main line Qa5 is theoretically the most promising one for Black. It transposes to 10.0-0 0-0?! 11.Rb1?! Qa5, where Black's compensation is not so clear as with 10.0-0 Nb6. } { [%cal Gf8b8] } (11... Ne8 $13) (11... Nb6 $13) (11... Ng4 12. Qc2 (12. Bd2 $13) (12. h3 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. f4 { If e4 were played before, Nd3 would be possible, but not here. } 14... Nc4! { Na3 and Nxb2 are vicious threats. } 15. Qc2 { White parries and threatens b3 (and e4) in turn. } 15... f5! $13 { Black stops e4 once and for all. This move is not typical of the Benko, but sometimes comes handy. }) 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 Bc4 { [%cal Gc4a2,Gc4d5,Ga8a2] } 14. Nd2 Bxa2 15. Rb5 { planning c4. } { [%cal Gc3c4] } 15... Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4,Ga2c4,Rd2c4,Rc2c4] } 16. c4 Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4,Gb6c4,Ga2c4,Rd2c4,Rc2c4] } 17. Rb2 Bxc4 18. Rxb6 (18. f4 Bxe2 19. Re1 Nd3 20. Rxe2 Nxb2 21. Bxb2 { [%cal Rf4f5,Rg2h3] } 21... Qd7 22. Ne4 $14) 18... Bxe2 (18... Qxb6 19. Nxc4 Nxc4 20. Qxc4 $14) 19. Rb3 Bxf1 20. Bxf1 $14) 12. Bd2 { There are no dangerous discoveries when the knight on c3 moves, Black can safely play: } (12. Qc2 { is another move order. }) 12... Rfb8 13. Qc2 { the key junction in the new fianchetto system, only considered by Pedersen under a different move order. } 13... Qc7 { usually a bad idea in the Benko, but here it is necessary for a tightrope save. } (13... Nb6 14. b3 Qa3 15. Bc1 Qa5 16. Rd1 $14 { White has achieved an ideal setup and plays for the win. } (16. Bd2 $10 { White can take the repetition and force a draw. })) (13... Ne8 14. Rfc1 { Modern engines and my old Komodo 8 give three alternatives where White's edge is clear. } (14. a4 Qd8 15. b3 Nc7 16. Rfd1 $14 { The almost unanimous first choice. }) (14. Rfd1 { a second choice for most engines } 14... Qb4 15. Re1 Nc7 16. e4 $14) (14. Rfe1 Qd8 15. e4 $14 { Stockfish's first choice }) 14... Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Qxa2 16. e4 Nc7 17. Re1 Qb3 $10 { attributed to Tukmakov by Pedersen }) 14. b3 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6d5,Gf6d5,Rc3d5] } 15. Nh4 { [%cal Rg2d5,Rc3d5,Gf6d5,Gb6d5] } 15... Qb7 16. Rfd1 { White has organized, but now Black can open the center and regain his pawn : } 16... Nfxd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bh6 { Maybe the most critical position for the whole opening } { [%cal Rd1d5,Rg2d5] } 18... e6! $10 { Komodo's preferred option introduces a series of "only moves" by Black. } (18... Nb4!? $13 { This tactical trick should equalize on the spot, but it is very complicated to work out all the lines. In practice, White scores well here. } 19. Qd2 Bxh6 20. Qxh6 Qc8 21. Bxa8 Rxa8 22. Nf3 f6 23. Qe3 Kf7 $14 { Williams, Leighton - Situru, Nathanael, 1-0, Bled ol (Men), 2002, https://lichess.org/ZLQjQaWZ }) (18... Bxh6!? $44 { the safest line for practical reasons } 19. Bxd5 Qc8 20. Nxg6 Ra7 21. Nh4 e6 22. Bg2 d5 23. e4 d4 24. e5 d3 25. Qc3 c4 26. bxc4 Rxb1 27. Rxb1 Qxc4 28. Qxc4 Bxc4 29. Bf1 Rxa2 30. Ng2 Rc2 31. f4 Bf8 32. Rd1 Bc5+ 33. Kh1 Bd5 34. h4 Rf2 35. Kh2 d2 { 0-1, Gonzalez Vidal,Y.-Perez Mitjans,O., Capablanca Memorial open 2006 https://lichess.org/RHAGJUjT }) 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. e4 Nb4 { Here we see why Qc2 was played earlier: The queen can now move away with a check. } 21. Qc3+ (21. Qb2+) 21... e5 22. Rxd6 Qe7 { Protect e5! } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 23. Rd2 $10 { Going back with the rook is the safest option, so White can hold a2. } { [%cal Rd2a2] } 23... Nc6 { The rest of the game is given for illustrative purposes. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 24. Rd5 Nd4 25. Qxc5 Qxc5 26. Rxc5 Bd3 27. Rb2 Nxb3 28. Rxb3 (28. Rxe5 $10) (28. axb3 Ra1+ 29. Bf1 Bxf1 30. f3 Bc4+ 31. Kg2 Rxb3 32. Rxb3 Ra2+ 33. Kg1 { And here Black has a perpetual check. } { [%cal Ga2a1] }) 28... Rxb3 29. axb3 Ra1+ 30. Bf1 Bxf1 31. f3 Ba6+ 32. Kg2 Ra2+ 33. Kg1 $10 { with a repetition. } (33. Kh3 { Is not possible: } 33... Bf1+ 34. Ng2 Bxg2+ 35. Kh4 (35. Kg4 h5+ 36. Kh4 Bxf3 37. Rxe5 f6 38. g4 Rg2 39. Re7+ Kh6 40. gxh5 Rg4+ 41. Kh3 gxh5 42. b4 Bg2#) 35... Bxf3 $19) *


[Event "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5: King Walk Variation"]
[Date "2019.04.01"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A59"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Accepted: King Walk Variation"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "King Walk Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/GRRAEO36"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.01"]
[UTCTime "02:28:08"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 { Benko Gambit } { My contributions to this chapter are based on two sources :
1) Steffen Pedersen (1999) "The Gambit Guide to the Benko Gambit", Gambit, pp. 13 & 22.
2) Valery Aveskulov (2012) "Attack with Black", Gambit, pp.167-8.
Quotations made for research purposes. The authors's analyses are not reproduced at length. } 4. cxb5 a6 { Accepted } 5. bxa6 { Fully Accepted } 5... Bxa6 { The correct move order would be to play g6 here, Bxa6 in response to Nc3, and d6 afterwards. A lot of reference games actually follow this inferior move order which would be punished by the double fianchetto variation (see chapter 3). } 6. Nc3 d6 7. e4 { Official name: "Yugoslav without 7...Bxf1", but that's exactly the move we are looking at here. Just remember Yugoslav.
White gives up castling rights and gets a strong center in return. } 7... Bxf1 8. Kxf1 g6 9. g3 (9. Nge2 $10 { Yugoslav with 7...Bxf1, Nge2 } { harmless and not instructive, as Black plays in the same way as usual }) (9. Nf3 Bg7 10. g3 O-O 11. Kg2 { A different move order for the King Walk Variation. }) (9. h3 Bg7 10. Nf3 O-O 11. Kg1 Nbd7 12. Kh2 { White has spent one more move on the king's walk to make Black's plan (Qa8) harmless. This used to be White's most dangerous attempt against the Benko before the discovery of 10.Rb1 in the fianchetto variation. } 12... Qa5 13. Re1 Rfb8 14. Re2 Ne8 15. Rc2 { This superb manoeuvre is associated with the name of Nenashev, a renowned Benko-killer of the late '90s. } 15... Qa6! { the sole antidote } 16. Bd2 { Aveskulov doesn't consider the move that gives White some advantage according to Pedersen. } 16... Nc7 17. Rac1 Bxc3! $146 { Modern engines indicate this clear-cut solution. } 18. Bxc3 Nb5 $10 { Black gets rid of White's dark square bishop and recovers the pawn, with equality. } 19. Bd2 (19. Ra1 Nxc3 20. bxc3 Nf6 $10 { The threat of Qc4 recovers the e4 pawn. }) 19... Qxa2 20. b4 Qa4 { the best square to deal with the coming e5 push. } 21. bxc5 Nxc5 22. e5 Na3 23. Ra2 Qxd1 24. Rxd1 { With the queens off the board, e5 is not dangerous. Black even has a repetition if he wishes so, according to Komodo. } 24... Nb5 (24... Nc4 $10) 25. Rb2 Nd3 26. Rb3 Nc5 $10 { draw }) 9... Bg7 10. Kg2 { The king is actually quite safe here due to the lack of light-squared bishops. } 10... O-O 11. Nf3 { King Walk Variation. White's plan is simple: hold the center and push the pawns on the a- and b-files.
Black wants to get both rooks onto these files and undermine the center. } { [%csl Be4,Bd5,Gb8][%cal Rb2b8,Ra2a8,Gf8b8] } 11... Nbd7 { Black knows where to put his rooks (a- and b-files). The placement of the queen is a big issue. When White's king is on g2, Black's queen belongs to a8, adding firepower on the a-file and putting pressure on d5 for various purposes (holding back e5, threatening e6 or even f5,...). The standard manoeuvre Ra6-Qa8 is in order. } (11... Na6 $13 { Black has quite a few problems in the contemporary line 11...Nbd7 12.a4 on top of the usual theory after 12.Re1 or 12.h3, so this fresh approach might well be the future of the Benko Gambit as a whole. }) (11... Qb6 $14) 12. Re1 { Anything slower lets Black play either Nb6 and Nfd7/Ne8, or Ra6 and Qa8 with an iron grip on e5 and a free hand on the queenside. Only the precise move order 12.Re1, that threatens e5, forces Black to find an unconventional solution like 13...Qa5 14.Nd2 Bxc3 or an early c4 push (see the note on the 16th move). } { [%csl Be4][%cal Re1e4,Rc3e4] } (12. h3 Ra6! { White has wasted a tempo with h3, so Black's plan cannot be disrupted here. } 13. Re1 Qa8 $44 { Here comes a typical Benko middlegame where Black plays for three results. }) (12. a4 { is the topic of chapter 5. }) 12... Ng4 { Black wants to clear the long diagonal to enhance his control over e5, but this move lets White make progress step by step with no particular difficulty. Still it is safer than the best alternative Ra6 because White cannot disrupt Black's typical Benko plan. } (12... Ra6!? 13. e5!? { White attempts to disturb Black's ideal placement. } (13. a4 Qa8! { ready to play Rb8 (preventing Nb5) and to answer an immediate Nb5 with Rc8, expelling the knight with Ne8-c7. Here Black has definite compensation. }) 13... dxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Rd6 $13 { Black is not worse, but this is not the typical Benko middlegame. In practice White has scored well from here. }) (12... Nb6 { Holding back the e5 push in this way, like in the fianchetto variation, exposes the knight. } 13. a4 $14) 13. Qe2 Nge5 { Pedersen's choice, not mentioned by Aveskulov } (13... Qa5! { "Black wants to take on c3" (Aveskulov). } 14. Nd2 { Pedersen stops here, not considering the counter-intuitive idea Bxc3. } 14... Bxc3 15. Nc4 Qa6 16. bxc3 Nge5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 { Aveskulov recommends to let White exchange himself. } 18. Bh6 Rfe8 $44 $146 { Aveskulov, Stockfish and Komodo confirm that Black has no problem here. }) 14. Nxe5 (14. Nd2 Nb6 15. f4 Ned7 16. a4! { Pedersen attributes this move to Gavrikov. "[...] if White can force the knight to move from b6, then he will gain a strong outpost on c4" (Pedersen). } (16. Nf3 Na4! { a thematic move that equalizes by freezing the a-pawn and exposing the b-pawn }) 16... Ra7 17. a5 Qa8 18. Qb5 Rb8 19. axb6 Rxa1 20. Qxd7 { Lugovoi, Aleksei - Khalifman, Alexander, 1/2-1/2, St Petersburg-ch, 1996, https://lichess.org/jfR5Jc5U } 20... Bxc3 { Stockfish's suggestion } 21. bxc3 $13 { If Black doesn't feel at home in this messy position, 13...Qa5 is the way to go. }) 14... Nxe5 15. f4 Nd7 16. Bd2 Qb6?! { Any traditional placement fails to get adequate counterplay. The rest of the game is given for illustrative purposes, as Black should not go down this way. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gb6b2] } (16... Nb6!? 17. b3 c4! { (Pedersen) } { Livshits, Ron - Gurevich, Dmitry, 0-1, Toronto op, 1998, https://lichess.org/pdPQT8V9 } 18. Rab1 $14 $146 { Still Komodo believes that White keeps an edge, an argument in favor of 13...Qa5. } (18. bxc4?! Qc8! { [%cal Gc8c4,Gb6c4] } 19. c5 Qxc5)) 17. a4 { Now Black can't take b2, because that would trap the queen. } 17... Rfb8 (17... Qxb2? 18. Reb1 Qc2 19. Ra2 $18) 18. Nb5 (18. Nd1 $14) 18... Bxb2 19. Rab1 Bg7 20. Na3 { [%cal Rb1b6] } 20... Qd8 { Here it is important that White controls the squares in front of the passed pawn. Every exchange has to support that idea. } 21. Rxb8 Rxb8 $14 (21... Qxb8 $14) *


[Event "Lichess study"]
[Date "2019.04.17"]
[White "Benko Gambit"]
[Black "King Walk 12.a4"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/A-Cielbleu"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A59"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Accepted: King Walk Variation"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "King Walk, 12.a4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/kKFwbMNo"]

{ This chapter is at the same time one of the most innovative and the riskiest of the study. It covers a variation that is not curently resolved and the stakes are so long-term that Stockfish at depth 23 is not of much use. A few key games and Komodo are the main guiding lights in this storm. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 Bxa6 6. Nc3 d6 7. e4 Bxf1 8. Kxf1 g6 9. g3 Bg7 10. Kg2 O-O 11. Nf3 Nbd7 (11... Na6 $13 { Black has quite a few problems in the contemporary line 11...Nbd7 12.a4 on top of the usual theory after 12.Re1 or 12.h3, so this fresh approach might well be the future of the Benko Gambit as a whole. }) 12. a4 { The latest soup in the old pot, with an impressive score for White ! The idea is to play quickly Nb5, Ra3, Bd2-c3. This move is not considered by any source quoted in the study. Of course, our analysis cannot be considered as final without a practical test at high level. } (12. Qc2 Ra6 13. a4 Qa8 { transposes to the lines following 12.a4. } 14. Bd2 (14. Ra3)) 12... Ra6 13. Qc2 (13. Bd2 Qa8 14. Nb5 Rc8 15. Qc2 c4 { Dubov's idea might solve Black's problems. } 16. Bb4 (16. Be3 { a move not attempted against Dubov } 16... e6 17. dxe6 fxe6 18. Nc3 Ng4 $146 { Komodo's line gives good compensation for Black. } 19. Rhe1 Nde5 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 $15 { despite the pawn minus. }) 16... Nc5 17. Bxc5 Rxc5 18. Ra3 Nd7 $44 { Fedoseev, Vl3 - Dubov, Daniil, 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Blitz 2014, https://lichess.org/31LM0coc
White can occupy c6 with a knight, usually a bad sign for Black. But here e7 can be defended by Bf6 and the rook on c5 put extra pressure on d5 to withhold the e5 push. The pawn on a4 ends up being a target. Black has enough compensation. }) (13. Nb5 { is not possible immediately because e4 is hanging. }) (13. Qe2 { trying to win a tempo on the Qc2-e2 line } { [%cal Re2a6] } 13... Qa8 14. Ra3 Rb8 { the relevant nuance in the Qe2 line } (14... e6?! { too soon here too } 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. Rd1 d5 17. Nb5 $14) 15. b3 Ne8 16. Nb5 Ra5 { threatens Rbxb5. } 17. Qa2 f5! 18. exf5 Qxd5 19. fxg6 hxg6 20. Re1 Ne5 21. Re3 Raxb5 22. axb5 Nc7 23. b6 Nb5 24. b4 c4 25. Ra5 Rxb6 $132) 13... Qa8 14. Ra3 { Not all engines agree on the fact that this move discourages e6. Rfb8 would be answered by Nb5. } (14. Nb5 Rc8 15. Bd2 c4 { transposes into 13.Bd2 and Dubov's model games. }) 14... Rc8 (14... e6?! { It turns out that it's too soon... } 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. Re1 d5?! { This moves plays into White's hand after Re1. } (16... Rc8 { a key move to prevent Nb5-c7. } 17. Ng5 { White can force d5 anyway. } 17... d5 18. exd5 exd5 19. Nb5 $14 { Black's damage control succeeded. }) 17. exd5 exd5 18. Nb5 Qb7 19. Ng5 $16 { Without Rc8, Black is suffering. His counterplay can never be against f2 in this line. }) 15. Rd1 { prepares to answer c4 with Nd4-c6. } (15. b3 { Otherwise Dubov's c4 push is in order. } 15... e6 $44 { But what is this rook doing on a3 now ? }) (15. Qe2 { a useful prelude to the same plan : Black proceeds but must insert Bf8 after Bf4. } 15... e6 16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Rd1 c4 18. Bf4 Bf8 19. Raa1 d5 20. e5 { the main difference : White doesn't need to exchange on d5. } 20... Ne8 21. Be3 Rb8 $132 { Black got what he wanted : a game with chances for both sides. }) 15... e6 16. dxe6 (16. Bg5 exd5 $44) 16... fxe6 17. Bf4 d5 18. exd5 (18. Nb5 Nxe4 19. Nc7 Rxc7 20. Bxc7 $15 { Black has more than enough for the exchange. }) 18... Nxd5 $146 { gets rid of the threat against c7. } 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Qe2 Nf6 21. a5 c4 $44 { White's pawns cannot support each other. If all his counterplay fails, Black can achieve a draw by trading his central pawns against White's queenside and holding a rook ending 3p vs 2p on one side. } *


[Event "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5: Modern Variation: 5.e3 (A)"]
[Date "2019.04.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Accepted: Modern Variation"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "Modern Variation: 5.e3 (A)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/JsWtBJM3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.04"]
[UTCTime "15:31:08"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 { Modern Variation. Like in other lines in which Whites doesn't capture a6 immediately, Black will very likely not get the two open files. The decision is again: play for the fianchetto or take b5? Both lines are playable. } { My contributions to this chapter are partly based on Valery Aveskulov (2012) "Attack with Black", Gambit, p.134.
Quotations made for research purposes. The author's analysis is not reproduced at length. } 5... axb5 { My recommendation. } (5... g6 { Is the main move, maybe because that might transpose into the Fianchetto line. But I don't think Black gets anything special here. White is just a pawn up, and Black has no compensation. } 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. a4 O-O 8. Nf3 Bb7 9. Ra3 e6 10. dxe6 (10. d6 $10 { Mildly annoying, but White can't hold that pawn for long. }) 10... fxe6 11. Qd6 { This move casts some doubts over 5...g6, but not everybody agrees on this. See B. Alterman (2011) "The Alterman Gambit Guide : Black Gambits 1", Quality Chess, p.74. } (11. Be2?! { The old move was not threatening. } 11... d5 { This is one of the rare situations in the Benko in which Black has the strong pawn center. } 12. O-O { The question now is, how to protect c5? Qe7 or Nbd7 are fine. The former steps out of the way of White's queen, and protect e6. The latter covers also the hole on e5. The engine says, Kh8 is the best move. } { [%csl Bc5,Be5,Be6][%cal Rd1d7,Gb8d7,Gd8e7,Gd7c5,Gd7e5,Gg8h8,Ge7e6,Rf3g5] } 12... Qe7 { [%cal Ge7e6,Ge7c5] } (12... Nbd7 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7c5,Gd7e5] } 13. Ng5 { [%cal Rg5e6] } 13... Qe7 $44) 13. Qc2 $44 { [%cal Rf1d1,Rd1d5] }) 11... Qc8 (11... axb5 12. Bxb5 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qc8 14. O-O Ne8 15. Qg3 Nc6 $13 { Alterman }) 12. Be2 Ne8 (12... axb5 13. axb5 $14) 13. Qg3 $14 { Black will stay under pressure for a long time. }) (5... e6 { In this line, White keeps a very small edge and Black doesn't need to study so hard. It's an acceptable trade-off. } 6. Nc3 exd5 (6... axb5 7. Bxb5 Bb7?! 8. e4 $16) 7. Nge2 (7. Nxd5 Bb7 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 Be7 $10) 7... Bb7 8. Nf4 axb5 9. Bxb5 Bd6 $14 { Lukacs, Peter - Plachetka, Jan, 1-0, Belgrade, 1984, https://lichess.org/BdGdNYe1 }) (5... Bb7 6. Nc3 axb5 (6... Qa5 7. bxa6 $14 { an independent line that looks less safe for Black than the text }) 7. Bxb5 Qa5 { transposes to the text. } (7... e6 8. e4 $16 { a transposition into a bad line for Black })) 6. Bxb5 Qa5+ { [%cal Ga5b5] } 7. Nc3 Bb7 { attacking d5. } { Up to now, Black's moves are forcing. The difficulty of this line starts now, but other lines appear objectively worse. } { [%cal Gb7d5,Gf6d5] } 8. Ne2! { the most dangerous move by far } (8. e4?! Nxe4 9. Ne2 Nd6 { [%cal Gd6b5] } 10. Ba4 (10. Bd3 Bxd5 $15) 10... g6 { And now Black can fianchetto the bishop. } 11. O-O Bg7 12. Bg5 { [%cal Rg5e7] } 12... h6 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Bxd6 exd6 $10 { This is very acceptable for Black. }) (8. Bc4 e6 { studied in part B, next chapter } 9. Bd2 Qb6) (8. Bd2 Qb6 { studied in part B, next chapter } 9. Nf3 (9. Bc4 e6 { transposes into 8.Bc4. })) 8... Nxd5 9. O-O Nc7 { Aveskulov prefers this move. } (9... Nxc3 { The computer's first choice plays into White's hand. } 10. Nxc3 e6 11. e4 Be7 12. Bf4 O-O $14 { The more Komodo thinks about this position, the more it likes White's perspectives. }) 10. a4 (10. Bc4 e6 11. e4 Be7 $10) 10... Nxb5 11. Nxb5 e6! $146 { Komodo and Aveskulov agree about this novelty in a position previously thought to be favorable for White. } 12. Ng3 (12. e4 { but Aveskulov doesn't mention Komodo's choice which leads to a long forced line. } 12... Bxe4 13. Bf4 Na6 14. Re1 Bc6 15. Nec3 { Nd5-c7+ is unstoppable. Black sacrifices back the exchange ! } 15... f6 (15... Be7 $13 { considered by Komodo as well }) 16. Nd5 h5 { to prevent Qh5+ } 17. Ndc7+ Nxc7 18. Nxc7+ Kf7 19. Nxa8 Qxa8 20. Bd6 Bxd6 21. Qxd6 h4 $44 { and now the h-pawn serves some positive purpose ! The position is easier to play for Black. }) (12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. Qxd6 Qa6 $15) 12... Qb6 13. e4 { less direct but no less dangerous than 12.e4 } (13. Qg4 f6 $10 { (Aveskulov) the only previous mention of 11...e6N. }) 13... Be7 { a safe line, maybe ? } 14. Qg4 g6 15. Bh6 { not at all ! } 15... Ba6 { Only this move holds ! Both sides face complicated problems and a series of quasi-forced moves unfolds (Komodo). } 16. Bg7 Bxb5 (16... h5 { too tempting to be true } 17. Qf4 Bxb5 18. axb5 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 Rh7 20. Bc3 h4 21. Nf1 Qxb5 22. Ne3 d6? { a false hope to stabilize the position } 23. h3 Nc6 24. Ra8+ Kd7 25. e5 d5 (25... Qb7 26. Qa4 d5 27. Nc2 $18) 26. Nxd5! exd5 27. Qg4+ Kc7 28. Rc8+ Kb6 29. Qd7 $18) 17. axb5 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 Rg8 19. Bc3 Qxb5 20. Qf4 f6 { Stockfish prefers h5, but Komodo gives back the pawn in this way. } 21. Qh6 (21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Qxf6 Qb4! 23. Qe5 Rf8 $10 { followed by the "St-Louis shuffle" (Kf7-g8) }) 21... Kf7 22. Qxh7+ Rg7 $10 { Black has given back the pawn but reached a compact, if a little weird, piece configuration. } *


