[ChapterName "Modern Variation: 5.e3 (B)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/l1vZoKX0"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 axb5 6. Bxb5 Qa5+ 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Bd2 (8. Bc4 e6 { The point is that White can't really take: the pawn is
pinned against g2. } { [%csl Bg2][%cal Gf6d5,Ge6d5,Gb7d5,Be4g2,Bd5g2] } 9. Bd2 (9. dxe6? Bxg2 10. exf7+ Kd8 11. Bd2 Bxh1 12. f3 Qb6 $17 { [%cal Gb6b2] }) 9... Qb6 10. Qb3 (10. e4 Nxe4 11. Nf3 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Rfe1 { Equal material and Black has the bishop pair. This is fine. }) 10... Qxb3 11. Bxb3 exd5 12. Nge2 Na6 13. O-O-O { is interesting. } { [%cal Rd1d5] } (13. O-O Be7 $10) 13... Nb4 { Black must react quickly, but then he can even count on some advantage. This move and the next ones can be made in various orders. This is the more forcing order. } 14. Kb1 c4 15. Bc2 Bc5 $146 16. Nd4 Bc6 { a key move in Black's defence and attack } 17. f3 O-O 18. Be1 Rfb8 19. Bh4 Ne8 $15 { Komodo }) 8... Qb6 { And this is the downside of axb5: the queen has to move
twice in the opening, and the faster development just doesn't happen. } 9. Nf3 { White has a statistically crushing score with this move, but he was on average the stronger player. The resulting positions are indeed double-edged. } (9. Bc4 e6 { transposes into the 8.Bc4 line. }) (9. Qb3 e6 10. e4 (10. Bc4 Qxb3 11. Bxb3 { transposes to 8.Bc4 }) 10... Nxe4! 11. Nxe4 Bxd5 12. Qd3 f5 13. Ng3 Bxg2 $15 { Why White still looks for improvements after this is a mystery for me and for Komodo. }) (9. e4? Nxe4 $15 { a typical mistake }) (9. a4 Nxd5 10. Nf3 { is another move order }) 9... Nxd5 10. a4 (10. Nxd5 { eases Black's task. } 10... Bxd5 11. a4 e6 12. Bc3 Be7 13. O-O O-O (13... Qb7 14. Ne5 O-O 15. Qg4 f5 16. Qg3 $14) 14. Nd2 f5 15. f3 $13 Bc6 $146 { Stockfish } 16. Nc4 Qb7 17. Na5 Qc7 $10 { White's initiative has petered out. }) 10... e6 11. O-O Be7 12. a5 (12. e4 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 O-O 14. Ne5 { Otherwise Bc6(xb5) equalizes. } 14... d6 $146 { Komodo } 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Qd3!? { at the crossroad of d4, b5 and g3 } 16... Nc6 17. a5 (17. Rfe1 Nb4 18. Qg3 (18. Qe2 Bc6 $10) 18... g6 $10) 17... Na7 18. Nb6 (18. Ba4 Ba6 $10) 18... Nxb5 19. Nxa8 Rxa8 20. Qxb5 Ba6 $10) 12... Qc7 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Bc3 O-O 15. Qa4 Bc6 16. Qg4 g6 17. Be2 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 d5 $10 { Komodo's assessment (0.00) implies that the position is sharp and might result in a forced repetition. } *


[Event "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5: Pawn Return (Shirov) Variation: 5.b6"]
[Date "2019.04.01"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Accepted: Pawn Return Variation"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "Pawn Return (Shirov) Variation: 5.b6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/rcC2xMB9"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.01"]
[UTCTime "16:06:44"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6 { Pawn Return Variation. The point is that White doesn't give Black the open a-file and the bishop on a6. This also opens opportunities for checks per Qa4. } { This variation also bears the name of Shirov. White agrees with Black's idea of a middlegame with mutual weaknesses, but he arranges the idea on his own term. My contributions to this chapter are based on two sources :
1) Jon Edwards (1993) "The Benko Gambit !", R&D Publishing, p.54.
2) Steffen Pedersen (1999) "The Gambit Guide to the Benko Gambit", Gambit, p.113.
Quotations made for research purposes. The authors's analyses are not reproduced at length. } { [%cal Rd1a4,Ra4e8] } 5... d6 { There is no need to capture b6 right now. } { All three defences are good. This is the simplest. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gc8d7] } (5... e6 { Black can play the like a normal Benoni now. e6 is the typical move here, trying to open the center immediately. } 6. Nc3 Nxd5 (6... exd5) 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. Qxd5 Nc6 9. Nf3 (9. e4) 9... Rb8 { is a complicated variation that is not objectively better than 5...d6. }) (5... Qxb6 { is playable as well. There are quite a few subvariations here. } 6. Nc3 d6 (6... g6 7. e4 d6 8. Nf3 Bg7) 7. e4 g6 8. Nf3 Bg7) 6. Nc3 { Prepares e4 and maybe Na4 to hold b6 for a while. } { [%cal Rc3a4,Ba4b6,Re2e4,Bc3e4] } 6... Nbd7 (6... Qxb6 { transposes to 5...Qxb6 } 7. e4 g6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Be2 { for example } 9... O-O 10. O-O Nbd7) 7. e4 (7. a4 a5 { This is actually the main line but it has fewer branches than 7.e4. } (7... Nxb6?! { too early } 8. e4 $36 g6 9. a5 Nbd7 10. Nf3 $14) 8. e4 g6 9. Bb5 Bg7 10. Nf3 (10. f4 O-O 11. Nf3 Nxb6 $10 { f4 only makes sense with the e5 push, so tying e4 to the defence of d5 is a good idea, good enough for equality. }) 10... O-O 11. O-O Ba6!? { Pedersen } 12. b7 Bxb7 { Now N(x)b6 is not needed anymore. } 13. Re1 Ne8 { Black expels the Bb5 with Nc7 and equalizes. } 14. Bf4 Nc7 $10 { Sokolov, Ivan - Fries Nielsen, Niels Jorgen, 1-0, Nordic Grand Prix, 1997, https://lichess.org/3MB9H7X9 } { The game is far from over, both sides have chances. That's what Black wants when he plays the Benko, that's what White wants when he plays 5.b6. }) 7... g6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Be2 (9. a4 a5! (9... Qxb6 { transposes to a line of the 5...Qxb6 variation where Black must be very careful to disentangle. There are many subtleties and subvariations, this is just impractical. Witness the following examples ! } 10. a5 (10. Nd2 $13 { [%cal Rd2c4] }) 10... Qc7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Rb8 13. Nd2 { Prevents the typical Ng4 Ne5 maneuver. } { [%csl Bg4][%cal Re2g4] } 13... Ne8 { Pins the knight on c3. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Gg7b2,Gb8b2] } (13... Rb4 $14) 14. Nc4 { And that unpins it. Black has a very crammed position now and needs to find a way to open the position. } { [%cal Rc4b2,Rc1b2] } 14... Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4] } 15. Ne3 (15. Nb6 Nd7 16. Nc4 $10) (15. f4?! Nxc4 16. Bxc4 $15 { Moskalenko, Viktor - Tukmakov, Vladimir B, 0-1, Hoogovens-B, 1992, https://lichess.org/a7f5rfTw }) 15... Qd8 $13 (15... Qb7?! 16. f4 Nd7 $14 { Lautier, Joel - Malakhatko, Vadim, 0-1, EU-ch 2nd, 2001, https://lichess.org/ci04ekIG })) 10. Bb5 O-O { transposes back into the 7.a4 a5 line. }) 9... O-O 10. O-O Nxb6 { Now this move is safe. Black plans Bg4xf3, Nfd7 (or Ne8-c7 is White plays a4) and Nc4 once White's bishop has left the f1a6 diagonal. } 11. Bf4 Bg4 $10 { Pfleger, Helmut - Benko, Pal C, 1/2-1/2, Skopje ol (Men) fin-A, 1972, https://lichess.org/UTP95vCd } { One of the stem games of the whole opening system ! } *


[Event "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5: Zaitsev Variation"]
