[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "Zaitsev Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/1XXFtgZX"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.10"]
[UTCTime "19:50:11"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. Nc3 axb5 6. e4 (6. Nxb5 Ba6 7. Nc3 g6 { transposes to the King Walk or Fianchetto variations. }) 6... b4 7. Nb5 d6 { If Black survives the early attack, he will probably be better because White's knight is stuck. Still the name of Zaitsev inspires respect in all openings, not just the Spanish/Ruy Lopez. The variation claimed many heads before some clear solutions were found. } 8. Nf3 (8. Bf4 g5 { This antidote is very well-known now. } 9. Bxg5 Nxe4 10. Bf4 Nf6 { The move order is important. Keep the pressure on d5. } (10... Bg7 11. Qe2 Nf6 12. Nxd6+ $14) 11. Nf3 Bg7 $15 { White's positional counterpart for the isolated pawn and stranded knight is insufficient. }) (8. Bc4 { Graham Burgess calls this the "Nescafe Frappe Attack". White would like to push e5 and then d6 as a double pawn sacrifice. Not sure I want to advertise the brand, but in any case the verdict on this line is definitely not an advertisement :) . } 8... Nbd7 (8... g6?! 9. e5 dxe5 10. d6 $44 { White's idea, sort of saying "Pawns just get in the way of aggressive pieces" ! }) 9. Nf3 Nb6 { the key move in this line ; the rest is usual. } 10. Bd3 g6 $10 11. b3 Bg7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. O-O Ba6 14. a4 Bxb5 $146 { Stockfish } 15. axb5 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Qd7 $10) 8... g6 { No panic ! The Benko is actually a solid opening ; no big change in the setup is needed here. } 9. Bc4 { Reversing the move order of 8.Bc4/9.Nf3 denies Black the opportunity to answer with an immediate Nbd7-b6. } 9... Bg7 (9... Nbd7 10. e5 $13 { is possible and messy. }) 10. O-O (10. e5?! dxe5 11. d6 O-O $17 { No Nescafe Frappe attack ! }) 10... O-O 11. Re1 Nbd7 12. a4 (12. a3 $10 { is the same thing. }) 12... bxa3 13. Rxa3 Rxa3 14. Nxa3 Ng4 $10 { Bacrot, Etienne - Nisipeanu, Liviu Dieter, 0-1, Balatonbereny GM, 1996, https://lichess.org/WuMyyTFy } *


[Event "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5: Dlugy Variation: 5.f3"]
[Date "2019.04.22"]
[White "Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Dlugy Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/A-Cielbleu"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Accepted: Dlugy Variation"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "Dlugy Variation: 5.f3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/vKQprZRT"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. f3 { Dlugy Variation. First played in the game Maxim Dlugy - Lev O. Alburt, 1986. The idea is to get e4 in early. It's usually very sharp. } 5... axb5 { Much easier to play than e6. This line is at the same time simple and promising. With just a few branches to study, Black gets the kind of game he's looking for. } (5... e6 { This variation can lead to insane complications. In the stem game, Alburt chose the relatively submissive 6...Qc7 and gave White a stable plus. } 6. e4 Qc7 (6... exd5 { a more recent approach with enormous complications. "Don't try this at home" ! } 7. e5 Qe7 8. Qe2 Ng8 { What a sad move to make! } 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Nh3 c4 $13 { is the main move here, but it looks a bit dubious: it gives White Be3, which is very strong. }) 7. Nc3 exd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9. Qxd5 Bb7 10. Bf4 d6 11. Qd2 $14 { Dlugy, Maxim - Alburt, Lev O, 1-0, USA-ch, 1986, https://lichess.org/PG9HcGZu }) (5... g6 6. e4 d6 $14 { lets White implement his ideas, with a foreseeable advantage for him. }) 6. e4 Qa5+ 7. Bd2 b4 8. Na3 d6 9. Nc4 Qd8 { Why is this better than Qc7 ? White will open up the queenside with a3 and Black can answer with e6 if the queen is on the d8h4 diagonal (guarding f6, maybe going later to h4). On top of that, the queen on c7 is exposed to Bf4. } (9... Qc7 10. a3 bxa3 (10... e6 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Bf4 $14) 11. Rxa3 Rxa3 12. bxa3 g6 13. Qa4+ Nbd7 $14) (9... Qa7 10. Bd3 (10. a3 g6 11. Bd3 Bg7 12. Ne2 O-O 13. O-O bxa3 14. Rxa3 Qb7 $14) 10... g6 11. Ne2 Bg7 12. O-O O-O 13. a3 bxa3 14. Rxa3 Qb7 $14) 10. a3 { With just a few lines, Black will be ready to face 5.f3 provided he answers with 5...axb5. There is really just one theoretical sequence of moves up to here. } 10... e6 11. dxe6 (11. Ne3 exd5 12. exd5 g6 $146 { Stockfish suggests this configuration, with equality. } 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bc4 bxa3 15. Rxa3 Rxa3 16. bxa3 Bg7 17. Ne2 O-O 18. O-O Re8 $10) (11. axb4 Rxa1 12. Qxa1 exd5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Qa8 Be6 15. bxc5 dxc5 $10 { Kuzubov, Yuriy - Hendriks, Willy, 1/2-1/2, Hastings Masters op, 2006, https://lichess.org/if9TmUoi }) 11... Bxe6 12. Ne3 (12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 d5 14. exd5 Nxd5 $10) 12... d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bb5+ Bd7 $10 15. Nxd5 Bxb5 16. Bg5 f6 $146 { Stockfish } 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Qxd8+ Kxd8 19. Bxf6+ Kc7 20. Bxh8 Nd7 $10 { a material imbalance but a balanced position } *


[Event "Lichess study"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My"]
[Date "2019.04.07"]
[White "Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Declined, variation index"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/A-Cielbleu"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Declined: Main Line"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "PART 2 : B.G. Declined"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/c0lyQPr2"]

{ All chapters (12-20) are in cruise mode. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 (2. Nf3 { The best way to answer this move depends on your choice of variations in various lines of the Benko Gambit or in the Blumenfeld Gambit. } 2... c5 { recommended } (2... e6) (2... g6 3. c4 c5 4. d5 b5 { transposes to the text. }) 3. d5 b5 { recommended } (3... e6) (3... g6 4. c4 b5 { transposes to the text. }) (3... d6) 4. c4 { transposes to the text. } 4... g6 { probably best avoided } (4... Bb7 { recommended })) 2... c5 3. d5 { There are three major deviations on move 3. We cover the Vaganian Gambit. The rest is mostly a matter of taste. } (3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d5 6. cxd5 Bc5 { the Vaganian Gambit }) (3. e3 g6 4. Nc3 (4. dxc5 Na6 5. a3 Nxc5 6. b4 Ne6 7. Bb2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O) 4... Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 8. O-O Nc6 { reversed Tarrasch defence (many move orders are possible) }) (3. dxc5 e6 4. Nf3 Bxc5 5. e3 O-O 6. a3 b6 7. Be2 Bb7 8. O-O d5 { a very harmonious setup that bears no particular name }) 3... b5 { Why do you play b5 in the first place ? You may hope that White will take, but chess is not checkers. The overall plan is to undermine White's center in such a way that the pawn on d5 becomes a weakness, as well as the squares left behind by the advances of the c- and d-pawns (c4, d3, d4). That is why Black will play bxc4 on the next move unless there are good reasons to proceed otherwise. } 4. Nf3 { the major move in the Benko Gambit Declined. } (4. Nd2 { Declined/Quiet Line }) (4. a4 { Declined/Sosonko Variation } 4... b4) (4. Bg5 { Declined/Bishop Attack } 4... Ne4) (4. f3 { Declined/Pseudo-Saemisch } 4... bxc4) (4. e4 { Declined/Hjoerring Countergambit }) (4. g4 { Mutkin Countergambit }) (4. Qc2 { the most dangerous way of declining the gambit } 4... bxc4) (4. Nc3 b4) (4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 (5. cxb5 a6 { with a transposition to one of the main lines of the Benko Gambit Accepted }) 5... bxc4) (4. e3) (4. b3 { Quite often played by clueless internet blitz players ! }) 4... g6 { probably the worst plausible reply. It is therefore important not to answer 2.Nf3 with 2...g6. } (4... Bb7 { recommended }) (4... e6 { the Blumenfeld Gambit }) 5. cxb5 a6 6. Qc2 { threatens c5 and e4 at the same time. Black has no fully adequate response in the spirit of the Benko gambit. } 6... d6 (6... axb5 7. e4 $14) (6... Nxd5 $13 { a concrete line full of tactical content }) (6... Bg7 7. Qxc5 O-O $13 { a very sharp gambit }) 7. e4 $14 { White can castle, keep the pawn and leave his bishop on the f1a6 diagonal. } *


[Event "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5: Pseudo-Saemisch: 4.f3"]
[Date "2019.04.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit Declined: Pseudo-Sämisch"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "Pseudo-Saemisch: 4.f3"]
