1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. f3 { Declined/Pseudo-Saemisch. This is very similar to the ➡ Dlugy Variation: White wants to get e4 in as early as possible, but here without the pawn exchange on b5. As in the Dlugy, Black hasn't the typical maneuver Ng4 Ne5, because f4 covers g4. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rf3g4] } 4... bxc4 { Black doesn't let White approach anything close to the positional advantages he gets in the Dlugy variation. This capture will be our recommendation by default when White declines the Benko gambit, but it doesn't always work. } (4... e6 5. e4 bxc4 6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5?! { is asking for a very unique gambit: } (7. Nxd5 $14 { This move is the reason why we recommend bxc4 instead of e6. }) 7... d4! 8. exf6 d5! 9. Nge2 { White's best move is giving the piece back! } (9. Nce2?! Qxf6 { This pawn center is a huge compensation for the piece. } { [%csl Bd5,Bd4,Bc4,Bc5][%cal Gf6e5,Ge5e1] } 10. Nf4 Be7 $17 { d5 is protected indirectly, because Black always has a check and will recapture the piece. } { [%csl Bd5] }) (9. Nb1 Qxf6 $19) 9... dxc3 10. Nxc3 $15) 5. e4 d6 6. Bxc4 g6 7. Ne2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nec3 Nbd7 { Black tries to advance the knight to b6 with a tempo. } { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] } 10. Be2 (10. a4 Ne8 $146 { This thematic move is useful to control e5, to prepare for f5 and to expel a piece landing on b5. It is, surprisingly, a novelty. } 11. Na3 Ne5 12. Be2 { The bishop wanted to go there anyway, but now f5 is coming. } 12... f5 13. f4 Nf7 $10) 10... Rb8 11. Na3 { Jirka, Jiri - Vuckovic, Bojan, 0-1, MNT op 5th, 2004, https://lichess.org/OGebmklH } { [%cal Ra3b5,Rc3b5,Re2b5,Rc1f4,Rf4d6,Rc3d5] } 11... Ne8 { In almost any case, Black should play f5 next to open the position. } { [%cal Ge8c7,Gc7b5] } 12. Qc2 f5 13. Bf4 { Prevents e6. } 13... Ne5 14. Kh1 Bd7 $10 *


