1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 (2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 c5 4. d5 b5 { transposes. }) 2... c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 { Declined/Main Line. The most common response is: } 4... g6 { An attempt to transpose to the ➡ Fianchetto Variation later. } { Black won't have the usual compensation for the pawn in this line. Maybe he can get a playable game by other means, but even that is far from clear. } 5. cxb5 { more precise than 5.Qc2 immediately, where Black can sidestep White's idea with b4. } (5. Qc2 bxc4 (5... Bg7 6. e4 O-O 7. cxb5 a6 8. Nc3 d6 9. a4 axb5 10. Bxb5 Na6 11. O-O Nb4 12. Qe2 $14 { same idea as in the text : Black's compensation for the pawn is clearly insufficient. }) (5... b4 6. e4 d6 $13) 6. e4 d6 7. Bxc4 Bg7 8. O-O O-O $14) 5... a6 6. Qc2 (6. b6 { Very similar to the ➡ Pawn Return Variation, and Black follows the same plan: } 6... d6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. e4 Bg7 9. a4 Qxb6 10. a5 Qc7 $13) 6... d6 (6... Nxd5 $13 { trying to get a broad pawn center ; a concrete line full of tactical content. }) (6... Bg7 { See B. Alterman (2011) "The Alterman Gambit Guide : Black Gambits 1", Quality Chess, p.124. It transposes into Alterman's recommendation in the Modern system after 6.e3. Alterman claims full compensation in the following lines. } 7. Qxc5 (7. e4 O-O $44 { followed by e6 }) 7... d6 $44 (7... O-O $44)) (6... axb5 7. e4 $14) 7. e4 $14 { White will castle without any problem and keep his bishop on the f1a6 diagonal. } *


