1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 (2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. c4 { This move order makes 4.Nf3 the most important way to decline the gambit. }) 2... c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 Bb7 { recommended by a process of elimination ; essentially Bb7 aims at making Nf3 look like a loss of time compared with the variation 4.Qc2 and 4.Nd2.
My contributions to this chapter are based on Valery Aveskulov (2012) "Attack with Black", Gambit, pp.118. Although Aveskulov proposes a full coverage of the Blumenfeld Gambit (4...e6), he also studies this alternative line. } (4... g6 { The previous chapter explains why this move is dangerous for Black. }) (4... e6 { transposes into the Blumenfeld Gambit, a totally different opening with a superficial similarity with the Benko. }) (4... b4 { With a totally closed queenside, Black might end up playing on his opponent's field and, in particular, with very little winning chance. }) (4... bxc4 { The default move when White declines the gambit, but here it gives White so much choice that it is practically unwise. }) 5. Qc2 (5. a4 { the most frequent move, but the line is simpler. } 5... Qa5+ (5... bxc4 6. Nc3 { "would grant White everything he was hoping for." (Aveskulov) }) 6. Bd2 b4 { The queenside is closed, so Black must have a plan elsewhere. } 7. Qc2 d6 8. e4 Nbd7 9. Bd3 g6 10. O-O Bg7 11. h3 { preparing Bf4... } 11... O-O 12. Bf4 (12. Be3 Nh5 $146 { Aveskulov (with the same idea) }) 12... Nh5 { ...and rightly so ! Black plans e5 and Nf4, after which he will be on equal terms with White on the kingside. } 13. Bh2 e5 $10 { Brunello, S. - Swapnil, SD., 1/2-1/2, 7th Chennai Open 2014-15, 2015, https://lichess.org/qH0jgpYC }) (5. Nbd2 bxc4 6. e4 e6 7. dxe6 dxe6 8. Bxc4 (8. e5 Nd5 9. Nxc4 Be7 { also transposes into a line of the 4.Nd2 variation. } 10. Qb3 Nb6 $15) 8... Be7 9. O-O O-O { transposes into the main line of 4.Nd2. }) 5... bxc4 6. e4 e6 7. Bxc4 exd5 8. exd5 Bxd5 { The pawn-grab is the distinctive feature of the variation compared with 4.Qc2 bxc4 5.e4 e6 6.Bxc4 or with 4.Nd2 bxc4 5.e4 e6. While White regains his pawn by force, Black gets good squares for his pieces. } 9. Bxd5 Nxd5 10. O-O Be7 11. Re1 Na6 { Stockfish opts for a safety-first move. } (11... Nc6 { riskier } 12. Qxc5 Nf6 $13 { Tkachiev, Vladislav - Ivanchuk, Vassily, 0-1, EU-ch blitz 29th, 2010, https://lichess.org/lvq9cy1N }) 12. Bg5 O-O 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Qc4 Nc7 15. Qxc5 Ne6 16. Qd6 Rb8 17. b3 Rb6 $10 { Ojeda, José Luis - Dulany, Larry D, 1/2-1/2, Interzonal IT/1 Group H, 2014, https://lichess.org/i56sryKD } *


