1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Qc2 { Together with the Fianchetto Variation with 10.Rb1, the contemporary 12.a4 line in the King Walk Variation, and the Modern system with 8.Nge2, this is one of the most critical systems against the Benko Gambit as a whole. This is not stressed by repertoire books on the Benko, as far as I know. } 4... bxc4 { My contributions to this chapter are based on Valery Aveskulov (2012) "Attack with Black", Gambit, pp.112-3. This source quotes in turn John Watson (2012) "A Strategic Chess Opening Repertoire for White", Gambit, p.209. Quotations made for research purposes. } (4... Qa5+ { Watson quotes Nikolai Pedersen (not to be confused with Steffen Pedersen, quoted in other chapters of this study) : "Against other moves, I think White has good chances of an edge". Watson's analysis convinced me to look for equality in another line against 4.Qc2. }) 5. e4 e6 6. Nc3 (6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 Be7 8. Nc3 d6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bf4 Nb6 12. Nd2 { (Watson) } (12. b3 Bg4 13. Nd2 Bh5 $10 { Drozdovskij, Yuri - Kasparov, Sergey, 1-0, Champions Challenge 163rd, 2006, https://lichess.org/YNj30JQn } { (Aveskulov) } { [%cal Gh5g6] }) (12. Bb5 Nbxd5 $17) 12... Bb7 13. Qd3 Nh5 14. Be3 f5 15. Rfe1 Bg5 $10 { (Aveskulov) }) (6. dxe6?! fxe6 $15 { a broad center at no cost } 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bxc4 Bb7 9. Nf3 Nc6 $15 $146 { Stockfish }) 6... exd5 7. exd5 (7. Nxd5 $146 { It is a remarkable feature of Aveskulov's book that he considers some potential novelties for his opponent too ! } 7... Nc6 8. Bxc4 Nxd5 9. exd5 Nd4 10. Qd3 Bd6 11. Ne2 Qe7 $10 { "with a comfortable position for Black" (Aveskulov) }) (7. e5 Ng4 8. Nxd5 { Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar - Bareev, Evgeny, 1-0, Wch Blitz 5th, 2009, https://lichess.org/eEQxlnbR } 8... Nxe5! $146 { (Aveskulov) } 9. Qe4 d6 10. f4?! f5 11. Qe3 Be6 12. Nc3 Nbc6 13. fxe5 d5 $44 { "I would not like to be White here" (Aveskulov) }) 7... Be7 8. Bxc4 d6 9. Nge2 { (Watson's choice) } (9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O { transposes to the line 6.Bxc4. }) 9... O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Ng3 Nb6 { same basic plan as if White's knight were on f3. } 12. b3 (12. Bb5? Nfxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bc6? { a tempting fork } 14... Nb4 15. Qa4 Nxc6 16. Qxc6 Rb8 $19) 12... Nxc4 { (Aveskulov) } 13. bxc4 Rb8 14. Re1 Ng4 (14... Re8 $146 { Aveskulov's recommendation } 15. Bf4 (15. Bd2 $14 { (Stockfish) Given this assessment, I decided to stick to 14...Ng4. }) 15... Rb4 $10) 15. Bf4 Bf6 16. h3 { Sedlak, Nikola - Vuckovic, Bojan, 1-0, SRB-chT Cup 50th, 2007, https://lichess.org/C3onWRJp } { (quoted by Watson, with a transposition) } 16... Be5! { Watson only considers Nxf2 "!" and concludes to White's advantage. A correspondence game goes down Stockfish's first line to reach an equal position. } 17. Bxe5 Nxe5 18. Nb5 a6 19. Na7 Bd7 20. f4 Qh4 21. fxe5 Qxg3 22. Nc6 Bxc6 23. dxc6 $10 { Helbich, Dr. Ján - Schuster, Peter, 1/2-1/2, WC29/ct04, 2009, https://lichess.org/Z5GzoMX9 } *


