1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nd2 bxc4 5. e4 e6 (5... Bb7 6. Bxc4 e6 { does not amount to the same ! White keeps an edge here. } 7. Ne2 exd5 8. exd5 Bxd5 { The pawn grab is forced and turns to White's advantage. } (8... d6?! { fails if the bishop is already on b7. } 9. Qb3 $16 { Stockfish }) 9. Bxd5 Nxd5 10. Ne4 Nb6 11. Bg5 $14 { Richter, Michael - Mocchi, Tullio, 0-1, Nova Gorica op 05th, 2000, https://lichess.org/bAghUiIa } { Here Black has no time to develop his pieces while White regains the pawn. }) 6. dxe6 (6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 d6 { Black lets the d5 pawn in place while it stands in the way of White's play. } 8. Ne2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. b3 Nb6 12. Re1 { Moskalenko, Viktor - Torrecillas Martinez, Antonio, 1/2-1/2, Barbera del Valles op, 1999, https://lichess.org/jTOy8KH6 } 12... Bf5 $146 { Stockfish } 13. Qf3 Bg6 $10 { Black can now play Nfd7-e5. }) 6... dxe6 7. Bxc4 (7. e5 Nd5 8. Nxc4 Be7 9. Nf3 Bb7 { a position usually reached from 4.Nf3 Bb7 and very promising for Black } 10. Qb3 Nb6 $15 { Hoang, Thanh Trang - Gu, Xiaobing, 0-1, Asia-ch (Women) 10th, 2003, https://lichess.org/ToClByq3 }) 7... Be7 8. Ngf3 Bb7 { It is no coincidence that this bishop lands on b7 only after Ngf3. } 9. O-O (9. e5 Nd5 10. O-O O-O { is just another move order. }) 9... O-O 10. e5 (10. Qe2 Nc6 11. e5 (11. Rd1 $10 $146 { Stockfish holds the balance with White. } 11... Qc7 12. b3 e5 { followed by Nd4. }) 11... Nd7 $15 { Flear, Glenn C - Rowson, Jonathan, 1-0, GBR-ch 94th, 2007, https://lichess.org/E6vVInK0 }) 10... Nd5 11. Ne4 { Palliser, Richard - Summerscale, Aaron, 1-0, Oxford University op 2nd, 2002, https://lichess.org/wenmYQDD } 11... h6 $146 { Stockfish claims a slight advantage for Black after a consolidation. } 12. Qe2 Nd7 13. b3 Qc7 14. Bb2 Rac8 $15 *


