1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4 { The Sosonko variation grants immediate equality (e.g. after b4) but deprives the Benko player from his usual counterplay, hoping to outplay him in the long run. White intends either to fianchetto both bishops or to freeze the queenside and storm the kingside shielded by his space advantage. } 4... b4 { This move makes more sense when White cannot challenge the head of the pawn chain with a3. } (4... bxc4 { The default move simply doesn't work here. } 5. Nc3 e6 (5... d6 { just gives White what he wants. }) 6. e4 exd5 $14 7. e5 (7. exd5)) 5. Nd2 (5. g3 g6 6. b3 Bg7 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Bg2 e6 9. e4 O-O 10. Ne2 exd5 11. exd5 d6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Nd2 Re8 $10 { Brenninkmeijer, Joris - Fedorowicz, John P, 0-1, Hoogovens-B, 1988, https://lichess.org/k5tJFzXc }) 5... g6 6. e4 d6 7. f4 { Without this move, White has nothing to play for. } 7... Bg7 8. Ngf3 O-O 9. Bd3 e6 { a necessary concession } (9... Re8 $146 { Stockfish and Komodo agree on this improvement. } 10. O-O Nbd7 11. f5! $14 { But a "counter-novelty" gives White all the long-term trumps ! The queenside is permanently inert and White has more space on the kingside. }) 10. O-O exd5 11. cxd5 Ba6 $10 { After the bishop swap, Black plays to neutralize e5 and to mobilize his own pawn majority on the queenside. } { Rodriguez Vargas, Orestes - Magem Badals, Jordi, 1-0, ESP-chT, 1995, https://lichess.org/ec4RVQ2t } *


