1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Bg5 Ne4 5. Bf4 Qa5+ 6. Nd2 g5 7. Be5 Rg8 { much more promising than f6, according to Stockfish. } 8. f3 (8. b4 Qxb4 9. Nf3 { Murshed, Niaz - Hodgson, Julian M, 1-0, Lloyds Bank op 16th, 1992, https://lichess.org/gk7joRJf } 9... Nxd2 $146 { Stockfish, Komodo } 10. Nxd2 d6 11. Rb1 Qa4 12. Qxa4 bxa4 13. Bc3 Bg7 14. Bxg7 Rxg7 $15) (8. Nf3 $146 { sensible } 8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2 (9. Nxd2 d6 10. Bg3 Bg7 $15) 9... Qxd2+ 10. Nxd2 d6 11. Bg3 Bg7 $10 { Stockfish, Komodo }) 8... Qxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Nxd2 10. Kxd2 d6 11. Bg3 bxc4 12. e4 Bg7 13. Bxc4 Bxb2 14. Rb1 Bf6 15. Ne2 Nd7 $17 { Zsinka, Laszlo - Gonzalez Perez, Arian, 0-1, Barcelona Sant Marti op-A 14th, 2012, https://lichess.org/CeXkHlSc } { The game went down Stockfish's first line stemming from 8.f3 (with an hesitation about 12...Ba6 or 13.Rb1 Ba6, also slightly preferred by Komodo) ; Black pushes h5 and is simply a pawn up. } *


[Event "Lichess study"]
[Date "2019.04.07"]
[White "Benko Gambit"]
[Black "Declined, minor lines"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/A-Cielbleu"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A57"]
[Opening "Benko Gambit"]
[StudyName "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[ChapterName "B.G. Declined, minor lines"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/7XIbfKXH"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. e3 { In this chapter, we study briefly a lot of minor or even weird lines whereby White declines the Benko gambit. The main attempts at declining the gambit get their own chapter. } (4. e4 { Hjoerring Countergambit } 4... Nxe4 5. Qf3 Qa5+ 6. Nd2 Nd6 7. cxb5 { otherwise bxc4 } 7... Bb7 { the most precise according to Komodo } 8. Nh3 g6 9. Be2 Bg7 10. O-O Nxb5 11. Bxb5 Qxb5 12. Re1 Na6 13. Ng5 O-O $17 { Let e7 fall and win d5. } 14. a4 { a tactical skirmish that doesn't change the assessment } 14... Qb4 15. Rxe7 Nc7 16. Qh3 (16. Rxd7 Bxd5 17. Rxd5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Rad8 $17 { Black recovers the material on d2. }) 16... h6 17. Qxd7 hxg5 18. Qxc7 Bxd5 $17) (4. g4 { Mutkin Countergambit } 4... Nxg4 5. e4 d6 6. cxb5 g6 { White has no play on the g-file. } 7. h3 Nf6 $15 { Garrido, Denis - Lostuzzi, Manlio, 1/2-1/2, Imperia op, 1996, https://lichess.org/YzlqrFIh }) (4. Nc3 b4 5. Na4 d6 6. a3 a5 { a key move when b4 can be met by a3, here at the cost of a tempo. } 7. Nf3 g6 8. e3 Bg7 { If White just plays sensibly, he stands equal. } 9. axb4 axb4 $15 { This recapture promises some advantage. }) (4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 (5. cxb5 { no problem with a transposition, since d6 is as useful as g3. } 5... a6 6. bxa6 g6 7. Nc3 Bxa6 { one of the main lines }) 5... bxc4 6. Nd2 { On other moves, Nbd7-b6 might hang on the pawn. } 6... g6 7. Nxc4 Bg7 8. Bd2 Nbd7 9. Bc3 O-O 10. Nh3 Nb6 { The pressure on d5 forces White's decision. } 11. Nxb6 axb6 $15) (4. b3 { Quite often played by clueless internet blitz players ! Played in https://lichess.org/q4kDUgCO/black#7 against Fuxia. } 4... e6 { I prefer this approach by far. White defends the base of the pawn chain, but the head is as vulnerable. } (4... g6 5. Bb2 Bg7 6. e4 O-O { Just wait. } (6... d6 7. cxb5 a6 8. Nd2 O-O { Ponomarenko, Vi - Moiseev, Vik, 0-1, Tula GM 2018, https://lichess.org/y11KMpjq }) 7. e5 (7. Bd3 bxc4 8. bxc4 d6 { Black has a harmonious piece setup here and is probably already equal. Plans are e6 to break up the center and Nbd7 to b6 to add pressure on c4. } { [%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6,Gb6c4,Ge7e6] }) 7... Ne8 $10) 5. dxe6 fxe6 6. Nf3 Be7 7. Nc3 bxc4 8. bxc4 O-O 9. e3 Nc6 10. Be2 d5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. O-O Rb8 13. Rb1 Rxb1 14. Nxb1 Qa5 $15 { Istratescu, A. - Shoker, S., 1/2-1/2, 32nd Metz Open 2014, https://lichess.org/YCcRY2zQ }) 4... Bb7 $146 { a novelty designed to put pressure on d5 } (4... bxc4 { The default move seems to work well. What is White's bishop doing on c4 if e5-d6 cannot be achieved ? White has lost a tempo with e3-e4-e5, so Black can prevent White's central play without extraordinary measures. } 5. Bxc4 g6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 $13 { Van Foreest, Jorden - Fedorov, Alex, 1-0, 21st European Teams, 2017, https://lichess.org/jL5JNuBi
Still I find this position too easy for White. Black's play doesn't challenge White's routine. }) 5. Nf3 g6 { Black needs to be precise with the move order if he chooses 4...Bb7. Stay ahead in development and keep an eye on e5. Answer Nc3 with b4, e4 with Nxe4 and cxb5 with Bxd5. } 6. Bd3 Bg7 { e4 was not threatened because of bxc4 7.Bxc4 Nxe4. } 7. O-O O-O { In which opening can Black fianchetto both bishops and be ahead in development ? Now Rfe1 is met by d6 on top of the above scheme. } 8. Qb3 { Here Stockfish and Komodo disagree slightly. } 8... Qb6 (8... bxc4 9. Bxc4 Ba6 10. e4 d6 11. Nc3 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 Nbd7 $10 { Stockfish }) 9. Nc3 b4 10. Na4 Qc7 11. e4 d6 $10 { Komodo's line ; Black plans Nbd7, Rfe8 and e6 (e5 if White answers with Bf4). } *


[Event "Benko Gambit: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5: Vaganian Gambit"]
