[UTCTime "00:59:20"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 { In practice White may avoid the gambit. } (5. Nb3 d5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Qxd5 Nxd5 8. e4 (8. Bd2 Nc6 9. Nc3 Be6 $15 { Klement, L. - Simacek, P., 0-1, ch-CZE Blitz 2017, https://lichess.org/IMenCtdG }) 8... Nb4 9. Na3 Be6 10. Bb5+ N8c6 $15 { Riha, Vaclav - Votruba, Pavel, 1/2-1/2, Elekes Memorial-B, 1982, https://lichess.org/VIjC0mai }) (5. Nc2 d5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Qxd5 Nxd5 8. e4 Nb4 9. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 10. Bd2 Nc6 11. Bb5 Bd7 12. Bxc6 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Bxc6 14. Nc3 O-O-O+ $10 { Andersson, Ulf - Langheinrich, Ferenc, 1/2-1/2, Bundesliga 0203, 2003, https://lichess.org/8xOcRhaL } { This is the driest line of the whole opening system. Even Ulf Andersson could only get a draw here. }) (5. Nf3 e4 6. Nd4 d5 7. Nc3 (7. cxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Bb4 9. e3 (9. Qa4+ Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Bd7 $10) 9... O-O $146 { Komodo, Stockfish } 10. Bd2 Qd6 11. Rc1 Qe7 12. a3 Bc5 13. Ncb5 Bg4 14. Qc2 Na6 15. Bc4 Rac8 16. b4 Bb6 17. h3 Bd7 $10 { followed by Nc7. }) 7... dxc4 8. Bg5 Qb6 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qxc4 Na6 $10 { Harshkou, M. - Kovalev, Vl, 0-1, 84th ch-BLR 2018, https://lichess.org/HB4cImuF } { might be even more tempting. Just don't take on b2 ! } (10... Qxb2?? 11. Rb1 Qa3 12. Ndb5 Qc5 13. Qxc5 Bxc5 14. Nc7+ $18) (10... Be7 $10 $146 { safety first })) 5... d5 6. cxd5 Bc5 { This is the Vaganian Gambit. Black's moves are very natural and promise an attack on the kingside : e4, Qe7, Bf5, Nbd7(-e5), Rfd8, Rac8.
My contributions to this chapter are based on Valery Aveskulov (2012) "Attack with Black", Gambit, pp. 83,88 & 101. } 7. e3 (7. d6?! { mistaken but tricky } 7... O-O 8. Nc7 Ne4 9. e3 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 (10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3+ 12. Bd2 Bxa1 13. Qxa1 Qxd6 14. Nxa8 Bf5 15. Qb2 Nc6 16. Qxb7?? Rb8 17. Qa6 Rb1+ 18. Ke2 Nd4+ $19) (10. Nd2 Qxd6 11. Nxa8 Rd8 $19) 10... Nxd2 11. Nxd2 Qxd6 12. Nb5 (12. Nxa8 Rd8 $19) (12. Rc1 Rd8 $19 { Alekseev, Vadim1 - Kolmakov, Pavel, 0-1, Korolev-ch, 2002, https://lichess.org/5V9RdEiL }) 12... Qg6! { the move to remember } 13. a3 { otherwise Rfd8 wins (Aveskulov). } 13... Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Nc6 $15 { "followed by Rd8 and Be6" (Aveskulov). }) (7. N5c3 { If the other knight comes to c3, a6 and sometimes b5 guarantee more than enough compensation for Black. } 7... O-O 8. g3 (8. h3 Bf5 9. e3 Nbd7 10. g4 Bg6 $44) 8... Qb6 (8... Ng4 9. e3 f5 10. Be2 Nf6 11. a3 Nbd7 12. b4 Bd6 13. Nd2 Nb6 $44 { Kortschnoj, Viktor - Hernandez, Gilberto, 1-0, Merida m, 1996, https://lichess.org/441rCjkC } { This line is analyzed and deemed satisfactory by B. Alterman (2011) "The Alterman Gambit Guide : Black Gambits 1", Quality Chess, p.270. }) 9. e3 Bf5 { Aveskulov prefers this move to Bg4. } 10. Bg2 e4 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Nd2 Rfe8 $44 { Beliavsky, Alexander G - Vuckovic, Bojan, 1-0, EU-ch 10th, 2009, https://lichess.org/D1rUuuyO } { If White keeps the pressure on e4, Black will play Bb4xc3. If not, Ne5 (or Bf8/Nc5) targets the d3 square. }) (7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2? { not a transposition } 8... Qb6 $17 { The pawn on f2 falls. }) (7. Bg5? Ne4 { What pin ? } 8. Be3 Bxe3 9. fxe3 O-O $17) 7... O-O 8. N5c3 e4 9. Nd2 { White's move order may vary, but Be2, Nd2 and a3 are logical. } 9... Qe7 10. a3 (10. Be2 Rd8 11. Qc2 Bf5 12. a3 (12. O-O Nbd7 13. Nc4 Rac8 14. Rd1 Ne5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 $15 { Servat, Roberto - Hoffman, Alejandro, 0-1, ARG-ch, 1995, https://lichess.org/KixmTRqB } { Black's attack will be dangerous. } 16. Bd2 Nxd5! $146 { (Aveskulov) } 17. Nxd5?? Bd6 $19 { wins the queen. }) 12... Nbd7 13. b4 Bd6 14. Bb2 Rac8 $44 { Goldsztejn, Gildas - Degraeve, Jean Marc, 0-1, La Fere op 7th, 2008, https://lichess.org/eAQZjeuC } { Black has played all the thematic moves that ensure enough compensation. Either Ne5-d3 or an attack on White's castle will follow. }) 10... a5 { Most modern engines agree about this move. Don't let White push b4 early and play Na6, unlike in the main line. } 11. Be2 Rd8 12. O-O (12. Qb3 Na6 { a slightly unusual path } 13. O-O Bd6 $146 14. Nc4 Nc5 15. Qc2 Bc7 16. Rd1 Bf5 17. Rd4 a4 $44) (12. Qc2 Bf5 { The pawn on e4 was attacked. } 13. g4 { Otherwise Na6 solves Black's problems. } 13... Bg6 { Stockfish initially condemns this move. } 14. h4 h6 15. h5 Bh7 16. g5 hxg5 17. h6 Nbd7 { the key defensive move } 18. hxg7 Bd6 (18... Rac8 $14 { Modr, Bretislav - Tseitlin, Mikhail S, 1/2-1/2, Prague, 1983, https://lichess.org/YZDz0Y14 } { Engines tend to prefer White here. }) 19. Rxh7 Kxh7 20. Ndxe4 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 Kxg7 22. Bd2 Be5 23. d6 Bxd6 24. Nxd6 Qxd6 25. O-O-O Nf6 26. Bxa5 Rac8 27. Bc3 Qe6 $10 { Komodo and Stockfish finally claim equality here. }) 12... Na6 $146 { Stockfish and Komodo concur. } (12... Bf5 { is the only move played here so far. } 13. Nb3 (13. Qb3 Nbd7 14. Qxb7 $146 { Novelty. Black gets some counterplay for the pawn. } 14... Rdb8 { The queen has only two squares now, and it can be attacked on both: } { [%csl Bc7,Bc6] } 15. Qc7 (15. Qc6 Nb6 16. Nb3 Rc8 { [%cal Gf5d7,Gd7a4] } 17. d6 { The only move! } 17... Qe5 18. f4 exf3 19. Qxf3 Bxd6 $10 { [%cal Gc8c3] }) 15... Bd6 16. Qc4 Bxh2+ 17. Kxh2 Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4] } 18. Qa4 Nfg4+ $15) 13... Bd6 $10 { Pesa, Ladislav - Odeev, Ahmet, 1/2-1/2, WS/MN/081, 2012, https://lichess.org/pcd3XmlA }) 13. Qc2 Bf5 14. Bf3 Ba7 15. Ncxe4 Nxd5 16. Qa4 Rac8 17. Qxa5 Bb8 18. g3 Be5 $44 { Komodo and Stockfish agree on Black's compensation for two pawns. White's backward development and structural weaknesses around his king makes his position practically difficult to hold, especially after a few exchanges. } *


