1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. c4 d4 4. b4 { This is a reversed Benko setup, technically a KIA/Sicilian Variation. It's playable, but it gives the opponent a bit more freedom regarding their setup, because they haven't committed to anything yet.
The basic problem I have with it, is that White doesn't have to fight for the initiative. There isn't really a point in playing a defense as White, except when you know the theory as Black very well and time is an important factor (blitz or bullet). } 4... cxb4 5. a3 bxa3 6. Bxa3 Nc6 7. d3 g6 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. Nbd2 Nf6 10. O-O O-O $10 { White's extra tempo is sufficient for equality without worrying about move order subtleties, but not more. } *


