1. d4 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 2. c4 { [%clk 0:04:58] } 2... c5 { [%clk 0:04:59] } 3. d5 { [%clk 0:04:55] } 3... b5 { [%clk 0:04:58] } 4. cxb5 { [%clk 0:04:53] } 4... a6 { [%clk 0:04:56] } 5. e3 { [%clk 0:04:52] } 5... Bb7 { This is a game I played in June 2019, a few months after completing the Benko study for Fuxia. The game illustrates the point of playing the Benko, getting an imbalanced game with chances for both sides even against a prepared opponent. I like the 5...Bb7 move order in the Modern line, provided it transposes into the main line 5...axb5 covered in chapters 6 and 7. } { [%clk 0:04:34] } 6. Nc3 { [%clk 0:04:47] } 6... axb5 { [%clk 0:04:11] } 7. Bxb5 { [%clk 0:04:46] } 7... Qa5 { [%clk 0:04:05] } 8. Bd2 { This line is the topic of chapter 7, quite a popular line at GM level. } { [%clk 0:04:44] } 8... Qb6 { [%clk 0:03:48] } 9. a4 { Nf3 is often played first, but Black has nothing better than a transposition (and treading carefully, as this is the most serious attempt at an opening advantage for White in the 8.Bd2 Modern line). } { [%clk 0:04:32] } (9. Qb3 e6 { Karpov, Anatoly - Miles, Anthony J, 1/2-1/2, Interpolis, 1986, https://lichess.org/7g5VmxnI }) (9. Bc4 e6 { Beliavsky, Alexander G - Caruana, Fabiano, 1/2-1/2, EU-chT (Men) 17th, 2009, https://lichess.org/sCGZYXTR } { Aronian, Levon - Bareev, Evgeny, 1/2-1/2, Wch Blitz 5th, 2009, https://lichess.org/QGzejwKt }) 9... Nxd5 { [%clk 0:03:23] } 10. Nf3 { [%clk 0:04:24] } 10... e6 { [%clk 0:03:13] } 11. O-O { Here too White chooses the most challenging move. It is clear that my opponent knows the line quite well. } { [%clk 0:04:22] } (11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Bc3 Be7 { Fressinet, Laurent - Bologan, Viktor, 1-0, Bundesliga 1112, 2011, https://lichess.org/gx3iVD9G }) (11. a5 Qc7 { Farago, Ivan - Bogner, Sebastian, 0-1, Liechtenstein op 30th, 2012, https://lichess.org/f7nZjaZW }) 11... Be7 { [%clk 0:03:12] } 12. Qc2? $146 { The first deviation by White is a mistake. } { [%clk 0:03:07] } (12. e4 { a debated line in which White is scoring well } 12... Nxc3 13. Bxc3 O-O 14. Ne5 d6! $146 { a novelty introduced in this study } 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Qd3 Nc6 $10 { and Komodo finds equality in a few more moves. Stockfish likes White at first, but its assessment converges towards equality as its thought horizon expands. }) 12... O-O?! { I postpone Nb4 for a move. In blitz it's better to play safe rather than to fetch every opportunity at the cost of prolonged thought. } { [%clk 0:03:03] } (12... Nb4 13. Qb1 O-O $15 { a more accurate way of reaching the same position as in the game }) 13. e4? { [%clk 0:02:57] } (13. Nxd5 Bxd5 $10 { White can maintain the balance in this way. }) 13... Nb4 $15 { [%clk 0:02:54] } 14. Qb1 { [%clk 0:02:44] } 14... N8c6 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 15. Bf4? { [%clk 0:01:38] } 15... d5?! { The positional continuation brings me a better game, so I neglect time-consuming tactical shots. } { [%clk 0:02:03] } (15... f5 { exposing the bishop if Black is allowed to take on e4 } 16. e5 Nd4 17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. Ne2 Qc5 $17 { Now e5 is lost. }) 16. exd5 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 16... exd5 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 17. Ne5?! { Exhanges favor Black's central passed pawn and active bishop pair. } { [%clk 0:01:34] } (17. Re1 Bf6 $15) 17... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:01:37] } 18. Bxe5 { [%clk 0:01:33] } 18... Bf6?! { [%clk 0:01:36] } (18... d4 { again a more precise move order } 19. Na2 Nd5 $17 { White cannot escape Black's plan seen in the game. }) 19. Bxf6?! { [%clk 0:01:32] } (19. Qf5 $15 { With this move, White would at least fight against Black's plan. }) 19... Qxf6 { [%clk 0:01:34] } 20. Qd1 { [%clk 0:01:14] } 20... d4 { [%clk 0:01:11] } 21. Na2 { [%clk 0:01:06] } 21... Nd5 $17 { [%clk 0:00:57] } 22. Qd3?? $19 { falls into Black's threats. } { [%clk 0:01:02] } (22. Qd2 Nf4 23. f3 $17 { and the game goes on. }) 22... Nf4 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 23. Qd2 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 23... Bxg2?! { not the most efficient execution } { [%clk 0:00:37] } (23... Qg5 24. f3 Nh3+ 25. Kh1 Qxd2 $19 { wins the queen. }) 24. Rfe1 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 24... Bd5 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 25. f3 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 25... Qg5+ { [%clk 0:00:21] } (25... Nh3+ { the shortest path } 26. Kh1 Qxf3+ 27. Qg2 Qxg2#) 26. Kf1 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 26... Bxf3 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 27. Qf2 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 27... Bg2+ { [%clk 0:00:13] } 28. Kg1 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 28... Nh3# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { [%clk 0:00:10] } 0-1


