1. e4 e5 2. d3 { C20 King Pawn Game/Leonardis Variation
I made this study only because I always forget how to play against this opening. } 2... Nc6 { Protect the pawn prophylactically, develop a piece. Can't be wrong. } { [%cal Gc6e5] } (2... f5 { C20 King Pawn Game/Clam Variation/King's Gambit Reversed }) (2... Nf6 3. f4 Bc5 { C20 King Pawn Game/Clam Variation/Radisch Gambit }) (2... d5 3. exd5 c6 4. dxc6 Nxc6 { C20 King Pawn Game/Weber Gambit }) (2... Bc5 3. Nf3 d6 4. c3 Bb6) 3. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3e5] } (3. f4 { One of the critical lines, very similar to a King's Gambit. } 3... exf4 4. Bxf4 d5 5. exd5 Qxd5 { [%cal Gc8g4,Gf8b4,Gd5a5] } 6. Nf3) 3... Nf6 4. Be2 { Now we have something like an Italian/Two Knights, but White's light-squared bishop is awful. } { [%csl Re2] } (4. g3 { This will very likely transpose to a King's Indian Attack. } 4... d5 { Let's open the center while it's still weak. } 5. exd5 (5. Nbd2 Bc5 { [%cal Gc5f2] } 6. Bg2 dxe4 7. dxe4 O-O 8. O-O { [%cal Rd2c4,Rc4e5] } 8... Qe8) 5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bg4 { Invite White to weaken the king pawns a little bit. } 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O Be7 9. Re1 { [%cal Rf3e5,Re1e5,Rg3g4] } 9... f6) 4... d5 { Attack! } 5. Nbd2 { Transposition to C44 King Pawn Game/Tayler Opening/Inverted Hanham } (5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Bd6 7. Re1 O-O $10 { And here Black has already equalized: The king is safe, and both bishop are looking at White's king. F5, f4 might be an idea to keep White's other bishop out of the attack. For example: } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8h3,Gd6h2,Gf7f5,Gf5f4] } 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 f5 { [%cal Gf8f6,Gf6g6,Gc8h3,Gf5f4] }) 5... Bc5 6. O-O O-O 7. c3 a5 8. b3 Re8 9. a3 *


