{ The Grünfeld is already a very good opening for Black. Playing it as White gives us an extra tempo and an excellent game. }
1. Nf3 { There are many different possible move orders. I start usually with Nf3, but 1.d4 works too. The idea behind Nf3 is to discourage Black from playing the Dutch or some other exotic stuff. } 1... d5 { Black can't play e5, so d5 is just logical. } 2. d4 { We prevent d5-d4 by Black. } (2. c4 { Leads to a different, but also playable line: The Réti Opening. See https://lichess.org/study/PI8tnkhk }) (2. g3 { Avoids the cxd4 line for now. } 2... c5 (2... Nf6 3. Bg2 c5 4. O-O Nc6 5. d4 e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 { And we have the Reversed Grünfeld Exchange variation. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gg2c6] } 8... Be6 9. Nc3 Rc8 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Qa4+ Qd7 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7 (12... Bxd7 { doesn't work, because } 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 { drops the central pawn. }) 13. Rd1! { Pin the pawn. } { [%cal Gd1d7] } 13... Bc5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5+) 6. c4 dxc4 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4 b5! 9. Qd3 (9. Qxb5? Nxd4!)) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 (4... e5 { Maybe black's best response. Misplace white's knight before they put their own knight on c6. } 5. Nb3 (5. Nf3?! { Blocks white's own bishop, so c4 is not possible. } 5... Nc6 6. Bg2 Be7 { [%csl Bg5][%cal Re7g5,Rc1g5] } 7. c4 d4! { White should really not allow that. Completeing the development is now difficult. } { [%csl Ba3,Bc3,Be3,Bf4][%cal Re7a3,Rd4c3,Rd4e3,Re5f4,Gb1c3,Gb1a3,Gc1g5] } (7... dxc4 { Is also fine. } { Csala, Jan - Dovzik, Juri, 0-1, SVK-ch, 1999, https://lichess.org/UjkbIvIB }) 8. e3 { Challenge the central pawns immediately. Note that this is now really a defense, played by white. } 8... Nf6 9. O-O { Transposes back into known territory. } 9... O-O 10. exd4 exd4 $15 { Black is slightly better despite the IQP. The lead in development is of course just a dynamic advantage, so black is now responsible for the attack. }) 5... Nc6 6. Bg2 Be6 7. O-O h6! { No Bg5 for white! } { [%csl Bg5][%cal Gc1g5,Rh6g5] } 8. Nc3 Nf6) 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Bg2) 2... c5 { This is D02 Queen's Pawn Game/Krause Variation. Not a bad choice in general. The main move for White is c4 here. But that move has to wait. } 3. g3 Nc6 (3... cxd4 { is probably the best move for Black here. } 4. Nxd4 e5 { Note that there's no weak c-pawn for Black. } { [%csl Bc6] } 5. Nb3 Nc6 (5... h6 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O) 6. Bg2 { [%cal Gd1d5,Gg2d5,Rd8d5] } 6... Be6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gg2d5,Gd1d5,Re6d5,Rd8d5] } 8... Nf6 { Add a third defender. } { [%cal Gc3d5,Gd1d5,Gg2d5,Re6d5,Rd8d5,Rf6d5] } (8... d4) 9. Bg5 { Now d5 is hanging, Black has to play e4 or d4. } 9... d4 (9... e4) 10. Bxf6 gxf6 (10... Bxf6 11. Ne4 Be7 (11... O-O 12. Nbc5 { [%cal Gc5b7,Gc5e6] } 12... Bc8 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. c3 (14. e3!? { [%cal Gf1f6] } 14... Rd8 { [%cal Rd8d1] } 15. exd4 { Black doesn't have to take back immediately, there is time for } 15... Qe7 { first. } 16. Ne4 Rxd4 17. Qh5 $13) 14... Qe7 { [%cal Re7c5] } (14... dxc3 15. bxc3 Qe7 { [%cal Re7c5] } 16. Qd5 $10) 15. cxd4 Nxd4 16. Rc1 Bg4 { [%cal Rg4e2,Rd4e2] } 17. f3 { Uncomfortable for White. }) 12. Nec5 { [%cal Gc5e6,Gc5b7] } 12... Bc8 { Black's pieces are now "undeveloped". } 13. c3 { Challenge the pawn chain immediately. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gc5d3] } 13... dxc3 14. Qxd8+ Nxd8 15. bxc3 { This is technically equal, but easier to play for White. } { Villamayor, Bong - Godena, Michele, 1-0, Wch U20, 1986, https://lichess.org/f6JS8uci } { [%cal Gg2b7] }) (10... dxc3? 11. Bxg7 cxb2 12. Rb1 Rg8 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Bxe5! $16 { This is very good for White. }) 11. Na4 (11. Ne4 { Main move. The engine doesn't like it. } 11... Qb6) 11... Bd5 { [%cal Rd5g2] } 12. Qd3 (12. e4 Bc4 { [%cal Rc4f1] } 13. Re1 a6 $13) (12. c4 Bxc4 13. Rc1 Bd5 14. e4 Be6 15. Nac5 { [%cal Gc5b7,Gc5e6] } 15... Bc8) (12. Bxd5 Qxd5 13. c4 { [%cal Gd1d5] } 13... Qd6 (13... Qxc4 14. Nac5 { [%cal Gc5b7] })) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 $13 { Despite the weird pawn structure, this is fine for Black. }) 4. Bg2 cxd4 (4... e6 { This means that we won't see e5 soon. } 5. O-O { A49 Zukertort Opening/Grünfeld Reversed. Other move orders have other names, but the ideas are the same. } 5... Nf6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 { Black can play almost anything here. The main moves are Bc5 and Qb6. } 6... Bc5 (6... Qb6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 Nf6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. e4 dxe4 (11... O-O 12. exd5 { [%cal Gg2a8] }) 12. Nxe4 { [%cal Gg2a8] }) 7. Nb3 Bb6 8. c4 Nge7 (8... dxc4?! 9. Qxd8+ Bxd8 10. N3d2 { Black is now seriously behind in development and should not try to hold the pawn. } 10... Nge7 (10... Na5?! 11. Na3 c3 12. bxc3 Nf6 13. Nac4 { Threatening a check that ruins castling. } { [%csl Bd6][%cal Gc4d6,Bd6e8] } 13... Nd5 (13... Nxc4 14. Nxc4 { [%csl Bd6][%cal Gc4d6,Bd6e8] } 14... Be7) 14. Nd6+ Kf8) 11. Nxc4 O-O)) (5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nc3 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gc3a4] } 7... Qd8 8. e4! d4 9. Na4 { [%cal Ga4c5,Ga4b6,Gd1d4,Gf3d4] } 9... Be7 10. e5) 6. c4 dxc4 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qxc4) 5. Nxd4 e5 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 (7. O-O { to prevent checks per Bb4+. }) 7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Rb8 (8... d4 9. Qa4 Rb8 10. Bxc6+ Bd7 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 dxc3 13. Be3 { Hillarp Persson, Tiger - Goloshchapov, Alexander, 0-1, EU-ch 2nd, 2001, https://lichess.org/CQTZjtm2 }) (8... Ne7 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. c4 { Mahjoob, Morteza - Sheikhi, Mohammad, 1-0, IRI-ch sf, 2005, https://lichess.org/gGY6qZ7K }) 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Ne7 11. Qa4 { [%cal Ga4c6,Ga4a7,Gc4d5,Gg2d5] } 11... O-O $14 *


