1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5 { Falkbeer Countergambit, named after https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Falkbeer. This is a nice countergambit, that comes with a few traps. The first one is that white can't take fxe5. The only good moves are exd5 and Nf3. } 3. exd5 (3. Nf3) (3. fxe5?? { Blunder. Now white will lose material. At least! } 3... Qh4+ 4. g3 (4. Ke2 Qxe4+ 5. Kf2 Bc5+ 6. d4 (6. Kg3?? { This is mate already. } 6... Qxe5+ 7. Kf3 (7. Kh4 Be7#) 7... Qf5+ 8. Ke2 Qe4#) 6... Bxd4+ 7. Qxd4 { The only move that prevents mate! } (7. Kg3 { Mate in 5: } 7... Qg6+! { [%cal Rc8h3,Rd4f2,Rg6g3] } 8. Kh4 Bf2+ 9. g3 Qe4+ 10. Kh5 (10. Kg5 h6+ 11. Kh5 g6#) (10. Bf4 Qxf4+ 11. Qg4 (11. Kh5 Qh6#) 11... Qxg4#) 10... g6+ 11. Kg5 h6#) (7. Be3 Qxe3#) 7... Qxd4+ 8. Ke1) 4... Qxe4+ { [%cal Re4h1] } 5. Qe2 Qxh1 $18) 3... exf4 (3... e4 { Staunton Line. Not that good anymore, because d3 gives white a better position. } 4. d3 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne7 { Protect the king from checks along the e-file. } 8. dxe4 (8. Bxg7?! { This gives black the g-file. } 8... Rg8 9. Bc3 Bg4 10. dxe4 Qxe4+ 11. Ne2 Nbc6 12. Qd3 Qe6 $10) 8... Qxe4+ 9. Qe2 Qxf4 10. Bxg7 Bg4!) 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bb5+ (5. c4) (5. Bc4) 5... c6 6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. Nc3 (7. d4 Bd6 8. Qe2+ Be6) 7... Bd6 8. Qe2+ Be6 9. Nd4 O-O 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Kh8 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. O-O Qb6+ 14. Kh1 Rae8 15. Qh3 (15. Qxd6 Qf2! 16. Qxf8+ Ng8 17. Rg1 Rxf8) *


