1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 { Attacking e4 and forcing } { [%cal Rf6e4] } 3. e5 { Note that this creates some light-square weaknesses. } { [%csl Bc4,Bd5] } (3. d3 { Isn't really an alternative. Too passive, and it gives Black too many options, which means it's hard to prepare. } { [%cal Re7e5,Rd7d6,Rb8c6,Rg7g6] }) 3... Nd5 (3... Ne4? { Loses the piece with } 4. d3 { There is no escape square for the knight. } { [%csl Bd6,Bf6,Bc3,Bc5,Bg5,Bg3,Bd2,Bf2][%cal Ge5f6,Ge5d6,Gb2c3,Gc1g5] } 4... Nxf2 5. Kxf2) 4. d4 { is the main move, but there are playable alternatives. } (4. Nf3 { (deserves a separate chapter) } 4... Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 { Stoltz Attack } 6... c4 7. Bc2 Qc7 { [%cal Rc6e5,Rc7e5] } 8. Qe2 g5 $10 { Stoltz Attack/Ivanchuk Line } { [%cal Rg5g4] } 9. h3 Bg7) 4... cxd4 { Smith-Morra Declined } { [%cal Gd1d5] } (4... e6 5. Nf3 (5. dxc5 Bxc5) 5... Nc6?! { Sherzer Variation } (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 O-O) 6. c4 $14) 5. Nf3 { [%cal Gd1d5] } 5... Nc6 6. cxd4 (6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 d5 (7... dxc3? { Just helps White's development. } 8. Nxc3 e6) 8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O dxc3?! (9... Be6 10. Nxd4 (10. Bxe6) (10. Na3) 10... Nxd4 11. cxd4 Bxb3 12. Qxb3 (12. axb3) 12... e6 (12... Qxd4? { This is very good for White: } 13. Be3 Qa4 14. Nc3 Qxb3 15. axb3 { [%cal Ge3b6,Ga1a8] } 15... Rb8 16. Bf4 Rd8 17. Rxa7 $14) 13. Nc3 { [%cal Gc1e3] } 13... Qb4) 10. Nxc3 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bg4 12. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5c7] } 12... Rc8 13. Be3 a6 14. Ng5! { [%cal Gg5f7,Gb3f7,Gd1d8] } 14... e6 15. Nd6+ Bxd6 16. Rxd6 Nd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Rxd5 $10 { Kaeser, Udo - Holzschuh, Stephan, 1-0, GER-ch 77th, 2006, https://lichess.org/3TmHj26z }) 6... d6 (6... e6 7. a3 (7. Bc4 d6 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Nc3) 7... d6 8. Bd3 dxe5 9. dxe5) 7. Bc4 Nb6 8. Bb5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 { Now we have an IQP position. The knight on e5 is already well placed. } { [%csl Bd4] } 9... Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Nc3 e6 12. O-O $10 Be7 13. Qg4 O-O 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Bh6 Bf6 16. Rfd1 Kh8 17. Ne4 Qe7 18. Bg5 Bxg5 19. Qxg5 Qxg5 20. Nxg5 Nd5 2