1. e4 c5 2. c3 { Denies his knight the square c3. } 2... Nf6 { Takes advantage of the fact that White can't play Nc3 to protect e4. } { [%csl Bc3] } 3. e5 (3. d3 { Hardly in the spirit of the position. }) 3... Nd5 { The knight on d5 is not well supported and hence a target. } 4. d4 (4. c4 { Moves a pawn twice in the opening, and after Nc7 there's a hole on d4. } { [%csl Bd4] } 4... Nc7) (4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 (5. d4 { Often transposes the the main line. }) 5... Nb6 (5... e6 6. d4 { Transposes to main line }) 6. Bb3 c4 7. Bc2 { A very double-edged approach. The bishop on c2 is a bit vulnerable. }) 4... cxd4 { White doesn't have to capture back immediately, because the pawn is pinned. } { [%cal Gd1d5] } 5. Nf3 { [%cal Gd1d5] } 5... Nc6 6. Bc4 (6. cxd4 { Black's aim will be to reduce the effectiveness of the center via d6, because the pawns on d4 and e5 have quite a good cramping effect. } 6... d6 (6... e6) 7. Bc4 (7. Bb5? Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. bxc3 Qxc3+) 7... Nb6 (7... e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 dxe5 10. dxe5 O-O) 8. Bb5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. O-O e6 12. Nc3 Be7) 6... Nb6 7. Bb3 d5 (7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 $36) 8. exd6 (8. cxd4 Bg4) 8... Qxd6 9. O-O Be6 (9... dxc3 10. Qxd6 exd6 11. Nxc3) (9... e6 10. cxd4) 10. Na3! (10. Bxe6 Qxe6 11. cxd4) 10... dxc3 (10... Bxb3 11. Qxb3 e6 12. Nb5 Qd7 13. Nbxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4) 11. Qe2 Bxb3 12. Nb5 Qb8 13. axb3 e5 *


