1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nc6 { Stafford Gambit. There are two ideas here:
1. Get ahead in piece development by trading off White's only developed piece and opening the pawns for the second bishop and the queen.
2. Set up some traps. More on that later.
Also note that Black's king is pretty safe if it can castle queen-side behind those four pawns. } { [%csl Bd7][%cal Gc8g4,Gd8d3,Ge8b8] } 4. Nxc6 { White has to accept. It's an extra pawn after all.
Around 10% of online players will decline the gambit and go back with the knight. That's very fine for Black. } (4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qe2 Qe7 6. d3 Nf6 $10 { Completely equal position. }) (4. Nxf7? { A very rare attempt to play a bad version of the ➡ Cochrane Gambit. } 4... Kxf7 5. Bc4+ d5! { The one and only move here. } 6. exd5 b5! { Counter-attack. } 7. O-O (7. Bxb5? Qxd5 { [%cal Gd5g2] } 8. Bxc6 Qe6+ { Lure White's queen away from c2. } { [%csl Bc2] } 9. Qe2 Qxc6 $17 { [%cal Gc6c2] }) 7... bxc4 8. dxc6 Qd5) (4. d4?! { It is important to take out the dangerous knight first. The e-pawn can't run away. } 4... Nxe5 5. dxe5 Nxe4 6. Bc4 (6. Bd3 Nc5 7. O-O Nxd3 8. Qxd3) (6. Qf3 Qh4) (6. Qe2 Nc5 7. Be3 Ne4) 6... Qh4 { [%cal Ge4f2] } 7. O-O Bc5 8. g3 Nxg3 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qd5+ Ke8 11. hxg3 Qxg3+ 12. Qg2 Qxg2+ 13. Kxg2 d6) 4... dxc6 { Now White has to protect the e-pawn. My recommendation is the very rare move Qf3. Most white players will go for d3 or Nc3 } { [%cal Gf6e4] } 5. Qf3 { Novelty! Good move, and a good surprise. Probably better than Qe2, because it doesn't block the bishop on f1. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } (5. f3 { f3 is not a nice move, but it keeps the option to play d4 later in one move. } { [%cal Rd2d4] } 5... Be6 (5... Bc5?! { Looks scary, doesn't do anything. } 6. c3 { [%cal Rd2d4] } 6... O-O 7. d4 Bb6) 6. Nc3 (6. Qe2 { Blomqvist, Erik - Holving, Rasmus, 1-0, Rilton Cup 37th, 2008, https://lichess.org/o8s54TIN })) (5. Nc3 Bc5 { [%cal Gc5f2] } 6. Bc4? { Second most common move online. A mistake. } (6. h3 O-O) (6. Be2 Qd4 7. O-O Nxe4 $10 { Black gets the pawn back, and that's it. Equal position. }) 6... Ng4 7. O-O? { Most common response. Another mistake. } (7. Rf1 { Sad move, but necessary. } 7... Qf6 { [%cal Gg4f2,Gf6f2,Gc5f2] } 8. Qe2 Nxh2 9. Qh5 { [%cal Gh5h2,Gh5f7,Gc4f7] } 9... Bd6 { The only good move. } 10. Rh1 { And it's getting messy. } 10... Bg4 11. Qxf7+ Qxf7 12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13. d4 { [%cal Ge4e5] } 13... Nf3+ 14. gxf3 Bxf3 15. Rh3 Bg4 { Equal material, but Black has the bishop pair. Black has a slight edge here, but they has to avoid further trades. }) 7... Qh4! { This is already lost for White. } { [%cal Gh4f2,Gg4f2,Gc5f2] } 8. h3 Nxf2 { [%cal Gf2d1] } 9. Rxf2 (9. Qf3?? Nxh3+ 10. Kh2 Nf2+ 11. Kg1 Qh1#) 9... Qxf2+ 10. Kh1 Be6 $19 { We protect f7 and prepare O-O-O. } { [%csl Gf7] }) (5. e5 Ne4 { Trap! Most people will try to push that knight away, because it's so … close. } (5... Nd5 { is the best move. } 6. d4 Bf5 (6... c5 7. Be2 Bf5 { [%cal Gd5b4,Gb4c2] })) 6. d3? { And now Black is winning. } (6. d4 { The only good move here. } 6... Qh4 { [%cal Gh4f2,Ge4f2] } 7. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2f2] } 7... Ng5 { [%cal Gh4d4] } 8. Be3 Bg4 { [%cal Gg4e2] } 9. Qd3 O-O-O { White is still better, but Black is more active. The engine thinks White is almost winning, but there is still a lot to play for. } { [%cal Gb1d2,Gh2h3,Gf8e7,Gg5e6] }) (6. Bd3?! Qd4! { [%cal Gd4f2] } 7. O-O Be6 { [%cal Ge8c8] } (7... Bc5?! { Doesn't work. } 8. Bxe4 Qxe4 9. Nc3 Qg6 { [%cal Gc8h3,Gg6g2] } 10. Ne2 $16 { White is just one pawn up and therefore better here. } { [%cal Ge2g3] }) 8. Qh5) 6... Bc5! { TRAP. Yes, we let the knight hanging. } 7. dxe4? { And now Black can get the white queen. } (7. Be3 Bxe3 8. fxe3 Qh4+ 9. g3 (9. Ke2?? Bg4# { [%csl Gf2,Gd2,Ge1,Gf3][%cal Ge4d2,Ge4f2,Gh4e1,Gg4f3] }) 9... Nxg3 { [%cal Gg3h1] } 10. hxg3 Qxh1 $19 { Black is clearly better here: equal material, but Black's pieces are more active, and White has to defend. Black can also create a passed pawn on the king side. } { [%cal Gc8h3,Gh3f1,Gd1e2,Gh7h5,Ge8b8] }) 7... Bxf2+ { [%cal Gd8d1] } 8. Ke2 (8. Kxf2 Qxd1) 8... Bg4+ 9. Kxf2 Qxd1 { [%cal Gd1c2,Ge8c8,Gb1c3] }) (5. Qe2 Bc5 { [%cal Gf6g4,Gc8g4] } 6. h3 O-O) (5. d3 Bc5 { [%cal Gc5f2,Gf6f2] } 6. Bg5?? { TRAP. Simple opening rule: Don't pin the opponent's knight when haven't castled yet. Here's why: } (6. Be2 Ng4! { Best move for Black. } { [%cal Gg4f2,Gc5f2] } (6... O-O { Righi, Egio - Warlick, John W, 1-0, Manila ol (Men), 1992, https://lichess.org/TWHRlwX5 }) (6... h5?! { Most common move online. } 7. c3! { Threatens d4. } (7. O-O? { Black wants an open h-file for the rook. Castling will just give them that. } 7... Ng4 8. Qe1 Qh4 9. Bxg4 hxg4 10. Bf4 { [%cal Rf4g3] } (10. h3?? gxh3 11. Qc3 hxg2 12. Qe5+ Be6 13. Kxg2 Qh3+ 14. Kg1 Qh1#) 10... Qf6 { [%cal Gf6b2] } 11. Qc1 Bd4 { [%cal Gd4b2] } 12. c3 Be5 13. Bg3 Bxg3 14. fxg3 { [%cal Rf1f6] } 14... Qg6 { [%cal Gg6h5,Gh5h2] } 15. Qf4 $14 { [%cal Rf4f7] }) (7. Nc3? Ng4 8. Bxg4 hxg4) 7... Bb6 8. a4 { [%cal Ra4a5] } 8... a6 9. Nd2) 7. Bxg4 (7. O-O?! h5 8. Qe1 (8. h3?! { Most people play this online. } 8... Qd6 9. e5 { The only move now. } (9. hxg4?? { Mate in 5! } 9... hxg4 { [%cal Gd6h2,Gh8h2] } 10. e5 Qxe5 11. Bh6 Rxh6 12. Re1 Qh2+ 13. Kf1 Qh1#) 9... Nxe5 { And now Black has gotten the pawn back – and is better developed. })) 7... Qh4 { [%cal Gh4f2,Gc5f2] } 8. O-O (8. g3 Qxg4 9. Qxg4 Bxg4) 8... Bxg4 9. Qd2 O-O 10. Qc3 { [%cal Rc3c5] } 10... Qe7) 6... Nxe4! { Black doesn't need the queen anymore! } 7. Bxd8?? { And now it's over: } (7. dxe4?? { Opens the file between the two queens. } { [%cal Gd8d1] } 7... Bxf2+ { Force the king away from the queen. } 8. Kxf2 (8. Ke2 Bg4+ { The king has to take the bishop now … and leave the queen unprotected. } { [%csl Gd3,Gd2,Ge1,Ge3,Gf3][%cal Gf2e3,Gf2e1,Gd8d2,Gg4f3] } 9. Kxf2 Qxd1 $19) 8... Qxd1 $19) (7. Be3 Bxe3 8. fxe3 Qh4+ 9. g3 (9. Ke2?? Qf2#) 9... Nxg3 10. hxg3 (10. Rg1 Ne4+ 11. Ke2 (11. Rg3 Qxh2! 12. Rg2 Qh4+ 13. Ke2 Bg4+ 14. Rxg4 Qf2#) 11... Qf2#) (10. Qf3?? Ne4+! { [%cal Ge4f2,Gh4f2] } 11. Kd1 Bg4 12. Qxg4 Nf2+ 13. Kd2 Nxg4 $19) 10... Qxh1) (7. Qe2 Bxf2+ (7... Qxg5 8. Qxe4+ Kd8 { [%cal Gh8e8] } 9. f4 Qf6 { [%cal Gf6b2] }) 8. Kd1 Qxg5 9. Qxe4+ Kd8 10. Be2 Re8 { Now Black is one pawn up and has the bishop pair. }) 7... Bxf2+ 8. Ke2 Bg4#) 5... Bc5 (5... Bg4 6. Qe3 Bd6 7. h3) 6. h3 { Protect the g4-square. } { [%csl Gg4] } 6... Qe7 7. d3 O-O *


