1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 { Russian Game/Three Knight Game.
White is trying to transpose into the rather dull Four Knights Game. That's okay for Black, but probably not what you want when you are playing the Russian Game. The best way to stay in the game is Bb4. } 3... Bb4 { Technically a gambit, because Black is giving up e5 … temporarily.
I found this line to be very easy to play with black, and my results are just great. If you play the Ruy Lopez with white, you should feel at home here with black. } { [%csl Be5] } (3... Nc6 { C46 Four Knights Game }) (3... d6 { Now it looks like something we can get from the Philidor. }) (3... Bc5?! { That bishop won't stay for long here. This is the reason why Bb4 is more accurate. } { [%cal Gc5f2,Gf6g4,Gg4f2] } 4. Nxe5 O-O 5. d4 Bb4) 4. Nxe5 { Now Black can either play Bxc3 followed by Nxe4 or castle first. } (4. Bc4 O-O 5. Nxe5 Qe7 { The knight has to go away. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 6. Nf3 { [%cal Gf6e4,Ge7e4,Gc3e4] } 6... Bxc3 (6... Nxe4? { That doesn't work yet. } 7. Nd5 { [%cal Gd5b4,Gd5e7] } 7... Qc5 8. Ne3) 7. dxc3 Qxe4+ 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Re8 { Prevents castling. } { [%cal Ge8e2] } 10. Bg5 Ne4 11. Bf4 { [%cal Gf4c7] } (11. Be3 d6 12. O-O $10) 11... d6 12. Nd4 { [%cal Gd4b5,Gb5c7] }) 4... O-O { Just castle. Black will get the pawn back eventually. } 5. Be2 (5. d3?! { That will not really save the pawn. } 5... d5 { [%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e1] } 6. Bd2 Re8 7. Nf3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 dxe4 9. dxe4 Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 Nxe4 $15 { [%cal Ge8e1] }) (5. f3 d5 $15) (5. Nd3 { [%cal Rd3b4] } 5... Bxc3 6. dxc3 Nxe4 { This is already very nice: black has the better pawn structure, and the king is safe. } 7. Be2 d6 (7... d5) (7... Re8) (7... b6!?)) 5... Re8 6. Nd3 (6. Nf3 Bxc3 7. dxc3 Nxe4 8. Be3) 6... Bxc3 7. dxc3 Nxe4 8. O-O Nc6 *


