1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 (2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 { Bishop's Opening/Urusov Gambit. Note that in the Bishop's Opening an exchange on d4 has happened already. The ideas are similar, though. } 4... Nxe4 5. Qxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bg5 c6 8. O-O-O d5 9. Rhe1! Be6 10. Qh4 Nbd7 11. Bd3) 2... Nf6 3. Bc4 { Urusov Gambit. Black should accept it. } { [%csl Ge4] } 3... Nxe4 { The only move that keeps the small advantage. } 4. Nxe5 (4. d4?! d5! 5. Bb5+ (5. Bb3 exd4 6. O-O (6. Qxd4 Be6 7. O-O Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 8. Ba4 Qd7 9. Bxc6 Qxc6 { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gc6c2] } 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qc4!) 6... Nc6 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Be6 9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3) 5... c6 6. Bd3 exd4) (4. d3 Nc5 5. Nxe5 d5 6. Bb3 Bd6 7. d4 Nxb3 8. axb3 Nc6) (4. Nc3 { Main move. Transposition to C27 Bishop's Opening/Boden-Kieseritzky Gambit } 4... Nxc3 5. dxc3 c6? { Leads to a more quiet game, but White is getting the pawn back. } (5... f6 6. O-O (6. Nh4 { [%cal Rd1h5] } 6... g6 { Black has to cover the h5-square. } { [%csl Bh5] } 7. f4 c6 8. f5 d5 9. fxg6 dxc4 10. Qh5 Kd7 11. g7 Bxg7 12. Qg4+ Kd6 13. Qxg7 Qf8 14. Qg3 Be6 $15 { Black is still a pawn up and slightly better, but the position is probably easier to play for White. }) 6... d6 7. Nh4 { [%cal Rd1h5] } 7... g6 8. f4 Qe7 9. f5 Qg7 10. Bd3 g5 11. Nf3 $15) 6. Nxe5 d5 7. Bd3 Bd6) 4... d5! { This is an important move: It blocks White's bishop and opens the diagonal for Black's bishop on c8. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gc8g4] } 5. d3 (5. Bb3? { By far the most common move. But not the best. } 5... Qg5! { A great multi-purpose move that is pointing out all the problems of this gambit at once. } { [%cal Gg5g2,Gg5e5] } 6. Qe2 (6. d3 Qxg2 7. Qf3 Qxf3 8. Nxf3 Nf6 { Protect the d-pawn. } { [%cal Gf6d5] } 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 $17 { Black will now castle long. So does White. With the bishop pair (poiting already in the right direction) and the extra pawn, this looks pretty good for Black. } { [%cal Ge8c8,Gb8d7,Gf8b4,Ge6b3,Gd7c5,Gh8g8,Gg8g4] }) (6. O-O { Funnily, this is the main move online. } 6... Qxe5 $19 { And now Black is winning. } { [%cal Gf8d6,Gd6h2,Gb8c6,Gc8e6] }) 6... Qxe5 (6... Qxg2 7. Rf1 Be6 { Protect the d-pawn. Note that h2 is hanging. } { [%csl Gd5,Rh2] } 8. Nf3 { [%cal Rf3h2] } 8... Bg4 9. Bxd5 Bxf3 10. Bxe4 $7 Bxe4 11. d3 { [%cal Re2e8] } 11... Nc6 { This forces White to take with the queen. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 12. Qxe4+ (12. dxe4?! Nd4 { [%cal Gd4c2,Gd4f3] } 13. Qd3 Nf3+ 14. Ke2 Nxh2 15. Rd1) 12... Qxe4+ 13. dxe4 O-O-O) 7. d3 Nc6 8. dxe4 Nd4 9. Qe3 Bc5 10. Qf4 Qxe4+ 11. Qxe4+ dxe4 $15) (5. Qf3 { [%cal Rf3f7,Re5f7] } 5... Be6 6. d4 f6 7. Nd3 (7. Qh5+? g6 8. Nxg6 Bf7 9. Qh3 Bxg6 10. Qe6+ Be7 11. Bxd5 Nd6 { [%cal Gg6f7,Bd6f7] } 12. Qh3 Nc6 $17)) 5... dxc4 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Be6 $15 *


