1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bc4 { Urusov Gambit. Black should accept it. } { [%csl Ge4] } 3... Nxe4 { The only move that keeps the small advantage. } 4. Nc3 { Main move. Transposition to C27 Bishop's Opening/Boden-Kieseritzky Gambit.
The idea is very similar to the ➡ Stafford Gambit: White gives Black a pawn and gets an open d-file and very fast development in return. } (4. Nxe5 { ➡ Urusov Gambit }) (4. d4?! { ➡ Urusov Gambit }) 4... Nxc3 { Black should take. } 5. dxc3 c6 { Leads to a more quiet game, but White is getting the pawn back. } (5... f6 6. O-O (6. Nh4 { [%cal Rd1h5] } 6... g6 { Black has to cover the h5-square. } { [%csl Bh5] } 7. f4 c6 8. f5 d5 9. fxg6 dxc4 10. Qh5 Kd7 11. g7 Bxg7 12. Qg4+ Kd6 13. Qxg7 Qf8 14. Qg3 Be6 $15 { Black is still a pawn up and slightly better, but the position is probably easier to play for White. }) 6... d6 (6... g6 { Closing the kingside immediately is certainly an option. } 7. Re1 Nc6) 7. Nh4 { [%cal Rd1h5] } 7... g6 8. f4 Qe7 9. f5 Qg7 10. Bd3 g5 11. Nf3 $15) 6. Nxe5 d5 7. Bd3 Bd6 $10 { Completely equal. This is certainly easier to play than the sharp f6 line. } *


