[StudyName "Spielmann-Indian: 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 c5"]
[ChapterName "Variations Overview"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9JuVuMvG/EPG2LXBO"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.09.15"]
[UTCTime "07:58:37"]

{ The Spielmann-Indian is named after Rudolf Spielmann (1883—1942), an Austrian chess player, whose risky play often reminded of the Romantic School of chess.

https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/eb/Rudolf_Spielmann.jpg

Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolf_Spielmann }
1. d4 { "Play the opening like a book, the middle game like a magician, and the endgame like a machine." —Spielmann } 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 { With this move White keeps the question of c4 open, depending on Black's next move. It is a way to avoid the Grünfeld, Queen's Indian and a few othe defenses based on White's c4. It's also a common move order to get into the London System. } { [%cal Bc2c4] } 2... c5 { A46 Indian Game: Spielmann-Indian. This is very similar to a reversed Réti Opening (1.Nf3 d5 2.c4) https://lichess.org/study/PI8tnkhk
The difference is of course that Black is one tempo down. Transpositions are not only possible but likely. } 3. d5 { A43 Benoni Defense/Benoni-Indian Defense/Kingside Move Order } (3. c3 e6 4. Bg5 d5 5. e3 Be7 (5... Nbd7 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. Bd3)) (3. c4 { A31 English Opening/Symmetrical Variation/Anti-Benoni Variation. As the name says, White refuses to play d5 and walk into Black's Benko or Benoni. } 3... cxd4 { And Black takes the center pawn of course. } 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d5 6. cxd5 Bc5 7. N5c3 O-O 8. g3 Qb6 { [%csl Rf2][%cal Rc5f2] } 9. e3 Bg4 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 e4) (3. e3 g6 (3... d5 4. c4 cxd4 5. exd4 { And now we have a Caro-Kann/Panov Attack with 5.Nf3. See my study on that: https://lichess.org/study/JWmJD6hp }) 4. Be2 (4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Be2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 8. O-O Nc6) 4... Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 8. Nc3 Nc6 { D94 Grünfeld Defense/Three Knights Variation/Burille Variation/Reversed Tarrasch }) (3. dxc5 e6 (3... Na6 4. g3 (4. c4)) 4. e3 Bxc5 5. c4 O-O 6. a3 b6) (3. Bf4 { A dubious attempt to get the London System. } 3... cxd4 4. Qxd4 (4. Bxb8 Rxb8 { And Black has the bishop pair. } 5. Qxd4 { [%cal Gd4a7] } 5... b6 6. e4 e6 7. e5 Bc5 8. Qh4) 4... d6 { comes with tempo: the threat is e5, forking queen and bishop. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 5. Qd2) 3... b5 { A46 Indian Game/Pseudo-Benko. "Pseudo", because there is no pawn on c4. Yet } (3... e6 4. c4 exd5 (4... b5 { E10 Blumenfeld Countergambit })) 4. c4 { A57 Benko Gambit Declined/Main Line. See https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/c0lyQPr2 } (4. Bg5 Qb6 { Protect the knight horizontally. } { [%cal Gb6f6] } 5. Bxf6 Qxf6 { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gf6b2] } 6. c3) *


