1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 { Pseudo-Benko. Similar to the real Benko — https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My —, but the pawn on d5 is weaker. } 4. Bg5 { Main move } (4. c4 { Transposes to Benko Gambit Declined, Main Line https://lichess.org/study/qaFqe6My/mBaMu1S4#7 }) (4. e3 { Here we have three options: Protect the pawn with a6, attack d5 with Bb7, or give a check with Qa5+. They are all fine. } { [%cal Rf1b5] } 4... a6 (4... Bb7 5. c4 g6 { And now we set up the usual Benko position. } 6. Bd3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 b4! 9. Ne2 d6 $10) (4... Qa5+ { I don't recommend this. The queen is misplaced here, and going back will cost some important tempi. } 5. Bd2 b4 6. c4 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Na3! { Tricks like this prove how wrong Qa5+ is. }) 5. c4 Bb7 { [%cal Gb7d5,Gf6d5] } 6. a4 b4 7. Bd3 g6 8. e4 d6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Nbd2 O-O $10) 4... Qb6 { Protects the knight from the side. } { [%cal Gb6f6] } 5. Bxf6 (5. a4 b4 6. a5 Qd6 7. c4 (7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. c3 g6 9. e4 Bg7 10. Bb5 Na6 $10) 7... e5 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ge5e4] } (7... Ne4 8. Bh4 Qh6 { [%cal Gg7g5] } 9. Nbd2 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 11. Nxd2 g6 $10) 8. Nbd2 { [%csl Be4][%cal Ge5e4,Rd2e4] } 8... h6 9. Bxf6 (9. Bh4 e4)) (5. Nc3 b4) 5... Qxf6 6. c3 g6 *


