1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. Bf4 { This is an attempt to get the London System. But if we take d4 right now, the typical London pawn chain is gone already. } 3... cxd4 4. Bxb8 { is the best move! } (4. Qxd4 d6 { Threatening e5, so the queen or the bishop have to move again. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 5. Qd2 { [%cal Rf4g5,Rf3g5,Rd2g5] } 5... h6 { Prophylactic move. } { [%csl Bg5][%cal Gh6g5,Rf4g5,Rf3g5] } 6. Nc3 e5 7. Bg3 (7. Nxe5?! dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. O-O-O+ Ke7 10. Bxe5 $17) 7... Bf5 { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gf5c2] } 8. O-O-O Nbd7 $10) (4. Nxd4?? { Serious mistake. } 4... e5! { And now we win material. } 5. Bxe5 Qa5+ 6. c3 Qxe5 $19) (4. c3 { A little gambit. } 4... dxc3 5. Nxc3 d6) 4... Rxb8 5. Qxd4 { [%cal Rd4a7] } 5... b6 6. e4 e6 7. e5 Bc5 (7... Nd5 { Avoids the queen trade. } { [%cal Gd5b4] } 8. Nbd2 (8. a3 Bc5 9. Qg4 O-O { Majzik, Levente - Kocsis, Janos, 1/2-1/2, HUN-chT2 9495, 1995, https://lichess.org/04IS7xJ8 }) 8... Bb7 9. Bd3 Be7 $15 { [%cal Ge8g8,Ge7c5,Gf7f5] }) 8. Qh4 Nd5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $15 { And this is quite good for Black: Ahead in development, bishop pair, and no pressing weaknesses. The king goes to e7, where it is relatively safe, because White has no dark-squared bishop anymore. After that we challenge the e-pawn with f6. } { [%cal Gd8e7,Gc8b7,Gf7f6] } *


