1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4 exd4 (3... Nxe4? { This is good for White. Comes out with equal material and a better position. Black should always play exd4 if it decides to accept the gambit. } 4. dxe5 c6 (4... Nc6? 5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Qd5+ Ke8 7. Qxe4) 5. Qe2 Nc5 $16 6. a4 Be7 7. Nf3) 4. Nf3 { This is the basic position for the gambit. } (4. Qxd4?! { Now it's a Ponziani Gambit. Allows Black to develop the knight to c6 with a tempo, because the queen is threatened. } 4... Nc6 5. Qe3 Bb4+ 6. c3 { Any other move than c3 allows Black to castle immediately – and then the attack is over. Downside: there is now only one square for knight and bishop. } { [%csl Gd2] } 6... Ba5 7. Nf3 $15) 4... Nxe4 (4... Nc6 5. e5) 5. Qxd4 { Bishop's Opening: Urusov Gambit, Keidansky Gambit } 5... Nf6 (5... Nd6?? 6. O-O f6 (6... Nc6 7. Re1+ Ne7 8. Bb3 $18) 7. Re1+ $16) (5... Nc5 { Played only once! See [Estrin - Taimanov] } 6. O-O Nc6 7. Re1+ Ne6 8. Qd3 Bb4 9. Nc3 O-O $10) *


