{ Every move is an answer to a specific question. If we are looking for the question to which 1.c3 is the answer, we might end up with: How can I play 2.Qa4? Sure, 1.c4 answers that too, but it gives Black a target and a lot of theory to continue. }
1. c3 { Now the only move that can prevent 2.Qa4 is b5. No one has ever played that. } 1... Nf6 (1... b5 { This gives White just the tempo back. } 2. e4 Bb7 3. Bxb5 Bxe4 4. Nf3 c5 5. d4 e6 6. O-O Nf6 7. Re1 Bb7 8. Nbd2 (8. Na3) 8... Be7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b4 Be7 $14) (1... d5 2. Qa4+ Bd7 (2... Qd7) 3. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7,Gb3d5] } 3... Nf6 { Black will get some compensation for the pawn, but it's not enough for an attack. The following line is generated by Stockfish 8, depth 30. } (3... Bc6 4. Nf3 (4. d4) 4... e6 (4... Nd7) 5. Nd4 (5. d4) 5... Nd7 (5... a6) 6. e3 Bd6 7. Be2 Qg5 (7... a5) 8. O-O Ngf6 9. f4 (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. d4 Rb8 11. f4 (11. Qc2) 11... Qg6 (11... Qh4) 12. Qd1 c5 $10) 9... Qg6 10. Qd1 (10. d3 O-O) 10... O-O { Completely equal, according to Stockfish. But I like Black better here. Their pieces are developed, and their king is safer. }) 4. Qxb7 Nc6 5. Qb3 e5 6. d3 e4 (6... Bc5) 7. Qc2 exd3 8. exd3 Bd6 9. d4 Qe7+ (9... O-O) 10. Be2 O-O 11. Nd2 Rae8 { [%cal Re7e2] } 12. Nf1 $10) (1... c5 2. Qa4) 2. Qa4 e5 (2... Nc6) 3. d4 Nc6 4. dxe5 Nxe5 5. Bf4 Ng6 (5... Bd6) 6. Bg3 Bc5 (6... Be7) 7. Nf3 (7. Nd2) 7... O-O 8. e3 (8. Nbd2) 8... c6 9. Qc2 (9. Nbd2) 9... Nh5 (9... d5) 10. Bd3 (10. Nbd2) 10... d5 $10 *


