1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 { A09 Réti Accepted. This is a very common – and serious inaccuracy. Black has now weakened their center, and there is no way to keep the extra pawn. But there are many ways to get an extremely sharp position. } 3. e3 { White will now regain the pawn and develop the light-squared bishop. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } (3. Na3 { Another option to regain the pawn. It's a bit slow. } 3... a6 (3... c5 4. Nxc4 Nc6 5. g3 b5 (5... f6?! { One of the main moves in the position. Prepares e5, but weakens the kingside. } 6. Bg2 e5 7. O-O Be6 8. b3 Nge7 9. Bb2)) 4. Nxc4 b5 5. Ne3 { Now White has moved a piece three times in the opening. Clearly not ideal. The slightly cramped position makes it not so easy to develop the bishops. This gives Black time to develop their own pieces without any pressure. } 5... Bb7 6. g3 { In the following three lines we end up in the same position after move 12. The concrete move order doesn't matter so much; just remember the resulting position. } 6... Nf6 (6... e6 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. b3 c5 10. Bb2 Be7 11. d4 O-O 12. Rc1 Rc8) (6... c5 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O Nf6 9. b3 Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Rc1 Nbd7 $10 12. d4 Rc8 $10) 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. b3 Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. d4 c5 12. Rc1 Rc8) 3... Nf6 { Black should not try to fight for that pawn. Just develop normally. } (3... Be6?! { Réti Gambit, Keres Variation. Black tries to hold the pawn. This doesn't work, and it's blocking the e-pawn. } { [%cal Re6c4] } 4. Na3 { We just attack it again, and now Black can't add another defender via b5, because we control that field too. } { [%csl Bb5][%cal Ga3c4,Gf1c4,Ba3b5,Yb7b5] } (4. Ng5 { Is also good. } 4... Bd5 5. e4 Bc6 6. Bxc4 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gg5f7] } 6... e6 7. d3) 4... Nf6 5. Nxc4 g6 { With the e-pawn being blocked, Black's best try is developing the dark-squared bishop to g7. } 6. b3 Bg7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Be2 $10 { We prepare castling too. This is fairly equal. White has still a slight edge. } { [%cal Ge1g1,Rc7c5,Re6d5] }) (3... Bg4 { This is actually rather harmless, because White always has a check to escape the pin. } { [%cal Gd1a4,Ba4e8] } 4. Bxc4 e6 (4... Nc6? 5. Qb3 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gb3b7] } 5... Nh6 6. Qxb7 Bd7 7. Bb5 Rb8 8. Qxc6! Rxb5 (8... Bxc6? 9. Bxc6+ Qd7 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 $18) 9. Qc2 $16) (4... Bxf3? { Mistake. This loses at least a pawn. } 5. Qxf3 { Forking two pawns. } { [%cal Gf3f7,Gc4f7,Bf3b7] } 5... Nf6 (5... Nc6?? { If Black doesn't protect f7, White has a mate in 3: } 6. Bxf7+ (6. Qxf7+ Kd7 7. Qf5+ Kd6 (7... Ke8 8. Bf7#) (7... e6 8. Qxe6#) 8. Qd5#) 6... Kd7 7. Qf5+ Kd6 (7... e6 8. Qxe6#) 8. Qd5#) 6. Qxb7 Nbd7 7. b3 $16 { [%cal Gc1b2,Ge1g1,Gb1c3] }) 5. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7] } (5. O-O Nf6) 5... Bxf3 6. gxf3 Qc8 7. d4 Nf6 8. Nc3 $14) (3... b5?! { Another attempt to hold the pawn. } 4. a4 { We undermine this pawn immediately. } 4... b4 { Probably Black's best option: give the pawn back, and grab some space. } (4... c6?! { This weakens Black's queenside a lot. } 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3b5] } 6... Bd7 7. Ne5! { A double-purpose move: it threatens the light-squared bishop, and it frees the square f3 for the queen. } { [%cal Ge5d7,Gd1f3,Bf3a8] } 7... Nc6 { Black has to close the diagonal pointing to the rook now! } (7... Nf6? 8. Qf3! { [%cal Gf3a8] } 8... Nc6 (8... b4 9. Qxa8 { Just take the rook. } (9. Bxc4 { Bxf7 would be mate now. } { [%cal Gc4f7,Ge5f7] } 9... e6 10. Qxa8 bxc3 11. Nxd7 { [%cal Gd7b8,Ga8b8] } 11... Nfxd7 12. bxc3 $18 { White will take tha a-pawn with the next move. } { [%cal Gc4a6,Ga1a5] }) (9. Ne2 { Playable, but probably too passive for the position. } 9... Bc6 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. Qxc6+ Nd7 12. Qxc4 $18 { White is just one piece up. Still winning. }) 9... bxc3 10. Nxd7 (10. bxc3 { Keeps the pawn structure intact. } 10... e6 11. Nxd7 Nfxd7 12. Bxc4 $18) 10... cxd2+ 11. Bxd2 Nfxd7 12. Bxc4 $18 { White is up an exchange, and that plus the bishop pair should be enough to convert the advantage. })) 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 9. Nxb5 { And now the pawn on c4 is hanging again. } { [%csl Gc4] } 9... e6 10. Bxc4 $16 { White is one pawn up and has some nice threats already. Clearly better. } { [%cal Ga1a6,Gd1f3] }) (4... bxa4? 5. Ne5! { This comes with the very strong thread of Qa4+. } { [%csl Bd7,Bc6][%cal Ge5d7,Gd1a4,Ba4d7,Ge5c6] }) 5. Bxc4 e6 6. O-O Nf6) (3... a6 { This does the sharper positions with Qa4+. } 4. Bxc4 e6 (4... b5? 5. Bxf7+! Kxf7 6. Ne5+ Kf6 (6... Ke8) (6... Ke6) 7. d4 { [%cal Gd1f3] } 7... Qd5 { [%csl Rg2][%cal Rd5g2] } 8. O-O g6 9. e4! Qxe4)) 4. Bxc4 e6 (4... Nc6? { A strategic mistake: Now Black cannot challenge White's d-pawn with c5 anymore, once d2-d4 is played. } 5. d4 (5. O-O { Passive, but absolutely fine. } 5... e6 (5... e5? { The second most common move on lichess! It's bad, really bad. } 6. Ng5! { This loses a pawn. At least. } { [%cal Gc4f7,Gg5f7] } 6... Be6 (6... Bg4 7. Bxf7+ Kd7 (7... Ke7 8. f3 h6 9. fxg4 hxg5 10. Bg6 $16) 8. f3 h6 9. Nc3 hxg5 10. fxg4 $16) 7. Nxe6 fxe6 8. Bxe6 $16) 6. d4 Bd6) 5... Bg4?! (5... g6 6. Qb3 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gb3b7] } 6... e6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O) 6. Qb3! { Attacking two pawns in one move. } { [%cal Gb3b7,Gc4f7] } 6... e6 { Of course. f7 is more important than b7. } 7. Qxb7 Bxf3 8. gxf3 { [%cal Gb7c6] } 8... Nb4 { Threatening a fork. } { [%cal Rb4c2] } 9. Bb5+ { White has active counterplay. } 9... Nd7 (9... c6 10. Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. Qxc6+ Nd7 12. Nc3 Rc8 13. Qa4 $16 { [%cal Ga4a7] }) 10. Bxd7+ { [%cal Gb7a8,Rd8a8] } 10... Kxd7 11. Qb5+ c6 12. Qc4 $16 { Covers c2. } { [%cal Gc4c2] }) (4... a6 5. d4 { This is a position that results from a QGA in most cases. } 5... e6 (5... b5) (5... c5) 6. O-O c5 { Transposition: D27 Queen's Gambit Accepted/Classical Defense/Main Line }) (4... Bg4? { White can win a pawn here: } 5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Ne5+ Ke8 7. Nxg4 { [%cal Gd1g4] }) 5. O-O c5 { This is why Nc6 earlier is bad. White has wide range of choices here for the continuation. } 6. d4 { This transposes to the Queen's Gambit Accepted. } (6. Nc3) (6. b3 Nc6 7. Bb2 { This is a line that you also can get out of a Nimzo-Larsen Attack. } 7... Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bd7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nf3 Bc6) (6. Qe2 a6) 6... a6 { [%cal Rb7b5] } (6... cxd4) (6... Nbd7) (6... Nc6) 7. Bb3 (7. dxc5) (7. a4) (7. Qe2) (7. Be2) (7. Nbd2) (7. Bd3?!) (7. b3) 7... Nc6 (7... cxd4) (7... Be7) (7... Nbd7) (7... b5 { [%cal Rc5c4] } 8. a4 b4 (8... Bb7) (8... c4 9. Bc2 Bb7 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. b3 cxb3 13. Bd3 { Attack two pawns with one move. Black has no way to hold both. } { [%cal Gd1b3,Gd3b5] } 13... b4 { [%cal Bf8b4] })) *


