1. Nf3 { d5 is not the only response Black can play. We need to know a few lines more. } 1... Nf6 { Here we will play } (1... c5 { e4 would transpose to a Sicilian, something I don't like. g3 allows b5, a very tricky line that I just don't want to learn. } 2. b4 (2. c4)) (1... g6) (1... f5) (1... d6) (1... e6) (1... b5 { Polish Defense } 2. e4 Bb7 3. d4 Bxe4 (3... a6 4. Bd3) 4. Bxb5 $14) 2. c4 { Here we have an English opening that can transpose into a King's Indian, if we allow it. But there are other options, the Neo-Catalan for example which is closer to the Réti. } 2... c5 (2... b6 { A15 English Opening/Anglo-Indian Defense/Queen's Indian Formation. A line suggested by Kaufman and Tiviakov.
Kaufman recommends to meet g3 with g6 and go for a double fianchetto. Otherwise play e6 and develop Black's dark-squared bishop towards c5. } { [%cal Gg2g3,Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Rb1c3,Re7e6] } 3. g3 (3. d4 Bb7 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 (5. a3 { E17 Queen's Indian Defense/Kasparov-Petrosian Variation } 5... d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Qc2 Nxc3 8. bxc3 (8. Qxc3)) 5... h6 6. Bh4 Be7 { Kaufman's line }) 3... Bb7 4. Bg2 g6 5. d4 Bg7 { Tiviakov's line }) (2... g6 3. Nc3 (3. g3 { We delay d4 as long as possible, maybe forever and play just d3 instead when necessary. } 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 6... e5 { Black's kingside development is complete, the typical e5 break prepares the queenside development. d4 is possible now, but let's play d3 instead. } 7. d3 (7. d4 Nbd7 { And we are in the King's Indian Defense again. } 8. e4 c6 9. h3 Qb6 10. Re1 exd4 11. Nxd4 Ne8 12. Nb3) 7... Nc6 8. Rb1 { Step out of the diagonal, and play b4 next if Black doesn't play a5 now. } { [%cal Rg7b2] } 8... a5 (8... h6 9. b4 Be6 10. b5 Ne7 11. Nd2 { [%cal Gg2b7] } 11... Qc8 { [%cal Rc8b7] })) (3. b4) 3... Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 { The board position becomes very closed now, and Black gets their kingside attack. } 12. Bf2 g5 13. Rc1 Ng6 14. c5 Nxc5 15. b4 Na6 16. Nd3 Rf7 17. Nb5 Bd7 18. a4 h5 19. Nxa7 Bf8 20. Nb5 Rg7 21. Kh1 Nh4 22. Rg1 g4 23. fxg4 hxg4 24. g3 f3 25. gxh4 fxe2 26. Qxe2 { White is fine here, but … this is not my taste. }) 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Rd1 a6 10. b3 Nbd7 11. e4 Qc8 12. Bb2 O-O *


