1. Nf3 c6 { Slav Invitation } 2. c4 { We play c4 anyway. e4 would transpose to a Caro-Kann. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd5,Gb5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc4b5,Gf3e5] } (2. e4 d5 { Caro-Kann } 3. Nc3 { B10 Caro-Kann Defense/Two Knights Attack }) 2... d5 { If we play d4 here, we are in an actual Slav Defense. Which is fine, but there's a lot of theory to know, and the c6 player might be prepared better. } (2... Nf6) 3. e3 (3. d4 { D11 Slav Defense/Modern Line }) 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 (4... a6 { is also common. It does prevent checks on a4 or b5 after cxd5 cxd5. } { [%csl Rb5,Rc4,Ra4][%cal Ra6b5,Rb7b5,Rb5c4,Rb5a4] } 5. Qc2 { is a useful move. Steps out of a possible queen trade and keeps an eye on e4.
Typical follow-ups are g6 and e6: Black wants to develop the dark-squared bishop. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2e4,Bd1d8,Bd8d1] } 5... g6 (5... e6 { Locks the light-squared bishop in temporarily. } { [%csl Bc8] } 6. b3 { Black should try to get more space in the center now by playing c5 or e5 soon. } 6... c5 (6... Bd6) (6... Nbd7 { prepares e5 } 7. Bb2 Bd6 { And now it's finally time to play d4: } { [%cal Rd6e5,Rd7e5] } 8. d4 { [%cal Gc4c5,Rd6e5,Rd7e5,Gd4e5] } 8... O-O 9. Be2 e5 10. cxd5 (10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. O-O Be6 $14 { Same position as after 10.cxd5. }) (10. Nxe5?! { The problem with this move is that Black is in time to protect the d-pawn with the queen, avoiding the IQP. } 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. O-O (12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 { Still no IQP. } 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. O-O Bf5 { This is completely equal and maybe even easier to play for Black, because the queenside pawns are on the right color, complementing the bishop. White on the other hand will it find easier to claim the open file, because the entry square d1 is covered by their bishop. } { [%csl Ba6,Bb7,Bc6,Rf5,Gd1,Gd8][%cal Ge2d1] }) 12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qe7 $10) 10... cxd5 11. dxe5 { And now Black has an IQP. } { [%csl Bd5] } 11... Nxe5 12. O-O Be6 $14 { This is good for White: The isolani is a liability in Black's position that makes it very unattractive to go into and endgame. This means trading pieces is in White's favor. } { [%cal Gf3e5,Bf2f4] }))) *


