1. Nf3 e5 { This is usually a plain mistake. Unless it isn't. } 2. Nxe5 Nc6 { And here comes the point: Similar to the Stafford Gambit (https://lichess.org/study/yVVpkkLT/iwwKQBmZ), Black plans to get a very quick development for the pawn. } 3. Nxc6 dxc6 { A04 Zukertort Opening/The Walrus.
White is technically better here – by more than a pawn, according to the engine. But in practical play this is quite dangerous.
My suggestion is to keep the position closed, let Black figure out how to get compensation, and develop without going for a space advantage. } { [%cal Rc8g4,Rf8c5,Bc5f2,Rd8f6,Bf6f2,Rg8f6,Bf6g4,Bg4f2,Bg4h2] } 4. d3 { [%cal Gc1f4] } (4. d4?! { Opens the position too much. } 4... Nf6) (4. e4 Nf6 { Transposes to a known position in the Stafford Gambit: https://lichess.org/study/yVVpkkLT/iwwKQBmZ#8 }) 4... Be6 (4... Bc5 { is not a good move, because in contrast to the Stafford Gambit, the e-pawn is still in its original position and can protect f2. } { [%csl Be2,Bf2] } 5. e3) (4... Nf6 { [%cal Rc8g4] } 5. h3 Be6) *


