1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 { Réti Opening } 2... c6 { c6 is one of the very few moves where White doesn't play cxd5. } 3. b3 { Anglo-Slav Variation, Bogoljubov Variation. Not playing d4 which would transpose to a Slav. b3 announces g3 already: White's bishop will press d5 from g2, so e3 isn't needed yet. Maybe e4 is possible later in one move. } { [%csl Be2,Yd5][%cal Bg2g3,Bf1g2,Yg2d5,Be2e4] } (3. d4 { Slav Defense }) 3... Bf5 { Like in the Caro-Kann, Black wants to get the bishop out of the pawn chain before playing e6. } { [%cal Re7e6] } 4. g3 Nf6 { London Defensive System.
The move order is not so important here. For example Nf6 first and Bf5 after that is also fine.
White can also play b3 on move 2 and so on. } 5. Bg2 Nbd7 { Covers e5. and protects the other knight on f6. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rd7e5,Gf3e5,Bd7f6] } 6. Bb2 e6 7. O-O Bd6 (7... h6 { Is nowadays the main move. It prevents Ng5, and it creates a retreat square for the light-squared bishop. } { [%csl Bh7,Rg5][%cal Gf3g5,Bf5h7] }) 8. d3 { The idea of this move is to discourage Black from playing b5 and to create a free square for the queenside knight. } { [%cal Rb7b5,Gb1d2] } (8. d4 { Also playable, but it does block the dark-squared bishop and allows b5 later or even immediately. } 8... b5 { My recommendation for Black. } 9. cxd5 (9. Nbd2 bxc4 10. bxc4 Rb8 { [%cal Rb8b2] } 11. Bc3 { Again, Black wins the open file, and the dark-squared bishop is slightly misplaced (and still blocked by White's own pawn). } { [%csl Bd4,Bc3] }) (9. cxb5 cxb5 10. Nc3 b4 { This is an annoying outpost in White's camp. } { [%csl Bb4] } 11. Na4 { This knight is out of play at the moment: no good squares to go. } { [%csl Rc5,Rb6,Rc3][%cal Ra7b6,Rd7b6,Rd7c5,Rb4c3] } 11... Rc8 { Take the open file. } 12. Rc1 { Challenge it immediately. } 12... O-O { This is still equal of course, just a bit uncomfortable for White. } { Couppey, Philippe - Lepelletier, Benoit, 0-1, FRA-chT2, 1994, https://lichess.org/myfe0jwv }) 9... cxd5 { Black is faster on that open file, and b4 is mildly annoying for White. } { [%cal Rc8c2,Ra8c8,Rb5b4] }) 8... O-O 9. Nbd2 { Note how both sides have developed their minor pieces: The bishops are free to move, not blocked by pawns (although White's light-squared bishop isn't so active at the moment). The knights protect each other and control important central squares.
Black has made good use of the extra tempo White needed for the double fianchetto and completed their development first.
However, White can trade off a knight for Black's (bad) light-squared bishop whenever they want. This means Black has to come up with an active move right now. } 9... e5 { Very aggressive. Black's threat is now d4, and this would restrict White's play for a long time.. } { [%cal Rd5d4] } (9... Qe7 { Nowadays the main move. It connects the rooks and protects the dark-squared bishop. It also clears the d8 square for Rad8 to help out in the center. And it overprotects the square c5, so White can not play c4-c5 in the near future. } { [%csl Bc5][%cal Rd6a3,Ra8d8] } 10. a3 { Is often a move here with two ideas: Restrict Black's dark-squared bishop a bit and maybe shift the entire pawn chain on the queenside to black squares. } { Radjabov, Teimour - Miroshnichenko, Evgenij, 0-1, Budapest FS02 GM, 1999, https://lichess.org/IHQ9hZvF } { [%cal Gb3b4,Gc4c5] }) 10. cxd5 cxd5 { White should play e4 here to enforce further trades and open the center. } 11. Rc1 (11. e4 { Is probably better. It's also the main move in the database (22 of 31 games). } 11... Bg6 { Main – and best – move in any normal database. The Lichess database doesn't have a single game with it. } (11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. dxe4 Qe7 14. Qe2 Rfd8 15. Rfd1 $14 { Ribli, Zoltan - Lengyel, Bela, 1-0, HUN-ch, 1975, https://lichess.org/PMouQriB }) (11... Be6 12. exd5 { White has an isolani now, but this is fine with all pieces still on the board. } { [%csl Bd3] } 12... Bxd5 13. Nc4 { [%cal Gc4d6] } (13. Ne4 { [%cal Ge4f6,Ge4d6] } 13... Bxe4 14. dxe4 { And now White got rid of the isolani, and they kept the bishop pair. } 14... Qe7 15. Qe2 Rfd8 $14 { Ribli, Zoltan - Lengyel, Bela, 1-0, HUN-ch, 1975, https://lichess.org/PMouQriB }) 13... Bc7 14. Re1 $14 { This is great for White. } { [%cal Gc4e5,Gf3e5,Ge1e5,Gb2e5] }) 12. d4! $146 { This is actually a novelty. Black has to respond to the threat dxe5.
In previous games people have played Nh4, Qe2, or exd5.
The engine's top moves are d4, Bh5, and exd4. } 12... Nxe4 13. dxe5 { And here Black has an isolani. } { [%csl Bd5] } 13... Be7 $10) 11... Qe7 { Protects the e-pawn, and the dark-squared bishop. } { [%cal Re7e5,Rf8d8,Ra8c8] } 12. Rc2 { Black should play h6 here to prevent Ng5. Or Be6 to meet e4 with d4. } (12. e4 { Still the best move. } 12... dxe4 (12... Bg4?! 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nc4 { [%cal Gc4d6,Gf1e1] }) 13. dxe4 Be6 14. Qe2 { Connect the rooks, so a trade on the c-file can be handled by the rooks only. } 14... Rac8 { [%cal Gf1c1,Ge2b5,Gf3g5] }) 12... a5 (12... Be6 13. e4 d4 14. Nc4 { [%cal Gc4d6] } 14... Rac8 15. Qe2 { [%cal Gf3g5,Gf1c1] } 15... Bxc4 16. bxc4 $10) (12... h6 13. e4 Bh7 { [%csl Bd3][%cal Rh7d3] } 14. Ne1 { [%csl Bd3][%cal Ge1d3,Rh7d3] } 14... Nc5 { [%cal Rc5e4,Rd5e4,Rh7e4] } 15. Qe2 $15) 13. a4?! { Inaccuracy. At least. a5-a4 was not a serious threat, and now not only the b-pawn is weak — Nc5 will come! —, but Black also has time to improve their position with h6.
Also Black owns now b4, a nice outpost later for a knight or a bishop. } { [%csl Bb3,Rb4] } (13. e4 { Again: this is the best move. It was never played in the game. } 13... Bg4 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nc4 { [%cal Gc4d6] } 15... f5 $14) 13... h6 { Black's light-squared bishop is now safe forever. } { [%csl Bf5] } 14. Qa1 $15 { Inaccuracy. Again. e5 is protected three times, and White cannot add a fourth attacker. Black is already slightly better. } { [%cal Gb2e5,Gf3e5,Rd6e5,Rd7e5,Re7e5,Ga1e5] } (14. e4 Bh7 15. Re1 $10) 14... Rfe8 { Overprotecting e5, so any of the current protectors can move away if needed. } { [%csl Be5] } 15. Rfc1 { This explains the idea behind Qa1: Making room for the kingside rook. But are these doubled rooks on the open c-file really so good? Where do they go? Black has all entry squares under control. } { [%csl Rc8,Rc7,Rc6,Rc5,Rc4,Bc2,Bc1][%cal Ra8c8,Re8c8,Rd6c7,Rb7c6,Rd6c5,Rd7c5,Rd5c4] } 15... Bh7 { A good prophylactic move. } 16. Nf1 { With the idea to move the knight to e3, but now b3 is unprotected. } { [%csl Bb3][%cal Gf1e3] } 16... Nc5 { And Black goes for the b3 pawn. See 13.a4. } { [%csl Bb3][%cal Rc5b3] } 17. Rxc5 { A rather drastic solution. There is some compensation, but probably not enough. } (17. N3d2 { Would protect b3 again, at the price of a very immobile position. } { [%csl Bb3][%cal Gd2b3] }) 17... Bxc5 18. Nxe5 Rac8 (18... Rad8 19. h4 d4) 19. Ne3 (19. Bh3 { [%cal Gh3c8] } 19... Rc7 20. Ne3 Qd6 21. d4 Bb4) 19... Qe6 (19... Bxe3 20. fxe3 { Damaging White's pawn structure. } { [%cal Rh7f5,Rf5g4,Rg4e2] } 20... Bf5 { [%csl Bg4][%cal Rf6g4,Bg4e5,Gf5g4,Gg4e2] } 21. Rf1 Qe6 22. Bd4 Rc2 23. Rc1 Rxc1+ 24. Qxc1 Ng4 25. Nxg4 Bxg4 26. Qf1) 20. h3 (20. Rxc5 { This is the best move Stockfish can find in the position. } 20... Rxc5 21. Nf3 Bg6 { [%csl Re2][%cal Rg6h5,Rh5e2] }) 20... Bd6?! { Inaccuracy. Now it's equal again, the engine even sees a slight edge for White! } (20... Bxe3 { Black could just start trading off material. } 21. fxe3 Rxc1+ 22. Qxc1 Rc8 { [%cal Rc8c1] } 23. Qa1) 21. Rxc8 (21. N5g4 { Would create a lot of pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal. } { [%cal Gc1c8,Gb2f6,Gg2d5] } 21... Nxg4 22. hxg4 { [%cal Gg2d5] } 22... Rxc1+ 23. Qxc1 Bxg3! { [%cal Re6e3] } 24. Bxd5 Qe7 $10) 21... Rxc8 (21... Qxc8 22. Nf3 Be7 $10) 22. Nf3 { Inaccuracy. A wasted chance. } (22. N5g4 { So much better. } { [%cal Gb2f6] } 22... Nxg4 23. hxg4 { [%cal Gb2g7] } 23... Bf8 24. Bxd5 Qd7 $14) 22... Be7 (22... Bxg3 { [%cal Re6e3] } 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24. Ng4 Be5 25. Nfxe5 fxe5 { And here's a nice tactic: } 26. Bxd5 { Black cannot take. } { [%cal Gg4f6,Gf6g8,Gf6d5] } 26... Qd6 27. Qxe5 Qxe5 28. Nxe5 Rc5 29. e4 $10) 23. Nd4 { [%cal Gd4e6] } 23... Qd7 24. Kh2 (24. Bc3 { [%cal Gc3a5] } 24... Bb4 25. Bxb4 axb4 26. Kh2) 24... h5 { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rh5g4] } 25. Qh1?! { Inaccuracy. This allows Black to open White's kingside. } { [%cal Gg2d5,Ge3d5] } (25. Nb5 { [%cal Gb2f6] } 25... Bg6) 25... h4 { And Lasker didn't wait. } { [%cal Re7d6,Bd6h2] } 26. Nxd5 hxg3+ 27. fxg3 Nxd5 28. Bxd5 Bf6 { And this is a very annoying pin that will decide the game. } { [%cal Rf6b2] } 29. Bxb7?! { Inaccuracy. Too greedy! } (29. Qf3 Rd8 30. e4 Qe7) 29... Rc5 (29... Rd8 { Would have won a pawn. } 30. e3 Bxd3 31. Bc6 Qd6) 30. Ba6?! { This does allow the queen to come into the game, but now the bishop is quite a bit out of play. The idea is to protect d3, so White can play e3 without losing d3. } { [%cal Gh1a8,Ga6d3] } (30. Bc6 Qd6 31. Be4 Bxd4 32. Bxh7+ Kxh7 33. Qe4+ f5 34. Qh4+ Kg6 35. Qxd4 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gd4g7] }) 30... Bg6 { Makes luft for the king. } { [%csl Bh7] } 31. Qb7?! { Hoping to get the black queen off the d-file. } { [%cal Rd7d4,Rf6d4] } (31. Bb5 Rxb5 (31... Qd6?! { Would allow White to consolidate the position a bit. } 32. Qg1 Rd5 33. e3 Rg5 34. e4 { [%cal Gg1d4,Gb2d4] } 34... Qc7 35. Bc4 Rxg3 { White cannot take back because of Be5. } { [%cal Rf6e5,Be5g3,Bc7e5] } 36. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5c7] } 36... Qxc4 37. bxc4 Rxg1 38. Bxf6) 32. Qa8+ Kh7 33. Nxb5 Bxb2 34. Qxa5 Qe6 { [%cal Re6b3] }) 31... Qd8?! (31... Qd6 { [%cal Rd6a6] } 32. Nb5 Qe6 33. Bxf6 Qxe2+ { [%cal Rc5c1] } 34. Qg2 Qxd3 { [%cal Rc5c2] } 35. Nc3 (35. Bc3 Be4 36. Nd4 { [%cal Ra6d3,Rg2e4] } (36. Qf2 Rf5 { [%csl Bh1][%cal Rd3f3,Bf3h1] }) 36... Qe3 37. Qd2 Rxc3 38. Qxe3 Rxe3) 35... Qxa6 36. Bd4) 32. b4 Rc7 (32... axb4 33. Qxb4) 33. Qb6 Rd7 34. Qxd8+ Rxd8 35. e3?! (35. Nc6 Rd6 { [%cal Gc6a5] } 36. Bb5 Bxb2 37. bxa5 Re6) 35... axb4 36. Kg2 Bxd4 (36... Ra8 37. Bb5 Be5 38. Kf3) 37. exd4 Bf5 { Going for the a-pawn. } { [%csl Re6,Rd7,Ba4][%cal Rf5d7,Bd7a4,Be6b3,Bb3a4,Rd8a8,Ba8a4] } 38. Bb7?! (38. Bc4 Ra8 { [%csl Ra4][%cal Ra8a4] }) 38... Be6?! (38... Bxd3 39. Kf2 Bc4 40. Bc6 f6) 39. Kf3 Bb3 { [%cal Rb3a4] } 40. Bc6 Rd6 41. Bb5 Rf6+ (41... Re6 { [%cal Rb3d1,Be6e2] }) 42. Ke3 Re6+ (42... Rf1 { [%cal Rf1b1,Rf1h1,Rb1a1,Ba1a4,Bb1b2,Bg1g3,Bh1h3] } 43. d5 Bxd5 44. a5 Rb1 45. Bd4 Re1+ 46. Kd2 Rh1 47. h4 Rh3 48. Bc5 b3) 43. Kf4 Re2 44. Bc1 Rc2 45. Be3 Bd5 { 0-1 White resigns. } { And now the b-pawn is unstoppable. } { [%cal Rb4b1] } 0-1


