1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6 3. c4 { Maróczy Bind } 3... e6 { Paulsen Line. This can get quite sharp } 4. Nc3 (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 { Transposition: B41 Sicilian/Kan Variation, Maróczy Bind, Réti Variation } 5... Nf6 (5... Bb4+ 6. Nc3 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Nc2 { [%cal Gc2b4] } 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3)) 4... Qc7 (4... Ne7?! 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nbc6) 5. Be2 b6 (5... Nc6 6. O-O { Probably the safest continuation. But it does allow Nd4. } (6. d4 { Prevents Nd4. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 { And here White should really castle. } 8. O-O Bb4 { Vareful now! This is a well known trap. } 9. Nxc6 { Simplification. } (9. f3?? { This is not only too passive, but it's also losing a piece: } 9... Nxd4! { The point is that White can't take the knight: } 10. Qxd4?? Bc5! $19 { And the game is over. }) 9... dxc6 10. Qb3 Bd6 { Aiming at h2. } { [%cal Rd6h2] } 11. h3 { The quiet line. } (11. f4 { The aggressive line. } { [%cal Gc1f4,Gf1f4] } 11... e5 12. f5 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 { [%cal Gc3a4,Gc4c5,Ga4b6,Gc1g5] } 13... h6)) 6... Nd4 7. d3) 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 { [%cal Rf6e4,Rb7e4] } 9. Qd3 (9. f3 { A common move in the Maróczy Bind, but I think it is better to preserve the option to play f4 in one move. } 9... Bd6 { [%cal Rd6h2] } 10. Kh1 Bc5 (10... Bxh2? 11. f4! Bg3 12. Qd3 Bh4 13. Qh3 Nxe4 (13... g5 { Doesn't work. } { [%cal Gc1g5] }) 14. Qxh4 Nc6 15. Nxe6!? (15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Qf2 $16) (15. Nxe4?! Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4e2,Gb7e4] } 16. Bf3 Nxf3 17. gxf3 Bxe4 18. fxe4 $14 { White is still better here, but the king is quite weak. }) 15... dxe6 16. Nxe4 Nd4 17. Bd3 { Kuybokarov, Temur - Nakauchi, G., 1-0, Australian Open 2017, https://lichess.org/P2yUrOkN }) 11. Be3 O-O 12. Na4 d6 13. a3 { [%cal Gb2b4] } 13... e5 14. Nf5 Bxe3 15. Nxe3 Nc6 $14 { Smirin, Ilia - Kamsky, Gata, 0-1, FIDE World Cup, 2005, https://lichess.org/RFabO0HJ }) 9... Nc6 10. Nxc6 dxc6 (10... Bxc6 11. Be3) *


