{ 6 times Karpov tried his Nimzo-Indian on Kasparov in their World Championship match in 1985. They had three draws, and Kasparov won the other three games.

Anand said later: "It's not an exaggeration to say that the reason he [Kasparov] became world champion is because of this opening."

Source: https://chess24.com/en/learn/advanced/video/opening-tips-from-a-world-champion/anand-nimzo-indian }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 { Three Knights Variation } 4... c5 { Undermine White's center immediately. Also a good move. The point is that White doesn't want to play e3 here, because it blocks their dark-squared bishop. And taking on c5 leads to a very ugly pawn structure after Bxc3. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Ge2e3,Rc1e3] } (4... b6 { Nowadays the main move with two ideas: On b7 Black's bishop can be a counter to White's bishop on g2, and on a3 it can attack White's weakest pawn on c4.
Karpov knew this move; it had been played since the very first Three Knights game in 1887 Berthold Englisch - Josef Noa.
Maybe he didn't play it in the whole match, because he thought Kasparov was too well prepared for it? } { [%csl Bc4][%cal Gc8b7,Gf1g2,Bc8a6,Ba6c4] }) 5. g3 { Kasparov decided just to ignore that pawn and develop the light-squared bishop instead. This is still the main move in the position. } (5. dxc5?! Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5 { This is no a position you want to have with White on move 6. } { [%cal Ga5c3,Ga5c5] }) 5... Ne4 { Very aggressive. } (5... cxd4 { Now the main move. This prevents that White creates the typical strong center. } 6. Nxd4 O-O) 6. Qd3 Qa5 { [%cal Gb4c3] } 7. Qxe4 Bxc3+ { bxc3 is of course forbidden. } 8. Bd2 (8. bxc3?? Qxc3+ { [%cal Gc3e1,Gc3a1] } 9. Nd2 Qxa1 $19) 8... Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Qb6 (9... Nc6 { Maybe it would have been better to keep the queen on a5 for now and to develop more pieces instead. } 10. dxc5 b6) 10. dxc5 Qxb2 11. Rb1 Qc3?! { Allows White to trade off queens, which is in White's favor. } (11... Qa3 { [%cal Ga3a2,Ga3c5] } 12. Bg2 (12. Rxb7 Qc1#) 12... Qxc5 13. O-O) 12. Qd3 { [%cal Gd3d6] } 12... Qxd3 { Black has to take. The threat of Qd6 is too strong. } (12... Qe5 13. Qd6 { Taking here repairs White's pawn structure. }) (12... Qa5 13. Bg2 { [%cal Gb1b7,Gg2b7,Gd3d6] }) 13. exd3 { This little pawn set, guarded by the light-squared bishop and the rooks, will decide the game. } { [%csl Bc5,Bc4,Bd3] } 13... Na6?! { [%cal Ga6c5] } (13... Nc6 14. Bg2 b6 15. cxb6 axb6 { [%cal Ga8a2,Gb1b6] } 16. Rxb6 { [%cal Gg2c6,Gb6c6] } 16... Rxa2 17. Bxc6 dxc6 { [%cal Ga2a1,Ga1h1] } 18. Ke2 Kd7 $14) 14. d4 (14. Rb5 Nc7 15. Rb1) 14... Rb8 (14... e5 15. dxe5 Nxc5) 15. Bg2 Ke7 16. Ke2 { Both are trying to get an active king in this endgame. } 16... Rd8 17. Ne4 (17. Rb3!? { Nice idea, suggested by Stockfish. } { [%cal Gb3f3,Gb3a3,Gh1b1] }) 17... b6 18. Nd6 Nc7 19. Rb4 { [%cal Gb4a4,Ge2d3,Gh1b1] } 19... Ne8 20. Nxe8 Kxe8 (20... Rxe8 { Keeping the king closer to the center. }) 21. Rhb1 Ba6?! (21... Bb7 { [%cal Gb7g2] } 22. d5 exd5 { Now it would be nice for Black to have a rook on e8. } 23. cxd5) 22. Ke3 { Step out of the pin. } 22... d5?! (22... Rdc8 { [%cal Ga6c4,Gc8c4] } 23. c6 Rc7 24. d5 exd5 25. cxd5 Ke7) 23. cxd6 Rbc8 { Going for White's c-pawn. } { [%cal Gc8c4,Ga6c4] } (23... Rxd6 { isn't possible, because } 24. c5 { wins the house. } { [%cal Gb4b8] } 24... Rdd8 25. c6 { [%cal Gb4a4,Gc6c7] }) 24. Kd3?! { There was a way to keep the pawn on d6: Bf1! } (24. Bf1! Bb7 25. Ra4 { [%cal Ga4a7,Gb1b6] } 25... Ra8 26. c5 { [%cal Gb1b7] }) 24... Rxd6 25. Ra4 b5 { [%cal Gd6a6] } 26. cxb5 Rb8 27. Rab4 Bb7 28. Bxb7 Rxb7 29. a4 Ke7 (29... g5 { immediately was probably Black's best option. }) 30. h4 h6 { [%cal Gg7g5] } 31. f3 { [%cal Gg3g4] } 31... Rd5 (31... f6 32. Rc4 e5 { [%cal Gd6d3] } 33. Kc3) 32. Rc1 Rbd7 (32... g5 33. hxg5 Rxg5 34. g4 f5 35. gxf5 Rxf5 { And now Black has a passed pawn and something to play for. } { [%csl Gh6] }) 33. a5 (33. f4 { Stop e5 for the moment. } 33... g5 34. fxg5 hxg5 35. h5!) 33... g5 34. hxg5 Rxg5 (34... hxg5 35. Rc8) 35. g4 h5 36. b6! axb6 37. axb6 Rb7 { Forced. } 38. Rc5 f5 39. gxh5 Rxh5 { [%cal Gh5h3] } 40. Kc4 { Steps out of the Rh3 threat. } (40. Rb3 Rh3) 40... Rh8 41. Kb5! { Active king. } 41... Ra8 42. Rbc4 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 42... Rbb8 43. Rc7+ Kf6 44. f4 Ra1 45. b7 Rb1+ 46. Rb4 1-0


