1. c4 e6 (1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 { different move order }) 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 { A13 English Opening/Neo-Catalan. The basic idea for white is to delay the move d4, maybe to never even play it. This leads to a very solid, positional play, and it doesn't allow most of the gambits a d4 player might face. } (3... b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O { Catalan Defense }) (3... dxc4 4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Bg2 a6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 8. a4 c5 9. O-O) (3... c6 { Kurajica Defense, similar to the Semi-Slav. } 4. b3 Nf6 5. Bg2) (3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Ne7) 4. Bg2 Be7 { Neo-Catalan Declined } (4... dxc4 { Neo-Catalan Accepted }) (4... c6 { Semi-Slav Defense }) (4... Bd6 { Bogoljubow Defense }) (4... d4 5. O-O c5 6. d3 { Reversed Benoni } 6... Nc6) (4... c5 5. O-O d4 6. d3 { Reversed Benoni, just a different move order. }) 5. O-O (5. d4 { Transposes to the regular closed Catalan. That's not the opening we'll look at in this study. It was the opening played in the highest rated game ever: Aronian - Carlsen, 2014 https://lichess.org/IpY1ThET#8 }) 5... O-O 6. b3 c5 7. cxd5 (7. Bb2 Nc6 8. e3 b6 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. d4 Rad8 13. Ne5 Qd6 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd7 Qf5 16. e4 Qg5 17. h4 Qh6 18. Bc1 g5 19. hxg5 Qg7 20. e5 Kh8 21. Bf4 Bxg5 22. Bxg5 Qxg5 23. Nxf8 Rxd1 24. Raxd1 Na5 25. Bxb7 { Miroshnichenko, E. - Nakhbayeva, G., 1-0, 3rd Al Ain Chess Classic, 2014, https://lichess.org/Rw0NI29A } 25... Nxb7) 7... exd5 8. d4 Nc6 9. Bb2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Be6 12. Nc3 Rc8 13. Qxa7 d4 14. Nb5 Bc5 15. Qxb7 Bg4 16. b4 Rb8 17. Qc6 Rc8 18. Qa6 { [%cal Gg2a8] } 18... Bb6 19. Na3 { [%cal Ga6e2] } 19... Re8 *


