[ChapterName "How I use studies"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mgquHh3e/hanEGvTc"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.23"]
[UTCTime "09:37:23"]

1. e4 { I use studies mostly to keep notes. As an open-source programmer, I'm used to share what I have learned, so a large part of my studies is public. } 1... e5 { That doesn't mean they are useful for everyone. } 2. Nf3 { My opening studies usually start with an "Opening Explorer": a list of all named variations and main lines. } 2... Nc6 { Sometimes a chapter in an opening study grows too big to be readable. Then I move that variation to a separate study. An example is my Caro-Kann/Panov study: https://lichess.org/study/JWmJD6hp } 3. d4 { ❦ Tip: Use a private study as a scratchpad. Just add everything new you learn in a separate chapter. If you decide to extend on that, export the chapter PGN, and use it in a new study. } *


[Event "Fuxia's Studies: What I miss in Lichess studies"]
[Date "2019.05.23"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B10"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Accelerated Panov Attack, Modern Variation"]
[StudyName "Fuxia's Studies"]
[ChapterName "What I miss in Lichess studies"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mgquHh3e/317AmZvK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.23"]
[UTCTime "09:44:46"]

{ I like Lichess studies a lot. It's an awesome feature. But there are still a few things I'd love to see improved. }
1. e4 { Start a chapter on a certain position without omitting the first moves. } 1... c6 { A search box for moves and comments. The browser search doesn't go into all chapters, just the current one. } 2. c4 { Free text chapters without a board. Just a simple text page. Would be useful for this chapter for example. } 2... d5 { MarkDown support for comments. Sometimes you need a proper list or some way to emphatize a few words. } 3. exd5 { A changelog! Right now I'm using the chat for this, but … the people who liked my study once will never know that there are updates. A separate changelog with editable entries could be used to update their "event list" on the front page. } 3... cxd5 { A second level for chapters. For example, in my Caro-Kann study, https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk, I have "sub-chapters" that I mark with leading dashes right now. That's just lame. } 4. cxd5 { Highlights for moves and/or move sequences. There are important motifs in many lines that you just have to know. Making them stand out in the notation pane a little bit would surely help the readers. } 4... Nf6 { Stretch both sidebars down to the bottom. It's a bit annoying to see only a small fraction of the moves or chapter list when there is so much free unused space under that box. } 5. Bb5+ { A better database. If you want to know who played a move first or if a move is a novelty, you have to use another database. I use https://chess24.com/en/analysis, it's excellent. } 5... Nbd7 { Reader comments on chapters! I get a lot of feedback on my studies, usually per private message, because I use the study chat as changelog. Having moderated comments per chapter would be very useful for authors and readers. } 6. Nc3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. d6! exd6 9. Qe2+ Qe7 { (This is how you take the fun out of the game for a Caro-Kann player.) } *


