1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 { Najdorf Variation } 6. Rg1 { Freak Attack, sometimes called the "Stop light variation" or "Petronic Attack". The idea is of course an early g4, which is a common idea in the Najdorf. This is the least subtle approach possible. } { [%cal Gg2g4] } 6... e5 { Main move and simplest answer. } (6... b5 { A fast counter-attack. The point is that White already has committed to queenside castling, and therefore Black doesn't have to wait with b5 like in most other lines of the Najdorf.
I call this the Topalov move, because this was how he kicked this line out of top level play back in 1999. } 7. g4 Bb7 8. Bg2 { This might be too passive. White has rather poor results with it. See Adams - Topalov and Polgar - Topalov, both 1999. } (8. g5 { Now it's a gambit! } 8... Nxe4 (8... Nfd7 { Nagy Hegyesi, Balint - Erdelyi, Zombor, 1-0, HUN-chT 0809, 2009, https://lichess.org/KxakgovP }) 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Qg4 (10. Qe2!? { Engine recommendation. Needs some exploration. }) 10... Bb7 (10... Bd5!? 11. Bg2 Bxg2 12. Qxg2 { [%cal Gg2a8] } 12... Ra7) (10... d5!? 11. Bf4) 11. Bg2 { "White's compensation is more dangerous than it may initially appear, as confirmed by several practical encounters."
—Ftacnik } 11... Qc7 (11... Bxg2 12. Qxg2 { [%cal Gg2a8] } 12... d5 { The only good move. } (12... Nd7?! { Looks natural, but it's deadly: } 13. g6! hxg6 14. Ne6! { Belousov, D. - Thing, Bibek, 1-0, World Blitz 2019, https://lichess.org/hoBvTuOx } { [%cal Gg2g6,Bc7a8,Bc7e8,Gg2a8,Re6c7,Re6d8,Bg6e8] } 14... Rxh2 { Sadly black's best option. } (14... Qb8?! 15. Qxa8! fxe6 (15... Qxa8? 16. Nc7+ Kd8 17. Nxa8 $16) 16. Qxa6 $16) 15. Qxa8 (15. Qxh2 fxe6 $14) 15... fxe6 16. Qxa6 $14) 13. Be3 g6 14. O-O-O Bg7 $10 { d5 is now a target, and white should try to push the f- and h-pawn } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Gf2f4,Rd8d6,Gh2h4,Rb8c6,Bg2d5,Bd1d5] }) 12. Bd2 (12. Be3 g6 (12... Nc6) (12... Nd7 13. f4 g6 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 15. O-O-O Rc8 $15)) (12. Bxb7 Qxb7 13. Be3 (13. Bd2?! { This doesn't work: } 13... g6 14. Bc3 b4 15. Bd2 $17 { Kerek, Krisztian - Anka, Emil, 0-1, HUN-chT 0607, 2006, https://lichess.org/psETjlzG }) 13... g6 14. O-O-O $15 { Petrosian, Tigran L - Ghaem Maghami, Ehsan, 1-0, Fajr op 12th, 2004, https://lichess.org/UPhG2xCY }))) (6... Nc6?! 7. g4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 e5 9. Qd1 d5) (6... g6?! 7. g4 Bg7 8. g5 Nfd7 9. Be3 { Sevian, Samuel - Firouzja, Alireza, 0-1, chess.com Junior Speed, 2019, https://lichess.org/Jt5hHneR }) (6... e6 7. g4 d5 8. exd5 (8. e5 Ne4 9. Nxe4 dxe4)) (6... h5 7. Bg5) 7. Nb3 Be6 (7... b5) 8. g4 d5 { The early d5 break is Black's best try in this line. Since White didn't play f3 to support the e-pawn. And now White has to make a decision: exd5 or g5. } { [%cal Rf6e4,Rd5e4] } 9. g5 { A temporary pawn sacrifice. } (9. exd5 { This leads to queen exchanges and a rather dry position with little chances to win for both sides. } 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 { Safe but dull. —Ftacnik } (10... Bxd5?! { Rarely played, but recommended by Ftacnik. He gives the following line: } 11. Rg3 { [%cal Gg3d3] } (11. Be3 Nc6 { [%cal Rc6b4,Bb4c2,Bb4a2] } 12. c3 { Looks very playable to me. (fuxia) }) 11... Nc6 (11... Be6 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bd2 Nc6 14. Na5 { [%cal Ga5b7] } 14... Kc7 { Morais, Gustavo João F. S - Kotlyanskiy, Edward, 1/2-1/2, CL/2010/B1, https://lichess.org/TYBPmI4T }) 12. Rd3 Nb4 13. Rd2 Qc8 { [%cal Rc8c2,Rb4c2] } 14. Rxd5 (14. c3 Be6 15. cxb4 Bxb4 16. f3 O-O $44 { Ftacnik says Black has enough compensation here. }) 14... Nxc2+ 15. Ke2 Nxa1 16. Rxe5+ Be7 17. Nxa1 Qxg4+ (17... O-O! { Maybe better than Ftacnik's Qxg4? } 18. Re4 (18. Rxe7? Qxg4+ 19. f3 Qc4+ 20. Qd3 Qxc1) 18... Rd8 19. Qe1) 18. Ke1 Qb4+ 19. Qd2 O-O $13) 11. Be3 (11. Qxd5 { This raises the question why you were going for Rg1 in the first place when you are now trading into a draw. A bit anti-positional in my eyes. } 11... Bxd5 12. Be3 Nc6 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. Bb6 Rd6 { Van Foreest, Jorden - Sasikiran, K., 1/2-1/2, Sunway Sitges Open 2016, https://lichess.org/A7tFjQB0 } (14... Rd7 { Harshavardhan, G B. - Aravindh, Chithambaram VR., 0-1, Asian Continental Blitz, 2019, https://lichess.org/E2GhUXKU })) 11... Qxd1+ (11... Nc6 12. Qxd5 (12. a3 $146 { Maybe playable? }) (12. c3 $146 { Or this? } 12... O-O-O) 12... Bxd5 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. Bb6 Rd6 $10 { Van Foreest, Jorden - Sasikiran, K., 1/2-1/2, Sunway Sitges Open 2016, https://lichess.org/A7tFjQB0 }) 12. Rxd1 Nd7 13. Bg2 O-O-O 14. a3 b6 $10 { Dominguez Perez, Leinier - Delgado Ramirez, Neuris, 1/2-1/2, Capablanca Memorial Elite 39th, 2004, https://lichess.org/jtbIcLLY }) 9... Nxe4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Bg2 (12. Be3 { [%csl Bd1,Gc1][%cal Ge1c1,Ba1d1] } 12... Kc7 13. O-O-O Nc6 14. Bg2 $10) 12... Bf5 13. Be3 Nd7 { [%csl Rb6,Gc5][%cal Rd7b6,Rd7c5,Gb3c5,Bc5e4,Ge3b6] } 14. O-O-O (14. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2e4,Gg2e4] } 14... Nc5 15. Nc4 { [%cal Gc4e5] } 15... Nd7 16. Nd2 $10 { Shytaj, Luca - Tocchioni, Doriano, 1/2-1/2, Montecatini Terme 12th, 2005, https://lichess.org/ALPuyChO }) 14... Kc7 $10 { Khader, Sami - Mouradian, Knarik Jacob, 1-0, Asia Cities-ch 16th, 2009, https://lichess.org/CHvNZsjX } *


