{ This game caught my eye today in the New In CHess Classic tournament:
https://chess24.com/en/watch/live-tournaments/meltwater-champions-chess-tour-new-in-chess-classic-2021-prelims/11/1/7

WGM Melanie Lubbe took the time to explain this to us viewers. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 (2... Nc6 3. Bb5 { Rossolimo, a variation Black is trying to avoid with the early e6. }) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 (6. Ndb5 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gb5d6] } 6... d6 { Prevents Nd6+. } 7. Bf4 e5 { Looks a bit odd to take two steps to e5, but this is normal. } 8. Bg5 a6 9. Na3 b5 { Transposes to the Sveshnikov. } { [%cal Gb5b4] } 10. Nd5) 6... bxc6 7. e5 { And this is the start of this line. It's getting very weird now very fast. } 7... Nd5 8. Ne4 { Looking at d6 like in the Sveshnikov, but here Black can't play d6 to prevent it. } { [%cal Ge4d6] } 8... Qc7 { [%cal Rf8d6,Rc7d6] } 9. f4 { Grand Prix style. } 9... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6b4,Rb4e1] } 10. c4 (10. Nd6+ { is not good: } 10... Bxd6 11. exd6 Nf6) 10... Bb4+ { Black has to get some initiative. } 11. Ke2! { Actually the best move. } (11. Bd2?! { Doesn't work: } 11... Qe3+ 12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nxf4+ 15. Kf2 Rb8 $15) 11... f5 12. Nf2 (12. exf6 { is playable. } 12... Nxf6 13. Be3 Qd8 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Bb7 16. Kd1 (16. Rd1 Rc8 17. g4 (17. Rg1 c5 18. g4 Rc6 19. Qe5 O-O 20. g5 Nh5 21. Bh3 d6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 { Wei Yi - Fier, A., 1-0, Aeroflot Open A 2019, https://lichess.org/WOdlwuXl }) 17... c5 18. Rg1 Rf8 19. f5 Qb6 20. fxe6 dxe6 21. g5 Nd5! 22. Qxb6 Nxb6 { Karjakin, Sergey - Yu Yangyi, 1-0, FIDE World Cup 2015, https://lichess.org/ARee1Qjd }) 16... c5 { [%cal Gf6e4] } (16... Qe7 17. Qxe7+ Kxe7 18. Be2 a5 19. Kc2 d5 20. b3 { Svidler, Peter - Leko, Peter, 1-0, WchT 5th, 2001, https://lichess.org/eYXe0XUY }) 17. Qxc5 Be4 { Tari, A. - Vidit, S., 1/2-1/2, 24th Sigeman & Co 2018, https://lichess.org/1qQvUt6g }) 12... Ba6 { Pinning the pawn on c4. } { [%cal Ga6c4] } 13. Kf3 { [%cal Gc4d5] } 13... Ne7 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Qd6 Qb6 17. b3 c5 18. Rd1 Bb7+ 19. Ke3 (19. Kg3 Qxd6 20. exd6 Ng8 { Fedorchuk, Sergey A - Petrov, Marijan, 1-0, Ouest Toulousain op-A 4th, 2009, https://lichess.org/0Wcweruj }) 19... Kf7 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Rxd7 Bc6 22. Rd2 Ra3?! { Weird move. } (22... g5! { Main move. Undermining the support for the annoying pawn on e5. } { [%csl Ge5] } 23. Nh3 (23. fxg5 Ng6 24. Nd3 Rhd8 25. Be2 { Ivanov, Alexander - Griego, David W, 1-0, World op 19th, 1991, https://lichess.org/6MpmOEWh } 25... Bxg2) 23... h6 24. fxg5 Ng6 25. gxh6 { Chandler, Murray G - Kasparov, Garry, 1-0, HSK-Kasparov sim, 1985, https://lichess.org/SS2P1eSi } 25... Nxe5) 23. Nd3 Rd8 24. Rg1 Be4 25. Nc1 Rxd2 26. Kxd2 Nc6 27. Kc3 Ra8 28. g3 Nb4 29. a4 Rd8 30. Be2 Bc2 31. Bh5+ Ke7 32. Bf3 Rd7 33. h4 Rd8 34. Rf1 Rd7 35. Rf2 Bd1 36. Bg2 g6 37. Rd2 Rxd2 38. Kxd2 Bc2 39. h5 Kf7 40. Bf3 gxh5 41. Bxh5+ Ke7 42. Bf3 h6 43. Kc3 Kd7 44. Kb2 Kc7 45. Na2 Nxa2 46. Kxa2 Bd3 47. Ka3 Bf1 48. Bh5 Bd3 49. a5 b5 50. cxb5 Bxb5 51. b4 cxb4+ 52. Kxb4 Ba6 53. Kc5 Bc8 54. Be2 Bb7 55. Bc4 Bc8 56. a6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


[Event "🐝 The Bee: 1.e4 e5 2.b3! 🐝: Variations Overview"]
[Date "2018.12.22"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C20"]
[Opening "King's Pawn Opening"]
[StudyName "🐝 The Bee: 1.e4 e5 2.b3! 🐝"]
[ChapterName "Variations Overview"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0W1011h6/ud8LbEA5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.22"]
[UTCTime "18:32:31"]

{ I named this opening after its signature move, 2.b3, the Bee. Because Bee 3. Got it?

Okay. }
1. e4 e5 { The strategical ideas are mostly inspired by the French/Réti Gambit, Sicilian/Snyder, Nimzo-Larsen Attack, and the reversed Petroff defense, depending on Black's response.
Chess engines don't like it at the beginning, but we can convince them with the moves in this study. } 2. b3 { Playing the Bee is almost cheating, because it's so good. } { [%csl Gf1][%cal Gb1d2,Gg1f3,Gd2d3,Gc1b2] } 2... Nf6 { Is the main move here. It makes sense: Black has no pawn to defend yet, and White has a weakness on e4. } (2... Nc6 3. Bb2 { Transposes to the Nimzo-Larsen Attack/Modern Line } 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qe2 d5 6. d3 (6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. Bxe5)) (2... d5?! { ➡ Center Gambit } 3. exd5) (2... c5 { Transposes into a rare line of the Siclian/Snyder in which c5 is played first. }) (2... c6 { Transposes into the Caro-Kann/Euwe Attack – https://lichess.org/study/4Aqycynk/UVdBvtb7 – although not a good variation for Black. }) (2... f5 { ➡ Dutch Gambit }) (2... Bc5 { [%cal Gc5d4] }) (2... g6 { The Bumblebee }) 3. Bb2 { We ignore the threat for now. We *want* an open center! } 3... Nxe4 { Yes! Thank you, Black. } (3... Nc6 { ➡ Two Knights Defense }) (3... d6?! { ➡ Philidada Variation. This is great for White. Now we can safely play d4 or f4 soon! } 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. d4 Nbd7 7. Bd3 { [%cal Gc3e4,Gd3e4] }) 4. d3 { Now go away, we need space. } (4. Qe2?! d5 5. d3 Nf6 6. Bxe5) (4. Bxe5? { Too early. Kick the knight away first. } 4... Qe7 5. Nf3 d6 6. Qe2 Nxf2! 7. Qxf2 dxe5 $15 { And now Black is a pawn up, and White has lost the strong dark-squared bishop. }) 4... Nf6 (4... Nxf2 { ➡ Heteropteron Gambit }) 5. Bxe5 { Exchange Variation.
The whole point of the opening. Now the center is wide open, and White's bishop will be very strong. } 5... d5 { The best move for Black with the idea to activate both bishops. Don't worry, no Black player has ever found that move. } { [%csl Bg4][%cal Rc8g4,Rf6g4,Bg4e5,Bg4d1] } (5... Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 c5 8. O-O) (5... Nc6 { Exchange/Delayed Two Knights Defense } 6. Bb2 { What else? }) (5... Qe7 { Exchange/Queen Pin Variation
Very similar to the Russian Game/Damiano Variation } 6. Qe2 { The only move. }) (5... Bb4+ { Exchange/Bishop Check Variation }) 6. Be2 { Let's keep g4 under control, we need this square later. } { [%csl Bg4][%cal Ge2g4] } (6. Nf3) (6. h3!?) 6... c5 (6... Nc6 { [%cal Rc6e5] } 7. Bb2 Bb4+ 8. Nd2 O-O 9. Nf3 d4! { This is mildly annoying. } 10. O-O) 7. Nf3 Nc6 *


