{ These games show practical examples of The Bee, what I have learned how both sides should play. If you play the Bee and have an interesting game, let me know! I'm always interested in more examples, and I might add your game to this collection. }
 *


[Event "Casual Blitz game"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/XUK7xMmA"]
[Date "2018.12.24"]
[Round "-"]
[White "fuxia"]
[Black "inute"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "1539"]
[BlackElo "1502"]
[TimeControl "300+3"]
[Termination "Normal"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C20"]
[Opening "King's Pawn Opening"]
[StudyName "🐝 The Bee: 1.e4 e5 2.b3! 🐝"]
[ChapterName "fuxia - inute, 2018, 2…Nc6, 1-0"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0W1011h6/7MRWdfVU"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]

1. e4 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 1... e5 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 2. b3 { [%clk 0:05:02] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 0:04:59] } 3. Bb2 { [%clk 0:05:03] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 4. d3 { This looks odd: doesn't it lock in my light-squared bishop? Yes, but it doesn't matter, as we can see soon. } { [%clk 0:04:55] } 4... d5 { I was happy about this move. An open center is exactly what I need! } { [%clk 0:05:01] } 5. exd5 { [%clk 0:04:51] } 5... Nxd5 { [%clk 0:05:02] } 6. Nf3 { [%clk 0:04:50] } 6... Bd6 { [%clk 0:05:01] } (6... Bg4 { would have been a tiny bit annoying. But since I wanted to play Be2 anyway, it would probably be okay. }) 7. Be2 { [%clk 0:04:41] } 7... O-O { [%clk 0:05:00] } (7... Nf4 { That move would definetively be annoying! }) 8. O-O { [%clk 0:04:43] } 8... Re8 { Time to solve the only weakness on the queenside. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rc6b4,Rd6b4,Rd5b4] [%clk 0:04:55] } 9. a3 { [%clk 0:04:38] } 9... Bf5 { I guess my opponent was preparing e4. } { [%cal Re5e4] [%clk 0:04:38] } 10. Nbd2 { but I wanted to develop this knight to d2 anyway, so … again, no problem. } { [%clk 0:04:38] } 10... Re6 { Announcing a maneuver that I had to stop. Luckily, he needed two moves for that, and that was time enough. } { [%cal Re6g6,Rf5h3,Bg6g3] [%clk 0:04:15] } (10... Nf4 { He didn't see it. Phew! }) 11. Re1 { Clear f1. } { [%csl Bf1] [%clk 0:04:35] } 11... Rg6 { [%clk 0:04:08] } 12. Bf1! { This is important and something to keep in mind in future games. With the bishop on f1 I can't get mated. Now I have equalized even in Stockfish's old-school eyes. } { [%clk 0:04:35] } 12... Qd7? { That was a very weird move. Almost everything else was better.
Now e5 was hanging, and I took it. My idea was to fork queen and rook at the end of the trades, so could not only win the pawn but also simplify so much that there were no tactics to miss anymore. } { [%csl Be5] [%clk 0:03:47] } (12... Bg4) 13. Bxe5 { I gave my good bishop … } { [%clk 0:04:21] } 13... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:03:41] } 14. Rxe5 { … and my rook! Here my opponent should have played the simple c6 and hope that the rest of the material would be enough to launch an attack. But the psychological pressure was too much for him: } { [%cal Ge5d5] [%clk 0:04:18] } 14... Bxe5 { Yes! } { [%clk 0:03:04] } 15. Nxe5 { [%cal Ge5g6,Ge5d7] [%clk 0:04:21] } 15... Qe6 { [%clk 0:02:30] } 16. Nxg6 { [%clk 0:04:21] } 16... Qxg6 { I don't know why he took with the queen and vacated the e-file. hxg6 looked positionally adequate to me. } { [%clk 0:02:31] } (16... hxg6 17. Qe2 Nc3 18. Qxe6 Bxe6) 17. Nf3 { That was another attempt to trade off material. Probably not the best move, because it allowed Bg4. I just needed d2 for my queen. } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Gf3h4] [%clk 0:04:14] } 17... Re8?! { Yes, you should put rooks on open files. But only if there are no other problems. } { [%clk 0:02:22] } (17... Bg4 { I could not answer with h3, because that he could just take. }) 18. Nh4 { I missed that this still allowed Bg4! } { [%cal Gh4g6,Gh4f5] [%clk 0:04:11] } 18... Qg5 { [%clk 0:01:57] } (18... Bg4 19. Nxg6 Bxd1 20. Nf4! Nc3 (20... Nxf4 21. Rxd1 { [%csl Gc3] })) 19. Nxf5 { [%clk 0:04:09] } 19... Qxf5 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 20. Qd2 { [%clk 0:03:52] } 20... Re6 { Again the rook lift idea? I don't know. It's way too slow. } { [%cal Re6h6,Rf5h5,Rh5h2] [%clk 0:01:30] } 21. Re1 { Using my opponent's backrank problem. } { [%clk 0:03:50] } 21... Nf4 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 22. Rxe6 { [%clk 0:03:37] } (22. Re4! { I missed this. He can't take that with the rook. } 22... Ng6 (22... Rxe4? 23. dxe4 { [%cal Gd2d8] } 23... Qg5 { [%cal Gg5d8] } 24. Qd7! { [%cal Gd7c7,Gd7c8] } 24... g6 25. h4! { [%cal Gg2g3,Gg3h4,Gg3f4] } 25... Qe5 26. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gd7f7] }) 23. Rxe6) 22... fxe6 { That was a bit surprising. I thought the whole ide of the knight on f4 was to recapture the rook with this piece. Maybe my opponent was afraid of further backrank threats. } { [%clk 0:01:10] } 23. Qb4 { [%cal Gb4b7] [%clk 0:03:12] } 23... b6 { [%clk 0:00:41] } 24. Qe7 { [%cal Ge7c7,Ge7e8] [%clk 0:03:02] } (24. Qa4 { Maybe better. } { [%cal Ga4a7,Ga4e8] }) 24... h6? { [%clk 0:00:36] } 25. Qxc7 { [%clk 0:02:58] } 25... Qd5?? { [%clk 0:00:11] } 26. Qxf4 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:02:39] } 1-0


