{ This is technically not a Bee for the first two moves, but with the very unusual 3.e4 it transposes to the Two Knight Defense in the Bee.

Note that this was a blitz game, inaccuracies are just normal. }
1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e4! { The Nimzo-Larsen setup is usually more a reversed Queen's Indian, so e3 is played instead of e4. } 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qe2 d5 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. Bxe5 Be6 9. g3 { I think this too slow. } 9... Bd6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O { And now it looks more like a King's Indian Attack. } 12... Bg4 13. Qd2 { The typical hiding square d2 for the queen. We can see this is in other games as well. } 13... Rfe8 14. Nc3 c6 15. h3 Bf5 16. Ne2 a5 17. a4 Qb4 18. Qxb4 axb4 { [%cal Re8e2] } 19. Nd4 { [%cal Gd4f5] } 19... Bd7 20. f4 Re7 21. Nf3 Ne8 22. Kf2 Nd6 23. Ne5?! (23. Rfe1 { This was an opportunity to claim the only open file. } 23... Rxe1 24. Rxe1) 23... Nf5 24. Rfe1 Nd4 { [%cal Rd4c2] } 25. Rac1?! (25. Nf3! Rxe1 26. Rxe1 Nxc2 27. Re7 Rd8 28. Ne5 { [%cal Ge5f7,Ge7f7,Be5d7] } 28... Bc8) 25... Kf8 26. g4 Rae8 27. Ke3 { [%cal Ge3d4] } 27... Ne6 (27... c5 { with that move Black could have won the pawn on c2, but White's a-pawn would have become a passed pawn: } { [%cal Rf7f6,Rf6e5] } 28. Kf2 { [%cal Gg2d5] } 28... Bc6 29. Nxc6 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 { [%cal Rd4c2] } 30... bxc6 31. Bf1 Nxc2 { [%cal Ga4a8] }) 28. Nxd7+ (28. d4 { [%cal Ge3d3,Gd4e5] } 28... f6 29. Nxd7+ Rxd7 30. f5) 28... Rxd7 29. f5 d4+ 30. Kf3 Nc7 31. Re4 Rxe4 32. dxe4 f6 33. Bf1 Ke7 34. Rd1 c5 35. Kf4 Kd6 36. h4 h6 37. Bd3 Na8?! (37... Rd8 38. Bc4 Na8) 38. Rg1 Nb6 39. a5 Nc8 40. g5 hxg5+ 41. hxg5 Re7? (41... Ne7 { Would watch the g6 square and prevent what happened in the game. } 42. Bb5 (42. gxf6 gxf6 { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gg1g6] }) 42... Rc7 43. Rg3) 42. gxf6 gxf6 43. Rg6! Rf7 44. Bc4 Rf8 45. e5+! { [%cal Gg6d6] } 45... Ke7 46. Rg7+ Kd8 47. Rxb7 { And White collects an important extra pawn: now the a-pawn is a passer. } { [%csl Ba5][%cal Ga5a8] } 47... fxe5+ 48. Kxe5 Rxf5+?? { Blunder. It looks like a funny little tactic that wins a pawn, but in the end Black can't stop the a-pawn anymore without losing the knight. } 49. Kxf5 Nd6+ 50. Ke6 Nxb7 51. a6! Kc7 52. a7 { 1-0 Black resigns. } (52. axb7 Kxb7 53. Kd5 { [%csl Gc5,Gd4,Gb4] }) 1-0


