[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.11"]
[UTCTime "07:52:17"]

1. d4 { The Grünfeld Defense, named after Ernst Grünfeld https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Gruenfeld who introduced it into international play at Vienna 1922, where, in his first game with the defense, he defeated future world champion Alexander Alekhine. It's one of the sharpest responses to the Queen's Gambit. } 1... Nf6 { A multi-purpose move against 1.d4. Black doesn't commit to a specific pawn structure and prevents 2.e4. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6e4] } 2. c4 g6 { Only now Black goes for a concrete plan: fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop. } 3. Nc3 { White prepares to play e4. } { [%cal Re2e4] } (3. Nf3 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 { Three Knights Variation }) 3... d5 { This is the Grünfeld defense. d5 prevents e4 again, and it invites White to take the pawn. There are several ways to continue. The main move was and is cxd5.
d4 is the center of the whole action for the following moves. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Re2e4,Bc3e4,Gd5e4] } 4. cxd5 (4. Nf3 { Three Knights Variation } 4... Bg7 5. Qb3 { Transposition: Russian Variation } { [%cal Gb3d5,Gc7c6] } (5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 { Transposition: Exchange Variation/Modern Exchange } 7... c5) 5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4) 4... Nxd5 5. e4 { And now White can play e4. } (5. Bd2 Bg7 (5... Nb6) (5... Nxc3?! 6. Bxc3 Bg7) 6. e4 Nb6 7. Be3) 5... Nxc3 { Black gives White a strong pawn center and gets a quick piece development with pressure in return. } { [%cal Gf8g7] } 6. bxc3 { Black has to prove now that White's strong pawn center is a liability rather than an asset. The advanced pawns give White a strong center, but they are also leaving unprotected squares behind.
Note that c3 is not protected. } { [%csl Bc3,Gg4,Gg7,Gc6][%cal Gf8g7,Gc7c5,Gd8a5,Ga5c3,Gc8g4,Gb8c6] } 6... Bg7 { This pins the d-pawn, because c3 would be under attack after d5. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Gg7c3] } 7. Nf3 { White develops a piece and adds a defender to d4. The downside is that this knight is a target for an attack via Bg4. That's why other moves have been tried, like Be3 or the very aggressive Bc4. } { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd8d4,Rf3d4] } (7. Be3 { [%cal Ga1c1,Gd4d5] } 7... c5 8. Qd2 Qa5 9. Rc1 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 O-O) (7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 { [%cal Gf2f3] } 8... Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. f3 Na5 12. Bxf7+ { Seville Variation, played by Karpov three times in his World Championship match against Kasparov in Seville, Spain. } 12... Rxf7 13. fxg4 Rxf1+ 14. Kxf1 Qd6 { [%cal Gd6h2] } 15. Kg1 (15. e5 Qd5) 15... Qe6 { [%cal Ge6e4] } (15... Rd8)) (7. Bg5 c5 8. Rc1 O-O 9. Nf3 Bg4) 7... c5 { Now Black makes use of that pin by attacking d4 from the side. If White is careless and makes a weak move, like Be2, Black can equalize immediately.
The best continuations here are Be3, h3 and Rb1. } { [%cal Gc5d4,Gg7d4,Gd8d4] } 8. Rb1 (8. Be2?! { Looks natural, but it is actually a bad idea. } 8... Nc6 { 4 attackers on d4 by Black and only 3 defenders on White's side. So … } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7d4,Gc5d4,Gc6d4,Gd8d4,Rf3d4,Rc3d4,Rd1d4] } 9. Be3 { seems logical, but now Black can remove one defender with } (9. d5?! { This is actually playable for White. There is some compensation for the exchange sacrifice. } 9... Bxc3+ { [%cal Gc3a1] } 10. Bd2 Bxa1 11. Qxa1 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 { White has the bishop pair and a better pawn structure in the center. Black is an exchange up and therefore slightly better. }) 9... Bg4! { Threatening Bxf3. This forced White to play } 10. e5 { weakening the light squares in the center. } { [%csl Bd5,Bf5] } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O (11... Qa5+ 12. Qd2 (12. Bd2 Qa3 { [%csl Gb2][%cal Ga3b2,Gb2a1,Gb2d4] } 13. Bc1) (12. Nd2 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Qc3 14. O-O Nxd4) 12... Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Bxe2 14. Kxe2) 12. O-O Qd7 { [%cal Ga8d8] }) (8. Be3) (8. h3) 8... O-O 9. Be2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxa2 12. O-O b6 { White has gambited a pawn here. The compensation is a much better development. } *


