1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. g3 { The point of this move order is that White manages to prevent Black from playing the symmetrical systems against g3 that start with the move c7-c6 and then d5. In those systems Black recaptures on d5 with the pawn, keeping the structure very solid. That's always been the most fireproof way for Black to deal with the g3 systems and is currently doing very well, so White players are understandably trying to avoid it. However, the position of the knight on c3 gives Black additional opportunities. } 5... Bg7 6. Bg2 Nxc3 (6... Nb6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. e3 O-O 9. O-O Re8) 7. bxc3 c5 { In this position White has a choice between 8.Nf3 and 8.e3. } 8. e3 (8. Nf3 cxd4 { This is my proposed solution in this line. } (8... Nc6 { is what most people play here, which is a fine move in itself, but after 9.0-0 it allows White a position I would recommend trying to avoid. } 9. O-O (9. e3 { is not what White plays 8.Nf3 for. } 9... O-O 10. O-O Qa5 11. Bb2 (11. Bd2 Qc7 12. Qc2 Na5 13. Rfc1 Rd8 14. Be1 Be6 $15 { Doss, Jason R - Shulman, Yuri, 0-1, Thompson Memorial op, 2000, https://lichess.org/mgBghGWT }) (11. Qb3 Rb8 (11... Qc7 12. Ba3 b6 13. dxc5 Rb8 $13 { Ljubojevic, Ljubomir - Topalov, Veselin, 0-1, Amber-blindfold 06th, 1997, https://lichess.org/5SACyMnL } (13... Bb7 { Bui, Vinh - Lechtynsky, Jiri, 1-0, Budapest FS09 GM, 2002, https://lichess.org/cLFR6BDO })) 12. d5 (12. Nd2 Bd7 13. Ba3 b6 14. Rfd1 Rfc8 15. Bf1 cxd4 16. cxd4 Bg4 $132 { Filippov, Valerij - Bologan, Viktor, 0-1, Vladivostok Zaitsev Memorial, 1995, https://lichess.org/tribCwAE }) 12... Qxc3 (12... Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bd2 b5 15. f4 Bg7 16. e4 e6 $15 { Navara, David - Bologan, Viktor, 1/2-1/2, Mainz Ordix op 14th, 2007, https://lichess.org/907UGcKZ })) 11... Rd8 (11... Be6 12. d5 Rfd8 $13 { Miton, Kamil - Volokitin, Andrei, 0-1, Bermuda-A, 2003, https://lichess.org/ayFccKFP }) 12. Qe2 (12. Qb3 Be6 13. Qa3 Qc7 14. Ng5 Bc4 15. Rfd1 Na5 16. Ne4 b6 17. Nd2 { Pasalic, Mehmed - Mikhalevski, Victor, 0-1, Chicago op 13th, 2004, https://lichess.org/DYBZMT7I }) 12... e5 (12... Be6 13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. Nxd4 (14. cxd4 Rac8 15. Nd2 Qa4 $13) 14... Bd7 $10 { Arnett, David A - Yermolinsky, Alex, 0-1, New York op, 1998, https://lichess.org/PwY7AgnN }) 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. c4 Bxb2 (15... Rd2 16. Qxd2 Qxd2 17. Bxe5 Bg4 18. Bxb7 Re8 19. Bf4 { Kotsur, Pavel - Bologan, Viktor, 1-0, Moscow Aeroflot op-A, 2004, https://lichess.org/Q1mvL66B }) 16. Qxb2 Be6 17. Qe5 Rd2 $10) 9... cxd4 (9... O-O?! { is not the best: } 10. d5 Na5 11. Bf4 Bf5 12. Rc1 Be4 13. c4 Bb2 14. Bh3 Bxc1 15. Qxc1 Bxf3 16. exf3 b5 17. cxb5 Qxd5 18. Bh6 { Potkin, Vladimir - Belov, Vladimir, 1-0, RUS-chT 17th, 2010, https://lichess.org/yd08Onqm }) 10. Nxd4!? { and now Black has a choice. } 10... Na5!? { I played this against Vladimir Potkin as I decided I didn't want to defend the endgame after 10... Nxd4, but I think this position is quite dangerous for Black. White has a number of options here which are potentially very, very unpleasant and make it hard to recommend. } (10... Nxd4 11. cxd4 Qxd4 { accepting the pawn sac, is now considered more or less a forced draw, but it's one that Black, not White, will clearly have to make, and in general after … } 12. Rb1 { … White will enjoy a slight pull with absolutely zero risk. Although this is of course a very viable option, it's not my recommendation. }) 11. Bg5 (11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qa3 Rc8 13. Rd1 Qb6 { and here I was already fine } 14. Qb4 Qxb4 15. cxb4 Ba4 16. Rd3 Nc6 17. Be3 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Rc7 { but the whole approach seems a bit risky to me. } { Potkin, Vladimir - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, Bundesliga 1011, 2011, https://lichess.org/CmshyLbZ }) 11... O-O (11... h6 12. Be3 O-O 13. Qc1 Kh7 14. Rd1 $16) 12. Qa4 Bd7 13. Qb4 Re8 14. Rad1 Rc8 $13) 9. cxd4 { The normal move. } (9. Nxd4 O-O 10. O-O Qc7! { [%cal Gc7c3] } 11. Rb1 (11. Qb3 Nc6 { The following almost forced line once again leaves the board almost empty } 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bf4 Qa5 14. Bxc6 Be6 $10 15. Qb4 Qxb4 16. cxb4 Bxa1 17. Bxa8 Bc3 $10 { Bologan, Viktor - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, Wch Rapid, 2012, https://lichess.org/jd0aqr7k } { Wojtaszek, Radoslaw - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, EU-ch 12th, 2011, https://lichess.org/Fjua9z8W }) 11... Qxc3 12. Nb5 Qa5 13. Bd2 Qd8 { leads to problems. } (13... Qxa2 { The simplest move. } 14. Nc7 { illustrates the point of 13... Qxa2, as it's met by } (14. Bb4 Bf5 { This results in the total annihilation of everything on the board and a quick draw. } 15. Bxe7 Bxb1 16. Qxb1 Qxb1 17. Rxb1 Nd7) 14... Rd8 { Reuker, Jari - Krause, Benedict, 0-1, German Youth Teams 2017, https://lichess.org/od5qDkG8 } { and after the bishop on d2 is lost only Black can be better. }) 14. Be3 Qa5 15. Qe1 Nc6 16. Qxa5 Nxa5 17. Nc7 Bf5 18. Nxa8 Bxb1 19. Rxb1 Rxa8 20. Bxb7 $16 { Aronian, Levon - Grischuk, Alexander, 1-0, FRA-chT Top 16 GpA, 2005, https://lichess.org/Xxtlf54s }) 9... Nc6 10. O-O { Once again inviting Black to take on d4. } (10. e3 O-O 11. O-O Be6 { is very nice for Black: } 12. Qe2 (12. Qa4 a6 13. Bd2 Bd5 $10) (12. Nd2 Bd5 $10) 12... Rc8 $13 { Tosic, Miroslav - Atalik, Suat, 0-1, YUG-chT, 1999, https://lichess.org/mJAv3DBD }) 10... O-O { Black once again declines the invitation. } (10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Rb1 O-O 13. Be3 { Aronian, Levon - Radjabov, Teimour, 1-0, Amber-blindfold 18th, 2009, https://lichess.org/aMOK1U9p } { Smirnov, Pavel - Giri, Anish, 1/2-1/2, RUS-chT 19th, 2012, https://lichess.org/brPJFgVx }) 11. Rb1 { White continues to insist. } (11. Bf4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Rc1 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Be6 $10) (11. Bg5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 $10) (11. e3 { here, abandoning the idea of sacrificing the d4-pawn, leaves Black perfectly fine after } 11... Be6 { His plan is quite transparent. He wants to put the bishop on d5, the rook on c8 and the queen will go to either d7 or a5. In general, if Black manages to neutralise the potentially very strong bishop on g2 he should be fine in this structure. }) 11... b6 { This is the move I propose here. I played it against Ruslan Ponomariov in the European Club Championship in 2011, and I think it gives Black an interesting position with definite potential for counterplay. } (11... Nxd4 { transposes to the endgame I described above. }) 12. d5 { The main move and the one Ruslan played against me. } (12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxa8 { shows the tactical justification for 11...b6, as Black now has the incredibly strong move } 13... Bf5 $15 { hitting the rook on b1 and threatening Qxa8 and then Bh3. Black regains material with interest and is already better. }) (12. Ng5 Bb7 13. d5 Na5 14. e4 h6 15. Nf3 { then either } 15... e6 { or the less concrete Rc8 lead to very double-edged positions which should be very playable for Black. } (15... Rc8 16. Bb2 Bxb2 17. Rxb2 Qd6 $13) 16. Ba3 Re8 17. d6 Qd7 $13 (17... Nc4 18. d7 Nxa3 19. dxe8=Q+ Qxe8 20. Rb3 Nc4 $13)) (12. Ba3 { is a quiet move Black can meet with } 12... Be6 { because a pawn is no longer hanging on b7. He again wants to play something like Rc8 and Qd7, when Black should be very comfortable. } 13. Rc1 Rc8 (13... Bd5 14. e3 Qd7 15. Re1 $14) 14. e3 Bxa2 (14... Qd7 15. Ng5 $14) 15. Ng5 (15. Qe2 Be6 16. Ng5 Bd5 17. Qb5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qe8 $10) 15... Na5 16. Rxc8 Qxc8 17. Bxe7 Re8 18. Bb4 Bc4 19. Re1 Qf5 20. Nf3 Qb5 $13) (12. e3 { gives Black additional possibilities, for instance playing } 12... Bf5 { first. }) 12... Bf5 { This is Black's point. You don't want to allow e2-e4 without putting up some resistance. The rook is now hanging so White has a choice. } 13. Rb5 (13. Rb2 { This isn't an exchange sacrifice Black should even seriously contemplate. I personally prefer } 13... Ne5 (13... Na5!? { is what Ruslan played here. } 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Qd3 (15. Rb1 { may be the best White has, which would transpose to the game between myself and Ruslan. } { Ponomariov, Ruslan - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, EU-Cup 27th, 2011, https://lichess.org/6GJIR8EP }) 15... Rc8 16. Rb1 (16. Rc2 Rxc2 17. Nxc2 Qc7 18. Ba3 Rc8) 16... Qc7 17. Nb5 Bxb5 18. Qxb5 Qc4 $10) 14. Nxe5 (14. Nd4 Nd3) 14... Bxe5 15. e4 Bd7 { The machine insists Black is very much alive and well in the position after this additional trade, but I'm not sure Black needs to trade off the knights. } 16. Rb1 Rc8 $13) (13. Rb3 Na5 14. Rb4 { White's plan here is to transfer the knight to c6. If he succeeds it would give him a big advantage, but I don't think it's very likely to happen. } 14... Rc8 15. Nd4 Qd6 { Entering a forcing line. } 16. Ba3 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Nc4 { Black successfully trades off a lot of material. } 18. Rxc4 Rxc4 19. Qxc4 Qxa3 { This position is equal. Black hangs on with forced lines, making this very playable for Black. } 20. e4 Bd7 (20... Rc8 21. Qb5 Bg4 22. h3 a6 23. Qxb6 Be2 24. Re1 Qxa2 25. Qb4 $14) 21. Qc7 Qa4 22. e5 Rc8 23. Qb7 Rc5 $10) 13... Na5!? (13... a6 { is of course possible here, but I was worried White would play } 14. Rb2 { and after } 14... Ne5 { or } (14... Na5 { the pawn on b6 might be hanging in some lines. I didn't want to weaken my queenside for no particular reason. })) 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Rb1 (15. Nc6 { doesn't work here as the pawn will be surrounded and eaten. }) 15... Rc8 { Black has rich counterplay because it's difficult for White to come up with any concrete plans, while Black has a lot of squares along the c-file he can use as shuttle points for his pieces - c5, c4 and even c3 in some cases. } 16. Bb2 (16. Bf4 { is natural, but I believe Black's play is somewhat easier after } 16... Rc4 17. e3 Qc8 $132 { He has very clear and well-defined plans. Next move he'll probably continue with Qc5, the second rook will come to c8 and Black's occupation of the only open file gives him very comfortable play. }) 16... Qc7 { Planning to put the queen on c4 and apply some pressure on the queenside. } 17. Ba3 { and here I missed a very nice shot at an advantage. } (17. Rc1 { is of course met by } 17... Qd6 { and the queen is ready to come to b4, which is also unappealing for White. } { [%cal Gd6b4] }) 17... Qc3 { would have given Black an excellent game. } (17... Qe5 { is what I played, and after } 18. Nf3 { the game was soon drawn. Ponomariov, Ruslan - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, EU-Cup 27th, 2011, https://lichess.org/6GJIR8EP }) 18. Nb3 { I couldn't quite make this work for Black because White now wants to play either Rc1 or Bb2, leading to beneficial trades e.g. Black might even have to recapture on a5 with the pawn because the queen will be driven away from c3. } (18. Bb2 { is of course met by } 18... Qc4 { and it's just a waste of a tempo, which wasn't what Ruslan planned. }) 18... Nc4 19. Bxe7 Ne3! { This is the very beautiful shot I missed. Black wins back a lot of material with a fantastic position. I looked at the position after } (19... Rfe8 20. d6 { for a while but couldn't find any direct counterplay. It's somewhat risky to give away the e7-pawn for absolutely nothing. })) 8... Qa5 { This is more ambitious than 8...0-0 and I think a stronger option. Black aims for immediate equality, and White now once again has a choice. } (8... O-O { has no particular drawbacks. } 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. O-O { [%cal Gd8a5,Gf8d8] } 10... Qa5 { In this structure Black aims to play Rd8, the queen is normally very safe on a5, or later a6, and Black tries to play on the light squares or go for an e5-break at an opportune moment. The position is very playable. } { [%cal Gf8d8,Ga5a6,Ge7e5] } 11. Qb3 (11. a4 Rd8 12. Rb1 Qa6 { and Black is fine: } 13. Nf4 cxd4 14. cxd4 Bf5 15. Rb5 Rac8 16. Bd2 b6 17. Re1 e5 { Marszalek, Maciej - Jaracz, Barbara, 1/2-1/2, Polanica Zdroj op-A 41st, 2005, https://lichess.org/QCpegDNg } (17... Bd7 { Rubinetti, Jorge Alberto - Sax, Gyula, 0-1, Nice ol (Men) fin-A, 1974, https://lichess.org/ceMmi67U })) 11... Rd8 (11... Bg4 12. Nf4 e5 13. h3 Bf5 14. g4 Bc8 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nd5 Be6 $13) (11... Qa6 12. Nf4 e5 13. Nd5 (13. dxe5 Nxe5) 13... Be6 $13 { Lieb, Harald - Heuer, Thomas, 1-0, BL2-Nord 0001, 2000, https://lichess.org/7LrKJR1i }) 12. a4 Bg4 13. f3 (13. Nf4 e5 $132) (13. Ra2 Be6 14. d5 c4 15. Qb5 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Rxd5 17. Qxb7 Qb6! $15) 13... Bd7 14. Ba3 b6 (14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Rab8 16. Rfe1 Be6 $13) 15. f4 Rac8 16. d5 { Lieb, Harald - Malisauskas, Vidmantas, 0-1, Berliner Sommer 14th, 1996, https://lichess.org/PeKr81lO } 16... Bg4! 17. Rf2 Bxe2 18. Rxe2 Qxc3 $15) 9. Ne2 { This has the disadvantage of allowing 9...cxd4. } (9. Bd2 O-O 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. O-O Qa6 { [%csl Rd2] } 12. Nc1 Bd7 13. Nb3 b6 14. dxc5 (14. a4 Rac8 15. a5 Nxa5) 14... Rac8) 9... cxd4 10. exd4 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 { Black has managed to force White to take on d4 with the e-pawn. I think that should be very beneficial for Black because in general White wants to take with the c3-pawn, opening up the c-file and the c3-square for the knight on e2. Black is very comfortable. Two high profile games continued } 12. Qb3 Rd8 13. d5 Ne5 14. Bg5 (14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Bg5 Qc5 16. Rfe1 h6 17. Be3 Qc7 18. Bf4 g5 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. Rac1 Rac8 21. Nf3 Bf6 { Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar - Grischuk, Alexander, 0-1, Wch Blitz 4th, 2008, https://lichess.org/pkxk7LPM }) 14... Re8 { Georgiev, Kiril - Kramnik, Vladimir, 1/2-1/2, Belgrade Investbank, 1997, https://lichess.org/7xXgo0pg } (14... Qc5 { is another safe way to meet 14.Bg5. }) 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. Rab1 b6 17. Bf4 Rac8 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. Nc6 Qxc3 { Georgiev, Kiril - Kramnik, Vladimir, 1/2-1/2, Belgrade Investbank, 1997, https://lichess.org/7xXgo0pg } *


