[Event "Grünfeld Defense: 3.g3 c6 4.Bg2"]
[Date "2018.11.22"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E60"]
[Opening "King's Indian Defense: Fianchetto Variation, Immediate Fianchetto"]
[StudyName "Grünfeld Defense"]
[ChapterName "3.g3 c6 4.Bg2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/FWTXoXwG/2fnznk7z"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2018.11.22"]
[UTCTime "14:13:54"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 { (fuxia: This is technically a King's Indian Defense, but it enters Grünfeld like structures soon) } (4. Nf3 d5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Ne5 { trying to save a tempo on Bg2, doesn't get White anywhere: } 7... Nfd7 8. f4 Nxe5 9. fxe5 O-O 10. Bg2 Be6 11. O-O (11. e4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 Qb6 $15) 11... Nc6 12. Be3 f6 13. exf6 exf6 { and Black is perfectly fine. }) 4... d5 5. b3 { This is just a mistake, first of all because in this position with Bg7 and 0-0 Black can transpose to a line covered later where Black is doing quite well, but also because White is somewhat underdeveloped while Black still has all his options open. } (5. Qa4 { A serious option, which Gabi Sargissian played against me in the same European Club Championship where the game against Ruslan Ponomariov was played. } 5... Nfd7 { is the best move in the position, which has been known about for quite a while, but slipped my mind. In this position Nb6 is a huge threat. } { [%cal Gd7b6] } (5... dxc4 { is what actually happened in my game against Sargissian. } 6. Qxc4 Be6 7. Qa4 { And only now } 7... Nbd7 8. Nf3 Nb6 9. Qd1 { Unfortunately I really did go on to lose the game. } { Sargissian, Gabriel - Svidler, Peter, 1-0, EU-Cup 27th, 2011, https://lichess.org/VCSXdgHE }) (5... Nbd7 { is the move I showed immediately in the video, and after } 6. cxd5 Nb6 7. Qb3 { I said that "the b8-knight is somewhat misplaced on b6 and in general belongs on c6, if at all possible. I couldn't achieve full equality here and went on to lose the game." }) 6. Qc2 { The main move, trying at least somehow to justify playing Qa4 on the previous move. Here the most precise way of playing is } (6. cxd5 { Black may even be able to claim a slight advantage here. After } 6... Nb6 7. Qb3 cxd5 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O Nc6 10. Rd1 O-O { it's clear that Black is already better developed. The bishop will come to f5 and Black has a lot of very obvious strengthening moves like Qd7 and Rc8, whereas White is already somewhat pinned down to the defence of the d4-pawn. The position is probably still equal, but if anyone is better here it's Black. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8f5,Gd8d7,Ga8c8] }) 6... dxc4 (6... Bg7 { could be played first, but then after } 7. Nf3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 Nb6 { White can play } 9. Qc2 { because you really don't want to take on d4 and give up your pride and joy, the dark-squared bishop. }) 7. Qxc4 Nb6 { Now White pretty much has to play } 8. Qd3 { as after 8. Qc2 Black will of course take on d4 and simply be a pawn up. But after } { [%cal Gd8d4] } 8... Bg7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Na6 { the queen is completely misplaced on d3. Black is ready to start counterplay with c5 here and, in general, I think Black stands very well. } { [%cal Gc6c5] }) (5. Nf3 Bg7 6. O-O O-O { Apart from the three main moves - 7. b3, 7.Qb3 and 7.cxd5 - White has the option of playing } 7. Nbd2 { This has the advantage of not allowing any forced theory, but the knight is quite badly misplaced on d2 and has no particular future there. A very harmonious way for Black to develop was pointed out, no doubt correctly, by Boris Avrukh in his book. } 7... Bf5 (7... a5 { is how many people immediately react to the knight coming to d2, with a4 to follow, but that's not really necessary. }) 8. b3 Ne4 9. Bb2 { If you give White an additional move he'll play Nh4, forcing Nxd2 Qxd2, and White will at least have a harmonious position with some plans, although I wouldn't really term that an opening advantage. } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Rf3h4] } 9... Qa5 { A strong and important move, pinning White down. The knight on d2 is stuck. You don't want to play Nxd4 because after Bxd4 Black is very comfortable. The bishop shouldn't be allowed to come to e4 so cheaply in this kind of structure. One attempt by White to solve his problems is } 10. a3 Nd7 11. b4 { but after } 11... Qd8 { it becomes clear that although Black has seemingly wasted two tempi on Qa5 and Qd8 White's expansion on the queenside has only created potential problems. For instance, he almost never wants to take on d5 because the c4-square will be weak for the rest of the game. If White plays something like } 12. Qb3 { which looks very natural, Black has a very nice idea. He can play } 12... Nb6 { creating the threat of dxc4 and Be6, winning material. White will feel very tempted to play } { [%cal Gd5c4,Gf5e6] } 13. c5 { and then just } 13... Nd7 { Once again, Black has seemingly lost a couple of tempi but now that the centre has been stabilised he'll have very easy play connected with the e7-e5 break, whereas White's initiative on the queenside is still in its very early stages. I think Black is already very comfortable here. }) 5... dxc4 6. bxc4 e5 { putting White's centre under immediate pressure. This really isn't advisable for White. } *


