[UTCTime "14:39:31"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5 { (fuxia: technically a King's Indian Defense) } (6. Ne5 Ne4 7. O-O O-O 8. Qb3 { is too fancy to be good: } 8... dxc4 9. Nxc4 Nd6 10. Ne5 (10. Nxd6 exd6 11. d5 Nd7 12. Nc3 c5 $132) 10... Be6 11. Qc2 Nd7 12. f4 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qb6+ 14. Kh1 Nf5 $15 { Inarkiev, Ernesto - Bosiocic, Marin, 1-0, EU-ch 11th, 2010, https://lichess.org/KbRB9h7t }) 6... cxd5 7. Ne5 (7. Nc3 Ne4 { A recurrent theme in these lines. Black aims to trade off the c3-knight as early as possible, preventing White from establishing knights on c3 and e5. The moment one of the knights moves you play Ne4 - which makes it very easy to memorise. } { [%cal Ge4c3,Rf3e5] } 8. Qb3 { is a very important subline here. It featured in a number of interesting games recently, with Hikaru Nakamura using it to beat Vladimir Kramnik at the 2012 Olympiad in Istanbul. } (8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Ne5 { should be met with } 9... Nd7 { which is followed by very typical annihilation in the centre: } 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Bxe4 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Bxd4 { leading to a position that Black will quite comfortably hold. For instance, after } 13. O-O { he might even consider playing } 13... Bh3 { and castling long in order to safeguard the only target for White's initiative, his weak b7-pawn. } { [%csl Gb7] }) (8. Ne5 Nxc3 9. bxc3 { transposes. }) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Nd2 e6 11. e4 { Attempting to force some favourable exchanges in the centre, but Black replied } 11... Nc6 12. Ba3 { was played by Erwin L'ami in a recent game played in the final rounds of the Rilton Cup in Stockholm against Ilya Smirin. } (12. exd5 Na5 { It transpires that White can't keep the pawn. } { [%csl Gd5] }) (12. O-O Na5 13. Qd1 Qc7 14. Qf3 { and now I suggest } 14... Bd7!? { One point of this move is that Black aims in many cases to take on e4 and play Bc6. If Black manages to get his bishop to c6 while White has failed to accomplish anything in the meantime Black will be doing very well. The main point, however, is to play Rfc8 in one tempo. } { [%cal Gf8c8] } (14... b6 { was played by Kramnik, and after } 15. Ba3 Rd8 16. e5 { Hikaru managed to win the game, though to claim he was better out of the opening would be a slight overstatement. He wasn't, but he still got a playable position. } 16... Ba6 17. Rfe1 Rac8 18. Bb4 Bh6 { Nakamura, Hikaru - Kramnik, Vladimir, 1-0, Istanbul ol (Men) 40th, 2012, https://lichess.org/K19cfM3W }) 15. exd5 (15. Ba3 Rfc8 { and it's important the rook attacks the c3-pawn in one tempo. White already has to be slightly careful in this position and should probably capture. } 16. exd5 exd5 17. Qxd5 { Black has a choice. } 17... Qxc3 { is perhaps simpler. } (17... Bc6 { is the forcing option: } 18. Qd6 Qxd6 19. Bxd6 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Rxc3 21. Bb4 Rd3 22. Bxa5 b6 { winning the piece back with an endgame that Black should hold. } 23. Nf3 bxa5 24. Rfd1 Rxd1 25. Rxd1) 18. Qxd7 Qxa3 19. Bd5 Qf8 { Black's next move is Rd8, driving the pieces away, and I think it will very soon end in complete equality. } 20. Rac1 Rd8 21. Qb5 Nc6 $10) 15... exd5 16. Nb3 (16. Qxd5 Qxc3 { is clearly unattractive }) 16... Nxb3 17. axb3 Rfc8 18. Bd2 Be6 $10 { and Black is just fine. }) 12... Re8 13. O-O Na5 14. Qd1 dxe4!? { Under favourable circumstances this exchange is something Black should actively encourage, and here it seems to refute L'Ami's idea. } 15. Nxe4 Nc4 { It's very important the bishop is on a3 so Black gains this important tempo. } { [%cal Gc4a3] } 16. Bc1 Bd7 { I think this is very comfortable for Black and he may easily go on to be better if White allows Bc6. } 17. Qb3 (17. Bg5 f6 18. Bf4 Bc6) (17. Nc5 { allows White to and try win the pawn on b7, but Black will have fantastic positional compensation based on the horrible bishop on c1. } { [%csl Rc1][%cal Rc5b7,Rg2b7] }) 17... Na5 { The easiest response. } 18. Qb4 { Other moves are even weaker. } 18... Bf8 19. Qb1 Bc6 20. Bg5 Be7 $10 { Black is very comfortable here. }) (7. O-O O-O 8. Ne5 (8. Nc3 Ne4 { Once again very comfortable for Black. If White plays } 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Ne5 { Black has a choice. } (10. Ng5 Qxd4 11. Nxe4 (11. Qxd4 Bxd4 12. Nxe4 Nc6) 11... Nc6 $10) 10... Nd7 { The simplest: } (10... Qd5 { is a well-known and decent move here. } { Cori, J. - Grischuk, A., 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Cup 2017, https://lichess.org/dDFFKugb }) 11. Nxd7 (11. Bxe4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bh3 13. Re1 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxe5 $10) 11... Qxd7 (11... Bxd7 12. Bxe4 Bh3 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bg2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Bxd4) 12. Bxe4 Qxd4 $10 { Black is fine. }) 8... Ne4 { After } (8... Ng4 { is an additional option for Black in this move order. } 9. f4 (9. Nxg4 Bxg4 10. Nc3 Nc6 { Grachev, B. - Svidler, P., 1/2-1/2, 67th ch-RUS 2014, https://lichess.org/8GpSPxeX }) 9... Nxe5 10. fxe5 Nc6 11. Nc3 Be6 { and Black is very comfortable. } 12. Kh1 (12. Be3 f6 $10) 12... Qd7 13. e4 Bg4 14. e6 Bxd1 15. exd7 Bg4 16. Bg5 f6 17. Be3 e5!? $13 (17... Bxd7 { Schulze, Ulrich - Ostojic, Predrag, 1/2-1/2, BL2-Sued-West 8788, 1988, https://lichess.org/1v0BR3SE }) (17... dxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxd7 19. Nc5 Bc8 $10)) 9. Nd2 { the one thing you shouldn't do is play } 9... Nxd2 (9... Bf5 { is fine for Black: } 10. Qb3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 { and although the mass exchanges have left Black with a somewhat strange pawn structure his far superior bishop on g7 ensures that isn't really felt. }) (9... Nd7 { is another option. }) 10. Bxd2 Nd7 { because that allows } 11. Bc3 { and this is the one position where White actually has some pull. }) 7... Ne4 (7... O-O { is somewhat naive. After } 8. Nc3 e6 9. O-O { White gets the tabiya of the g3 cxd5 cxd5 variation. This has been discussed in very high level games over a long period of time, including in a number of Kasparov-Karpov games. Generally speaking, Black is doing quite well here but the character of play isn't to everybody's taste. White gets quite a bit of pressure after } 9... Nfd7 10. f4 (10. Nf3 { is the latest trend in this position. It looks somewhat counterintuitive, but has a point. Black needs to be precise here. })) 8. Nc3 (8. O-O O-O 9. Nd2 Bf5!? (9... Nxd2 10. Bxd2 Nd7 11. Bc3 $14) (9... Nd7!? { Andersson, U. - Handke, F., 1-0, 2nd Bundesliga West 2016-17, 2017, https://lichess.org/8Twi0LH8 }) 10. Qb3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Rd1 Rb8 15. Qc2 (15. Qa4 Rb5 16. Qxa7 Rd5 $40) 15... Rb5! (15... Qd5 16. b3 Rfc8 17. Ba3 { Xiao, Yiyi - Ni, Shiqun, 1/2-1/2, CHN Team Women 2017, https://lichess.org/bgbyhjWH }) 16. Be3 Qd5 $10) (8. Nd2 Nd7 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Bxe4 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Bxd4 13. O-O Bh3 $13) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. O-O { We've come to the central position of this whole line. } 10... Nc6 { This is a move I've played on a number of occasions with very decent results, but I just thought it was kind of boring. I wanted to show you something else... but nothing else works! } (10... Nd7!? { This is the move I wanted to recommend to you, but instead I'd like to share a slight disappointment. This move isn't very well-known in this variation and I thought it was an improvement on all the theory starting with 10...Nc6, but with great regret I had to shelve the idea. } 11. Nxd7 { White should take, as allowing Nf6 just isn't a good idea. } (11. Nd3 Nf6 $10) 11... Qxd7 { If Black is allowed to play b6 and follow it up with Ba6 he may even be slightly better, so White plays } { [%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] } 12. Qb3 Rd8 13. e4 dxe4 (13... b6 14. Qxd5 { [%cal Rd5a8] } 14... Qxd5 15. exd5 Bb7 16. Re1 Rd7 17. a4 $14) 14. Bxe4 Qe6 (14... e5 15. d5 (15. Bg5 Re8) (15. Re1 exd4 16. Bg5 Rf8 17. Rad1 Qe6 18. cxd4 (18. Bd5 { ☆ } 18... Qf5 19. Be7 Re8 20. cxd4 $16) 18... Qxb3 19. axb3) 15... Qc7 (15... f5 16. Bd3 $40) (15... b6 16. Bg5 Re8 17. d6 Rb8 18. Be7 Bb7 19. Bxb7 Rxb7 20. f4) (15... Bf8!?) 16. Ba3 Bf8 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. c4 Kg7 19. Rab1 Rb8 20. Qc3 $14) (14... Qc7 { I thought this just equalised, but then I discovered White has the very strong } 15. Bd5! { This looks odd, but is quite unpleasant to meet. } (15. Bf4 e5 $10) 15... Rxd5 (15... e6 16. Bf4 { Only now, and e5 is impossible as the pawn on f7 will be hanging after everything is exchanged. } { [%csl Bf7] } 16... Qa5 17. Bg2 e5 18. Bg5 { I couldn't find equality for Black in this position. } 18... Rd6 (18... Re8 19. Bd5 (19. Rfe1 h6 20. Be3 exd4 21. Bxd4 Be6 22. Qxb7 Rad8 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Qb4 $14) 19... Be6 20. Bxe6 fxe6 21. Be3 (21. dxe5 Qxe5 22. Bf4 { Márquez Abreu, Carlos Javier - Tyulenko, Yuri Viktorovich, 1/2-1/2, CAPEA40-sf-04 (ESP), 2013, https://lichess.org/TU3DJg0J }) 21... b6 22. dxe5 (22. Rac1 exd4 23. cxd4 Qd5 24. Qxd5 exd5 25. Rc7 $14) 22... Qxe5 23. Rac1 $14) 19. Be7 (19. dxe5 Bxe5 20. Rae1 $14)) (15... Bh3 { White even has a choice here. } 16. Re1 (16. Bxf7+ Kh8 17. Be6 (17. Re1 Qc6 { [%cal Gc6g2] } 18. d5 Qf6 19. Be6 Bxe6 20. Rxe6 Qxc3 $10) 17... Bxe6 (17... Bxf1 18. Bf4! $16 { and there's no equality for Black. }) 18. Qxe6 Qxc3 19. Rb1 b6 20. Bb2 Qc7 21. Rfe1 $14) 16... e5 (16... e6 17. Bf4 $16) 17. c4 (17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Bb2 Re8 19. c4 Bxb2 20. Qxb2 Rac8 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. Qxb7 Qe5 { [%cal Ge5a1] } 23. Qxf7+ Kh8 24. Rf1 Bxf1 $10) 17... Re8 18. Rb1 exd4 (18... Rab8 19. dxe5 Bxe5 20. Qe3! $14) 19. Qd1! b6 20. Bxa8 Rxa8 21. Qf3 Qc8 22. Re7 Bf5 23. Rb5 $14) 16. Qxd5 Bh3 (16... Be6 { Keene, Raymond - Andersson, Ulf, 0-1, Orense, 1975, https://lichess.org/h33PqZZq }) 17. Re1 Qxc3 { [%cal Gc3a1,Gc3e1] } 18. Bg5 $16) 15. Bg2 $14) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qa4 { To my great surprise this was played against me in successive rounds of the 2011 World Cup, first by a young Vietnamese player and then by Fabiano Caruana, as a serious attempt to fight for an advantage. } (12. Ba3 Ba6 13. Re1 Re8 14. e4 e6 { is how the old theory starts. In most cases the bishops will summarily be exchanged in this position on the f8- and f1-squares. In general, only slight precision is required of Black to hold. It's somewhat unspectacular and less than adventurous, but very sound. } { [%csl Bf8,Bf1] } 15. h4 (15. e5 Bf8 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 (16... Rxf8 17. Qa4 Bb5 18. Qa3 Qc7 19. Bf1 Bxf1 20. Rxf1 c5 $10 { Nyzhnyk, Illya - Piorun, Kacper, 1/2-1/2, POL-chT, 2011, https://lichess.org/1dIbbzos }) 17. h4 Kg7 18. Rb1 Qe7 19. Bf1 Bxf1 20. Rxf1 Reb8 21. Qd2 Rb6 $10 { Ragger, Markus - Miroshnichenko, Evgenij, 1/2-1/2, AUT-chT 0910, 2010, https://lichess.org/OAbgEa3Z }) 15... Bc4 16. e5 Rb8 17. Qd2 Bf8 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Bf1 Bxf1 20. Kxf1 h5 (20... c5 21. h5 $40 { Tregubov, Pavel V - Yandemirov, Valeri, 1-0, Russian Club Cup, 1998, https://lichess.org/MJXplBc4 })) 12... Qb6 13. Bf4 (13. e4 Qa6 (13... Ba6 14. Re1 e6 15. Bf4 Bd3! { An important move, preventing the rook from getting to b1. Black is just fine here. }) 14. Qb4 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Be6 { This isn't very precise because in the position after } 16. Bf4 Rfe8 17. Rfe1 Rac8 18. Bg2 Qc4 19. Qa3 c5 { Fabiano was short of time and repeated moves. } 20. Bf1 (20. Bb7!? { If he's played this I'm not entirely sure Black has full equality. }) 20... Qd5 21. Bg2 Qc4 22. Bf1 Qd5 23. Bg2 { Caruana, Fabiano - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Cup, 2011, https://lichess.org/l3tQzJ3L }) (13. Re1 { ☆ } 13... Qa6 14. Qb4 e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. e4 Rb8 17. Qc5 Bg7 18. Bf4 { [%cal Rf4b8] } 18... Rb5 19. Qd6 Qa5 { [%cal Ga5c3,Rd6c6,Re4d5,Gg7c3] } 20. exd5 cxd5 21. Rad1 { Parsons, Larry - Evans, Dr. Gordon R, 1/2-1/2, ENG-USA 2012, https://lichess.org/Z6Ghirlb }) 13... Qa6 14. Qb4 Bf5 15. Rfe1 Rfe8 16. e4 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Rxe4 e6 19. a4 Rad8 (19... Qb6 { After this move I was slightly worse, although the game was eventually drawn. } 20. Rb1 $14 { Nguyen, Ngoc Truong Son - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Cup, 2011, https://lichess.org/LHdf4jJ8 }) 20. Rb1 Bf8 (20... Rd5 { is apparently sensible, but shows the slight danger in the position, since it runs into } 21. Qe7 { and Black has serious problems to solve. } 21... Rdd8 (21... Rxe7?? { fuxia: Not possible, it's mate in 6: } 22. Rb8+ Bf8 23. Bh6 Re8 24. Rxe8 Qf1+ 25. Kxf1 Rd8 26. Rxd8 c5 27. Rxf8#) 22. Qb4) 21. Qb3 c5 22. dxc5 Bxc5 $10 { Black should equalise without too much trouble as it's very difficult for me to believe that Black can be seriously worse in this position. } *


