1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. Qb3 { (fuxia: technically a King's Indian Defense) } 6... O-O 7. Nc3 { This is best met by } 7... Qb6 8. O-O Rd8 { and now White has a very wide choice (at least seven reasonably good moves), but I believe Black is fine in every line: } 9. c5 (9. Qxb6 { isn't really a problem for Black, as after } 9... axb6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Rxd5 12. Rd1 { his position is comfortable almost regardless of what he does, although I think } (12. e3 Rd8 13. Bd2 c5 14. Bc3 Nc6 15. Ne5 Nxd4 16. exd4 cxd4 17. Bb4 Bxe5 18. Bxe7 Re8 19. Bb4 Be6 20. Rfe1 { Kavalek, Lubomir - Ogaard, Leif, 1/2-1/2, Manila, 1975, https://lichess.org/rAHSVwPR } 20... Bf6) 12... Bf5!? { is a very sensible move here, trying to stop e4. If I was Black in this position I'd already be wondering whether I was better. } (12... Rb5 13. e4 Be6 14. a3 Bb3 15. Re1 Ra4 16. Bf1 Rba5 17. Bd2 Ra8 18. Bc3 c5 19. Bb5 R4a7 20. Rac1 $14 { Rogozenco, Dorian - Donchev, Dimitar I, 0-1, EU-chT (Men) 10th, 1992, https://lichess.org/jDve836x }) (12... Be6 13. a3 Rb5 14. Bf1 Nd7 15. e3 Rf5 16. Nh4 Rfa5 17. Bd2 Ra4 18. Bc3 Nf6 19. Nf3 Ne4 { Rausis, Igors - Vachier Lagrave, Maxime, 1/2-1/2, FRA-chT Top 16 GpA, 2007, https://lichess.org/xWyTiHOn })) (9. cxd5 Qxb3 10. axb3 Nxd5 11. Bg5 Kf8! { Covering the only possible weakness - e7. Ever since the game between Peter Heine Nielsen and Teimour Radjabov it's been known that this is very nice for Black. } 12. Rfc1 Be6 13. Bd2 h6 14. e3 Nd7 15. Ne1 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 g5 17. Nd3 Bf5 18. Nc5 Nxc5 19. Rxc5 Bg6 20. Bc3 e6 21. b4 a6 { Nielsen, Peter Heine - Radjabov, Teimour, 1/2-1/2, FIDE-Wch k.o., 2004, https://lichess.org/7skF4gu7 } 22. Rca5) (9. Bf4 dxc4 (9... Bf5 10. Nd2 Be6 11. c5 Qa6 12. Qc2 b6 13. cxb6 axb6 14. b4 Nbd7 15. a4 h6 16. h3 Qb7 17. Nb3 Ne8 { Bu Xiangzhi - Ju Wenjun, 1/2-1/2, China zt 3.5 2014, https://lichess.org/Eq26jpQG }) 10. Qxc4 Qxb2 { is a possible but very dangerous move that I played in a blitz game against Maxime Vachier-Lagrave. White gets a lot of compensation. } (10... Be6 { Black has simple equality after } 11. Qd3 Na6 12. Qc2 c5 13. Na4 Qb5 14. Nxc5 Nxc5 15. dxc5 Rac8 { Alekseev, Evgeny - Radjabov, Teimour, 1/2-1/2, Astrakhan FIDE GP, 2010, https://lichess.org/mjjLvtkM }) 11. Rab1 Qa3 12. Ng5 e6 13. Bc7! (13. e4 { is bad, and after } 13... b5 14. Qd3 b4 15. Rb3 Qa6 { I had a great game in: } { Vachier Lagrave, Maxime - Svidler, Peter, 0-1, Wch Blitz 5th, 2010, https://lichess.org/8RwdvR2m }) 13... Re8 14. Nce4 { and White has compensation for the pawn. }) (9. Qa3 { This would be a very interesting idea if Black allowed c4-c5, with a big spatial advantage for White, but he of course just plays } 9... dxc4 10. Qxe7 Re8 { is a perfectly sensible move, and } (10... Bf5? 11. Na4 { [%cal Ra4b6,Re7d8] }) (10... Na6 { This is my idea here, and I'm keeping to the tradition of letting you know what I have written in my notes. } 11. Ne5 (11. Na4 Qc7 12. Qxc7 Nxc7 13. Bf4 (13. b3 cxb3 14. axb3 Ne4 15. e3 { Inarkiev, Ernesto - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, RUS-ch 66th, 2013, https://lichess.org/2lqrtI3f }) 13... Ne6 14. Be5 b5 15. Nc3 b4 { and Black gets a lot of counterplay on the queenside: the bishop will come to a6, the rook to c8 and Black will play c5. I'm not worried about Black's prospects at all. } 16. Nb1 Bb7 17. a3 c5 18. dxc5 b3 19. Nbd2 Rac8) (11. Rd1 Re8 12. Qa3 Bf5 13. Ne5 Qb4 { This is very strong. After } 14. Qxb4 Nxb4 { the pawn on c4 will probably be lost, but at the very least Black will have a repetition with Nc2-b4 on every move. } { [%csl Gc2,Gb4][%cal Gb4c2,Gc2b4,Bc2a1,Bf5b1] } 15. e3 Nc2 16. Rb1 Rad8 17. Nxc4 { and Black has a choice between the immediate draw and the more ambitious } 17... b5 (17... Nb4 $10) 18. Na5 b4 19. Ne2 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Bxb1 21. Naxc6 Rd7 22. Nxb4 a5 $15) 11... Be6 12. e3 Re8 13. Qa3 Qb4 { is fine: } 14. Qa4 (14. Bd2 Qxa3 15. bxa3 Nd5 16. Ne4 Nb6) 14... Qxa4 15. Nxa4 Rad8 16. Bd2 Bd5) 11. Qd6 (11. Qa3 Na6 { Giri, Anish - Wang, Yue, 1/2-1/2, World Cities-ch GpF, 2012, https://lichess.org/nYDqGC8d }) 11... Bf5 12. Qf4 Na6 13. h4 Nb4 14. g4 Nbd5 15. Qd2 Ne4 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Qf4 Be6 { led to an edge for Black in } { Burmakin, Vladimir - Midoux, Sebastien, 1-0, Porto San Giorgio op 19th, 2006, https://lichess.org/S9UlRnDK }) (9. h3!? { This is a useful pass move in this position, but Black has a very concrete way of replying. } 9... dxc4 (9... Qxb3 10. axb3 Na6 { Is also possible. } 11. Be3 { Lingnau, Carsten - Schaefer, Markus, 1/2-1/2, Bundesliga 9394, 1994, https://lichess.org/gILjQaBi }) (9... Bf5!? { Svidler, P. - Kramnik, Vladimir, 1-0, Tal Memorial Blitz 2016, https://lichess.org/VAd3tros } { Li Chao2 - Vachier Lagrave, M., 0-1, World Blitz 2017, https://lichess.org/SerkWybg } { Eljanov, P. - Volokitin, And, 1/2-1/2, Qatar Masters Open 2014, https://lichess.org/t9tpjqMu } { Sedlak, Nikola - Vachier Lagrave, Maxime, 1/2-1/2, Khanty-Mansiysk ol (Men) 39th, 2010, https://lichess.org/NdfsXWae }) (9... h6 { Akopian, Vl - Radjabov, T., 0-1, World Blitz 2015, https://lichess.org/8yzBjRvP } { ☆ }) 10. Qxc4 Be6 11. Qd3 Na6!? { I couldn't find complete equality here. } (11... Nd5?! { looks sensible, but after } 12. Bg5! { there are some questions to answer. } 12... Na6 (12... Qa6 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. e4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 f6 16. Bh6 Nb6 $13) 13. e4! { [%cal Rg5e7] }) (11... Qa6 { is an idea I very much like here. } 12. Qc2 { White needs to keep the queens on the board. } 12... c5! 13. dxc5 Nc6 { I think you'll recognise this as a structure that's seen in a lot of positions in the Qb3 Grünfeld. Here, as there, Black has fantastic compensation. At the cost of a single pawn he's opened up the whole board for his bishops, while the c5-pawn will most likely drop off in the immediate future. } { [%csl Bc5][%cal Ge6b3,Gg7d4] } 14. Be3 (14. Bf4 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. e4 Qc4 17. Qxc4 Bxc4 18. Rfe1 Nb4 $13) 14... Nd5 15. Bd2 (15. Nxd5 Bxd5 { Vitiugov, N. - Svidler, P., 1/2-1/2, 67th ch-RUS 2014, https://lichess.org/gATiSqm6 }) 15... Nxc3 16. Bxc3 Qc4 17. Rac1 Qxc5 18. Bxg7 Qxc2 19. Rxc2 Kxg7 20. a3 Bd5 $10) 12. e4 Ne8 (12... Nb4 13. Qe2) 13. Rd1 Nd6 (13... Nb4 { ☆ } 14. Qd2 (14. Qe2 Bxd4 15. Nxd4 Rxd4 16. Be3 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Qa5 18. b3 Na6 19. Qb2 f5 20. Ne2 Nd6 21. Rxd6 exd6 22. Qf6 Qe5 23. Qe7 Bc8 24. Qd8+ Kf7 25. Bd4 { Wen Yang - Zhou Weiqi, 1/2-1/2, TCh-CHN 2015, https://lichess.org/iGaCDa5I } { Ding Liren - Xu, Xiangyu  CHN, 1-0, TCh-CHN 2015, https://lichess.org/LZbOTQ1U } 25... Qe7)) 14. b3 c5 15. Be3 Rac8) (9. Rd1 Qxb3 (9... Na6 { is a move it's important not to play. I once did against Ernesto Inarkiev, and White replies } 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Na4 { and suddenly Black has tactical problems. }) (9... Bf5 { is Black's normal response, threatening to take on b3 and play Bc2, winning a pawn. } 10. Qxb6 (10. Ne1 { In a FIDE Grand Prix event, once more against Ernesto, I played } 10... dxc4 { which I think is a decent move. } (10... Be6 { is very solid and fine for Black. } 11. c5 Qxb3 12. axb3 Nbd7 (12... Na6 { ☆ (fuxia: A rather new move and not part of Svidler's book) } 13. Bf4 Nd7 { Dreev, A. - Anurag, M., 1-0, 21st Corsica Masters Open, 2017, https://lichess.org/AqF7aVwS } (13... Nh5 { Cumming, David R - Wieringen, Cor A. van, 1/2-1/2, MT-Geet/C (NED), 2014, https://lichess.org/RWM8URJW })) 13. b4 a6 $10 { Anic-Nataf, Vichy FRA-ch Pool A 2000 }) 11. Qxc4 Na6 12. e4 { White's only logical continuation. } 12... Be6! (12... Bg4? { was a serious mistake. I thought it was interesting to draw the bishop to f3 and only then play Be6. } 13. Bf3 Be6 14. d5! { White was better in Inarkiev-Svidler, Astrakhan FIDE GP 2010, as it transpires that after } { Inarkiev, Ernesto - Svidler, Peter, 1-0, Astrakhan FIDE GP, 2010, https://lichess.org/ZlQj0SKl } 14... cxd5 15. exd5 { Black seriously misses the tempo he would win by playing Bg4 and hitting the rook on d1. }) 13. Qa4 (13. d5 cxd5 14. exd5 Bg4 { and as I mentioned, the fact that White needs to take a tempo to deal with the threat to his rook leaves Black very comfortable. } { [%cal Gg4d1] }) 13... Bg4 { There's a subtle difference between this position and the position with the queen on c4, but Black is fine here, as the following analysis shows: } 14. f3 (14. Bf3 Nc7 (14... Bh3 15. e5 Ng4) 15. e5 (15. Bxg4 Nxg4 16. Nf3 (16. h3 Rxd4 17. Rxd4 Bxd4 { [%cal Gd4f2] } 18. hxg4 Bxf2+ 19. Kf1 Bxe1 20. Kxe1 Qg1+ $19 { [%cal Gc7e6] }) 16... e5 17. Bg5 Qxb2! $17) (15. Qc4 Ne6 16. Be3 (16. Bxg4 Nxg4 17. Qe2 Nf6 18. e5 Nd5 $10) 16... Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Ng4 18. Qe2 Nxe3 19. fxe3 c5 $13) (15. Qa3 Bxf3 (15... Rxd4 16. Be3 e5 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Na4 Qa6 19. e5 Bh3 20. Bg2 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Ng4 22. Nf3 Bf8 { [%cal Gf8a3] } 23. Qb3 c5 $132) 16. Nxf3 Nb5 { [%cal Gb5a3] } 17. Nxb5 Qxb5 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 18. Re1 e5! 19. Bg5 (19. dxe5 Rd3 { [%cal Gd3f3,Gd3a3] }) 19... h6 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 $10) (15. Kg2 { ☆ (engine suggestion) } 15... a5 16. h3 Bxf3+ 17. Nxf3 Ne6 { Qb4 is a plan. After the queen exchange on b4 or a4, the knight on c3 can't protect e4 anymore. } { [%cal Gb6b4,Gf6e4] } 18. a3 { Prevents Qb4. }) 15... Bxf3 16. Nxf3 Nfd5 17. Qc4 Ne6 18. Ne4 Qb4 19. Qc2 Rac8 20. Be3 f5 21. Nc3 (21. Neg5 Nxe3 22. fxe3 Nxg5 23. Nxg5 Bh6 { [%cal Gh6e3,Gh2h4,Ga2a3,Gg5e6,Ge6d8] }) 21... f4 $13) (14. Nf3 Qb4 (14... e5! 15. dxe5 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5,Gg7e5] } (15... Rxd1+ 16. Qxd1 Nd7 17. h3 (17. Qc2 Nxe5 18. Be3 { [%cal Ge3b6] } (18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Be3 Bd4 $10) 18... Qa5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. h3 (20. f4 Bc7) 20... Be6 21. f4 Bc7 22. a3 Bb6 { [%cal Gb6e3] } 23. Qe2 Bxe3+ 24. Qxe3 Qb6 { [%cal Gb6e3] } 25. Qxb6 axb6 26. e5 Nc5 27. Rd1 f6 $10) 17... Bxf3 18. Qxf3 (18. Bxf3 Nxe5 { [%cal Ge5f3] } 19. Be2 Rd8 20. Qb3 Nc5 { [%cal Gc5b3] } 21. Qxb6 axb6) 18... Nxe5 19. Qe2 Nc7 20. Be3 { [%cal Ge3b6] } 20... Qb4 21. Bf1 Ne6 $10) 16. Bg5 { [%cal Gg5d8] } 16... Re8 17. Rd2 Nxe5 (17... Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Nxe5 19. Be2 Nc5 { [%cal Gc5a4] } 20. Qc2 $16) 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Be3 { [%cal Ge3b6] } 19... Qb4 20. Qxb4 Nxb4 21. a3 $14) 15. h3 (15. Qc2 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Rxd4 17. Be3 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Qc4 19. Kg2 Qe6 $10) 15... Qxa4 16. Nxa4 Be6 17. Nc3 (17. Ng5 Bc8 18. Nc3 Nb4 19. Nf3 Ne8 { [%cal Gg7d4,Gb4c2,Gc2d4] } 20. Rb1 Be6 { Duliba, Dr. Edward P - Novak, Joze, 1/2-1/2, MT-Latash (RUS), 2013, https://lichess.org/TBW8iR16 }) 17... Nb4 18. Ne1 { Jumabayev, R. - Vachier Lagrave, M., 0-1, World Rapid 2015, https://lichess.org/exQCAeNK }) 14... e5!) 10... axb6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Rxd5 (12... cxd5 13. Bf4 Rc8 14. Ne5 e6 15. f3 Nc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Rd2 f6 18. e4 e5 19. Be3 { Jankovic-Muslic, CRO 2001 }) 13. Nh4 Rxd4 14. Be3 Rd6 $13) 10. axb3 Bf5 11. Ne1 Na6 (11... e6? 12. h3! $16) 12. Ra4 h6 13. Bf4 Ne4 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. f3 (15. Nb5? Bd7 $17 { [%cal Gd7a4] }) 15... Nxc3 16. bxc3 g5 17. Bd2 e5 18. e3 $14 { Portisch, Lajos - Hort, Vlastimil, 1/2-1/2, Tilburg, 1979, https://lichess.org/3NUGqmdd }) 9... Qxb3 10. axb3 Na6 11. Bf4 { In this position Black has a lot of counterplay based around playing e5. } (11. h3 Nd7 12. Bf4 (12. Rd1 Re8 { Tan Zhongyi - Wang Jue, 1/2-1/2, ch-CHN w 2017, https://lichess.org/z72kPDpR }) 12... Nf8 13. Ra4 Bf5 14. Rfa1 Ne6 15. e3 Be4 16. g4 Nxf4 17. exf4 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Nc7 { Tregubov, Pavel V - Vorobiov, Evgeny E, 1/2-1/2, Moscow Aeroflot op-A, 2004, https://lichess.org/WAx1ABCO } 19. f5 $15) 11... Nd7 12. Rfd1 (12. Ra3 Re8 (12... f6 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nf8 15. Nc3 Ne6 { [%cal Ge6f4,Ge6d4,Gd8d4] } 16. Be3 Nb4 17. Ra4 Nc2 { [%cal Gc2e3,Ge6d4] } 18. Rc1 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Nc7 { Bologan, V. - Ragger, M., 0-1, 21st European Teams, 2017, https://lichess.org/1clVQJHk }) 13. Bh3 f5 14. Rc1 e5 $15) 12... Re8 { Making the threat of e5 very real. } (12... e5?! { is important not to play immediately, as I did against Aronian in the World Team Championship. } 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 { In this position I realised that Nxc5 isn't quite right, so I played } 15... Bf5 { first, but after } 16. Ra5 Bc2 17. Rd4 Bxb3 18. f4 $14 { I barely managed to draw. It's not very comfortable for Black. }) 13. e4 (13. h3 h6 14. g4 b6) 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nb4 { This position has seen serious discussion in grandmaster practice. I played it myself against Konstantin Sakaev and was fine, while it's also occurred in some of Gata Kamsky's games. Black is generally doing ok, as can be seen from the following analysis. } 15. Bd2 (15. Nc3 Nf6 16. Be5 Be6 17. Nd2 Red8 18. Nc4 Nbd5 19. Ra3 h5 20. Rda1 a6 $10 { Bocharov, Dmitry - Kamsky, Gata, 0-1, FIDE World Cup, 2005, https://lichess.org/IXKnfmgP }) (15. Bg5 h6 16. Bd2 Nd5 $13 (16... Nc2 17. Ra4 f5 18. Nc3 e5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. b4 $13 { Tregubov, Pavel V - Vachier Lagrave, Maxime, 1-0, Paris-ch int, 2007, https://lichess.org/BFfjkAjn })) 15... Nd5 16. Nc3 N7f6 17. Ne5 Be6 18. Nc4 Red8 19. Ne2 (19. Bg5!? Nb4 (19... h6 20. Bxf6 Nxf6 21. Na5 Rab8 22. Bxc6 $13 { [%cal Ga5c6] } 22... bxc6 23. Nxc6 Bxb3 24. Rd2) 20. Ra4 Nfd5 { [%cal Gd5b4,Gd5e7] } 21. Bxe7 Nxe7 22. Rxb4 Bxd4 23. Rxb7 Bxc5 $10) 19... Bf5!? { would be even better. } (19... Ne8 20. Na5 Rd7 21. Bf3 Rad8 22. Be1 Rb8 23. Nc4 { Sakaev, Konstantin - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, RUS-ch Superfinal 60th, 2007, https://lichess.org/PBEB7VWG }) (19... Rd7 20. Na5 Ne8 (20... Bf5!?) 21. Bf3 Rad8 (21... h5) 22. Be1 Rb8 23. Nc4 b6 24. b4 (24. Ra3 Rdb7 25. cxb6 axb6 26. Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c6] } 26... Rc7 { Sakaev, Konstantin - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, RUS-ch Superfinal 60th, 2007, https://lichess.org/PBEB7VWG }) 24... Nxb4 { [%cal Ge6c4,Gb4c2] } 25. Nxb6 axb6 26. Bxb4) 20. Nc3 Nb4 21. Ra4 Nc2 22. Na5 Rxd4 23. Nxb7 Bg4 $15 *


[Event "Grünfeld Defense: 3.Nf3 Bg7 4.g3 c6 5.Bg2 d5 6.b3"]
[Date "2018.11.23"]
