1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. b3 { Starting position } 6... O-O 7. O-O { There are of course many slow possibilities available to Black in this position like a7-a5, Bf5, Nbd7 or Ne4, but I feel it's better to treat this position forcefully. } (7. Bb2 { doesn't change anything, since after } 7... dxc4 8. bxc4 c5 { White can't play } 9. d5 e6 10. Nc3 exd5 11. Nxd5 { due to } 11... Nxd5 12. Bxg7 { and the beautiful shot } 12... Ne3! { and Black is just better. }) 7... dxc4 8. bxc4 c5 { Immediately attacking the white centre. } 9. Bb2 { The main move here. } (9. e3 Nc6 10. Bb2 Qb6 { gives Black a lot of play against the white centre. This is very similar to lines we'll discuss later, but if anything I think it's more comfortable for Black. } 11. Qc1 (11. Qe2 cxd4 12. exd4 Bg4 13. d5 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nd4 $10) 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 $10) 9... Qb6 (9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qb6 { is also possible immediately, but I think this is somewhat less precise. }) 10. Qb3 (10. Qc1 { is met by the simple } 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 { and the c1-square isn't ideal for the queen and Black can safely simplify in the centre. } 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Nd2 Be6 14. Rb1 (14. Qc2 Rab8 { Hou Yifan - Villanueva, Mar, 0-1, PRO League Group Stage, 2018, https://lichess.org/CbgTvy7g }) 14... Qa6 15. Ba3 Rfe8 16. Rb3 Nd7 { Goldin, Alexander - Yandemirov, Valeri, 0-1, RUS-ch, 1995, https://lichess.org/wAbe3tdS }) 10... Ne4 (10... Nfd7 { looks like a decent move, but it runs into the very strong } 11. Nc3! { In general, you shouldn't allow any position where White gets the knight to d5, from where it can completely dominate the position. } { [%cal Gc3d5] }) 11. e3 { It's time to cement the centre somewhat. } (11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 cxd4 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Bxd4 Nc6 $15) 11... Nc6 { Threatening Na5 with problems for White, so he has little choice. } { [%cal Gc6a5] } (11... Nd6 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Na4 Qd8 14. Rfc1 b5 15. Nxc5 Bxc4 16. Qc2 { Burmakin, Vladimir - Anisimov, Pavel, 1-0, Pardubice Skanska op, 2004, https://lichess.org/7hy8kU0N }) (11... cxd4 12. Bxd4 Qa6 (12... Qxb3 13. axb3 Nc6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Nd4 $14 { Porat, S. - Khmelniker, I., 1-0, TCh-ISR 2015, https://lichess.org/Mf6fU3oA }) 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nd4 Nc5 15. Qb2 Qf6 16. Nc3 e6 17. Qa3 Nbd7 18. Rab1 a6 19. Rfd1 $14 { Nielsen, Peter Heine - El Kher, Henrik, 1-0, DEN-ch, 1999, https://lichess.org/z0ijHOSS }) 12. Ne5 (12. Rd1?! Na5 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Na3 Be6 15. Rac1 Nd6 $15) (12. Nc3 { is a possible try, but Black has a variety of options. I quite like the move } 12... Bf5 { here. } (12... Qxb3 13. axb3 Bf5) 13. Qxb6 (13. Nd5 Qxb3 14. axb3 e6 15. Nf4 cxd4 16. exd4 Rfd8 { [%cal Gd8d4] } 17. Rfd1 Nc5! $15 { [%cal Gg7b2] }) 13... axb6 14. Nd5 e6 15. Nxb6 Ra6 16. Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f8] } 16... Rd8 17. Nde5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rb6 { [%cal Gb6b2] } 19. Ba3 { [%cal Ga3c5] } 19... cxd4 20. Bxe4 Bxe4 21. Be7 { [%cal Ge7d8] } 21... Re8 22. Bc5 dxe3 23. Bxb6 e2 24. Rfe1 Bxe5 { [%cal Ge5a1] } 25. Rxe2 Bxa1 26. Rxe4 Ra8 $10 { [%cal Ga8a2] }) (12. Qxb6 axb6 13. Na3 Bg4 $17 { [%cal Gg7b2] }) 12... Nd6 (12... Nxe5!? 13. dxe5! (13. Qxb6 axb6 14. dxe5 Nd6 $146 { [%cal Gg7b2] } 15. Nd2 Ra4 $132)) 13. Nxc6 (13. Nd2 { It's important to start with } 13... cxd4 (13... Be6? { allows White the forced variation } 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Bd4 { and White wins some material. Something to avoid. } 16... Qa5 17. Nxc6 { [%cal Gc6a7,Gc6e7] } 17... Qc7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qc3+ Kg8 20. Na5 Rab8 21. Rfc1 Rfc8 22. Qe5 Bh3 23. Nab3 Rb4 24. c5 Qb7 25. f3 $16 { Giri, Anish - Nielsen, Peter Heine, 1-0, Amsterdam NH Hotels 5th, 2010, https://lichess.org/P4xyaG8R }) 14. exd4 Be6 { and Black is fine. This was seen, for instance, in a game between Dmitry Jakovenko and myself some years ago. } (14... Nf5!?) 15. Rfe1 { CONTINUE } (15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Nxc6 (16. Qxb6 axb6 17. Nxc6 Rfe8) 16... Qxc6 17. d5 Rfb8! $15) (15. Rfc1 Rfc8 16. Qxb6 (16. c5 Bxb3 17. cxb6 Ba4 18. bxa7 Rxa7 19. Ndc4 Nxc4 20. Rxc4 Rd8 21. Nxc6 bxc6 22. Bxc6 Bxc6 23. Rxc6 Bxd4 24. Bxd4 Rxd4 25. Rc3 g5 { Zhou, Weiqi - Ding, Liren, 0-1, Danzhou 1st, 2010, https://lichess.org/DV1S4fa8 }) 16... axb6 17. f4 Ra4 { was a way to play on: } (17... Nxe5 { and a draw was agreed in Jakovenko, Dmitrij - Svidler, Peter, 1/2-1/2, RUS-chT 17th, 2010, https://lichess.org/iNVKQkR1 }) 18. d5 Nxe5 19. fxe5 Bd7 20. exd6 (20. Bf1 Nf5) 20... Bxb2 21. dxe7 Ba3 $15) 15... Na5 16. Qxb6 axb6 17. d5 Bf5 18. Rac1 Rfc8 19. Bf1 e6 20. Bd4 exd5 21. cxd5 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 b5 $10) (13. dxc5 { ☆ } 13... Qxc5 { [%cal Gc5e5,Gg7e5] } 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 { Transposes to normal line. } 16. Nd2 (16. Rc1 Be6 17. Nd2) 16... Be6 17. Rfc1) 13... bxc6 14. dxc5 (14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Bxc6 Ra7 $13 (15... Nxc4!? $13) (15... Bh3 { ☆ } 16. Bxa8 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 Rxa8 $10)) 14... Qxc5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Nd2 { This is Boris Avrukh's recommendation in his book on the white repertoire against the Grünfeld, and as with everything else Boris does this has gained quite a cult following. I myself faced this in a game against Viktor Laznicka at the Khanty-Mansiysk Olympiad, where I had serious problems. In general I had to analyse this position carefully, as I realised that people do intend to play it with a view to getting an opening advantage. But after } 16... Be6 { Black is fine. } 17. Rfc1 (17. Qa4 { can just be met by } { [%cal Rg2c6,Ra4c6] } 17... Rfc8 18. Rfc1 (18. Rab1 Nxc4 19. Rfc1 Nb6 20. Qa6 Qd6 21. Ne4 Qe5 $10) 18... Rab8 19. a3 (19. Rab1 Rxb1 20. Rxb1 a5 (20... Nxc4 21. Qc2) 21. a3 Qe5) (19. Nb3 { [%cal Rb3c5] } 19... Qe5 { and Black is fine due to counterplay against the c4-pawn. } { [%cal Ge5a1] } 20. Qxa7 (20. c5! { ☆ (fuxia: I don't see how Black is fine here. c5 is such a natural and strong move. Svidler doesn't address this.) } 20... Nb5 21. Qf4 Qxf4 22. gxf4 Bd5 23. Na5 { [%cal Ra2a4] } 23... Nc7 24. Rcb1 Na6 $10) 20... Bxc4 21. Na5 Ra8 22. Nxc6 Rxa7 23. Nxe5 Rxa2 $10) 19... Rb2) 17... Rab8 18. Qd3 Rfc8 19. Nb3 Qb4! 20. Qd4+ Kg8 21. Qxa7 Nxc4 22. Qc5 f6 23. Rc2 Qxc5! 24. Nxc5 Na3 { [%cal Ga3c2] } 25. Rc3 Rb1+ 26. Rxb1 Nxb1 27. Rc2 { [%cal Ge6a2] } 27... Na3 28. Rd2 Bc4 { and the a2-pawn is safely blockaded while Black is ready to improve his position further. Although White's position once again looks very nice there's no way to pose Black any particular problems. Black is fine here. } *


