1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 { Brinckmann Attack } 4... Bg7 5. Rc1 { To be honest, you're unlikely to face this move very often, but it's a fun and instructive line to look at. It's a rare occurrence in modern theory that as early as move five Black has an option that leads to unclear and double-edged positions. I'm talking, of course, about } (5. e3 O-O) 5... Nh5 { which should be mandatory for anyone playing Black here, and something to welcome with open arms.
White has two and a half options. The half is 6. Be3 } 6. Bd2 { The main move, giving Black a choice of whether to start with 6...c5 or 6...dxc4. Both will likely lead to the same position, although c5 at least gives White a choice. } (6. Bg5 h6 7. Bd2 (7. Bh4 c5 8. e3 (8. Nxd5 Nc6 9. e3 cxd4)) 7... e5!? (7... dxc4 8. e3 Be6 9. Ne4 (9. Nf3 c6 { Pinter, Jozsef - Popovic, Petar, 1-0, Thessaloniki ol (Men), 1988, https://lichess.org/Tlw9OdnM }) 9... O-O 10. Nf3 Bd5 { Heinig, Wolfram - Colovic, Aleksandar, 0-1, Bad Woerishofen op 21st, 2005, https://lichess.org/ODesEPkA }) 8. e3 exd4 9. exd4 O-O (9... dxc4?! 10. Qe2+ Kf8) 10. cxd5 Nf6 $10) (6. Be3 { a really odd-looking move once played by Ivan Sokolov, but after } 6... dxc4 7. Qa4+ { Black's simplest response would have been } 7... Nc6 8. Nf3 (8. d5 Bxc3+ { isn't an option. } { [%cal Gd8d5] }) 8... O-O 9. Qxc4 Be6 10. Qc5 Qd6 $15 { Black is clearly fine. His pieces are better and more harmoniously developed while the bishop on f1 will still need quite some time to join the fray. } { [%csl Bf1] }) 6... dxc4!? (6... c5!?) (6... e5 7. e3 exd4 8. exd4 O-O 9. cxd5 Nf6 { Aleksandrov, A. - Artemiev, V., 1/2-1/2, 18th ch-EUR Indiv 2017, https://lichess.org/IY2AS9q6 }) 7. e3 c5 8. Bxc4 { The only serious move in this position. } 8... cxd4 9. exd4 { The main position of the whole Rc1 line. } 9... Bxd4 { is an additional possibility I want to propose for Black. After all, if you're offered a whole pawn why not at least consider taking it? } 10. Nb5 { The move White will probably play, creating the threat of Nc7+. You can castle here. } { [%cal Rb5c7] } 10... Bb6!? { The most adventurous move in this position. } 11. Qb3 { [%cal Rc4f7] } 11... O-O 12. Bh6 Nc6 { Giving up the exchange on the spot is preferable. } 13. Bxf8 Qxf8 14. Nf3 Nf4 15. O-O Be6 { Black has excellent compensation for the exchange and is doing very well here. I sincerely recommend this position to anyone who wants slightly more exciting play after 8...cxd4 9.exd4. } *


