1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 { Grünfeld Defense } 4. cxd5 Nxd5 { Exchange Variation } 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 { Classical Variation.
Recommended by Schrantz. } { [%cal Gg1e2] } (7. Nf3 { Problematic. After } { [%cal Gf3d4] } 7... c5 { White can't play just casual moves like Be2 } 8. Be2 (8. Rb1 { is a way to make 7.Nf3 work, but it sacrifices the pawn on a2: } { [%cal Gb1b7] } 8... O-O { [%cal Gd8a5,Gc5d4] } 9. Be2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qa5+! 11. Bd2 Qxa2 $13 { Now Black is one pawn up, and the pawns on a and b are connected passed pawns.
White on the other hand has the initiative, and their pieces are better developed. } { [%csl Ga7,Gb7] }) 8... Nc6 9. Be3 Bg4! { This will remove one defender for d4, so White is almost forced to play } { [%cal Rf3d4] } 10. e5 { and weaken many light squares. } { [%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gf5,Ge6] }) 7... c5 8. Ne2 { [%cal Gc5d4,Gd8d4,Gg7d4,Re2d4,Rc3d4,Rd1d4] } 8... Nc6 (8... O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Bg4 { Main move } (10... Qc7 { [%cal Gf8d8,Gd8d1,Gc7c4] } 11. Rc1 Rd8 12. Bf4 { [%cal Gf4c7] } 12... Qd7 { [%cal Gd7d4,Gg7d4,Gc5d4,Gc6d4] } (12... e5) (12... Be5!) 13. d5 Na5 14. Bd3) 11. f3 Na5 { [%cal Ga5c4] } 12. Bd3 (12. Bxf7+ Rxf7 13. fxg4 Rxf1+ 14. Kxf1 (14. Qxf1 Nc4 { [%cal Gc4e3] } 15. Qc1 (15. Bf2?! Nd2 16. Qd1 Nxe4)) 14... cxd4 15. cxd4 e5 16. d5 Nc4 17. Bf2 Qf6 18. Kg1 Rf8) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Be6 { [%cal Ge6c4,Ga5c4] } 14. d5 (14. Rc1 Bxa2 15. Qa4 Be6 16. d5 Bd7 17. Qb4 e6 (17... b6?! { [%cal Ga5b7] } 18. Ba6) 18. Nc3 exd5 19. Nxd5 Be6 20. Rfd1 Bxd5 21. exd5 Re8 22. Bf2) (14. Qa4?! a6! { [%cal Gb7b5,Gb5c4] } 15. Rac1 b5 16. Qa3 Nc4 { [%cal Gc4e3] } 17. Bxc4 Bxc4 { [%csl Ge2][%cal Gc4e2] } 18. Rfe1 Bxe2 19. Rxe2 Bxd4) 14... Bxa1 15. Qxa1 { The bishop on e6 is not really hanging, because that would expose White's bishop on d3. } { [%csl Ge6] } 15... f6! 16. Bh6 (16. Qd4 Bf7 17. Bh6 Re8 18. Bb5 e5! { [%cal Ge8e7] } 19. Qf2 (19. dxe6? Rxe6 $17) 19... Re7 20. Bd3 (20. f4 { Topalov, Veselin - Shirov, Alexei, 1-0, Corus, 2007, https://lichess.org/PA42jWrO } 20... exf4 21. Qxf4 Qb6+ 22. Kh1 Bxd5 23. exd5 Qxb5 24. Qxf6 Qe8 25. Qd4 Rd8) 20... Rc8 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc8c4,Ga5c4] } 21. f4 Nc4 22. fxe5 Nxe5 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Ge5d3,Ge5g4,Gg4f2,Gg4h6] } (22... fxe5? 23. Bg5) 23. Qxf6 { [%cal Gf6g7] } 23... Bxd5 (23... Qb6+ { [%cal Gb6f6,Gb6g1] } 24. Qxb6 axb6 $10) 24. exd5 Ng4 (24... Nxd3?? 25. d6! Rd7 26. Qe6+ Kh8 27. Rf8+ Qxf8 28. Bxf8) 25. Qf4 Nxh6 26. Qxh6 Qb6+? (26... Qxd5) 27. Kh1 Qe3 { [%cal Ge3d3,Ge3h6] } 28. Qh4! Re5? 29. Qf6 Ree8 30. Bxg6! hxg6 31. Qxg6+ Kh8 32. Qf6+ Kh7 33. Qf7+ Kh8 34. Nf4 { Topalov, Veselin - Shirov, Alexei, 1-0, Morelia/Linares 25th, 2008, https://lichess.org/m4qteZIS } { [%cal Gf4g6] }) 16... Re8 { [%cal Gd8b6] } 17. Kh1 Rc8 18. Nf4 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7a4,Ga4c2] } 19. e5 Nc4 20. e6! Ba4 21. Nxg6! hxg6 22. Bxg6 Ne5 23. Be4 (23. Bxe8? { Trading is a very bad idea here; White is down on material and can't win such an endgame. } 23... Bxe8 $17) 23... Bc2 24. Bxc2 Rxc2 25. Qd1 $10 { [%cal Gf3f4] } 25... Kh7 (25... Qc7 26. f4 Rc1 27. Qxc1 Qxc1 28. Rxc1 Ng4 29. h3 Nxh6 30. g4) 26. f4 Kxh6 27. fxe5) 9. Be3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 (11. Qd2 { Avoids the draw } 11... Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 O-O 13. Rhd1 Rd8 14. Ke1) 11... Qd8 12. Be3 { Allows Black a draw by repetition: } (12. d5 { Exchange sacrifice that prevents the draw. } { [%cal Gg7a1] } 12... Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4] } 13. Bc3 O-O 14. Bb3 Qb6 15. f4 Ng4 { [%cal Gg4f2,Gb6f2] } 16. Bd4 { Svidler decided not to trade the dark-squared bishops and to go into an endgame instead. } 16... Qa5+ 17. Qd2 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 e5 19. h3! exd4 20. hxg4 g5 21. g3 Bxg4 22. e5 Bxe2 23. Kxe2 Rfc8 24. Rad1 Rc3 25. Rd3 Rac8 26. d6 b5 27. Rxc3 dxc3 28. e6 Kf8 29. e7+ Ke8 30. Bxf7+! { Kramnik, Vladimir - Svidler, Peter, 1-0, Dortmund, 1998, https://lichess.org/z7UOuiWa }) (12. Bc3) 12... Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Qd8 14. Be3 *


