1. Nf3 c5 { Zukertort Opening/Sicilian Invitation. If we want a reversed Grünfeld, we don't play e4, of course. } 2. g3 d5 { Transposition: King's Indian Attack/Sicilian Variation. } 3. Bg2 Nc6 { Transposition: King's Indian Attack/French Variation } 4. d4 e6 5. O-O { And now it transposes again to Zukertort Opening/Grünfeld Reversed } 5... Nf6 (5... cxd4) (5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nc3 { Now Black can either develop the knight to f6 and exchange the bishop, or move the bishop a second time and lose a tempo, or retreat with the queen and also lose a tempo. That's why the engine thinks this position is much better for White (+0.8). } { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gc3a4,Ba4b6,Ba4c5] } 7... Qd8 (7... Bb4) (7... Nf6) 8. Na4 (8. e4) 8... Be7 9. c4! Nf6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. e4 Nb6 12. Nc3 { [%csl Rb6] } (12. Nxb6 Qxb6 13. Qe2 e5 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Rac1 Qe7 { Nicolas Zapata, I. - Flear, G., 0-1, Gibraltar Masters 2014, https://lichess.org/CvZYEcOb }) 12... Qxd1 13. Rxd1) *


