{ This game was played by the Peruvian master Esteban Canal - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esteban_Canal - against an unknown amateur in a simultaneous exhibition he gave at Budapest in 1934. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 c6 5. Nf3 { Normal Scandi main line so far. } 5... Bg4 6. Bf4 { A rather unusual move. But it does take away the retreat square for Black's queen. } { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gf4c7,Ra5c7] } 6... e6 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bb4 { This is strategically dubious: The other pieces are still not developed. } { [%csl Ba8,Bb8,Bg8,Bh8] } 9. Be2 Nd7 10. a3 { Taking axb4 isn't a thread yet, because that would lose the rook on a1, but … } 10... O-O-O?? (10... Be7 11. O-O Ngf6 { That would be okay. Not great for Black, but playable. }) 11. axb4! { … now it is! The idea of this rook sacrifice is of course to remove the queen from the corner with the king. } 11... Qxa1+ 12. Kd2! { Offering a second rook. } 12... Qxh1 (12... Ne5 { The point here is to give the king an escape square. } { [%csl Bd7][%cal Re5f3,Bc8d7] } 13. Bxe5 Qxh1 14. Qxf7 { [%cal Gf7c7,Ge5c7] } 14... Rxd4+ 15. Ke3! Ne7 16. Kxd4 Kd8 17. Qxe6 Qxg2 18. Qd6+ Ke8 19. Qb8+ Kd7) 13. Qxc6+! bxc6 14. Ba6# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { Boden's mate. } 1-0


