{ The Toikkanen Gambit is a rare line in the Caro-Kann/Accelerated Panov Attack. It is not really a gambit. But it's very beautiful. You'll get a perfect harmony between tactical and positional challenges for both sides in almost all variations. }
1. e4 (1. c4 { Different move order, same result. } 1... c6 2. e4 d5) 1... c6 2. c4 d5 3. e5 { This is already the Toikkanen Gambit. There are different responses that lead to very different games. dxc4 is the best. } 3... dxc4 { This is the best response … and one of the rarest. } 4. Bxc4 { And this move is the reason why I don't call it a gambit. It's also the best move, according to Stockfish 8/depth 47. } (4. Nf3 { The Gambit line. }) 4... Qd4 { [%cal Rd4c4,Rd4e5] } 5. Qe2 { [%cal Re2c4,Re2e5] } 5... b5?! (5... Bg4 6. f3 Bf5 { is better }) 6. Bb3 Bg4 7. e6! Bxe2? { Now White collects the compensation: } (7... fxe6 { is better } 8. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3d4] } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qe5+ $14) 8. exf7+ Kd7 9. Nxe2 { A bishop … } { [%cal Ge2d4] } (9. fxg8=Q? Bg4) 9... Qg4 10. fxg8=Q { … a knight … } 10... Rxg8 11. Bxg8 { … and a rook } 11... Na6 $14 { White is a bit better here, mostly due to the material imbalance. } { [%csl Be2][%cal Gb1c3,Bc3e2,Ge1g1] } (11... Qxg2?! 12. Be6+ { Black can't take the bishop, because of the knight fork. } { [%cal Ge2f4] } 12... Kc7 (12... Kxe6?? 13. Nf4+! Kf7 14. Nxg2 $18) 13. Rg1 Qe4 14. Bg4 e5 15. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 15... Qc4 16. b3 Qf7 $16) *


