1. e4 c5 2. b3 b6 { The general idea for White here is to place the BISHOPS on b3 and d3 where they are aiming at Black's king side. White mights fianchetto both bishops alternatively, although this looks a bit anti-positional to me.
Black has similar ideas: bishops on b7 and d6, supported by the Queen on c7.
The queen side KNIGHTS are usually exchanged early on d4 or c6, prior to castling. That's why White has to play d4 as soon as possible. } { [%csl Bc6,Bd4][%cal Gc1b2,Gb2g7,Gf1d3,Gd3h7,Gc8b7,Gb7e4,Gf8d6,Gd6h2,Gd8c7,Bg1e2,Be2d4,Bd4c6,Bb8c6] } 3. Nc3 { Prevent d5. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Gc3d5,Ge4d5] } (3. Bb2 Bb7 4. d3) 3... Bb7 4. Bb2 e6 (4... Nc6 { [%cal Rc6e5,Rc6d4] } 5. g3 (5. Nge2 Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 e6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Bd3 $10) (5. Nf3 e6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Bd3 $10) 5... Nf6 6. Nge2 (6. Bg2) 6... e5 7. Bg2 $10) 5. d4 { Best move according to the engine. It resolves the tension on d4 and enables queen side castling. } (5. Nf3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Bd3 Bd6 { White will castle long now, Black will probably castle short, because the pawn structure is better there.
White will then start to push the king side pawns. } 10. Qe2 Be5 { [%cal Ge1b1,Re8g8,Bh1e1,Gf2f5,Gg2g5,Gh2h5,Rd8c7] }) 5... cxd4 6. Qxd4 { [%cal Gd4g7] } 6... Nc6 { White has to be very precise now. } { [%cal Rc6d4,Rc6b4,Rf8b4] } 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. f3 $10 { Bd3 runs into Nb4, and then Black can exchange their knight against the bishop. } { [%cal Ge1c1] } (8. Bd3 Nb4 { [%cal Rb4d3] } 9. Nf3 Nxd3+ 10. cxd3) *


