1. e4 e6 2. c4 { Steiner Variation. The idea here is to get an IQP or a Maróczy Bind, depending on Black's reaction } 2... d5 (2... c5 { Transposes to a Sicilian, but that's okay. } 3. Nf3 { And now we are in the Sicilian/Kramnik Variation, a very solid Maróczy Bind. } (3. Nc3 { is also playable. } 3... Nc6 { But then Black takes control over d4, and that's a bit uncomfortable. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Rc6d4] } 4. g3 g6 (4... Nf6 5. Bg2 d5 6. exd5 exd5 7. cxd5 Nb4 { [%cal Rb4d3] } 8. d3! Nfxd5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Ne2 Be7 11. O-O O-O $10) 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. Nge2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 d6 9. Rb1 b6 10. a3 (10. Be3 Nd4 11. b4 Bb7) 10... Bb7 11. b4 Qd7) 3... Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 { The idea here is to play f4 in one go if we can, that's why we don't play f3 to protect the pawn. } 8... e5 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 d6 11. h3 (11. Na4 d5 12. exd5 cxd5 13. a3 Be7 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Bc5 { Kramnik, Vladimir - Kasparov, Garry, 1-0, PCA/Intel-GP, 1994, https://lichess.org/OzoZLvKD }) 11... Be6 12. Rc1) 3. exd5 { We take it. Doesn't matter with which pawn. } (3. e5?! { Doesn't work. The advanced pawn is hard to defend. } 3... dxc4 (3... d4 4. d3 Nc6 (4... c5) 5. f4) 4. Bxc4 c5 5. Nf3 (5. d4 { Transposition to the French/Advance Variation.
We can reach this position also per 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c4 dxc4 5. Bxc4 } 5... cxd4 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nbd2) 5... Nc6 6. O-O Nge7 7. Nc3) (3. cxd5 exd5 4. exd5) 3... exd5 4. cxd5 { Now we are in a situation that is close to a normal Scandinavian minus two pawns.
The main difference is that we are playing with an isolated queen's pawn (IQP) on d2. Which means, we have to push this pawn, we are responsible for the attack, and we want to avoid an endgame with that pawn, so we don't trade off too much material. Especially the dark-squared bishop will be important in the future. } { [%csl Bd2,Bc1][%cal Yc1h6] } (4. d4 { Transposition: Exchange Variation/Monte Carlo Variation.
But we don't want to transpose into well known theory, right? }) 4... Nf6 (4... Qxd5?! { The problem with this move is that White now can push the d-pawn soon and get it to the important square d5. } 5. Nc3 { Develop with a tempo. } 5... Qd8 { Best move. Sad for Black. } (5... Qe6+) (5... Qe5+ 6. Be2 Bg4?! { I had that in a game recently. } 7. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3b7] } (7. d4 Bxe2 (7... Qe6? 8. Qa4+ Qd7 (8... Nd7 9. d5 Qe7 10. Qxg4 $18) 9. Bxg4) 8. Ngxe2 Qa5) 7... Bxe2 8. Ngxe2 b6 $16) (5... Qa5 6. Nf3 (6. Bc4 { Our light-squared bishop will be on this diagonal anyway. } { [%cal Gc4f7] } 6... Nc6) 6... Nf6 7. Bb5+ c6 8. Qe2+ Be7 9. Bc4 Na6 (9... O-O?? 10. Qxe7)) 6. Bc4 (6. d4 { Push the IQP. } 6... Nf6 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rf6d5,Rd8d5] } 7. Nf3 (7. d5? { We don't have enough active pieces to protect this pawn. })) (6. Nf3) 6... Bd6 7. Nf3 Nf6 (7... Qe7+) (7... Ne7?! { We get a free pawn! } 8. Ng5! { [%cal Rc4f7,Rg5f7] } 8... Nf5 (8... O-O?!) 9. Bxf7+ Kf8 10. d3 h6 11. Qh5! Nd4 { [%csl Rc2,Re7][%cal Rd8e7,Re7e2,Rd4c2,Re7f7] } 12. Bg6 Qe7+ (12... Nc2+? 13. Kd1 Nxa1? 14. Re1 { [%cal Re1e8] } 14... Be7 15. Qf3+ { Now it's mate in 19 moves. } 15... Bf6 16. Qd5 Bg4+ 17. f3 Qd7 18. fxg4 hxg5 19. b3) 13. Kd1) 8. Qe2+ { Throw in a check. } 8... Qe7) 5. Nc3 (5. Bb5+ { The engine doesn't like this move, but French players hate it! } 5... Nbd7 (5... Bd7?! 6. Bc4 { And now Black has to WORK to get the pawn back. } 6... Bd6?! 7. Qe2+! Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Bxe7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Nge2 a6 $14 { Li, Qun - Kjartansson, David, 1-0, Wch U20 41st, 2002, https://lichess.org/qbzNHZgE }) 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Nf3 (7. d4 O-O 8. Nf3 Nb6 9. O-O Nbxd5 10. Re1 c6 11. Bc4 Be6 12. Bb3 Re8 13. Bg5 Qb6) 7... O-O 8. O-O (8. d4 Nb6 9. O-O (9. h3 Nbxd5 (9... Bf5 10. O-O a6 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nfxd5 13. Re1 Re8 14. Bd2 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bf6 16. c4 Qd7 17. Bg5 Qc6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qb3 Qc6 20. Ne5 Qe6 21. Rac1 Rad8 22. a4 a5 23. Re3 f6 24. d5 Qc8 25. Ng4 Qd7 26. d6 Rxe3 27. Nxe3 Kf8 28. c5 Nc8 29. Qxb7 cxd6 30. c6 Qxb7 31. cxb7 Nb6 32. Nd5 { Vachier Lagrave, Maxime - Bacrot, Etienne, 1-0, Bundesliga 1213, 2012, https://lichess.org/GrA7t3Ee }) 10. O-O Bf5 11. Re1 Bb4 12. Bd2 c6 13. Bc4 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne4 15. Rc1 Qf6 16. Ne5 Rfe8 17. f3 Nd6 18. Bb3 Be6 19. Qe2 h6 20. Qf2 Nb6 21. c4 Nd7 22. Bc3 Qd8 23. d5 cxd5 24. cxd5 Bf5 25. Qg3 Nf6 26. Ba1 Nh5 27. Qf2 Nf4 28. Kh2 f6 29. Nc4 Nd3 30. Qg3 Rxe1 31. Nxd6 Rxc1 32. Nxf5 Qf8 33. d6+ Kh7 34. Ne7 Rxa1 35. Qg6+ Kh8 36. Qxd3 { Vachier Lagrave, Maxime - Caruana, F., 1-0, GCT Blitz Paris 2016, https://lichess.org/hufC9eTY }) 9... Nbxd5 (9... Bf5 10. Re1 Nfxd5 11. Ne4 Bb4 12. Bd2 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 Nf6 14. Nc5 Rb8 15. h3 c6 16. Bf1 Nbd7 17. Qf4 Bg6 18. Bc4 Nb6 19. Bb3 Nbd5 20. Qd2 b6 21. Nd3 Rc8 22. Nde5 Qd6 23. Nxg6 hxg6 24. Rac1 Rfd8 25. Ne5 Nd7 26. Nc4 Qf6 27. Ne3 Nxe3 28. Qxe3 Nf8 29. Qe5 Qxe5 30. Rxe5 Rc7 31. Rce1 Rxd4 32. Re7 Rxe7 33. Rxe7 Ne6 34. Rxa7 c5 35. Bxe6 fxe6 36. Rb7 Rb4 37. b3 Kf8 38. Kf1 c4 39. bxc4 Rxc4 40. Rxb6 Rc1+ 41. Ke2 Rc2+ 42. Ke3 Rxa2 43. Rxe6 Kf7 44. Rb6 Ra3+ 45. Kf4 Ra2 46. Kg3 g5 { Spassky, Boris V - Kortschnoj, Viktor, 1/2-1/2, Elista m, 2009, https://lichess.org/prdXTUQJ }) 10. Re1 c6 11. Bc4 Be6 12. Bb3 Re8 (12... h6 13. Ne5 Re8 14. Qf3 Bf8 15. Bd2 Nb4 16. Ne4 Nbd5 17. Ng3 Nd7 18. Rad1 Qc7 19. Nh5 f6 20. Ng6 Bd6 21. Nxg7 Kxg7 22. Qh5 Bxh2+ 23. Kf1 Bf4 24. Nxf4 Nxf4 25. Bxf4 Qxf4 26. Bxe6 Re7 27. Rd3 Rae8 28. Rg3+ Qxg3 29. fxg3 Rxe6 30. Qxe8 Rxe8 31. Rxe8 Kf7 32. Ra8 Ke6 33. Rxa7 b5 34. Ke2 f5 35. Kf3 Nf6 36. a3 Ng4 37. b3 Nf6 38. a4 Ne4 39. a5 Nd2+ 40. Kf4 Nxb3 41. a6 { Benjamin, Joel - Van der Sterren, Paul, 1-0, Munich SKA, 1994, https://lichess.org/0ERbVVDC }) 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd5 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Qd2 Qa5 18. c4 Qxd2 19. Nxd2 Nc7 20. d5 Rd8 21. dxe6 Rxd2 22. exf7+ Kxf7 23. c5+ Kf6 24. Rxe7 Kxe7 25. Re1+ Kf6 26. h4 g5 { Salgado Lopez, I. - Fressinet, L., 1/2-1/2, TCh-FRA Top 12 2014, https://lichess.org/acyJSt4V }) 8... Nb6 9. d4 Nbxd5 10. Re1 c6 11. Bc4 Be6 12. Bb3 Re8) 5... Nxd5 6. Nf3 Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. Bc4 Nb6 