15... Bxh2+ (15... Qxh4 { This does keep the advantage, but there is a much better line. } 16. g3 Qh3 17. Nxf8 Nb4 18. Qf1 Qxf1+ 19. Rxf1 Kxf8) (15... Qd6 { This gives White Bg3, and that's bad for Black. } 16. Bg3 Nxg3 17. Nxf8 Ne4 18. g3 f5) 16. Kf1 (16. Kxh2? Qxh4+ 17. Qh3 Qxh3+ 18. Kxh3 fxe6 { [%cal Gf5d4,Gc6d4] } 19. Rad1) 16... fxe6 (16... Qxh4 { Not a bad move, but you are stopping your own attack with this. } 17. Nxf8 Ncxd4 18. Nd7) 17. Bxd8 Ng3+ (17... Raxd8 { This allows White to trap your bishop with g3. } 18. g3 Bxg3 19. fxg3) 18. Qxg3 Bxg3 { Well done! I missed this in my game: https://lichess.org/m0naSaYW/black#29
Tricks on dark-square diagonals are always a motif in the Caro-Kann, because the pawns are on light squares. } *


