1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d5!? { White should take this pawn } 3. cxd5 { Black can't just take back this pawn. It wouldn't be a gambit in that case. :) } (3. Nc3?! e6 { And we are in normal QGD waters. Boring! }) (3. Nf3 c6 { Slav Defense. Boring! }) 3... c6! { Here is our gambit. It's called the Tan Gambit. } (3... Nxd5 4. e4! { Now White can play e4 with a tempo. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5) 4. dxc6 { Nc3 and Nf3 transpose to the Slav Defense/Exchange Variation. } (4. Nf3 cxd5) (4. Nc3 cxd5) (4. g3 cxd5 5. Bg2 { A position you can get get from the English Opening/Anglo-Indian Defense }) 4... Nxc6 5. Nf3 e5! { The whole point of this gambit is an open center and a rapid development. Giving the e-pawn away temporarily is an idea that we know already from the Budapest Defense. } (5... Bg4 { is playable. } 6. e3 e5 7. dxe5 (7. Bb5?! e4 8. h3 exf3 9. hxg4 fxg2 10. Rg1 Qd5 { [%cal Gd5g2,Gd5b5] } 11. Nc3 Bb4 { Drozdovskij, Yuri - Dobrov, Vladimir, 0-1, EU-ch Internet Cand 3rd, 2006, https://lichess.org/1EErB5jc }) 7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nxe5 { [%cal Gg4f3,Ge5f3] } 9. Bb5+ Nc6 { [%cal Ge8c8] } 10. Ke2 $14) 6. dxe5 (6. e3 exd4 (6... Bb4+) (6... Bg4) 7. Nxd4 (7. exd4) 7... Nxd4 (7... Bb4+) 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. exd4 Bb4+ 10. Nc3 (10. Bd2) 10... O-O) (6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Ng4 { [%cal Gg4f2] } 9. Ke1 Bc5 10. e3 Nxe5 { Ends up in our main line. }) 6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Ng4 { Forcing … } { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gg4f2] } 8. Ke1 { … and after … } 8... Bc5 9. e3 Ngxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Bd2 { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rd2c3,Rc3e5] } 11... f6 (11... Bf5 12. Bc3 Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 Bxd3 14. Nd2) (11... O-O 12. Bc3 Re8 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. Nb3) 12. Bc3 Be6 13. Bxe5 fxe5 14. Bb5+ Kf7 15. Ke2 *


