{ This opening is named after the Polish-Argentine grandmaster Miguel Najdorf. }
1. e4 c5 { B20 Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { B57 Modern Variations, Main Line } 5. Nc3 a6 { B90 Najdorf Variation. Black's plan is usually to start a minority attack on the queenside and exert pressure on White's e4-pawn. This is often carried out by means of ...b5, ...Bb7, and placing a knight on c5, or c4 via b6. } { [%csl Bc4,Bc5][%cal Gb7b5,Rc8b7,Bb8c5] } 6. Bg5 (6. Be2 { B92 Opocensky Variation } 6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O O-O { Opocensky Variation/Traditional Line } (8... Be6 { Opocensky Variation/Modern Line } 9. f4 Qc7 10. f5 Bc4)) (6. h3 { B90 Adams Attack }) (6. g4 { B90 Dekker Gambit }) (6. Rg1 { B90 Freak Attack }) (6. Be3 { B90 English Attack. Main line nowadays. } 6... Ng4 { English Attack/Anti-English }) (6. g3 { B91 Zagreb (Fianchetto) Variation }) (6. f4 { B93 Amsterdam Variation }) 6... e6 7. f4 { Threat: 8.e5. } { [%cal Re4e5] } 7... Be7 (7... b5 { B96 Polugayevsky Variation } 8. e5 dxe5 9. fxe5 Qc7 10. Qe2 { Polugayevsky Variation/Simagin Line }) (7... Nc6 { B96 Neo-Classical Defense }) (7... Qb6 { B97 Poisoned Pawn Variation. Main move nowadays. } 8. Qd2 Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 { Poisoned Pawn/Accepted }) 8. Qf3 Qc7 { B98 Traditional Line } (8... h6 9. Bh4 g5 { B98 Goteborg (Argentine) } (9... Qc7 { Browne Variation }) (9... Nbd7 { NN } 10. O-O-O Qc7)) 9. O-O-O Nbd7 { B99 Main Line. Often also called the "Old Main Line". 10.g4 or 10.Bd3 are common continuations. } { [%cal Gg2g4,Gf1d3] } *


