{ Not a threat, just an invitation for Black to play Nf6 with a tempo. }
1. e4 c5 2. Qg4?! { Amazon Attack.
I found only one game for that in the database: between Anna Lena Luepken and Elisabeth Rieper, Lingen-ch, U11 Girls, 1995. Black won. } (2. Qh5 { Another way to get to the position on move 3. } 2... Nf6 3. Qh4) 2... Nf6 3. Qh4 { The same position can be reached via 1.e4 c5 2.Qh5?! Nf6 3.Qh4, a line that Nakamura tried 3 times. He lost every game. } 3... Nc6 4. c3?! (4. Be2) (4. Nf3 d6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. O-O e5 (6... g6 7. d3 h6 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Rc8 11. Re1 Bg7 12. Nc3 b6 13. a4 Bb7 14. a5 g5 15. Qa4+ Nd7 16. a6 Ba8 17. Qxd7+ Qxd7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5a7] } 19... Bc6 20. Nxa7 Rc7 21. Nxc6 Kxc6 22. f4 g4 { Rapport, R. - Grischuk, A., 0-1, chess.com Speed 3m+2spm 2017, https://lichess.org/YZF4ItZo }) 7. d3 Be7 $15) 4... d5 5. d3 e5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Nf3 (7. Nd2 { Just a different move order. } 7... h6 8. Ngf3 O-O) 7... O-O 8. Nbd2 h6 9. Bxf6 (9. Bxh6? { Invites Black to trap White's queen: } 9... Nxe4! { [%cal Re7h4] } 10. Qh5 g6 { The queen is trapped. } { [%cal Re7h4,Rc8h3,Rg6f5] } 11. Bxf8 Qxf8 12. dxe4 gxh5 13. exd5 Nd8 { Nakamura, Hikaru - Karjakin, Sergey, 0-1, Karjakin-Nakamura m, 2005, https://lichess.org/JXEItvYU }) 9... Bxf6 10. Qg3 d4 11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O Rc8 13. Rfc1 { Nakamura, Hikaru - Markus, Robert, 0-1, Champions Challenge 92nd, 2005, https://lichess.org/0qf4gRYz } *


