{ Sharp, needs careful play on both sides, but Black is getting better out of the opening. If you don't remember the exact lines, keep in mind that you should attack White's queen with every move. Do not allow White to develop the pieces. }
1. e4 c5 2. d4 { Smith-Morra Gambit } 2... cxd4 3. Qxd4 Nc6 4. Qd1 Nf6 5. Bc4 { Coles Sicilian Gambit } { [%csl Be4] } 5... Nxe4 6. Bxf7+! { The whole point of this line. } 6... Kxf7 7. Qd5+ e6 (7... Ke8?! { Too passive! } 8. Qxe4 d5 9. Qe2 g6 $15) 8. Qxe4 { Looking at the lichess online database, we can see that many other moves besides d5 have been tried here. d5 is the best, but let's see what happens if Black doesn't find it. } 8... d5 (8... Qa5+? { Pointless counter-attack that allows White to develop their pieces finally. } 9. Nc3 d5 10. Qf4+ Kg8 $10 { Again, White has equalized by developing their pieces faster. }) (8... Be7 { This one is okay, just a bit too passive. } 9. Nc3 d5 10. Qf3+ Bf6 11. Nge2 Ne5 { [%cal Re5f3] } 12. Qg3 Bd7 $15) (8... Qf6 { Doesn't attack anything and gives White time to develop the pieces. } 9. Nf3 d5 10. Qe2 h6 $15) (8... Nb4? { Terrible. } 9. a3 Nc6 10. Nc3 d5 11. Qd3 Be7 $10 { Completely equal position now. }) (8... Bc5 { The idea here is probably to get the rook from h8 into the game. } 9. Qf3+ (9. Nf3 { The only response I could find the database. Dubious. } 9... d5 10. Qf4+ Qf6 11. O-O e5 $15) 9... Kg8 { The only move. Now the rook on h8 is out of the game for a long time. } (9... Qf6? 10. Qh5+ Qg6 11. Qxc5 $16) (9... Kg6? 10. Qg4+ Kf7 11. Qh5+ Kg8 12. Qxc5 $16) 10. Nc3 d5 11. Bf4 $10 { Now White has equalized, because they are way ahead in development. }) 9. Qf3+ Qf6 { Exchanging queens on the black side is not what White wants. Then Black can create a passer later with their three connected pawns, and it wouldn't help White's development. } 10. Be3 (10. Bg5 Nd4 11. Bxf6 Nxf3+ 12. Nxf3 gxf6 $16) (10. Qxf6+?! gxf6 11. Ne2 Nb4 $16 { [%cal Rb4c2] }) 10... Qxf3 (10... d4 { That's a move, but it's probably not good to push the pawns so early. Develop pieces first, so you can support the pawns properly. } 11. Bg5 Qxf3 12. Nxf3 e5) 11. Nxf3 e5 12. c3 Be7 13. O-O (13. Ng5+ Kg6 { Weird engine recommendation. But it does send the knight back, and White has neither a light-squared bishop nor a queen anymore, so light squares are rather safe.. } 14. Nf3 d4! 15. cxd4 exd4 { White can't take that pawn. It's poisoned. } { [%csl Rd4] } 16. Bf4 (16. Bxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bf6! { [%cal Rf6b2] }) (16. Nxd4? Bf6 17. Nxc6 Bxb2 18. Ne7+ Kf7 19. Nd5 Bf5 20. Nd2 Bxa1) 16... Nb4 { [%cal Rb4c2] } 17. Kd2 Rf8 { [%cal Rf8f4] } 18. Re1 { [%cal Re1e7] } 18... Nd5 { This makes b4 free for the bishop who can attack the king and the rook now from there. So White has to take that bishop and give up an exchange. } { [%csl Bb4][%cal Rd5f4,Rd5e7,Rf8f4,Re7b4,Rb4e1] } 19. Rxe7 Nxe7 20. Bd6 Re8 21. Na3 (21. Nxd4? { Still a poisoned pawn! } 21... Rd8 22. Bxe7 Rxd4+ 23. Ke3 (23. Kc1? Bf5 24. b4 { [%cal Re7b4] } 24... Re8 25. Bc5 Re1+ 26. Kb2 Re2+ 27. Kb3 Rd3+ 28. Kc4 Rc2+ 29. Kb5) 23... Rd1 { Now the knight can't move. }) 21... Be6 22. Nb5 { [%cal Rb5c7] } 22... Nf5 { [%cal Rf5d6] } 23. Bf4 (23. Nc7? Nxd6 24. Nxa8 Ne4+ 25. Ke1 Rxa8 $19) 23... Bc4 { [%csl Re2,Bd4][%cal Rc4e2,Re8e2,Ra8d8,Rd8d2] } 24. Nc7 Re2+ 25. Kd1 Rd8 26. Ne5+ { [%cal Re5g6,Re5c4] } 26... Kf6 27. Nxc4 { Now the material situation isn't so bad for White anymore. } 27... Rxf2 { [%cal Rf2f4] } 28. Be5+ Kf7 $17) 13... h6 $17 { Material is equal, but Black has two center pawns and the bishop pair. } *


