{ Just a different move order for the Flohr Variation, 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Qc7. But White doesn't have to play the "missing" moves and can prepare d4 with c3. Not dangerous at all. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Qc7?! { Quinteros Variation. Named after https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miguel_Quinteros } 3. c3 (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3) (3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 { Transposes to the Paulsen Variation/Bastrikov }) 3... Nf6 (3... d6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd3 g6 6. h3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Be3 b6 9. Nbd2 e5 10. Re1 Nc6 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. Rad1 Rad8 14. Bg5 Rd7 15. Nf1 Rfd8 16. Ne3 Ne7 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Bc4 Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 20. Nxd1 Qc6 21. Qb3 Qxe4 22. Bxf7+ Kg7 23. Ne3 Qb1+ 24. Nf1 e4 25. Nd2 Qe1 26. Be8 Bd5 27. Qa4 Bh4 28. g3 e3 29. fxe3 Bg5 { Smyslov, Vassily - Polgar, Judit, 0-1, Women-Veterans, 1995, https://lichess.org/AU1t8760 }) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bd3 dxe5 8. Nxe5 e6 9. O-O Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nd2 c5 12. Nf3 Bd6 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Qa4+ Bd7 15. Qg4 g6 16. Bh6 Bf8 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. Rac1 Qb6 19. Ne5 Be8 20. Nc4 Qd8 21. Be4 Qf6 22. Bxd5 exd5 23. Ne3 Qxb2 24. Nxd5 Kg7 25. Rc3 { Timman, Jan H - Quinteros, Miguel Angel, 1-0, Mar del Plata, 1982, https://lichess.org/WfuanD1e } *


[Event "Sicilian Sidelines: Staunton-Cochrane - 2.c4"]
[Date "2018.03.16"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B20"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Staunton-Cochrane Variation"]
[StudyName "Sicilian Sidelines"]
[ChapterName "Staunton-Cochrane - 2.c4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dBsFYZ3Q/5waCpYsa"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2018.03.16"]
[UTCTime "07:44:34"]

{ Playable for both sides. Black should prevent White from building a Maróczy Bind. d7-d5 should be played as soon as it's safe in order to open the position. Otherwise White can maintain more space in the center for a long time.

This variation deserves a separate study. }
1. e4 c5 2. c4 { B20 Staunton-Cochrane Variation } 2... Nc6 { [%cal Rc5d4,Rc6d4] } (2... Nf6 { White can now play the annoying move e5 and maybe trap the knight if it goes to e4. But if Black just plays Ng8, White will very likely lose the e-pawn, or it will be an expensive liability.
e5 is a move for a very short time control. } 3. Nc3 { The stronger move in a longer game. } (3. e5 Ng8 $10 { The only move. } (3... Ne4? { This knight is toast. } 4. d3 Qa5+ (4... Nxf2 5. Kxf2) 5. Ke2 { Nothing else! We don't want to give Black a piece for the knight. } 5... Nxf2 6. Kxf2 $18) 4. Nf3 (4. d4 $146 { Novelty. Perhaps not a good one. } 4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qc3 g6 7. e6 f6 $15) 4... Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. exd6 (6. d4 { Or open the position completely. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 dxe5 (7... Nxe5 { [%cal Re5g4,Rc8g4] } 8. Be2 g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Be3 Nf6 { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rc8g4,Rf6g4,Re5g4] } 11. h3 O-O $15) 8. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 10. b3 e6 $15 { Black is just a pawn up here. }) 6... e5 7. Ne4 { The engine doesn't like this move, but I think it's mildly annoying. :) }) 3... Nc6 { [%cal Rc6d4] } (3... e6 { Transposition to English/Mikenas-Carls/Sicilian }) 4. Nge2 e6 5. d4 { And now Black has to decide: allow a Maróczy Bind (cxd4), or go for a sharp line (d5)? Black must prevent the move d5 by White somehow. } 5... d5 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bc5 7. Nb3 Bb4 { [%cal Rf6e4] } 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Ne5 { White can't move the bishop. } { [%cal Re5d3,Re5c4,Rf6e4] } 10. f4 Qb6+ 11. Kh1 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 d5 $13 14. e5 (14. cxd5 exd5 15. exd5 (15. e5 Ne4 { [%cal Re4f2,Rb6f2] } 16. Be3 Qc6 $10) 15... Re8 $10 { Take the open file. }) 14... Ne4 15. cxd5 Nf2+ 16. Rxf2 Qxf2 17. Be3 Qh4 18. c4 b6 $10) (5... d6?! 6. d5 Ne5 7. f4 Ng6 $16 (7... Nxc4? 8. Qa4+ { [%cal Ra4c4] })) 6. exd5 exd5 7. Bg5 Be7 (7... dxc4?!) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Ncxe7 { This knight, not the other one. :) You still don't want to allow d5. } 10. dxc5 O-O $10) 3. Ne2 (3. Nf3 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. g3 Be7 6. Bg2 f5 $10) 3... Nf6 { [%cal Rf6d5] } (3... e5 { The downside of e5 is that d5 now is close to impossible for a long time. The position will stay closed. } 4. Nbc3 { [%cal Rc3d5] } 4... Nge7 5. d3) 4. Nbc3 e6 { [%cal Re6d5,Rf6d5,Rd8d5] } (4... e5 { Prevents d4. } 5. g3 d6 6. Bg2) 5. d4 d5 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bc5 7. Nb3 Bb4 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O) 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 dxe4 (7... Be7) 8. d5 (8. Nxe4? cxd4 { [%cal Rf8b4,Rd8a5,Ya5e1] } 9. Nxf6+ gxf6 10. Bd2 Qe7 { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rd4d3] } 11. Qc2 Be6 12. O-O-O Qd7 $17) 8... Nb4 9. Ng3 Be7 10. Bb5+ Kf8 (10... Bd7 11. d6! Bxb5 12. Nxb5 Nd3+ 13. Ke2 O-O 14. dxe7 (14. Nxe4 Nxb2) 14... Qxe7 $10) *


