{ In this study I want to explore a rather weird line in the English opening. I saw this first in the game Svidler - MVL, 2018, and I didn't understand why either side would go for that. White's position is messed up, and Black is down two tempi. So what's the point? }
1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 (4. d4?! { Certainly playable, but it leads to a rather dry position. } 4... cxd4 5. Nxd5 Nxd5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 $10) 4... Nxd5 { Symmetrical Variation, Three Knights Variation } 5. e4 { Avoiding a Grünfeld position. Now it's more a a Sicilian. However, this move creates a hole on d3. } { [%csl Bd3][%cal Rd5b4,Rb4d3] } (5. d4 { This is probably the best move for White here, but it is also what Black wants: a Grünfeld position. } 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 g6 7. e4 Bg7 { And here we are in the Exchange Grünfeld. This is the reason why White isn't playing d4: they want to avoid this line. }) (5. g3) 5... Nb4 6. Bc4?! { The main move. } (6. Bb5+ { This is the one move to avoid the following mess. } 6... N8c6 (6... Bd7 7. a3 N4c6) 7. O-O a6) (6. d4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Bd7 (7... N8c6?! 8. a3 dxc3 (8... Bd7) (8... Qb6) (8... Qd6) (8... Na6? 9. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gb5c6] } 9... Bd7 (9... Nb8 10. Bf4 { [%cal Gf4b8] } 10... Bd7 11. Nf3 $16)))) 6... Nd3+ 7. Ke2 (7. Bxd3?! Qxd3) (7. Kf1?! Nc6) 7... Nf4+ 8. Kf1 { White's position is messed up, and Black is down two tempi. So what's the point? } 8... Ne6 { Black has only two pieces developed, the pawn and the knight.
White is two tempi up, but the misplaced king will cost extra tempi finding safety. The lead in development is a dynamic advantage, meaning: it will fade away over time. So White is under pressure to attack as soon as possible to make use of that. } { [%csl Bf1] } (8... Nd3 { Sometimes Black goes just back. After Ke2, this leads to a quick draw by repetition, if both players want that. } 9. Qe2 { is the main move. I think Qb3 is more active. } (9. Qb3 { [%cal Gc4f7] } 9... e6 { The only move. } 10. Qb5+! $13 { A nice multi-purpose move, that is asking Black some important questions. } { [%cal Gb5b7,Gb5e8,Gc4d3] } (10. Bb5+?! Nc6 11. Na4 { [%cal Gb3d3,Gb5d3] } 11... Nb4 12. a3 Qa5 $13 { Jakovenko, Dmitrij - Caruana, Fabiano, 1/2-1/2, RUS-chT 20th, 2013, https://lichess.org/L2N4vC3r } { [%cal Ra5b5] })) 9... Nxc1 10. Rxc1 e6 $13) 9. b4 { Is better than d3, because it makes d4 possible and a strong grip on the center. Black should probably just ignore this, because the extra pawn wouldn't be for long, and develop instead. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 9... g6 (9... cxb4 10. Ne2) 10. bxc5 Bg7 { Black is still controlling d4. This is why the engine is recommending Bxe6 here. The problem with this move is that White is giving Black the bishop pair. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Rd8d4,Re6d4,Rg7d4] } 11. Bxe6 (11. Bd5 $146 { Novelty! It's an interesting try, I think. It does block the view of Black's queen on d4 without giving up the light-squared bishop immediately. } 11... Qa5 { [%cal Re6c5] } (11... O-O 12. d4 { Maybe too early? } 12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 e6 14. Bf4 { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gf4c7] } 14... exd5 { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gf4c7] } 15. Nxd5 { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gf4c7,Gd5c7] } 15... Nc6 { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gd5c7,Gf4c7] } 16. Nb5 { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gb5c7,Gd5c7,Gf4c7] }) 12. Rb1 { [%cal Gb1b7,Gd5b7] }) *


