1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. d3 c6 { Main line here is h6. If White takes immediately (7. dxc6), it will lose castling rights. } (6... Nxd5? 7. Qf3 $16) (6... h6 7. Nf3) 7. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2e8] } (7. dxc6 Nxc4 8. dxc4 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 { Losing Castling right without queens is not often a problem. White king will find a home on the k-side later. } 9... bxc6 10. Nc3 Bf5 11. Re1 Bd6 12. f3 O-O 13. Nge4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bc7 15. Be3 Rfd8+ 16. Ke2 Be6 17. b3 f5 18. Nc5 Bf7 19. Kf1 $16 { White is a pawn up, the 2 black bishops are not very strong }) (7. O-O { No game for that in the database. } { Natural move } 7... cxd5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. c4 h6 (9... dxc4? 10. Bxc4 $16) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nf3 Bd6 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 O-O 14. Re1 Re8 $10) 7... Bd6? { Black should take the pawn on d5. -0.4 → +0.6. Maybe the decisive mistake. From now on White is slowly getting better and better. } (7... cxd5 8. Qxe5+ Be7 9. Bb5+ Nc6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 $10) 8. dxc6 { This situation is the main problem of 6…c6. } { Black should avoid this with 7....cd5: } { [%cal Gc4f7,Gg5f7] } 8... O-O (8... Nxc4 9. dxc4 { Would prevent a potential trade on f2. }) 9. Nc3 (9. Bxf7+ Rxf7 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. cxb7 Bxb7 12. O-O { Also interesting. White is now behind in development, but up in material with a much better pawn structure and a safe king. Black's king is awkward. }) 9... Nxc4 10. dxc4 bxc6 11. Nge4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Be7?! (12... Bc7 { Why would you give up the protection for the e-pawn? } 13. O-O f5 14. Ng3 Qe7 15. b3 { White is better. It is not clear how the bishop pair gets active. After c5 to get the nice b7-square white can bring his knight to d5. }) 13. Bd2 f5 14. Nc3 Bd6 15. O-O-O Qe7 16. b3 Bd7 17. Rhe1 { Prevents Black's f4. } { [%cal Ge2e7] } 17... Rae8 18. Na4 { Frees c3 for the bishop. } (18. g3 e4 19. Kb1) 18... Kh8?! { The king makes itself a target for White's black square bishop. Better to keep it on a light square. } 19. Bc3 { Black's queen is now slightly overloaded. } { [%cal Gd1d7] } 19... Bc8 20. Rxd6?! { A prophylactic Kb1 would have been better. } 20... Qxd6 21. Bxe5 Qd8?! (21... Qa3+ { [%cal Ge8e2] } 22. Kb1 f4 23. g4 Kg8 24. Nb2) 22. f4 Kg8 { See the note on 18…Kh8. } 23. Qf3 { [%csl Rc6] } 23... Qh4 (23... Re6 24. Qf2 { [%csl Ra7] } 24... Rg6 25. g3 Rf7) 24. g3 Qh6 (24... Qxh2?? 25. Rh1) 25. Nc5 Rd8 26. h4 Rfe8 27. Qc3 Qh5? (27... Re7 28. Kb2 Qg6 29. Qb4 { [%cal Gb4e7] } 29... Rf8 30. Nd3 Rb7) 28. Kb2? (28. Bxg7 Rxe1+ 29. Qxe1 { [%cal Ge1e7] } 29... Qe8 30. Qc3 Qf7 31. Qa5) 28... Qf7 29. Qa5 h6 30. Nd3?! (30. Rc1 Rf8 31. Re1 a6) 30... Qg6? (30... a6 31. Nc5 { [%cal Gc5a6,Ga5a6] } 31... Qg6 { [%cal Gg6g3,Gg3e1] } 32. Rg1) 31. Qxa7 { [%cal Ge5g7,Ga7g7] } 31... Qxg3?? (31... Rd7 32. Qf2) 32. Rg1 Rxd3 33. cxd3 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { This Opening line requires both good tactical and positional skills. } 1-0


