1. e4 (1. Nf3 { A04 Reti Opening } 1... Nc6 { A04 Zukertort Opening/Black Mustang Defense } 2. e4 f5 { Just a different move order. }) 1... Nc6 { Nimzowitsch Defense } 2. Nf3 { Nimzowitsch Declined. It's called "declined", because the invitation to occupy the center with 2.d4 has been declined for now. Nf3 is the most common move here though, so you have a good chance to get the opportunity to play: } 2... f5 { This is called Lean Variation but most people know it as Colorado Gambit. } { The engine prefers White already, but in practical play this isn't so bad: after exf5, Black has traded the f-pawn for a center pawn and can occupy the center with their own pawns. We will also see that this isn't necessary a gambit. Black will get this pawn back, albeit that isn't the main point of this line. } 3. exf5 { Best move actually. Called Colorado Counter Accepted. Whatever Counter means. } (3. e5 { Push Variation }) (3. d3 { Pawn Chain Variation }) (3. Nc3 { Two Knights Attack }) (3. Bc4? { Italian Variation } 3... fxe4 4. Bxg8 Rxg8 (4... exf3 5. Bd5 fxg2 6. Bxg2 { Racz, Zoltan - Majzik, Levente, 1/2-1/2, HUN-chT2 9495, 2017, https://lichess.org/yTkaWbj6 }) 5. Ng5 d5 $17) (3. Bb5 { Spanish Variation }) 3... d5 { Be as aggressive as possible and go towards the center. } { [%cal Gc8f5] } 4. d4 (4. g4? { Some people try to hold that pawn. Yummy! } 4... h5 5. gxh5 { The only thing you can do with that pawn. } (5. Bb5) (5. g5) (5. h3? hxg4 { White's rook is hanging, they can't take back. } 6. Ng5 Bxf5 7. hxg4 { Trading the rook for the very active bishop is the best move here! } (7. d4) 7... Rxh1 8. gxf5 e5 9. d3 (9. Ne6) (9. fxe6) 9... Qf6 10. Be3 Bc5)) (4. Bb5) (4. Nc3) (4. Nh4) (4. b3) 4... Bxf5 { Black gets their pawn back. And two pieces are already developed. } 5. Bb5 (5. Bd3) (5. h3) (5. Bf4) (5. c3) (5. Be2?!) 5... e6 (5... Qd6) (5... Nf6) 6. Ne5 (6. O-O) (6. h3) (6. Bg5) (6. Bxc6+) 6... Ne7 7. Qh5+ { Main move here. I guess that check looks too tempting. Castling first would be better. } (7. Bg5) (7. Nc3) (7. Ba4) (7. g4) (7. Bf4) 7... g6 (7... Bg6?) 8. Qh4 (8. Qe2 { [%csl Re6][%cal Re2e6] }) 8... Bg7 (8... a6 { Levacic, Patrick - Brumen, Dinko, 1/2-1/2, Zagreb, 2017, https://lichess.org/P8AEykjy }) 9. Bg5 Qd6 10. O-O a6 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 12. Bxc6+ Qxc6 *


