1. e4 Nc6 { Nimzowitsch Defense } 2. Nf3 { Nimzowitsch Declined. It's called "declined", because the invitation to occupy the center with 2.d4 has been declined for now. Nf3 is the most common move here though, so you have a good chance to get the opportunity to play: } 2... f5 { The engine prefers White already, but in practical play this isn't so bad: after exf5, Black has traded the f-pawn for a center pawn and can occupy the center with their own pawns. We will also see that this isn't necessary a gambit. Black will get this pawn back, albeit that isn't the main point of this line. } { This is called Lean Variation but most people know it as Colorado Gambit. } 3. Nc3 { Two Knights Attack. While does develop a piece, it also does cost a tempo. } 3... fxe4 4. Nxe4 d5 { Best move. Just go for the center, and prepare to get the ls-bishop out. } (4... e5) (4... Nf6) 5. Ng3 (5. Nc3?! { Looks nice, but gives away the advantage White had so far. } 5... d4 (5... e5) 6. Ne4 { This knight has moved 4 times already. } 6... Nf6 7. Ng3 { Same situation as 5.Ng3, but Black has one more piece developed, and their pawn is further advanced. } 7... Qd5! { Prophylactic move: Guard e5 or h5, prevent Bb5, and prepare O-O-O. } { [%csl Gh5,Ge5,Bb5][%cal Ge7e5,Gh7h5,Gd5b5,Rf1b5] } 8. Be2 g5 { [%cal Gg5g4] } 9. c4 Qg8) 5... e5 6. Bb5 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nf6 (8... Qd6) (8... Ne7) 9. Nh5 (9. O-O) (9. Bxc6+) (9. Qc3) 9... Kf7 10. Nxf6 gxf6 11. O-O *


