[Event "Slav Defense: Basic position and variations"]
[Date "2017.07.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D45"]
[Opening "Semi-Slav Defense: Normal Variation"]
[StudyName "Slav Defense"]
[ChapterName "Basic position and variations"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4thDzDJA/rrKcVWwS"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.07.06"]
[UTCTime "19:27:52"]

{ The Slav is one of the primary defenses to the Queen's Gambit. Although it was analyzed as early as 1590, it was not until the 1920s that it started to be explored extensively. Many masters of Slavic descent helped develop the theory of this opening, including Alapin, Alekhine, Bogoljubov, and Vidmar. }
1. d4 d5 (1... c6 2. c4 Nf6 { A50 Slav Indian } 3. Nc3 d5 { Transposes to the main line. } (3... g6 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 Bg7)) 2. c4 c6 { D10 Slav Defense. } 3. Nc3 { The pressure on Black's center prevents 3...Bf5? since after 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Qb3 White wins a pawn. Black can try the Winawer Countergambit, 3...e5, which was introduced in Marshall–Winawer, Monte Carlo 1901, but this is thought to be slightly better for White. The most common continuation is 3...Nf6 when 4.Nf3 transposes to the main line. White can also play 4.e3 when it was thought Black could no longer play the "Pure" Slav with 4...Bf5 (and had to choose between 4...e6 or 4...a6) due to 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3. Therefore, "Pure" Slav players sometimes meet 3.Nc3 with 3...dxc4, the Argentinian Defense, which can transpose to the main line of the "Pure" Slav. Recently the Gambit 4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 Nc6 7.Qxb7 Bd7 has revitalized 4...Bf5. } (3. e3 Nf6 (3... Bf5 4. Qb3 (4. Nf3 e6 5. Nc3 Nd7 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3) 4... Qc7 5. Nf3 e6 6. Bd3) 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nf3 { Transposes back into the main line. }) (3. cxd5 { D10 Slav Defense: Exchange Variation } 3... cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 e6 9. Rc1) (3. Nf3 { D11 Slav Defense: Modern Line } 3... e6 (3... dxc4 4. e3 b5 5. a4 Nf6 6. axb5 cxb5 7. b3 e6 8. bxc4 bxc4 9. Bxc4) (3... Bf5? { Mistake! } 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3 Qb6 6. Qxd5 $14) (3... Nf6 4. e3 { D11 Slav Defense: Quiet Variation } (4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 Bf5 7. e3 e6 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O O-O) (4. Nc3 { D15 Slav Defense: Three Knights Variation } 4... dxc4 { D15 Slav Defense: Two Knights Attack } { [%cal Gb7b5] } (4... e6 { Transposition: Semi-Slav Defense }) (4... Bf5? { Not recommended against the Three Knights Variation. } 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 { And now we have a serious problem already. } { [%cal Rb3d5,Rb3b7] } 6... Bc8 { That's actually the best move. We have lost an important tempo. }) 5. a4 { D16 Slav Defense: Alapin Variation. Prevents b5. } { [%csl Rb5] } (5. e4?! b5 6. e5 Nd5 7. a4 e6 8. axb5 Nxc3 9. bxc3 cxb5 $15) (5. Ne5 b5 6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 a6 8. O-O e6 9. b3) 5... Bf5 { D17 Slav Defense: Czech Variation } 6. e3 { D18 Slav Defense: Czech Variation, Classical System, aka Dutch Variation. } { [%cal Rf1c4] } 6... e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] } 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. O-O { D19 Queen's Gambit Declined: Slav, Dutch Variation } 8... Nbd7 9. Qe2 { [%cal Re3e4] } 9... Bg6 { In case of Nh4, Black can now move to Bh5. } 10. e4 { e4 is the target here. } { [%csl Be4][%cal Re2e4,Rc3e4,Gf6e4,Gg6e4] } (10. Nh4 Bh5 11. Nf3 e5 $15) 10... Bxc3 { Remove one defender … } (10... O-O 11. Bd3 Bh5 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qe3 Be7 15. Bd2 Nb8 $10) 11. bxc3 Nxe4 { … and grab the pawn. } 12. Ba3 { Prevents short castling. Black cannot take the c3-pawn, because then b7 will fall and probably a7 too. So b7 has to be protected first. } { [%csl Rf8] } 12... Qc7 { Now c3 is hanging. } (12... Nxc3? 13. Qb2 { [%cal Rb2c3,Rb2b7] } 13... Nd5 14. Qxb7 { Threat is Bxd5 cxd5 Rfe1 Be4 Ng5. } 14... Rb8 15. Qxa7 $14) 13. Rfc1 O-O-O 14. a5 Rhe8) 4... Bf5 { D12 Slav Defense: Quiet Variation, Schallopp Defense } (4... e6 5. Bd3 Nbd7 6. O-O) (4... Bg4 { D11 Slav Defense: Quiet Variation, Pin Defense }) (4... a6 5. Bd3 Bg4 6. Nbd2)) 4. Qc2 Nf6) 3... Nf6 (3... Bf5? { Too early! } 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7,Gb3d5] } 5... Nf6 (5... Qd7? 6. e4 Bxe4 7. Bb5 Nc6 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. d5 e6 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Ba4 $16) (5... Nc6 { Gambit line. Black gives a pawn for faster development. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 6. Qxb7 Bd7 { Threat: 7...Rb8 8.Qa6 Nb4 9.Qxa7 Nc2+ 10.Kd1 Nxa1 } 7. Qb3 Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4c2] } 8. Qd1 { [%cal Rd1d4] } 8... Nb5 9. Nxd5 e6 $10) 6. Qxb7) (3... dxc4 { Argentinian Defense? } 4. e4 { D1 Slav Defense/Slav Gambit/Alekhine Attack } (4. e3 b5 5. a4 b4 6. Ne4 Qd5 7. Nd2 (7. Ng3) 7... c3 8. bxc3 bxc3 9. Nb1 Qa5 10. Qc2 Na6! 11. Qxc3 Nb4 12. Bd2 e6 { [%cal Gf8b4] } 13. Nf3 Nf6) 4... b5 5. a4 b4 6. Na2 (6. Nce2 Nd7 7. Nf3) 6... Nf6) 4. e3 (4. Bg5?! dxc4 5. a4 Qa5 { [%cal Ga5g5] } 6. Bd2 (6. Bxf6? { Mistake. Main move online! } 6... exf6 7. e3) 6... e5! 7. dxe5 Qxe5) (4. Nf3 g6 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Bf4 Bg7 7. e3 O-O) 4... e6 5. Nf3 { D45 Semi-Slav Defense: Main Line } 5... Nbd7 *


