1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { C41 Philidor Defense. This is a rather passive move. It doesn't develop a piece, and it doesn't fight for squares in the center. But it's very solid.
The pawn structure indicates already that our light-square bishop will be important. } { [%cal Gc8g4] } 3. d4 { The most challenging move. White threatens to play d5, which would restrict Black's development, or dxe5 which also leads to very unpleasant positions. So we take that pawn. } { [%cal Rd4d5] } (3. Bc4 { → Chapter 3.Bc4 } 3... f5?! $14 { Lopez Countergambit }) (3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4) 3... exd4 { Exchange Variation } (3... Nf6 { Nimzowitsch Variation #2 } 4. Nc3 (4. dxe5 { Nimzowitsch Variation } 4... Nxe4 5. Qd5 { Nimzowitsch Variation/Rellstab Variation
Best move here. Rarely played online. } (5. Nbd2 { Nimzowitsch Variation/Sokolsky Variation }) (5. exd6?! Bxd6 (5... Nxf2?? { I have seen that in a game when I was playing against the Philidor. } 6. Qe2+! { [%cal Ge2f2,Ge2e8] } 6... Be6 7. dxc7 Bb4+ 8. c3 Qxc7 9. Qxf2 Bc5 10. Bb5+ { Start trading pieces immediately. } 10... Nd7 11. Bxd7+ Bxd7 12. Be3 Be7 13. O-O $16) 6. Bd3 Nc5) 5... Nc5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. exd6) (4. Bc4 { Nimzowitsch Variation/Klein Variation }) 4... Nbd7 { Lion Variation/Larobok Variation } 5. Bc4 Be7 6. Bxf7+ { Lion Variation/Bishop Sacrifice } (6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Bxf7+ { Lion Variation/Delayed Bishop Sacrifice }) (6. Ng5 O-O 7. Bxf7+ Rxf7 8. Ne6 { Lion Variation/Forcing Line }) (6. O-O O-O 7. Qe2 c6 8. a4 exd4 { Lion Variation/Sozin Variation })) (3... f5?! { Philidor Countergambit } 4. Nc3 { Philidor Countergambit/Zukertort Variation }) (3... Bd7?! { Philidor Gambit }) (3... Qe7?! 4. Nc3 c6) (3... Bg4?! 4. dxe5 Nd7 { Alapin-Blackburne Gambit } (4... Bxf3 { Main move online. Not good! } 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Qb3! { [%cal Gb3b7] } 6... b6 7. Bc4 Qd7 8. O-O) 5. exd6 Bxd6 6. Be2 Ngf6) (3... Nd7 { Hanham Variation } 4. Nc3 (4. Bc4 c6 (4... Nb6 { Hanham Variation/Sharp Variation }) 5. c3 { Hanham Variation/Delmar Variation } (5. O-O { Hanham Variation/Krause Variation } 5... Be7 6. dxe5 { Hanham Variation/Steiner Variation }) (5. Nc3 { Hanham Variation/Schlechter Variation })) 4... Ngf6 { Lion Variation } 5. Be2 (5. g4 { Lion Variation/Shirov Gambit }) 5... Be7 6. O-O c6 { Lion Variation/Lion's Claw I } (6... h6 { Lion Variation/Lion's Claw II })) (3... Nc6 4. d5 Nce7) 4. Nxd4 (4. c3 { Bird Gambit } 4... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 5. Qxd4) (4. Qxd4 { The Qxd4 line is rarely played, but we have to learn it, because it can lead to uncomfortable positions sometimes. } 4... Bd7 { Boden Variation }) (4. Bc4 { Morphy Gambit }) 4... Nf6 { Develop and force White to take care of the e4-pawn. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } (4... g6 { Larsen Variation }) (4... Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. O-O Be7) 5. Nc3 { Protect e4. } (5. Qf3!? { [%cal Rc1g5,Gc8g4,Rb1c3,Rd4f5,Gg7g6,Bf8g7] }) 5... Be7 { Prepare castling. This bishop can't move after the castling, so it can easily exchanged for a knight by White later. } (5... g6 { White doesn't attack at the moment, so Black can take the time to fianchetto the bishop. This is rarely played, and it might weaken the d6-pawn, but it's playable. } 6. Be3 { Best move according to the engine. Rare. } (6. Bg5 { Main move according to the database. A bit annoying. } 6... Bg7 7. Qd2 h6 8. Bf4 { Pointing out the weakness of Black's d-pawn. The c-pawn is almost locked. } { [%cal Rf4d6,Gc7d6] } 8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 { Yes, Black has doubled pawns now. But they got the open b-file in return. Still, White's position is a little bit better. })) 6. g3 (6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6 8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3) (6. Bc4 O-O) (6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. f4 { And here comes White's attack. } 8... Bf8 (8... c5 9. Nb3 Nc6 10. Bf3 Bf8) 9. Bf3 c5 10. Nb3 (10. Nde2) 10... Nc6 11. Re1 c4 12. Nd4 d5) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. O-O *


