1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 { This has no name. It's the second most common move online after 3.d4. Be7 and Nf6 are equally good according to the engine. But Nf6 might lead to an uncomfortable situation. } 3... Be7 { It is important to move the bishop first, so Black has an eye on g5. If Black moves the knight first, White might be tempted to try an annoying attack.
On the other hand: If Black knows how to play that, they can "invite" White to go for that attack. } { [%csl Bg5][%cal Ge7g5] } (3... Nf6 4. Ng5 { Now we have to use the same tactic as in the Polerio Defense in the Two Knights Defense. See https://lichess.org/study/9cAiplbq/HB4zT7BY } { [%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] }) 4. Nc3 (4. d4) 4... Nf6 5. d4 (5. d3 { Most common move online. }) (5. O-O O-O (5... Bg4 { [%cal Gg4h5,Gh5g6,Gg6e4] })) 5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. O-O (7. Nxc6 bxc6 { Now we block two important key squares. } { [%csl Bb5,Bd5] }) 7... Nxd4 { We have to eliminate that strong pawn. } 8. Qxd4 O-O 9. Bg5 { Main move online. } (9. Bf4 { Best move according to engine. Now we try to bring our bishop to f6. } 9... Nd7 10. Rad1 Bf6 11. Qd2) *


