[UTCTime "10:37:31"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 { I thought for a long time Be7 is played here instead of Nf6 in order to avoid Ng5. But let's look at Nf6 Ng5 and see what happens. It's good for Black! } 3... Nf6 4. Ng5 { This is not a good line for White. Black can equalize easily now.
Now we have to use the same tactic as in the Polerio Defense in the Two Knights Defense. See https://lichess.org/study/9cAiplbq/HB4zT7BY } { [%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] } 4... d5! { Block the bishop. } 5. exd5 h6 { Don't take back yet, push the knight away first. h6 is of course a long-term weakness, because it gives White an opportunity to sacrifice a bishop there later. } 6. Nf3 { Now we still can't take back, because e5 is hanging. } { [%cal Rf3e5] } 6... e4 { So we push it forward. } 7. Ne5 (7. Nd4 c6 { Attack the pawn with a pawn while White can't take. What could be better? } { [%cal Gd8d4] } 8. d3 cxd5 9. Bb5+) (7. Qe2?!) 7... Bd6 { I prefer this line over Qe7. It's slightly less messy. } (7... Qe7 { This gets a bit messy. But if you know the line, it's playable. } 8. d4 exd3 9. f4 Ng4 { [%cal Gg4e5,Ge7e5] } 10. Bxd3 f6 (10... Nxe5 11. fxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Qe2 Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 Bd6 $10 { Completely equal. }) 11. h3 fxe5 12. hxg4 exf4+ 13. Qe2 { Note that the material is equal, and the engine also thinks the position is equal.
Black has few options now, but none of them change the evaluation. } 13... Bxg4 { Probably the best continuation. } (13... g5 { This means we will castle long — or not at all. And we give the rook on h8 for a bishop. } 14. Bd2 (14. Bg6+ Kd8 15. Qxe7+ Bxe7) 14... Bxg4 15. Qxe7+ Kxe7 { The black squared bishop wants to go to g7. } { [%cal Gf8g7] } 16. Bc3 Rg8 17. Bh7 Rg7 { Weird position, the engine analysis is rather confusing. } 18. Bxg7 Bxg7) (13... Qxe2+ { The least messy line. } 14. Bxe2 Bd6 $10 { [%cal Gd6f4] } (14... g5)) 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 15. Bxf4 $10 { This is rather unpleasant for Black, but technically equal. } { [%cal Rf4c7] }) (7... Nxd5? { Does NOT work! } 8. Nxf7 Kxf7 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qxd5+ Qxd5 11. Bxd5+ $16 { And here White is not only a pawn up, Black's pawn structure and kingside is also messed up. }) 8. d4 Nbd7 (8... exd3 9. Nxd3 O-O 10. O-O) 9. Bb5 (9. Bf4) (9. Nxd7) (9. f4) 9... O-O 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 11. Bxd7 Qxd7 { Connect the rooks. Black is now completely developed! In contrast to White. } { [%cal Ga8f8,Gf6d5] } 12. c4 b5 $10 *


