1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3 5. dxc3 (5. bxc3?! { This is bad for the same reasons as bxc6 is bad in the Ruy Lopz/Exchange: White has now an isolated a-pawn, it's difficult to develop the dark-squared bishop to a good square. And once Black plays b6, the bishop has no use on a3, and the same is true for the rook on the semi-open b-file. } { [%csl Ba2,Bc1][%cal Gb7b6,Ra1b1,Rb1b6] } 5... d5 { Black is not a hurry to play b6. Development in the center has priority. } 6. exd6 (6. d4 c4 { grabs more space and shuts down the entire queenside. } (6... Nc6 { is the main move. } 7. Be2 Bg4 8. Rb1 Qc7 9. O-O e6) 7. g3 (7. Be2?! e6 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gf8a3,Rc1a3] } 8. O-O Qa5)) 6... e6! 7. d4 Bxd6 8. Bd3 Qc7 $10) 5... Nc6 (5... Qc7) (5... e6) (5... d5) 6. Bf4 (6. Bc4) 6... e6 (6... h6) (6... d5) (6... Qb6) (6... Qc7) 7. Qe2 (7. Bg3) (7. Qd2 Qc7 (7... h6) (7... b6) 8. O-O-O (8. h4) (8. Be2) 8... a6 (8... b6) (8... h6)) (7. Bc4) (7. Bd3) (7. Bb5) *


