1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 { C61 Ruy Lopez: Bird Variation. The basic problem here is that Black moves a piece twice during development. White should just take it. } 4. Nxd4 { This is the only move I recommend. } 4... exd4 5. O-O { Note how much ahead White is already in development: 1, piece out, one pawn in the center, castled king, and the rook is ready to go to e1. Black has just one pawn out, and even that is a doubled pawn. Their kingside isn't so easy to develop in the view of e4-e5, and the d-pawn is in an absolute pin for now. } { [%csl Ge4,Gb5,Gg1,Rd4,Bd7,Bf6][%cal Gf1e1,Ge4e5,Bg8f6,Ge5f6,Gb5e8] } (5. Bc4 Nf6 6. O-O Nxe4 (6... d6) (6... d5 7. exd5 Be7 8. Qf3 Bg4 9. Qf4 O-O 10. h3 Bd6 11. Qxd4 { Saric, Iv - Carlsen, M., 1-0, 41st Olympiad Open 2014, https://lichess.org/vRm7GQXd }) 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qd5+ Kg7 10. Qxe4 Qf6 11. d3) (5. d3 c6 6. Bc4 (6. Ba4 Nf6) 6... d5) 5... Bc5 (5... Ne7 { Paulsen Variation }) (5... c6 6. Bc4 Nf6 7. Re1 d6 8. c3 Ng4 { [%cal Rd8h4] } 9. h3 Ne5 10. d3 dxc3 (10... Nxc4 11. dxc4 dxc3 12. Nxc3 Be7 13. Bf4 O-O) 11. Nxc3 Qh4) (5... g6 6. d3 Bg7 7. c3 (7. f4)) 6. d3 c6 7. Ba4 (7. Bc4 d5 8. exd5 (8. Bb3 Ne7 9. f4!)) *


