1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 { A80 Dutch Defense/Hopton Attack
This is actually the best move here. It points out the weakness Black has created in their own position and prevents the development of the e-pawn.
The origin of this line is a game between R Hopton and F Eastwood in 1860: https://lichess.org/FSAQsgOx } 2... h6 (2... g6 3. Nc3 { A setup similar to the Veresov Attack https://lichess.org/study/WHwhHyO8 that allows an early e4. } 3... Bg7 4. e4 fxe4 5. Nxe4 (5. f3 Nc6 6. d5 Ne5 7. fxe4 Nh6 8. Nf3 Nhf7 9. Bf4) 5... d5 { Most people play Nc5 here, but I don't see the point. Black can attack that knight easily with b5, develop their own bishop with a tempo and prevent White's fast development. Nc3 keeps the knight on the queen side as a protector, Ng3 helps with a king side attack. } 6. Nc3 (6. Ng3) (6. Nc5?! b6 7. Nb3 Nf6 { Black has equalized already. } 8. Bb5+ { Provoke Black to open the queen side as well, so the king won't have a safe place ever. } (8. Nf3) 8... c6 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 { Guliev, Sarhan - Glek, Igor V, 1-0, Stare Mesto, 2017, https://lichess.org/b2jErPng }) 9... O-O $10) 6... Nc6 { [%cal Rc6d4,Rg7d4] } 7. Bb5 Nh6 8. Qe2 (8. Nf3) 8... Nf7) (2... Nf6 3. Bxf6 { Ruin Black's pawn structure … } 3... exf6 4. e3 { … then go on developing the pieces. } (4. c4 d5) 4... d5 5. c4 Be6 (5... Bb4+) (5... c6) 6. Nc3 dxc4 7. d5 Bf7 (7... Bd7) 8. Bxc4) 3. Bh4 (3. Bd2 { This seems to be too passive. } 3... Nf6 4. e3 { Main move? Even more passive; White's bs-bishop can't move much anymore. } (4. Nf3) (4. c4) 4... e6 (4... d6)) (3. Bf4) 3... g5 4. e3! { Black can't take the bishop now. That would be mate in 1.
Bg7 and Nf6 are the only good moves to eliminate White's mate threat. } (4. e4 { [%cal Rd1h5,Rh5e8] } 4... Nf6 (4... Bg7) (4... Rh7) 5. e5 e6 6. exf6 (6. Bg3) 6... Qxf6 7. Bg3 f4 8. Bxf4 (8. Qh5+) (8. Nc3) 8... Qxf4) (4. Bg3 { Not the best move, but it invites Black to run into a nice trap: } 4... f4? 5. e3 { Threatens mate with Qh5# } { [%cal Rd1h5] } 5... h5 6. Bd3 Rh6?? 7. Qxh5+ Rxh5 8. Bg6# { Teed, Frank Melville - Delmar, Eugene, 1-0, New York 1896 }) 4... Bg7 (4... gxh4?? 5. Qh5#) (4... Nf6 5. Bg3 d6 6. h4 g4 7. h5) 5. Bg3 { White can insert a check as a zwischenzug here, but I don't see an advantage in that. } (5. Qh5+ Kf8 6. Bg3 { The queen is slightly misplaced now. Getting it back loses a tempo, and the engine thinks Black has equalized already. }) 5... c5 (5... d6) (5... Nf6) 6. c3 Qb6 { [%cal Rb6d4,Rg7d4] } 7. Nf3 (7. Na3!? cxd4 8. Nb5! { Now the queen can't help on d4, because of Nc7+. And there is no check with Qb4 possible after the exchange. } { [%csl Bc7][%cal Gb5c7,Bc7a8,Bc7e8,Gb5d4,Gb5c3] } 8... Na6 9. cxd4) *


