1. d4 f5 2. e4 { A82 Staunton Gambit, named after Howard Staunton, who introduced it in his match against Bernhard Horwitz. See the game [Staunton Horwitz] and the Game Collection [Staunton Gambit, Romantic Era]
An excellent resource on this line is Roeland Pruijssers' video on 2.e4 in his series on the Dutch: https://chess24.com/en/learn/advanced/video/the-dutch/2-e4 } 2... fxe4 (2... d6 { Balogh Defense }) (2... e6?! 3. exf5 exf5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 d6 6. O-O $16) 3. Nc3 { Accepted } (3. Nd2 { American Attack }) (3. Bg5) (3. f3) 3... Nf6 4. Bg5 { A83 Staunton Gambit/General Variation. I have no idea why there are two different ECO numbers with the same name. } (4. g4 { Tartakower Variation }) (4. f3 { Blackmar's Second Gambit }) 4... g6 (4... Nc6 5. d5 Ne5 6. Qd4 (6. Qe2! { Line recommended by Roeland Pruijssers. } { [%cal Gc3e4,Ge2e4] } 6... Nf7 { [%cal Rf7g5] } 7. Bxf6 exf6 8. Nxe4 Be7 9. d6! cxd6 10. O-O-O $10 O-O 11. Nc3) (6. f4) 6... Nf7 7. Bxf6 (7. Nh3) (7. h4) 7... exf6 (7... gxf6?!) 8. Nxe4 (8. Qxe4+) (8. O-O-O)) (4... c6 { Chigorin Variation }) 5. f3?! { Black should not take the pawn! } (5. Bxf6?! { See Pruijssers } 5... exf6 6. Nxe4 d5 7. Ng3 Bd6 8. Bd3 Nc6 { [%cal Rc6d4] } 9. c3 (9. Qe2+ Kf7 $17) 9... Qe7+ 10. N3e2 (10. N1e2?! f5 { [%cal Rf5f4] }) 10... Bd7 11. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3d5] } 11... Qf7 12. Nf3 (12. Qxb7? Rb8 $17) 12... O-O-O 13. Nd2 Rhe8 $15) (5. h4 { See Pruijssers } 5... d5 6. h5 Bf5 7. Bxf6 exf6 8. g4 Be6 9. hxg6 { h7 is pinned } 9... Qd7 10. g5 fxg5 11. Qh5 Qg7 12. Qxg5 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gg5d5] } 12... c6 13. f3 hxg6 14. Rxh8 Qxh8 15. fxe4 Be7 { [%cal Re7g5] } 16. Qxg6+ Bf7 17. Qf5 Bh4+ 18. Kd2 Qxd4+ 19. Bd3 Qf6 $10) 5... d5 (5... exf3?! 6. Nxf3 Bg7 7. Bd3 (7. Bc4 { [%csl Gg8,Be8][%cal Gc4g8] })) 6. Bxf6 (6. fxe4?! Nxe4 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Bc4 Nc6 { [%cal Rc6d4,Rd8d4,Gd1d4] } 9. Ne2 { [%cal Ge2d4] } 9... Na5 10. Bb3 Nxb3 11. axb3 $15) 6... exf6 7. fxe4 dxe4 8. Nxe4 { And now White got the pawn back. } *


