lack resigns. } 1-0


[Event "Morphy - Harrwitz"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1858.09.09"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Daniel Harrwitz"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "J. Lowenthal"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A84"]
[Opening "Dutch Defense: Rubinstein Variation"]
[StudyName "Dutch Defense: 1.d4 f5"]
[ChapterName "Harrwitz - Morphy, 1858 [Rubinstein] 0-1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hqK4ih1U/VOSFfZic"]

1. d4 { Notes by J. Lowenthal } 1... f5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 { A84 Dutch Defense: Rubinstein Variation } 3... Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 5. Qb3 c5 { A very similar position occurs in the Sicilian opening, and then, as here, this move is important and effective. } 6. d5 e5 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 d6 9. Ne2 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 Qg6 13. O-O Nd7 14. b4 b6 15. f3 h5 { A measure of precaution, to prevent White from playing g4, and having in view also the advance h4 if he should play Ng3. } 16. Bc2 Bb7 17. Ba4 Qf7 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. bxc5 { The exchange of Pawns here showed want of judgment for after giving up his Bishop, the c-pawn was, of course, rendered very weak by the line of play adopted; indeed, it was fatal to his game. } 19... bxc5 20. f4 e4 21. Rab1 Ba6 22. Rfc1 (22. Qc2 Qc7) 22... Qa4 { The prompt advantage which Mr. Morphy takes of the slightest error of his opponent, is the chief characteristic of his game, and it is well
illustrated on this occasion. } 23. Ng3 h4 24. Nf1 Rab8 25. Nd2 Rb6 { Very well played; for if as was the case, the Rooks be exchanged, the b-pawn is soon thrown up and a free passage secured for the c-pawn, and if the exchange be not made, Black
doubles his Rooks on the b-file, with a far superior game. } 26. Rxb6?! (26. Kf2 Rfb8 27. Rxb6 axb6 28. Rg1 Qa5 29. Qb2 Qa4 30. g4 hxg3+ 31. Rxg3 Rb7 32. Qf6 Qd1 $10) 26... axb6 27. Qb3?! (27. Kf2 { Fuxia: Engine suggestion. I don't see how this is better. } 27... b5 28. Rg1 bxc4 29. g4 hxg3+ 30. Rxg3 Qd7 31. Rg6 Qe7 32. a4 Rb8 33. a5 Rb4 $17) 27... Qxb3 28. Nxb3 b5 { Excellently followed up, the c-pawn can now march on unimpeded, and embarrass White sorely. } 29. cxb5 Bxb5 30. Na5?! (30. Nd2 Ra8 31. Ra1 Kf7 32. Rb1 Bd3 33. Rb3 Kf6 34. Kf2 Ra6 35. Ke1 Ra5 36. h3 c4) 30... Ra8 31. Nb7 Ra6 32. Rc3?! { This is
an interesting position } (32. a4 Bd3 33. Kf2 Kf8 34. g3 Ke7 35. gxh4 Rxa4 36. Rg1 Ra2+ 37. Kg3 Bc4 38. Kh3 Bxd5) 32... Kf8 33. Nd8 Bd7 34. Rb3 Ke7 35. Rb8?! (35. Nc6+ Bxc6) 35... c4 { The skilful manner in which Mr. Morphy terminated the game commands our praise and is deserving of close attention. } 36. Kf2? (36. Nc6+ Bxc6) 36... c3 37. Ke2 Rxa3 38. Nc6+ Bxc6 39. dxc6 c2 40. Kd2 Rc3 { When Mr. Harrwitz played 38 Nc6+, he evidently overlooked that his opponent, on his 40th move, could play as in the text. } 41. Kc1 Rxc6 42. Rb3?! (42. Rg8) 42... Kf6 43. Ra3?! (43. Rb2 Rc3 44. Rxc2 Rxe3 45. Kd2 Rb3 46. Ke2 d5 47. Rc6+ Ke7 48. Rc2 Ke6 49. Rc6+ Kd7) 43... g5 44. g3? (44. fxg5+ Kxg5) 44... hxg3 45. hxg3 gxf4 46. gxf4 Kg6 47. Ra5 Rc5?! (47... Rc3 48. Rd5 Rd3 49. Ra5 Rxe3 50. Kxc2 Kf6 51. Kd2 Rd3+ 52. Ke2 Rf3 53. Ra8 Rxf4 54. Re8) 48. Ra6?! (48. Ra8 Rc3) 48... Rc3 49. Rxd6+?? (49. Ra8 Rxe3 50. Kxc2 Kf7 51. Rd8 Ke7 52. Rh8 Rf3 53. Kd2 Rxf4 54. Rh3 Ke6 55. Ke3 Ke5) 49... Kh5 50. Rd2 Kg4 51. Rg2+ Kf3 52. Rg5? (52. Rh2 Rxe3) 52... Rc5 53. Rh5 Kxe3 54. Rh4 Kf3 { White resigns. } 0-1


