{ In this chapter you can find all named lines, many transpositions, and the most played lines even if they don't have a name. Plans, ideas and so on are explained in the individual chapters. }
1. c4 { A10 English Opening } 1... Nf6 { A15 Anglo-Indian Defense. The point here is that you can transpose to your preferred 1.d4 opening if White is playing that. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } 2. Nc3 { Queen's Knight Variation } (2. Nf3 { King's Knight Variation } 2... g6 { King's Indian Formation } (2... e6 3. g3 a6 { Romanishin Variation } (3... b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 { Queen's Indian Formation }) 4. Bg2 b5 { Romanishin Gambit }) (2... d5 { Scandinavian Defense. Note that this is still in the Anglo-Indian Defense, not a transposition. :) } 3. cxd5 Nxd5 { Scandavian Defense/Exchange Variation }) (2... d6 { Old Indian Formation }) (2... b6 { Queen's Indian Formation }) 3. Nc3 (3. g3 c6 { Slav Formation } (3... d5 { Grünfeld Formation }) (3... b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 { King's Indian Formation/Double Fianchetto }) 4. Bg2 (4. b3 Bg7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Bg2 d5 7. O-O) 4... Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 (6. Nc3 d5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. d4 Ne4 (8... Nc6 9. Ne5 e6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Na4 Nd7) (8... e6 9. Ne5 (9. Bf4 Nc6 10. Rc1 (10. Ne5 Nxe5 (10... Bd7 11. Qd2 (11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Be5) 11... Nxe5 (11... Nh5)) 11. Bxe5 Bd7 12. Qb3 (12. Qd2)) 10... Bd7 11. Bd6 Re8 12. Ne5) 9... Nfd7 10. f4 (10. Nf3 Nc6 (10... Nf6 11. Ne5 Nfd7 12. f4 (12. Nf3 Nc6)) 11. Bf4 Nf6 (11... Qb6 12. Na4 Qa6)) (10. Nxd7 Bxd7) 10... Nc6 11. Be3 Nb6 12. Bf2) 9. Ne5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qa4 Qb6 13. Ba3 Qa6 14. Qxa6 Bxa6 15. Rfe1 (15. Rfb1)) (6. b3 Ne4 7. d4 d5 8. Bb2) 6... d5 { D78 Neo-Grünfeld Defense: Classical Variation, Original Defense }) 3... Bg7 4. e4 { Anti-Anti-Grünfeld } (4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O e5 7. d3 Nc6 8. Rb1 a5 9. a3) 4... d6 5. d4 { E90 King's Indian Defense: Normal Variation, Rare Defenses }) (2. e4 { Achilles-Omega Gambit } 2... Nxe4 3. d4) (2. d4 { And here you can go for the Nimzo-Indian, Queen's Indian … whatever you want. In this study we are looking at the other lines. }) 2... g6 (2... e6 { Hedgehog System } 3. e4 { Flohr-Mikenas-Carls Variation } (3. Nf3 b6 { Queen's Indian Formation. Yes, there are multiple lines with that name. ECO names *are* weird. } (3... Bb4 { Nimzo-English Opening } 4. g4 { Zviagintsev-Krasenkov Attack } { [%cal Gh1g1,Gg1g7] } 4... O-O 5. g5 { Krasenkow, Michal - Romanishin, Oleg M, 1-0, Leonid Stein Memorial, 2000, https://lichess.org/14UVwFKY }) 4. e4 Bb7 5. Bd3 { Queen's Indian Variation. Note it's a "Variation" now, not a "Formation". Doesn't really matter.
The point of all these queenside fianchettos by Black is the same: Put pressure on e4 and later on g2 with that light-squared bishop and the help of d7-d5 and/or f7-f5. } { [%csl Rf5,Be4,Bg2][%cal Rb7e4,Rf7f5,Rf5e4,Re4g2] }) 3... c5 { Flohr-Mikenas-Carls Variation/Sicilian? Chesstempo and Lichess have different opinions about the name. } (3... d5 4. e5 d4 5. exf6 dxc3 6. bxc3 (6. fxg7 cxd2+ 7. Bxd2 Bxg7) 6... Qxf6 7. Nf3) (3... Nc6) 4. e5 Ng8 { Flohr-Mikenas-Carls Variation/Nei Gambit }) (2... e5 { Transposes to A22 English Opening: King's English Variation, Two Knights Variation, basically a reversed Sicilian } 3. Nf3 Nc6) (2... d5 { Golombek Defense (Chesstempo) or Anglo-Grünfeld Defense (Lichess) } 3. cxd5 (3. d4) 3... Nxd5 4. g3 (4. Nf3 { Anglo-Grünfeld Variation #3 }) 4... g6 5. Bg2 Nb6 { Anglo-Grünfeld Variation #1 } (5... Nxc3 { Anglo-Grünfeld Variation #2 } 6. bxc3 Bg7)) (2... c5 3. Nf3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 { Transposition: A30 English Opening: Symmetrical Variation, Hedgehog Defense } 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4) 3. Nf3 (3. e4 d6 4. d4 Bg7 { Transposition: King's Indian Defense/Normal Variation }) 3... Bg7 4. e4 { Anti-Anti-Grünfeld } 4... d6 5. d4 { E90 King's Indian Defense: Normal Variation, Rare Defenses } *


