1. d4 d5 (1... Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 { Alternative route to this position. }) 2. Nc3 { D00 Queen's Pawn Game/Veresov Attack named after the Soviet chess player Gavriil Veresov, also known as Chigorin Variation. Transpositions to the Caro-Kann, Nimzowitsch and French Defenses are possible and quite common. I will ignore those in this study. } 2... Nf6 (2... f5 $14 { A80 Dutch System } 3. Bf4) (2... e5 $14 { D00 Shaviliuk Gambit } 3. dxe5) (2... h5 $14 { D00 Shropshire Defense } 3. Bg5) (2... Bg4 $14 { D00 Anti-Veresov } 3. f3) (2... c5 $10 { D00 Irish Gambit } 3. e4 dxe4 4. d5) (2... Bf5 $10 { D00 Alburt Defense } 3. f3) (2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 $10 { D00 Fianchetto Defense }) (2... Nc6 3. e4 { Transposition: B00 Nimzowitsch Defense/Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubov Variation }) (2... c6 3. e4 { Transposition: B15 Caro-Kann Defense } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4) (2... e6 3. e4 { Transposition: C10 French Defense Paulsen Variation }) 3. Bg5 { D01 Richter-Veresov Attack, named after Veresov and the German GM Kurt Richter. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richter-Veresov_Attack } (3. f3 $15 { D00 Richter Attack }) (3. Bf4 e6 4. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5c7,Gf4c7] } 4... Na6 5. e3 c6 6. Nc3 $10) 3... Nbd7 (3... e6 4. Nf3 $10 { D01 Classical Defense } (4. e4 $10 { Transposition: C11 French Defense/Burn Variation })) (3... Ne4 $14 { D01 Boyce Defense }) (3... Bf5 4. Bxf6 $10 { D01 Veresov Variation } (4. f3 $10 { D01 Richter Variation })) 4. Nf3 { D01 Two Knights System } 4... g6 $10 { D01 Two Knights System/Gruenfeld Defense. The actual "main line" in this opening. } (4... e6 5. a3 Be7 $10) (4... h6 5. Bf4 a6 $10 (5... c6)) (4... c6 5. e3 h6 $10) *


