1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 { The idea is to delay capturing the d5 pawn for another move, avoiding the loss of time that Black incurs in the ...Qxd5 lines after 3.Nc3. } 3. d4 { Modern Variation } (3. c4 { allows a little Gambit: } 3... e6 (3... c6 4. Nc3 cxd5 5. d4 e6 6. Nf3 Be7 7. a3 O-O) 4. dxe6 Bxe6 { Black is now ahead in development. } 5. d4) (3. Bb5+ Nbd7 4. Nc3 a6) 3... Nxd5 (3... Qxd5 { Rare alternative. }) (3... Bg4!? { Portuguese Variation. Black gives up the d-pawn in order to achieve rapid development and piece activity; the resulting play is often similar to the Icelandic Gambit. } 4. f3 Bf5 5. Bb5+ Nbd7 6. c4) 4. c4 Nb6 (4... Nf6 { Marshall Retreat Variation, preferred by Tartakower. }) (4... Nb4?! { Kiel Variation. Black is hoping for 5.Qa4+ N8c6 6.d5? b5! with a good game. However, White gets a large advantage here. } 5. a3 (5. Qa4+ N8c6 6. a3) 5... N4c6 6. d5 Ne5 7. Nf3 (7. f4 Ng6 8. Bd3 e5 9. Qe2)) 5. Nf3 g6 6. a4 N6d7 { Prepare c5 for a double attack on d4. Downside is a hindered development. } 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Bf4 O-O 9. Be2 *


