1. e4 d5 2. e5 { Instead of an open, tactical game, White goes for a rather closed position. } 2... c5 { Prevent d4 that could support e5. } (2... e6 3. c3 (3. d4 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Na3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bd7) 3... c5) (2... Bf5 3. d4 e6 4. c3 c5 { Now we have Caro-Kann like position. } 5. Nf3 Nd7 6. Be3 Ne7) (2... d4 3. Nf3 c5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. O-O e6 6. Na3 Bd7) 3. c3 (3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nh6 5. Nc3 a6) (3. Nf3 a6 4. c3 Bg4) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4) 3... Nc6 (3... Bf5 4. Bb5+ Nd7 5. d4 e6 6. Nf3 a6 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Rc8 9. Na3 Ne7 10. h3 Ng6 $15) 4. d4 { This can also arise from a Sicilian/Alapin. See: } { Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar - Gashimov, Sarkhan, 1/2-1/2, Dubai op 5th, 2003, https://lichess.org/ks6cNLgN } 4... cxd4 5. cxd4 Bf5 6. Bb5 (6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 (7... Qb6 8. Nf3 Rc8 { [%cal Rc8c1] } (8... e6 { Reizniece, Dana - Zimina, Olga, 1-0, Wch U20 Girls, 2001, https://lichess.org/uc6a7h3C }) (8... Qa6? { Mistake. } 9. Qxa6 bxa6 { Tindall, Brett - Wallace, John Paul, 0-1, Sydney QVB Masters, 1999, https://lichess.org/gXeoZEWC })) 8. Nf3 { Agdestein, Simen - Wang, Yue, 1/2-1/2, Amsterdam NH Hotels 3rd, 2008, https://lichess.org/9nzxixPn }) *


