1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ng4 4. Bf4 { Rubinstein Variation. The main line. This is very likely White's best response. } 4... Nc6 { The best move in terms of practical play. } (4... g5?! { Mamedyarov's pet move. This leads to all sorts of complications, mostly for Black! } 5. Bg3 Nc6 (5... Bg7 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. h4 { Same as in the 7.h4 line above. } (7. Nc3 Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5) (7. e3 Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5)) 6. Nf3 Bg7 { And now Black will get the pawn back. } 7. h4 { Interesting counter attack. That pawn has only one defender currently. } { [%cal Rh4g5,Rf3g5,Gd8g5] } 7... h6 { White's best option here is simply development. } (7... Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 { Nc3, Qc2, and e3 are the best options for White. See the follow-up for 7...h6. } 9. Nc3 g4 10. e3 d6 11. Be2 Be6 12. Rc1 O-O 13. b3 c6 14. h5 f5 15. h6 Bf6 16. Qd2 Qe7 17. f4?! gxf3 18. gxf3 Kh8 19. f4 Rad8 20. Qc2 Ng4 21. Bxg4 Rg8 22. Ne2?! (22. Bf3 Rxg3 23. Kf2) 22... Rxg4 23. Kf2 d5 24. Rcd1 Re8 25. c5 Bf7 26. Qc1? (26. Qd2 Qxc5 27. Nd4 Re4) 26... Qe4 27. Nd4?? { Wojtaszek, R. - Jobava, Ba, 0-1, Tata Steel Challengers, 2014, https://lichess.org/w9NNfBQa } (27. Rh2)) 8. e3 (8. Nc3 Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 $16) (8. Qc2 Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 $16) (8. hxg5 hxg5 9. Rxh8+ Bxh8 { And now the same as in the previous three lines. }) 8... Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 $16) (4... Bb4+ 5. Nd2 (5. Nc3 Nc6 (5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 7. Nf3 Qe7 8. Qd5 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6) 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qe7 8. Qd5 f6 { An important move! Black doesn't get the pawn back, but it will get a better structure. } (8... Qa3?! { [%cal Ga3c3] } 9. Rc1 f6 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Qd2 { [%cal Rf4c7] } 11... d6 (11... O-O 12. Bxc7 Ne4 13. Qd5+ Kh8 14. Rc2 (14. Qxe4?? Qxc1#) 14... Qa4 15. Rb2 Qa3 16. Rc2 Qa4 { Draw by move repetition. }) 12. Qe3+ Ne7) 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Qd3 d6 11. g3 O-O 12. Bg2 Bg4 13. O-O Rae8 $10) 5... d6!? { Instead of trying to get the pawn back, Black goes for faster development. This is actually the best and most common move in this position. } (5... Nc6 { Looks to me like a more solid approach than d6. } 6. Nf3 Qe7 7. e3 (7. a3 Ngxe5!? 8. Nxe5 (8. axb4?? Nd3#) 8... Nxe5 { [%cal Ge5d3] } 9. e3 $10 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 d6 $10 { Adhiban, Baskaran - Ponkratov, P., 0-1, World Blitz 2015, https://lichess.org/BZKcN3EE }) 7... Ngxe5 8. Be2 (8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O d6 11. Nb3 b6 { Karpov, Anatoly - Short, Nigel D, 1-0, Candidates sf1, 2016, https://lichess.org/F0kQ6KIG }) 8... Nxf3+ 9. Bxf3 Ne5 10. Be2 O-O $14) 6. exd6 { Almost everyone plays Qf6 here. The engine says Bxd6 is better … } 6... Qf6 { A real multi-purpose move! That's why it's so attractive. } { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gf6f4,Gf6d6,Gg4f2,Gf6b2] } (6... Bxd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 { [%cal Gg4h2,Gd6h2] } 8. Qb3 O-O (8... Nxh2? { This knight will fall. } 9. c5 Qe5 10. Nc4 Qh5 11. g4 Qh4 12. Bg2 { [%cal Rg2b7,Rb3b7] } 12... Nc6 13. Ne3 $16) 9. Ngf3 Nd7 10. e3 b6 $14) 7. e3 { [%cal Rd1g4,Gf6b2] } 7... Qxb2 8. Nf3 Bxd6 (8... cxd6? { Not a good idea. White gets a nice initiative now. } 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. Nd4! { [%csl Bb5][%cal Rd4b5,Bb5a3,Bb5d6,Bd6c8] } (10. Rb3 { Weaker than Nd4. } 10... Qa5 11. a3 Bc5 $16) 10... Qa5 11. Rxb4! Qxb4 12. Nb5 { Black can only try to run away now. } { [%csl Bd6,Bc7][%cal Rb5d6,Rf4d6,Bd6c8,Bd6b4,Rb5c7,Bc7e8,Bc7a8] } 12... O-O (12... Ne5? 13. Nc7+ $18 { [%cal Rc7e8,Rc7a8] }) 13. Bxd6 $16 { [%cal Rd6b4,Rd6f8] }) 9. Bxd6 cxd6 $14 { Now Black plays with an IQP. Best moves for White are: Ne4, Be2, and Nd4 in that order. } 10. Ne4 { Qb4+ is in the air, so White won't take that pawn immediately. } { [%cal Ge4d6] } (10. Be2 { No discovered attack on the knight, White's queen has to protect the rook on a1. } { [%cal Gc8g4] } 10... Nf6 $14 (10... O-O { Balazs, Gabor1 - Fodor, Tamas Jr, 1/2-1/2, Paks op, 2008, https://lichess.org/6F9k5C6J })) (10. Nd4 Nc6 $14 { Gunina, Valentina - Turova, Irina, 1-0, RUS-ch (Women) 58th, 2008, https://lichess.org/FPQLTgjn }) 10... O-O $14) 5. Nf3 (5. e3 { Just give up the pawn on e5, and develop instead. This leads to a quiet, equal game. } 5... Ngxe5 6. Be2 (6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Rc1 O-O $10) 6... g6 $10) (5. Nc3 Ngxe5 6. e3 Bb4 7. Rc1 O-O $10) 5... Bb4+ (5... Bc5?! { Doesn't lead anywhere. } { [%cal Gg4f2,Gc5f2] } 6. e3 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 (7. Nc3) 7... Qe7 8. a3 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Ngxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. c5 O-O $14) 6. Nbd2 (6. Nc3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qe7 8. Qd5 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Qd3 d6 11. g3 Bg4 (11... O-O) (11... Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Bg5 Be6 (13... O-O) (13... c6) 14. Bg2 c6 15. Rb1 (15. Bxf6) (15. O-O))) 6... Qe7 7. e3 (7. a3 { This move forces Black to go into the exchange. Well, almost. Bc5 and Bxd2 are also possible, but not as good as the exchange. } 7... Ngxe5 (7... Bc5) (7... Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Ngxe5 (8... O-O 9. c5 Ncxe5 (9... Qxc5?! 10. e3 Re8 11. b4 Qe7 12. Qc3) 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. e3) 9. Nxe5 Nxe5) 8. Nxe5 (8. axb4 { The Kieninger Trap! } 8... Nd3#) 8... Nxe5 9. e3 (9. axb4 Nd3# { Still: The Kieninger Trap! })) 7... Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Bxd2 { Now the knight isn't pinned anymore, and there isn't a good retreat square for Black dark-squared bishop. That's why most players play Bxd2 here. The downside is that White has now the bishop pair. } (10... Ng6 { Sets up a little trap. And even if White doesn't fall for it, Black can avoid giving White the bishop pair. } { [%cal Gg6f4] } 11. Bg3 (11. Bxc7? d6! $17 { … and the bishop is lost. } { [%csl Ga5,Gb6][%cal Ge7c7,Gb4a5,Ga7b6] }) 11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. c5 d6 15. cxd6 Qxd6 16. Rfd1 Qe7 $14 { This is about equal. But as always in almost symmetrical positions: the side with the extra tempo is slightly better. }) (10... d6 11. Nb3 b6 12. a3 Bc5 13. Nxc5 bxc5 14. b4 Nd7 15. Bg4 Re8 $14 { With the bishop pair and the better pawn structure, White might try to exchange heavy pieces and go into a better endgame. }) 11. Qxd2 d6 12. b4 { Grabbing some space. } 12... Rd8 (12... Re8) 13. Qc3 a5 14. a3 Bg4 15. f3 Be6 $14 *


