1. Nc3 d5 2. e4 { This has no name, but it is a position that could arise from a Scandinavian Defense — 1.e4 d5 2.Nc3 — if White is very adventurous. This is good for Black: In contrast to the regular Scandinavian, Black doesn't have to move the queen early, and d4 comes with a tempo. } 2... d4 3. Nce2 (3. Nb1 { This looks very odd, but it has been played, and White is not yet significantly worse. } 3... e5 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d3 Bd6 6. c3 c5 $15 { Black is ahead in development and space. These are still dynamic advantages, meaning: they will fade away after a while, so Black should try to make use of them with aggressive play. }) 3... e5 { White has a choice here. The main move is Ng3; the other opetion will very likely step out of Black's common knowledge. } 4. Ng3 { The main idea here is to clear e2, so the light-squared bishop can be developed. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } (4. Nf3) (4. c3) (4. d3) (4. f4) 4... Be6! { A very important move! Black should not allow White to play Bc4, because that bishop will be very annoying and difficult to remove. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ge6c4] } 5. Nf3 { Main move. Attacks e5. Nc6 isn't a good defense, because it gives White Bb5, pinning that knight. Nd7 blocks the queen's view. Not so terrible, but it's something you rather don't do with advanced pawns. } { [%cal Gf3e5] } (5. c3 { Challenge Black's center immediately. Note that d4-d3 isn't possible anymore, because the bishop is watching this square now. } { [%csl Bd3][%cal Bf1d3] }) 5... f6 { Is the best move here. This looks odd, but as long as White doesn't have Qh5+ before Black has castled, it's okay. } 6. Bb5+ { Provoking Black to play c6. The idea is that after f6, Black would probably rather castle long. But once c6 has been played, the queenside isn't so safe anymore either. This is a motif that we see in many openings. } { [%cal Be8b8] } (6. c3 d3! 7. Nh4 { The idea is Qf3 to attack the pawn on d3 with queen and bishop. } { [%cal Gd1f3,Bf3d3,Bf1d3] } (7. Nxe5?! { An interesting idea to open the position. White does get 3 pawns for the piece, but will probably profit more from the open position. } 7... fxe5 8. Qh5+ Bf7 9. Qxe5+ Ne7 10. Qb5+ { [%cal Gb5b7,Gb5d3] } 10... Nd7 11. Qxd3 { Black can now claim some space with h5 or c5. } 11... h5 { [%cal Gh5h4] } (11... Ng6?! 12. Qc2 c5 13. d3 Qc7 14. Nf5 Be6 15. Ne3 Be7 16. g3 O-O { Henri, James - Chacon, Paulo Edison Terres, 0-1, CCO17/S1, 2006, https://lichess.org/f9eWXWXG }) 12. h4 c5 $17 { It's difficult for White to complete development here. Black might castle long soon after Qb6 and control the center via Ne5 and c4. } { [%cal Gc5c4,Bf7c4,Gd7e5,Gd8b6] })) 6... c6 (6... Nd7) (6... Nc6) 7. Be2 (7. Ba4 Na6 { [%cal Ga6c5,Bc5a4,Bc5b3] } (7... Nd7) (7... h5 { Engine suggestion. }) 8. Bb3 Bxb3 9. axb3 d3! 10. O-O Nb4 { [%cal Gd3c2,Gb4c2] } (10... h5 { Engine line. No king safety here. } 11. Ne1 h4 12. Nf5 g6 13. Ne3 dxc2 14. N3xc2) 11. Ne1 (11. cxd3 Nxd3)) 7... Qd7 8. O-O c5 9. d3 Bd6 $15 { Bischoff, Peter - Kunte, Abhijit, 1/2-1/2, Biel MTO op, 1998, https://lichess.org/wG9PR9wL } *


