1. g4 { A00 Grob Opening. Named after the Swiss International Master Henri Grob (1904–1974).
The winning rate is 38%/17%/45%. This makes it the second most decisive and worst first move for white after 1.Na3. But it does have a strong surprise element, and if Black doesn't know how to respond it can be quite good for White. These games are usually decided withing the first 20 moves. } 1... d5 (1... e5 2. h3 (2. Bg2 d5 3. c4 { Spike/Hurst Attack }) (2. c4 { English Attack (not an ECO name) }) 2... Nc6 { London Defense }) (1... g5 { Double Grob } 2. f4 { Double Grob/Coca-Cola Gambit }) (1... f5 { Alessi Gambit }) (1... c5 { "Sicilian Variation". Not an ECO name, but the third-common response. Most people stick to their plan and play Bg2 here. } 2. Bg2 Nc6 3. e4 e6) (1... g6 2. Bg2 Bg7 3. Nc3) (1... h5 2. gxh5 Nf6 3. Bg2 Rxh5) (1... c6 2. Bg2 d5) 2. Bg2 { Grob Gambit } (2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 { Zilbermints Gambit } 3... h5 { Zilbermints Gambit/Schiller Defense } (3... e5 4. d3 { Zilbermints Gambit/Zilbermints-Hartlaub Gambit })) (2. h3 e5 3. Bg2 c6 { Keene Defense } 4. d4 e4 5. c4 Bd6 6. Nc3 Ne7 { Keene Defense/Main Line }) 2... Bxg4 (2... h5 3. gxh5 { Grob Gambit/Basman Gambit }) (2... c6 { Grob Gambit/Declined } 3. c4 dxc4 4. b3 { Grob Gambit/Richter-Grob Gambit } (4. Na3 Bxg4 5. Nxc4)) (2... e5 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 { Grob Gambit/Keres Gambit }) 3. c4 { Grob Gambit/Fritz Gambit } 3... c6 (3... d4 { Romford Countergambit } 4. Bxb7 Nd7 5. Bxa8 Qxa8 $15 { Grob Gambit/Fritz Gambit/Romford Countergambit }) (3... Nf6 4. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7,Gc4d5] } 4... c6 5. Qxb7 Nbd7) 4. Qb3 e6 5. Qxb7 { White gets the pawn back. That's why this is not a gambit. } 5... Nd7 6. Nc3 (6. Qxc6 Rc8 7. Qa6 Rxc4 8. Na3 Rc8 (8... Qc8) (8... Bxa3!? 9. Qxa3 Ne7 10. d3)) 6... Ngf6 (6... Ne7) 7. h3 (7. Qxc6 Rc8 8. Qa6 dxc4) 7... Bf5 (7... Bh5) 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 { [%cal Gb5c7] } 9... Rc8 10. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3d4,Gd4c6,Gd4f5] } (10. Nxa7) 10... Bc5 11. Qa6 Nb8 12. Qa4 O-O $17 *


