[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.10.12"]
[UTCTime "23:57:24"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Bc5?! { I call this the Patzer variation, because it is usually played by people who don't know theory, and it's bad for Black. } 4. Nxe5 { This is kinda the only move. Invite Black to be forked on d4. } 4... Nxe5 (4... Bxf2+?! { Another way to get a pawn back. Not a good one as we will see. } 5. Kxf2 Nxe5 6. d4 Ng6 { Now White can't castle anymore, and the king is exposed. But the pawn on d4 is more worth than the one on f2, and White has the bishop pair. } { [%cal Gd1f3,Gc1e3,Gf1c4] }) 5. d4 Bd6 { Black probably wants to keep the bishop and take back the pawn. } (5... Bxd4? 6. Qxd4 d6 $16) 6. dxe5 Bxe5 7. f4 (7. Qf3 Nf6 8. Bf4 Qe7 9. Bxe5 Qxe5 $14) (7. Be2 d6 8. Qd3 Nf6 9. Nd1 { Don't allow Black to double the pawns by taking c3. } 9... Nd7 $10) (7. Bd3 { Most played move. } 7... Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 c6 $14 { Narayanan, SL. - Aradhya, Garg, 1-0, 54th ch-IND Challengers, 2016, https://lichess.org/h27ktEGG }) 7... Bxc3+ (7... Qh4+?! 8. g3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qh6 $16) 8. bxc3 d6 9. Bc4 Qh4+ 10. g3 Qe7 $14 (10... Qh3 { Pedzich, Dominik - Romanishin, Oleg M, 1/2-1/2, MK Cafe op-A, 1997, https://lichess.org/hSAztjAc }) (10... Qf6 { Lagarde, Maxime - Bacrot, Etienne, 0-1, FRA-ch 87th, 2012, https://lichess.org/aSaNHO3J }) *


