[Opening "Four Knights Game: Scotch Variation, Krause Gambit, Leonhardt Defense"]
[StudyName "3 and 4 knights opening: Theory, gambits, and important games"]
[ChapterName "4K/Scotch/Krause Gambit: 4…Bb4 5.Nxe5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/CUqgKXgk/g40yHABN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.08.28"]
[UTCTime "04:58:41"]

1. e4 { The Krause Gambit is named after Orla Hermann Krause (http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessplayer?pid=23850) who worked in the 1920s with Aron Nimzowitsch on opening theory. See [Nimzowitsch - Leonhardt] for the debut of this gambit and the Leonhardt defense. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 Bb4 { exd4 is the normal continuation here for a good reason. Bb4 invites White to play this gambit. } 5. Nxe5 { C47 Krause Gambit. Best move in this position. } 5... Qe7 { C47 Leonhardt Defense. Named after Paul Leonhardt. } (5... Nxe4 6. Qf3 { [%cal Ge5f7,Gf3f7] } (6. Qg4 { Preferred response to Nxe4. } { [%cal Gg4e4,Gg4g7] } 6... Nxc3 7. Qxg7 Rf8 8. a3 Nxd4 { [%cal Rd4c2] } 9. axb4 Nxc2+ 10. Kd2 Nxa1 11. bxc3 $16 { The engine gives +1 here. } 11... Qe7 12. Bc4 { Trap the knight } { [%csl Gb3,Gc2] } 12... d6 13. Ng4 { [%cal Gh1e1,Be1e8] } 13... Be6 14. Re1 (14. Nf6+ Kd8 15. Re1 d5 16. Ba2 { Just a different move order. }) 14... d5 15. Nf6+ Kd8 16. Ba2 h6 17. Re2 { Protect the bishop against threats on the a-file. } { [%cal Ge2a2] } 17... a5 $16 { +2.1 }) 6... Nf6 (6... Nxc3?? { Trap! } 7. Qxf7#) (6... Nd6 { [%cal Rc6d4] } 7. Be3 O-O) (6... Nxe5?? 7. Qxe4) 7. Be3 O-O (7... Qe7 8. Bd3 Nxe5 (8... d5 { Sukandar, I. - Ali Marandi, C., 1-0, St Louis Winter Classic B, 2017, https://lichess.org/YFSAaNNd }) 9. dxe5 Qxe5 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O (11... Qxc3?! 12. Bf4 { [%cal Gf4c7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8] } 12... Kf8 13. Qg3 { [%cal Gf4c7] } 13... Nh5 14. Qh4 { [%cal Gh4d8] } 14... Nf6) 12. Bd4) 8. Bd3 Re8 9. O-O (9. Nxc6?! { This is just helping black to develop the ls-bishop. } 9... dxc6 { Adams, Michael - Howell, James C, ½-½, Lloyds Bank op 16th, 2016, https://lichess.org/K8HjH47g } (9... bxc6 { Xu, Xiangyu CHN - Xiu Deshun, ½-½, TCh-CHN 2015, https://lichess.org/a3ZPk39k })) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Rxe5 12. Bd4 Re6 $10) (5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qe7 7. Nxc6 (7. f3) 7... Qxe4+ 8. Be2 (8. Qe2) 8... Qxc6 { [%cal Rc6c3,Rc6g2] } 9. O-O O-O { SF 8, depth 43, gives +0.19 for this move, +0.32 for Qxc3, and +0.46 for d5. King safety over material it seems. } (9... Qxc3 10. Rb1 O-O 11. d5 Qe5 12. Bf3 d6 13. Re1 Qf5 { [%cal Rf5c2] } 14. Re7 (14. Rb4 { Nitin, S. - Lin Chen, ½-½, 20th HZ Open 2016, https://lichess.org/So8bz56P }) 14... Re8 15. Rxc7 (15. Be4?! { The knight has to protect the rook on e8. } 15... Qg4 16. Rxe8+ Nxe8 17. Qxg4 Bxg4 18. Rxb7 Be2 $14) 15... b6 $14) (9... d5 10. a4!?) 10. Rb1 { SF 8, depth 43: +0.18, c4: +0.12, Qd3: +0.08 }) 6. Qd3 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] } (6. Nxc6 { Slightly worse than Qd3. } 6... Qxe4+ 7. Be2 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qxc6 { [%cal Rc6c3,Rc6g2] } 9. Qd3 Qxg2 10. Bf3 Qh3 $10) (6. Bd3? { Bad idea. } 6... Nxd4 { [%cal Re7e5] } 7. Nf3 Nxf3+ 8. gxf3 Nd5 { [%cal Rd5c3,Rb4c3] } 9. Qd2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bd6 $15 { It's just -0.7, but the whole position looks very ugly for White. }) 6... Nxd4 { Best move here (SF 8, depth 40), second best is Bxc3, but Nxe5 (third best) is usually played. } (6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 Nxe4 8. Qe3 Nd6 { Recommended by SF8, depth 42. } 9. c3) (6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qxe5 8. Bd2 O-O 9. O-O-O d6 (9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Qf4+ { [%cal Rf4f2,Rf4c1] } 11. Rd2 Qxe4 12. Qg3 { [%cal Gg3c7,Gc3f6] } 12... Qe7 $14) (9... Bc5 { [%cal Rc5f2] } 10. f4 Qd4 11. h3 Qxd3 12. Bxd3 d6 $14) 10. f3 Bd7 $14) 7. Qxd4 Bc5 { [%csl Rd5,Re3,Gd3] } (7... c5 8. Qe3 Qxe5 9. Bd2 O-O (9... b6) 10. O-O-O b6 $14 (10... Re8 11. a3 Ba5 12. f4 (12. Bc4) (12. f3 { Rausis, Igors - Kogan, Artur, 0-1, Paris op, 2017, https://lichess.org/s5M7vmTo }) 12... Qe6 { [%cal Ge3c5] } 13. e5)) 8. Qd3 { White can protect the pawn, but not the knight. } 8... Qxe5 9. Be3 Bxe3 10. Qxe3 d6 { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rc8g4,Rf6g4] } 11. O-O-O (11. f4 Qa5) (11. Be2) 11... O-O $14 *


