1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 { C46 Four Knights Game } 4. Bc4 { C46 Four Knights Game/Italian Variation } 4... Nxe4 { And this is the reason why White isn't playing this line. Black equalizes now easily, and the bishop can't stay on c4. } (4... Bc5 { C46 Symmetrical Variation. Not a good option for Black. This position is usually only reached by the Giuoco Piano, one of the the dullest lines known to mankind. } { Short, Nigel D - Carlsen, Magnus, 1/2-1/2, London Classic 3rd, 2011, https://lichess.org/6jkHhmiY }) 5. Nxe4 (5. Bxf7+ { C47 Noa Gambit. Doesn't work: Black can push then knights away with d5, e4, and h5-h4. } 5... Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 7. Ng3 (7. Neg5+ Kg8 8. d4 h6 9. Nh3 Bg4 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nf4 c6) 7... e4 8. Ng1 h5 { [%cal Rh5h4] }) 5... d5! 6. Bd3 (6. Bxd5?! { Giving up the bishop pair without compensation. Don't do that. } 6... Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qd6 $17) 6... dxe4 (6... f5 7. Nc3 e4 8. Bb5 exf3 9. Qxf3 Be6) (6... Nb4 7. Nc3 (7. Ng3 e4 8. Be2 exf3 9. Bxf3 Be7) 7... e4 8. Bxe4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Bf5 10. O-O { Best option. Recapture the piece later. } (10. d3 Bxe4 11. dxe4 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Bc5 { [%csl Rf2][%cal Rc5f2] } 13. Ke2 Nxc2 14. Rb1 f5 $10) (10. a3 Qe7 11. O-O Nxc2 12. Qxc2 Bxe4 13. Qc3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 O-O-O $15) 10... Bxe4 11. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e8] } 11... Qe7 12. d3 O-O-O 13. Nd2 Qc5 { [%csl Bc2][%cal Rc5c2,Rb4c2,Bc2a1,Bc2e1] } 14. Nxe4 Qxc2 15. Qg4+ Kb8 16. Bg5 f6 17. Rec1 Qxb2 18. Rab1 { [%cal Gb1b4] } 18... Qxa2 $17) 7. Bxe4 $10 { Note that this bishop has moved three times in the opening … and ended up on a rather unfortunate square. Black can now develop the rest of their pieces without further pawn moves. } { [%cal Gf8d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] } 7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Re8 (9... Nb4 10. d4 f5 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. Bd3 (12. Bxb7 Bxb7 13. dxe5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 h6 15. Bf4 g5 16. Bc1 Rad8 17. exd6 Qxd6 { Gray, Garvin - Mulder, John, 1/2-1/2, AUS/2017/IT (AUS), https://lichess.org/IFtYFSdg }) 12... Nxd3 13. cxd3 $10) *


