1. e4 { This is the debut of the Krause Gambit. Nimzowitsch worked together with Orla Hermann Krause on chess theory. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 Bb4 5. Nxe5 Qe7 { C47 Four Knights Game: Scotch Variation, Krause Gambit, Leonhardt Defense. This game is where the Leonhardt defense got its name from. Qe7 is still the best move in that position. } 6. Nxc6 { Qd3 is much better, because it protects e4. } 6... Qxe4+ 7. Be2 Qxc6 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qxc3 10. Rb1 O-O 11. d5 Qe5 12. c4 Re8 13. Bd3 d6 14. Bb2 Qh5 15. Qd2 Ne4?! { (-0.39 → 0.20) Inaccuracy. Best move was b6. } (15... b6 16. f3 Nd7 17. Rfe1 Bb7 18. Qf4 Ne5 19. Bc2 Ba6 20. Bxe5 Rxe5 21. Rxe5 dxe5 22. Qe4) 16. Rbe1 Bf5? { (0.27 → 2.48) Mistake. Best move was f5. } (16... f5 17. Bxe4) 17. Qf4 { [%cal Gd3e4,Gf4e4,Ge1e4] } 17... Qg6 18. Re3 { [%csl Bf5][%cal Ge3f3,Bf3f5] } 18... Kf8 19. h3 { Prevents Bg4. } { [%csl Gg4] } 19... h5 20. Rf3 Bd7?! { (2.57 → 3.14) Inaccuracy. Best move was Ng5. } (20... Ng5 21. Bxf5 Nxf3+ 22. Qxf3 Qg5 23. Bc1 Qf6 24. Qxh5 g6 25. Qh6+ Kg8 26. Bd3 Qc3 27. Qd2) 21. Re1 { Black resigns. F5 doesn't work anymore, because the black king is in the same file. } { [%cal Gf4f8] } 1-0


