[Event "Macleod Attack: 1. e4 e5 2. c3: Variations Overview"]
[Date "2017.11.27"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C20"]
[Opening "King's Pawn Game: MacLeod Attack"]
[StudyName "Macleod Attack: 1. e4 e5 2. c3"]
[ChapterName "Variations Overview"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/4yvmDHNB/Wcbj3jqG"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.11.27"]
[UTCTime "10:00:10"]

1. e4 e5 2. c3 { C20 King's Pawn Game/Macleod Attack.
The idea is to play d4 and to build a strong center. But Black can attack the e4 pawn immediately, and get a strong center and fast development for themselves.
This is the main difference to the Saragossa opening (1.c3, also very passive) where White at least doesn't give Black a target on e4.
The main problem for White is now what to do with the knight on b1. } { [%csl Bb1][%cal Gd2d4] } 2... d5 { Best response. } { [%cal Gd5e4] } (2... Nc6) (2... Nf6 { Most common response. } { [%cal Gf6e4] } 3. Nf3 { This creates a Petrov situation in which both sides attack the king pawn with a knight. But Black is faster here. } { [%cal Gf3e5] } (3. d4) (3. d3) 3... Nxe4 4. d3 (4. Qe2 d5) (4. Nxe5?! Qe7) 4... Nf6 5. Nxe5) 3. exd5 (3. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3e5] }) (3. d3) 3... Qxd5 { Note how this queen cannot be attacked by the b1 knight. Looks like an improved Scandinavian for Black now! } 4. d4 { The tension will now build up around these two pawns. Don't forget that e5 can be pushed to e4 any time! } { [%csl Gd4,Re5] } 4... Nc6 { [%cal Rc6e5,Rc6d4,Bd5e5,Bd5d4] } (4... Nf6) 5. Nf3 (5. Be3) 5... Nf6 { Black has now developed the knights towards the center, and the bishop have free diagonals. White has no threat. } (5... Bg4) (5... Bd6) (5... Bf5) 6. Be3 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ (7... Qa5+) 8. Nc3 Qa5 9. Qb3 (9. Bd2?!) (9. Qc2?!) 9... O-O *


