{ The Tarrasch Defense, a variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined, is listed under the ECO codes D32 to D34. }
1. d4 { It was advocated in the early 20th century by the German master Siegbert Tarrasch, who contended that the increased mobility Black enjoys is well worth the inherent weakness of the isolated center pawn. } 1... d5 { The debut of this defense was in 1887, see [Crewe - Hall] } 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/General. Black makes an aggressive bid for central space. After White plays cxd5 and dxc5, Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5. Such a pawn may be weak, since it can no longer be defended by other pawns, but it grants Black a foothold in the center, and Black's bishops will have unobstructed lines for development. } 4. cxd5 (4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/Symmetrical Variation }) (4. Nf3 { NN } 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bd2 (7. Ndb5 Nc6 { This position can also arise from the English Opening/Symmetrical Variation/Anti-Benoni Variation/Spielmann Defense. See [Ljubojevic - Topalov, 2002] for an example. https://lichess.org/IWfcqNR6 } 8. Nxd5 exd5 { [%cal Rb5c7,Bc7d5,Bc7e8] } 9. e3 (9. Qxd5 { Black cannot take the white queen immediately. } { [%cal Rb5c7,Bc7d5,Bc7e8] } 9... Bb4+ 10. Bd2 O-O 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 { [%cal Gd8d2,Gb4d2] } 12. Nc3 Be6 $10) 9... a6 $10) 7... e5 { Very rare move. } (7... Bc5 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. g3 { Back to the normal plan. } 9... Nc6 10. Bg2 O-O $10 { See [Wang - Gustafsson, 2015] https://lichess.org/opNfY2OY }) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 (8... exd4?! 9. e4 Bd6 10. Bc4 Nc6 $10) 9. Rc1 Nd7 (9... Na6 10. Nf3 e4 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qd4 Bc6 13. Qxd5 Bxd5 14. Nd4 Be7 $10) (9... exd4?? 10. Rxc8+ Ke7 11. Qc2 { [%cal Re2e4] }) 10. Nb3 Bd6 $10) 4... exd5 (4... cxd4 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/Schara Gambit } 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 Be6 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/Von Hennig Gambit }) 5. Nf3 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/Two Knights Variation } (5. dxc5 d4 6. Na4 b5 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/Tarrasch Gambit }) (5. e4 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/Marshall Gambit }) 5... Nc6 6. g3 { D33 Tarrasch Defense/Rubinstein System } (6. dxc5 d4 7. Na4 b5 { D32 Tarrasch Defense/Gruenfeld Gambit }) 6... Nf6 { D33 Tarrasch Defense/Prague Variation } (6... c4 { D33 Tarrasch Defense/Swedish Variation } 7. e4 { D33 Tarrasch Defense/Swedish Variation/Central Break }) 7. Bg2 Be7 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Prague Variation/Main Line } (7... Bg4 { D33 Tarrasch Defense/Wagner Variation }) 8. O-O O-O { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation } 9. Bg5 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Carlsbad Variation } (9. dxc5 Bxc5 (9... d4 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Classical Tarrasch Gambit }) 10. Na4 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Reti Variation }) 9... cxd4 (9... Be6 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Endgame Variation } 10. Rc1 c4 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Bogoljubow Variation }) (9... c4 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Advance Variation }) 10. Nxd4 h6 (10... Re8 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Petursson Variation }) 11. Be3 Re8 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Main Line } (11... Bg4 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Spassky Variation }) 12. Rc1 Be6 { D34 Tarrasch Defense/Classical Variation/Chandler Variation } *


