{ There are multiple ways to get a KIA setup, you don't have to start with Nf3.
If you start with 1.e4, you can delay the decision to play a KIA, for example when you face a defense that you're not comfortable with. }
1. Nf3 (1. e4 e6 (1... c6 2. d3 { B10 Caro-Kann Defense/Breyer Variation } 2... d5 3. Nd2 e5 4. Ngf3 Bd6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2) (1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. g3 Nc6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7) (1... e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { Petrov's Defense } (2... Nc6 { Normal King's Knight Opening, transposes to the same position as the Petrov's Defense after d5. } 3. g3 Nf6 4. d3 d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2) 3. d3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2) 2. d3 { C00 French Defense/King's Indian Attack }) (1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O) 1... d5 (1... c5 { A04 Zukertort Opening/Sicilian Invitation } 2. g3 d5) (1... e6 { A04 Zukertort Opening/Queen's Gambit Invitation } 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 b5 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 a5 11. h4 b4 12. N1h2) (1... f5 { A04 Zukertort Opening/Dutch Variation } 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. d4) (1... g6 { A04 Zukertort Opening/Kingside Fianchetto } 2. d4 Bg7 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 Nc6 7. Nc3) (1... b5 { A04 Zukertort Opening/Polish Defense }) (1... Nc6 { Zukertort Opening/Black Mustang Defense. Transposes into something well known eventually: } 2. d4 (2. e4 { Nimzowitsch Defense } 2... d6) (2. c4 e5 3. Nc3 { English Opening/King's English/Three Knights }) 2... d5 { Chigorin Defense }) 2. g3 { A07 King's Indian Attack } 2... Nf6 (2... e5?! { Omega-Delta Gambit }) (2... c5 { A07 Sicilian Variation #1 } 3. Bg2 { A08 Sicilian Variation #2 } 3... Nc6 { French Variation (says lichess, I couldn't confirm this elsewhere) } 4. O-O (4. d4 e6 5. O-O { A49 Zukertort Opening/Grünfeld Reversed }) 4... e6 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. e4 O-O 8. Re1 { A08 Sicilian Variation #3 }) (2... Bg4 { Keres Variation } 3. Bg2 Nd7) (2... g6 { Double Fianchetto } 3. Bg2 (3. b4 { Smyslov Variation }) 3... Bg7 4. O-O e5 5. d3 Ne7 { Pachman System }) (2... b5 { Spassky Variation. Similar idea as in the Smyslov variation: The other side has already commited to a fianchettoed bishop by moving the g-pawn, so they will very likely not go after the b-pawn with that bishop, because that would leave a hole on the g-file.
Still, it doesn't really develop anything and shouldn't be played so early. } { [%csl Bg2][%cal Rf1b5,Gf1g2] }) (2... g5 { A00 Hungarian Opening/Wiedenhagen-Beta Gambit }) 3. Bg2 g6 (3... c6 4. O-O Bg4 { Yugoslav Variation }) 4. O-O Bg7 5. d3 O-O { Wahls Defense } *


