1. e4 { Here we start with e4 and go for the KIA only after: } 1... c5 2. Nf3 { Black has many possible moves here. } 2... d6 (2... Nc6) (2... e6) 3. g3 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 4. d3 { Now Black can go for a Dragon setup or just play Nc6. } (4. e5 { is not so good: } 4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 Qd5 { [%cal Rd5h1,Rd5e5] } 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Bg2 Qe6+ 8. Kf1 { and we can't castle anymore. }) 4... g6 (4... Nc6) 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nbd2 Nc6 8. c3 { Restrict the knight and free the dark-squared bishop from protecting b2 against Black's bishop. } { [%csl Bd4,Bb4][%cal Gc3b4,Gc3d4,Rc6b4,Rc6d4,Rg7b2] } 8... Rb8 { This prepares queenside attack with the flank pawns. Let's slow that down: } (8... e5) 9. a4 { [%csl Gb5][%cal Ga4b5] } 9... a6 10. Re1 b5 11. axb5 axb5 12. d4 { Time to add some tension to the center. } 12... Nd7 { [%cal Rg7d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4,Gc3d4,Gf3d4] } 13. Nf1 { This is a very typical move for the KIA. Here is helps protecting d4. } { [%cal Gc3d4,Gd1d4,Gf3d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4,Rg7d4] } 13... b4 14. Be3 { d4 is now overprotected: it has more defenders than attackers, which means that every defender can move away if needed.
The square in front of an overprotected pawn is often critical as we will see soon. } { [%csl Bd5][%cal Gc3d4,Ge3d4,Gd1d4,Gf3d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4,Rg7d4] } 14... bxc3 (14... cxd4 15. cxd4) 15. bxc3 cxd4 16. cxd4 { We have to be very careful here. But … Black's dark-squared is more worth than pour rook. It prevents Black from getting checkmated. So we can allow this trade. } { [%cal Rg7a1] } 16... Nb6 { Threat is Bg4, pinning our knight. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rc8g4,Rg4d1] } 17. d5! { [%cal Rg7a1] } (17. Rc1?! Na5 { Sammour Hasbun, Jorge E - Petrosian, Tigran L, 1/2-1/2, Dos Hermanas Internet f 8th, 2007, https://lichess.org/23N5iZdY }) 17... Bxa1 (17... Ne5) 18. Qxa1 Nb4 19. Bh6! { And we have an attack. } { [%cal Gh6g7,Ga1g7] } 19... f6 { The only move for Black. } 20. Rb1 (20. Ng5?? Nc2!) (20. Bxf8? Nc2!) 20... Nd7 21. Bxf8 Kxf8 *


