1. Nf3 b5 { This ruins every hope for a reversed Grünfeld, because White can't play c4 now. And fianchettoing the light-squared bishop is also risky.
In other words: a KIA is probably not the best response here, but we should know what to play instead. } 2. e4 { Not d4, as this leads to a rather cramped position. } (2. d4?! Bb7 3. e3 a6 { See my game against IM Will Paschall https://lichess.org/UITi7T94 I had a decent position there, but it wasn't fun to play, and I lost in the endgame. }) 2... Bb7 3. Bxb5 { is the main move. I don't really like this pawn exchange. The point is that Black's light-squared has to move back later, wasting a tempo, while White's bishop can stay on b5 for a while and pin Black's d-pawn. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gb5e8] } (3. e5 a6 4. d4 (4. a4 b4 5. d4 e6 6. c3 (6. Bg5 Be7 7. Be3 Nh6 8. Bxh6 gxh6 9. Qd2 Bf8 10. Bd3 Rg8 11. Qf4 Rxg2 12. Nbd2 d5 { Forintos, Gyozo V - Smith, Alan A, 1-0, Manchester Benedictine op 5th, 1982, https://lichess.org/sosZ6MO5 })) 4... e6 5. Bd3 (5. a4 b4 6. Bd3) 5... d6 6. O-O Nd7 7. exd6 (7. a4 dxe5 8. dxe5) (7. Bf4 dxe5 8. Bxe5 Ngf6) (7. Nbd2 Bxf3 8. Nxf3 d5 9. a4 c6 10. axb5 axb5 11. Bd2 { Voloshin, Leonid - Bucinskas, Valdas, 1-0, Pardubice Czech op, 2007, https://lichess.org/Of12R1EW }) 7... Bxd6 8. a4 Ngf6 9. Nbd2 b4 10. Nc4 O-O) (3. d4 Bxe4 4. Bxb5 Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 Be7 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Ba4 O-O 9. Re1 d6 $14) 3... Bxe4 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4 e6 6. c4 { Get some space. } 6... Be7 (6... c6 7. Ba4 h6 (7... Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nxe4 { And White has the bishop pair. } 9... Nxe4 10. Bc2 f5 (10... d5 11. Re1 f5 12. Ne5) (10... Nf6 { is a rather poor move that }) 11. Re1 d5 12. Ne5 { This is a very nice outpost. } 12... Bh4 { [%cal Rh4f2,Re4f2] } 13. Re2 Bf6) (7... Bb4) 8. Bf4 { [%cal Gb1c3] } (8. Nc3 Bh7 { That's a safe place, but the bishop doesn't do anything there. } { Melkumyan, Hrant - Vedder, Henk, 1/2-1/2, EU-ch 14th, 2013, https://lichess.org/bScnMQ1Y })) 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Ba4 d6 *


