[StudyName "Evans Gambit"]
[ChapterName "Variations Overview"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/cJcRi5KU/cQTOWUI3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/fuxia"]
[UTCDate "2017.08.15"]
[UTCTime "09:48:42"]

{ This gambit was named after Captain William Davies Evans who was the first one playing it in the early 19th century. It became very popular among players like Adolf Anderssen, Paul Morphy and Mikhail Chigorin but got out of favor after a while until Kasparov revived it in the 1990s. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { C50 Italian Game } 3... Bc5 { C50 Giuoco Piano. Normal continuations here are c3, O-O, and d3. } 4. b4 { C51 Evans Gambit. Black has two options here: accepting or declining the gambit. If it accepts, the bishop is distracted from the a7-g1 diagonale and White has the chance to open the center with c3 and d4. If it declines, the b-pawn will occupy important space, and with the support of a4 White can create an attack on the queen side. } 4... Bxb4 { Accepted. "The best way to refute a gambit is to accept it” —Wilhelm Steinitz } (4... Bb6 { Declined }) (4... b5 { Fontaine Countergambit }) (4... d5 { Hein Countergambit }) (4... Nxb4 { Another way to accept the gambit. Very rarely played. Has no name. }) 5. c3 Ba5 { Main Line } (5... Bc5 { MacDonnell Defense } 6. d4 exd4 7. O-O (7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 { Harding Variation }) 7... d6 8. cxd4 Bb6 { MacDonnell Defense/Main Line } 9. Nc3 { Morphy Attack } (9. d5 Na5 10. Bb2 Ne7 { Paulsen Variation }) 9... Na5 (9... Bg4 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qb3 Na5 12. Bxf7+ Kf8 13. Qc2 Kxf7 { Mortimer-Evans Gambit }) 10. Bg5 { Goering Attack }) (5... Bd6 { Stone-Ware Variation }) (5... Be7 { Anderssen Variation } 6. d4 Na5 { Anderssen Variation/Cordel Line }) 6. d4 (6. O-O { Slow Variation } 6... d6 7. d4 Bb6 { Lasker Defense } (7... exd4 8. Qb3 { Waller Attack })) (6. Qb3 { No name. played by Jobava, Nunn, and Sutovsky. }) 6... exd4 { Pierce Defense } (6... d6 { Bronstein Defense } 7. Qb3 { Tartakower Attack. See [Nisipeanu - Caruana] }) (6... Nf6 { Laroche Variation }) (6... b5 { Leonhardt Countergambit }) 7. O-O (7. Qb3 { No name. Short has played this a few times with little success. } 7... Qe7 8. O-O Bb6 9. cxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. Ba3 d6 13. Rad1 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Qe5 $10) 7... dxc3 { Compromised Defense } (7... Nf6 { Anderssen Defense }) (7... d3 { Dufresne Defense }) (7... b5 { Johner Defense }) (7... Nge7 { Mieses Defense } 8. Ng5 (8. cxd4 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Ba3 (10. Qb3 Be6))) 8. Qb3 Qf6 9. e5 Qg6 (9... Qf5 10. Nxc3 Nge7 11. Ba3 O-O 12. Rad1 h6 $10) 10. Nxc3 Nge7 11. Ba3 $10 { Compromised Defense/Main Line } *


