1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5 { Averbakh Variation. It prevents the immediate 6...e5 } 6... c5 { Averbakh Variation/Benoni Defense. And indeed, this creates a Benoni pawn structure: } (6... e5? { Loses the rook. } 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Nd5 { [%cal Gd5c7,Gd5f6] } 9... Nxd5 10. Bxd8 $16) (6... h6?! { Playable, but weakens the kingside a little bit. } 7. Be3 e5 8. d5) (6... Na6 7. Qd2 e5 8. d5 c6 9. f3 Qa5 10. Bd3 { [%csl Ge2][%cal Gg1e2,Ge1g1] } 10... Nc5 11. Bc2 b5 12. cxb5 cxd5 13. Bxf6 (13. exd5 Bb7 14. Rd1 a6 { This looks like a Benko now. } 15. a3 { threatening b4 with a fork. } { [%cal Gb2b4] } 15... Ncd7 16. bxa6 Bxa6 17. Nge2 Nb6 $15 { Leitao, Rafael Duailibe - Smirin, Ilia, 0-1, New York op, 2000, https://lichess.org/oqpJ4mC2 } { Threating Nc4 } { [%cal Gb6d5,Gf6d5,Ga5d5,Rc3d5,Rd2d5,Rd1d2,Bb6c4] } (17... Rfc8 { probably stronger than Nb6. }) 18. Ne4 (18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Rfc8 20. O-O Nc4 21. Rb1 { Leitao, Rafael Duailibe - Smirin, Ilia, 0-1, New York op, 2000, https://lichess.org/oqpJ4mC2 }) 18... Qxd2+ 19. Bxd2 $15 { Black has lots of options here. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gf8c8,Gb6c4] }) 13... Bxf6 14. Nxd5 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Bg5+ 16. Ke1 Rb8 $14 { [%cal Gb8b5] }) (6... Nbd7 7. Qd2 { [%cal Gg5h6] } 7... e5 8. d5 Nc5 { [%cal Gc5e4,Gf6e4] } 9. f3 (9. Qc2 { [%cal Gc2e4,Gc3e4] }) 9... a5 $14 { White will play h4 and g4 here, combined with O-O-O. Quite dangerous. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rb2b4,Ge1c1,Gg2g4,Gh2h4] }) 7. d5 (7. dxc5 dxc5 (7... Qa5 { Playable, but hunting the queen gives White tempi. } 8. Bd2 Qxc5 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. Be3 Qa5) 8. Qxd8 (8. e5 Nfd7 9. f4 f6 10. exf6 exf6 11. Bh4 Nc6 (11... Nb6 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Ne4 { [%cal Gh4f6,Ge4f6] } 13... Nc6 14. Nxc5 Nb4 { [%cal Gb4c2] } 15. Kf1 (15. Kf2 Rd2 { [%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2,Gd2e2,Gd2b2] } 16. a3) 15... Nc2 { anyway } 16. Rc1 Ne3+ 17. Kf2 Re8 $10) 12. Qd5+ { This is a bit annoying and probably the reason why Nc6 is so rare. } 12... Kh8 13. Nf3)) (7. Nf3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. O-O Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Be6 11. Qd2 Qa5 12. Rac1 Rfc8 13. b3 a6 14. f4 { Pointing out how misplaced Black's light-squared bishop is. Black has tried a number of moves here. The engine likes Rc5 best. Looks a bit risky, but it does prevent f5. } { [%cal Rf4f5,Bf5e6,Bf5g6] } 14... Rc5 15. Qe3 Re8 { Mobilizes the knight on f6 which was pinned against e7. And once the knight has moved, Black has Bxc3 and then Qxa2. In other words: Re8 prepares a queenside attack. } { [%csl Be7,Bf6,Bg4][%cal Rg5e7,Gh7h6,Gb7b5,Bg7c3,Gf6g4] } 16. h3 { Prevents Ng4. }) 7... e6 8. Qd2 { [%cal Gg5h6] } 8... exd5 9. exd5 (9. cxd5) 9... Qb6 10. Nf3 Bf5 11. Nh4 Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. f3 h6 (13... Qxb2?! 14. Rc1) 14. Bxh6 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Qxb2 16. O-O Bc2 17. Rac1 Re8 { [%cal Ge8e2] } 18. Qd2 Qf6 { [%cal Gf6h4] } 19. g3 (19. Rxc2) 19... Ba4 20. f4 { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gh4f3] } 20... Nd7 21. Rf2 Re7 22. Nf3 Rae8 $10 23. Bd3 (23. Bf1) *


