1. Nf3 { [%eval 0.1] } { I played this with the intention to get a reversed Grünfeld on the board. } { [%clk 0:15:00] } 1... c5 { [%eval 0.19] } { Looks like my opponent rather wanted to play a Sicilian. } { [%clk 0:15:00] } 2. g3 { [%eval -0.1] } { I declined that invitation. Of course. } { [%clk 0:14:57] } 2... Nc6 { [%eval 0.37] } { This is actually the Main move in this position! } { [%clk 0:14:57] } 3. Bg2 { [%eval 0.11] } { Just wait for d5 … } { [%clk 0:14:55] } 3... d5 { [%eval 0.19] } { … and there it is. } { [%clk 0:14:55] } (3... e5 { was possible, and then I wouldn't have any good plan besides playing a KIA with a space disadvantage. }) 4. d4 { [%eval 0.03] [%clk 0:14:53] } 4... cxd4 { [%eval 0.46] [%clk 0:14:48] } 5. Nxd4 { [%eval 0.41] [%clk 0:14:53] } 5... Nf6 { [%eval 0.38] [%clk 0:14:45] } 6. O-O { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 0:14:48] } 6... e5 { [%eval 0.11] [%clk 0:14:36] } 7. Nxc6 { [%eval 0.24] } { Now we have the Exchange Variation/Modern Variation reversed. Lichess is still calling it "King's Indian Attack/French Variation". } { [%clk 0:14:47] } 7... bxc6 { [%eval 0.53] [%clk 0:14:35] } 8. c4 { [%eval 0.08] [%cal Gg2c6] [%clk 0:14:45] } 8... Be6 { [%eval 0.08] [%clk 0:14:25] } 9. Nc3 { [%eval 0.23] [%clk 0:14:42] } (9. Bg5 { Maybe I should have done this, before my opponent could play h6? } 9... Rc8 10. Qa4 Qd7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 { Not so clear. White has the better pawn structure, and the king is quite safe. But Black has the bishop pair, and the open g-file can become very useful. } 12. e3 d4 13. exd4 exd4 14. Nd2 (14. c5 Bxc5 15. Rc1 Qe7 16. Bxc6+ Kf8 17. Nd2 Kg7 $13 { Nakamura, Hi - Anand, V., 1/2-1/2, 5th Zurich CC 2016, https://lichess.org/dJ34SZSW }) 14... c5 15. Qa3 (15. Qb3 Bg7 16. Qd3 O-O 17. f4 Bf5 18. Be4 Bxe4 19. Nxe4 Rfe8 { Efimenko, Z. - Mekhitarian, K., 1/2-1/2, 23rd Abu Dhabi Masters, 2016, https://lichess.org/h16XpyFz }) 15... Be7 16. Qd3 h5 17. Nf3 Rb8 18. b3 { Efimenko, Z. - Cornette, M., 1/2-1/2, Bundesliga 2016-17, 2017, https://lichess.org/BlisvN1M }) 9... h6 { [%eval 0.72] } { Prevents Bg5, but now I get an important tempo: } { [%clk 0:14:09] } 10. Qa4 { [%eval 0.42] [%clk 0:14:27] } (10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qa6 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gg2d5] } 12... Bc8 13. Qb5+ Bd7 14. Qb7 { Mojzis, Jaroslav - Suran, Jan, 0-1, CZE-chT 9798, 1997, https://lichess.org/JyccWrCk } { [%cal Gb7a8] }) 10... Qd7 { [%eval 0.78] [%clk 0:12:32] } (10... Bd7 { Transposes to the 10.cxd5 line. } 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Qa6 Bc8 13. Qb5+) 11. Rd1 { [%eval 0.53] } { Add more pressure. } { [%clk 0:14:23] } 11... Be7?! { [%eval 1.1] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Rd8. } { I guess my opponent wanted to castle. But he didn't have time for that, because now I win a pawn. } { [%clk 0:12:12] } (11... Rd8 12. b3 Bc5 13. Ba3 Bxa3 14. Qxa3 Qe7 15. Qa5 e4 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Nb5 Rd7 18. Nd4) 12. cxd5 { [%eval 1.03] [%clk 0:13:36] } 12... Nxd5 { [%eval 1.11] [%clk 0:11:52] } 13. Nxd5 { [%eval 0.95] [%clk 0:13:13] } 13... Bxd5?? { [%eval 5.2] } { Blunder. Best move was cxd5. } { [%clk 0:11:46] } (13... cxd5 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5+ Ke6 17. e4 a5 18. Be3 a4 19. f4 exf4 20. gxf4) 14. Bxd5?? { [%eval 1.01] } { Blunder. Best move was e4. } { I was so focused on that pawn, that I missed the pin on the queen. e4 would have ended the game immediately. } { [%clk 0:13:08] } (14. e4 Rd8 15. Be3 O-O 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Qxd7 Rxd7 18. Rxd5 Rxd5 19. Bxd5 Rd8 20. Bb3 a6) 14... cxd5 { [%eval 1.13] [%clk 0:11:35] } 15. Qxd7+ { [%eval 1.0] [%clk 0:13:06] } 15... Kxd7 { [%eval 1.07] [%clk 0:11:32] } 16. Rxd5+ { [%eval 1.08] [%clk 0:13:04] } 16... Ke6 { [%eval 1.14] [%clk 0:11:21] } 17. e4 { [%eval 1.11] [%clk 0:12:55] } 17... Rad8 { [%eval 1.25] [%clk 0:11:12] } 18. Be3 { [%eval 0.82] } { So I traded my e-pawn for Black's a-pawn. } { [%clk 0:12:25] } (18. Rxd8 { was also possible, but I liked the idea to get two connected passed pawns. } { [%csl Ga2,Gb2] } 18... Rxd8 19. Be3) 18... Rxd5 { [%eval 0.84] [%clk 0:11:08] } 19. exd5+ { [%eval 0.86] [%clk 0:12:25] 