1. e4 { lichess: https://lichess.org/w07f0tSa
chess24: https://chess24.com/en/watch/live-tournaments/tata-steel-masters-2018/3/1/5 } 1... e5 { https://youtu.be/Sg89vnHwvhA } 2. Nf3 { https://youtu.be/_P4MHLybrsM } 2... Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 { C42 Russian Game: Classical Attack, Staunton Variation.
Both players had this position before (in Rapid games), so Anand decided to go for something else: Qc2, a move that Caruana had never faced before on the board. He did of course prepare for it. } 9. Qc2 { Anand had played this line three times before. See the comment on move 10. } (9. Re1 { Anand, V. - Caruana, F., 1/2-1/2, Champions Showdown Rapid, 2016, https://lichess.org/ZKRxKkC9 }) (9. Nc3 { Anand, V. - Caruana, F., 1/2-1/2, Saint Louis Rapid 2017, https://lichess.org/ycwTvVZv }) 9... Na6 { Anand's threat was *not* to take the knight on e4. That would give Black a nice initiative. } 10. a3 { Prevent the knight from going to b4. } { [%csl Gb4] } (10. Bxe4?! dxe4 11. Qxe4 Re8 12. Qc2 Nb4 13. Qc3 Bf5 { [%cal Rb4c2,Rf5c2] }) 10... Bg4 { White can still not take the knight. } (10... f5 { Anand, Viswanathan - Shirov, Alexei, 1/2-1/2, Amber-blindfold 12th, 2003, https://lichess.org/H8BePeDu }) (10... Re8 11. Nc3 Bg4 { Anand, Viswanathan - Piket, Jeroen, 1-0, Amber-blindfold 10th, 2001, https://lichess.org/DtZjfx07 } (11... Bf5 { Anand, Viswanathan - Kasimdzhanov, Rustam, 1-0, FIDE World Cup final, 2002, https://lichess.org/uI9ZcFKl })) 11. Ne5 (11. Bxe4?! dxe4 12. Qxe4 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qh4 { [%cal Rh4d4,Rh4h2] }) 11... Bf5 { White really wants to play f3 soon, but that's not possible yet. } (11... Bxe5 { The main move in this position. Maybe better than Bf5. But it's also very drawish. That might have been the reason for Caruana to take a different route. } 12. dxe5 Nac5 13. f3 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Nc5 15. Qd4 Nb3 { [%cal Rb3a1,Rb3d4] } 16. Qxg4 Nxa1 17. Bh6 g6 18. Bxf8 Qxf8 19. cxd5 Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Nc2 21. Qd7 Ne3 { Timofeev, Artyom - Wang, Hao, 1/2-1/2, RUS-CHN Summit Men 4th, 2007, https://lichess.org/gRJLhAMk }) 12. b4 { Prevents Qb6+ } (12. f3? Bxe5 { Threatening Bxd4+. } 13. dxe5 Qb6+ 14. c5 Nexc5 15. Bxf5 Nb3+ 16. Kh1 g6 17. Ra2 Nd4 { [%cal Rd4c2,Rd4f5] } 18. Be3 $17) 12... Nc7 $146 { (0.37 → 1.02) The engine calls this an inaccuracy, the database a novelty. Maybe not a good one. Anyway, the knight had nothing to do anymore on a6, so moving it away does make sense. } (12... Bxe5 13. dxe5 Bg6 14. Be3 Nc7 15. f3 Ng5 16. Rd1 Bxd3 17. Rxd3 Qe7 18. f4 Ne4 19. Nd2) (12... Re8 { Best move, according to Stockfish. } { Rebord, Mauricio - Glinz, Adolfo Gustavo, 1-0, ARG/C23/final (ARG), 2010, https://lichess.org/4ZSQdBWz }) (12... f6 { Main move, according to the lichess database. } 13. Nf3 Bg6 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Qxc3 dxc4 17. Qxc4+ Rf7 { Leko, Peter - Ivanchuk, Vassily, 1/2-1/2, Amber-blindfold 15th, 2006, https://lichess.org/g4qtJM5h }) 13. f3?! { (1.02 → 0.36) Stockfish: Inaccuracy
The main problem with this move is that it exposes the king for checks from d4. We will see how difficult this is for White in the following moves. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Rd4g1,Rd8d4] } (13. cxd5 cxd5 14. f3 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Rc8 16. Qe2 (16. fxe4?! dxe4 17. Rxf5 Ne6 18. Qd1 exd3 19. Rf2) 16... Bg6 17. Bb2 Ng5 18. f4 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Ne4) 13... Bg6 { Now Black can retreat the knight without leaving the bishop hanging. But taking the knight is still not possible for White. } 14. c5 (14. fxe4? { Would be a mistake: } 14... Bxe5 15. dxe5 dxe4 16. Qc3 (16. Bxe4?! Qd4+ { [%cal Rd4g1,Rd4a1] } 17. Rf2 Qxa1 $17) 16... exd3 $17) (14. cxd5 { Maybe better than c5? } 14... Bxe5 15. dxe5 Qxd5 { [%cal Rd5d4,Rd4g1,Rd4a1] } 16. Bb2 Ng5 17. Bxg6 hxg6) 14... Bxe5 15. dxe5 Ng5 (15... a5 { White can still not take the knight because of the hanging rook on a1. Caruana played a5 later … too late probably. } 16. Bb2 (16. fxe4? dxe4 17. Bc4 Qd4+ 18. Kh1 Qxa1) 16... Ng5) 16. Bb2 { Finally solving the hanging rook problem. Playing f4 immediately was also an option. } (16. f4 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Ne4 18. Nc3 Nxc3 19. Qxc3 f5 20. Be3 { Prevents d4? Hmm, maybe not. } 20... Ne6 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Re6d4,Rd8d4] } 21. Bd2 d4 22. Qb3 { [%cal Rb3g8] } 22... Qd7 $10) 16... d4?! { (0.06 → 0.71) Inaccuracy } (16... Bxd3 17. Qxd3 a5 18. f4 Ne4 19. Nd2 axb4 20. axb4 Rxa1 21. Bxa1 f5 22. exf6 Nxf6 23. Re1) 17. f4 Nd5 { [%cal Rd5e3,Re3c2,Re3f1] } 18. fxg5 Ne3 19. Qd2 Bxd3 { Enforce Qxd3, so the pawn on g5 isn't protected anymore. } { [%cal Rd2g5] } 20. Qxd3 Nxf1 21. Kxf1 Qxg5 22. Nd2 (22. Bxd4? Qf4+ 23. Bf2 Rad8 { [%cal Rf4c1] } 24. Qc2 Rd4 25. g3 Qf3 { [%cal Rf3h1] } 26. Nc3 Rfd8 27. Qe2 Qxc3 28. Bxd4 Rxd4) 22... Qxe5 23. Nf3 (23. Nc4 { Anand regretted later that he didn't go for that. But letting Black's queen take h2 is not an easy choice. } 23... Qxh2 24. Qxd4 f6 25. Nd6 { The knight would block both rooks here. } { [%cal Rd6b7] } 25... b6 $16) 23... Qh5 24. Qxd4 { [%cal Rd4g7] } 24... f6 25. Qc4+ Kh8 (25... Qf7 { The line Anand was hoping for. } 26. Qxf7+ Rxf7 27. Nd2 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Rd2c4,Rc4d6] }) 26. Bc1! { Moving the bishop to a better square. } (26. Bd4 Rfd8) 26... Rfe8 { Prevents Be3. } { [%csl Be3] } 27. Bf4 a5?! (27... Qf5 { The line Anand was expecting. } 28. Bd6 Re3 29. Kg1 Rae8 30. Rf1 Qg6) (27... Rad8 { Engine suggestion. }) 28. Bd6 axb4?! (28... Qf5 29. Qc3 a4) 29. Qxb4 { [%cal Rb4b7] } 29... Qd5?! { (0.34 → 0.92) Inaccuracy } (29... Qf7 30. a4 Re3 31. Rb1 Qg6 32. Bg3 Re7 33. Ra1 Qe4 34. Qxe4 Rxe4 35. a5 g5 36. h3 $10) 30. Qxb7 h6 (30... Ra4 31. h3 h6) 31. Kg1 Ra4 32. h3 { Make some luft for the king. } 32... Rc4?! (32... Kg8 { Without that move the rook on e8 cannot move because of Bf8! } 33. Qb2 Re3 34. Qb8+ Kh7 35. Qb1+ Qd3 36. Kh2 Qxb1 37. Rxb1 Rexa3 $14) 33. Qb2 Qd3?! { (1.13 → 1.74) Inaccuracy. Probably an attempt to get Re2 in. } (33... Re3 34. Kh2 Ra4 35. Ra2 Kh7 36. Qb1+ Qe4 37. Qxe4+ Rexe4 38. Rb2 Rxa3 39. Rb7 Kg8 40. Rb6) 34. Ra2 Qd1+?! { (1.62 → 2.49) Inaccuracy } (34... Ra8 35. Qb7 Rca4 36. Kh2 Qe4 37. Rb2 R4a7 38. Qb4 Ra4 39. Qxe4 Rxe4 40. Rb6 Rc4 41. Rxc6) 35. Kh2 Rc1 (35... Ra4 36. Qb7 { [%cal Rb7c6] } 36... Qd5 37. Rd2 { [%cal Rd2d5] } 37... Qe4) 36. a4? { (2.37 → 1.30) Stockfish: Mistake
Fuxia: I don't see what the point of this move is. If this was a waiting move to give Black the opportunity to make a mistake … then it worked quite well. } (36. Qb7 Qa4 37. Rd2 Qa8 38. Qf7 Rg8 39. Nd4 Qa6 40. Re2 Qd3 41. Re8 Rxe8 42. Qxe8+ Kh7) 36... f5?? { (1.30 → 4.42) Blunder } (36... Re6 37. Bf4) 37. Qb7 f4?! { (4.12 → 4.96) Inaccuracy } (37... Qh1+ 38. Kg3 Rc3 39. Qf7 Rce3 40. Bf8 Qe1+ 41. Kh2 Qc3 42. a5 Qf6 43. Qxf6 gxf6 44. Bd6) 38. Bxf4 Rxc5? { (4.68 → 7.11) Mistake } (38... Qh1+ 39. Kg3 Rxc5 40. Qf7 Rg8 41. Re2 Qf1 42. Re8 Rxe8 43. Qxe8+ Kh7 44. Qe4+ Kg8 45. Bxh6) 39. Rd2 Qxa4 40. Qf7 (40. Bxh6! gxh6 41. Qf7 Qe4 42. Rd6 Rh5 43. Rg6 Qe7 44. Rg8+ Rxg8 45. Qxe7 Rd5 46. Qf6+ Kh7 47. Qxc6 Rh5) 40... Rg8 41. Be5? { (6.40 → 4.78) Mistake } (41. Ne5 Qe4) 41... Qc4?? { (4.78 → 18.57) Blunder } (41... Qa5 42. Qf4) 42. Rd6 { Black resigns. } { [%cal Rd6h6] } 1-0


