[UTCTime "23:20:54"]

{ The Maróczy Bind is a pawn formation, named after the Hungarian grandmaster Géza Maróczy and primarily, but not exclusively, played against the Sicilian Defence. }
1. e4 { It is characterized by white pawns on c4 and e4, with White's d-pawn having been exchanged for Black's c-pawn. } 1... c5 { White's c- and e-pawns control the d5 square, making it difficult for Black to free his position with ...d5. Black often settles for the less active ...d6 instead. } 2. Nf3 { White's space advantage enables them to go for a "grinding" strategy. The minor pieces are grouped behind the advanced pawns and not traded off. } 2... Nc6 { White's ls-bishop is the "bad bishop", because is often stays very passive. A knight, a bishop or the queen are usually placed on d4, except when they are in danger of being traded. f4 is often a good move to open up Black's king side. } 3. d4 { Black's strategy is a pawn break on the queen side and a trade of minor pieces in order to get some space in the center. Ideally, Black should try to trade off White's bs-bishop. } { [%cal Ra7a5,Rb7b5] } 3... cxd4 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 4. Nxd4 g6 { https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uVGKrrucJbo } 5. c4 { https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LD1GxlCgNE8 } *


